<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' MAGIC ONCE AGAIN DEFEATS PACERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Larry Johnson was loitering on the perimeter, all
alone again. And as soon as Latrell Sprewell discovered him,
Johnson fielded the pass and unleashed a spinning 3-pointer that
stirred up echoes for the Pacers in flight.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre was unfolding all over again. As Johnson's shot
neared the rim, Patrick Ewing inexplicably appeared to tap the ball
in as it fell into the net. But no official waved it off; there was
only the sight of the blood rushing from the face of Pacers Coach
Larry Bird one more time at Madison Square Garden on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like a rewind of the Eastern Conference finals last
spring when Johnson devastated the Pacers with a 3-point shot that
was turned into a 4-point four-leaf clover on an official's
questionable call. Now this? Now a no-call?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think Patrick touched it, but then he said he did,''
said Johnson, whose aim looked good with 21.7 seconds left on a
play that gave the Knicks a 2-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was coy, saying he ``couldn't remember'' what happened on
Johnson's shot and just rejoiced in the jumper he could recall.
After Reggie Miller tied the score with two free throws, Ewing took
the chance to puncture the spirits of the Pacers all over again.
</P>
<P>
   On a play that was designed for Allan Houston, Ewing ended up
with the ball in his hands with 5 seconds on the clock. He grabbed
the ball with two hands, felt Dale Davis on his back and then spun
toward the baseline for a fade-away jumper. From 11 feet, from the
fingertips of the 37-year-old, from memory, he put down the
game-winning shot with 2 seconds left to give the Knicks an 83-81
jab at the Pacers. Instead of embarrassment for Ewing, there was
elation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found a good spot on the floor,'' said Ewing, who finished
with 20 points. ``I was able to hit my patented shot.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one last attempt by the Pacers. But just 24 hours
after Tim Hardaway blindly heaved up a game-winner at the buzzer in
Miami, Miller's fling from the top of the key to win the game fell
off the back of the rim. This time, the Knicks held off a rival
bent on putting a dent in their confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a game about your mentality,'' Houston said. ``It's
about how you respond. We found a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers couldn't believe they lost. After the game, the
official Joe Crawford watched the replay of Johnson's shot and
acknowledged that the crew should have called offensive
goal-tending call on Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing right there and had a better view,'' Bird said.
``It has happened to us before. You have to accept it and move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will take it. They won despite the Pacers'
aggressiveness. Indiana went to the free-throw line 24 times while
the Knicks went 7 times. The Knicks did hold the Pacers to 38
percent shooting from the field and received a 20-point boost from
Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   The victory did not do much to help the Knicks in the Eastern
Conference standing. Although the Heat lost on Monday night, the
Knicks are two games behind Miami for the second seeding with five
games remaining. Miami also holds the tie breaker if the two end
with identical records.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy had his concerns about how his team would
respond on Monday night after losing on Hardaway's heave Sunday in
Miami. The team flew back into New York around 1 a.m. on Monday,
knowing that its chance of catching the second-seeded Heat was
fading. Not only did the Knicks leave Miami trailing the Heat by
three games, but they had lost any tie breaker by dropping the
season series, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that ball going in Sunday night, it made those two teams
virtually uncatchable unless Indiana and Miami fall flat on their
face,'' Van Gundy said before Monday night's game. ``But that
should do nothing to deter us from our long-term goal. The excuses
are there if we want to give in to them. This is when mental
toughness is tested. We can list the excuses: hangover after last
night, playing our fourth game in five nights, and Miami and
Indiana are uncatchable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did not look uninterested. Their usual 1,000-watt
jolt, Sprewell, got the Knicks going in the right direction when he
took a Mark Jackson turnover down the court for a dramatic
two-handed dunk in the opening two minutes of the game. Sprewell
then came up with another steal and drive to the basket on his way
to 10 first-quarter points.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he baited Jalen Rose, the Pacers' most versatile
weapon, into three quick fouls in a 22-second span near the
four-minute mark of the first quarter. At that point, the Pacers
were slipping into the abyss, down by 20-12. But the familiar
military cut of Chris Mullin appeared and began to frustrate
Sprewell with his perimeter offense.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin, along with Travis Best, started an 11-3 run that
resulted in the Pacers' taking over the lead, 35-34, with 5:44 left
in the second quarter. Suddenly, the Knicks were not getting back
in transition, Houston was in a 2-for-8 start from the field, they
were getting beaten to the boards and they turned the ball over
twice in a 30-second span.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, Van Gundy sent Ewing back into the game after a
five-minute break to restore some size and order. Sprewell also
returned after a quick rest, and the Knicks were back on their way.
An 8-3 run that helped give the Knicks a 44-40 lead at the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
