<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' ENIGMA IS MENTAL WITH YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates is direct, blunt and honest.
</P>
<P>
   He offers no excuses or long-winded explanations. He doesn't
sugarcoat anything. The Rangers' main problem against the New York
Yankees, Oates said, is mental.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of things, but first of all, you have to
believe you can win,'' Oates said. ``I don't think we're dealing
with anything physical. I think we have enough talent to be on the
same field with them. Certainly, they have a great ballclub and
play very well. But I think what we're dealing with here is more
mental than physical.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Rangers are dealing with is complete domination by the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   They are 19-38 against New York since the start of the 1996
season, including a 1-9 record in three division playoff series
losses, the last two in which they've scored a total of two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' mission is to either change that or consign
themselves to being perennial doormats to the best team in
baseball. Since owner Tom Hicks has made it clear he has no
interest in such a distinction, this could be as good a time as any
to get it turned around. The Rangers are scheduled to play the
Yankees tomorrow in New York's home opener, postponed from today
because of a forecast calling for rain and cold. It will be the
first meeting between the teams since last year's divisional
playoff sweep by New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be interesting,'' shortstop Royce Clayton said.
``It's not us against them or anything like that. It's just a good
test for this team, a series against the best team in the world.
I'd like to see how we stack up against them.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been good lately, in the regular season or the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Especially the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have been swept in three consecutive games by the
Yankees in the division playoffs in each of the past two seasons.
The Rangers' flop last year was enough to convince Hicks and
general manager Doug Melvin it was time to change things. Melvin
started the makeover by trading two-time Most Valuable Player Juan
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers outfielder Chad Curtis was with the Yankees both years
and admitted his old teammates were a little surprised how
thoroughly the Rangers were dominated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into the series both years with a lot of respect for
what the Rangers had done, but also confident based on what we had
done,'' Curtis said. ``But once they were down 2-0, you could look
across the field and see they weren't sure they knew what they had
run into.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Rangers had run into superior pitching. The
Rangers hit .152 last year in the playoffs and .140 the year
before, mind-boggling numbers considering how good their offense
was during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But second baseman Luis Alicea said the Rangers had the wrong
approach offensively and must change to beat the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play the little man's game,'' Alicea said. ``We
can't be trying to hit home runs. Get guys over, take a walk,
instead of swinging at pitches out of the strike zone, which is
what we've been doing. They're not going to give Raffy \RPalmeiro\S
or Pudge \RRodriguez\S anything good to hit, so take the walk and
let the other guy do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the Yankees do. Watch them. They battle and battle
every at-bat, take what the pitcher is giving them. They don't try
to hit home runs. If they do, it's because they're strong and
they're good hitters. But hitter after hitter, they just battle. We
can do the exact same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rusty Greer, ``The offense just hasn't done what it's
capable of in the past two playoffs. Other than that, we've played
pretty well. The pitching has been good, and the defense has been
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get frustrated when you lose to a particular team. We have
great respect for what they've accomplished and what they continue
to accomplish. But the way we have to look at it is that any team
we play is more than beatable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are hardly the only team that has trouble with the
Yankees. Over the past four years the Yankees have averaged 100
victories a season and are 35-10 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure every team is asking the same question: Can we beat
the Yankees?'' Palmeiro said. ``Right now, they're the team ahead
of the pack. Eventually some team will beat them. Hopefully it will
be us, or it will another team and we'll beat that team.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some hope this season. The Yankees' starting rotation,
especially David Cone and Roger Clemens, is a little older and less
effective. There is also the hope that the loss of Curtis, Chili
Davis, Tim Raines, Joe Girardi and Darryl Strawberry will take
something away from the fabulous depth the Yankees have enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers also know they could win both games at Yankee
Stadium this week and still have it mean nothing in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have won the World Series three of the last four
years,'' Curtis said. ``They know what games are important and what
series is big. If they got swept by a team during the regular
season, come the end of the year and the playoffs, I don't think it
would mean that much.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least it would be a start. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
