<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA'S SAMUELS CONFIDENT HE'S THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 PREVIEW-OFFENSIVE LINE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NFL scouts are unanimous in ranking Alabama's Chris Samuels as
the prize offensive lineman in Saturday's draft. But if there still
is any doubt, ask Samuels his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very rare when you get a good left tackle, and I'm very
good,'' said Samuels, who can't recall the last time he allowed a
sack.
</P>
<P>
   Samuels, a 6-foot-5, 322-pounder, has an ego to match his build.
That's one reason the Washington Redskins, who have the second and
third choices, have fallen in love with him.
</P>
<P>
   They also like the way he plays the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``On game day, the intensity level I carry is so high,'' Samuels
said. ``I want to rip somebody's head off. When I get out on the
field, I'm motivated to dominate a guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The only question about Samuels is the health of his right knee,
which was injured in the season opener when Alabama running back
Shaun Alexander fell on him. Samuels had arthroscopic knee surgery
late last season, forcing him to miss the Orange Bowl after 42
consecutive starts for the Crimson Tide. He also sat out the Senior
Bowl and the NFL combine workouts, but he since has run a 5.12 in
the 40-yard dash.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the combine, everyone felt it was routine,'' Redskins coach
Norv Turner said. ``The way he was moving, you sure couldn't tell
he had a bad knee.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuels was a receiver in the eighth grade and a backup
quarterback as a high school freshman. Then, he had a growth spurt.
He weighed 240 as a sophomore and 260 as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I kept my quick feet,'' said Samuels, who wears a size 15
shoe. ``I would run with the linebackers \Rat Alabama\S a lot of
times, and I beat a lot of the linebackers in the footwork drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could have played a lot of positions _ tight end,
defensive end. I know I can play tight end. There's no doubt about
it. They could have put me at fullback. I could have done it all.''
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSIVE LINE Name School Height Weight 40 time Comment 1.
Chris Samuels Alabama 6-5 322 5.12 Outland winner coming off knee
surgery 2. Stockar McDougle Oklahoma 6-51/2 351 5.41 Will be a
weight watcher 3. Chris McIntosh Wisconsin 6-61/2 315 5.33 LT
expected to convert to RT 4. Todd Wade Mississippi 6-71/2 325 5.20
Could be solid bookend at RT 5. Adrian Klemm Hawaii 6-4 306 4.98
Has started at LT, RT and TE SLEEPER Name School Height Weight 40
time Comment Leander Jordan Indiana (Pa.) 6-4 330 5.42 Can he make
the transition from small college? STOCK FALLING Name School Height
Weight 40 time Comment Chad Clifton Tennessee 6-5 330 4.97 Not a
good run blocker nn
</P>
