<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS A FLIP OF THE SWITCH ENOUGH FOR THE STARS?
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Due to zero options, the Stars have to say what
they do say. And Mike Modano says it best, with his prediction of
``now we flip the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   He means, of course, that emotional/energy switch. It goes from
``off'' to ``on.'' And with this, the defending Stanley Cup champs
will suddenly reinvent themselves, fueled once again by the playoff
passion of 12 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the common and constant theme yesterday at the Stars'
Valley Ranch bunker, with coach Ken Hitchcock, while very
optimistic, noting that ``a big gray area'' will exist when the
postseason is launched tomorrow night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock is wondering what kind of ``gear'' the Stars will come
with in the first-round opener against Edmonton's them-again
Oilers. ``Why do we even have the regular season?'' asked Modano.
``Why don't we take off those seven months, then show up in April
and play Edmonton?''
</P>
<P>
   It is the third time in four years the Stars have opened the
playoffs against the Oilers, and the fourth consecutive year
they've met in the postseason. But this first-round encounter is
not necessarily about the opposition _ until late Sunday night it
was sure to be San Jose. Instead, the focus will center on a local
search for something lost. Something that was so prevalent with the
Stars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I noticed it today,'' said Brett Hull after yesterday's
optional practice. ``It's felt different on the ice. The enthusiasm
and the electricity was there. This comes with the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it really work this way in pro sports? Can a team go
winless in the last eight days of the regular season (two ties in
five games), and then immediately locate the ``on'' switch? In
general, the answer is no. But while the Stars have to publicly say
otherwise, do they really believe that stuff?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe it,'' said Modano, ``more so now than ever,
because we have been there, we have won \Rthe Stanley Cup\S and we
have a first-hand knowledge of all the different circumstances that
come into play.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything we've gone through this season with injuries,
to still end up with 100 points and in first place, I think we
surprised ourselves in doing this well. But we know what we're
playing for. It wasn't about the last week. It's about right now. I
believe we will flip that switch now that the playoffs are here.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the regular season, getting a playoff read on the Stars
is murky at best. The off-season was very short, so much so the
Stars came back in October and went through several months of
appearing disinterested and fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-driving Hitch seemed dismayed, but a clearing-of-the-air
locker room session between the second and third periods in Atlanta
in late November jumped started the club. For awhile, the Stars
seemed back on track, but ...
</P>
<P>
   The injuries to key people kept coming, and coming, and,
frankly, that's what ``the big gray area'' is all about for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The glass is half-full if you believe, based on the severe
nature of the injuries, that the ``real'' Stars will finally
surface in the playoffs, even with a still-ailing Sergei Zubov
questionable for the Edmonton series. The glass if half-empty if
you believe championships in pro sports are normally won by teams
that have few regular-season distractions, including injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But the X-factor is what happened over the final eight days of
the regular season _ playoff momentum did build in those five
games, except in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Which prompted an old NHL hand like Kirk Muller to hark back to
the Stanley Cup championship club he played on in Montreal. ``In
1993, we lost eight of the final 10 regular-season games,'' said
Muller. ``Having been though that, which was worse than this, I've
got no concern, because so much depends on the makeup of your team.
With the veterans here, everyone knows how to prepare for what's
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's a Hull, who gave a confused look yesterday when the
subject of lost momentum kept coming up. ``It's irrelevant,'' he
said. ``Building momentum starts right now. Now is when we've got
to start putting together wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton has served as a postseason momentum builder for the
Stars. Since the Oilers shocking first-round upset three years ago,
the Stars have won eight of nine from Edmonton in the playoffs. But
it hasn't been dominance by any means. The norm is very physical,
punishing one-goal victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we won games because we flat outplayed teams,''
said Hitchcock. ``This year we've won at times because we've
outmanuevered teams. Starting right now, we've got to rediscover
last year's gear.''
</P>
<P>
   And also discover that ``switch,'' then flip it. If, of course,
there actually is one. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
