<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARSG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS HAVE LEHTINEN BACK, BUT CAN HE BE EFFECTIVE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Stars didn't know how much they missed Jere
Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   Until he came back.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these things that you forget about, that he does so well,
they come back,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``He makes
everybody around him better.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the Lehtinen who creates the space allowing Brett Hull
to poke in the Stanley Cup-winning goal. This is the Lehtinen who
hangs back so Joe Nieuwendyk can cheat in for one more shot, and
win the Conn Smythe trophy. This is the tireless Lehtinen who is so
boundless, he pulls his linemates along with him as he moves up and
down the ice in a seven-game series against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   But is this the Lehtinen who is back after missing 65 of the
Stars 82 regular-season games?
</P>
<P>
   That answer might just go a long way in answering another: Can
they repeat?
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough for Lehtinen to just be playing. He has to be
the player who kills penalties, who prevents odd-man rushes and
neutralizes an opponents' best offensive threat.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he has to be himself.
</P>
<P>
   If he is, he could be the key to the Stars repeating as Stanley
Cup champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't expect too much,'' said Lehtinen, who played Sunday for
the first time since re-injuring his right ankle Jan. 19. ``It's
been like three months since I played.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was 81 days.
</P>
<P>
   But, who's counting? Well, the Stars for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a comfortable feeling when Lehtinen is on the ice for
us,'' Hitchcock said. ``He makes everybody around him better.''
</P>
<P>
   Who else was counting? Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough and frustrating,'' he said. ``It's been a long
season even though I haven't played. It's not normal yet, but it
will be there in a little while. The main thing is that it's strong
enough it's not going \Rto break\S again. The more I play, the
better I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time this season he's testing that theory.
The first time he came back after missing 30 games and returned
Dec. 29. The ankle wasn't ready. He played in eight games before a
second operation was required, this one to set pins in the bone to
stabilize the ankle.
</P>
<P>
   He missed 35 more games before playing in the regular-season
final against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first period I was a little nervous to go in there,''
Lehtinen said. ``I was thinking, `What's going to happen?', but
during the game it was more normal.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial reports from Lehitnen read as follows: 13 minutes
and 41 seconds, 18 shifts, four shots, two hits, one block, a
plus-one rank against the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same as it was before, so that's good,'' he said
with a smile and a shrug. ``It's been so long, and I don't want to
hurt it again. We have to take it a little easier than the first
time. We want to make sure it's strong enough to play.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lehtinen's mind, the question of the ankle's stability is
answered: It's going to hold. After all the time he spent
rehabbing, it better be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets that one game in and everybody is like, `wow,'''
defenseman Brad Lukowich said. ``He raised the confidence of the
team. A lot of the guys work around him and what he does on the
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how quickly will he regain his back-to-back
Selke-winning form.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy injury for hockey. He will probably start off
a little slow and work his way back,'' said winger Kirk Muller, who
suffered a similar injury when a puck bounced off his ankle when he
was playing for Florida. ``Mine didn't break, but it took about a
year to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is trying to keep it up strength wise. I would
play for a couple of periods, and it would get weak and tired.
Hopefully, it can stay strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen was still suffering from some soreness and did not
attend yesterday's optional skate. But, with the playoffs beginning
tomorrow night, stealing time for extra rest might be harder than
returning from the injury itself.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Hitchcock trying to get a feel for how effective
Lehtinen can be while juggling lines to put him on. Does he play
with Brett Hull and Joe Nieuwendyk? Does he play with the checking
line of Guy Carbonneau and Mike Keane?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll upgrade him again and see how he feels, see how many
minutes we can get out of him,'' Hitchcock said. ``I think a lot of
his game will be based on how many minutes we think he can play.
For us to be effective, Lehtinen has to get further up the line.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the details. A Jere Lehtinen at 70 or 80 percent is
better than most defenders at 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A two-time Selke winner? You want him in your lineup,''
Nieuwendyk said.
</P>
<P>
   He's in. This time, Lehtinen hopes, for good.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
