<HEADLINE>
ZUBOV'S CONDITION STILL UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD AND MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov said yesterday
that his slightly torn MCL feels ``not bad,'' but he didn't know
when he'd be able to return to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Zubov said. ``As soon as I can play, I'll be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said yesterday he doesn't expect Zubov
back for either Game 1 or 2 of their first-round playoff series
against Edmonton but is hopeful that Zubov could be ready in time
for Game 3 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov will be evaluated today to see if there's any progress. He
tore the right medial collateral ligament in his right knee March
29 against Florida and was expected to miss 2-4 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been feeling really strong and was really excited to get
\Rthe playoffs\S going,'' Zubov said. ``It's been very
frustrating.'' MOMENTUM OVERRATED?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are 0-3-2-1 in their past five games, matching their
longest winless streak of the season. For a team out to repeat as
Stanley Cup champions, the Stars don't put little stock in how they
finished the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's irrelevant,'' Brett Hull said. ``We didn't play
that well last year going in. A couple of bad games at the end of
the season isn't going to stop us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were 3-2 in their last five regular-season games last
season, losing their final two. Even Ken Hitchcock seems a bit
sympathetic about the team's lack of motivation down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we clinched the Pacific, our physical play dropped
off,'' Hitchcock said. ``You would like to be playing better. I
would like to see our impact players have better performances. But,
there is no point in fighting that fight.'' nn
</P>
