<HEADLINE>
FOR COWBOYS, SECOND IS OFTEN FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ To most Americans, there's a stigma attached to
being second, especially in the world of sports, where being second
often is synonymous with being a loser.
</P>
<P>
   To Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, a second-round pick, the team's
only selection over the first three rounds of this weekend's NFL
draft, is synonymous with getting a player who can immediately help
the Cowboys win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will get a starter,'' Jones said yesterday as the Cowboys
continued their evaluation meetings. ``I expect nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys don't have a selection until the second round, 49th
overall, because they traded their first-round picks in 2000 and
2001 to Seattle for big-play wide receiver Joey Galloway. Moreover,
the Cowboys don't have a third-round pick this year because they
traded that to Seattle a year ago for wide receiver James McKnight,
who spent all last season on injured reserve after major knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to death with Galloway and McKnight,'' Jones
said. ``As for our second-round pick, I'm hoping that Larry Allen
will be there for us again. That would be a player who we have
slotted to go in the first round ... who falls to us in the second
round. That's what we're really hoping for.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the draft is such an inexact science, there are examples
of ``first-round'' values in the second round of almost every NFL
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, 46th selection overall from Sonoma State, was such a pick
for the Cowboys in 1994. He has gone to the Pro Bowl, as well as
made All-Pro, each of his past five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the least action \Rfive picks over seven
rounds\S we've had in any draft since I've owned the Cowboys,''
Jones said. ``In that sense, it's going to be a little strange for
us ... but we're going to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys used the 49th pick in 1996 to take Georgia
linebacker Randall Godfrey, who became a three-year starter and the
team's leading tackle in the middle last season, before signing
with the Tennessee Titans as a unrestricted free agent. Godfrey was
lured away by a five-year, $25-million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second round has been good to us,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys used their past two drafts to land offensive linemen
with second-round picks: Flozell Adams, a starter now at left
tackle, and Solomon Page, who will compete this summer for a
starting job at right guard. Adams was the 38th pick overall in the
'98 draft; Page, 55th overall in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Darren Woodson, a five-time Pro Bowler, was a
second-round pick in '92 (37th overall); but wide receiver Jimmy
Smith (36th overall), whom the Cowboys picked in '92 but let get
away when Smith broke his leg as a rookie and underwent an
appendectomy as a second-year player, might have been a bigger
second-round steal. Now with Jacksonville, Smith led the NFL with
116 catches last season.
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the Cowboys' Ring of Honor, safety Mel Renfro was
a second-round pick in 1964. Because there were only 14 teams in
the NFL then, Renfro was the 18th selection overall _ the highest
pick spent by the Cowboys on a defensive back until Kevin Smith
(first round, 17th overall) 28 years later.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also have done well when they've traded away their
second-round pick, as they did in 1963 to Chicago to acquire
linebacker Chuck Howley, another Ring of Honor member, and in 1997
in a trade with Detroit to drop down into the third round to take
linebacker Dexter Coakley, now a Pro Bowler, plus get an extra pick
in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everything has worked out perfectly for the
Cowboys among their second-round picks. In 1995, a blocking tight
end named Kendall Watkins (59th overall) blew out his knee in a
preseason game during his second season and was never a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, fullback Daryl Johnston (39th overall in '89) and
linebacker Ken Norton, Jr., (41st overall in '88) were part of the
Cowboys' Super Bowl landscape during the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The message is clear: If you're holding a second-round pick in
the NFL, be patient and stick to your guns. Remember that in 1991,
Dan McGwire and Todd Marinovich were first-round selections, 16th
and 24th overall, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Favre was taken in the same draft by Atlanta in the second
round, 33rd overall.
PAST 49s
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the past 10 players selected 49th overall in the
NFL draft are still in the league, and only two of them are
starters. Here is the rundown: Year Name Position Drafted by
Comment 1999 Joe Montgomery RB Giants Led Giants in rushing (348)
as rookie backup. 1998 Kenny Mixon DE Miami Lost starting job with
Dolphins in '99. 1997 Torrian Gray DB Minnesota Used by Vikes
strictly in nickel packages. 1996 Randall Godfrey LB Dallas Signed
$25 million deal with Tennessee Titans. 1995 Barret Robbins C L.A.
Raiders Ex-TCU Horned Frog now a Raiders starter. 1994 Toby Wright
DB L.A. Rams Out of the league. 1993 Roosevelt Potts RB Colts Last
carry was in '98, cut by Dolphins in '99. 1992 Troy Auzenne OT
Chicago Out of the league. 1991 Chris Zorich DT Chicago Out of the
league 1990 Pat Terrell DB Philadelphia Out of the league.
WHOM WILL THE COWBOYS TAKE?
</P>
<P>
   A look at whom NFL experts think the Cowboys might take in the
upcoming draft:
</P>
<P>
   Mel Kiper: Lewis Sanders, CB, Maryland
</P>
<P>
   Joel Buchsbaum, ``Pro Football Weekly:'' Mark Roman, DB, LSU
</P>
<P>
   Ourlads' Scouting Services: Deltha O'Neal, CB, California
</P>
<P>
   ``NFL Insider:'' Dwayne Goodrich, CB, Tennessee; John Romero, G,
California; or Arturo Freeman, S, South Carolina nn
</P>
</TEXT>
