<SLUG> BC-RAC-SCHEDULING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY FACTORS INVOLVED IN HORSE RACING SCHEDULING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ When the thoroughbred season starts
Thursday at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie, Larry Craft is in
charge of the racing schedule. His title is director of racing, and
he formulates the races that determine which horses compete against
each other every day at the track.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved with the schedule-making of other sports have the
same goal as Craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we come up with our home football schedule, we try to
create a balance where it's competitive for our team and enjoyable
for our season-ticket holders,'' said Jack Hesselbrock, associate
athletic director for internal operations at TCU. ``We try to have
a marquee non-conference home game every year. We had Oklahoma two
years ago and Arizona last year. In future years we'll have
Northwestern and Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   If full fields of horses are any judge, Lone Star's races have
been competitive. According to Lexington, Ky.-based Equibase, Inc.,
the official statistics keeper for horse racing, Lone Star led the
nation in field size the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been some marquee events. When former Kentucky
Derby winner Real Quiet raced at Lone Star last year, attendance
hit 21,000. The average attendance last year was 9,370.
</P>
<P>
   Craft writes the conditions _ the parameters of competition _
for all of Lone Star's races. There will be close to 400 by
season's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to satisfy three constituents,'' Texas Thoroughbred
Association executive director Dave Hooper said. ``No. 1, he's got
to put on a good show for the public. No. 2, he's responsible to
management at the track, which is looking for full fields and
maximized handle \Rbetting\S. And third is the horsemen \Strainers
and owners\S. He's got to put on the type of race that fits the
stock stabled at his track.''
</P>
<P>
   Craft has been writing races since 1977 when he became racing
secretary at what is now Philadelphia Park. He later held the
position at Oaklawn Park in Hot Springs, Ark., before coming to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 1,400 horses stabled at Lone Star. To keep
track of their racing status, Craft writes information about horses
into grids on a sheet about two feet square in size. That two-foot
square sheet folds out like an accordion to about five feet long.
And there are at least two other accordion-like grid sheets
depending on the age of the horses Craft is tracking.
</P>
<P>
   Other than stakes races, there's no set schedule that dictates
the day-to-day racing for the entire season at Lone Star. Instead,
Craft develops the information off the grids into a condition book
that's written and rewritten at least five times throughout the
73-date season. One condition book has the schedule for about 15
days of racing.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Craft said he hopes he can write the book in such a way
to please everyone. The condition book is circulated in the barn
area, and the trainers find the events that suit their horses'
ability and enter them 48 hours prior to the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``All horses on the grounds, or most horses, will have a race in
which they can run in that book,'' Craft said. ``You try to put all
the horses you have into groups. You're writing races for groups of
horses.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups are dictated by the age of the horse, class levels of
competition, the distances horses are judged best suited to run,
gender and surface (dirt track or the turf course).
</P>
<P>
   In terms of age, 2-year-olds always race against 2-year-olds.
For about half of the year, 3-year-olds race against other
3-year-olds. As the season progresses, 3-year-olds will race
against older horses. Males almost always race against males, and
females almost always against females.
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing can be compared to football again when it comes to
class levels of competition.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL grew unhappy with its scheduling system of rotating
opponents each year after the 1977 season because, according to the
NFL's ``Record &AMP; Fact Book,'' the formula ``often resulted in
competitive imbalances.''
</P>
<P>
   So the league changed to a formula that determined the schedule
according to the final regular-season standings from the previous
season. Teams that finish first in their division must play the
other first-place teams within their own conference from the
previous season. Likewise, a last-place team gets the other two
last-place teams within the conference.
</P>
<P>
   It's produced longshot Super Bowl contestants the past two
seasons, including champion St. Louis this year. The Rams went from
worst to first in the NFC West en route to the title.
</P>
<P>
   In horse racing, horses who have never won compete in maiden
races. Once they win, they can advance up the competition ladder to
allowance races. If those events prove too tough for the horse, a
trainer can enter into claiming races. Stakes races are the highest
levels of competition at the track.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming races usually aren't as tough as allowance races, but
there is a trade-off. To get into the easier race, a trainer and
owner risk losing the horse through the claiming process. That's
when another owner purchases the horse out of the race for a set
price. It's horse racing's equivalent of the waiver wire in other
sports.
</P>
<P>
   As in other sports, not everyone is pleased with the schedule.
Craft admits that he hears it from trainers when they don't get the
race to fit their horse. They're often looking for the easiest
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a racing secretary's job is to make it as competitive as
possible,'' Hooper said. ``They've always got people coming in and
complaining or making a request. Not everyone is going to be
comfortable in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of blaming the schedulemaker extends to horse racing.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
