<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3090 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BEER-BILLBOARD-LADN     04-11 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-BILLBOARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE BREWS ON SUNSET STRIP AS BEER AD RISES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ West Hollywood, this beer's for you.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to remove a landmark, 100-foot-high Marlboro Man
billboard on the Sunset Strip last year, the Philip Morris Co.
plans to erect a new ad that some say is just as politically
incorrect: a 95-foot tall, three-dimensional Miller beer bottle,
complete with a cap that pops and spouts steam.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has ignited a bitter debate over land use policy,
alcohol abuse and whether the cigarette maker is toasting West
Hollywood or striking back at tobacco opponents who brought down
the Marlboro Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, this is a satirical thrust at the anti-smoking
people,'' said UCLA art history professor Al Boime, who has studied
outdoor art and advertising in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try to imagine a huge bottle like that _ it's insulting and I
think undignified even in the Sunset area.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agree, including West Hollywood officials and
anti-drunk-driving advocates who oppose replacing one
vice-glorifying billboard with another. They argue that outdoor
alcohol ads tend to lure underage drinkers _ just as tobacco
billboards allegedly lured young smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing when there's such a serious problem with
alcoholism in America _ and driving under the influence and binge
drinking on college and high school campuses,'' said Tina Pasco,
director of Mothers Against Drunk Driving Los Angeles. ``There's a
real lack, I feel, of moral responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Miller Brewing, a Philip Morris subsidiary, said
they do not market to underage drinkers and they encourage the use
of designated drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miller is committed to marketing its products responsibly to
adult consumers, 21 and over,'' said Miller spokesman Ron Acosta.
</P>
<P>
   He said the bottle will likely display the company's ``Think
When You Drink'' slogan. The company is also running at least two
television ads that support the use of designated drivers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the old Marlboro Man site is a prime spot for
advertising and that the beer ad is not meant as a negative message
to West Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the premier locations in the country,'' Acosta
said. ``It's a high-visibility location. West Hollywood is a place
where a lot of tourists and consumers go for enjoyment.''
</P>
<P>
   For 17 years, the rugged Marlboro cowboy stood guard over Sunset
Boulevard, king of the Strip's billboard jungle and a cultural icon
of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than just an advertisement for cigarettes; it was a
nostalgic symbol of the wild, untamed West, said Ken Breisch,
director of the Historic Preservation Program at the University of
Southern California's architecture school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of image that Marlboro wanted to create of the West
is perhaps what made people associate it with Los Angeles,''
Breisch said.
</P>
<P>
   But the tobacco industry's $206 billion litigation settlement
with 46 states forced Philip Morris to take the Marlboro billboard
down in April 1999. Under the settlement, the state Department of
Health Services was allowed for a limited time to put up a figure
some nicknamed ``Impotent Man'' _ basically a parody of the macho
cowboy with a limp cigarette illustrating a danger of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Now the state's time has expired, and Philip Morris has use of
the site back.
</P>
<P>
   West Hollywood City Councilman Paul Koretz is upset but feels he
can't oppose this sign unless the city passes a wholesale ban on
alcohol billboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not particularly happy that the Marlboro Man was replaced
by a beer icon,'' Koretz said. ``But I also feel, since we don't
have any kind of law against it, that we don't have any
justification under the First Amendment to pick that particular one
and say we don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The design submitted to the city indicates the bottle itself
will be about 60 feet tall and 16 feet wide, on a 35-foot stand,
according to Lisa Heep, West Hollywood's planning manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cap will move up and down and liquid is going to bubble
out of the top,'' Heep said.
</P>
<P>
   Acosta would not confirm the sign's details because the company
is still finalizing the design, so the final product could end up
being different.
</P>
<P>
   Boime believes the sign is Marlboro's revenge _ and a way to
reassert its corporate manhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the anti-smoking symbol of the Impotent Man, we now
replace it with this huge phallic symbol of the beer bottle,''
Boime said.
</P>
<P>
   West Hollywood regulations, which encourage creative billboards
on the Sunset Strip, allow the city planning staff to approve them
without public input.
</P>
<P>
   West Hollywood Planning Commissioner John Altschul is appealing
the staff's decision in this case, saying that while he doesn't
object to the content, it deserves a public hearing. In response,
Miller has challenged his right to file an appeal, an issue that
will be heard by the City Council on Monday, according to Heep.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Koretz tried to get the West Hollywood City Council to
pass a ban on alcohol and tobacco billboards on the Strip. He said
he succeeded on the tobacco issue, passing an ordinance that forced
the Marlboro Man to come down only a few weeks before the national
settlement had the same effect.
</P>
<P>
   But there was too much resistance at the time from other council
members and the business community to pass an alcohol ad ban,
Koretz said, and he doubts such an attempt would be successful now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3092 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CHINESE-THEATER-LADN     04-11 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-THEATER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MPAA EYES CHINA MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Carrying Hollywood's hopes to tap into the huge
market in China, the head of the Motion Picture Association of
America said he will urge the Senate on Tuesday to pass a sweeping
trade pact to build theaters and screen 50 films a year there.
</P>
<P>
   MPAA President Jack Valenti said passage of permanent normal
trade relations (PNTR) could quintuple the number of American films
shown to China's 1.2 billion people, cut tariffs and foster joint
development of theaters and distribution ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tremendous opportunities in China,'' said Valenti, who
has been Hollywood's point man in Washington since 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be the losers if we exclude China from full trading
status and let other countries take advantage of those
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing pent-up demand for movie theaters in China, Valenti said
there is now only one screen per 122,000 people, compared with one
for every 8,600 people in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The MPAA's member companies are The Walt Disney Co., Sony
Pictures Entertainment, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, Paramount Pictures,
Twentieth Century Fox Film, Universal Studios and Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti will make his pitch Tuesday before the Senate Commerce
Committee, chaired by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. The pact has wide
bipartisan support in the Senate, but faces an uncertain future in
the House.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to affecting the movie industry, the measure would
give China the same low-tariff access to U.S. markets enjoyed by
nearly all other U.S. trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents include organized labor and human rights activists who
want the United States to continue to review China's trade status
annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an irrevocable step,'' said Thea Lee, assistant
director of public policy for the AFL-CIO in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we give China PNTR, we can't turn around and change our
mind or take action if China violates agreements or workers'
rights. We need to withhold PNTR and keep the current system. It
gives us more flexibility and leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valenti said China's vast potential for growth and profits
presents tremendous financial opportunity for Hollywood, which
depends on foreign operations for 48 percent of its revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, movie makers and studios received only $20 million
from operations in China, he said. By comparison, the U.S. box
office took in a record $7.5 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's tentative China deals include an increase in the
annual quota on foreign films from 10 to 50 over three years.
China's quota has been frozen at 10 since 1995, a year after ``The
Fugitive'' became the first U.S. movie legally shown in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. film producers have averaged eight films per year under the
quota.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have also tentatively agreed to permit foreign
investment and profit sharing in joint video distribution ventures
and to lift their ban on cinema ownership. American and other
foreign firms would be allowed to own up to 49 percent of companies
that build, own or operate movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Also, China would lower tariffs on films from 9 percent to 5
percent and the tariff on home videos from 15 percent to 10
percent. It would also agree to step up its crackdown on video
piracy and other copyright violations.
</P>
<P>
   China has agreed to the pact, which was announced in November by
U.S. trade envoys, contingent on congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The House has scheduled a May 22 vote on the measure, which is
backed by the Clinton administration and business interests. The
Senate has not yet scheduled its vote.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few Southland House and Senate members have announced
their stands on the China trade issue.
</P>
<P>
   Solid supporters of giving PNTR to China include Sen. Dianne
Feinstein and Rep. David Dreier, R-Covina. Reps. Howard P. ``Buck''
McKeon, R-Santa Clarita; James Rogan, R-Pasadena; and Jerry Lewis,
R-Redlands; have said they are leaning toward a yes vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Baca, D-Rialto, has weighed in with a no vote, arguing
that PNTR will hurt American workers by exporting more jobs
overseas. Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills, is also opposed to
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Undecided lawmakers include Sen. Barbara Boxer, and Reps. Grace
Napolitano, D-Montebello; and Stephen Horn, R-Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti, who has made four trips to China in the past two years
to work on copyright issues, said Chinese officials ``fulfilled all
the pledges they made'' to fight piracy, including the permanent
shutdown of 79 pirate video plants since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO's Lee is less enthusiastic about China's record and
argues that granting PNTR will send the wrong message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be saying that all of past flouting of the rules was
acceptable, that all the repression of trade unions and workers'
rights and the piracy was OK,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 0115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3093 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-CHINESE-THEATER-LADN     04-11 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-THEATER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MPAA EYES CHINA MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
