   Last year, movie makers and studios received only $20 million
from operations in China, he said. By comparison, the U.S. box
office took in a record $7.5 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's tentative China deals include an increase in the
annual quota on foreign films from 10 to 50 over three years.
China's quota has been frozen at 10 since 1995, a year after ``The
Fugitive'' became the first U.S. movie legally shown in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. film producers have averaged eight films per year under the
quota.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have also tentatively agreed to permit foreign
investment and profit sharing in joint video distribution ventures
and to lift their ban on cinema ownership. American and other
foreign firms would be allowed to own up to 49 percent of companies
that build, own or operate movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Also, China would lower tariffs on films from 9 percent to 5
percent and the tariff on home videos from 15 percent to 10
percent. It would also agree to step up its crackdown on video
piracy and other copyright violations.
</P>
<P>
   China has agreed to the pact, which was announced in November by
U.S. trade envoys, contingent on congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The House has scheduled a May 22 vote on the measure, which is
backed by the Clinton administration and business interests. The
Senate has not yet scheduled its vote.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few Southland House and Senate members have announced
their stands on the China trade issue.
</P>
<P>
   Solid supporters of giving PNTR to China include Sen. Dianne
Feinstein and Rep. David Dreier, R-Covina. Reps. Howard P. ``Buck''
McKeon, R-Santa Clarita; James Rogan, R-Pasadena; and Jerry Lewis,
R-Redlands; have said they are leaning toward a yes vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Baca, D-Rialto, has weighed in with a no vote, arguing
that PNTR will hurt American workers by exporting more jobs
overseas. Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills, is also opposed to
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Undecided lawmakers include Sen. Barbara Boxer, and Reps. Grace
Napolitano, D-Montebello; and Stephen Horn, R-Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti, who has made four trips to China in the past two years
to work on copyright issues, said Chinese officials ``fulfilled all
the pledges they made'' to fight piracy, including the permanent
shutdown of 79 pirate video plants since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO's Lee is less enthusiastic about China's record and
argues that granting PNTR will send the wrong message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be saying that all of past flouting of the rules was
acceptable, that all the repression of trade unions and workers'
rights and the piracy was OK,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
