<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, April 11.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-SHOCK-TV (Hilversum, the Netherlands) _ Oprah Winfrey
dropped out of shock television long ago. Maury Povich migrated
from audience shoutfests to the million-dollar-quiz biz. Even Fox
TV was shaken enough by the fallout from ``Who Wants to Marry a
Millionaire?'' to quash a plan to crash a jet into the desert for
prime time entertainment. But the European producer John de Mol is
serenely undeterred. Witness his latest brainstorm, ``Chains of
Love,'' a post-millenial evolution of ``The Dating Game'' in which
contestants compete for a date while chained together for up to
five days in handcuffs and ankle irons. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-LAND (Chegutu, Zimbabwe) _ About 4,500 white farmers
own more than half of Zimbabwe's fertile farms, including more than
2 million acres of fallow land that Western donors agree could be
better used by peasant farmers. But despite repeated threats over
the past 20 years, the government has never seized any property
without paying for it, land experts and commercial farmers say. By
Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NEIGHBORHOODS (Shenyang, China) _ For urban Chinese who
are middle-aged and beyond, the old ``neighborhood committees''
that watched over every household are among the more obnoxious
memories of the early decades of Communist rule. Staffed, as lore
has it, by one's nosiest neighbors, the committees were empowered
to scrutinize every visitor, report every antisocial activity and
even monitor pregnancies. On the more positive side, they also
sorted out neighborly disputes, watched out for burglars or fallen
power lines, and sometimes even ran convenient food shops. Over the
last 20 years, with the decline of Marxist fervor and the emergence
of a more diverse society, the committees waned but they never
quite disappeared. Now, with experiments here and 19 other cities,
the government is trying to reinvent this venerable institution,
replacing the legendary ``seven grannies with eight teeth between
them'' with more professional, somewhat younger staffs that can
link up citizens up with vital social services. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-SECURITY (Washington) _ A law enforcement armada from a
half-dozen city and federal agencies is preparing for mass rallies
here this week as organizers try to extend the protest against
global economics that plunged Seattle into violent street
confrontations in November. City officials are emphasizing the
city's openness to peaceful protest while also preparing for the
civil disobedience that some demonstrators have threatened as they
vow to disrupt meetings of the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS-III (Salt Lake City) _ Of the 100 episodes of
rampage killings examined for this series by The New York Times,
none better illustrates than the case of Lisa Duy just how
difficult it can be to enforce a key provision of the nation's
fundamental gun control law. That provision prohibits people who
have been involuntarily committed to mental institutions from
buying a handgun. But laws in most states guard the privacy of the
mentally ill, so gun background checks typically fail to turn up
mental health histories. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOBBY (Albany, N.Y.) _ In flush times, the Legislature has
become a leaner place, and partisan politics is only partly to
blame. Stung by embarrassing revelations that Philip Morris treated
scores of lawmakers last year, and then underreported the expense,
the Republican-controlled Senate adopted a voluntary ban on free
meals with lobbyists and gifts over $25. The Democratic-led
assembly refused to go along, although 10 of its members have
individually pledged to abide by the ban. Now the shrinking
waistlines are just one indication that a deeply entrenched
lobbying culture has begun to change. By Winnie Hu.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED-STUDENTS (Undated) _ Mark Breimhorst cannot take tests
the way other students do: He has no hands. So when he was applying
to business schools in 1998, Breimhorst received permission from
the Educational Testing Service to take the Graduate Management
Admissions Test on a computer with a trackball, and was given 25
percent more time to accommodate his disability. Under the
longstanding policy of the testing service, his results were mailed
out with the notation, ``Scores Obtained Under Special
Conditions.'' Breimhorst, a 29-year-old graduate of Stanford
University, was not admitted to business school. Now, in a federal
lawsuit that could affect hundreds of thousands of students with
disabilities, he is challenging the way the testing service flags
the scores of students who use accommodations to take the exams.
The lawsuit asserts that such flagging is a kind of scarlet letter.
By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BUSH-HEALTH (Undated) _ Texas has had one of the nation's
worst public health records for decades. More than a quarter of its
citizens have no health insurance. The state ranks near the top in
the nation in rates of AIDS, diabetes, tuberculosis and teen-age
pregnancy, and near the bottom in immunizations, mammograms and
access to physicians. But since George W. Bush became governor in
1995, he has not made health a priority, his aides acknowledge. He
has never made a speech on the subject, his press office says. But
with health care near the top of the election agenda, Bush _
starting on Tuesday with a speech in Cleveland _ will begin
discussing insurance and other health issues. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-PLANE-CRASH _ The V-22 Osprey is a classic case of a
military program that wouldn't be stopped. The crash of an Osprey
on Saturday night in Arizona, which killed 19 Marines, came after
years of arguments inside the Pentagon against building it, and
years of dogged efforts by Congress to protect the $37 billion
program. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LOBBY (Washington) _ How Microsoft is lobbying to
improve its image in the wake of a judge's ruling that it has
violated antitrust laws. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES-ADS (Undated) _ The magazines that are doing well have
never had it so good. Magazines like In Style, Vogue, Vanity Fair
and W are so packed with advertisements that they blowing past
their records for size, heft and length. They are part of a growing
breed: the obese magazine, publications so fat that if they were
people, they ought to be in a high school auditorium sweating to
the oldies with Richard Simmons. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo cilents. Graphics
have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   STANLEY-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The Stanley Works may tell
investors about the need to be patient, but the company's chief
executive appears to have failed to heed the same advice. Three
years after John M. Trani, a rising star at General Electric, took
over as chief executive of Stanley Works, investors are still
looking for some of the GE management magic. For his efforts,
though, Trani pulled a sizable pay increase out of his company last
year. Trani, who had an impressive performance at GE's medical
systems division, was greeted with much enthusiasm when he took
over Stanley at the end of 1996. But the much-anticipated revival
has yet to take place. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   IRIDIUM (Chicago) _ In the coming months, Iridium LLC, the
bankrupt global satellite telephone company, will begin sending 88
giant satellites spiraling toward Earth, where they will burn up in
a fitting and fiery end to one of the colossal corporate failures
in recent memory. After spending more than $5 billion on a system
that promised to communicate ``with anyone, anytime, virtually
anywhere in the world,'' Iridium could muster only about 55,000
subscribers, not enough even to pay interest on its start-up costs.
By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HIGHTECH-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ As 3Com makes plans to become a
much smaller networking solutions company, shedding several
slower-growing operations, executives have decided to change
agencies. The San Francisco office of FCB Worldwide, which has
handled the 3Com account since the company consolidated agencies in
October 1997, is losing the assignment, effective on July 1, to the
New York office of Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners. FCB San Francisco will
continue as the agency for the Palm computing unit, which is being
spun out of 3Com. The 3Com shift is indicative of the ferment among
high-technology marketers as competition intensifies in that
fast-moving, free-spending category. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROME-EXHIBIT (Philadelphia) _ Imagine a city where Jacques-Louis
David insisted on working to execute a momentous commission from
the French king; where a 21-year-old aspiring artist from
Philadelphia named Benjamin West was taken to meet the pope; where
Fragonard, Piranesi, Anton Raphael Mengs, Antonio Canova, Angelika
Kauffmann and Jean-Antoine Houdon all lived, dined, traded ideas
and drank coffee together. That was Rome in the 18th century. With
those artists and others of many nationalities studying, working,
competing and cross-pollinating, cosmopolitan Rome _ not Paris _
was the cultural capital of Europe. That, at least, is the thesis
of ``The Splendor of 18th-Century Rome,'' a blockbuster exhibition
on view through May 28 at the Philadelphia Museum of Art. By Judith
Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ The Amsterdam Baroque
Orchestra and Choir perform Bach's St. Mark Passion as part of the
Lincoln Center Great Performers Series. Reviewed by Bernard
Holland.
</P>
<P>
   COWARD-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Noel Coward's Suite in Two
Keys'' - Lortell. Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Shakespeare's Kings,''
John Julius Norwich _ the author of a three-volume history of
Byzantium, among other books, and a member of the House of Lords _
sets out to assess just how closely Shakespeare's works correspond
to actual English history. Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FAILSAFE-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Fail Safe.'' Reviewed by Ron
Wertheimer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Bogota, Columbia) _ Thomas L. Friedman argues
that Columbia is a country deserving of U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
Yankee pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre, who has been diagnosed with
bone marrow cancer. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-TIGER-STADIUM (Detroit) _ The new Tiger Stadium opens this
week and Detroit has high hopes for its effect on downtown
development. Some say those hopes are too high.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTEROIDS (Undated) _ Taking cautious baby steps, a robotic
spacecraft is to settle Tuesday into a closer orbit of an asteroid
it has been circling for almost two months. Guided by gentle shoves
from small thruster rockets, the craft, NEAR Shoemaker, is taking
up a circular orbit 62 miles from the center of the asteroid Eros
for more detailed studies. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FRUIT-FLY (Undated) _ The Drosophila fruit fly, whose genome
was just decoded, has attained vast prominence in human affairs
because it is one of the principal model organisms studied by
biologists as a means of understanding the general design of life.
Because of the unity of evolution, the fly's genes and those of
people overlap considerably. Their advocates, who call themselves
fly people, are easily provoked into confessing that they think of
people as large flies that lack wings. By Nichols Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GALAXY-CANNIBALISM (Undated) _ Astronomers have long
suspected that a dark secret about Earth's galaxy, the Milky Way.
They have even seen other galaxies engaging in the macabre behavior
at the core of this secret. But without irrefutable proof,
astronomers refused to admit that it might be commonplace closer to
home. Now, sadly, they have that proof. The Milky Way is a chronic
cannibal. It consumes other galaxies and makes their stars its own.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEPATITIS-C (Washington) _ The discovery of 50-year-old Army
blood samples in helping scientists determine what the best course
of treatment may be for hepatitis C. Now, some contend that
aggressive treatment, which can be painful and cause side effects,
should be used in almost all cases. Other say that the odds of
contracting symptoms of the disease are small and the more moderate
approaches are called for. By Gina Kolata. (1950 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT1) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VA-ARCHEO (Philadelphia) _ With new evidence, archaeologists
have more firmly dated a site in Virginia at 15,900 years, making
it much earlier than sites found on the West Coast and raising the
possibility that first human occupation sites were on East Coast.
It also gives further credence for placing human in the Western
Hemisphere earlier than previously thought. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIG-ICEBERGS (Undated) _ Two mammoth icebergs have broken
off the Antarctic ice cap in the past several weeks, including one
that is the largest in more than four decades. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GORILLA-TECH (Undated) _ Since Dr. Dian Fossey began
studying the mountain gorillas of Rwanda and adjoining countries in
the 1960s, researchers have tracked, with some interruptions, the
fortunes of these engaging creatures in a perpetually endangered
jungle. Now, a collaboration of several American and Rwandan
institutions is taking that program to the edge of high technology,
using remote sensing from satellites and aircraft and electronic
trackers on the ground to create a vastly expanded, instantly
accessible record of the gorillas and their habitat in digital
form. By James Glanz. (1325 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients. Map
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VAROS (Washington) _ Remedios Varo, considered one of the
greatest surrealist painters of the 20th century, is at last
beginning to receive international acclaim, including the
admiration of a cadre not always known for its art house savvy: the
scientific community. In a recent symposium, an expert described
how the artist metaphorically conveyed some of the most
revolutionary and complex scientific theories of the age, from
Einstein's special theory of relativity and Darwin's theory of
evolution by natural selection to the premise that humans are the
stuff of stars. By Natalie Angier (ART ADV: Photos [NYT3,4) have
been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on the
tail of Comet Hyakutake (it's 330 million miles long), e. coli
contamination in cow manure and ways to kill it, and the thornback
ray's method of purging its stomach. By Henry Fountain. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-DIET (Undated) _ Medicare is now undertaking a radical
diet experiment in several centers to determine if critically ill
heart patients can become better by radically altering their diets
and their daily routines under the Dean Ornisch diet. They hope to
determine if they can cut costs for heart procedures through
preventive steps. They also should reveal on a large scale just how
effective the diet, which has its critics, really is. By Barbara
Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BROCKOVITCH-SCIENCE (Undated) _ Reflections column. Many
scientists are offended by the movie ``Erin Brockovitch.'' The
problem, they say, is not that they cannot enjoy a good yarn in
which virtue triumphs over evil and the little guys win. It is a
more subtle: while it is easy to see that the sex and even the
violence in movies are fantasies, it is hard for any but scientists
to discern when science in movies crosses the line from verity to
hyperbole and indoctrination. The end result, some say, is to help
perpetuate misconceptions about scientific evidence and about the
risks of everyday life. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: With
the arrival of spring, allergies are not necessarily inevitable.
Many drugs, old and new, are on the market now and have proved to
be highly effective. Some are grossly underused. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHILDREN-ALONE (Undated) _ Twelve to 14 percent of American
children ages 5 to 12 spend some time home alone after school, a
new study has found, but the period without adult supervision
averages only an hour, most of the children are older, and many
seem to welcome a measure of privacy and independence. The study
also outlines just what the children do when the parents are not
home. By Leslie Berger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: What is the
rationale behind daylight saving time? You can't really ``save''
daylight. By C. Claiborne Ray.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
