<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3104 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-HMO-SUIT-LADN     04-11 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-SUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NET SUED BY DOCTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Health Source Medical Group Inc. on Monday sued
Health Net, one of California's largest health maintenance
organizations, claiming the firm forced physicians to accept low
rates in exchange for their services.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in Los Angeles Superior Court, charges that
Woodland Hills-based Health Net committed a series of fraudulent
and unfair business practices that presented a threat to the
public, doctors and patients.
</P>
<P>
   Health Net is a subsidiary of Foundation Health Systems Inc. and
serves about 2.2 million members in California.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David M. Frisch, president of Health Source, said the suit
alleges that Health Net fraudulently induces health care providers
to deliver services without contracts that comply with regulatory
requirements in California.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks a permanent injunction precluding Health Net
from engaging in the same or similar misconduct toward any health
care providers, restitution to individual doctors and at least $3
million in damages for harm caused Health Source.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't comment on the specifics because we haven't been
served with the suit,'' said Health Net spokeswoman Lisa Kalustian.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, ensuring the health and well being of our members is
always a foremost priority for us,'' Kalustian said. ``It's
regrettable that Health Source has chosen to try and resolve their
difficulties through the court system, rather than discuss them
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn E. Solomon, an attorney with Hooper, Lundy and Bookman in
Los Angeles, which represents Health Source, said he couldn't
comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts don't see much hope for Health Source's case in the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't receive adequate capitation rates, don't do
business with the health maintenance organization,'' said Todd
Richter, an analyst with Bank of America Securities in New York.
``Nobody is forcing them to take that business.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit also alleges that Health Net induced doctors to provide
services to its members at below cost by falsely promising to enter
into an agreement that would make up the below-cost payments
retroactively.
</P>
<P>
   The health care giant is also accused of setting reimbursement
rates at levels that do not adequately compensate physicians for
services provided to Health Net members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inadequate payment rates threaten not only the viability and
continued existence of IPAs, medical groups and health care
providers, they also ultimately will disrupt patient care and
destroy physician-patient relationships,'' said Frisch in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Frisch said the lawsuit alleges Health Net sets pharmacy budgets
at levels that don't adequately reimburse doctors for services
provided and that the HMO withholds access to necessary records so
as to perpetuate their underpayment for services.
</P>
<P>
   ``HMOs are going to have to reimburse health care providers at
level that will cover the costs of the services being provided or
the public eventually will be left with no adequate sources of
health care,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Los Angeles, Health Source is an independent physician
association comprising approximately 300 doctors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
