<HEADER>
A3120 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-L     04-11 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' SCHOENEWEIS WINS BUT DISARCINA ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Scott Schoeneweis was the last pitcher to be
named to the Angels' starting rotation, but he was the club's first
to throw a shutout in nearly two years, blanking the Toronto Blue
Jays on three hits in the Anaheim Angels' 6-0 victory Monday night
before 14,338 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The shutout was the third in the major leagues this season, the
second in the American League. The others were thrown by Arizona's
Randy Johnson and Toronto's David Wells. It was the first
complete-game shutout by an Angels pitcher since Chuck Finley shut
out Tampa Bay on April 17, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Angels was tempered a bit by the
announcement after the game that shortstop Gary DiSarcina was
placed on the 15-day disabled list with a bruised left thumb.
DiSarcina suffered the injury Saturday trying to field a smash by
Boston's Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did all kinds of tests,'' manager Mike Scioscia said.
``It was negative, but you could see some hot spots so you know
it's going to take some time. Knowing DiSarcina, he was going to do
some things to try to manipulate it and end up retarding his
progress. It's tough to get a guy like DiSarcina on the DL; it's
like trying get a bull in a catbox.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels called up infielder Keith Johnson to replace
DiSarcina on the roster, but Benji Gil will be the shortstop until
DiSarcina can return on April 24. The Angels made another roster
move, optioning pitcher Mike Fyhrie to Triple-A Edmonton to make
room for Ramon Ortiz, who will start tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got only seven hits in Monday's game, but that was
enough. Garret Anderson drove in three runs with a double and
sacrifice fly, and Troy Glaus drove in the other three with his
second home run of the season. And it was more than enough for
Schoeneweis, who also won his first start of the season vs. the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis (2-0) did exactly what Scioscia expected him to do
after picking him over the veteran Kent Mercker for the final
rotation spot -- throw his hard sinker, mix in his fastball and
changeup, and get groundballs. Of the 27 outs, 19 came came on
grounders, and four others on strikeouts. The only hits he allowed
were Marty Cordova's fifth-inning single, Homer Bush's sixth-inning
double and Alex Gonzalez's eight-inning infield single.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something he has to bottle, bottle his approach,''
Scioscia said of Schoeneweis, who was making only his second career
major league start. ``He didn't get rattled out there. He showed me
he stayed with his game plan no matter the situation. That's a mark
of a guy developing as a pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Blue Jays came to scoring was a result of
Schoeneweis' first walk of the season. Bush walked to lead off the
fourth, took second on a wild pitch and stole third. With one out,
Bush tried to score from third on a comebacker by Carlos Delgado.
Schoeneweis knocked the ball down, retrieved it and threw Bush out
at the plate. It took a good play by catcher Bengie Molina, who
caught Schoeneweis' low throw and made a swiping tag all in the
same motion.
</P>
<P>
   In Schoeneweis final two spring starts in Arizona, he gave up a
total of 16 runs. But he got the nod over Mercker, despite the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a testament to the confidence they have in me, which I
appreciate,'' Schoeneweis said. ``They want me to keep the ball
down and that's what I've been doing. Keep the ball down and things
will work out. And tonight, the ball was hit to guys ... finally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see the execution of his pitches in the spring,''
Scioscia said. ``You know Arizona. It's tough to say this or that
about the numbers. He had good stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
