<HEADER>
A3121 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ANIMAL-WAYSTATION-LAD     04-11 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-WAYSTATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMAL LOVERS BACK REFUGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DONNA HUFFAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After a state order to close the Wildlife
Waystation, hundreds of callers offered donations and help Monday
to defend it against allegations that it is harming the
environment, workers at the exotic-animals sanctuary said.
</P>
<P>
   The outpouring of support for the internationally renowned
animal-rescue center came while state Department of Fish and Game
officials met with prosecutors for two hours to discuss whether to
file criminal charges that clean-water laws were violated.
</P>
<P>
   No consensus was reached. Prosecutors were shown excerpts of a
videotape that state officials say show violations seen by
inspectors two weeks ago, said District Attorney's Office
spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the videotape shows animal waste washing
into Waystation streams that dump into the Tujunga Wash _ something
that poses a serious health and safety risk to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their chief concern is for the health of the animals and the
public and the 130 people who live on the premises,'' Gibbons said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy District Attorney John Paul Bernardi, head of the
division handling environmental and occupational-safety cases,
plans to meet with the Waystation's lawyer to discuss the tape and
the state order.
</P>
<P>
   The center's founder and director, Martine Colette, said the
Waystation has done nothing wrong, but will work with officials to
correct any problems and continue operating the sanctuary for 1,200
exotic animals.
</P>
<P>
   Fish and Game Department officials ordered the Waystation to
stop giving public tours, reduce its animal population and stop
taking in more animals. Colette said she was overwhelmed by public
support after the order was issued Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outpouring of help and love from the community always
makes you feel wonderful. But I still know the gates are closed,
and dozens of baby animals who need help could die because I can't
help them,'' Colette said.
</P>
<P>
   Most calls Monday came from animal lovers and Waystation members
who want to donate money to help, she said. Several environmental
attorneys offered free legal services, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The state order came after an inspection of all of the cages and
pens that hold the 1,200 lions, tigers, monkeys, owls and other
exotic animals rescued from sites including research laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Waystation workers pick up and dispose of solid waste, but
remnants of excrement and urine are washed out of the cages and
into Little Tujunga stream, state officials said. That pollutes
water and is a violation of the clean-water law, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Colette said workers do not intentionally wash any waste into
the stream, but some might drain there.
</P>
<P>
   Mervin Hee, Fish and Game's regional patrol chief, could not be
reached after Monday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Colette said the closure order could have been avoided and the
Waystation's ``good name spared'' if Fish and Game officials had
told her years ago to alter the way the Waystation cleans its
cages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing business in this manner for 25 years. We live
at the bottom of a valley,'' she said. She said she would work with
Fish and Game officials to adopt an alternate plan for removing
animal waste.
</P>
<P>
   Colette denied allegations by state officials that the
Waystation has a chimpanzee with hepatitis B. As proof, she
presented a certificate from October 1995 that indicates Boee the
chimp is a carrier of hepatitis C but ``he is not a danger to
public health.'' The document says Boee's type of hepatitis is not
excreted in feces or urine, is not airborne and is transmitted only
by blood-to-blood contact.
</P>
<P>
   The Waystation has been rescuing sick or wayward animals since
it opened in 1976 in the hills of the Angeles National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Fish and Game officials have been pressuring the Waystation to
improve cages, some of which are crowded or do not have roofs. But
that has been difficult, Colette said, because the center's annual
budget of $2.5 million is derived exclusively from private
donations and tour fees.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-day inspection two weeks ago, state officials
said they found one-third of the cages adequate, one-third cramped
and one-third in need of drastic change.
</P>
<P>
   Former Waystation employee Fred Perry said Monday that spraying
the animals' pens is called ``blasting the cages.'' Runoff dumps
into the creek, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said the practice has been going on at the Waystation
compound for at least the three years he lived there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3122 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-PACBELL-LADN     04-11 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PACBELL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE BEAUTY BY THE BAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They officially open Pacific Bell Park today,
and know this right off: There will be no swimming dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area types will be able to contain their disappointment,
what with the rest of their downtown gem being almost more than
they dared imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly after four different ballot initiatives aimed at
building a publicly financed ballpark were all shot down.
</P>
<P>
   So the team that tried to move to Tampa, that tried to build
stadiums in Santa Clara and San Jose, now gets the latest retro
ballpark, and it was worth all the disappointments and all the
waiting. Maybe not all the cold nights at Candlestick, but The City
is plainly all aflutter over its $319-million, waterfront beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really thrilled,'' said San Francisco Giants executive
vice president Larry Baer. ``We like to think it's Wrigley Field
meets Camden Yards. The tradition and intimacy of Wrigley, and the
modern architectural techniques of Camden Yards. That's our handle
on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken us two decades to try and get a ballpark built.
It's been kind of a crusade.''
</P>
<P>
   Only this one should have employed the Navy. If Pac Bell Park
had anymore of a water theme, it would be docked in Long Beach next
to the old Spruce Goose dome.
</P>
<P>
   The 40,800-seat ballpark is built right to the edge of San
Francisco Bay in the China Basin district. Balls hit over the
right-field wall will actually land in a small channel that
connects to the bay. Since it's a six-foot drop from the concourse
outside the stadium to the water, and with no ladder nor ramp,
there has been a natural concern for the overzealous diving in for
a Barry Bonds home run, only to have to be fished out of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   To remedy this, the Giants are talking of bringing in some dogs,
specially trained to retrieve any balls landing in what has been
nicely renamed McCovey Cove. Alas, for today's 1 p.m. opener
against the Dodgers, the bay has yet to go to the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're still in negotiations with the dogs,'' Giants
spokesman Jim Moorehead said. ``No, my understanding is they're
still in training.''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of an extended spring training for water fetch.
</P>
<P>
   The ballpark was originally scheduled to face downtown. But wind
tests convinced the Giants to aim their diamond away from the city,
though there will still be plenty of wind whipping through the
stadium. This is, after all, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium design now looks familiar to those who have seen new
stadiums spring up in Denver, Cleveland and elsewhere. There is the
brick exterior and walls, the forest green seats and railing, the
luxury suites, the similar light stands. All very tasteful, but no
longer unique.
</P>
<P>
   But what truly sets this ballpark apart is the backdrop, which
from almost any location or level, borders on the spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   The field level gets you extremely close to the action but
offers limited views. The vistas are everywhere else, though. From
the third-base line, there's a view of the bay and the Oakland
hills. From first base, the Bay Bridge and Oakland skyline. From
the upper deck, it's the waterfront and the downtown skyline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's built right on the edge of the water the way no other
ballpark has ever been built,'' Baer said. ``San Francisco is a
city of views and it's only fitting that its team play in a
ballpark filled with views.
</P>
<P>
   ``The architects compared its water setting to the Sidney Opera
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so picturesque, but certainly unique, is the kids section
behind left field.
</P>
<P>
   There, larger than commercial life, is a tilted 80-foot
Coca-Cola bottle. Inside the structure are four slides. To its
right is a three-fingered replica of a 1927 glove. Dubbed the
world's largest baseball mitt, it was designed in Berkeley, built
in Oakland and carried across the bay on a barge. It's 518 feet
from home plate. There is also a 50-by-50-foot diamond that
duplicates Pac Bell Park, designed for those under age 7.
</P>
<P>
   The field itself has its own unique design. It's only 307 feet
down the right-field line, but then there is a 25-foot wall. The
corner disappears from view from those along the first-base side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see some calls that umpires are going to miss already,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Of more concern to Johnson is the multiple surfaces balls can
bounce off in right and the open bullpen just beyond the
right-field line. The bullpen mound is tucked between the field and
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think that's an accident waiting to happen,''
Johnson said. ``It may be closer for the fans, but I don't like it.
I don't like humps or jagged things in ballparks. In right, it
could take any kind of bounce off of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Right field has open archways where fans can watch the game
behind rubber coated fences for free. There is padding along the
bottom of the fence, built beneath brick walls.
</P>
<P>
   Balls will be taking some unexpected bounces.
</P>
<P>
   There is a corner in right-center 421 feet from home plate that
has a yellow line going up the 25-foot wall. Hit one off the wall
to the right of the line, and it's in play. Hit one a couple inches
to the left, and it's a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Above the left-center bleachers is the giant scoreboard,
complete with clock.
</P>
<P>
   All and all, a comfortable, attractive and distinctive stadium
built solely for baseball. Something San Francisco has never had
and is completely embracing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is beautiful,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has responded. Baer said they reached their 33,000
season-ticket mark, and have already sold out 77 of their 81 home
games.
</P>
<P>
   To help pay for the ballpark (note to would-be NFL owners in Los
Angeles: It was a privately financed ballpark), the Giants sold
16,000 private-seat licenses to raise $70 million and another $75
million in sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing is a place to park. Pac Bell Park
requires the use of public transportation, since it has only 5,000
parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the city is forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a dream come true,'' Baer said. ``People say San
Francisco isn't a good baseball town. Really, it can be a great
baseball town with a good facility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
