<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS FALL TO SHAQ-LESS LAKERS IN OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Sonics looked for and badly needed a gap, some
type of breakthrough from a funk ill-suited at this point in the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   So call it impeccable timing that they found the Los Angeles
Lakers Monday night with an opening at Staples Center made extra
wide by the absence a 7-foot-1, 330-pound man.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal lounged in street clothes Monday
because of a sprained left ankle. And the Sonics sat in ideal
position to upend the NBA's best team as well kindle a consistent
pulse before the playoffs begin in 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how opportunistic the Sonics with strong
performances from two unusual suspects, they succumbed to the
Lakers in a 106-103 overtime loss.
</P>
<P>
   A check of their cadence after the emotional defeat revealed the
Sonics were a bit limp after a third consecutive defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call Dr. Joyce Brothers,'' center Horace Grant said. ``The
psyche of this team is not good right now. I don't know ... the
(remedy) is to get a win. If the outcome was different, it would
have given us a big lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the eighth-seeded Sonics fell 1{ games behind the idle
Sacramento Kings for seventh place in the Western Conference
playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Sonics, they have been more than a
respectable team on the road. Following a home game Wednesday
against Minnesota, the Sonics play at Dallas Friday and at Houston
Sunday. Then, the Sonics travel to Sacramento for what could be the
most pivotal game this season.
</P>
<P>
   They easily could have turned their mood around Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point, though, happened with about a minute left in
the extra period. With the Sonics trailing 102-100, Lazaro
Borrell's game-tying basket was erased when Ruben Patterson was
called for an offensive foul.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics fell behind 104-100 on a pair of Glen Rice free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen Rice flopped,'' Patterson said. ``It was a bad call.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Sonics went down gunning.
</P>
<P>
   Shammond Williams' 3-pointer gave them life with 10.4 seconds
left. But Lakers forward A.C. Green beat the Sonics down court for
an uncontested dunk. Seattle then ran its final play with 4.7
seconds remaining in the game, but Vernon Maxwell's buzzer-beating
shot fell short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty drained,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``Our
team is drained by (the loss). But that's the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice forced the extra period when his 18-footer fell as time
expired in regulation. Rice caught the ball on the baseline with
1.4 seconds left and launched the game-tying basket over Jelani
McCoy and Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers began that possession with half the 24-second shot
clock. Their final play was rushed because Williams tipped away an
entry pass to Brian Shaw. The ball bounced out of bounds, setting
up Rice's heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' defensive gem was another example of his proven
reliability whenever he's afforded significant playing time. He
finished with a team-high 28 points, which included several clutch
baskets in crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1 NBA sophomore made a pair of free throws that broke
a 92-92 tie with 12.1 seconds left in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal called what the Sonics are experiencing ``buzzard's
luck.'' Despite that, the sparsely-used Borrell and Williams
provided a couple of positive notes. Borrell made a rare appearance
and immediately made himself a factor.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed 73-60 at the start of the fourth quarter when
Williams and Borrell ignited a run. Borrell scored eight points
during a 13-2 run that got the Sonics within 75-73 with 7:28 left
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams made a couple of 3-pointers during that stretch _ one
where the Sonics stunned the Lakers without the help of their
starters. The Sonics outscored the Lakers 34-21 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the starters struggled, Gary Payton finished with 22
points and 12 rebounds. Payton's work on the boards was indicative
of how weak the Sonics' front line was against a Shaq-less Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker fouled out with 3:27 left in the extra period after
again struggling through a lethargic performance. Baker had nine
rebounds but just three points and made only one of eight field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that Los Angeles was without its biggest starter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal missed a second game in a row after sitting out a loss
Sunday to the San Antonio Spurs. He was considered a game-time
decision against the Sonics. But O'Neal never appeared before his
locker before the game. Instead, he laid on a table in the
trainer's room before joining teammates on the court, wearing sky
blue slacks and a matching checkered shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' offense looked dormant without O'Neal taking high
percentage shots in the paint and drawing double teams. A virtually
lock for the MVP award this season, O'Neal's absence allowed the
Sonics to defend the Lakers straight up.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles became a jump-shooting team, and the Sonics did not
allow good looks at the basket. Kobe Bryant had the toughest time
for the Lakers. He missed 10 of his first 12 shots, and the Lakers
shot 28 percent in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics didn't shoot much better. Payton got off to a
3-for-11 start, and his teammates came out just as flat. Still, the
Sonics clung to a 40-39 lead at halftime after shooting 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
