<HEADLINE>
SHAQ GETS MINI-VACATION BECAUSE OF INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A precautionary move to avoid aggravating
Shaquille O'Neal's sore left ankle has turned into a week-long
break for the Los Angeles Lakers' big man.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, O'Neal missed his second straight game with the mild
sprain, and with the Lakers not playing again until Friday night,
he'll have taken off a full eight days between games.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson is confident O'Neal will be back at full
strength by the time the Sacramento Kings arrive. O'Neal hasn't
played or practiced since spraining his ankle at Golden State last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But a gift from the scheduling gods has allowed O'Neal to take
the mini-vacation and only miss two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny how that works out, isn't it?'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal previously nursing a sore hamstring, Jackson said
the Lakers had earlier scoped out this week as a possible time to
rest the MVP candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seattle game obviously was one that looked like it would
be perfecto, because that would give him from Saturday to Friday
(off),'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal could play if needed, but Jackson bristled at the
suggestion that the time off was in part a reward for a long season
of 40-minute games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that a reward? I don't consider that a reward, no,''
Jackson said. ``I don't consider that a reward at all. I think it
behooves a player to play 82 (games). You get paid to play 82, you
play 82, and that's the philosophy I have. And when I played,
that's the way I wanted to play.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal hasn't spoken to reporters since last Wednesday, and he
declined again before Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Through a team spokesman, O'Neal later said he hoped to play
Friday and commented, ``(Trainer) Gary Vitti's doing a great job.
The ankle's making progress, and it feels better.''
</P>
<P>
   Playoff time: If the NHL's Kings - the Lakers' roommate and
landlord - extend their own first-round playoff series to six
games, they will play at home Sunday, April 23. That means the
Lakers probably will be forced to open their first-round series on
Saturday, giving them one less day to practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sunday is obviously better,'' Jackson said, noting the
Lakers close out the regular season with back-to-back games in
Dallas and San Antonio on April 18 and 19. ``If we travel back a
late night after a ballgame, that's a long-flight situation....
You'd certainly like to have a day off before you start practicing.
If you only have one day to prepare for a team, that's not a whole
lot of time or fun. We'd like to have a couple days to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Derek Fisher is playing despite a bone spur in his
left ankle. Robert Horry continues to nurse a pair of sore knees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
