<HEADLINE>
SMOLINSKI EYES QUICK RECOVERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Bryan Smolinski, the second-line center who
suffered an apparent season-ending knee injury nine days ago,
skated Monday and hopes to join the Los Angeles Kings for their
first-round playoff series against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings open Thursday against the Red Wings at Joe Louis
Arena. Smolinski, who tore the medial collateral ligament in his
right knee in a collision with Phoenix's Travis Green, will be
fitted for a brace, but coach Andy Murray isn't certain he will see
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still a very serious injury,'' Murray said. ``There is a
very good chance he won't play. But he skated today and we'll see
what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski, tied for fourth on the club with 58 points, was given
a four-to-six week recovery time after an MRI revealed the torn
MCL, the ligament that stabilizes the sides of the knee.
</P>
<P>
   Since Smolinski was injured during the final week of the regular
season, he wasn't expected to return in time for the playoffs. The
Kings also are without winger Nelson Emerson, who has a fractured
left index finger that will be in a splint for another week.
</P>
<P>
   Team doctors ruled out surgery for Smolinski but didn't expect
him back until training camp. But head trainer Pete Demers noticed
the knee did not swell up overnight after the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a first sign the situation might be a little
better,'' he said. ``They don't do surgery on the MCL much anymore.
It seems to heal well on its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy returns: Right wing Ziggy Palffy, who has missed almost a
month with a sprained right shoulder, continued to work out Monday
and says he will be ready to go Thursday night against the Red
Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is much stronger and the extra five days off will help even
more,'' said Palffy, who was the Kings' leading scorer at the time
of the March 15 injury. ``This is my first playoff and I am very
excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: Defenseman Jaroslav Modry, who played well
during scratches to Aki Berg and injuries to Rob Blake, probably
won't play during the Detroit series. Teams go with three defensive
units. For the Kings, Blake and Mattias Norstrom are the top two.
The other groups are Garry Galley/Sean O'Donnell and Berg and Jere
Karalahti.... The Kings had a team dinner Monday night and were
scheduled to leave for Detroit at 11 this morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
