<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LONGBEACH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN NUNN BACK IN ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The plan - at least the original one -
called for Morris Nunn to sit back on a comfortable couch with his
feet up and a cold drink in his hand while the 2000 CART FedEx
Championship Series was unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven years in racing - as a driver, team owner and the
last eight as the engineer for CART champions Jimmy Vasser, Alex
Zanardi and Juan Montoya at Target/Chip Ganassi Racing - was
enough. He first informed Ganassi of his retirement plans in August
at the CART event in Lexington, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   It was time, the 61-year-old Nunn reasoned, to take it easy.
However, he never found his way to the easy chair.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when the CART season began at the Homestead-Miami
Speedway on March 26, Nunn was in the pits as a team owner watching
promising young Brazilian Tony Kanaan pilot the Hollywood/Reynard
Mercedes for the newly formed Mo Nunn Racing team.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we won the championship with (Montoya) I was done,''
said Nunn, a native of Walsall, England. ``I had my own Formula 1
team in Europe and said I would never do it again unless the
situation was financially sound. Mercedes hasn't been getting very
good results (the last two years), so it was kind of a new
challenge. Suddenly I got motivated because I love a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   There haven't been many racing challenges that Nunn hasn't met.
After 10 years in Formula 1, Nunn joined the Indy Cars in 1984 and
engineered Emerson Fittipaldi's CART championship and Indianapolis
500 victory in 1989 with Patrick Racing. He joined Ganassi Racing
in 1992 and became one of CART's most respected individuals after
engineering the past champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good leader and a great guy,'' Vasser said. ``There's
no doubt in my mind he will build a winning team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunn's first task after forming the team with partners Rod
Campbell and Bruce McCaw was to find a driver. Nunn thought his
first driver would be Helio Castro-Neves, but the young Brazilian
opted to sign with Marlboro Team Penske. Valencia's Bryan Herta,
who left Team Rahal, was a strong possibility at one point and
Kanaan became a candidate after opting to leave Forsythe
Championship Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a better opportunity for me,'' said the
25-year-old Kanaan, who wasn't hired until February and had limited
testing opportunities. ``He is the engineer every driver in the
paddock wants. Call me a freshman at the University of Mo.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kanaan calls himself a freshman, he has shown proven
ability over the past two years to compete with the top drivers. He
was on the pole in last year's Toyota Grand Prix of Long Beach,
started second at Laguna Seca and won the Michigan 500 by holding
off Montoya after race leader Max Papis ran out of fuel two turns
from the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony is a racer,'' Nunn said. ``He's 1,000-percent
concentrated on getting to the front and winning races. I don't
think he had the equipment to be consistently up front in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   No CART team has won its first event, but Kanaan and Mo Nunn
Racing threatened to do that in the season-opening Grand Prix of
Miami on March 26.
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan ran with the leaders much of the day in Miami and was in
front during laps 105-108. However, a pair of pit mistakes kept him
from climbing on the podium, and he had to settle for a respectable
10th place.
</P>
<P>
   What Nunn and Kanaan are sure about, however, is a shared
optimism about what will happen during this weekend's Toyota Grand
Prix of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about it, we have last year's pole-setter and the
engineer who won the race,'' Kanaan said. ``What better combination
could there be?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 0250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
