<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES TEST STARS' RESOLVE TO REPEAT AS CHAMPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Here come your defending Stanley Cup champions,
make of them what you will. And people are trying, really trying,
to figure out just what to make of them.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly as the playoffs open, no one is about to take the
Dallas Stars lightly. They have all that talent, all that
chemistry, all that experience.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's just a tad difficult to proclaim them everyone's fave
to hold aloft another Cup, given their somewhat unique regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a season that saw them stumble out with a major
championship hangover, only to see injuries reduce them to
something decidedly mortal.
</P>
<P>
   Try last place in the Pacific Division on Nov. 28, holding onto
a 9-11-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really concerned whether the group was enjoying the
challenge that was ahead of them,'' said Stars coach Ken Hitchcock.
``I was thinking at times the group felt the challenge might be a
little too big. That once they reached the top of the mountain,
maybe the climb back up wasn't something they wanted to do again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars slowly began to get back to playing their kind of
hockey, though bodies still kept pulling up lame seemingly by the
day. But after that Nov. 28 low, the Stars put together the
second-best record in the league. They went 34-15-5 over their next
54 games and won the division.
</P>
<P>
   Then they ended the season 0-3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, they play when it counts. All year long with the Stars,
there has been a feeling that when it came time to get serious
(read: playoffs), they would be there. Take away the bookends to
their season - and goalie Ed Belfour's friends in hotel security -
and it's still been a marvelous season. And the Stars, too, believe
they will step up come the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hunger will be back,'' said center Mike Modano. ``That
thought of last season will be back in our minds, and wanting to go
through that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Said center Guy Carbonneau: ``I think if you asked the players
around the league, they know what we were missing and what kind of
game we were still playing. I'm sure everybody knows we're going to
be one of the teams to beat in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau knows something about a Stanley Cup champion
struggling to find the fire early the next season. Carbonneau - at
40 the oldest player in the NHL - won Stanley Cups as a member of
the Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   And there, too, it would be hard for the defending champions to
have their game in top form to start the following season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the same thing,'' he said. ``Only I've never seen that
many injuries in one year.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries almost made it easy to disregard their dismal start.
During their championship season last year, the Stars lost only 181
man-games due to injury. This year, they lost 391.
</P>
<P>
   Jere Lehtinen, who's won the Selke Trophy as the NHL's best
defensive forward the past two seasons, missed most of the season
with a fractured ankle. He only returned from his second stint on
the injured list in Sunday's regular-season finale against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Derian Hatcher, their defensive player of the year last season,
top scorer Brett Hull, Joe Nieuwendyk, Grant Marshall - all
significant players - and scores of others were lost for chunks of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Not that those able bodied were exactly fired up about starting
a new campaign. Less than three months after defeating Buffalo for
the Stanley Cup, they were back in training camp. A scrappy team
struggled to find its emotional base.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bit of a hangover,'' Modano said. ``You just don't
have that enthusiasm, that energy, that motivation to get up for
every game in October, November, December. It was tough. And that
first couple of months, everyone was out to get us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody was a little concerned. It could have been a
situation where we just packed it in, and really kind of written
the season off. But somewhere along the line we just kind of pecked
away at our game, pecked away at the standings, and found games to
get points where we shouldn't have been getting points.''
</P>
<P>
   A win here, a healthy body there, an opponent no longer peaked
to defeat the champions, and the Stars began to remember how they
had won the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you've gone around the league once, then you can really
start focusing on your season,'' Carbonneau said. ``Because
everywhere you go, it's new to them. They want to congratulate you,
tell you how good you are. Sometimes it goes to your head and you
forget to work. It's difficult to figure out it's that hard to win
games.''
</P>
<P>
   By midseason they were again one of the league's top teams. This
is still the team of Modano, Hull and Belfour. Nobody was really
buying into that curious start.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a bit of a rocky start for the year with injuries,
but it's also tough when you come off winning the Cup,'' said Ducks
coach Craig Hartsburg. ``It's a pretty short summer to get your
focus back on the next season. Then every team wants to beat you
when you come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're back on track, playing a great defensive game.
They'll be a tough team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs have a way of awakening any dormant emotions, not
that their final 43-29-10 regular-season record is anything to get
sheepish over.
</P>
<P>
   Still, things start to get serious for the Stars on Wednesday
when they host Edmonton in their playoff opener. Ultimately, Dallas
will be judged not by any early struggle with intensity or health,
but by what it does in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what we did last year, it doesn't matter
what we did earlier in the year,'' said defenseman Darryl Sydor.
``We've had a lot of adversity and faced it well, but we still want
to do more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
