<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS' OLAUSSON RETIRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Sunday's 4-3 loss to the Los Angeles Kings
wasn't only the final game of the 1999-2000 season for Fredrik
Olausson, it was the final game of his Anaheim Mighty Ducks and NHL
career.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year old Swedish defenseman said he wants to spend more
time with his wife and three daughters and plans to introduce his
girls to Europe. Oluasson has offers to play in Europe where teams
play only twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   The understated Olausson surprised many with his decision, which
he announced to a selected few players after Sunday's game. Paul
Kariya didn't find out until Monday and Oleg Tverdovsky didn't know
for sure until told by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty big loss,'' said Tverdovsky, who thought
Olausson was either tired or kidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed playing with him, especially on the power play.''
</P>
<P>
   The power play was Olausson's bread and butter the past two
seasons, when he combined for 31 goals and 90 points for the Ducks
after being signed as free agent in August, 1998. Anaheim had the
league's No. 1 power play unit last season, and after an
embarrassingly slow start this season Anaheim featured the best
power play from Feb. 1 through the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to his offensive skills and big slap shot,
Olausson's quiet leadership will be missed, especially by the
team's young defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a guy you love to have on your club,'' said general
manager Pierre Gauthier. ``We will miss him as much as a person as
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He only says something when it was real important,'' said
Tverdovsky, who teamed with Olausson on the points the second half
of the season. ``He is quiet, but he shows it (emotion) when you
needed it the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg called Olausson the team's emotional leader down the
stretch, and the defenseman admitted he was hoping to get one last
playoff run. But he also said now is the time to make a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with my decision,'' he said. ``You never know
how much you are going to miss it six months ... a year from now,
but I've had a great time over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year veteran played with Winnipeg, Edmonton, Anaheim and
Pittsburgh before returning for a second stint with the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Olausson was playing for Winnipeg when Teemu Selanne burst upon
the NHL scene with the Jets in 1992 and the winger said his
teammate's decision caught him offguard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's surprising because he can still play,'' said Selanne, who
Olausson said had already tried to talk him out of his plans.
``It's a shame, what a great guy he is. It's a sad thing. What a
great career he's had and what great memories we have.''
</P>
<P>
   ___In the past week Kariya has taken himself to task for his
performance on the ice as well as his leadership skills. But Monday
it was revealed that the Ducks' captain suffered a broken foot, not
a bruise, when he blocked a shot on Feb. 16 versus Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke his foot again and never told anybody and played
through it,'' said Hartsburg, who admitted the Ducks covered up the
injury. ``He's going to do anything he can to help this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who also broke his foot in the playoffs last season, was
perhaps the NHL's hottest player when he was injured. He scored
five points the night he was hurt and had 20 goals and 34 points in
21 games before sitting out seven games, Feb. 21-March 8.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Kariya struggled when he came back, recording
only three assists in his first five games. However, he got
stronger as the season came to an end, scoring seven goals and 14
points in the last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   __Selanne admitted that his back was sore much of the season,
but refused to use that as a reason for his decline in production.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are absolutely no excuses, everybody has injuries,''
said Selanne, who scored 33 goals and 85 points and finished fifth
in the NHL in scoring this season after scoring 47 goals and 107
points in 1998-99. ``I don't even want to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, who said his back will require some rehab in the
offseason, will be busy in the next few months. Selanne and his
wife, Sirpa, are expecting their third child in five weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
