<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS MAY HAVE THEIR INSPIRATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The talk in the Los Angeles Kings dressing room
Monday was about Bryan Smolinski, but it was hard not to think
about Kirk Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   There are the Michigan State roots, thinning hair and razor
stubble. There is a gimpy knee. And no L.A. team since Gibson's
Dodgers in 1988 has been as big a postseason underdog as this
year's Kings against the mighty Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   But just seven days after an MRI revealed a torn medial
collateral ligament that all but ended his season, Smolinski skated
Monday for Kings coaches and medical personnel. He will be fitted
for a brace and is hoping to play Thursday when the Kings open
their best-of-seven series at Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' Kings coach Andy Murray said. ``I don't really
know if he will be able to play, but we just figured there was no
way. This is a guy who has no quit. The power of the playoffs is
something.''
</P>
<P>
   You might remember, the Dodgers had dropped 10 of 11 to the New
York Mets during the 1988 season but won a seven-game playoff.
Gibson was injured in that series and batted just once in the World
Series against heavily favored Oakland. His home run off Dennis
Eckersley is legendary, and the improbable Dodgers won the title in
five games.
</P>
<P>
   That bit of whimsy aside, the Kings' task is daunting. A healthy
Smolinski would not have swung the momentum the Kings' way.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings finished the season with a 48-23-10 record, which
was second best to St. Louis in the Central Division. It also was
the second-best mark in the NHL. Their 108 points marks the fifth
time in the last seven full seasons that they have reached 100.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those years they won the Stanley Cup, giving coach Scotty
Bowman eight in his illustrious career.
</P>
<P>
   By beating the Mighty Ducks in Sunday's regular-season finale,
the Kings reached 94 points, the fourth-best season in club
history. In two of those three seasons, they went out in the first
round and lost in the second round in the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that never caved in all season, even when it
would have been easy to,'' said Kings winger Ziggy Palffy, who has
missed almost a month with a sprained right shoulder. ``With all
the injuries it would have been easy to say, not this year. But
there is something about this team that is special.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 14 points that separated the two this season and all
the tradition over the years, the Kings went 2-2-1 against the Red
Wings this year. Murray, who has raised the bar for his team by
stressing accountability, idolized Bowman growing up outside
Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bowman, who has been known to intimidate referees, got
a late call that impacted the outcome of their Dec. 10 matchup, the
feisty Murray stormed into the officials dressing room to dispute
the call.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings won the next two meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a position-by-position look at the Red Wings/Kings
series:
</P>
<P>
   CENTER
</P>
<P>
   KINGS: The loss of Bryan Smolinski with a knee injury also
crippled the Kings' depth at the position. Enforcer Ian Laperriere
has moved into Smolinski's spot on the second line. Bob Corkum, a
valuable faceoff man, takes over on the third. Jozef Stumpel,
sidelined much of the first half with injuries, has been
outstanding in the final month, especially with winger Glen Murray.
With Palffy back, Murray heads to the second line.
</P>
<P>
   RED WINGS: Steve Yzerman might be the best two-way player in the
game. He also has 61 playoff goals. He has been bothered by a
sprained right knee, which slowed him at the end of the season.
Second-line center Igor Lirionov had just nine goals, but his 38
assists stabilize a unit that was shaken by injuries all season.
Sergei Fedorov missed 15 games with injuries, but still finished
with 27 goals. Had four game winners in '97 playoffs. ADVANTAGE:
Red Wings
</P>
<P>
   LEFT WING
</P>
<P>
   KINGS: Luc Robitaille led the Kings in goals (36) and points
(74) even though he missed a month with a broken left foot. Kings
leader in playoff games (114) and goals (47). Doesn't need much ice
to create offense, which is critical in playoffs. Because of
Palffy's injury, spent much time on the second line. The same is
true for Craig Johnson, the team's fastest skater, and Jason
Blake. &QL; 
RED WINGS: Brendan Shanahan led the club with 40 goals. The pending
unrestricted free agent was rewarded with a four-year, $26 million
contract that should serve as a morale boost. Vyacheslav Kozlov
missed 11 games with injuries and his 18 goals are the
second-lowest total of his career. Tomas Holmstrom plays with
Fedorov on the third line, which is a scoring unit for Detroit.
Kirk Maltby adds grit. ADVANTAGE: Red Wings
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT WING
</P>
<P>
   KINGS: Ziggy Palffy is a bona fide sniper, but his sprained
right shoulder has not been tested in game conditions. Red Wings
got physical with Palffy during the regular season and that won't
change. Glen Murray matched a career-high with 29 goals, including
the game-winner Sunday in OT. Played extremely well with Stumpel
with Palffy out and the two will work together. Kelly Buchberger
added grit and the occasional goal after coming over from Atlanta.
Nelson Emerson, another part of the deal, is out and will be
missed.
</P>
<P>
   RED WINGS: Pat Verbeek is a 500-goal scorer who was brought in
during the regular season and worked well with Yzerman. This is the
fifth team he has helped take to the playoffs. Darren McCarty
played just 25 games this year due to a persistent groin injury.
Doug Brown played just 50 games and gritty fourth-liner Martin
Lapointe could be moved up to play with Lirionov. ADVANTAGE: Kings
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   KINGS: Captain Rob Blake was a Norris Trophy candidate until
Chris Pronger blew away the field. Blake and Mattias Norstrom
formed an impressive tandem, but the Kings might try Blake with
other defensemen and put Norstrom with rookie Jere Karalahti. Garry
Galley and Sean O'Donnell will remain intact. Aki Berg is the other
defenseman, but the Kings would like to reward Jaraslov Modry for a
strong finish.
</P>
<P>
   RED WINGS: Many think Nicklas Lidstrom passed both Blake and
Pronger as the league's top defenseman. He led the team in assists
(53) and led all NHL defenseman with 73 points, 11 more than
Pronger. But Detroit is holding its breath to see if Chris Chelios
will be ready for the first round. Chelios, second to Pronger with
a plus-48, was injured during the final week of the regular season.
Steve Duchesne rebounded from last year's disaster with the Kings
for 41 points. ADVANTAGE: Red Wings
</P>
<P>
   GOALTENDING
</P>
<P>
   KINGS: The team waited all season for Stephane Fiset and Jamie
Storr to get healthy and be effective at the same time. Now they
have it. Fiset will be the playoff starter. After returning from a
groin injury, he went 5-0-1 and the Kings lost just once in their
last 10 games. Fiset played on Colorado's Stanley Cup winner in
1996, but played only one minute behind Patrick Roy.
</P>
<P>
   RED WINGS: Chris Osgood has been inconsistent this season with a
2.39 goals-against average, although a 30-14-8 record doesn't sound
too bad. Neither do his six shutouts. But he became a Bowman
whipping boy late, probably as a ploy to prove no one is safe.
Don't expected to see Ken Wregget in this series. Slumping or not,
Osgood, with 53 playoff appearances, gets the nod over Fiset.
ADVANTAGE: Red Wings
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL TEAMS
</P>
<P>
   KINGS: Played well on the power play, but never recovered after
injuries to Robitaille and Palffy. Blake was moved back to point on
the power play this season, but his shot lacked consistency in the
second half. Galley and Karalahti picked up some of the slack.
Kings also allowed 12 short-handed goals, second worst in the NHL.
Penalty killing was the third-lowest overall (80 percent), but was
much better on the road.
</P>
<P>
   RED WINGS: Finished third overall with a 19.6 conversion ratio.
Yzerman had 15 goals with the man advantage and Shanahan added 13.
Lidstrom and Fedorov each had four short-handed goals. Red Wings
were fifth in penalty killing (88.5). ADVANTAGE: Red Wings
</P>
<P>
   COACHING
</P>
<P>
   KINGS: Andy Murray is the reason the Kings are the fifth seed in
the West. He took over for fired Larry Robinson this season and
kept the team moving forward when it was buckled by injuries.
Stressed accountability and got it.
</P>
<P>
   RED WINGS: Bowman's eight Stanley Cup rings says it all. He won
five straight with Montreal, but also one with Pittsburgh and two
with Detroit. He is gruff, but also a master motivator who is not
afraid to use negative reinforcement. He also can alter the outcome
of games by fixing his menacing glare on officials. ADVANTAGE: Red
Wings
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
