<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUMPS NOT YET A CONCERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels hitting coach Mickey Hatcher is
faced with his first minicrisis - the early slumps of Mo Vaughn,
Tim Salmon and Garret Anderson. Going into Monday's series opener
against the Blue Jays, Vaughn was hitting .217, Salmon .136 and
Anderson .200. They had just one extra-base hit each.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher, however, says that's no reason to make any drastic
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing with them is the same thing if they were
hot,'' Hatcher said. ``The same program, the same routine. We'll
talk about their swings, watch video ... you don't want them
thinking about their mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Mo's working on a few things. He thinks his
timing's off, so we're doing some drills. Garret's hit some balls
hard, just right at people. Salmon's struggling, but he's working
hard. And he's getting pitched well, nobody's made any mistakes
with him. It's not a time to make major changes or panic. Just
stick with the program and see where it takes them.''
</P>
<P>
   All three say they normally don't start fast, then start to hit
a few weeks into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about it too much,'' Vaughn said. ``We've faced
some tough pitchers, so you just keep taking your trips (to the
plate). It's going to click. Usually it takes me a couple weeks to
where I'm unloading.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon noted that the past two years, he's started fast and
ended up getting injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is a sign that I'll be in the lineup all year,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon has been busy looking at videotape of himself hitting,
some from two or three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at the tapes if for nothing else just to reinforce
that I can hit the ball,'' he said. ``I'm not breaking anything
down. I'm not studying my mechanics. It's just something that when
you're not hitting the ball, it's nice to see yourself getting some
hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz a go: Ramon Ortiz will make his first start of 2000
tonight, a big deal for the club considering the scare he gave them
during spring training. On March 13, just before his scheduled
start against the Cubs in Mesa, Ariz., Ortiz felt tightness in his
right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The next day he was diagnosed with a small tear of the labrum
(tissue) in his right shoulder. The Angels took a cautious
approach, but he has passed every test and is ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy, my arm's feeling good,'' Ortiz said. ``This year my
arm's stronger than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's excited,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ''This guy's a
joy. There's only been one day I haven't seen him smile and that
was the day he was supposed to pitch against the Cubs.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Belcher?: Tim Belcher threw between 45 and 50 pitches
in a simulated game Monday afternoon, but he wasn't as happy as
after his last workout. Belcher waved off reporters who approached
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim wasn't as sharp as he was the other day,'' Scioscia said.
``That happens in rehab. He'll be fine. He wasn't as good as far as
command or crispness of his breaking stuff. But it's not a setback.
Tim at times sets a huge ceiling for himself, as far as what it
should be. His expectations are far greater than what we're looking
for at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said it remains possible that Belcher will begin a
rehab assignment sometime next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
