<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RAMON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING RAMON GETS THE BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There were many times last year when Ramon Martinez
turned to his wife, Doris, and with anguish in his voice asked if
she thought the time had come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I give up?'' he would say.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Martinez knew the depths of the pain her husband felt in
his damaged right shoulder. And the frustration of not even being
able to pick up his children, 5-year-old Doranni or 3-year-old
Kisha, even as they clung to him, waiting to be lifted so they
could cover his face with kisses. She listened, and she encouraged
him to endure.
</P>
<P>
   He appealed to his new teammate, Bret Saberhagen, who knew the
agony of having a shoulder cut open and put back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him many times, `Did you feel this bad?' '' Martinez
said. ``I was shocked. I felt like I didn't want to pitch anymore.
Even grabbing a baseball hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `No, no, keep working, you'll be fine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez went to his brother, Pedro, who knew how much he loved
the game, and how much pride he took in being one of the best, and
how much it worried him that he would never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going through hell,'' he told his younger brother.
``There's so much pain. I'm working so hard and I'm not seeing any
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez, who lionized his older brother, wished he could
take the pain away. But all he could do was try to lift his brother
wih his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do it,'' he said. ``I believe in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Through those long lonely months last summer, as Ramon Martinez
was working his way back to the big leagues by going back to the
lowest rungs of the minor leagues, he leaned on his wife, his new
friend, and his brother. And watching Pedro's brilliance from afar
carried him through his lowest moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about last year,'' he said, ``was watching
Pedro pitch. I felt I was in it. I was excited. It motivated me.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that he made it back in September, pitched
gallantly in the playoffs in October, and now is poised to pitch
the Red Sox' home opener against the Minnesota Twins. He is not
Pedro. He is not the Ramon he once was, the pitcher who struck out
18 Atlanta Braves one night in 1990 or the one who spun a no-hitter
against the Florida Marlins in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But neither should he be judged, he said, on his first start
last week in Seattle, when he gave up seven runs and recorded just
four outs _ the shortest start of his career in which he was not
injured or tuning up for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in baseball know what I am capable of doing,'' he
said Sunday morning in Anaheim, before his brother stopped a
four-game Sox losing streak with a 5-2 win over the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``But some of the fans, they still want to know more about me. I
feel that I don't have anything to prove, but I have to show them
more than my last start, which is the worst game I've had in a
while. I feel bad. I'm so competitive. I get so frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened. It can happen to anybody. But I'm 100 percent
sure that in October, when the season ends, I'll have good
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been three years since Ramon Martinez first tore the
rotator cuff in his right shoulder. He delayed having surgery for
as long as he could, but when he tore it even more the following
spring, he had the operation. That was June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He will be the first to tell you that he is not the same pitcher
who once relied on a fastball that consistently was 93-94 miles per
hour. He's in the 86-88 m.p.h. range now, occasionally touches 90,
and hopes that as his shoulder grows stronger, he'll add another
mile or two. He still has his changeup, one that Pedro says is even
better than his own, and as long as he keeps his pitches down,
Ramon said, he can be effective.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen in Seattle, His pitches were all over the
place. He walked five, and Jay Buhner hit a high changeup into the
next area code. At the time, Martinez refused to blame the weather,
but he said Sunday that, of course, it's harder to get loose in
cool weather once you've had surgery. And there were days in spring
training when he felt soreness in his shoulder. ``But that's only
because we were doing so much throwing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After watching video of his outing and huddling with pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan, Martinez is confident his problems are
correctable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top half of my body, I was rushing a little,'' he said.
``My left shoulder was kind of flying open, mostly in the stretch.
We worked on it (Saturday) it was fine. I have a better idea about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be games I struggle a little bit, but also
some real good games. As long as I'm healthy, I'm sure I will help
this team a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon the Elder said he hoped that Sunday's win by Pedro the
Younger would start a streak. He also knows that because Pedro had
Boston's only two wins during the season-opening six-game trip that
Boston fans will be skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez once worried aloud about how his brother would be
received in Boston. Ramon Martinez said the reception has been
beyond anything he has ever experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it,'' he said. ``It feels nice. It feels tense. Every
pitch you throw counts. A guy gets a base hit, the crowd goes
crazy. Even when they boo, it's because they want so much to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to Nomar (Garciaparra) and I asked him, because
he used to live in LA, if he ever thought about signing with the
Dodgers or Angels. He said, yeah, at first he wanted to play for
the Dodgers _ until he got to Boston and felt this atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dodger fans are kind of quiet. You can be pitching a no-hitter
into the sixth or seventh inning, they start getting excited. In
Boston, it's a lot different. Even in the first inning, it's like a
World Series, especially last year, when I faced the Yankees. It
was unbelievable. It was like you hear everybody screaming, every
single pitch you throw. It was a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, for the moment, comes not from the champion
Yankees, but from the penny-ante Twins. And while Martinez already
shudders about the forecast, there's no place he'd rather be than
on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, ``this is worth all the pain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
