<HEADER>
A3226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-SPEED-BOS &LR;      04-11 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-SPEED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERE-FAST CHIPS ADVANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer chips tend to get faster and more energy efficient as
they get smaller. But it's also harder to make these smaller chips
work properly, which is why a new breakthrough by scientists at IBM
Corp. may soon be emulated throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's laboratories have a strong reputation for developments in
pure science _ the company's researchers have won five Nobel
Prizes. But most of the work at IBM's labs is intended to produce
better and more products. And improving the performance of
microprocessors is a high priority at the company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, IBM scientists figured out a way to use copper instead
of aluminum to create the tiny circuits that connect the millions
of transistors on a microchip. Copper is a much better conductor of
electricity than aluminum, says Bijan Davari, a vice president at
IBM's Semiconductor Research and Development Center in East
Fishkill, N.Y. ``(With) aluminum, the resistance is too high,''
Davari says.
</P>
<P>
   By switching to copper-based chips, each circuit can be made
thinner without losing the ability to carry electrons. In addition,
these smaller chips will run cooler and use less electricity.
</P>
<P>
   But there are miles of these tiny copper circuits on each chip.
Today's circuits are incredibly small _ only 0.18 micron, hundreds
of times thinner than a human hair. Now IBM wants to build chips
with circuits just 0.13 micron wide, and with just 0.1 micron of
space between any two circuits.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a problem. ``When they get that close,'' says Davari,
``they start interacting with each other.'' There's electrical
interference or ``crosstalk'' between the circuits. And that can
cause the chips to become unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   What was needed was a new kind of insulator that could fit in
those 0.1 micron gaps and seal off the circuits from each other.
Davari says that he and his lab mates have developed it. It's not a
glamorous or romantic sort of breakthrough, but it's vital for the
production of powerful chips that consume little electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the chips that drive today's portable devices, like
cell phones and handheld computers. Most of these devices offer
very limited functions, in order to preserve their limited
batteries. There's no way today's Palm Pilot could include a
computer chip powerful enough to recognize and transcribe your
voice, so that you could take notes simply by talking to it.
</P>
<P>
   Davari says that his research will help make it possible to make
chips that are more than powerful enough, and can still be driven
by a small battery. ``It allows you to reduce the power dissipation
by a factor of two, three, four,'' says Davari.
</P>
<P>
   He points to the recent ballyhoo about chips from Advanced Micro
Devices Inc. and Intel Corp. that have speeds as high as one
gigahertz. These superfast chips run in power-gobbling desktop
computers. But Davari says that in a few years, IBM's technology
will lead to the development of equally powerful chips that'll run
for hours in pocket-size devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM has always been one of the leaders in terms of making
these kinds of enhancements,'' says Nathan Brookwood, principal
analyst for the market research firm Insight 64 in Saratoga, Calif.
Other firms are embracing IBM-style copper chips. In the same way,
Brookwook expects that IBM's circuit-insulation ideas will catch on
throughout a chip industry that faces the big challenge of making
its products smaller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
