<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY REVOLUTION IS SHAKING THE IVORY TOWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT WEISMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
Catching up 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Colleges and universities, once slow to change, suddenly are
running on Internet time. High-tech classrooms, visiting
entrepreneurs, and distance-learning programs are commonplace. And
now business school curricula is being refashioned.
</P>
<P>
   MIT was one of the first to embrace electronic commerce. Last
fall, it established an e-Business track at its Sloan School of
Management and a Center for eBusiness(at)MIT to research e-commerce
issues ranging from pricing and profits to digital markets.
</P>
<P>
   Other graduate business schools are similarly grappling with
technology-driven changes, pushed in part by the interests of their
tech-savvy students. More than a dozen US business schools are
overhauling or reshaping their programs and courses to focus on
technology or to integrate it into their overall training.
</P>
<P>
   It's not always an easy transition at leafy campuses where the
new economy can seem remote. But institutions that have long prided
themselves on teaching the tried and true economic and management
philosophies are retooling.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth College's Amos Tuck School, marking its centennial
this year, calls itself the oldest graduate business school in the
world. Next January, it will roll out a new curriculum with
technology at its core. Included will be the Tuck General
Management Forum, requiring every first-year student to craft a
business plan that will incorporate technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't just want to be a repository of tradition,'' said
Philip Anderson, associate professor of business administration,
who will be teaching a technology course to first-year Tuck
students under the new curriculum. ``We want to start our second
century by innovating.''
</P>
<P>
   Within academia, a debate is emerging over how to integrate
technology with business education. Sloan and a few like-minded
schools have designated e-commerce as a separate discipline, at
least for now. Other schools, such as Tuck, are weaving technology
into all management training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't put the Tuck brand on anyone who doesn't have a
fundamental understanding of technology,'' Anderson insisted.
``It's no longer a specialty, something that can be delegated to a
chief technology officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader Tavassoli, director of the e-Business track at Sloan, has
a different take. ``Given the speed of changes, we decided to make
a strong commitment,'' Tavassoli said, though he acknowledged the
e-business track might only be ``a transitional solution for maybe
five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph G. Morone, president of Bentley College, said the school
began offering an Information Age MBA last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus of our entire graduate school, and our entire
institution,'' Morone said, ``is the integration of information
technology into the core business curriculum. Every core field of
business is being transformed by the information age.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tap into Harvard
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to go to Harvard Business School to tap its
intellectual capital. A new portal called HBS Working Knowledge
(www.hbsworkingknowledge.hbs.edu) lets you do it online.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Michalak, executive director of HBS's Baker Library, said
the concept for the Web site came from HBS graduates who wanted
useful and concise information that could help them in their
business lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our alumni were having withdrawal symptoms,'' Michalak said.
``They didn't want to read lots of stuff. They wanted `just enough,
just in time and just what I'm looking for.' ''
</P>
<P>
   HBS Working Knowledge launched for HBS alums last October; it
was opened to the public in December. Michalak said 4,400 people
have registered, about half of them alums.
</P>
<P>
   Among its features are summaries from Harvard Business Review
articles and the HBS Toolkit, a lifetime customer value calculator
for business people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the essence of technology-assisted education,'' said
Judy Uhl, vice president for higher education at HBS Publishing.
``We're using the computer to teach people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
