<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-VISIONARY-ART-     04-11 1641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-VISIONARY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HIGH-TECH VISIONARY LIKES THINGS LOW-KEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Imagine you were a nerdy 14-year-old in Philadelphia in
the 1950s, a science-fair kid enraptured by a gee-whiz book called
``Giant Brains or Machines That Think'' that forecast an astounding
future for computers.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine hanging onto that rapture through high school and
college, not dropping it as an adolescent fantasy, but actually
shaping your career around it, knowing there would be a computer
revolution back when the transistor was the epitome of high
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being Patrick J. McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, soft-spoken, worth billions now, McGovern could be the
archetypal geek. His career, dating to his first job in a one-room
office in Newtonville, Mass. in 1959, has moved seamlessly from the
days of the mainframe behemoths, to the minicomputers of the '70s,
to the PCs and Macs of the '80s, to the Web, handhelds, wireless,
B-to-B, and whatever the sizzle of the next
</P>
<P>
   nanosecond is likely to be.
</P>
<P>
   How did he know way back when that computers were no flash in
the pan?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mainframe era, we identified 140,000 people around the
world who used computers,'' McGovern said in an interview at the
headquarters of his privately held International Data Group. ``We
predicted that based on miniaturization and other factors there
would be one billion users by the year 2000. . . . By the end of
1999 there were 950 million users.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith in that uncannily accurate forecast enabled McGovern to
make his fortune the way the real money was made during the
California gold rush: by selling shovels to the miners.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern owns some of the world's most influential publications,
databases, and trade shows in high tech _ from the annual Macworld
Expo and a dozen others like it to the high-flying weekly Industry
Standard magazine to the hugely popular ``For Dummies'' book series
to a raft of PC and networking journals from Boston to Beijing. In
China alone, his tech magazines make him the biggest foreign
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at 62, McGovern can easily blend into a crowd, even in
Boston where he has been based for 36 years. He does not enjoy the
celebrity status of a Steven Jobs, Bill Gates, or Steve Case. Few
would term him insanely great, outrageously outspoken, or a pirate
of Silicon Valley. He even eschews the techie tie-less look,
favoring straight-ahead business suits, white shirts, and
conservative neckware.
</P>
<P>
   His main interest outside his company is MIT, from which he has
a degree in biophysics and where he is a trustee. McGovern and his
wife, Lore Harp McGovern, recently made headlines by donating a
whopping $350 million to the creation of a McGovern Institute for
Brain Research at MIT. He also quietly supports the Handel &AMP; Haydn
Society, works to promote classical music education in Boston
schools, has offered modest backing to Democrats such as former
governor Michael S. Dukakis, and chips in for various worthy
causes.
</P>
<P>
   But his local profile is low. Howard Foley, president of the
Massachusetts High Technology Council, said he hasn't talked with
McGovern for 10 years, but chalked that up to the global direction
McGovern has taken since making his headquarters in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt he was a couple of chapters ahead of us,'' Foley
said.
</P>
<P>
   While McGovern maintains a home in Hollis, N.H., and another in
the San Francisco area, he really lives in hotels. He logged
400,000 miles and spent 20 weeks on airplanes last year, he said.
Even at IDG headquarters, he can't settle. He works at a standup
desk.
</P>
<P>
   And here's an example of how his companies sell shovels to gold
miners: When Microsoft formally launched Windows 2000 on Feb. 17,
IDG's events division provided the presentation stage at the San
Francisco conference site. The company also launched a publication
for people who deal with the operating system, brought out 15 books
on Windows 2000, developed a special Web site, and then began
gathering data on Windows 2000 usage for sale to industry
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   There's revenue in all of those ventures, said Kelly Conlin,
IDG's CEO. Despite the close relationship with the Redmond, Wash.,
giant and other software powerhouses who advertise with or
otherwise engage the services of IDG, Conlin said, McGovern has
never allowed his publications' editorial independence to be
compromised.
</P>
<P>
   This despite the fact that, as far as can be gleaned from
everyone _ even rivals _ the man's a teddy bear. He is known (don't
groan) as the company's ``chief encouragement officer'' and
universally referred to as plain old ``Pat.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees have good reason to be happy. McGovern has enriched
hundreds of them through an employee stock ownership program. His
far-flung enterprises are all run as virtually independent nations.
He advises and counsels but doesn't micromanage.
</P>
<P>
   He spends most of his time as head cheerleader. Some of this
verges on the shmaltzy. For instance, he writes ``good news notes''
on rainbow-decorated paper to his employees. He personally hands
out bonuses to the 5,000 US staffers, a feat that takes him from
Dec. 1 to Dec. 16 each year. He squires every employee _ there are
another 7,000 IDG workers outside the United States _ to dinner on
his or her 10th anniversary with the company.
</P>
<P>
   His $2.6 billion business could be called Pat's Info Shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``At heart, Pat is a familial figure,'' said John Battelle,
chairman of the Industry Standard, the San Francisco-based Internet
business magazine that has been one of McGovern's recent
Midas-touch creations. ``He loves his company. He is not a
fist-pounding organization man. He is not a temperamental visionary
like Jobs, he is not a hands-on manager like Jack Welsh'' of
General Electric. ``He is his own character.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern acts as an in-house venture capitalist and allows each
of his 120 units the latitude of an independent company. Where he
differs from every other new-age executive is that McGovern has
been letting a thousand flowers bloom since the late '60s _ long,
long before it became popular. Back then, the very model of a
corporation was the central-command approach of a Harold Geneen of
ITT.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1968, I had only been in business for four years and
typically I wanted to stay in charge of everything,'' he said.
``I'd make all the decisions and sign all the checks.''
</P>
<P>
   That couldn't last. McGovern came up with a three-point plan:
Conduct thorough market research; hire a passionate person to run
the new venture; provide assistance, training, funding, and backup
but otherwise stand back. Each time one of his units gets to
200-300 people, he splits it off. That size, he says, is optimum
for growth and accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one case every couple of years where we have to
change a CEO because of bad business performance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of his great recent successes has been IDG Books based in
Foster City, Calif. When McGovern appointed John Kilcullen to run
the unit in 1990, it was publishing uninspired technical manuals
and losing money. Kilcullen said he recalled a friend needing to
learn Microsoft's DOS programming language but being frustrated
because the manuals were too wonky. What he needed, he complained,
was ``DOS for dummies.''
</P>
<P>
   A light bulb went on. Kilcullen brought the ``For Dummies'' idea
to McGovern. There are now more than 400 titles, as far afield as
``Sex for Dummies,'' and 75 million copies in print. IDG Books
Worldwide had revenues of $180 million last year and has acquired
CliffsNotes, Frommer's guides, and the publishing rights to the
Betty Crocker and Weight Watchers brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that in the future the new brands for
education won't be Harvard, Columbia, or Yale,'' Kilcullen says
boldly. ``They'll be `Cliff's College' or `Dummies College.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For years, IDG's chief rival was Ziff Communications, which had
PC Week, a direct rival to McGovern's ComputerWorld. Both were
privately owned companies. Ziff's approach was to concentrate on
the domestic market; IDG went global.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s it was very much like Coke and Pepsi'' between IDG
and Ziff, said Michael Kolowich, former president of ZDNet, an
offspring of Ziff-Davis. ``I'm not sure I really saw the global
synergy'' that McGovern pursued. And McGovern's approach prevailed.
With Bill Ziff's retirement in 1994, the Ziff empire has been been
parceled out.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern himself gives no indication of retiring, though his new
MIT research center will keep him in town more, and a recent public
offering of IDG Books and a planned one for the Industry Standard
may indicate a gradual breakup of IDG as well.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern sees his future linked to the new MIT brain center. It
is an interest, he said, that has remained constant throughout his
career, beginning with that ``Giant Brains'' book written,
coincidently, by computer pioneer Edmund Berkeley, who hired
McGovern for that Newtonville job at a pioneering magazine called
Computers and Automation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sure that there are better ways of presenting
information that will produce better learning, better
communications, and better education,'' he said. ``For instance,
only 15 to 20 percent of the information received by the optic
nerve is being sent back to the visual cortex. A lot of what we are
seeing is sampling, which is why eyewitnesses have different
recollections of what has happened. Perhaps we could improve
that.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rupert Murdoch or Bill Gates started talking about tinkering
with your visual cortex, it would sound chilling. Plain old Pat
just sounds helpful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
