<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ NOSEDIVE A RUDE AWAKENING FOR DOT-COM INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nasdaq nosedive was rude awakening for dot-com investors
</P>
<P>
   Something snapped last week.
</P>
<P>
   The giddiness, the smugness, was gone. Worry crept into the tone
of venture capitalists as they sought to reassure their investors,
to calm the nerves of IPO-hungry entrepreneurs and to pretend they
weren't sobered by the prospect of a cooling stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``One deal blowing up after another,'' grumbled one venture
capital partner, cursing under his breath as he rushed from a phone
conference into a meeting last week. ``This is ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a two-day plunge in the Nasdaq to bring reality back
into focus. The dive, following a few rocky weeks for tech stocks,
knocked some lofty Internet-related shares off their highs by half.
And the ride down came with a bleakness the dot-com world has been
dreading.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech companies on the brink of going public are now
scrambling to keep their plans on target, even as some investment
bankers are urging them to hold off.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, old economy IPOs such as Krispy Kreme Doughnuts and
MetLife zoomed unexpectedly last week, as investors lunged for
companies with track records and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Julian Robertson should have held on a bit longer.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of New York's famed Tiger Management hedge fund is
shutting down his operation because technology stocks have so badly
outrun his preferred playing ground of out-of-favor value stocks
for the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no quick end in sight . . . (to) the bear market in
value stocks,'' Robertson lamented in a March 30 letter to his
investors. He also predicted darkly, ``The current technology,
Internet and telecom craze, fueled by the performance desires of
investors, money managers and even financial buyers, is unwittingly
creating a Ponzi pyramid destined for collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been the battle cry of value folks for some time now.
And it rang hollow until last week.
</P>
<P>
   Now the venture community finds itself at the heart of this
vexing time for investors. Venture firms must balance the demands
of their investors _ who have entrusted them with hundreds of
millions of dollars to invest, at what may be the market's peak _
with their own unbridled optimism and love of new technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen so many good deals,'' says Dan Nova, a
managing general partner with Highland Capital Partners in Boston.
He dismisses the notion that there's too much money chasing too few
deals. But he acknowledges that the smart money is not ignoring the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: If the portfolio managers at places like Fidelity
Investments and big pension funds don't want to buy the stocks the
venture gurus are bringing out, the IPOs will flop.
</P>
<P>
   This environment is going to demand more patience, says Michael
Carusi, a general partner with Advanced Technology Ventures in
Waltham, Mass. Venture firms may have to taper their investments in
new companies, he says. That's because the companies they've
already invested in may need additional rounds of funding if they
can't go public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very careful,'' says Carusi, who with his partners
raised a $400 million fund, ATV's sixth, in January.
</P>
<P>
   How are venture investors, such as pension funds and endowments,
feeling after last week's stock market scare? The experienced ones
seem to be taking it in stride.
</P>
<P>
   Says Scott Henderson, executive director of Massachusetts' $32
billion pension fund for state workers, ``We're long-term investors
in this asset class as in every other asset class.'' The returns in
venture capital have been extraordinary lately, he says, adding,
``But we don't expect them to last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Newer entrants to venture investing may not realize the ups and
downs they're in for. Some have loaded up on venture capital for
the first time ever. Says one Boston venture capitalist of the slew
of newcomers, ``It's amateur time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Putnam Investments' parent, insurance broker Marsh &AMP; McLennan
Cos., is getting deeper into private equity.
</P>
<P>
   MarshMac's Marsh &AMP; McLennan Capital Inc. has launched a
Communications and Information Fund, with the help of another
subsidiary, Mercer Management Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   The fund (size not disclosed) plans to make $5 million to $10
million investments in broadband, wireless and Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam last year bought a 25 percent stake in Thomas H. Lee Co.,
the Boston buyout firm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
