<HEADLINE>
INTERNET WORLD IS A FREE-FOR-ALL FOR CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was the land of the free last week at Internet
World, the semi-annual conference of all things connected with the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   There were free briefcases, free martinis, free long-distance
phone calls, free high-speed Internet access, free legal advice _
even free money.
</P>
<P>
   All this added a frenzied quality to the meanderings of the
40,000 convention goers. They buzzed from booth to booth in search
of giveaways, dragging away giant bags ladened with stuffed
animals, T-shirts, keychains, yo-yos, rubber stress balls,
chocolate malted milk balls, and Chinese ``tranquility'' balls.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't free, it wasn't worth considering. Companies that
came empty-handed sat embarrassingly idle as neighboring booths
bearing gifts were mobbed.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the free-for-all, it would be tempting to conclude that
this collection of tchotchkes would make a telling time capsule of
the Internet Age, where billions of venture-backed marketing
dollars are flung away in a desperate attempt to garner attention.
</P>
<P>
   For the consumer, the goods technically were free. That, of
course, wasn't the case. Take for example, the money booth,
sponsored by Namezero.com, which was also giving away registrations
to Internet domain names, a service that normally costs between $35
and $70 a year per name.
</P>
<P>
   In the money booth, cash blew about while participants flailed
around grabbing as many dollar bills as possible in 20 seconds. The
hourly event made for a good spectacle, and it attracted dozens of
people at each giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for a chance at the money booth, people had to sign
up for a ``free'' domain name and walk around the convention
wearing buttons bearing the company's name and logo. The domain _
say, www.yourname.com _ would be free of annual registration fees
as long as the registrant hosts a banner advertisement on his or
her site.
</P>
<P>
   ``How free is free?'' asked Bobby Orbach, a scout for Techfarm,
a California start-up incubator, who was attending his fifth
Internet World. ``The vast majority of the time, there's always a
catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Another company, FreeDSL.com in Newport Beach, Calif., gave away
high-speed Internet access, a service that typically costs $50 a
month. In exchange, consumers had to put up with ads and allow the
company to track their Internet surfing patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that they're watching you all the time,'' said
Orbach, who noted that many such companies are cropping up
throughout the country. In other words, the bargain often requires
consumers to give up a degree of privacy and grant companies the
possibility of future sales, Orbach said.
</P>
<P>
   FreeRide.com, in its name alone, sums up this new economy ethos.
The New York company awards points to consumers who surf and buy
products through its site. The points can be redeemed for books,
music, movie tickets, and a host of other items.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, gimmicky giveaways have existed for as long as
technology conventions have been around. But the unprecedented flow
of venture capital money into Internet companies has raised the
stakes and given companies free reign to promote their products and
services. The result is a one-upmanship that prompts companies to
be ever more flashy in their freebies, say those who have attended
such conventions for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies are going to spend most of their money on
marketing. And that means pens, billboards, booze, and just about
anything that gets attention over the noise level, because the
noise level right now is very high,'' said John C. Dvorak, a
technology columnist and veteran convention goer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether companies get their money's worth is anyone's guess,
particularly when all the free gizmos start to look alike and
consumers get better at glazing over the company logos on their
mugs and pens.
</P>
<P>
   Said Dvorkak: ``The fact is, most of these companies are not
very memorable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
