<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-OUTLETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP AIMING FOR WEB ACCESS VIA ELECTRICAL OUTLETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A consortium of some of the technology industry's heaviest
hitters was to announce this week an effort that would eventually
allow consumers to connect their appliances to the Internet through
ordinary electrical outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is called HomePlug and is being tested at the
Chelmsford, Mass. laboratories of Cisco Systems Inc. It is being
heralded by its backers as a novel and inexpensive way for
consumers to bring the Internet to the plethora of gadgets
anticipated to flood the average home.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to take advantage of the electrical outlets that
already exist in abundance in virtually every American home rather
than rely on the far fewer numbers of phone jacks or cable outlets
to plug everything from televisions and toasters to stereos and
personal computers to the Internet. Once plugged in, the devices
will also ``talk'' to one another, so consumers, for example, can
turn on the coffee maker with their PC.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the premier technology for home
networking,'' said Philip Hunt, vice president of the HomePlug
Powerline Alliance. The consortium includes Cisco, Compaq, Intel
Corp., 3COM, Advanced MicroDevices Inc., Motorola, Texas
Instruments, Radio Shack, Diamond Multimedia, Intellon, Conexant,
and Enikia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power plugs are ubiquitous,'' Hunt said. ``They're everywhere.
And they're convenient. If you have a power cord on it today, we
can connect it tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Mantovani, president of HomePlug, said the ability to
use existing power lines is especially attractive in countries
outside the United States, where the ratio of phone jacks to
electrical outlets is much lower. In the United States, the average
house has 40 electrical plugs and 3.5 phone jacks. In other
countries, the average is 30 power plugs and 1.5 phone jacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go outside the US, the availability of phone lines
suddenly becomes very limited,'' Mantovani said.
</P>
<P>
   HomePlug will not actually provide Internet service; companies
such as America Online and Bell Atlantic will continue to sell
Internet access. Rather, HomePlug creates a way for multiple
gadgets and computers to share that Internet connection without
having to wire everything to a central modem.
</P>
<P>
   The market for home networking is potentially immense. More than
30 million homes, roughly 30 percent of all US households, will
have more than one computer by the end of the year, Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of homes that network those computers together is
tiny and the number of those that will use electrical plug as a
means to networking those computers is smaller still, according to
estimates from International Data Corp., a technology consulting
firm based in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 4.3 million households are expected to have home
networks, but only a fraction of those homes will rely on power
lines to link their computers, said Schelley Olhava, research
analyst with IDC. Meanwhile, other methods using wireless,
ethernet, and phone technology are more popular forms of bringing
together computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not enthusiastic about power-line technology because
there hasn't been a single standard that all companies can rally
around,'' Olhava said.
</P>
<P>
   HomePlug, the recently formed alliance, acknowledged the
shortcoming and is trying to change that by coming up with a de
facto standard that the entire industry will stick to.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major problems so far is that companies haven't
been talking to each other,'' said Mantovani. ``So there's no
common understanding of how these products should work. But
consumers want interoperability. They want all of their devices to
be compatible. That's going to be our primary focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge facing the group is the aggressive timeline
that it has given itself. HomePlug members say they will agree to a
final set of standards by October and have products on store
shelves by the end of the year or early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very tight schedule,'' acknowledged Mantovani. ``But
we need to work fast in order to have this be adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever technology emerges also has to be ultra-simple if it is
to be accepted by the mass market, said Todd Hanson, senior analyst
at Dataquest in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``True home networking has to be brain-dead simple for the mass
market,'' said Hanson. ``At the same time, it has to be
comprehensive enough for the most sophisticated user. But the
biggest challenge is for them to overcome people's fear of home
networking. The concept is just too scary, too abstract for most
people. They have to present it in terms of the benefits it
provides, like getting Internet access on your television, for
example. Then people will understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
