<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE BECOMES A SAFE HAVEN FOR INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As technology stocks have faltered over the past two weeks,
investors have sought out General Electric Co. the way flood
victims seek out higher ground. As of Monday that flight to safety
made GE the stock with the greatest market value, $523 billion,
surpassing Microsoft and Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   In a tumultous world, GE is an island of stability. The company
always delivers on its earnings forecasts; its top and bottom lines
grow at a double-digit clip every year; its chief executive, Jack
Welch, is far and away the most admired businessman of his
generation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a company you can't help but love. But is it possible to
love GE too much? (Doesn't that sound like the title of a Jerry
Springer episode?) At least a few money managers are starting to
wonder if investors' passion for the company have pushed GE's stock
to unrealistic levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stock has taken on cult status,'' said one Boston money
manager, who asked to speak anonymously, because his firm has a big
position in GE stock. ``There is almost a religious fanaticism
about the confidence people have in the company and Welch.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Black of Delphi Management in Boston, a noted value
investor, calls GE a terrific company whose stock is way
overvalued. ``It's a sacred cow,'' complained Black. ``You're
paying an awful lot for the stock relative to its growth rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Black is referring to the favorite measure of the value
investor: the relationship of the stock price to a company's
long-term growth prospects. Money managers refer to this measure as
PEG, and they arrive at it by taking a stock's price-to-earnings
ratio and dividing it by the company's long-term growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   You got that? It sounds complicated, but it really isn't.
Consider GE, for example. It sells at price-to-earnings ratio of 42
and its earnings are expected to grow at just over 14 percent per
year, according to the analysts who track the company. That gives
GE a PEG of 3. The higher the PEG, the pricier the stock _ that is,
the more you are paying for a certain level of earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The GE ``premium'' pops out when you compare the company to
other blue-chip stocks with similar growth prospects. Financial
stocks offer the best comparison because GE derives about 40
percent of its earnings from its financial services division.
</P>
<P>
   American International Group, a well-respected insurer, has a
PEG of 2.11; State Street Corp. has a PEG of 1.96; American Express
1.70; Citigroup, 1.42. Among blue chips in other fields, Wal-Mart,
with a PEG of 2.94, is one of the few to approach GE territory.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say there are other reasons for concern. GE is heavily
dependent on finance at a time of rising interest rates. Also, its
earnings are pumped up by sales of stakes in Internet companies.
According to Barron's, GE recorded over $300 million in gains from
venture investments in the fourth quarter of last year and another
$400 million in this year's first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there is the succession issue. Welch has
said he will depart next April, leaving some awfully big shoes to
fill.
</P>
<P>
   GE fans, a very large group, says such skepticism is
unwarranted. ``I would say the stock is somewhat undervalued,''
argued Richard Skaggs, a portfolio manager for Loomis Sayles.
Skaggs would not be surprised to see the stock reach $200 a share
by the end of 2001, up from $159.4375 Monday. Nicholas Heyman, an
analyst for Prudential Securites and a well-known GE booster,
recently upped his price target on the stock to $210.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-GE case rests on a few key elements. The first is
reliability. GE always makes its numbers. In uncertain times that
counts for a lot. ``Investors are willing to pay a premium for that
dependable, steady growth,'' said Paul McManus, manager of John
Hancock's Core Equity fund.
</P>
<P>
   The second pillar of support for GE is momentum. The mammoth
company isn't just growingly steadily, it is growing faster.
Revenue growth, which was 14 percent in 1998 and 15 percent last
year, is expected to reach 16 percent this year. ``As we enter the
new millennium, things are starting to explode,'' said Anthony
Forcione, an analyst with State Street Research.
</P>
<P>
   In late March GE said it would exceed Wall Street's target for
first-quarter profits, thanks to a bigger than expected increase in
orders. The stock has risen sharply since then.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Welch. At a session with GE executives last
fall, he said, ``Don't worry about succession because the system is
there. That system is not Jack Welch. It's a system.'' Much of Wall
Street believes just that. They are convinced that Welch has so
recast GE in his image that the company can continue its winning
ways even after he is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Welch is right. Maybe GE is such a great company it is
worth the premium Wall Street has accorded it.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, maybe not. Great companies can be overvalued _
even if they are not technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre (617-929-2918) and Charles Stein (617-929-2922) can
also be reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
