u f BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-11 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA ISSUE IS LITMUS TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The AFL-CIO is targeting some of organized labor's strongest
congressional allies in a major effort to get them to vote against
the proposed bill to grant permanent normal trade relations status
to China.
</P>
<P>
   A series of new television advertisements was recently launched
to pressure certain House and Senate Democrats who may be leaning
toward voting for the bill, which would also scrap Congress's
annual review of China's human rights and trade record. Under the
current process, Congress must decide each year whether to continue
a free trade relationship with China after reviewing China's
progress in human rights and fair trade access to its market.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is strongly backed by President Clinton, who has been a
strong ally of labor, as well as by Vice President Al Gore, who has
been endorsed by the AFL-CIO and the Communications Workers of
America in his bid to succeed Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore, as well as the forthcoming GOP presidential
nominee, Texas Governor George W. Bush, argue that granting
permanent trade status to China will result in more jobs for US
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet organized labor strongly believes that the massive increase
in trade with China under this bill will result in more jobs losses
among American workers and will make life worse for the nation's
working families. The growing trade deficit with China, they
further argue, has already cost hundreds of thousands of US jobs
and lowered the wages of American workers.
</P>
<P>
   The national AFL-CIO's campaign has included Massachusetts
Senator John F. Kerry among its congressional targets, apparently
because he has not yet taken a position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The national ad urges voters to call members of Congress,
including Kerry, and tell them to vote against the China trade bill
and to keep China on probation, in reference to that portion of the
bill that would end Congress's annual review of China's human
rights and trade record.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the AFL-CIO's national campaign has excluded Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy. Some say that despite his vote for the
labor-opposed NAFTA bill earlier this decade, this exclusion was
out of respect for his long and successful labor record that has
virtually elevated him to labor's patron saint in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The state AFL-CIO, however, said it is lobbying Kennedy as well
as Kerry and is heavily lobbying at least three Massachusetts
members of the US House including Representatives Edward J. Markey,
Martin T. Meehan, and Richard E. Neal.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other members of the Massachusetts delegation, the
AFL-CIO views Representatives Joseph Moakley, Barney Frank, James
McGovern, John Tierney, John Olver, Michael Capuano, and William
Delahunt as opposed to the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   The labor organization is particularly focused on Markey,
Meehan, and Neal, for good reason. While the AFL-CIO and other
critics expect the bill to pass the Senate, they see a close vote
in the US House, and they suggest that members of the Massachusetts
delegation could determine the outcome of that vote.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO is aware that the vote of two or three Massachusetts
members could well determine the outcome of the bill in the House.
With organized labor having an influence in the outcome of some
state congressional races in recent years, as some elected House
members can testify, their vote on the permanent trade bill could
determine how much support labor will provide them in future
re-election bids.
</P>
<P>
   What the AFL-CIO is telling them, in effect, is that if they
vote for the permanent trade bill, they are voting against the
state's working families. And these congressmen are likely to be
reminded in future elections of how they voted when they ask
working families to vote for them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
