<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-11 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST OF ALL, JOB-HOPPERS SEEK SATISFACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To her friends, Maura Fitzsimmons is somewhat unusual: The
31-year-old biologist has worked at the Massachusetts Water
Resources Authority for 10 years, longer than many professionals
her age.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends change jobs every four years,'' she said.
``People want top dollar and, depending on what they do, they can
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Job-changing, for some the fastest and surest route to monetary
and career advancement, is a critical problem for employers
confronted with low unemployment and, as a result, a labor
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are bonus-hopping, which means they are staying just
long enough to collect that $5,000 or $10,000 bonus,'' said
Marc(cq) Drizin(cq), vice president of Businesses Alliances at
Walker Information, an Indianapolis research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The US Labor Department reports the length of stay at US
companies among workers ages 25 to 34 has steadily declined,
dropping from three years in 1983 to 2.7 years in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Two trends have contributed to the labor shortage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, US employers saw a 3.5 percent net increase in job
applicants, with the influx of large numbers of college graduates
and women into the work force. By the mid-1990s, however, the
percentage of new employees entering the work force had dropped to
1.2 percent. Low unemployment and a tight labor market are expected
to lower that percentage even further to 0.4 percent by 2012.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happens, we will see for the first time in our
history a net decrease of employees, or less people entering the
work force than are retiring,'' Drizin &UR;  &LR; said. ``So, if we think it
is harder to find and keep people today, just wait. It will get
even tougher, because Americans are having fewer children and we
have a large generation, the boomers, leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Human resource consultants say there are numerous ways to retain
good staff. Some point to the importance of ``soft'' benefits or
traits, what most people call intangibles. Soft traits include
appreciation for a job well done, concern for workers' well-being,
trust in their abilities, honesty, and fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Build those traits into your corporate culture, Drizin said, and
you will be rewarded with greater loyalty and concern for the
company's health and survival. Leave them out, and don't be
surprised when workers turn their backs and march out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bookbinder, a principal at Towers Perrin in Boston, said
that job satisfaction depends largely on the kind of work you do
and where you do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are working at a call center and someone offers 75
cents more per hour at another company, then you just might
leave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many issues here. Learning and development and work
environment are just two of them. The work environment is where
caring and concern and trust come in. But the ability to advance,
or the just the ability to work in different sections of a company,
are also important.''
</P>
<P>
   For some employees, he said, the key questions are:
</P>
<P>
   Does this job guarantee high visibility?
</P>
<P>
   Am I in a place where my work will be seen, where I am more
likely to develop a following, even a name?
</P>
<P>
   Does this job offer career security, as opposed to job security?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other factors that are also becoming incredibly
important to people, (such as) the reputation of the company,''
added Bookbinder. ``Do others think of this particular company as a
good place to work?''
</P>
<P>
   For those in the software industry, job-hopping may have less to
do with ``soft'' benefits and more to do with who is doing the most
interesting, challenging, or innovative work.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who want to be with the best don't think too much about
whether it is a fair and trusting environment,'' noted Bookbinder.
``Dot-com people are more motivated by opportunities that are
linked to pay in various ways. They want an environment that looks
hip. Many of these companies have espresso machines, but, of
course, what it takes to retain people will require much more than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is age.
</P>
<P>
   ``A young person fresh out of college is more willing to put up
with a lot if it means being with the best and being able to
maximize learning and development,'' he said. ``Microsoft never
competed directly with pay or benefits in the beginning. Instead,
it told people, `Look, one day we'll rule the world.' People bought
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Juris(cq) of Hewitt Associates, a benefits consultancy
in Lincolnshire, Ill., said employees today, particularly those
between ages 25 and 34, first look for competitive pay, solid
benefits, and stock options. Then, the softer benefits come into
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salary and benefits must be competitive to draw people, but
once they are earning a competitive salary, people want to feel as
if they make a difference,'' he said. ``They want to feel needed,
trusted, and respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the real world, this would be true of all workplaces,''
Juris added. ``The fact is, at many jobs this is not the case. But
with the job market as competitive as it is, employees now have a
choice, which should be a wake-up call to employers.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, it isn't. Most employers are still operating under
the old paradigm: Throw more money their way and they will stay.
This type of thinking is tripping up some employers, reports the
Hudson Institute and Walker Information.
</P>
<P>
   At a Northeastern University meeting with business leaders and
entrepreneurs last week, representatives from both research firms
reported that less than half of all employees (45 percent) feel a
strong attachment to their organization or believe that it deserves
their loyalty (42 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The findings were gathered in random polls of 2,293 adults
employed at firms with a minimum of 50 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings: Twenty-four percent were committed to their
employers and planned to stay for two years or more; 33 percent
were not committed and planned to leave before the two-year mark;
and 39 percent described themselves as ``trapped,'' meaning they
were not committed but were unable to leave for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to describe the six workplace factors that had the
greatest influence on an employee's commitment, those surveyed
cited fairness, including fair pay; care and concern; satisfaction
with day-to-day activities; an employer who trusts the employees;
knowing the company has a solid reputation; and work and job
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Employers spend far too little time showing staff they care
about their workers' well-being, according to the survey.
Communication and appreciation of new ideas and contributions were
among other factors needing more attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, pay is a satisfier,'' Drizin said. ``If you throw
money at a person, you will get them to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the behaviors you get from employees who are only staying
for the money differ markedly from the behavior of those who stay
for that and other reasons such as fairness, honesty, and
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diane E. Lewis is a member of the Globe staff. She can be
reached at 617-929-2069, by e-mail at work(at)globe.com, or at The
Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
