<HEADER>
A3317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     04-11 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, April 11, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR-INVESTMENTS (San Francisco) _ Three months after it cut
San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown in on a string of red-hot IPOs,
the Morgan Stanley Dean Witter investment bank was chosen to
underwrite a $28 million bond issue for San Francisco International
Airport, The San Francisco Examiner has learned. By CHUCK FINNIE
and LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-PLANE (San Antonio) _ The father of a Marine killed in
last weekend's crash of an MV-22 Osprey said Monday his son
complained two months before the accident that the tilt-rotor craft
was ``fragile'' and unsafe to fly. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   BATS-FARMERS (D'Hanis, Calif.) _ A huge swarm of bats is helping
farmers fight pests. Rodney Sams, an agricultural consultant who
specializes in pest management, says farmers are using fewer
chemicals in one area because the bats are keeping bugs under
control. By CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SECURITY (San Francisco) _ The Internet gold mine is
finally getting the protection it deserves. Equinix Inc., of San
Jose, Calif., is unveiling Silicon Valley's first high-security
``Internet Business Exchange,'' a Fort Knox-like structure that
will house some of the heavy-duty equipment that makes the Net
click. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ Christopher Reich's terrific
debut thriller, ``Numbered Account,'' was on the New York Times
bestseller list for 11 weeks. His post-World War II thriller, ``The
Runner,'' should do even better. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-DIMAGGIO-MEMORIAL (San Francisco) _ San Francisco officials
are ready to play hardball with a Florida lawyer who wants to keep
San Francisco from renaming the North Beach Playground after
baseball great Joe DiMaggio. The move comes despite a demand from
Morris Engelberg, the attorney for DiMaggio's estate, who
threatened to sue to stop the name change. He said a more fitting
tribute to DiMaggio would be to rename the Bay Bridge or San
Francisco International Airport _ not a mere concrete playground _
after him. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WOMEN (San Francisco) _ Parlaying deep-pocketed investors, a
strong television presence and the popularity of the World Cup
champions, a women's professional soccer league plans to begin play
next spring. The Women's United Soccer Association has approved
teams for the San Francisco area and seven other markets: Atlanta,
Boston, New York,
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, Orlando-Tampa, San Diego and Washington. By
CHRISTOPHER ARGYRIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In the coming presidential
election, women hold the key swing votes, and what's the key to
winning those votes? Well, here's a clue. A poll recently found
that women respond positively to anything politicians do ``for the
children.'' Call me a male cynic, but when I hear people say
they're doing it ``for the children'' I look for the adults who are
using children as pawns. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
