<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3319 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK12-COX     04-11 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Income tax return errors can cause you to lose time or money
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There are two kinds of tax bloopers.
</P>
<P>
   One costs you time, because you messed up and the Internal
Revenue Service expects you to straighten out your return.
</P>
<P>
   The other costs you money, because it caused you to miss out on
any number of tax-saving provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a short list of common mistakes. First the ones that cost
you real money if you overlook them or decide to skip the extra
paperwork:
</P>
<P>
   _ Child tax credit. In years past, according to professional tax
preparers, too many people have overlooked this item. It can reduce
a family's tax bill by as much as $500 for each dependent child.
Check the instruction booklet that came with your tax form for
details.
</P>
<P>
   The child or dependent care credit is an additional benefit,
available under some circumstances, to families that paid someone
else to care for children under 13 or adults who can't care for
themselves. Form 2441 has the details.
</P>
<P>
   You can get copies of that and other IRS forms and publications
from IRS offices or on the Internet at www.irs.gov/formspubs
/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   _ Education credits. The Hope credit can be worth up to $1,500
for those with educational expenses. The lifetime learning credit
can reduce taxes by a maximum of $1,000. See Form 8863 for details.
</P>
<P>
   _ Missed deductions. Mortgage interest and charitable gift
deductions are fairly obvious. Medical expenses require more
paperwork but may result in a savings if out-of-pocket spending is
high.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people overlook certain miscellaneous expenses, which
include things like tax preparation fees, job-hunting expenses, the
fee for a safe-deposit box, a variety of work-related expenses and
even gambling losses. Check out Publication 17, which is available
free from the IRS, for details.
</P>
<P>
   _ Interest on student loans. The maximum deduction went up from
$1,000 to $1,500. See the instruction booklet for income
limitations and other details.
</P>
<P>
   _ Excess Social Security withholding. If you had more than one
employer and earned more than $72,600, too much Social Security tax
may have been held back from your paychecks. You're allowed a
credit for the amount of FICA taxes withheld above $4,501.20.
</P>
<P>
   _ Earned-income tax credit. Don't claim it unless you are
certain you are entitled to it. This provision provides credits,
and possibly refunds, to low-income working people. But too many
people have tried to scam the system, and the IRS is watching for
cheaters.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are the fumbles that will make the IRS kick
back your return. Surprisingly, the feds expect at least 8 million
taxpayers to make one or more of these elementary mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   These are mistakes that could slow processing of your return _
and any refund you have coming:
</P>
<P>
   _ Missing signatures. If you're filing jointly, be sure both
spouses sign the return.
</P>
<P>
   _ Missing or incorrect Social Security numbers. Don't forget to
give numbers for your children or other dependents. In 1998,
270,000 people got a child's number wrong. Believe it or not,
160,000 flubbed their own Social Security numbers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mistakes in arithmetic. Double-check each entry, including
addition and subtraction. The IRS checks all returns for math
errors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Illegible handwriting. If the tax collectors can't read it,
they can't process it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Missing information. Make sure you've filled in all the blanks
and that you include all necessary forms and schedules.
</P>
<P>
   _ Incorrect numbers copied from one form or schedule to another.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tax table goofs. Many people copy the wrong line of the tax
tables.
</P>
<P>
   Your fifth-grade teacher was right: Always check your work
before you turn it in.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
