<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Childhood dreams come true in a
chinaberry tree
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Norma Whitney Busby
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   I was seven when I discovered gifts of the chinaberry tree.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1939, and mother and daddy had been left penniless by the
low economic activity of that period.
</P>
<P>
   My grandparents persuaded them to move into their home on a
small farm in rural Georgia until the crunch was over.
</P>
<P>
   It was bitterly cold the morning we drove to that old house.
Gusts of wind whistled through every crack in our battered truck,
and peaks of frosty, reddish clay glistened like crystals along the
bumpy dirt road.
</P>
<P>
   When we finally arrived, daddy wheeled into grandfather's neat
yard and parked beside a strange looking tree.
</P>
<P>
   Mother saw me looking at it. ``It's an umbrella-chinaberry
tree,'' she said. ``Your dad and I sat under it when we courted.''
</P>
<P>
   Its branches, low-hanging and shaped like an umbrella, seemed to
offer shelter against the hardships my parents endured.
</P>
<P>
   We carried our few possessions up the squeaky wooden steps to
the door and knocked. Anxious hands helped us inside.
</P>
<P>
   The room was warmed by hugs and crimson flames dancing in the
fireplace. Grandma lifted me up to snuggle on her aproned lap. We
rocked in her old cane chair so close to the blaze that our legs
glowed from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   At bedtime I skipped barefoot over the cold linoleum floors,
jumped between frigid sheets and snuggled under a hand-stitched
quilt that smelled of moth balls.
</P>
<P>
   A light bulb dangled from the high ceiling, swaying to and fro
and casting shadows on bright papered walls. A picture of Jesus
hung above the mantel.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most beautiful room I had ever seen. At first I was
too excited to sleep. But warmth from the fireplace and a twig from
the chinaberry tree, tapping against a window pane, finally lulled
me to dreamland.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning after a breakfast of hot biscuits and homemade
blackberry jelly, I slipped on a hooded jacket and ran outside to
explore my new home.
</P>
<P>
   I quickly discovered that my grandparents' large yard was ruled
over by a tough old rooster. When he saw me coming he ruffled his
feathers, lowered his beak and began to give chase.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing the front yard, I was able to make a hasty getaway by
pulling myself onto a low branch of the chinaberry tree. That was
the first of its many gifts I would learn of as time passed.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I was in the chinaberry tree, my imagination soared
like a chariot pulled by a white mythical creature, carrying me
into a world where childhood dreams came true.
</P>
<P>
   In spring the chinaberry surrendered clusters of fragrant,
lilac-colored flowers to fashion skirts for stick dolls.
</P>
<P>
   In summer the tree offered shade and a cool place for my family
to sit and sip sweet tea.
</P>
<P>
   In fall the tree gave berries for pretend tea served in tiny
cups made from acorns.
</P>
<P>
   The chinaberry tree inspired my love for birds. I watched them
pluck fruit and nest in its dense growth. I listened to their
melodic twills.
</P>
<P>
   I played in the chinaberry tree all spring, summer and fall. It
was in the chill of winter that Daddy got a job and the time came
for us to move away.
</P>
<P>
   Before we left, I ran to tell the tree goodbye, shoo the rooster
and hug my grandparents. We all wept. It had been a happy year.
</P>
<P>
   Recently my husband Bob and I were in the area. We drove by the
old home place. I had not seen it in years.
</P>
<P>
   It was deserted. Bob stopped the car for a moment so I could
look. But my benefactor, the umbrella-chinaberry tree, was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen,'' I whispered to Bob. ``Did you hear that? A child
laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the wind,'' he scoffed.
</P>
<P>
   We drove off, but I glanced back for one last look. I saw a
faint shadow, plainly in the shape of an umbella. It stretched
gracefully across the untidy yard.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Whitney Busby is a writer living in Rutledge, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(AT)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
