<HEADER>
A3321 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0412-CO     04-11 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0412-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spring cleaning for dummies
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _The house is a shambles. I've ripped it apart
on the pretense of spring cleaning. Now comes the phase where I sit
in the middle of the mess and congratulate myself on having begun
early enough to finish by lilac time. I've made it only once in 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   Today I awoke with the Windex in one hand and a polishing rag in
the other, ready to launch a daybreak attack, but that didn't
happen. Instead, I'm sitting on the office floor among stacks of
old math books - everything from my son's
</P>
<P>
   fifth-grade ``Elementary School Mathematics'' to my own
``College Math for Dummies Who Absolutely Cannot Make It Through
Real Algebra'' text. I'm trying to calculate my body mass.
</P>
<P>
   I never should have stopped for tea, toast, and the morning
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that the Miss Americas are getting skinnier?
According to experts from Johns Hopkins School of Public Health,
based on body mass calculations, most winners of the coveted crown
are now falling into the ``undernourished'' category. Pitiful, my
mama would have called it.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s, contestants had a body mass index in the range now
considered normal _ 20 to 25. Rosemary LaPlanche, the 1941 winner,
was tops at 22.4. The lowest at 16.9 was 1986 winner, Susan Akin.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, I was obsessed. And although I have no desire to
starve myself into a stick figure with Barbie bosoms, I have, for
some obscure reason, determined life will not be worth living if I
cannot figure out how to divide my weight by the square of my
height _ before lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers hold the same combination of fascination and dread for
me that tarantulas do for arachnaphobics _ with one major
difference. The spiders can be avoided by staying out of Texas and
giving up bananas. Numbers, on the
</P>
<P>
   other hand, are inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Body mass index is weight divided by the square of height,''
the article explains. Okay. I ought to be able to do that. My
calculator has one of those squiggly things that means square roots
_ I think. So I try it.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary computations show that I'm in the ``starving to
death but not looking like it'' range at 17.17.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I need ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe I should have converted my height, 5-feet-3, into
inches instead of punching in 5.3. I try again and come up two
index points lower, 15.75.
</P>
<P>
   I am rapidly wasting away.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could be that my calculations need rethinking. Maybe the
height (in inches this time) is supposed to be multiplied by
itself. I try that but run into a problem with the decimal point.
If I move it left, I end up with the body mass of a praying mantis.
Two places to the right and I'd have to be 6-feet-5 to fall back
into the acceptable range.
</P>
<P>
   I call a friend for help. Gail comes down from the ladder where
she's been sorting through volumes for the used book dealer who's
due to arrive at any minute, and reaches into her desk drawer for a
calculator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read me the problem,'' she says and I do.
</P>
<P>
   Number crunching sounds. ``Mmm.'' Punch, punch. ``No! Stupid!
Wrong formula!'' She's talking to herself. ``Height into weight.''
More tapping. Then, ``Aha! Got it! You have a body mass index of
1.98.'' I thank her and suggest she get back
</P>
<P>
   to her books. It's easier than trying to explain.
</P>
<P>
   I think about calling my son at his office, but it might
embarrass him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I could try down at the bank. They're always real nice
about returning my checkbook to reality whenever I've wandered off
into thenever-never-land of debits and credits.
</P>
<P>
   The phone rings. It's Gail again. Says she's got it figured out
now. ``It's weight divided by height squared, times age. Your body
mass is 0.0004771.''
</P>
<P>
   She's worse at this than I am. According to her calculations,
I'm as good as gone. Either way, I decide, it's back to the
dustrag. If I'm going _ I might as well go clean.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
