<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two tykes from Cuba
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ This is how wars get started: You have an
assumption that gets built into a presumption, which becomes a
pretension. Then you have a person, who becomes a personification.
Ultimately it hardly matters that it's a 6-year-old who doesn't
know Che Guevara from Tinky Winky.
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievable, the train of baggage that follows Elian Gonzalez'
every step. What should be a simple custody case has become a
fuse-point for potential street combat, not to mention political
dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's fashionable _ and easy _ to beat up on Attorney
General Janet Reno, she has dealt with this particular embroglio
with clarity.
</P>
<P>
   The oceans may foam with rightful outrage about Fidel Castro.
The questions may linger about what the future holds for the boy
back in his homeland with his father, but Reno is on the mark:
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to start judging parents on the basis of their
political beliefs, we would change the concept of family for the
rest of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno cuts through the foam. This is not about political systems.
This is about prejudging a parent's fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is. And we reserve the right to prejudge.
</P>
<P>
   The other day in the oddest of convergences, the front page of
the Waco Tribune-Herald conveyed the story of two little Cuban
boys. One, of course, was Elian. The other was little Alberto
Melis.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto is not so little any more. He's 51 and Waco's new chief
of police.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago in December he came to Miami with his mother _
on a tourist flight, not a perilous Caribbean trek _ and the family
sought asylum. Ultimately he would become an accomplished Florida
cop, chief of the Lauderhill Police Department and now the Waco
PD's top man.
</P>
<P>
   What's made the Melis appointment newsworthy, aside from the
fact that Waco got a cop with a reputation for community policing,
is that a few people weren't happy that he is Cuban-born. They
certainly don't speak for the city council, which supported him
unanimously, or for most Waco citizens. But I'm imagining their
numbers exceed what the rest of us would wish.
</P>
<P>
   One letter to the editor asserted that only a native is suited
to enforce our laws. ``It really comes down to a thing called
loyalty,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   My own prejudices show through here, but here's a guess. I'll
bet that most of the people who became squeamish about hiring
51-year-old Alberto Melis as Waco police chief are at the same time
gung-ho about keeping 6-year-old Elian here. They'll say that
regardless of any paternal issues, the best place for the boy is
America.
</P>
<P>
   They may well be right, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Melis' family was right when it made its flight from Cuba.
Millions of immigrants were right when they come to these shores
seeking freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, those who judge Gonzalez's father by virtue of his
having stayed in the nation of his birth are trying to jab a rain
cloud with a lance.
</P>
<P>
   And those who judge Alberto Melis' loyalty or ability based on
the nation of his birth are, simply, people looking for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   The title ``American'' isn't necessarily decreed at birth. Quite
often, it is acquired.
</P>
<P>
   The prejudice against Melis begs the question: If Elian were to
stay, would he have every opportunity a native-born child had? To
be a Central Texas police chief, for instance? We should hope.
</P>
<P>
   Something tells me that in some eyes, as soon as his trophy
status wore off, Elian would be ``just another foreigner out to
take an American's job.''
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
