<HEADER>
A3324 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SHARP-DRIVING12-COX     04-11 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't like gas prices? Reduce your usuage
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The good news at the gas pump is that gasoline prices should be
coming down. The best guess as to when is ``by summer.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if summer were declared next Monday, it would be later
than anyone who is currently filling gas tanks would like.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, you can do something to stretch your gas
mileage, short of purchasing a more fuel-efficient vehicle.
Remember, these are baby stretches. Just like a diet, don't expect
to see huge immediate results, but consider the gain over a month
or six weeks. It will add up to a tank of gas, more or less.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you can do is eliminate jackrabbit starts. When
that light turns green, push lightly on your accelerator pedal. You
really don't have to plant your size nine in the carburetor to get
where you are going.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you are going, think about how you are going to stop.
Think about stopping well before you get to the intersection or
stop sign. Instead of jabbing on the brakes at the last minute,
coast to that stopping point.
</P>
<P>
   You may or may not have an onboard computer in your car that
tells you instant gas consumption. If you do, you can check this
for yourself. If you don't, allow me to relate my experience.
</P>
<P>
   I was driving an Audi A8 equipped with a digital readout of
mileage to empty. With a full tank, the gauge read 425 miles. If I
jumped on the accelerator, it dropped immediately to 400 miles.
When I backed off the throttle _ not slowing down but only opening
the throttle part way _ the number began to creep back toward 415
miles. When I took my foot completely off the accelerator and
allowed the car to coast the last couple of hundred feet to the
stopping point, the number went back to 420 miles. This is a
graphic example of what to do with the car's brake and accelerator
pedal to improve overall fuel consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is to just slow down. I know that isn't a popular
concept, but you are kidding yourself if you think the sticker's
fuel-efficiency tests are run at Atlanta interstate speeds.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I have owned a pickup truck equipped with a
454-cubic-inch engine. Drive it over 70 mph, and the only way you
will ever see better than 6 (yes, that's right, 6) mpg is to push
it off a cliff. Drop the speed to 55 mph, and you'll get 8 mpg. It
may not sound like much, but that 2 mpg is a 33 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Going on a long trip? The driver of that 18-wheeler really can
be your good buddy. A big rig punches a big hole in the air. The
air behind that rig is ``soft'' air. It doesn't take as much fuel
to move your vehicle in soft air. I'm not suggesting that you draft
6 feet off the big rig's back bumper. You can travel as far back as
10 car lengths and still reap the benefits of the soft air.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the most straightforward thing you can do is reduce
the amount that you drive. It's easier than you think. Instead of
running to the store every time the notion hits you, plan your
week's errands. Pick up last-minute items on the way home from
work; don't make a special trip later.
</P>
<P>
   With a little forethought, you can reduce your daily fuel usage.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp's column is written exclusively for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
