<HEADER>
A3325 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TESTDRIVE-KIA12-COX     04-11 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-KIA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low-end Kia Sportage offer some offroad capability
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's little, loud and generally viewed as being crude
and underpowered, but the Korean-built Kia Sportage has some
noteworthy pluses, including a strong record in off-road racing.
</P>
<P>
   The Sportage, available in two- and four-wheel drive with two
trim levels, is built to be cheap, but start adding options and the
bottom line can pass the $20,000 mark. The test base Sportage with
part-time four-wheel drive, automatic transmission, AC and CD
player totaled $19,509.
</P>
<P>
   Kia, which has been importing sedans and sport-utilities since
1991, also offers a convertible Sportage base-priced at $14,445.
Like the four-door Sportage, its future is uncertain after the
buyout of Kia by Hyundai.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the four-door Sportage remains a decently
equipped vehicle with specially prepared versions winning class
competitions in the SCORE and Silver State desert races, which
probably have about as much relationship to real-world use as
stock-car races do to daily driving of production cars.
</P>
<P>
   Despite frequent criticism for its lack of sophistication, the
Sportage is regularly referred to as a ``handsome'' vehicle.
Simplicity reigns, with clean body lines and no garish gingerbread
adorning the exterior. The visual appeal does drop inside the
Sportage, though, with the tester sporting lots of gray plastic and
cloth. The effect is not objectionable, but it isn't uplifting,
either. Dull, you might say.
</P>
<P>
   Like classmates such as the Suzuki Vitara and Chevrolet Tracker,
the Sportage does have the plus of maneuverability _ so long as it
is in two-wheel drive. In four-wheel drive, the Sportage binds up
in turns, and the test vehicle developed a groan and creak in the
dash when switched to four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Not all buyers are really going to need the four-wheel-drive
version, but it is relatively easy to shift in and out of
four-wheel drive. Kia uses a center console shift stick, while many
SUVs have push-button systems.
</P>
<P>
   The 2.0-liter, four-cylinder engine is certifiably one of the
noisiest around, but it moves the 3,200-pound Sportage around quite
well once it revs up to the 4,000-rpm range. The noise does not
abate at cruising speed.
</P>
<P>
   The interior has good room for adults and all-around visibility
impeded only slightly by the rear seat headrests and a full-size
spare tire mounted on a swing-away holder on the swing-open rear
door. The 25.8 cubic feet of cargo space can be doubled by folding
down the rear seat, which sits fairly well.
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much can be said of the Sportage overall, too. Kia
set out to make it a low-end vehicle with some off-road capability
and succeeded, although the cost cutting that went on did rob it of
any mechanical or comfort sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 Kia Sportage four-door sport-utility vehicle
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $19,999 (base: $16,295, plus $450 delivery)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 2.0-liter, four-cylinder engine (130 horsepower),
optional four-speed automatic transmission with two-speed transfer
case ($1,000)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: Dual air bags, driver's-knee air bag,
side-impact beams, optional anti-lock brakes ($490)
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: Air conditioning, $900; stereo
radio with CD player, $475; rear wiper, $125; floor mats, $69; roof
rack, $195
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 19 mpg regular unleaded city, 22 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
