<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We can't fix your car as a `class project'
 &HT;    By Nora Roberts
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I often receive letters and even phone calls from readers with
similar questions and concerns about their vehicles. Rather than
address them individually, I thought I would discuss the subjects
in general.
</P>
<P>
   Readers often contact me about having the automotive students
work on their vehicles as ``class projects.''
</P>
<P>
   The state automotive curriculum offers the students a
combination of theory and applied skills in specific areas of the
vehicles. The hands-on lab portions of these classes are limited to
working with training components, vehicles provided by the school
and, occasionally, a student's personal vehicle when the repairs
needed are appropriate to the class being taught at that time.
</P>
<P>
   This method allows the student the experience of real-world
problems while progressing at a regulated pace under the
supervision of an instructor. It maintains a professional
shop/classroom atmosphere without promoting a ``hobby shop''
environment, and it eliminates any element, real or perceived, of
interference with the retail automotive repair industry.
</P>
<P>
   We are in the business of training mechanics/technicians to go
to work in the repair shops around town. It is unwise to cut the
throats of our students' potential employers by competing with
them. No, we do not work on outside vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   I get many questions from do-it-yourselfers about specific
repairs on their vehicles. For instance: ``A shop in town wants to
charge me $200 to put shocks on my 1974 Ranger, but I can buy them
for $4.99 apiece at the local discount parts store. What do I need
to do to put them on in my driveway?'' or ``What kind of tools do I
need to check my 1987 Peugeot's computer system?''
</P>
<P>
   What you need isn't me _ it's automotive repair manuals. That is
where you need to start your search for this kind of information.
Like most serious technicians, I have spent many years and dollars
accumulating these occupants of my personal automotive library
shelves. They are as important to the success of repairing a
vehicle as any of my hand tools. Working without a manual is about
as productive as trying to pound nails with a rock.
</P>
<P>
   Before you decide to use your primary source of transportation
as your next home fix-it victim, do a little research. Most of the
larger discount parts chains catering to the driveway repair crowd
stock a generous selection of repair manuals for sale at reasonable
prices. Buy the one you need for the car you're about to dissect,
and read the section on the repair you want to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time for some honest self-evaluation and unbiased
situation overview. Do you possess the skills, tools and time to do
the job yourself? Without all three, you could end up in a much
worse mess than you started with.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have the time to learn Peugeot computer systems? Are the
$4.99 shocks the same quality as the $200 quote, or will you need
extensive dental work after driving over the first railroad
crossing?
</P>
<P>
   When you throw up your hands or throw down your tools in
frustration, don't expect to get your questions answered by a
competent technician on the other end of a phone line. He or she
doesn't make a living answering questions or giving out free
mechanical advice.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly age-old mechanic/technician terminology surfaced
again from a somewhat less than ardent reader. I looked up some
definitions in a couple of dictionaries.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic (n) 1: manual worker. 2: one who repairs machines or 1:
a workman skilled in making, using or repairing machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Technician (n) 1: a specialist in the technical details of a
subject or occupation. 2: one who has acquired the technique of an
art or other area of specialization.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have a problem or identity crisis with either of these
words. I am both and will wear either badge proudly. There is no
shame in hard work and dirty fingernails, and I continually pay a
technician's dues.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
