<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The demagoguery against the census reached a new
low last week when the U.S. Senate adopted a resolution in effect
telling Americans just to skip any census questions they don't feel
like answering and assuring them they won't be prosecuted, fined or
``in any way harassed by the federal government'' for taking a
hike. That is, the demagoguery reached a new low so far. It is not
clear that the competition is over. (Teepen, Cox News Service.)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ It has become commonplace to gripe about the
census. Invasion of privacy is the most used depiction. Actually,
the census doesn't ask you much that it doesn't already know.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _The house is a shambles. I've
ripped it apart on the pretense of spring cleaning. Now comes the
phase where I sit in the middle of the mess and congratulate myself
on having begun early enough to finish by lilac time. I've made it
only once in 16 years. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _WACO, Texas _ This is how wars get started: You
have an assumption that gets built into a presumption, which
becomes a pretension. Then you have a person, who becomes a
personification. Ultimately it hardly matters that 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez doesn't know Che Guevara from Tinky Winky. (Young, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
