<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3366 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r p BC-FAIRCHILD-PEGGY-NOONA     04-11 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-PEGGY-NOONAN-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH NOONAN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``p'' political news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By SUSAN WATTERS  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Conservative columnist Peggy Noonan, the sweet-talking former
White House speechwriter who gave George Bush his line about ``a
thousand points of light,'' has had her share of first lady
dust-ups. As the only female speechwriter for Ronald Reagan, she
refused requests to write for Nancy Reagan. Later, when she penned
a few gentle words about former Democratic presidents for Barbara
Bush, that first lady never delivered them.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Noonan has always had something nice to say
about America's first ladies _ until now. In her new book, ``The
Case Against Hillary Clinton,'' Noonan throws down the gauntlet,
charging Clinton with everything from ``narcissism'' and
``selfishness'' to ``breathtaking gall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Other presidents and first ladies do their work, leave their
imprint and make a graceful exit,'' she writes. ``But the Clintons
_ they'll stay until the last footlight fizzles and pops, and then
we'll have to wrestle them to the floor of the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the first first lady's run for the U.S. Senate,
Noonan is ready to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of imagine myself with a megaphone saying, `This isn't
good!''' she says, sitting on an overstuffed sofa in her cozy Upper
East Side apartment on opening night of this year's presidential
primary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary Clinton's ambition knows no bounds,'' she continues.
``Her No. 1 priority is to be elected to the Senate. That's her way
of staying in the game. Then she wants to return to the White House
to be the first woman president.''
</P>
<P>
   Noonan got the idea for her book last July while writing one of
her regular columns for the Wall Street Journal, in which she
described Hillary as ``the mad boomer,'' eager to represent a state
``that she had no connection to, no history with and no previously
demonstrated interest in.''
</P>
<P>
   And Noonan acknowledges that Hillary could win: ``She has a
real, serious shot. One can't help but assume she is going through
the awkward days of her campaign now and in the last three or four
months, when it really counts, she will have her sea legs and be
highly functioning as a first-rate candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is helped, Noonan says, by her shameless lack of loyalty
to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If her campaign absorbs money that would otherwise have gone
to Gore, that's fine with her,'' Noonan says. ``She doesn't care
who the presidential nominee is, as long as it's somebody who will
help her numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the spate of recently released Hillary books promising
scandalous new revelations about the controversial first lady,
Noonan's polemic focuses on Clinton's political record and what she
describes as her ``prison matron'' need for government to
``discipline people.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing simply and clearly, she accuses the first couple of
``small-time, tin-horn, me-first gimme-ism'' unworthy of liberal
ideals.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Noonan's obvious antipathy for Clinton _ whom she has
met several times in Washington _ the two women share some common
ground. Each experimented on both sides of the political aisle,
starting at an early age.
</P>
<P>
   Four years before Hillary became a Goldwater girl at her
suburban Chicago high school, 9-year-old Noonan, one of seven
children in an Irish Catholic family, was passing out bumper
stickers for John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my parents' stickers and surreptitiously put them on
the neighbors' cars,'' she recalls. ``Unfortunately, I didn't know
you were supposed to put them on the bumper. And in those days, the
stickers were really sticky.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 27, after graduating from New Jersey's Fairleigh
Dickinson University, she got a job with CBS News radio. Despite
being CBS' token conservative, she spent three years writing for
Dan Rather before leaving to join Reagan's speechwriting shop.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, she divorced her husband and returned with her son to
New York, where she wrote her best-selling political memoir, ``What
I Saw at the Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Noonan has little doubt that George W. Bush will be
the Republican presidential nominee, although she wonders about his
parents' role on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something odd about it when the father says, `Here's
my boy. He'll make a good president,''' she explains. ``When John
Kennedy ran for president, his parents were hidden. Old Joe never
came out of hiding, and we didn't see the old lady until
inauguration night, when she was interviewed wearing the same dress
she'd worn when she was received by the King and Queen of England
in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot to be said for hidden parents,'' Noonan adds,
taking a sip from her ever-present cup of coffee.  &QL; p &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Like her hero, Ronald Reagan, Noonan understands the power of
nostalgia. ``I miss America when it was boring, when you came home
at 5 p.m. to a dinner of mashed potatoes, a little roast beef and
creamed corn out of a can,'' she says with a sigh. ``There was no
self-esteem movement in the old America. Nobody really thought they
deserved a Hermes scarf.'' (She herself likes her neckwear long and
tasseled.)
</P>
<P>
   She also misses the idea of a simpler first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the next first lady can be whoever she wants without
being pushed into an activist role by those who say Hillary Clinton
broke boundaries,'' Noonan says. ``Imagine someone who is happy
with her husband and children, who has her own career and wants to
take on a special issue, such as mental health. In the end, she may
have to fight to be who she wants.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan Watters is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
