<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SHOPPING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: A ROOM WITH A VIEW ... FOR A GOOD PRICE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. ONE COLOR SLIDE, AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE, CAN BE
SENT TO YOU ELECTRONICALLY. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Hotels have become as adept as the airlines at shifting their
prices to suit the marketplace. So when it comes time to shop
around, a single call or a simple visit to a Web site is rarely
enough. It's usually worth calling the hotel directly and visiting
their Web site. Granted, there are times when the prices for the
same room are identical, but there are also times when there are
sharp differences.
 &HT;    For example, there may be incentives for booking through the Web
site. A hotel may be trying to funnel more traffic through its
Internet site and offering a discount for those who do so.
 &HT;    There are also special offers floating around and it's vital to
inquire about them. That's because these offers are not always
targeted at every traveler who's staying at the property. A special
may be aimed at a local market, to beef up weekend stays. It may be
targeted regionally; or nationally. So it always pays to ask _ just
as it always pays to use every additional discount, from those
offered by the American Automobile Association and the American
Association of Retired Persons.
 &HT;    For big city hotels, start with hotel brokers like Quikbook (381
Park Ave. South, New York, N.Y. 10016; 800-789-9887;
www.quikbook.com), Express Reservations (3825 Iris Ave., Boulder,
Colo. 80301; 800-356-1123; www.express-res.com) and Hotel
Reservations Network (8140 Walnut Hill Lane, Suite 800, Dallas,
Texas 75231; 800-96-HOTEL; www.180096hotel.com).
 &HT;    Figure on discounts from 15 percent to 40 percent off published
rates in major U.S. city hotels, based on availability, of course.
Use their maps and descriptions to find a property. Then call the
hotel directly to make sure it is indeed a rock-bottom price.
 &HT;    Unfamiliar with a city? Head to one of the city guides on
Digital City (www.digitalcities.com), which is probably the best
city guide on the Web. It now offers hotel reservations through a
link with Travelocity.com (www.travelocity.com).
 &HT;    Other online agencies, such as Expedia.com (www.expedia.com),
also offer the ability to book hotels online. These rates are
usually subject to some discounting, also referred to as a
``preferred rate.''
 &HT;    If your ideal vacation paradise must include sand and palm
trees, Pleasant Holidays (2404 Townsgate Road, West Lake Village,
Calif. 91361; 800-242-9244; www.2hawaii.com) is a master discounter
known for putting together some of the best-priced
air/hotel/transfer deals to Hawaii and Mexico, utilizing a vast
stock of hotels and condos.
 &HT;    Consumers should also contact airlines like American, Delta and
United or visit their Web sites and peruse the air/hotel/transfer
packages that they market. Their prices are often favorable because
they move so many people.
 &HT;    What's more, there are often short-term sales that might appeal
to the undecided. There might be a fire sale on unsold beach
vacations to Jamaica, Miami or Puerto Rico. Those same airlines'
tour desks also offer vacations, and sales, to Asia, Europe and
Latin America. That can be the best way to get a good rate on a
foreign hotel.
 &HT;    For upscale resorts, such as the Four Seasons and Oberoi chains,
in Asia or the Caribbean, a travel agent can be a godsend. It's
also true for luxury hotels in Europe. But expect to be charged a
fee for such service.
 &HT;    A good agent who's a member of the consortium called Virtuoso
(500 Main St., Suite 500 E, Fort Worth, Texas 76102; 800-401-4274;
www.apitravel.com), formerly known as API Travel Consultants, can
often get travelers an upgrade or other perks. It's not discounting
but value-added service that they provide.
 &HT;    Virtuoso is now partnering with Travelocity.com on a new
``Specialists Referral Network.'' It's fee-based and allows Web
travelers a chance to use the expertise and clout of a Virtuoso
member.
 &HT;    For those who are booking a major chain hotel on their own _
from a Sheraton to a Westin to a Hyatt _ visit their Web site, call
their toll-free number and then call the front desk directly. There
may be a disparity in price.
 &HT;    Sometimes it's the local phone call that yields the best deal.
Why? Because it's the manager's price. He's the one looking at the
advance bookings with an eye to filling his property. An unsold
room provides no revenue.
 &HT;    But it's different with smaller, independently owned hotels or
small, mid-priced chains. Book directly with them or use their Web
sites.
 &HT;    The Web route is a good strategy for those who are taking charge
of a European vacation, for example, and their French or Italian
won't pass muster on an international phone call. Besides, small
European hotels often won't budge from their posted prices.
 &HT;    Small hotels are not subject to the yield management and
consequent multiple prices for the exact same room that major chain
hotels have. The price difference has to do with room size, with
smaller rooms priced accordingly. The price-sensitive traveler
should ask about such rooms.
 &HT;    The bottom line is that with a few calls, some Web browsing and
a little perseverance, every traveler should be able to get the
best possible price on a hotel room.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Everett Potter is a New York City-based free-lance travel
writer.) 
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
