<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3383 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-11 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLITICIANS AND MEDIA: THE GREAT EXPLOITERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the coming presidential election, women hold
the key swing votes, and what's the key to winning those votes?
Well, here's a clue. A poll recently found that women respond
positively to anything politicians do ``for the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this explains why George W. Bush has been hanging out with
little kids in schools and talking like an educrat, or why Al Gore
has been supporting the Miami Cubans who have been acting like
children.
</P>
<P>
   Call me a male cynic, but when I hear people say they're doing
it ``for the children'' I look for the adults who are using
children as pawns.
</P>
<P>
   One word: Elian.
</P>
<P>
   When those wackos in Miami, Al Gore or Fidel Castro, say they're
looking out for the 6-year-old's interests, does anyone believe any
of them? They're just waging political combat on the battlefield of
a little boy's psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Give him back to his dad and let him go home. By the time he
grows up, Castro will be dead, and Elian can make his own decisions
about coming to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Do it for us, the grown-ups who have to listen to the childish
idiocy about Elian all day, every day in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about exploitation of children. Elian has been a major
profit center for CNN and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Doing it for the children will be a major media theme on or
about April 20, the first anniversary of the slaughter at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The media love anniversary stories because they're easy to plan.
And anniversary stories of massacres give them the chance to rerun
all that gruesome footage. If it's kids who were massacred, the
gruesome footage can be rerun in the name of moral lessons and for
society, the schools and the children.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Columbine High School already have been planning
for the anniversary, which they call ``A Time to Remember, A Time
to Hope.'' They even have a copyrighted logo for the event.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, a lot of kids are worried about being overrun by
reporters. Somebody had the bright idea of having kids express
their willingness to be interviewed by wearing buttons saying
``Yes'' or ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   They're doing it for the children. I like Denver columnist
Michael Roberts' suggestion that reporters wear signs on their
press badges saying ``How's my reporting? Call 1-800-JERKWAD.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbine now means more than a flower resembling a flock of
doves. It's a watershed in bloodshed, used in phrases like ``in
post-Columbine America.''
</P>
<P>
   In post-Columbine America, children aren't better or worse off
than they were in pre-Columbine America. But the terms of adult
political debate have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The murders of 12 students and a teacher at Columbine have been
used by politicians on the left to push for gun laws, and
politicians on the right to push for prayer in schools. Politicians
and pundits all across the spectrum blamed the massacre on violent
movies and video games.
</P>
<P>
   The media are still making money off Columbine, and the
politicians are still finding the lessons they wish to find.
Millions are being spent on metal detectors to place at school
doors, even though the likelihood of being shot in school is about
the same as being hit by lightning on a sunny day.
</P>
<P>
   CNN reports on its Web site that the number of kids fatally shot
in school is 29 in the last 18 months, but acts as if that's an
epidemic, even though the rate of such murders has been declining
for a decade. It just looks like an epidemic because of the copycat
factor.
</P>
<P>
   Adults consistently rate schools as unsafe places, while the
kids, teachers and cops who occupy schools rate them as very safe.
The problem is that adults have been watching too much CNN and
MSNBC, not that kids have been playing too many violent video
games.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the New York Times did all of us a service by analyzing
the mass killers of the last 50 years. The story showed that few of
the killers were addicted to violent movies or video games, but
most had mental disorders that went unnoticed by those around them.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools are not only adding metal detectors, they're adding
mental detectors, in the form of profiles of kids who may be
violent. Of course, these profiles are unreliable. And since the
threat of school shootings is so small, they're as unjustifiable as
those zero-tolerance policies that expel kids for bringing plastic
butter knives to school.
</P>
<P>
   But all those adults are doing it for the children, and that
gives them license to do anything.
</P>
<P>
   What we really should celebrate are kids who do it for the kids.
That's what Diane Sawyer will be doing on ``Good Morning America''
one day next week as the networks commemorate the anniversary of
the Columbine massacre.
</P>
<P>
   As her guests, she will have Lance Kirklin, who was badly
wounded at Columbine, and Rashad Williams, a student in California
who helped raise tens of thousands of dollars for Kirklin's medical
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rashad is really excited about it,'' said his mother, Sheila
Burton-Harrison, ``because he'll get to see his buddy again.''
</P>
<P>
   These are great kids, what America is all about. Kids today
aren't so bad, and we adults have to remember that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
