<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-TESTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS SEEN AS SCHOOLS TESTING BATTLEGROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY AND DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts may be carrying a new banner in the
nation's public school testing wars: Backlash capital.
</P>
<P>
   The third round of MCAS testing begins this week, and protests
are planned at school districts across the state as students,
parents, and some teachers are expected to voice their hatred for
the test, and the singular place it has come to occupy in education
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But students who walk out of school or otherwise boycott the
exam could be facing some of the toughest consequences yet: While
Cambridge says students will not be penalized, Brookline will
average a ``zero'' into students' English grades if they refuse to
take the test. In Arlington, a group of 20 students planning to
boycott the MCAS have been told they will be suspended for three
days.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Massachusetts' students and teachers who will be
watching the fallout across the state. Increasingly, parents in
other parts of the country are using Massachusetts as a model to
craft their own attacks on standardized tests. Many are copying the
boycotts and the letters of protests generated by many
Massachusetts residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew about Massachusetts' testing; it's been in the news a
lot. I went on the Internet, Massachusetts popped up,'' said Lisa
Amspaugh, leader of a revolt group in Georgia, where students also
need to pass a test in order to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, FairTest, the national antitesting group that's based
in Cambridge, is acting as a grass-roots guide: They are linking
parents from Virginia to California via e-mail to share protest
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is not something that is being pushed by
established organizations,'' said Monty Neill, head of FairTest.
``FairTest's goal is to help coordinate a national movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Although other states have had mandatory statewide testing
longer than Massachusetts has, few have been hit with organized
large-scale protests. Now, 18 states have imposed tests that
students must pass to graduate from high school. As these kinds of
tests have gained momentum, opponents have searched for ways to
turn the tide, arguing that it is unfair to withold diplomas on the
basis of a single, written test. Last week, two congressmen from
Virginia and Minnesota proposed federal legislation that would
prevent states from relying solely on test scores to award
diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at how other states are reaching the grass
roots, how they are convincing businesses it's not the right thing
to do, and joining forces with teachers and reaching legislators,''
said Mickey VanDerwerker of Parents Across Virginia United to
Reform the Standards of Learning.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to MCAS will undoubtedly continue to grow in
Massachusetts as 2003, when students who do not pass the test will
first be denied diplomas, draws near. This year, the testing will
be spread among more grades. This week's test, an English
composition exam, will be given on one day for grades 4, 8, and 10.
During May 15-26, students in grades 4-8 and 10 will take tests in
math, science, English, and history.
</P>
<P>
   In many communities, conflicts are expected between students and
administrators. In Western Massachusetts, a group of students whose
e-mail membership reaches Boston will be organizing a different
kind of protest: During the exam, instead of answering the
questions, they will write essays about why they think MCAS should
be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, administrators have promised to suspend the group
of sophomores who have been pledging to boycott the tests since
November. ``It's a penalty that has some bite to it,'' said Charles
McCarthy, principal of Arlington High School, of the three-day
suspensions. ``A one-day suspension is self-defeating. It gives
kids what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   But students said they were trying to set an example for future
MCAS test-takers. They say their reasons are simple: One test
doesn't determine a person's intellect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like the high-stakes nature of it; some people have
trouble taking the test,'' said Chris Carmody, one of the student
protesters. ``It's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cambridge, where school officials are expecting a large
boycott, superintendent Bobbie D'Alessandro said that while they
are encouraging students to take the test, they are also providing
alternatives for those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no reprisals for families or faculty who do not
choose to take or give the test. We are trying to provide a
productive atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   While the state Department of Education frowns on boycotting
MCAS, Commissioner David P. Driscoll respects a student's right to
skip the test. However, he has said that boycotting the test ``is
not accepting their responsibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
