<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-SNOWY-OWLS-ART-BO     04-11 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SNOWY-OWLS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PLOTTING THE MYSTERIOUS FLIGHT OF SNOWY OWLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WILSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The owl, white-faced and yellow-eyed, silently watches a raft
of black ducks floating in the saltmarsh off the windswept Duxbury
Beach. With a few pumps of her enormous wings, the owl sets upon
the surprised flock, grabs an unlucky victim with powerful taloned
feet and carries it skyward.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner is served.
</P>
<P>
   Snowy owls, masters of the Arctic tundra, have long made
Massachusetts their winter home, coming down from the frigid, dark
polar regions for the abundant food in New England. Here, these
ghost-white birds leave an indelible impression on all who see
them, whether they're snatching ducks in Duxbury or patrolling for
rats on the grasslands at Logan Airport in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, precisely because the birds nest across a vast, largely
inaccessible region from Siberia to Northern Europe, scientists
know far less about snowy owls than they do about other great birds
of prey like the bald eagle and peregrine falcon. A population
estimate is hard to come by, and efforts to study the birds in
their winter quarters have raised as many questions as they answer:
for no apparent reason, their numbers in Boston fluctuate widely
from dozens in some winters to none at all in others.
</P>
<P>
   Now, researchers hope that the duck hunter in Duxbury and five
other owls will help them solve the mysteries of the snowy owls,
from their population trend to the forces that determine their
nomadic wanderings. With transmitters strapped to their backs,
these birds will be tracked by satellite over the next 1 to 2
years, allowing scientists to know where they go, where they hunt,
and perhaps even how they die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about them excites me,'' said Denver Holt, founder
of the Owl Research Institute in Charlo, Montana, and one of two
key researchers behind the transmitter project. ``Do snowy owls
wander randomly or do they know . . . they can go somewhere else if
they find no (food in one area). Will we see any predictable
movement patterns over time?''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts officials say the transmitters will greatly speed
up scientific progress in understanding the owls, allowing
conservation officials to confront potential threats such as heavy
metal pollution recently discovered in the Arctic or the legal
hunting of owls in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our learning curve is going as fast as the technology will let
us,'' said Thomas French, assistant director of the Massachusetts
Division of Fisheries and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Birders and owl researchers know that many snowy owls spend the
winter somewhere in a swath that starts in the Pacific Northwest
and extends eastward through the Canadian prairie Provinces,
northern tier states and Great Lakes and New England. What's hard
to predict is where and when the owls will congregate in the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike migratory birds that follow the same paths to the same
places year after year, snowy owls follow no obvious pattern.
Researchers who apply identification bands to the owls at Logan
Airport, led by Norman Smith of Massachusetts Audubon's Blue Hills
Trailside Museum, have caught as many as 43 snowy owls in a season
and as few as zero.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, ornithologists know by observation and examining
regurgitated owl pellets what snowy owls eat and how they spend
their time while wintering in New England. But the researchers can
only shrug if you ask them where the snowy owls go in April and
May. They don't know what route the birds take or where they're
going. They don't even know whether the birds prefer to nest near
an ample supply of lemmings _ the birds' main food source _ or
whether the owls are loyal to the same nest year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking animals by attaching satellite transmitters has been an
important research tool since the 1980s. The ``charismatic
megafauna'' of the Arctic _ caribou, grizzly and polar bears, musk
ox and whales _ have been tracked and retracked. Even smaller fauna
such as geese and ducks have been extensively studied. But, until
now, snowy owls, the most nomadic and unpredictable of all the
North American owls, have been overlooked, in part because they
have no political constituency, such as a hunters' advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Both Smith of Audubon and Holt of the Owl Research Institute
have been studying snowy owls for years with Smith studying them on
the New England wintering grounds and Holt prying into their summer
nesting areas around Barrow, Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Holt have affixed transmitters to six snowy owls. Holt
captured his snowy owls (two males and a female) last July on the
nesting grounds in Alaska. Smith netted his owls (two females and a
male) at Logan Airport, releasing them on Duxbury Beach over the
past three months.
</P>
<P>
   The transmitter weighs little more than an ounce and is held to
the bird's back by Teflon straps across the animal's chest that the
owls seem to barely notice. Dental floss and glue join the straps
at cross points so the transmitters don't slip or chafe.
</P>
<P>
   Microcomputers inside the transmitters send a periodic signal to
any one of four National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
satellites in low polar orbits. Initially, the transmitter signals
for eight hours every 200 hours _ though the frequency of signals
will increase at key times _ and staff at the Snake River Raptor
Refuge in Idaho gather the data and e-mail each researcher with
updates.
</P>
<P>
   Already, just a few weeks after their release, the Massachusetts
birds are behaving in unexpected ways, to the delight of the
researchers. One owl, a male, had already travelled 250 miles to
the northwest at last satellite check-in, reaching an area just
west of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The two other owls, both caught more recently at Logan and
released at Duxbury Beach, are still in the state. The female is
hanging out near Sandy Neck in Barnstable, while the other male
headed north to George's Island and then Hull.
</P>
<P>
   These three animals may serve as a living rebuttal to the
once-conventional wisdom about the owls that come to New England.
Researchers once believed that they came here in high numbers
mainly when the supply of lemmings and other food sources in the
north was low, leaving these birds both desperate for a meal and
with a poor chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scientific literature says these birds (in Massachusetts)
supposedly aren't going to make it back to the Arctic. The
literature says that these birds come here to die. But we've had
birds that have returned to the Arctic (based on banding
returns),'' said Smith, noting that one bird is already well on his
way home.
</P>
<P>
   ``What stimulates these birds to move? No one has a clue and we
wouldn't have a clue to where these owls are without the
transmitters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some 4,500 miles from Boston on the other side of the
continent, three other snowy owls, released in the Barrow area last
July, are also moving in ways that surprise the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Two owls have left Alaska altogether, crossed frozen areas of
the Chukchi Sea, flown south of the Arctic Circle past St. Lawrence
Island in the Bering Sea and across to the Siberian peninsula
Chukotskiy Poluostrov, nearly 700 miles from Barrow.
</P>
<P>
   The Owl Research Institute's third tagged bird, a male, presents
a mystery. The transmitters relay temperature. This bird's pack is
cold and has not moved since mid-December. That means that either
the owl has died or the transmitter has fallen from the bird.
</P>
<P>
   Although the snowy owls are not listed as threatened or
endangered, that reflects ignorance as much as studies of the
species' good health. For instance, snowy owls may face more human
predators than records suggest: the owls are hunted legally in four
game management areas in Alaska, as long as the birds are eaten or
used for clothing, and the Inuit in Canada shoot an unknown number
of snowy owls. In addition, anecdotal evidence suggests that large
numbers of snowy owls may be trapped for food in remote areas of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Both Smith and Holt hope to attach more transmitters to snowy
owls in the winters ahead. Smith has funding both from an anonymous
donor and a small grant from the Nuttall Ornithological Club at
Harvard University to tag more owls. Holt looks to a five-year
horizon and support from foundations and private donors to fund his
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take many years to unravel this,'' said Holt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
