<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3405 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-UNIVERSAL-BOS &LR;      04-11 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-UNIVERSAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL ADDS AN ON-SITE HOTEL AND A WILD NEW RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The visitors from Portofino, Italy, gazed in
wonder at the Portofino Bay Hotel, with its bright buildings,
boats, and bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' said one of them. ``It looks 95 percent like the
real Portofino.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the other 5 percent?'' the visitor was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No garbage cans here.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, perhaps, is as it should be because this is Orlando,
where reality is a sometimes thing. Almost everything here is a bit
brighter, a bit cleaner, a bit cheerier. Take this new hotel at
Universal Orlando, as the theme-park resort is now calling itself.
Here _ for a price, of course _ guests stroll, swim, and stay in a
peaceful environment while just a few minutes away flash and crash
predominate as superheroes battle the forces of evil and the movies
inspire rollicking rides.
</P>
<P>
   The 750-room Portofino Bay Hotel, which opened late last year,
represents more than a hotel to Universal. Rather, it is the final
ingredient in creating a multibillion-dollar, self-contained resort
complex. Now people can stay at Universal and go to its two theme
parks and its shops, restaurants, and night spots without ever
having to get in a car or even encounter one, unless it's part of a
theme-park ride. So although Universal Orlando is only a fraction
of the size of that place a few miles down the road called Walt
Disney World _ 840 acres vs. 43 square miles _ everything is now in
place for an alternative, or additional, vacation experience.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels are nice (and this one seemed quite nice), but the theme
parks and their attendant thrills are the big draw, and new
attractions are constantly added to keep the crowds coming back.
That's why Universal opened its second park, Islands of Adventure,
last year, featuring superhero rides that whirl and twirl and hurl,
roaring dinosaurs, splashy water adventures, and attractions
involving the whimsical characters created by Dr. Seuss. And that's
why the resort's original movie-based theme park, Universal Studios
Florida, is scheduled to open an alien adventure sometime this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Men in Black: Alien Attack, inspired by the 1997 Will Smith
movie, will let participants determine the outcome of the ride by
zapping aliens and thus scoring points. So far that sounds a little
like Disney World's Buzz Lightyear attraction, but in this ride,
the 120 animatronic aliens fight back, sending the ride vehicles
spinning crazily out of control _ or so it will seem, thanks to a
computerized gadget called a ``roving motion platform.'' When the
ride is over, and the planet is presumably saved once again,
occupants of the various ride vehicles will be rewarded (or
condemned) with everything from a hero's welcome to a loser's
farewell. There are 12 possible endings.
</P>
<P>
   Alien Attack will be in good company at Universal Studios
Florida, with attractions such as Back to the Future, The E.T.
Adventure, Jaws, Earthquake, Twister, Terminator 2 3-D, Woody
Woodpecker's Kid Zone, and old banana-breath himself, King Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while Universal may not have the cuddly quality of the
Disney parks (and Woody Woodpecker will never replace Donald Duck
in my heart), it has some of the best and most envelope-pushing
rides anywhere. Universal's Islands of Adventure theme park, which
opened last year, dishes out the thrills with attractions like the
Amazing Adventures of Spiderman, which puts you in the middle of a
3-D battle so startling that it is worth waiting out any
computer-related delays that may occur if the ride is being
fine-tuned. Other attractions include the Incredible Hulk Coaster
(so speedy that one ride was plenty for me . . . for life), Dudley
Do-Right's Ripsaw Falls flume trip, Dr. Seuss's One Fish Two Fish
Red Fish Blue Fish ride, The Jurassic Park River Adventure (watch
out for that 85-foot drop!), and Triceratops Encounter, where you
can meet and pet a dino crafted so realistically that she even, er,
wets.
</P>
<P>
   Universal will no doubt be anxiously gauging how much repeat
business the new Islands of Adventure park attracts. Helping to
lure parkgoers back will be two new attractions scheduled to open
this summer. Storm Force, at the park's Marvel Super Hero Island,
will be a whirling indoor ride that with sound, light, and special
effects will create a thunderstorm adventure. And The Flying
Unicorn will be a child-sized roller coaster at the Lost Continent
Island. Youngsters will journey through a mystical forest on the
back of a unicorn.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of Universal Orlando is CityWalk, 30 acres of
nightclubs, shops, movies, and themed restaurants. The newest
restaurant there is NBA City, a joint project of the Hard Rock Cafe
and the National Basketball Association. In addition to food, there
are electronic games and scenes of basketball's greatest moments on
giant video screens. When I walked in, who should be on the screen
but number 33 himself, Larry Bird, shown in his Boston Celtics
days, with the big screen showing him larger than life. But then he
always has been.
</P>
<P>
   The parks and CityWalk give visitors at least two full days and
nights of activities, and that's where the Portofino Bay Hotel
comes in. Because this Loews hotel is on the premises, adults who
have had enough adventures can let their older children walk (with
no highways to cross) or take a shuttle boat to the parks.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty, however, for those who stay behind at the
Portofino, which has gone way outside the boxy look to create a
hotel that gives the appearance of dozens of adjoining buildings,
covered with trompe l'oeil art, as are the buildings in the actual
town in northwest Italy. Inside, opera and other music play in the
public areas _ you might, for instance, hear Puccini in the
restrooms. Many staff members, recruited from Central Florida's
Italian community, are from Italy or at least speak Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the hotel's nine restaurants carry on the theme.
Particularly intriguing is Mama Della's, where the story is told
that because Mama's children grew up, she decided to convert her
house into a restaurant. Thus, the various rooms have different
wallpaper, the chairs and plates don't always match, and the
atmosphere is homey. Strolling musicians sing Italian songs, and if
you're lucky you might be there when Mama herself joins in. The
Delfino Riviera, meanwhile, is coolly elegant. (Both restaurants
have won praise from critics who know more about fine dining than I
do. I know what I like, however, and Mama's lasagna and the
Delfino's osso buco were fine by me.) For fun eating, there's the
Trattoria del Porto, where Universal characters drop in from time
to time. For instance, I was treated to the sight of Popeye doing
the twist in the trattoria.
</P>
<P>
   The Portofino also has three pools, a half-dozen shops or
boutiques, nine ballrooms or meeting rooms, and a spa and fitness
center. (I don't indulge in spa treatments myself, but my wife
always welcomes the opportunity, saying they leave her as relaxed
as cooked spaghetti.)
</P>
<P>
   All of this, however, shouldn't be considered a substitute for
the real Portofino, garbage cans and all. And the hotel people know
this: General manager Crawford Sherman, who spent part of his
childhood in Portofino, says his fondest wish is that his hotel
will inspire people to want to travel to the actual village. It did
that for me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
