<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC'S BOGUS CASE AGAINST ALEXIS HERMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not to pile on poor ABC News _ the place is having
a month from hell _ but it was hard not to notice how little the
network did with the announcement last week that Labor Secretary
Alexis Herman had been exonerated after another of those
multimillion-dollar independent counsel investigations of
``charges'' that turned out to be bogus.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was ABC's story, brought to the Justice Department
with all the fanfare a TV network can produce, pumped up with
helium and then, at the moment of truth, essentially ignored.
</P>
<P>
   This tale lacks the hype and celebrity buzz associated with the
network's other headaches _ its inability to acknowledge that in a
farcical search for ratings it sent Leonardo DiCaprio to interview
President Clinton about the environment; and its handling of
another interview with Elian Gonzalez, age 6.
</P>
<P>
   But the mistreatment of Herman is every bit as revealing because
it illustrates the extent to which journalism standards have
plummeted in this age of commercialism and competition-driven
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The story is not very complicated. A guy named Laurent Yene from
Cameroon in the 1990s ended up in a personal and business
relationship with Vanessa Weaver, a woman who used to be Herman's
partner in a consulting firm. Both relationships ended four years
ago, whereupon Yene began saying ugly things about her and her
former partner, who had bought Herman's interest in their firm when
Herman entered the Clinton administration in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly Thing No. 1: Yene claimed that Herman agreed to accept a 10
percent kickback in cash on every piece of business she steered to
him and Weaver in their effort to represent people and firms
seeking government assistance. He claimed to have handed Herman a
cash-filled envelope.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly Thing No. 2. Yene also claimed that Herman, at his
encouragement, was part of scheme to get a Singapore businessman
seeking a satellite license to make illegal contributions to the
Democratic Party through Weaver and her sister, Caryliss. There was
no direct corroboration of any of this, but, hey, this is modern
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Yene hung around in the shadows during Herman's irresponsibly
delayed confirmation as labor secretary in 1997 but was paid no
serious heed. But late that fall, ABC began greasing the
independent counsel skids by getting around the no-evidence
problem.
</P>
<P>
   First, it got the guy on camera making his claims. Second, it
let him show his array of bank statements and other documents that
do not contain a single mention of Herman and permitted him to say
they showed a fancy scheme to get money to her. Third, they did
what the courts never allow for good reason, they gave Yene a
polygraph that he ``passed.'' And fourth, investigative guru Brian
Ross walked the guy into the Justice Department and reported that
officials were looking into charges that consisted of ABC's report.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Attorney General Janet Reno hired an independent
counsel, as she always has. This one will end up costing about $4
million after taking nearly two years. As things turned out, the
businessman from Singapore, Abdul Rahman, was indicted for making
illegal contributions of $150,000 to the Democratic Party in the
names of the Weaver sisters. When that was reported two months ago,
it was given a sinister tone because it was part of the ``Herman
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was the clue that the probe by Maine Republican
Ralph Lancaster was winding down. There were no charges against the
Weaver sisters, much less Herman, because there was no evidentiary
link to Rahman's contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Herman is in fact one of those people who labor valiantly to
make public life worthwhile. She was a Democratic Party star in the
period leading up to Clinton's election and before that a labor
relations expert known as a go-to person for Fortune 500 firms. Her
record as labor secretary has included the deft settlement of an
ugly Teamsters strike, the completion of a long effort to
consolidate the department's bewildering array of job-training
programs into a simpler, efficient system, and she is one of the
key people who has made welfare-to-work a success.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this ridiculous ordeal, Herman never complained. The
easy way out would have been to say that this was just another
example of what made the independent counsel system such a joke for
more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But there has always been more to this than too much
partisanship. A standards-challenged press has been the critical
triggering mechanism at every juncture. The editors and producers
who enable this behavior are kidding themselves if they don't think
the public has caught on to the game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
