<HEADER>
A3407 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-FAMILY-BOS &LR;      04-11 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FAMILY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDEAS ON WHAT TO SEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just what is a family vacation? The answer may seem simple
enough, but just as there are new interpretations of what a family
is, so, too, are there many ideas of what a family vacation is.
</P>
<P>
   No longer does ``family'' just mean mom, dad, and the kids. The
term could mean a single parent has the children, or it could
include grandparents, grandchildren, or extended families. And the
family vacation no longer means heading to the beach and booking a
cabin for a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   Families are on the move. And the travel world is out to help
with lots of family-friendly ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island just held a swearing-in of a bumper crop of family
travel ambassadors. Right on the steps of the capitol in
Providence, Governor Lincoln Almond welcomed Mr. and Mrs. Potato
Head as the state's newest ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Potato Head, created by Rhode Island-based Hasbro in 1952,
was selected to be the spokespud of the ``Rhode Island . . . The
Birthplace of Fun!'' promotion to encourage families from across
the nation to vacation in the tiny state. Throughout Rhode Island,
6-foot-tall Mr. Potato Heads, each decorated in styles ranging from
a mosaic bikini-clad beach beauty to a bejeweled sparkling spud,
will sprout at visitor attractions, restaurants, and recreational
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are encouraged to call 800-507-6700 for a free family
fun guide and information on a contest to locate at least three Mr.
Potato Head statues and win prizes, including, naturally, a
treasure chest of Hasbro toys. In 1999, Disney's Family Fun
magazine cited the state in four categories: top cities
(Providence); top zoos (Roger Williams Park Zoo); top tourist towns
(Newport); and top historic sites (the Newport mansions).
</P>
<P>
   A growing trend is to travel to the far corners of the world for
adventure. Thompson Family Adventures of Cambridge, Mass. has trips
to Africa, Nepal, Egypt, Alaska's wild areas, and the Galapagos.
The company's founders, Rick Thomson and Judi Wineland, have been
living an adventurous life for more than 20 years with homes both
in the Boston area and Tanzania. And, having children of their own,
they understand what traveling with the kids is all about, allowing
time for relaxation and adventure. Trips are planned to coincide
with spring breaks, summer vacation, and school holidays, and are
priced for family budgets.
</P>
<P>
   When travelers book a trip, the children are enrolled in an
Adventurer's Club, matching them with pen pals from where they will
be traveling as well as with others who will be traveling with
them. They also will be sent material geared to their age on the
destination, and once there they will participate in hands-on
activities designed for them. For details, call 800-262-6255 or
visit www.FamilyAdventures.com.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is to head for the hills _ ski resorts in summer
offer great family escapes. Waterville Valley in New Hampshire has
a Summer Unlimited plan that begins at $61 a day per person and
includes lodging, use of the athletic club with its pools and
exercise equipment, boating, mountain biking, tennis, golf, camp
for the kids, and more. For details, call 800-GO VALLEY or visit
www.waterville.com. In Vermont, Smugglers' Notch has been winning
accolades for its children's programs _ both summer and winter _
for years. It's so good, they guarantee fun or refund the cost of
funless times. Call
</P>
<P>
   Or you could head to a resort. Connecticut's Sunrise Resort is
the last remaining family vacation place of the ``Dirty Dancing''
genre. And it's not just surviving, it's thriving. This 140-acre
resort has been cited in magazines and books. The resort offers a
complete vacation package, including three meals daily and lots of
activities and entertainment. And it's family owned. It's also very
accommodating, with lodging that ranges from space for tents and
RVs to waterfront cottages and motel rooms. For information on this
Moodus, Conn., resort, call 800-225-9033 or visit
www.sunriseresort.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of going to Florida, instead of the usual
Disney World or Universal Studios tour, let the kids get their
hands dirty on a summer camping experience that includes
hand-feeding giraffes, giving a black rhinoceros an afternoon mud
bath, or maybe even assisting a veterinarian in conducting a
physical exam on an exotic white tiger.
</P>
<P>
   All this is possible during one of the Sea World/Busch Gardens
Adventure Camps at Busch Gardens Tampa Bay. There are camps for
different age groups _ even parents and kids as well as teachers.
These camps are not for everyone: You can get dirty, it can be hot,
but it might be the experience of a lifetime. And it's not all
work. Nights are for fun activities and there are adventures along
the Gulf of Mexico beaches and canoe trips. Of course, Busch
Gardens is famous for its roller coasters and other rides as well
as live shows and a water park. For more information, call Will
Darnall at 813-987-5780 or visit www.buschgardens.org.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows of the fun of Disney World, Disneyland, Universal
Studios, and other theme parks, but how about a Revolutionary Fun
Vacation Package? Virginia offers 400 years of fun, all within a
few days and all without a lot of travel. At first, kids might not
be enthusiastic about going to Colonial Williamsburg, but throw in
the great theme park attractions of Busch Gardens Williamsburg,
Water Country USA, and two more historic attractions, Jamestown
Settlement and the Yorktown Victory Center, and you've got a
getaway that offers great history, learning, and fun.
</P>
<P>
   And lest the kids think going to Williamsburg is just for
adults, let them know history there is kid-friendly. America's
oldest and largest outdoor living history museum lets kids get up
to their elbows in cake batter in an 18th-century household. This
gives a new meaning to hands-on, and it's just one of the things
children will love doing in this 18th-century capital. At Jamestown
Settlement, they'll learn about one of the earliest settlements in
America, and the Yorktown Victory Center brings the American
Revolution to life.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, a family of four can vacation beginning at $715,
including lodging and admissions. Prices depend on length of stay,
dates of travel, and accommodations sought. For information, call
the Colonial Williamsburg Foundation at 800-400-2851. Packages are
available May 6-Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego is another area with lots of variety. Here one can
visit Legoland California, a ``country just for kids (2-12).''
There's also Sea World San Diego, with not only whales, penguins,
and dolphins but interactive play areas and even dolphin
interaction programs. Then there is the San Diego Zoo, a
world-famous showcase for 3,800 animals of 800 species, and San
Diego Wild Animal Park where a monorail takes visitors to view
3,500 animals roaming free. All this and we haven't mentioned the
museums, beaches, the nearby desert, nearby Mexico, or the historic
missions.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you might stay home. Home in this case is Boston,
and it's a great city for family vacations. People travel around
the world to see Boston's historic sites. Instead of spending lots
of money on air fares, head into this family-friendly city.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau produces a great
Family Fun guide to attractions and hotels with special family
deals. They'll even send you a discount book to help cut costs.
Call 888-SEE BOSTON or, on the Web, visit www.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to take a cruise. Temptress Adventure Cruises,
which travels along Costa Rica and Panama, has five-night family
cruises with adult fares beginning at $1,210 and children 12 and
under receiving a 50 percent discount June 3-Aug. 30. Temptress
cruises at night, leaving the days for exploring and
eco-adventures. On-board naturalists lead daily excursions. For
information, call 800-336-8423 or, on the Web, visit
www.temptresscruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you head to Europe, drop by Kensington Palace in London to
see a showcase of six generations of royal children's clothes from
1810 to the outfits worn by Prince Charles and Princess Anne at
their mother's coronation in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Family vacations even include mulitgenerational ones for women.
Explorations in Travel has outdoor and cultural vacations for women
over 40. And on their multigeneration trips, all they ask is that
one participant be over 40, the others over 21. For information,
call 802-257-0152 or, on the Web, visit www.exploretravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   For busy parents and even grandparents looking for help, travel
agencies are ready and willing to put together vacations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
