<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-TOSCHES-BOS &LR;      04-11 1595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-TOSCHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICK TOSCHES WRITES ELEGANTLY ABOUT AMERICA'S UNDERBELLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nick Tosches enters a room with the authority of an
Old World aristocrat _ and the wariness of a mean-streets tough.
You better be tough, if you expect to get away with wearing a silk
homburg in the West Village on a weekday morning. ``I always felt
that that was one of the rewards of being 50, you could wear a
homburg,'' he says with a lazy grin, ``that and the strength of
merely having gotten there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosches (rhymes with galoshes) has reason to grin. He's just
come out with two books, ``The Devil and Sonny Liston,'' a
biography of the late heavyweight champion, and ``The Nick Tosches
Reader,'' a gathering of three decades of writing for publications
as various as Teenage Wasteland Gazette and Vanity Fair (where he's
a contributing editor).
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick has the ability to get completely loose and seem to be
saying whatever pops into his mind _ to say things that are
scabrous, outrageous, confusing _ and at the same time do this in a
stylistic framework of absolute eloquence and really pristine
form,'' says Greil Marcus, a longtime friend and the author of such
books as ``Mystery Train'' and ``Invisible Republic.'' ``It's like
there's a wild heart beating in this late-19th-century dandy.''
</P>
<P>
   Another friend, Peter Wolf, lead singer of the J. Geils Band,
likens the ``Reader'' to ``a box set, with the early works, the
demos. You get a chronicle of a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an apt analogy, for Tosches' best-known writing has been
about music. He began his career back in the early '70s, patrolling
the wilder shores of rock criticism. He wrote a flaunting, bravura
prose and would occasionally review records he hadn't listened to _
or, on at least a couple of occasions, that didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   Tosches' first book, ``Country'' (1977), about country and
western music, demonstrated a bent for maniacally detailed research
that he would later bring to bear on Jerry Lee Lewis (``Hellfire,''
1982) and Dean Martin (``Dino,'' 1992). The latter book helped
begin the current Rat Pack revival, something that causes Tosches
bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that admirers of ``Dino'' run the gamut from Regis
Philbin to the novelist Don DeLillo suggests just how difficult it
is to peg Tosches. Forced to assign him to a category, though, one
could do worse than ``American id studies.'' Tosches' writing
abounds in characters who make Sonny Liston seem almost subdued:
rockabilly anarchs, Vegas libertines, Machiavelli-quoting hit men
(Tosches has written two novels about the Mafia, ``Cut Numbers''
(1988), and ``Trinities'' (1999), as well as ``Power on Earth,'' a
1986 biography of Michele Sindona, the notorious Italian financier
whose clientele included both the Mafia and the Vatican. Sex and
drugs and (of course) rock 'n' roll figure prominently, as do
violence, redemption, and what Wolf laughingly calls ``spending the
other side of midnight together.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nothing so well captures the Toschean ideal as the
tribute he pays to the jump blues singer Amos Milburn in his 1984
collection, ``Unsung Heroes of Rock 'n' Roll.'' Milburn's voice,
Tosches writes, ``bespoke the ceaseless saxophones of salvation,
the crossing and uncrossing of restless nylon knees, the eightfold
path of the unfiltered Kool, and the miracle of Our Lady of the
After-Hours Joint.''
</P>
<P>
   At his most characteristic, Tosches can read like a cross
between the King James Bible and a peep show. His sentences leer
and jeer, hoot and holler _ yet all the while retain an Old
Testament cadence. ``Nick can really write like a 17th-century
Puritan when he wants to, (there's) a lot of Cotton Mather in
him,'' says Marcus. ``His books have a film-noir aspect,'' adds
Wolf. It's a tribute to Tosches' talent (as well as his
unusualness) that they're both right.
</P>
<P>
   In person, the film-noir aspect is more visible. A residue of
considerable Camel smoke coats his voice, and Tosches has the
tight-drawn skin of a man once likelier to respond to thirst than
hunger. ``Nick and Jerry Lee look quite a bit alike these days,''
deadpans Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Tosches points out that, thanks to diabetes and the sheer
passage of time, he now leads a far tamer life. He admits to a
measure of surprise, as well as pleasure, at having reached the
half-century mark. ``So many things I've done and been involved
in,'' he sighs. ``up until even 10 years ago _ drugs, alcohol,
general lifestyle habits, dissipation (we have so many nice words
for so many terrible things). But the physical cause of death would
have been drugs and alcohol, if not being shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosches' past is as colorful as his writing. He grew up in, as
he puts it, ``this Golden Triangle'' of Newark, Jersey City, and
Manhattan. Disarmingly cynical and charmingly surly, he learned at
an early age _ courtesy of his father, a tavern owner _ that few
things in this life are on the level. ``I was a kid working for
him,'' Tosches explains. ``Payday came. He gave me the money and
said, `Aren't you going to count it?' I said, `No, I trust you.'
He'd shortchanged me. It was just his way of telling me, hey, this
can happen when you're in a world among thieves.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosches, in fact, had his run-ins with the law and claims to
have written his first five books on a stolen typewriter. Does he
think he could have ended up a made man?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. It was the environment I grew up in, and for the most
part these characters were among the most benign forces in the
neighborhood.. . . Bookmakers, shylocks, killers, whatever, and I
became aware of this at a very early age because there were certain
really nice, gentlemanly people in the neighborhood who didn't have
jobs. So I said to my mother, `What does Louie do for a living?'
`Oh, he's in the rackets.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the rackets (or, for that matter, college), Tosches
held what he describes as ``a bunch of strange jobs, both
legitimate and illegitimate.'' They included tending bar, pasting
on labels at the Lovable Underwear Company (Tosches swears that's
the real name), and catching snakes at the Miami Serpentarium. One
bite on the shin, and he headed back north. This was in 1972, the
year Tosches got married. He later divorced and remains single.
</P>
<P>
   Tosches sold his first piece, at 19, to the Boston-based rock
magazine Fusion. By the time he moved to Nashville in the mid-'70s
to research ``Country,'' he was supporting himself exclusively
through his writing.
</P>
<P>
   What drew Tosches to country music, he says, was its providing
him with ``a renegade subject . . . damned, ignored, and
dismissed.'' His fondness for outsiders and extreme cases is
patent. And it's hard to imagine more of a renegade, someone more
outside or extreme, than Charles ``Sonny'' Liston. A convicted
felon who didn't so much box his opponents as maul them, Liston
lived the gangsta life long before there was such a thing. Even
worse, from respectable society's viewpoint, he succeeded at it.
``The bad guys are supposed to lose,'' Liston liked to say. ``I
change that. I win.''
</P>
<P>
   The '60s generation embraced Muhammad Ali, who twice defeated
Liston, as a symbol of rebellion. Tosches, who is convinced Liston
threw both fights to Ali, sees Liston as the true outlaw. ``Ali
presented a very benign, lovable character,'' Tosches says. ``He
fit right in the hypocritical capacity of middle-class, white
America to embrace blacks. He was entertaining . . . whereas Sonny
was just real. He was so pure, it was almost like a gift from God.
He transcended black, white, racism, good, and evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonny really was a tragic figure _ a term too freely used, but
in his case justified _ and I felt I wanted to restore his soul to
some sort of dignity.. . . He offers us an opportunity to see byond
this whole racial thing . . . to see a man so deprived in so many
ways, so set against in so many ways, who lived and endured.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Reader'' can be seen as Tosches' own, literary monument to
three decades of living and enduring. ``When the book was finally
done, there was something about that phrase `30 years' that had
some sort of weight to it that made me feel good. Here was the big
postcard from what I did with my summer vacation. And, God, now I
can fool them all: It's like I spent half the time (screwing) up,
and now it looks like I'm prolific. You stick around long enough
and you look prolific.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to go from picking up cigarette butts out of
urinals, which is how I started out (and I've never flicked one in
since), to the great leap forward of waiting for a $20 paycheck so
I could buy a barbecued chicken and a quart of milk, to now having
financial complaints that sound so utterly luxurious I never could
have imagined them in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Tosches will publish a book on an obscure minstrel
singer named Emmett Miller, who looms large in ``Country.'' Two
years later, he hopes to publish ``In the Hand of Dante,'' a novel
set simultaneously in the early 1300s and today that braids
together ``The Divine Comedy'' and organized crime. And somewhere
down the road _ by the time he hits 60? _ there's what Tosches
calls his ``dream'': ``to do my own translation of `The Divine
Comedy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   To go from the Mob to medieval epic _ ``Great Balls of Fire'' to
terza rima _ Dino to Dante? Tosches takes another puff on another
Camel, then smiles his all-knowing smile. ``Sometimes I think God's
greatest blessing to us is delusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
