<HEADER>
A3417 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      04-11 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE BOOK OF RUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ruth C. Ellis doesn't understand all the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning author Alice Walker called her a woman of
``power, audacity and joy.'' Whenever she attends a public event,
people cluster around her, wanting to talk to her, hug her, just
spend some time in her aura. There have been gushy e-mails from
France, adoring phone calls from England. And ``Ruth Ellis Day'' is
celebrated each February in Detroit as part of Black History Month.
</P>
<P>
   But Ellis is perplexed by all the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just an ordinary little woman,'' she said. ``I sometimes
wonder what this is all about; I'm not that important.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, Ellis is that important. A woman of abundant spirit,
hers is a refreshingly resilient soul, especially in a society that
doesn't always embrace the things Ellis embodies. According to the
award-winning documentary on her life, ``Living With Pride: Ruth
Ellis at 100,'' she is the ``oldest `out' African-American known.''
The film, by Yvonne Welbon, can be seen on the cable's Sundance
Channel April 17.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Ellis recalls her mother taking her to see the
Wright Brothers on one of their earliest flights; her
neighborhood's jubilance the day World War I ended; and how her
father, with only a sword, defended the family's home during race
riots in 1908. Even during a brief conversation, Ellis is a living,
breathing history book.
</P>
<P>
   While being the oldest known black lesbian is the reason Ellis
has become a celebrity in the lesbian and gay community, it's a
distinction she playfully challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do they know I'm the oldest?'' said Ellis, who celebrated
her 100th birthday last July, during a recent phone interview from
her home in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   That feistiness is what attracted filmmaker Welbon, 37, who
first saw Ellis at a women of color dance in Bloomington, Ind.,
three years ago. Ellis _ then a mere nonagenarian _ spent entire
evening wearing out various partners on the dance floor. Welbon was
instantly intrigued by this energetic spite of a woman with the
ready grin and shock of white hair.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, Welbon, who lives in Chicago, visited
and filmed Ellis, including Ellis's trips to Provincetown to attend
Golden Threads, an annual gathering for lesbian and gay senior
citizens. ``I'm the oldest one there,'' Ellis offered. ``Of course,
I'm the oldest one every place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She likes to be around people her age, but of course, there's
no one her age,'' Welbon joked. ``The woman who founded Golden
Threads was 93, and when she saw Ruth she said, `Thank you for
making me a baby dyke, Ruth!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Springfield, Ill., on July 23, 1899, Ellis was the
youngest of four born to Charles Ellis Sr. and Carrie Faro. Her
mother died from a stroke when Ellis was 12, and she was raised
under the protective eye of her father, who had little patience for
boys hanging around his only daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy used to tell me, `Boys and books don't go together,'
'' Ellis said. ``So, if he came home and saw me on the front porch
talking to a boy, I got balled out.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father's discouragement of male suitors was just fine with
Ellis. She recalled falling in love with her high school gym
teacher, and learning about homosexuality from such books as the
Radclyffe Hall classic, ``The Well of Loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what Ellis learned was self-taught, including bowling,
piano, photography, and typesetting, which led to Ellis opening her
own printing shop in Detroit. It was also in the Motor City where
Ellis began her 30-year-plus relationship with Ceceline ``Babe''
Franklin, a woman she met at a dance in Springfield. The two women
bought a home and lived together until shortly before Franklin's
death in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has been single since Franklin's death, Ellis never
wants for companionship. She has a large circle of friends, which
seems ever larger since Welbon's documentary began making its way
through various film festivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be a celebrity. I just want to be as I am,''
Ellis said. ``I'm like Popeye the sailor man _ `I am what I am, and
that's all that I am.' I didn't think I had enough history to make
a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Having recently witnessed the turn of yet another century, Ellis
isn't enjoying what she has seen so far. People aren't ``living
right, '' she said, and ``they aren't compassionate and friendly
like they should be.'' She is discouraged with the persistence of
racism, and just doesn't understand homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``God loves everybody. Some people in the church don't believe
that because they don't accept gay and lesbian people,'' said
Ellis, a devout churchgoer. ``But God accepts them; otherwise, He
wouldn't have put them here.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's that matter-of-fact pride that makes Ruth Ellis an icon
in the lesbian and gay community. Even though arthritis has lately
limited her mobility _ ``Old age has got a hold of me,'' she said _
she still gets out as often as possible, courtesy of her friends.
She's planning her annual P-town sojourn, and her 101st birthday
party is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the youngsters tell me I'm an inspiration,'' she said.
``Well, I guess I'm just glad this old lady can inspire someone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
