<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FAMILY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOY OF A FAMILY TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Family vacation: What makes those words so magical? Is it the
memories? The sharing of laughter and fun? Yes to both, but mostly
it is the joy of just being with one another.
</P>
<P>
   During our ``normal lives,'' we are so busy we don't have much
time for one another. But on vacation, the opposite is true _ our
time revolves around one another.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, my family vacationed at Yellowstone. It was one of
my best trips, and one reason I had so much fun was that I was with
my family.
</P>
<P>
   On a family vacation, you have time to learn things about each
other you never knew. You also have time to look around and learn
more about the earth. Besides being fun, Yellowstone was beautiful,
and gave our family new things to learn: the park's history and
facts about geysers, hot springs, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Another nice thing about that vacation was our lodgings. At the
Roosevelt Cabins, the first place we stayed in the park, we shared
a tiny, one-room building. At the main lodge, though, we would all
sit on the large porch, with its many rocking chairs. My sister,
Natalie, and I always brought a board game, and we would play
quietly while our parents read.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, we would head back to the lodge for a huge
family-style dinner. Once we were full, we would drive around
looking for wolves and other wild animals.
</P>
<P>
   One night, we walked to the stables for an Old West cookout. The
leaders of the group first gathered us together and told stories.
Then we were given the option to ride horseback or in a horse-drawn
buggy to the dinner site. We had a delicious dinner and told more
stories. We rode back, and we went to bed.
</P>
<P>
   The second place we stayed at was the Old Faithful Inn, right
next to Old Faithful. The inside was amazing; everything was shiny
and made of wood. When we walked in and looked up, we were
surprised to see that each floor had a big balcony.
</P>
<P>
   The inn was huge, and had a lot of nooks and crannies that were
great fun to discover. My sister and I got to have our own room for
the first time on a trip, and we used a shared bathroom down the
hall. Our parents were next door.
</P>
<P>
   Built onto the ceiling of the inn was a small room that
resembled a treehouse. It was called the Crow's Nest, but
unfortunately was closed to the public for safety reasons. There
was also a huge fireplace surrounded by chairs where people sat and
read while listening to piano music coming from the second-floor
balcony.
</P>
<P>
   During our stay at the inn, we did a lot of lounging around, and
spent a good amount of time on the second-floor porch watching Old
Faithful erupt hourly. My sister and I wrote letters and stories
galore.
</P>
<P>
   One morning we got up early for a guided walk through a geyser
basin. We saw lots of eruptions and other interesting sights.
</P>
<P>
   The entire stay was great, mostly because we had time to sit
together, read together, and have fun together.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, we are planning to go to California, and we are
expecting the trip to be just as much fun as Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years from now, we will all look back on our family
vacations, and be very glad we had the opportunity to do such a
wonderful thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Elizabeth Shribman is a sixth-grader in the Washington, D.C.,
public schools.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
