<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DIMAGGIO-MEMORIAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     SAN FRANCISCO MOVES AHEAD WITH PLAN TO NAME PARK FOR DiMAGGIO  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RACHEL GORDON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ City officials intend to proceed with naming a
small park for Joe DiMaggio, despite threats from a Florida lawyer
who says the baseball legend deserves a more prominent memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Gavin Newsom, who has been pushing to find a civic
honor for DiMaggio, said Monday that the city would move forward
with plans to hang the Yankee Clipper's name at the North Beach
Playground.
</P>
<P>
   Dom DiMaggio, Joe DiMaggio's only surviving sibling and a
baseball star in his own right, supports the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city has been very good to my family, starting with my
immigrant parents and continuing to this day,'' DiMaggio, a former
All-Star center fielder with the Boston Red Sox, said in a written
statement from his Florida home. ``As far as I'm concerned, the
city can determine for itself the way in which it wants to honor
its native sons.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio, who died in March 1999 at the age of 84, lived a
block away from the playground and played ball there as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown signed on to the proposal Monday to rename
the 2 1/2-acre playground in DiMaggio's honor.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes despite a demand from Morris Engelberg, the
Hollywood, Fla., lawyer handling DiMaggio's estate, who threatened
to sue to stop the name change.
</P>
<P>
   He said a more fitting tribute to DiMaggio would be to rename
the Bay Bridge or San Francisco International Airport, not a
concrete playground, after DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Newsom earlier this year, Engelberg said he would
``pursue all legal means available to stop the unauthorized use of
Joe DiMaggio's name.''
</P>
<P>
   After checking with the city attorney on San Francisco's legal
standing, Newsom said he was confident the city would prevail if
any legal action is taken.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, the Recreation and Park Commission voted 20
years ago to rename North Beach Playground for DiMaggio, though the
move was never consummated with a changing of signs and city maps.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the city will not use DiMaggio's name for
commercial purposes. Therefore, Newsom has concluded that City Hall
has the green light to name the playground after DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city has a bedrock foundation legally,'' Newsom said.
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
