<HEADLINE>
KEEPING THEM CALM IN THE CAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Family travel is often accompanied by a question: How do you
keep the kids from tearing one another apart during long car rides?
Here, from SmarterKids.com, are portable products that the Web
site's educators have rated highest for fun and learning:
</P>
<P>
   --Brain Quest for Car _ The game includes 1,100 cards with
questions and answers about America, as well as original games
designed to be played in the vehicle. (Workman, $8.95, for grades
3-6.)
</P>
<P>
   --Electronic Hand-Held Yahtzee _ This one-player device lets a
youngster experience all the joys of the traditional game. (Milton
Bradley, $14.95, grades 2-12.)
</P>
<P>
   --Feltkids Travel Playset _ A sturdy case with a handle unfolds
to reveal _ ta da! _ a blue felt playing surface for 24 felt pieces
depicting a boy, a girl, and travel-related items. (Learning Curve,
$24.95, toddlers to Grade 1.)
</P>
<P>
   --Kids Trip Diary _ This activity book has pages to help
children prepare for their trip, record their memories (and perhaps
write nasty notes about their siblings), and play travel games.
(Marlor Press, $5.95, grades 1-5.)
</P>
<P>
   --Rush Hour _ It's a sliding block puzzle designed to challenge
sequential-thinking skills, whatever that means. There are 16
puzzle pieces, 40 challenge cards, and four levels of play. (Binary
Arts, $13, grades 3-12.)
</P>
<P>
   And who knows, if such products keep the kids busy enough, they
may ask ``Are we there yet?'' only a couple hundred times! &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: When you set out in the car for your family vacation
_ or any other time _ be sure your children are properly buckled in
the proper seat for their size. Six out of 10 children killed in
crashes are not restrained. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What is London's most-visited tourist attraction?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``My brothers and sisters and I used to find the biggest,
most beautiful tree . . . make a treehouse in it, and pretend it
was the grandest house in all the world'' _ Dolly Parton,
explaining the inspiration behind a huge treehouse, which is part
of the new Dreamland Forest at Dollywood in Pigeon Forge, Tenn. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: Oklahoma law forbids taking a bite out of
another's hamburger. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fabulous photos in family-friendly Philly: When your family visits
Philadelphia, you'll surely photograph your children near the
Liberty Bell and in front of Independence Hall. But consider also
taking photos at these spots, with these poses: on the steps of the
Museum of Art, imitating Rocky of movie fame; aboard the RiverLink
Ferry, with the city in the background; in front of the LOVE statue
at JFK Plaza; posing as ``The Thinker'' statue in front of the
Rodin Museum; in front of the walk-through heart at the Franklin
Institute; and eating a cheese steak sandwich at Pat's Steaks. The
suggestions are from photographer Bob Krist via the Greater
Philadelphia Tourism Marketing Corp. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Killer Web site: Everyone has a Web site these days _ even Shamu
the killer whale, a resident of SeaWorld Florida in Orlando. To see
Shamu in action, go to www.shamu.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Yeah, right: From a letter sent to the Orlando tourism people:
``Please send me four Disney World tickets _ I'll send you the
money later.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lions for lions' sake: A lion, long the symbol of MGM, is now in
residence at the MGM Grand Hotel/Casino in Las Vegas. In fact, a
few lions live there. The Lion Habitat, inside the property, has a
variety of the beautiful beasts, including Goldie, Metro, and Baby
Lion, descendants of MGM Studio's marquee lion, Metro. A
see-through walkway tunnel runs through the habitat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Madame Tussaud's wax museum; it attracts some 2
1/2 million visitors a year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
