<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-TOWN LIFE IN ZAMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUKUNI, Zambia _ The barefoot girls on the road gang are
fiercely attacking weeds with mattocks. Well, it isn't exactly a
road, just one of the pathways through this village of 8,000
inhabitants not far from the Zambian end of that mighty African
waterworks: Victoria Falls. There is no automotive traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these teenagers seem good-natured about swinging their
long-handled tools on a hot, sunny afternoon, about keeping the
sandy crimson right-of-way neat. After all, as slender 22-year-old
Albina Similonga (a sort of one-woman Mukuni chamber of commerce)
explains, heavy-hitting _ plus lifting _ is traditionally women's
work in this locale. As well as such other toil as tending
children, goats and cows, raising the food _ corn, millet,
vegetables, chicken, beef _ and cooking it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is better for the women lately, since we got a pump,''
says Albina, who has graduated from high school and has a less
strenuous (moreover, remunerative) job, showing visitors around for
a tourist agency. ``Before the government drilled the well and put
in the pump, we had to walk miles to a spring and back, carrying
heavy jars of water.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Helen Chalmers, in Harare, the capital of neighboring
Zimbabwe, had suggested, ``When you go to the falls, you might as
well cross the border and look in at Mukuni and see how most people
in this part of Africa live. Village life.''
</P>
<P>
   Small town stuff. Good. I liked her idea since I'd been raised
in a tranquil Ohio town of about the same population, also lying
amid farmland. Some people had water pumps when I was a boy. But
they were adjoining the kitchen sink, not communal. And the houses
weren't circular structures of mud and boughs with conical,
grass-thatched roofs. We probably missed something.
</P>
<P>
   My last stopover in Zambia, 30 years earlier, covering a State
Department good will tour of tennis champs Arthur Ashe and Stan
Smith, had been confined to the capital, Lusaka. It had the usual
leading city amenities: paved streets, electric lighting, plumbing
_ leftovers from the British colonies, Northern Rhodesia and
Nyasaland, prior to their combination as independent Zambia in
1964.
</P>
<P>
   At first not much good will was dispensed in our direction
because the day before we landed Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda,
paying a call on Washington, had been told that President Nixon,
was too busy to see him. It was headlined in Lusaka as a snub, a
national insult.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ashe turned down some of the heat. On TV he charmed the
local populace, intrigued by a significant champion with a black
face. He made points with his statesmanlike demeanor, by holding
instructional sessions for African kids _ and beating the tall,
blond Smith in an exhibition match.
</P>
<P>
   On that junket through Africa, Smith (the better player at the
time) was virtually nameless, a far-down second banana. Obviously
it was the Ashe tour. As in the heavyweight championship days of
Joe Louis's ``bum of the month club'' victims, Stan was the ``bum
of the layover'' in the eyes of Arthur's admirers.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we got to Zambia, Smith, unassuming sportsman and
close friend of Ashe, was getting rankled by the lack of attention
being paid him. Frank Deford of Sports Illustrated straightened him
out. ``Stan, have you been paying attention to where we are? You're
along strictly for the ride. You are the Big O _ for opponent. The
other guy. The foil. That's all. At least you're getting room and
board.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith had to laugh, thereafter enjoying the role of Big O,
frequently spoiling the show by beating Ashe. There were no tank
towns on that itinerary. Just teeming principal cities where tennis
courts were available, along with US diplomatic corps ambassadors
to furnish the room and board for nomadic sporting ambassadors.
It's a shame those State Department tours involving a variety of
American athletes have died. The athletes are too busy making too
much money to volunteer themselves as makers of good impressions
for their country.
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago. But things haven't changed much since in
Albina's quiet hometown or mine. Of course, rural Ohio and Zambia
aren't very similar, but small-town folks are generally friendly
anywhere, proud of their settlement. Mukunians are no exception. My
town had maybe a half-dozen saloons, indoor establishments serving
trademarked brands. Mukuni guys prefer to make their own at home.
Boiling the bark of waterberry trees, they produce a strain of
white lightning called ``kachasu,'' that they drink while lying
around is the shade of leafy trees in wood-fenced yards. The
climate is favorable to year-round outdoor imbibing, an exercise in
light lifting they seem to specialize in. Sometimes noisily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kachasu is very powerful,'' says Albina, ``and is a very old
custom.'' Looks like it. Mukuni goes back to the 15th century, aged
something like 400 years senior to my former hamlet where the elder
swillery, a tavern called the Polish Village, is a youngster, about
75. But it may be only a matter of time before the PV's regular
communicants plant waterberry trees and introduce kachasu moonshine
to Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   With the Songwe Hills a few miles away forming a hazy blue
backdrop and a nearby forest as scenic substitute for indoor
outhouses, the villagers appear content and healthy. Their life
pattern, far from indolent, would seem serious slo-mo to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The men with a trade, woodcarvers, sit on the ground of alfresco
studios. Shielded from the sun by low-hanging branches, they shape
animal and human figures from deep-purple-striped zebra wood. They
do good work. It's on sale at a market near the village chief's
stockaded residence, considered by the locals ``a palace,'' and
called Lumpasa (lion's den) in their dialect. Chief Patrick
Mufalali's place is accorded palatial status because of the
substantial size and appearance of the main house (graced by TV
antenna), a collection of outbuildings in a generous courtyard, and
the fact that his domicile has windows. What's more: glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chief isn't home today,'' says Albina, ``but I will show
you some nice homes. Smaller, of course, but very pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   This is like strolling with the mayor. Everybody knows Albina.
An aged lady named Rosemary waves, and we stop to talk. Sitting
beside a pile of small nuts from a native tree, the knobbly-barked
maketi, Rosemary is opening them with a handy implement: a rock.
Not a balletic movement, but this nutcracker's sweet as she pounds
and explains that the nuts can be pressed for cooking oil or ground
up into flour.
</P>
<P>
   Operating her open-air beauty parlor farther along, Isabel
Muzamba has a couple of teenage customers, and everybody's busy.
While Isabel braids her hair, Theresa nurses her baby and stems
beans. Regina, awaiting her turn with the hairdresser, is cutting
up bean leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This scene would please an efficiency expert,'' says my
friend, Aurelio.
</P>
<P>
   Albina takes us into a family compound where the odors are
delicious. The lady of the house, Veronika, has a beef stew
simmering in a black iron pot over a small wood fire. Aurelio
wonders about taking pot luck, but Albina says that, though we'd be
welcome, there's a large family to be fed.
</P>
<P>
   She wants us to meet Rosa Keelo at a location down the lane, the
householder at, apparently, the village showplace. Rosa's ground
floor is concrete, not ground, and she owns a rare TV set
(battery-run) to the great pleasure of her four kids. A pretty
mulberry bush decorates the earthen compound that is spotlessly
brushed.
</P>
<P>
   The Keelos are people of substance (meaning numerous cattle),
occupying three huts within their perimeter: a kitchen, one for the
kids, the other for the parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope you can come back and spend more time,'' Rosa says as
her offspring beam at the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope you can come to Boston,'' says Aurelio, ``although
Boston drivers are scarier than the lions around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I wish I had time to get my hair braided by the
adroit coiffeuse, Isabel Muzamba
</P>
<P>
   But Aurelio says, ``Forget it. Please accept that you are on a
career bad hair trip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
