<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTIC FUN ABOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not July 4 but next weekend Boston will hold an
all-American celebration almost equal to the Independence Day
holiday. Patriots Day weekend, April 15-17, celebrates the 225th
anniversary of the American Revolution, and more than 200,000
visitors are expected to be on hand to watch reenactments of the
shot heard round the world, Paul Revere's ride, and, of course, the
104th running of the Boston Marathon. What a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Only Massachusetts and Maine, once part of Massachusetts, mark
Patriots Day. It is a legal holiday in the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   The reenactments include the battles with the redcoats on
Lexington Green. In Concord, there will be encampments of
Minutemen, and for the first time since 1775, the events of the
first day of the war for independence will be reenacted in
chronological order.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the celebration will be a weeklong Let Freedom Ring!
2000 program of tours, parades, and performances related to the
events of 1775. Along Boston's famed Freedom Trail, the Old North
Church will be the scene of a lantern service (it was from its
steeple that Revere watched for the signal, one if by land, two if
by sea), and performances of ``Paul Revere Tonight!'' On April 17 a
parade featuring the Ancient and Honorable Artillery (the nation's
oldest military organization) will begin at City Hall Plaza, and
along the trail there will be a Revolutionary Ramble, with costumed
guides. On April 17, runners from more than 51 countries will take
to the road from Hopkinton to Boston's Copley Square, a 26-mile
event that ranks behind only the Super Bowl as the largest
single-day sporting event in the world.
</P>
<P>
   For complete information on the celebration, as well as hotel
packages, call the Boston Convention and Visitors Bureau at
888-SEE-BOSTON or, on the Web, visit www.BostonUSA.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Maine Patriots &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, the 10th annual Patriots Day Weekend Celebration will
be held in Ogunquit April 14-16. The celebration marks the
unofficial opening of the season and there will be two big tents on
Ogunquit Beach for the Taste of the Town, Beach Bazaar and Crafts,
Saturday Casino Night, Beach Golf, and a fireman's cookout as well
as music and Kidstown rides and games. For information, call the
Ogunquit Chamber of Commerce at 207-646-2939.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
African exhibit &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nyanja! Africa's Inland Sea'' opens April 15 at the New
England Aquarium in Boston. The exhibit offers an inside look at
the animals, people, and research of Africa's Lake Victoria, the
world's second-largest lake and the celebrated source of the Nile
River. An enormous Nile crocodile will welcome visitors to the
exhibit, which includes a wetlands display complete with a spongy
floor and a crawl-under python tunnel, as well as hundreds of
treetop-dwelling giant spiders and their babies. For more
information, call 617-973-5200.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
$5 Amtrak fare &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate the fifth anniversary of Amtrak's Vermonter, the
line is offering a $5 one-way fare anywhere between St. Albans and
Springfield. The special fare is good any Saturday or Sunday in
April except Easter. The Vermonter has a special baggage car
designed to carry skis, snowboards, and fully assembled bicycles.
The care car serves a variety of made-in-Vermont foods and
beverages. The Vermonter serves St. Albans, Burlington, Waterbury,
Montpelier, Randolph, White River Junction, Windsor, Claremont,
N.H., Washington Falls, and Brattleboro. For information, call
800-USA RAIL.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vietnam volunteers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's been nearly 25 years since the end of the Vietnam War. For
those interested in witnessing its rebirth and renewal firsthand,
Global Volunteers in sponsoring a two- or three-week service
program in this Southeast Asian country. Participants will be asked
to teach conversational English to students of all ages. No special
skills are required beyond an open mind and an interest in other
cultures. Openings are on June 17-July 8, July 8-29, and Oct.
14-Nov. 4. The fee to participate is $2,195 and includes all food,
lodging, and ground transportation. Air fare is extra; however, all
costs including air fare, are tax deductible. For information,
write to Global Volunteers, 375 E. Little Canada Road, St. Paul, MN
55117, telephone 800-487-1074, or visit www.globalvolunteers.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gold on view &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's gold galore in Houston and Baltimore. Now through May
28, The Walters Art Gallery in Baltimore if featuring ``Gold of the
Nomads: Scythian Treasures from Ancient Ukraine.'' The treasures
are of the Scythians, the fierce, nomadic horsemen who roamed the
European steppes from the seventh to third centuries BC. These
marauders were patrons of lavish gold and silver objects. Many of
the items on view were only recently unearthed and are seen for the
first time outside Ukraine. For information, call 410-547-9000. The
exhibit will later travel to Los Angeles County Museum of Art July
2-Sept. 24; the Brooklyn Museum of Art, Oct. 29-Jan. 21, 2001;
Royal Ontario Museum, Feb. 18-April 29, 2001; the Nelson Atkins
Museum of Art, Kansas City, May 27-Aug. 11, 2001; and the Grand
Palais, Paris, Sept. 25-Dec. 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Museum of Natural Science offers ``Kremlin Gold:
1,000 Years of Russian Gems and Jewels'' from April 15-Sept. 4.
More than 140 golden relics, jeweled masterpieces, and precious art
objects, many of which have never traveled beyond the Kremlin walls
since they were crafted centuries ago, will be on view. Items range
from the 4th to 12th centuries, pieces created in the Kremlin
workshops between the 13th and 18th centuries, a select number of
Faberge Imperial Easter Eggs crafted in St. Petersburg during the
19th century, and award-winning contemporary works from the last
half of the 20th century. For information, call 713-639-4629 or
visit www.hmns.org.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the exhibit will be another called ``Gold: Highlights
from The Harvard University Collection,'' featuring many items
collected in California in the early 1850s. And, through Sept. 7,
the Wortham IMAX Theatre will feature ``Gold Fever,'' which looks
at cultures around the world and the significant roles gold plays
in these cultures. Gold has had a mystique going back 5,000 years.
It was the first metal used by humans. People have chased and
fought for it over the centuries, and it still remains an allure
today, said the film's director, David Lickley. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Artichoke time &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Monterey County, Calif., springtime is artichoke time, where
you can not only watch the harvest but feast on the horny green
globes at area restaurants. Castroville, the ``artichoke capital of
the world,'' holds its annual Artichoke Festival May 20-21. The
festival is best known for crowning Marilyn Monroe its first
Artichoke Queen 41 years ago. For information on the county, call
877-MONTEREY or visit www.GoMonterey.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Island of the month &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Express has begun an ``Island of the Month'' program,
with Curacao beginning the new season. Travelers who book and pay
with an American Express card receive a $100 gift check, a fifth
night free at a participating hotel, and a discount book for use in
shopping, dining, and entertainment. Packages must be booked
between now and May 15 for travel through Dec. 15. For information,
call 888-AXP-0086 and ask for the Island of the Month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Open house &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 250 of Virginia's outstanding homes, gardens, and
historic landmarks will have their welcome mat out for America's
Largest Open House during Historic Garden Week in Virginia, April
22- 30.
</P>
<P>
   Properties on the tour range from farmhouses to penthouses, from
stately 17th-century National Historic Landmark manors to new
millennium villas. Virginia's 67th annual Historic Garden Week is
the oldest and largest statewide house and garden tour in the
nation. Three dozen tours are scheduled during the week, from the
Eastern Shore to the Shenandoah Valley. Prices range from $10 to
$25 per event. For a brochure, call 804-644-7776 or, on the Web,
visit www.VAGardenweek.org. A 200-page guidebook may be reserved by
sending a $5 donation payable to Historic Garden Week, 12 E.
Franklin St., Richmond, VA 23219. For information on touring and
staying in Virginia, call 804-786-4484, and for bed-and-breakfast
reservations, call 800-934-9184.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sales tax out &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has ended the city's
sales tax of 8.25 percent on the purchase of clothing and footwear
items costing less than $110. During the past three years the city
has held seven sales-tax-free weeks, during which New York City
retailers saw sales increase as much as 77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gardens to view &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some gardens that are open to the public? ``The
Garden Conservancy's Open Days Directory: The Guide to Visiting
Hundreds of America's Best Private Gardens'' (Abrams, $14.95)
offers gardens that are open to the public on select weekend days
from March through October. This year 17 new cities were added to
the book, including destinations in New Hampshire and Long Island's
North Shore. The book can be ordered ($14.95 plus $3.50 shipping)
by writing to the Garden Conservancy, PO Box 219, Cold Spring, NY
10516 or calling 888-842-2442.
</P>
