<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY FUED, A POLARIZED CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Defiance has given way to disgusted resignation.
</P>
<P>
   After the surge of energy that followed the Miami-Dade mayor's
threat to disregard federal law 13 days ago, the reality has set in
that Elian Gonzalez's transfer back to his father _ and return to
Cuba _ is pretty much a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   For his supporters in the Cuban-American exile community here,
this comes as a bitter blow. Once again, they fear, Fidel Castro
will win. Once again, the patriarch in his seemingly endless autumn
is poised to have the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters held a model of Fidel wearing a bra outside the
Gonzalez family home Monday, but the grim attempt at humor did
little to dispel the gnawing, palpable frustration of the 100 or so
protesters at the barricades.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has steadily stepped up the heat since
Elian's Miami relatives walked out of negotiations last Thursday.
The US government's proclamations that the transfer of the
six-year-old boy back to his father, Juan Miguel, will definitely
happen has taken on new weight, coming as it does now not from
Robert Wallis, the head of the Miami office of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, but from Janet Reno, the US attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, Elian's supporters have little to cling to. His claim
for asylum is weak, and his Miami family's claim to custody _ even
if that were an issue, which Reno insists it is not _ is even
weaker. Supporters continue to call on Juan Miguel to come to Miami
so this can be settled ``as a family,'' but why should a father
have to negotiate with long-lost relatives for his own son?
</P>
<P>
   They are a family with irreconcilable differences, as this is a
city whose views of this crisis are far apart.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami Herald/NBC poll published Sunday confirmed the strong
sense that the matter of Elian has polarized Miami. While
Cuban-Americans opposed the boy's return to Cuba by a margin of 83
percent to 9 percent, every other ethnic group, including other
Hispanics, overwhelmingly supported it.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the gulf is unusual, even for an issue involving
Cuba. Rob Schroth, who conducted the poll, was quoted in the Herald
stating that the gap was the largest he had seen in 20 years of
polling Miami-Dade County, truly a tale of two cities.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance to the transfer appears to be crumbling for
several reasons, but one of them is the failure of its leaders to
persuasively make their case to the world. The world, they say,
simply does not understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't understand our pain,'' said Victor Silva. ``I came
to the United States in 1961 when I was seven years old and I've
seen that pain in my own family. I was Elian back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he admitted that the large-scale civil disobedience promised
a few days ago seems increasingly unlikely. ``We are a law-abiding
people,'' he said. ``We march, we walk, but we'll obey the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Disbelief that Juan Miguel is speaking for himself remains
strong. He must be a puppet, people here say. He has no choice but
to do Castro's bidding, both for his own sake and that of his
family on the island. It is simply inconceivable to many exiles
here that he would choose a life under Castro for his son over
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The unhealed wounds of exile are never far from the surface in
Miami. Cuban-Americans are a wildly successful immigrant group, an
American success story. They have remade Miami, a city so different
from the one I was born in that it amounts to a different town. Yet
the big prize _ the end of Fidel, the family reunion _ remains
maddeningly elusive. Even their neighbors are puzzled that they
still care, but, then, it isn't their fight.
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that this is at heart a family feud, and that
is true. But it is not just a feud of the Gonzalez klan. A much
larger extended family _ separated by 90 miles, 41 years, and
irreconcilable notions of government and liberty _ is finding that
reunion is impossible, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Adrian Walker is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
