<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IDIOMS STOP MAKING SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can use an everyday idiom for years, and suddenly, one day,
the words look absurd: What does it mean to egg on someone who's
spoiling for a fight? Or maybe you're a fan of professional
verbivore Richard Lederer, who makes a specialty of finding
``contradictions'' in the language: ``How can blunt speech and
sharp speech be the same?'' he asks in ``Crazy English.'' And don't
take that nonstop flight, warns Lederer: ``You'll never get down.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect stranger and broad daylight had Heidi Berger's mother
wondering _ and, writes Berger, ``I had to agree with her they made
no logical sense. Can you enlighten us as to how they came about?''
</P>
<P>
   No problem, to use a more recent catchphrase. Berger's
expressions aren't especially opaque, as idioms go _ in fact,
perfect stranger is in my desk dictionary, illustrating the use of
perfect to mean ``pure, utter, sheer, absolute.'' The reason you
can talk perfect nonsense or have a perfectly awful time is that
perfect comes from the Latin for ``to finish''; its first sense is
completeness rather than goodness.
</P>
<P>
   Broad daylight is also in current dictionaries, with broad
meaning ``extending all about, full''; this may be the only common
phrase with exactly that sense, but it's no more of a stretch than
other figurative uses of the word _ a broad hint, a broad view.
</P>
<P>
   But English offers plenty of idioms that are more obscure.
What's a square meal? Why is a sticky situation a pickle, or even a
pretty pickle? Hot under the collar is obvious _ it would translate
into any language whose speakers wear tailored shirts. But easy as
taking candy from a baby? Clearly coined by someone not familiar
with your typical baby's grip strength. When you make no bones
about it, what are dem bones? And what does a corn dodger dodge?
</P>
<P>
   Other languages have weird idioms too, of course. Peter
Sokolowski, who edits French books for Merriam-Webster, offers the
example il n'y en a pas 36 _ which means ``there aren't many of
them,'' but translates literally as ``there aren't 36.'' Why 36?
Qui sait?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes idioms can be tracked to their origins, but caution is
recommended. Whenever an expression is no longer transparent, folk
etymologies spring up to explain it: Witness the wide circulation
on the Internet of ``Life in the 1500s,'' a collection of spurious
derivations for both unexplained phrases, like raining cats and
dogs, and quite traceable ones, like dead ringer and saved by the
bell.
</P>
<P>
   Even reputable sources can disagree _ which means someone's
leading you astray. Take (up) to the nines, meaning ``to
perfection,'' which we now use almost exclusively in dressed to the
nines. Penguin's Dictionary of English Idioms (1994) says it's ``a
corruption of medieval English `to the eyne' _ `to the eyes,'
meaning from head to foot.'' Sounds perfectly plausible,
considering such similar constructions as armed to the teeth, up to
my eyeballs in work, a lady to her fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Heritage Dictionary of Idioms (1997) says the
original meaning has been lost _ and opines that it probably
``alludes to the fact that nine, the highest single-digit numeral,
stands for `best.' '' (Or did, before the movie ``10'' made that
number the synonym for perfection.)
</P>
<P>
   Penguin says cut no ice, meaning ``have no influence,'' refers
to a skate blade cutting into ice; American Heritage traces it to
the days of iceboxes, when the iceman would saw off a chunk for
each customer. They can't both be right _ so check carefully before
you start telling your friends what idioms ``really'' mean.
</P>
<P>
   Derivations are a secondary issue, though, as long as we all
agree on what the expressions mean now. Objecting to them on
grounds of ``logic'' simply misunderstands the nature of language:
All these symbols are arbitrary (why call a shoe a shoe, or a
lentil a lentil?), and we constantly use combinations of words that
can't be reduced to their literal meanings: He went ballistic, I've
got to knuckle down, she gets my goat. Exploring the origins of
``crazy English'' can be fun, but don't get sidetracked by the
notion that idiomatic language ``doesn't make sense.'' To sensible
people, it's perfectly clear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to
her at The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.
</P>
</TEXT>
