<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PEOPLE IN GRAHAM THINK THE TOWN OUGHT TO BE IN PICTURES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once you get beyond the stacks of rusted oil-well equipment,
Graham blossoms into a picturesque town. And now some members of
the community think that picture ought to be on the silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Graham's Main Street Motion Picture
Committee is holding a special event intended to heighten
Hollywood's recognition of the North Texas city. That shouldn't be
difficult, because Hollywood has heretofore never recognized
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has invited Earl Bellamy, a motion picture
director, to take a look at the town and lend his advice. Graham
wants to know what it has to do to draw movie crews. It wants to be
a movie location.
</P>
<P>
   Bellamy has directed movies and television shows. His TV credits
include ``MASH,'' ``The Andy Griffith Show,'' ``Get Smart,'' ``The
Love Boat'' and ``Fantasy Island.'' His movies include ``Seven
Alone'' and ``Fluffy.''
</P>
<P>
   The later stars Tony Randall and Shirley Jones. It is a film
about a college professor who believes that all animals can be
domesticated, even a lion. The film will be shown Wednesday night
at the National Theatre on the town square's west side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Joyer brought us the idea of drawing movies here,'' said
Claire Spivey, executive director of the Graham Chamber of
Commerce. ``Joe is in the oil business here in Graham, but his
father was a director in Hollywood, and he knew Mr. Bellamy.''
</P>
<P>
   Spivey said that once the idea of movies was raised, several
people in the community began to consider the possibility
seriously. Tickets to Wednesday night's meeting with Bellamy have
sold quickly.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that two of Bellamy's friends also will be on
hand _ Dale Robertson and Dean Smith. Robertson, some people will
remember, was agent Jim Hardie in ``Tales of Wells Fargo''; Smith
began his career as a stuntman and as an actor appeared in the John
Wayne movies ``Big Jake,'' ``Rio Lobo'' and ``El Dorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is originally from Breckenridge, and he attended school in
Graham. He, too, has offered to help the town find its way into the
movie business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just think our community is unique,'' Spivey said. ``We
have the largest town square in America. We have a fort near here.
We could use a new industry, the new revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham has what amounts to two town squares placed together. On
one side rests the Young County Courthouse; on the other sits an
American Legion post, the Sheriff's Department and an old post
office that is now a museum and art center.
</P>
<P>
   The fort is Fort Belknap, established in 1851 as the
northernmost of a chain of forts from the Red River to the Rio
Grade that protected Texas against hostile Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the other forts, Belknap hasn't been fully
restored, and it needs a little work if it is to ever serve as a
movie set. ``I believe it could be used,'' Spivey said, ``but it is
one of the forts that probably needs a little more attention. It
doesn't have the barracks-style setup like Fort Concho in San
Angelo.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Graham does sit in a beautifully preserved part of the
state. Long, rolling hills filled with mesquite, cedar and post oak
surround the city. Development has been held to the nearby
oilfields, where low-profile pump jacks are hidden behind trees and
rocks. Only an occasional power line ruins the open horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly recognize that there are a lot of beautiful parts
of Texas,'' Spivey said. ``But we believe ours is unique too, and
we hope to create an interest in it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
