<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3449 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES     04-11 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOOK SET IN POST-WAR EUROPE OFFERS ADVENTURE ON THE RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOBBIE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (``The Runner.'' By Christopher Reich. Delacorte. $26.95. 448
pages.)
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Reich's terrific debut thriller, ``Numbered
Account,'' was on the New York Times bestseller list for 11 weeks.
His post-World War II thriller, ``The Runner,'' should do even
better.
</P>
<P>
   Devlin Parnell Judge had spent the war working in the U.S.
Attorney's office in New York. Now he is in Paris as a member of
the International Military Tribunal, which will try Nazi leaders
for war crimes. Judge has a personal reason for being on the
tribunal. On Dec. 17, 1944, 113 Americans surrendered to a German
tank column at Malmedy, Belgium. They were disarmed and herded into
a field, where the Germans opened fire. Then two SS officers went
into the field and ``administered the coup de grace as necessary.''
Seventy-three were killed and 40 escaped by running into the nearby
woods or playing dead. Among the dead was Judge's brother, Francis
Xavier Judge, a chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Devlin Judge tracks down a German report that names
the SS officer who gave the order to fire, Major Erich Seyss, known
as Germany's White Lion, the runner who was expected to defeat
Jesse Owens at the 1936 Olympics. Then Judge learns that Seyss has
just escaped from a prisoner-of-war camp in Bavaria. He gets
permission to go to Gen. George Patton's headquarters in Bavaria
and lead the hunt for Seyss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Runner'' is an intriguingly crafted cat-and-mouse hunt
that takes Judge and his prey from Bavaria to Berlin and back to
Patton's headquarters. The intensity of the chase is fueled by
realistic dialogue and well-drawn characters. Move over, Jack
Higgins and Robert Ludlum, Reich has grabbed hold of your genre and
made it sing.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (``Half Moon Street.'' By Anne Perry. Ballantine. $25. 311
pages.)
</P>
<P>
   Anne Perry's latest Victorian mystery featuring Bow Street
Superintendent Thomas Pitt has a lost feel to it. Something key is
missing.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, Pitt is called to the banks of the Thames to
inspect the body of a male murder victim found drifting in a punt.
The victim's hands and feet have been chained to the sides of the
punt, he is wearing a torn green dress and flowers are strewn
around the body.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering that a French diplomat has been reported missing,
Pitt sends a constable to the French Embassy in London to request
that someone come to take a look at the body. The envoy says the
victim is not the missing diplomat, so now Pitt has two cases to
solve.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt's investigation will lead him to a photography club and a
very bohemian actress. And throughout the investigation, Pitt seems
a lost soul because his wife, Charlotte, and his children are away
on holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte's absence clearly hurts ``Half Moon Street'' because
in all the previous books in the series, Charlotte's involvement in
his investigations added greatly to the stories. There is nothing
wrong with the plot, the dialogue or the pacing. But it desperately
needs the warmth that Charlotte has given to the series.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (``Blind Instinct.'' By Robert W. Walker. Berkley Books. $21.95.
369 pages.)
</P>
<P>
   If you are a fan of Patricia Cornwell's series featuring Dr.
Kate Scarpetta, you will enjoy ``Blind Instinct,'' whose
protagonist is Dr. Jessica Coran, the FBI's top forensic
pathologist.
</P>
<P>
   Working at the Behavioral Science Unit at Quantico, Va., Coran
is awaiting the shipment of the body of a man who had been
viciously attacked and killed by a pack of rabid dogs. He carried
no identification. His entire body is covered in tattoos. If they
can find the artist, they can learn the victim's identity, then
figure out who wanted him dead.
</P>
<P>
   Before the body arrives, she receives a call from Inspector
Richard Sharpe of New Scotland Yard asking what she knew about
murder by crucifixion. Sharpe says he and his colleague believe an
unidentified woman died of the wounds she received when she was
nailed to a cross. ``Then you are already wrong,'' Coran tells
Sharpe. ``If she hung from the cross for any length of time, and
from the sound of her wounds _ I've heard talk over the Internet
about the case, and the gaps where gravity did its work around the
spike  &Cx1f; _ then I must say she died of asphyxiation, not her
crucifixion wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks later, Sharpe shows up at Quantico and says there
are now two more victims. He requests that Coran go to London to
help in the investigation of the crucifixion murders. Her superiors
agree, and she flies to London to help develop a profile that will
help track down the killer. Meanwhile, she stays in touch with her
aides at Quantico and continues to work on the case of the tattooed
man.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Walker deftly handles the two investigations. Coran
and Sharpe are both very likable and believable characters. The
murders are ingenious. Well-paced, ``Blind Instinct'' is worthy of
the bestseller list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
