<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM PROVES LOVE HASN'T GONE OUT OF STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the ferocious storm that tore through the
Metroplex recently, many heartwarming stories of courage and
compassion have emerged. I have seen numerous media stories
detailing the heroic acts of men and women who risked life and limb
to protect their families.
</P>
<P>
   It's good to know that love has not gone out of style.
</P>
<P>
   In my own neighborhood, I personally witnessed an act of bravery
that I think deserves a Medal of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the storm, I was in bed using an adding machine
to count the days to my retirement. It was a beautiful, sunny
evening, and I was totally unaware of the evil winds blowing our
way. My children, who were watching television in another room,
alerted us to the storm warnings. Moments later, as if on cue, the
sky became ashen with fear. The calm winds became restless, and the
clouds started to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's just another Texas thunderstorm, I thought. It'll blow
over like they always do. I barely stirred from my resting place.
My family, however, hovered in front of the television watching the
progress of the storm. My spouse, who thinks I'm afraid of
thunderstorms, invited me to join the family in the den. I declined
until the thunder and lightning got into a shouting match.
</P>
<P>
   Like a kid, I went running into the den with my pillow and my
blanket. My husband smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about the children,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   As the storm grew worse, we huddled and debated whether or not
we needed to move into the closet or bathroom. The storm was a few
miles southwest of our home when the pitter-patter of hail began to
serenade us through the window. My spouse located the flashlight
while I lit a few candles in anticipation of a power outage.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I remembered the family that lives in our back yard.
Marie Antoinette and her husband live on our patio. My husband
tried to make them move but they refuse to leave. Marie is
expecting twins, so I asked him to let them stay until the children
are born and then we can find them a nice home. He's mad because
they killed his hanging plants. Marie resides in one plant with her
eggs and the Dad lives in the other one.
</P>
<P>
   They're pretty quiet birds and they don't poop all over the
place, so I don't have a problem with them. The plants were going
to die eventually, anyway. Now those crows that sit on the roof and
peck at the gutter really tick me off, but these birds are nice. I
don't know what kind of birds they are, but they look sort of like
doves. They have huge necks like Mike Tyson and long tails that
hang out of the plants when they roost. They're not white, though.
I learned only eight colors in elementary school, so it's hard for
me to describe anything that's not one of those colors. If you've
seen the book ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' they're the same shade as
the background on the cover. If you haven't seen the book, then
they're sort of gray.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I gathered up my courage and peeped out of the window to
see how our Marie and company were faring. The hanging plants were
whipping around like a trapeze at the circus. It seemed like they
would fall from the hooks at any moment. The petals on the flowers
had blown away, leaving me a clear view of Marie's little head
peeking over the edge of the basket. The Dad's adopted nest was
deserted. I didn't know that an animal with a brain the size of
marble could have that kind of determination. She was determined to
protect those eggs, come what may.
</P>
<P>
   I considered going outside and putting the basket in a sheltered
area on the patio, but then the warning sirens started blaring and
I had to concern myself with my own family.
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, we were spared any damage in the storm and my heart
goes out to all of the families who suffered such tremendous losses
in the tornado. The following day, I remembered Marie and her
family. I went onto the patio and there she was, still sitting in
her basket, defying the odds.
</P>
<P>
   If it's natural to love your children to the extent that you'd
risk your life for them, it must be unnatural to feel any other
way. That's as basic as the birds and the bees. Don't you think so?
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
