<HEADLINE>
RIPPLEWOOD PLANS TO INVEST IN JAPANESE CHEMICAL INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Ripplewood Holdings LLC, the Wall Street investment firm
that recently bought one of Japan's nationalized banks, said
Tuesday that it is pursuing investment opportunities in Japan's
chemical industries.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Greenwich Chemical Partners LLC, Ripplewood plans
to use some of its $1 billion fund for Japanese investments to buy
stakes in chemical concerns here. Greenwich Chemical, headed by
John A. Georges, the former top executive of International Paper,
is one of Ripplewood's ``industrial partners,'' an investment and
advisory firm that will oversee the investments in this particular
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The firms said they believe that the Japanese chemical industry
is poised to follow patterns that are reshaping its counterpart in
the United States, where companies such as Monsanto and DuPont are
moving into areas like agricultural biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect they're in a different stage in terms of their
willingness and know-how, but they will move in similar
directions,'' Georges said.
</P>
<P>
   Georges said Ripplewood is in the process of purchasing a
specialty chemical company in the United States for roughly $500
million. That deal will give it a plant and research lab in Japan.
He declined to name the company because the deal has not been
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Ripplewood leads the consortium of investment banks that bought
bankrupt Long-Term Credit Bank from the government, making it the
first foreign owner of a Japanese bank.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has also announced plans to buy Japanese hotel
properties in partnership with Marriott. Thus far, however, those
plans have bogged down over differences about the value of the
properties, with Japanese hotel owners complaining privately that
Ripplewood is seeking exceedingly low sale prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
