<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3473 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MAYOR-INVESTMENTS-HNS     04-11 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-INVESTMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RECORDS SHOW LINK BETWEEN MAYOR, INVESTMENT BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHUCK FINNIE and LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three months after it cut Mayor Willie Brown in
on a string of red-hot initial stock offerings, the Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter investment bank was chosen to underwrite a $28 million
bond issue for the San Francisco International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Airport Director John Martin on March 23 chose Morgan Stanley
for the bond deal because the investment company submitted a
competitive bid that carried the lowest interest costs, airport
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they were unaware of the mayor's stock trades
when Morgan Stanley was selected as lead underwriter on the bonds,
issued to pay for the construction of an airport parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   According to public records, after a Morgan Stanley broker
steered some lucrative stock deals to Brown, the company was
soliciting bond underwriting business at the airport, which is run
by a commission appointed by the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In a financial disclosure report filed last week with the San
Francisco Ethics Commission, Brown said he had invested in eight
companies during a four-week period last year at the height of his
re-election campaign. The shares, representing companies that were
selling stock for the first time, soared in value on the day they
were first traded publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, his press office said Brown bought the shares
independently as an e-trader, but later the mayor said he invested
$25,000 through a Morgan Stanley broker. Three months later, the
IPO portfolio Brown bought was valued at about $40,000, according
to stock tables.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley is a big player in municipal finance in
California, and in 1997 Brown himself tapped the company to
underwrite $100 million worth of bonds for the new San Francisco
49ers stadium. The project has stalled and the bonds were never
issued.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Morgan Stanley said it had no bond business with the
city. After reporters called the company's attention to the airport
bonds, Ray O'Rourke, a Morgan Stanley spokesman in New York, said
that the investment bank had not mentioned the airport deal because
it viewed the airport as an independent agency.
</P>
<P>
   He said the investment bank's bond underwriting business is
managed separately from its stock brokerage services and that the
company got no help from the mayor's office in landing the airport
bond deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a competitive bid. We offered the very best interest
rate and we were awarded the loan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said the bank was reviewing its brokerage
arrangement with Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make absolutely sure no industry regulations or
internal policies were violated,'' he said. ``We are concerned
about the appearances this situation presents.''
</P>
<P>
   No laws or regulations prohibit investment banks from giving
preferential treatment to elected officials looking for a piece of
a highly sought after IPO, finance experts said.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has banned
so-called ``pay for play'' dynamics in municipal finance, schemes
in which investment bankers made hefty campaign donations to local
officials in exchange for the right to compete for lucrative
municipal bond underwriting contracts. Violators can be barred from
bidding on public finance deals for up to two years.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC and the National Association of Securities Dealers also
have moved to regulate so-called ``spinning'' of hot IPO shares, in
which brokerage firms seeking corporate finance business steer IPOs
to the personal investment accounts of executives at the companies
being wooed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither set of rules applies specifically to the scenario of a
brokerage tossing hot IPOs to a powerful politician while at the
same time it is seeking bond contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Political Reform Act forbids California officials
from accepting gifts valued at more than $300. But the 1974 law
apparently does not apply to initial stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no Political Reform Act implications because there
were no IPOs when the act was written,'' said Robert Stern,
president of the Center for Government Studies in Los Angeles and
the law's co-author.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's foray into IPO investing ``certainly is a story and
certainly is news, but I don't think it is illegal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, O'Rourke and Rose Pak, Chinatown activist and a
Brown confidante, offered details of how the mayor became a stock
trading client of Morgan Stanley during a chance meeting with a
broker from Morgan Stanley's Fremont office at a San Francisco
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   By this account, the broker, whom O'Rourke and Pak declined to
identify, approached Brown and pitched the mayor on investing in
the initial public offering of United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   The broker, according to O'Rourke, hoped that by cutting Brown
in on some IPOs he would cultivate him as a long-term client.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing sinister. He was just in awe and worshiped the
mayor,'' Pak said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown opened an account with Morgan Stanley and on Nov. 9 bought
$20,000 worth of UPS stock at the initial price of $50, according
to a memo on the transactions provided by the mayor's office. The
stock rose to $67 at the close of its first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   In the month that followed, according to the memo, Brown bought
a handful of shares in seven hot IPOs, including such market
winners as Cache Flow Inc., which rose from $24 to $126 on its
first day of trading, and McAfee Communications, which went from a
$12 opening price to $44 at first close.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Brown flipped the IPO shares his broker sold him,
selling his 25 shares of Microsoft spin-off Expedia Inc. two days
after buying them, making a $975 profit.
</P>
<P>
   According to his disclosure report, Brown held onto the other
stocks he bought from Morgan Stanley at least until the end of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   By last week, those stocks had risen in value from their
purchase price of $25,000 to more than $40,000, a $15,000 gain.
Brown has declined to comment on whether he still owns the stocks.
He told a reporter last week that he had closed the Morgan Stanley
account because the commissions were too high.
</P>
</TEXT>
