<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATS-FARMERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN `GOTHAM CITY,' FARMERS SEE OLD ENEMIES VANISH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   D'HANIS, Texas _ Joel Curtis was baffled. The traps he hangs in
his pecan orchard to determine how much pesticide to spray usually
snare between 80 and 100 moths each. But the numbers last spring
were down to only a handful.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis thought the warm, dry winter might have killed the
destructive insects. He eventually would entertain another
possibility after he and his son Jeff noticed a large, dark mass
swirling one evening over the nearby Seco Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just about dark, and I said, `Look at the
blackbirds,''' Curtis said recently. But he and his son reflected
that blackbirds don't usually arrive until the fall. ``And we
looked and looked, and Jeff said, `That's not blackbirds. That's
bats.'''
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that bats made their home in the narrow foot-deep
crevices under the eastbound and westbound highway bridges of U.S.
90 and a parallel railroad bridge near the Curtis farm, which is
west of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Squeezed into the dark spaces between concrete beams, the bats
are small and hard to see, but their presence is impossible to
overlook.
</P>
<P>
   The ground is covered with linear mounds of pungent guano, and
the bats' squeaky chatter is audible even over the steady rumble of
trucks and cars traveling overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Gotham City of Highway 90,'' Joel Curtis said as
the mammals congregated overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Sams, an agricultural consultant who specializes in pest
management, believes the insect-eating bats are keeping Curtis'
pecans from being assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Merlin Tuttle, founder and executive director of Bat
Conservation International, an Austin-based educational group,
estimates the D'Hanis bat colony is bigger than the 1.5 million
bats that inhabit the Congress Avenue bridge in Austin, the largest
urban bat colony in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle told a public health conference last month that there
were some 2 million bats in D'Hanis.
</P>
<P>
   In that lecture, Tuttle described the results of new research on
the immense agricultural impact of Texas' 100 million Mexican
free-tailed bats. These are the most common of the state's 33 bat
species, and the predominant species found in the Austin and
D'Hanis colonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they found is that the bats were flying down night after
night to eat crop pests that come out of agricultural areas near
San Antonio,'' Tuttle said. ``Each spring _ and this is very little
known _ there are literally billions of the most costly farm pests
in America that migrate into the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican free-tailed bats fly as high as two miles into the
air to intercept egg-laying female moths that carry hundreds of
eggs each, Tuttle said. If one bat eats just 20 moths in a single
night, Tuttle said, it is as effective as a farmer paying $32 to
spray 2 acres of cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle said irrational fear by humans of the winged mammals has
led to the destruction of large colonies in caves and mines in
Mexico and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very lucky here,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
