<HEADER>
A3557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MARINE-PLANE-HNS &LR;      04-11 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-PLANE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FATHER OF CRASH VICTIM QUESTIONS SAFETY OF MARINE AIRCRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The father of a Marine killed in last weekend's
crash of an MV-22 Osprey said his son complained two months before
the accident that the tilt-rotor aircraft was ``fragile'' and
unsafe to fly.
</P>
<P>
   In what would be their final conversation, William D. Nelson
said his son, Staff Sgt. William Bryan Nelson, described the Osprey
as a problem-plagued craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he told me, it was so fragile every time they took it up
and each time they brought it back (it) had all kinds of problems,
all kinds of parts, things that went wrong that wasn't really
imaginable,'' Nelson said in a telephone interview from his home in
Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he didn't think it was safe to fly, and that's all he
told me,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft crashed Saturday at an airport 30 miles northwest
of Tucson, Ariz., killing 19 Marines.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps and the manufacturers of the aircraft, Bell
Helicopter Textron of Fort Worth, Texas, and Boeing Co. in Ridley
Park, Pa., said the Osprey was safe.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Helicopter Textron spokesman Bob Leder noted the Osprey had
logged more than 4,000 hours in the air since making its first
flight in March 1989. He said the craft, which can take off and
hover like a helicopter but fly like a plane, had passed extensive
testing and ``performed extraordinarily well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no indication from anywhere that there's a fundamental
flaw in the aircraft,'' Leder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where the word fragile could have entered into
the lexicon in describing the Osprey,'' a Marine Corps spokesman,
Capt. Pete Mitchell, said in response to Nelson's comments.
</P>
<P>
   But some congressional supporters of the Osprey, among them Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, expressed concern about reports of
problems with the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison and Rep. Ciro Rodriguez, D-Texas, called for an
exhaustive investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family members of the fallen Marines deserve a thorough
investigation of the accident, and Marines everywhere need
assurances that the MV-22 is an airworthy aircraft,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we must be sure what happened before they go forward
with any further training or testing operations,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   The crash was the third Osprey accident in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Two crew members safely ejected when an Osprey crashed at
Boeing's Flight Test Development Center in Wilmington, Del., on
June 11, 1991. Another V-22 fell into waters off Quantico, Va., on
July 20, 1992, killing seven. A pair of badly wired gyros was
blamed for the first crash, while mechanical failure was found to
have triggered a fire that disabled an engine in the second
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines have ordered 360 Ospreys to be delivered over a
decade at a price of $44 million each. The Air Force Special
Operations Command has bought 50 V-22s, while the Navy wants a
fleet of 48.
</P>
<P>
   Faster and able to carry more than the CH-46 ``Sea Knight''
helicopter now used by the Marines, the Osprey is able to hold 24
combat-ready soldiers, hover and land like a helicopter and post
cruising speeds of 325 mph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
