<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-DIVERSIFY-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDI ARABIA TO EASE RESTRICTIONS ON FOREIGN INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Anxious to demonstrate a new economic openness
that could help its bid to join the World Trade Organization and to
expand its private sector, Saudi Arabia announced a new law Tuesday
that will permit foreigners to own their investments and property
in the kingdom without a Saudi partner.
</P>
<P>
   The law, approved by King Fahd on Monday, also promises to
strengthen judicial protection for investments, foster greater
public disclosure in financial dealings and lower corporate taxes
on foreign companies with profits exceeding 100,000 rials (about
$26,600) a year, the official Saudi Press Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The easing of restrictions on foreign investors has been under
discussion for some time but intensified in the last six months,
after the king told his country that it could not ignore the trend
toward globalization and free markets. The new investment code is
also supported by Crown Prince Abdullah, a powerful figure who has
taken on a wider role in the country's affairs from his ailing
brother Fahd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law aims to improve the investment environment in the
kingdom, remove existing obstacles, improve efficiency and ensure
flexibility,'' said Hashem Yamani, the industry and electricity
minister, in a statement carried by the Saudi news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Yamani's ministry now licenses most direct foreign investment,
but investors in projects related to other areas have sometimes had
to apply to multiple ministries.
</P>
<P>
   The new law would set up a single agency to consider investment
projects and reduce bureaucratic delays. The agency would be
required to act within 30 days on proposals from foreigners, who
would also gain the right to appeal its decisions.
</P>
<P>
   For more than four years, Saudi Arabia has been negotiating for
entry into the World Trade Organization, the Geneva-based group
that sets the standards for global commerce. Membership in the
organization greatly enhances a nation's ability to export goods
and services. The Saudi application for membership has been
hindered by the country's laws, regulations and traditions that
favor Saudis, impose high tariffs and subsidize some exports like
petrochemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, foreign investors in the insular Gulf kingdom needed
a Saudi national as a partner to do business _ first as a sponsor
in order to obtain a work visa and then as a majority partner in
any project. Foreigners were allowed to hold a maximum stake in any
business of just 49 percent and could not own property, engage in
distribution or internal commerce.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Acting as a paid sponsor for foreigners, who must relinquish
their passports to the sponsor while in the country, has been a
common method for members of the large extended royal family to
earn extra income.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, most Gulf countries have searched for ways
to diversify their economies and wean themselves from near-total
dependence on oil revenue, a quest that took on new urgency when
world oil prices plummeted a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At enormous cost, for example, Saudi Arabia became a major wheat
exporter by investing in agriculture as part of a plan to become
self-sufficient in food. But up to 85 percent of its export
earnings and about 40 percent of its gross domestic product still
comes from oil.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment now is centered on oil-related industries
like petrochemicals, and Saudi Arabia is expected to maintain its
government monopoly on oil exploration and development. But
representatives of 10 international oil companies have been invited
to Riyadh later this month to discuss proposals for investing in
other areas of the oil industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
