<HEADER>
A3564 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-NETFUTURE-EFFECT-NYTS     04-11 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFUTURE-EFFECT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRARY EXPECTATIONS AND THE `180-DEGREE EFFECT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Chuck Martin is the author of ``Net Future,'' published by
McGraw-Hill, and chairman of the Net Future Institute. He also is
author of The New York Times Business Bestseller ``The Digital
Estate.'')
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By CHUCK MARTIN  
 c.2000 Chuck Martin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most companies have discovered that the dynamics of the Internet
are different from those of the traditional business environment.
But many have not realized just how different they are, and how
much change may be involved in blending them.
</P>
<P>
   The collision and integration of the traditional and online
worlds create a new dynamic of contrary expectations. In this new
world, things are not as they appear, and they're certainly not an
extension of the past. In fact, they often are exactly the opposite
of what one would expect.
</P>
<P>
   I call this impact of the Net ``the 180-degree effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The most famous early example was Netscape's giving away its
browser, which was then its key product. That challenged the
assumption that the core product should be what people pay for. It
stood the notion of ``value'' on its head. Value was no longer
measured by revenue from base product, but by market share and
speed of product introduction.
</P>
<P>
   What does the 180-degree effect look like in the Net Future?
</P>
<P>
   -- Customers are charged less for delivery of several pounds of
groceries ordered online than for an ounce of paper delivered
overnight by the same delivery company.
</P>
<P>
   -- Real-time stock quotes, formerly a core asset for Wall Street
brokers, become available to all through the Net.
</P>
<P>
   -- America Online not long ago paid content providers to supply
information to its network. Now it's the other way around. Content
providers offer hefty fees to be featured on AOL. The company even
became the acquirer of Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   -- Customers used to simply buy the product. Now, in true
180-degree fashion, customers are providing the product.
Amazon.com, which began by supplying a large inventory to its
customers, is now letting customers supply the inventory. Anyone
can list an item for sale in Amazon's zSHOPS; the seller is
responsible for shipping. And like eBay and other sites, Amazon.com
runs online auctions.
</P>
<P>
   With so many opportunities, many companies have to decide which
businesses they are not in, rather than which businesses to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   The 180-degree effect will increasingly affect how companies
need to develop their approach to E-Business and how to blend their
traditional and online operations.
</P>
<P>
   How should a company use the 180-degree effect to advantage?
First, by starting to think that way. When looking at how to move
its business into the Net environment, a company should think about
what it would do in a ``normal'' world. What would the business
plan look like? Put all the elements on paper -- every assumption
and every projection, five years out.
</P>
<P>
   Then -- and this is the hard part -- challenge every single
assumption. What if the entire pricing strategy were exactly
reversed? What if a competitor was not one of the company's
traditional competitors, but from a different industry altogether?
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate question that arises from this change involves the
entire value chain of the company. When considering the impact of
the Net, a true E-Business thinks about product conception,
manufacturing, distribution and consumption. But it also needs to
think about what would happen if that entire chain were subject to
the 180-degree effect. What if the process were flipped end-to-end,
so that the value chain is driven by the customer rather than by
the company?
</P>
<P>
   The concept of the consumer truly being in charge of the
process, using mechanisms such as real-time feedback and enhanced
information distribution, is probably one of the most powerful
business notions brought about by the Netting of the world. It
involves much more than lip service or a mission statement with
platitudes about ``the customer coming first.'' It requires both
action and attitude to take a hard look at whether some fairly
dramatic changes are needed to stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   For some companies, that, too, may feel like a 180-degree
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   (Chuck Martin can be reached at
cmartin(at)netfutureinstitute.com.)
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
