<P>
   CHEFS (New York) _ Chefs have gone from being essentially
blue-collar workers to true professionals, as much in demand as
athletes. The top players, like Daniel Boulud and Jean-Georges
Vongerichten and Alice Waters, have become brand names, and their
proteges, like Richard. Farnabe, use those brands as a springboard
for their careers. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   COLE-ORGANIC-FARM (Washington, Va.) _ Sunrise at Sunnyside Farm
is greeted by a ritual that startles the uninitiated. Workers
advance upon windowless structures on wheels scattered around the
539 acres and lower the sides, releasing thousands of peeping
chickens eager for a good day's work at what they do best. Eating
bugs. David Cole, venture capitalist, philanthropist and organic
farmer, uses these coops on wheels to move his chickens where the
pecking is needed most. The mobile units are just one of many
labor-saving methods he employs on the organic farm he started five
years ago in the middle of Rappahannock County, home to the very
rich who have made their money elsewhere and to farmers who barely
make a living. By Marian Burros.
</P>
