A3579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      04-11 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COLUMN: TANDOORI IN A FLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two ways to think of tandoori chicken. Strictly
defined, it is chicken marinated in yogurt and spices and cooked in
a tandoor, a clay oven that is most often used to bake bread. But
you can also think of it as chicken in a yogurt and spice sauce
that is simply grilled or broiled.
</P>
<P>
   In much tandoori-style cooking, the yogurt is used not only as a
flavoring but as a tenderizer. But today's chicken needs no
tenderizing. To make a quick, really easy tandoori chicken, start
with a boneless, skinless breast. You can assemble the marinade in
less time than it takes to preheat the broiler or grill.
</P>
<P>
   The chicken breasts sit in the yogurt mixture for as little as
five minutes, and it doesn't make a whole lot of difference if you
allow them to sit longer. A soak of about an hour allowed a little
more of the flavor to permeate the flesh, but after six hours the
chicken began to turn mushy.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant flavors in most tandoori marinades are garlic,
ginger and coriander, although cumin, cardamom, turmeric and other
typically Indian spices are sometimes added. Paprika adds a little
heat as well as the traditional red color. Lime juice accentuates
and freshens the acidity of the yogurt, and a garnish of minced
cilantro adds color.
</P>
<P>
   The yogurt mixture is so creamy and delicious that I like to
double the quantity and broil the chicken so I can use the cooked
sauce and meat drippings to top cooked rice. If you don't make rice
or prefer to grill halve the quantities for the yogurt and spices
below.
</P>
<P>
   FAST CHICKEN TANDOORI
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   Juice of a lime
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   Minced cilantro for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat broiler or grill. Combine yogurt, ginger, garlic,
paprika, coriander, half the lime juice and salt and pepper to
taste in a large bowl. If chicken breasts are whole, cut them in
half. Dredge chicken in yogurt mixture and marinate 5 to 60
minutes, as time allows.
</P>
<P>
   2. If you're broiling, line a baking sheet with aluminum foil
for easier cleanup. To broil, put chicken breasts on pan, underside
facing up; reserve any marinade that does not cling to the breasts.
Broil 3 to 4 minutes, or until lightly browned. Turn chicken and
spoon remaining marinade over. Broil on smooth side another 3 to 4
minutes, or until lightly browned. Garnish, add remaining lime
juice over chicken and serve, spooning the cooked marinade over the
meat and, if you're serving it, over some rice.
</P>
<P>
   3. If you're grilling, simply grill 3 to 4 minutes a side, or
until chicken browns and is cooked through, brushing with the
marinade from time to time. Garnish, add lime and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
