<HEADLINE>
A CORNUCOPIA OF SEDER WINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the wide range of kosher wines available these days,
choosing bottles for the Passover seder should be no more difficult
than picking wines for Thanksgiving. Come to think of it, that may
be a problem, since the annual Thanksgiving selection seems to
paralyze many people.
</P>
<P>
   So first things first: relax. Choosing the right wine merits no
more agonizing than achieving featherweight matzo balls. Of course,
you may enjoy the wines recommended here more than others.
</P>
<P>
   A seder is a dinner party, and the usual guidelines apply: for
large groups, consider less-expensive bottles and offer both red
and white. For smaller groups, you may decide to pay more.
</P>
<P>
   Kosher wines can be as expensive as any other category.
Laurent-Perrier, a very good Champagne house, offers a kosher
bottle for around $50, and you can spend $25 to $50 for a cabernet
sauvignon from Herzog, the fine-wine label of Baron Herzog, a big
kosher producer.
</P>
<P>
   You can offer a progression of wines if you like, beginning with
a dry white like the Beckett's Flat semillon from Australia, made
from the same grape as dry white Bordeaux. Follow with a riesling
or a Barbera d'Asti and then a cabernet sauvignon. Finish with a
sweet wine, and not necessarily one of those sticky Concord grape
wines to which many Jews cling sentimentally, but a fine sweet wine
that makes a delicious dessert like the Gan Eden late-harvest
gewurztraminer.
</P>
<P>
   What makes a wine kosher? There is no strict agreement on this
point, though in general kosher wine must be made with equipment
used exclusively for kosher wines and handled only by observant
Jews who use only kosher ingredients. Many kosher wines are
flash-pasteurized _ heated briefly and then brought back to normal
temperature _ although, again, people disagree on whether this is
necessary and how it affects the wines.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that these wines, called mevushal, can be handled by
the general public and remain kosher. Yet not all kosher wines are
mevushal, and it's only occasionally clear from the label whether a
wine is or is not. Regardless, these wines are good first and
kosher second.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's Flat, Semillon, Margaret River, Australia, 1999, $26
</P>
<P>
   A zesty dry wine with appealingly fruity aromas and citrus
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Gan Eden, Late Harvest Gewurztraminer (umlaut over u), Monterey
County, 1997 $12.50
</P>
<P>
   Beautifully balanced sweet wine with classic floral aroma. and
honeyed fruit flavor. A great value.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog Special Reserve, Cabernet Sauvignon, Alexander Valley,
1997 $26
</P>
<P>
   Rich and concentrated yet soft and easy to drink, with aromas of
plum, cassis and menthol.
</P>
<P>
   Baron Herzog, Chenin Blanc, Clarksburg, 1999 $7
</P>
<P>
   Slightly sweet yet bright and refreshing, with peach and grassy
aromas and citrus flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Hagafen, Johannisberg Riesling, Napa Valley, 1999 $14
</P>
<P>
   Slightly sweet and almost dry with peach and lemon flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Bartenura, Barbera d'Asti, 1998 $8
</P>
<P>
   Almost purple, grapey but dry and nicely acidic. Pleasant and
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Listed in order of preference. Prices are those paid in various
Manhattan wine shops.
</P>
</TEXT>
