<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-CUBANS-ART-2TAKES-     04-11 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CUBANS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION CITY, N.J.: THE CUBAN-AMERICAN HEARTLAND, NORTHERN VERSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT28, 30 were sent April 10 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION CITY, N.J. _ Eyes wide with rage, their voices raw from
shouting, the graying Cuban exiles marched through the streets last
week carrying posters of Elian Gonzalez, votive candles and
American or Cuban flags. Some wept as they chanted ``Libertad para
Elian'' while others nearly hissed as they offered unkind words for
Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly Cuban-born, a number of them former political prisoners,
the 200 or so demonstrators had come from across the New York
metropolitan area to add their voices to the louder, more potent
outcry from their compatriots in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways it was a predictable scene in an unpredictable
place. The protest was not in Miami, but in this densely populated
blue-collar city just across the Hudson from Manhattan, which along
with the other towns of Hudson County is home to the biggest bloc
of Cuban immigrants outside Dade County, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than the stereotypical scene of Cuban unanimity, life
in Union City is a window onto the twists, complications and
ambiguities of the Cuban-American experience as it plays out in
``La Zona Norte,'' as Cuban-Americans call the New York
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban immigrants here, for the most part, favor keeping Elian
Gonzalez in the United States, much as their countrymen in Miami
do. But the Cuban population here tends to be more liberal than in
Miami. It is not clustered in an insulated enclave, and is
undergoing suburbanization much like any other ethnic group. And
Union City, which once was dominated by Germans, the Irish and
Italians, became overwhelmingly Cuban for a while, but Cuban
migration and the arrival of new immigrants from elsewhere in Latin
American have significantly cut the Cuban numbers here.
</P>
<P>
   In short, its history is a microcosm of the pull between
assimilation and cultural identity that is the story of the
immigrant experience in America. So even the Cubans who settled
here, then took off for the green suburbs nearby, still return to
Bergenline Avenue on weekends for cups of thick, strong Cuban
coffee, staples like guava paste and yucca or the politically
charged banter that fills the Union City Cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, there's nothing I can't buy in my local
supermarket, but I still come here to shop anyway,'' said Vivian
Ortiz, 39, an insurance adjuster who grew up off Bergenline Avenue
but now lives in suburban Ridgefield. ``It's silly, but I can't get
this place out of my blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban roots of Union City can be traced to Lyda and Manuel
Rodriguez, a newlywed couple from the central Cuban town of
Fomento. They were the first Cubans in the area, arriving in 1948,
and when news of their success took hold in Fomento and others soon
followed, many of them finding jobs in the area's embroidery mills.
``When we arrived, everyone was German or Italian,'' Mrs. Rodriguez
said in a telephone interview from her home in Tampa, Fla. ``But
soon enough, that changed.'' By the early 1960's, when it became
clear that Castro had embraced communism, the trickle of Cuban
immigration became a flood.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Miami were alarmed by the surge and pushed federal
authorities to help relocate some of the refugees elsewhere. With
an abundance of manufacturing jobs and a solid Cuban presence,
Union City and nearby towns received many of them. Today, the
largest group of Cubans in Hudson County are from rural Fomento,
unlike Miami, where Havana residents tended to settle.
</P>
<P>
   Albio Sires, 49, the mayor of West New York, whose family
arrived here when he was 11, remembers being the only
Spanish-speaking student in school. By the time he got to high
school in 1967, he said, Cubans were a majority in West New York.
``It must have been very difficult for the Irish and the
Italians,'' he said. ``One day they woke up and they were living in
a Cuban town.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to their views on Castro, there is very little to
distinguish Cubans from Florida and New Jersey. Among the two dozen
people on Bergenline Avenue who spoke about Elian Gonzalez, nearly
all of them thought he should remain in the United States, even if
it meant separating him from his father.
</P>
<P>
   While their antipathy toward Castro rivals that of their
countrymen in Miami, New Jersey's Cubans tend to be less
conservative on social issues and nearly every Cuban-American
official in the state, from Rep. Robert Menendez to the mayors of
Union City and West New York, are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   So when it comes to other issues, like affirmative action,
public assistance and civil liberties, the two communities are
often far apart.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Martinez-Fernandez, chairman of Rutgers University's
department of Puerto Rican and Hispanic Caribbean studies, said
that although Cuban immigrants dominate the Miami political
landscape, in New Jersey they have always had to form political
alliances with other ethnic groups. That, he said, has helped make
them more liberal. ``They have never been able to call the shots
like their brethren in South Florida so their politics are not as
conservative or rabidly Cuba-centered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's proximity to Havana also adds fuel to its impassioned
political climate, one that becomes more inflamed each time a Cuban
refugee turns up on a Florida beach. ``Cuban balseros are not
likely to wash up on the Jersey Shore,'' he said, using the word
for refugees who arrive on rafts.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are only 85,000 Cubans in Hudson County, most
elected officials agree that their political heft far outweighs
their numbers. After Italians, they are the largest group of
foreign-born residents in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cubans are one of the most influential groups in the state
because they are so united in purpose, so willing to get involved
and because they vote in numbers disproportionate to their size,''
said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who is a darling of Cuban
exiles and well known in Washington for his hard-line stance
against Castro.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, though Cuban refugees are widely credited with
revitalizing a place that had clearly seen better days, ``Havana on
the Hudson,'' as Union City is sometimes called, is beginning to
feel less and less Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   Like the European immigrants who settled here before them, they
are leaving town for suburbs to the north and west. On Bergenline
Avenue, where more than 90 percent of the businesses were once
Cuban-owned, grocery stores and restaurants are more likely to be
run by Colombians, Ecuadoreans, Peruvians and Dominicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who can afford a house in Bergen County these days
seems to be moving,'' said Yolanda Prieto, a sociology professor at
Ramapo College who is writing a book about the area's Cuban
community. ``Still, even though they are leaving Union City in
droves, they aren't going very far from Bergenline Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate that only 20 percent of Union City's 60,000
residents are Cuban, down from 80 percent in 1970, but the city is
still the symbolic heart of New Jersey's exile community and a
center for anti-Castro activity. Dozens of cultural clubs,
congregations, business groups and political organizations are
based here, as is a branch of the politically influential Cuban
American National Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   And there are still two bus companies that provide direct
service to Miami, one of them named, appropriately enough, Omnibus
La Cubana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like an umbilical cord,'' said Marian Cordova,
the manager of the competing bus line, Astro Eastern, which makes
the trip in 30 hours. But in a sign of the times, she said, fewer
and fewer Cubans are filling the seats. ``Our average passenger
used to be an elderly Cuban visiting family in Miami,'' she said.
``Now they're usually South or Central American, and they're going
to Miami to explore job opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisandro Perez, a sociologist at Florida International
University, said many of the 300,000 who settled in other parts of
the country have been heading south. Dade County now contains 63
percent of the nation's Cubans, he said, up from 42 percent in
1970. ``Miami has become a vacuum sucking Cubans from other
places,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the migration is not a one-way street. Union City's mayor,
Raul Garcia, 36, who was born in Cuba but grew up here, said he was
beginning to see a new trend _ many of the childhood friends who
left town after college have been returning, especially to the posh
condominiums sprouting along the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some of it is nostalgia, but look how close we are to
Manhattan,'' he said, sitting at his desk, a small cigar humidor at
his back. ``I think we'll become chic, sort of a Cuban Hoboken.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
