<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PINK MOON' SHINES BRIGHTLY ON VOLKSWAGEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the name of the song in the current Volkswagen Cabrio
commercial in which teens are driving to a party in a convertible
Cabrio at night?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.G., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: That's ``Pink Moon'' by Nick Drake, and it's included on a
1992 CD re-release of the ``Pink Moon'' album he recorded 20 years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Volkswagen commercial began airing, the album has
returned to the bestseller charts _ it's currently in the Top 50 of
all music sold by Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, which Volkswagen calls ``Milky Way,'' also has its
admirers. ``The `Milky Way' commercial is so beautiful, so honest
in ways that supersede the very purpose of advertising that it
makes me want to cry like a baby at its grand statement,'' Joey
Sweeney writes in Philadelphia Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy ``Pink Moon'' online and find out about 11 other
Volkswagen commercials at the company's Web site: www.vw.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which state is the ``Buckeye State''?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.L., Wyckoff, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ohio, which got that name from the Ohio Buckeye tree that
grows primarily in the Mississippi and Ohio Valley regions.
</P>
<P>
   The nickname was popularized by the 1840 presidential campaign
of William Henry Harrison of Ohio, who adopted a buckeye log cabin
and canes as his symbols.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of informally calling its athletic teams
``Buckeyes,'' Ohio State University officially adopted the name in
1950.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the trees and their nuts are of little practical
use,'' an Ohio State history states. ``The wood does not burn well,
the bark has an unpleasant odor, and the bitter nut meat is mildly
toxic. Still, the tree has grit. It grows where others cannot, is
difficult to kill, and adapts to its circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the 1960s animated series ``Mighty Heroes'' available on
video?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.O.S., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Toon Tracker, a mail-order source for hard-to-find cartoons,
sells a 90-minute video containing 12 episodes of the series for
$25.
</P>
<P>
   For ordering information, write to Toon Tracker, Box 143,
Rochester, WI 53167, or visit the Web site
toontracker.hypermart.net.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Mighty Heroes,'' created by animator Ralph Bakshi, were
Cuckoo Man, Diaper Man, Rope Man, Strong Man and Tornado Man.
Bakshi later directed the animated films ``Fritz the Ca,t''
``Wizards'' and ``Lord of the Rings.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
