<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chairs for charity
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, April 13.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Metro Atlanta Furniture Bank no longer simply
cherishes its future. It's accessorizing it, too.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit organization, which provides furniture to the
needy, is sponsoring its sixth annual fund-raiser in which local
and national artists and interior designers take an unfinished
chair frame and get really creative. The chairs are then auctioned
at a gala.
</P>
<P>
   But in a new twist, organizers of Chairish the Future are adding
tables, lamps, mirrors and other decorative items.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to broaden the appeal of the event and make it as
accessible to as many people as we can while giving our artists the
opportunity to stretch their creativity,'' said J.Ed Marston, the
furniture bank's assistant director.
</P>
<P>
   Among this year's national participants will be Maya Lin,
designer of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington. The artist
is donating a chaise she designed for Knoll. Other designers and
manufacturers include Dakota Jackson, Bernhardt and Lowenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Marston expects the event to feature some 100 chairs, many of
which were designed from a basic frame donated by Shelby Williams
Industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most Atlantans, I'm very fortunate to have a nice,
well-furnished home, a job and the ability to care for myself, and
I consider myself lucky,'' said Joe Urban, an artist who
participates each year. ``Unfortunately, there are too many people
in this city who are struggling just to provide shelter for
themselves and their children. I'm excited that my art can help
these people make their homes more livable.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's auction and gala raised more than $35,000. ``It blew
everything before it out of the water,'' Marston said.
</P>
<P>
   The chairs will be on display at Lenox Square mall, in Atlanta,
on April 22-29, during which silent bids can be made. Final bids
will be accepted during an April 30 gala and live auction at
Maggiano's Little Italy restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   ``Chairish the Future'' gala and auction
</P>
<P>
   Where: Maggiano's Little Italy restaurant, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   When: 6 p.m. April 30
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $50
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404-355-8530,
</P>
<P>
   Ext. 223
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
