A3595 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE13-COX     04-11 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sharing treasured gifts keeps connections alive
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, April 13.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many fine gardeners stand firm on the grand tradition
of sharing plants. My mother, for example, used to say with great
conviction: ``Plants should not be bought; they should only be
shared. Or pinched.'' (As in her telling a friend, ``Honey, that
plant sure is pretty, but it could stand a pinching. I'll do it.'')
</P>
<P>
   Each time Mother got a pinch, or a whole plant, she started
growing a relationship that always reminded her of the giver. Gift
plants in her home and garden spoke volumes about the people and
times she'd known and loved. So it goes for us all: Pass-along
plants act as connective tissue binding present, past and future.
</P>
<P>
   While shared plants certainly deserve the attention we give
them, they are not alone in enriching our connections. A good many
gardening gifts have been passed along to me, including a watering
can, a shovel, a trowel and fork. A reference book. Each one has _
and tells _stories.
</P>
<P>
   The watering can belonged to the late Celestine Sibley. I don't
know how old it is, but it is a work of art. Great form and
function. Designed for plain utility, but also with
unself-conscious style and elegance, the metal can has aged to a
lovely gray. Wavy, raised markings decorate one side. They look
like old-fashioned plants to me.
</P>
<P>
   The long-spouted can was given to me by Celestine's
granddaughter, Celestine Sibley Fleming, who writes and gardens and
lives with joy and passion, talents reflecting those of the
beloved, departed family matriarch whose name she shares. Noting
the quarter-century friendship I had with Celestine, Sibley said of
the metal treasure, ``I know my grandmother would want you to have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A treasure of words and pictures came through the mail, a gift
from newspaper colleague Rheta Grimsley Johnson. Rheta, a soulful
writer who has more frequent-driving miles than any scribe I know,
found the book ``at the bottom of a box in a junk store in
Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   What a find it is, this hefty volume, ``The Practical Book of
Outdoor Flowers'' by Richardson Wright, published in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   His wisdom and wit show up early, reminding me, philosophically,
of one of Rheta's gardening-writing heroes, Henry Mitchell, and of
Celestine: ``It is unwise to make a garden your master. Enjoy your
gardening. Have a sense of humor about it. It is not the whole of
life; it is a necessary part of a full life.''
</P>
<P>
   Verna Blackstock, Decatur gardener and cook extraordinaire,
would agree. She shared part of her full gardening life with me _
the cast-aluminum trowel and fork for scratching in the dirt and
unearthing weeds. ``Maybe you can use these up on your mountain,''
Verna said, knowing I needed all the help I could get with that
rocky top in Fannin County.
</P>
<P>
   And the shovel. It belonged to my father, who for decades used
the sharp-edged tool with a 4-foot handle to dig in his Meridian,
Miss., garden. Until, finally, he could garden no more. And live no
more.
</P>
<P>
   I continued to press the shovel into service until last year,
when it finally gave out, its handle breaking during a dig. The top
of the handle, well-crafted wood and metal, remains art, like the
watering can.
</P>
<P>
   That can continues to serve. Its first job in my garden was to
water a chinaberry tree, one of several Celestine and I got as
gifts (along with a sumptuous meal) from friend Britt Flowers in
Newnan, Ga., several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, my pass-along chinaberry is blooming this year, for the
first time. Celestine would enjoy that.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May's column appears every other week.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail him at leemay(at)altavista.com.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
