<HEADER>
A3596 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOMEGARDEN-REVIEW13-C     04-11 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEGARDEN-REVIEW13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home and garden book reviews
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, April 13.
 &HT;    By Sheila Reed
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southern Living Landscape Book
</P>
<P>
   Edited By Steve Binder. Oxmoor House. $24.95. 416 pages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Overview: Count this one among the must-haves for your
library. This book has the goods on stunning garden makeovers,
step-by-step techniques for creating landscape plans and expert
advice on plants, structures and layout. There's even a local
connection: Atlanta landscape architect Bill Stewart's magnificant
back yard is one of the dozens featured.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Not-to-miss sections: ``Planning With Purpose,''
``Understanding Your Site,'' ``Principles of Landscape Design'' and
``Designing Your Garden.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recommended for: Anyone who gardens, or wants to. Would make a
good housewarming gift.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bottom line: This one's a keeper. The pictures alone provide
loads of info.
</P>
<P>
   _Sheila Reed
</P>
<P>
   Wildflowers of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   By Hugh and Carol Nourse. University of Georgia Press. $29.95.
83 pages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Overview: More of a picture book than a tomb with a lot of
text. And with 85 of the most beautiful photographs imaginable _
that's just fine. ``This book is a photographic celebration of the
diversity and beauty of Georgia's wildflowers. It is not a
systematic treatment; these are just some of the best photographs
we have made during our eight-year odyssey around the state,''
write the Nourses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Not to miss sections: The entire book is a
</P>
<P>
   visual delight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recommended for: Wildflower lovers, nature lovers, hikers _
anyone who is wise enough to appreciate the beauty of the outdoors.
Schoolteachers should get a copy of this one; it's never too early
to teach young ones about Georgia's plant life.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bottom line: These pictures are worth several hundred words
and at least $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   _Sheila Reed
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration, Decoration: Starting Points for Stylish Rooms
</P>
<P>
   By Judith Wilson. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $35. 160 pages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Overview: ``Starting points'' is an apt description of this
book. It has eight major topics to peruse; the chapters on color,
fabric and natural light were most useful. Least effective were
radiant space, minimal dimension and travel. ``Colors demand an
instant and personal response from every individual. Once a color
is introduced onto walls or into furnishings, it automatically
becomes a focal point.'' This isn't hot-off-the-press news, but it
provides a good point to ponder. Some good hands-on information.
Nice chatty writing style.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Not to miss sections: Excellent photo-
</P>
<P>
   graphs throughout.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recommended for: People who already know what they want in a
home but likes to see how the other half lives. Also, a good
starting point for someone who doesn't have a clue.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bottom line: A decent investment, if you've got $35 to spare.
</P>
<P>
   _Sheila Reed
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Reed writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
