<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Soft on Microsoft
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The consulting firm founded by Ralph Reed, former leader of the
Christian Coalition, apologized Tuesday for encouraging ``a small
number of individuals'' to express their views about the Microsoft
case to George W. Bush, and said it would halt the contacts.
Century Strategies was never ``retained for the purpose of
influencing Governor Bush'' and was hired before Reed began working
for Bush's campaign, the firm said, adding that although Reed is a
senior consultant to the Bush campaign, he has never asked the
candidate to take a position on the government's antitrust case
against Microsoft. The firm did, however, admit to encouraging
citizens ``to express their views to presidential candidates of
both parties,'' including Bush. All this came after The New York
Times reported that Microsoft hired Reed more than a year ago to
get Bush to support the Microsoft position if he wins in November.
Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer told The Associated Press Tuesday that
Reed ``never talked to the governor about Microsoft. There's been
no personal lobbying.''
</P>
<P>
   OHIO _ CROSSROADS OF CAMPAIGNING
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore drew a diverse crowd of kids in blue jeans and adults in
business suits to a town meeting at Vandalia-Butler High School in
Vandalia, Ohio, a Dayton suburb. Tuesday, Ohioans got a double dose
of presidential campaigning. Gore visited classes and ate lunch
with students in Columbus as part of his pledge to spend a day at a
school every week or two during the campaign. He spent the night
before at the home of a teacher and her family. George W. Bush, was
unveiling his ``New Prosperity Initiative'' in Cleveland: a $42
billion plan to give the working poor credits for health insurance
and rental vouchers for home down payments. He also plans to offer
tax credits for banks that match the savings deposits of poor
people.
</P>
<P>
   RUNOFFS IN TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   Two Democrats were vying in Texas Tuesday for the right to run
against Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison in November, while two
Republicans sought the nomination for retiring GOP Rep. Bill
Archer's seat. In the Senate race, retired military lawyer Gene
Kelly, who lost six previous statewide races, and Charles Gandy, a
former one-term state representative, emerged from a field of five
Democrats in the March 14 primary. Hutchison will be the heavy
favorite in November. Oilman Peter Wareing and state Rep. John
Culberson vied in a Republican runoff for Archer's seat.
</P>
<P>
   RUDY AND THE LIBERALS
</P>
<P>
   Third parties in New York have always had an influential
following in New York, and state Liberal Party chief Ray Harding
says Republican Rudy Giuliani is seeking the party's endorsement in
his Senate race. Harding said the party's policy committee would
meet May 6 to interview Giuliani and other candidates. But state
Conservative Party chief Michael Long said that Giuliani ``would be
shutting the door to possible Conservative Party backing'' it he
went after the Liberals' nod. Giuliani would use Liberal Party
support, according to the New York Daily News, to try to blunt
Hillary Rodham Clinton's criticism that he's ``out of step'' with
moderate New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   RUDY AND THE LADIES WHO LUNCH
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani began a series of statewide ``Women for Rudy''
lunches to reinforce his support among Republican female voters, a
group that has largely remained loyal as polls show that his
reaction to the fatal shooting of Patrick Dorismond, an unarmed
black man, has caused a drop in his support among men. At the
Women's National Republican Club in midtown Manhattan, Giuliani
received a hero's welcome from 250 guests, many of whom said they
felt better off because of the mayor's fight against crime and his
economic policies. Today, Giuliani has slated a ``Women for Rudy''
lunch in Rochester and a ``women's town hall meeting'' in Buffalo.
On Thursday, Giuliani is to attend a ``women for Rudy'' lunch in
Mineola, on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   OK TO TALK ABOUT ELIAN IN OHIO, BUT MAYBE NOT IN FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to win the hearts of a roomful of undecided voters in
Ohio, Al Gore broke his recent silence and shared his views on the
custody dispute over Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban refugee.
Gore said the Elian's relatives should be allowed to try to work
out among themselves the escalating custody dispute over the boy:
``With tensions as high as they are and with both sides trying to
figure out a way to come to a resolution, I think that we need to
encourage the talks between the family members themselves. Let the
entire family, including the Florida relatives, talk with one
another without people from the U.S. government or the Cuban
government or lawyers on either side.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW POLL HAS BUSH BUSTING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has pulled slightly ahead of Al Gore, 50 percent
to 41 percent, in a new CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. Eight percent
had no opinion, and 1 percent chose ``other.'' A poll taken March
30-April 2 had Bush and Gore in a statistical tie, 46 percent to 45
percent. The poll has a 3 percentage point margin of error. In a
hypothetical race with the Reform Party's Pat Buchanan, according
to the poll, Buchanan takes a tiny slice of voters from Bush, who
drops to 48 percent, with Gore still at 42 percent and Buchanan
with 4 percent support.
</P>
<P>
   SO, WILL IT BE COHEN FOR V.P.?
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton favors Defense Secretary William Cohen as Al
Gore's running mate, according to the Christian Science Monitor.
The newspaper said that was revealed by ``friends of the president
who have had conversations with him in recent days.'' Clinton, the
Monitor reported, ``sees Cohen, a Republican, as a ticket-sharer
that would give Gore the help he needs to win ... among moderate
Republicans and independents'' _ and that ``Gore knows Clinton has
one of the country's best political minds.''
</P>
<P>
   SOME GAYS STILL FEELING LEFT OUT
</P>
<P>
   During his hard-fought primary campaign when he was seeking the
support of conservatives, George W. Bush refused to meet with gay
Republicans or representatives of the 11,000-member Log Cabin
Republicans. Now, Bush's first-ever meeting with gay Republicans
may bolster his ``compassionate conservative'' image, but it has
has irked Log Cabin leaders. Bush's invitation-only meeting
Thursday in Austin, Texas, is to be with 13 gay Republicans,
including rank-and-file Log Cabin Republican members. Among those
not invited were leaders of the Log Cabin organization, which had
endorsed John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   CAUTION: TEXAS MAY BE HAZARDOUS TO YOUR HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   Texas has had one of the nation's worst public health records
for decades. More than a quarter of its citizens have no health
insurance; it ranks near the top in the nation in rates of AIDS,
diabetes, tuberculosis and teenage pregnancy _ and near the bottom
in immunizations, mammograms and access to physicians. Since George
W. Bush became governor in 1995, he has not made health a priority,
his aides acknowledge, or made a speech on the subject. In 1999,
his administration fought unsuccessfully to limit access to the new
federal Children's Health Insurance Program in 1999. But with
health care near the top of the political agenda, The New York
Times reports that Bush is planning to start discussing health
issues soon, possibly as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S ALL ABOUT CONTROL
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush began taking control of the Republican National
Committee by naming a former Texas party chairman, Fred Meyer, head
of the RNC Victory 2000 campaign. Meyer chaired the Texas GOP from
1988 to 1994, helping it reverse years of Democratic rule, and was
a senior adviser in Texas Sen. Phil Gramm's failed 1996
presidential campaign. Bush campaign officials noted that Meyer is
close to John McCain. Bush also moved his campaign political
director, Maria Cino, to the RNC, where she will be a deputy for
political and congressional relations. And Jeanne Johnson Phillips,
one of Bush's original Texas fund-raisers, will be RNC deputy
chairman for finance.
</P>
<P>
   GORE'S MOM GETS HER BACHELOR'S
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's mother, 88 and frail, returned Monday to the club _
then men's only _ where she was thrown out in 1971. Shortly after
that, the club opened its dining room to women. Her son saluted her
there for teaching ``through quiet dignity and deliberation one
woman can make all the difference.'' Pauline LaFon Gore was at the
Nashville City Club to receive an honorary bachelor of arts degree
from Union University, a private Baptist school in West Tennessee,
where a scholarship was established in her name. She was to have
traveled to the university campus in Jackson to receive her degree,
but because of her health the event was moved to the club in
Nashville where she was ousted as a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   THE UNFRIENDLY SKIES
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before last week's Senate primary in Pennsylvania,
according to Roll Call and the Washington Times, Democratic Rep.
Ron Klink and Republican Sen. Rick Santorum found themselves
sitting directly across the aisle from one another on a commercial
flight from Pittsburgh to Philadelphia. The news outlets reported
that the flight attendant recognized Klink, a four-term House
member and former TV newscaster, and wished him well in his Senate
challenge to Santorum, then asked him for an autograph. Santorum
apparently isn't as recognizable. ``Nary a word on the flight was
exchanged between the House member and the senator,'' Roll Call
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
