<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEFILTE-FISH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEFILTE FISH: THE NEXT GENERATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT7 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 By JOAN NATHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For almost 80 years, first in Russia and then in America, Dora
Solganik of Cleveland has been performing the gefilte fish ritual
for Passover: schlepping to the fish market, choosing the best fish
``by the look in its eyes,'' and transforming it into the
quintessential Seder dish.
</P>
<P>
   Using a wooden bowl and a half-moon-shaped chopper, she cuts up
the fish with onions, crying a little, chopping a little, until her
mix is just the right consistency. Then she molds it into oblong
patties. Every year she makes 25 pounds, and this year, her 94th,
is no different. Solganik, though, is increasingly the exception.
</P>
<P>
   More and more people have been turning to commercially prepared
frozen loaves of ground fish, sometimes even spiked with almonds
and raisins or jalapenos. These new, more American flavors are
rapidly replacing the classic, fishy-tasting blends, made from
carp, whitefish and pike, and the smooth texture indicates they
have never felt the blade of a hand chopper.
</P>
<P>
   One company, A&AMP;B Famous Gefilte Fish in Monsey, N.Y., boasts
that its blend is ``the way Grandma made it ... such gefilte fish
with so little effort.'' The emphasis is on efficiency and
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Gefilte fish became a Passover staple because of a suggestion in
the Talmud to eat fish. Since cooking on the Sabbath is prohibited,
the fish balls were cooked in advance and served cold. Eventually
gefilte fish became the Eastern European first course for holiday
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything Jewish, gefilte fish (literally ``filled fish'')
has had quite a journey. Eve Jochnowitz, a culinary ethnographer in
New York, said: ``The first ancestors of gefilte fish came from
France in the late Middle Ages, where a couple of the oldest
cookery manuscripts include stuffed fish mixtures with almonds and
saffron.''
</P>
<P>
   The mixture was always stuffed back into the skin and baked in a
crust or poached, with leftover filling formed into patties,
covered with fish skin and simmered in the same pot. Later, the
artful but laborious stuffing step was discarded and the patties
became the gefilte fish eaten today.
</P>
<P>
   Until the new wave of gefilte innovations, the last great change
was fish in the jar, in World War II. Now frozen loaves are taking
over. Brooklyn shops like Ossie's Fish in Borough Park and Raskin's
in Crown Heights create their own mix of whitefish, pike, carrots
and onions.
</P>
<P>
   Among those adventurous enough to make gefilte fish at home, the
latest version comes from immigrants from the former Soviet Union,
who grew up with authentic gefilte fish, stuffed back into the
skin.
</P>
<P>
   Anya Kushner, the cook at Primorski restaurant in Brighton
Beach, Brooklyn, makes gefilte fish year-round from a recipe she
learned growing up in Odessa. First she sautes onions, then grinds
them with carp and whitefish and mixes in egg and seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Although her mother boned the fish, then sewed the skins
together to encase the stuffing, Kushner simply places a few long
sheets of skin on a piece of aluminum foil, fills them with the
chopped fish mixture, then covers it with more skin and encloses
the whole ``fish'' in the foil. She simmers it in a broth colored
red with beets. The result has the look of a whole fish without the
mess.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kushner and other Russians insist that the gefilte fish
mix should be at least 75 percent carp, others prefer at least 50
percent whitefish. But a bigger debate is over horseradish, the
traditional accompaniment for the Passover dish and the symbol of
slavery when the Jews were in Egypt under the pharaohs.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it's indispensable for taste and to clear nasal
passages at this springtime festival, when pollen is in the air;
others liken it to tomato sauce on good ravioli _ all it does is
cover up the flavor. No matter. Along with gefilte fish, red or
white horseradish is as essential to Passover as matzo and four
cups of wine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLIFIED ODESSA-STYLE GEFILTE FISH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Total time: 1{ hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 arge onions, peeled
</P>
<P>
   \ up kosher-for-Passover oil
</P>
<P>
   2 atzos
</P>
<P>
   2 edium carrots, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 beets, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ground fresh carp
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ground fresh whitefish
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Red or white horseradish for garnish.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Chop 3 onions and saute until soft in the oil in a frying
pan, then pulse in a food processor until chopped but not mushy.
</P>
<P>
   2. Soak the matzo in cold water until moistened. Drain and
squeeze dry.
</P>
<P>
   3. Put carrots, beets and last onion in a fish poacher or wide
pot. Add 8 cups water and bring to boil; reduce to simmer.
</P>
<P>
   4. To the ground fish, add ground onions, matzo, eggs, salt and
pepper and mix well with your hands to a tacky consistency.
</P>
<P>
   5. Lay 2 large sheets of foil out on a counter, carefully spoon
the fish mixture on top, fold sides of foil up around fish and
tightly seal. Gently place in pot, adding water if necessary to
almost cover the fish. Simmer 1 hour. Remove from heat, cool in
broth, and serve or refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, carefully remove foil, place fish on a platter,
decorate with the cooked vegetables, and garnish with horseradish.
Yield: 15 to 20 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York has plenty of good commercial gefilte fish and real
horseradish. Some stores, as noted below, also sell frozen gefilte
fish. Here are a few favorite sources: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELI'S MANHATTAN, 1411 Third Avenue, (212) 717-8100, and ELI'S
VINEGAR FACTORY, 431 East 91st Street, (212) 987-0885, sell the
best I have tasted: their traditional premium, made with matzo meal
and flecks of carrot. It is sold by the pint (two pieces) at both
stores, at $12. Traditional gefilte fish is $9.95.
</P>
<P>
   CITARELLA, 1313 Third Avenue and 2135 Broadway, (212) 874-0383,
sells plump full-flavored gefilte made in the traditional torpedo
shape from whitefish, pike, a little sugar, egg and onions. Each
weighs six ounces; $6.99 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   OSSIE'S FISH MARKET, 1314 50th Street, Borough Park, Brooklyn,
(718) 436-4100, has authentic fresh gefilte fish mix for $5.50 a
pound; frozen gefilte fish comes in rolls in several flavors:
classic, salmon, lemon-dill, almond-raisin, jalapeno, Cajun and
horseradish, $6 each to serve six. All are kosher. Although the
flavors are unusual, the texture of the frozen logs is too rubbery
for my taste. Delivers to Manhattan daily.
</P>
<P>
   RASKIN'S FISH MARKET, 320 Kingston Avenue, Brooklyn, (718)
756-9521, is a very traditional kosher fish market using live carp
for fresh gefilte fish, $4.50 a pound, and ready-made 22-ounce logs
_ sweet and nonsweet _ made with whitefish, pike and mullet for
$4.49 a pound. A traditionalist, I prefer their frozen logs to any
others because they seem to have more texture, with flecks of
carrot for color. Delivery to Manhattan available.
</P>
<P>
   RUSS &AMP; DAUGHTERS, 179 East Houston Street, (212) 475-4880 or
(800) 787-7229, makes fresh gefilte fish, although a little sweet
for my taste, from salmon and whitefish, matzo meal, eggs, onions,
white pepper and fresh dill. It costs $2.49 by the ball and $7.96
by the loaf. Overnight delivery available.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND AVENUE DELI, 156 Second Avenue, (212) 677-0606, makes
very soft patties from whitefish and pike, with matzo meal and
large carrots, very close to homemade. Each is $7, with overnight
shipping available. It also sells strong red horseradish for $5 a
pint.
</P>
<P>
   GUSS'S LOWER EAST SIDE PICKLES, 35 Essex Street, (212) 254-4477,
(800) 252-4877, is certified kosher, with a tradition of
hand-grated red and white horseradish since 1910. An eight-ounce
jar is $7, with overnight shipping available.
</P>
<P>
   MOTHER-IN-LAW'S RUSSIAN GOURMET HORSERADISH, distributed by
Royal Baltic, is so called because it is so hot it might drive away
a mother-in-law. An 8.8-ounce jar, white or red, is $2.59; (718)
385-8300 for stores. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
