<HEADLINE>
PARSLEY VARIETIES  
 TASTES OF HUNGARY  
 GOGGLES FOR ONION-CHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is there any difference between curly parsley and flat-leaf
(Italian) parsley, other than appearance? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There is an important difference: taste.
</P>
<P>
   Curly parsley, with its ruffled leaves, makes an attractive
garnish, but generally has little flavor. Flat-leaf parsley,
preferred by most chefs, has a much more intense taste.
</P>
<P>
   If a recipe doesn't specify which kind of parsley to use, you
may choose either one, though the flat-leaf type will add more
pizazz. However, recipes whose flavor relies on parsley, like a
parsley pesto, will usually call specifically for the flat-leaf
variety. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Having just returned from Budapest, I'd like to know where to
find Hungarian specialties, like paprika sauce or goulash. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The Yorkville Packing House in Manhattan, 1560 Second Avenue
(81st Street; (212) 628-5147), sells an array of Hungarian
specialties, including an authentic Hungarian goulash and paprika
sauce. It also has a mail-order service, and there is a Web site
for Hungarian specialties:
http://members.aol.com/HungImprts/Ottos.htm &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there any truth to the old wives' tale about burning a
candle next to you as you chop onions to stop your eyes from
tearing?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Unfortunately, there's not. When onions are cut and their
cell structure disturbed, allicin, a volatile substance that
irritates the eyes, is released. Burning a candle does nothing to
diminish the effect of allicin. But, there are other ways to make
chopping onions a less tearful experience.
</P>
<P>
   The first is rather impractical: cutting onions under cold
running water. The water will wash away the allicin before it can
irritate your eyes. However, not only is this somewhat dangerous as
the knife can slip, it will also produce a flavorless, water-logged
onion.
</P>
<P>
   A more convenient method is to chill the onion before cutting
it. The cold will reduce the volatility of the allicin, though
you'll have to chop quickly before the onion warms up.
</P>
<P>
   The last method is probably the most effective, and is the
method I use. As anyone with contact lenses or glasses knows,
creating a barrier between your eyes and the onion vapors works
wonders. If you have perfect vision, you can try wearing sunglasses
(only if your kitchen is very bright and the lenses not too dark)
or investing in a pair of goggles. The kinds sold at hardware
stores are inexpensive, and one pair will fit every onion-chopping
member of your household. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Questions about food and cooking can be sent to Food Chain, the
Dining section, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York
10036-3959, or by e-mail to dining(at)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
