<SLUG> BC-PBHG-SLATTERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLATTERY RESIGNS AS MANAGER OF NEW OPPORTUNITIES FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank P. Slattery V, who had a phenomenal first year as a
manager of the PBHG New Opportunities Fund but then stumbled over
the past month amid market turbulence, resigned Tuesday and said he
would pursue other opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Slattery, who goes by the nickname Quint, joined PBHG in 1998,
after two years at Merrill Lynch, which he joined after graduating
from Princeton University. He began running the New Opportunities
Fund in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Slattery, 27, did not return a telephone call seeking comment on
his departure, which was announced by the company.
</P>
<P>
   For the 12 months ended March 31, the New Opportunities Fund
showed a total return of 533 percent, more than twice the return of
any other mutual fund with assets of at least $30 million,
according to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But while the fund had been very volatile for its entire life,
that volatility had increased in March, as the fast-growing
technology stocks that he specialized in came under selling
pressure on some days.
</P>
<P>
   During its first year, the worst period for the fund came last
summer, when it lost 15.2 percent of its value over a period of
slightly under a month. But since the fund peaked March 9, it has
suffered dramatic swings. At its low April 4, it was down 42.1
percent from the peak. It had fluctuated since then, but was still
down 38.5 percent from the peak through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Slattery's strategy called for putting about 80 percent of the
fund's money into the 30 fastest growing companies, and holding
them no matter how high their price rose. The remaining 20 percent
of the fund was used for quick investments, often trying to
anticipate what stocks would get hot, and then selling them after
they had gained a dollar or two.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Slattery said that during the first
year of the fund's existence, it had shown gains of at least 1,000
percent on three stocks: MicroStrategy, SDL Inc. and Infospace.
Each of them peaked in March and has fallen substantially since
then. Through mid-afternoon Tuesday, they were down 33 percent, 53
percent and 85 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Slattery grew up in Villanova, Pa., the son of a leasing company
executive. ``I've been around finance all my life,'' he said last
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
