<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3602 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-DIXIECHICKS-EARL-TEX     04-11 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIXIECHICKS-EARL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS-FORT WORTH RADIO STATION LATEST TO SAY GOODBYE TO `EARL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dixie Chicks aren't the only ones saying goodbye to Earl.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-Fort Worth country station KSCS/96.3, one of only two
major country stations left in the north Texas area, has joined
about a dozen other stations around the nation in opting to pass on
playing ``Goodbye Earl,'' the latest single from the phenomenally
popular Dallas-bred trio.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy started to simmer when ``Earl'' was released on
the band's second disc, the Grammy-winning ``Fly,'' last Aug. 31;
now, more than six months later, it's boiled over because ``Earl''
is in release as a single and is being played in rotation on radio
stations. It's caused one of the biggest flaps in country music
since Garth Brooks' eyebrow-raising video for ``Papa Loved Mama.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' video depicted a truck driver plowing his truck through
a wall of a motel, where, supposedly, his wife was cheating on him.
Violence was more implied than real, though; the song isn't
blatantly violent, and you don't see anyone get hurt in the video.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Chicks' ``Earl'' is about revenge. Two women,
Mary Anne and Wanda, conspire to murder Earl, Wanda's abusive
husband. But the lyrics are far more graphic. A sample:
</P>
<P>
   ``They worked out a plan/And it didn't take them long to
decide/That Earl had to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the Chicks condoning violence, or trying to shed light on
abuse?
</P>
<P>
   Let the debate begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our listeners don't wanna hear it,'' says Dean James,
operations manager and program director for KSCS. ``We played it
for a few days, and we got a ton of negative reactions. People were
saying it promotes violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction was overwhelming. This is gonna sound like a
corporate cop-out, but we're gonna do what the majority of our
listeners want us to do, and our listeners are telling us that they
don't want to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda O'Brien, assistant program director at KSCS, says another
reason the station is declining to air it is because it contradicts
its anti-violence campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had raised nearly $200,000 for Project Safe in Dallas,
and the whole point of this place is to teach people how to deal
with their anger,'' she says. ``How do you explain that one week
you're raising money for an organization like this, and the next
week, you're playing a song from the Dixie Chicks that's like, `Oh,
we poisoned Earl.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's a different story over at Dallas' WOLF/105.3 FM (The Wolf),
a competing country station that plays ``Earl'' up to seven times a
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most requested records we've had, and it has
been since it came out,'' says Smokey Rivers, the station's
assistant program director. ``We haven't had the negative calls and
e-mails. Our audience is younger and I think they understand that
the Chicks are trying to convey a message in a tongue-in-cheek
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Violence in music has been present from the earliest country
songs to heavy metal to, most recently, hip-hop. Although the
overwhelming majority of the 150 country stations in the United
States are playing the song, the Chicks are touching a nerve with
``Earl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference is, the Dixie Chicks are singing about
violence in a very funny, tongue-in-cheek way, '' says Phyllis
Stark, Nashville bureau chief for magazines Billboard and Country
Airplay Monitor. ``They may be the only ones who can get away with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, this may be a case of new band, old story.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen was attacked for writing about two teens on a
shooting spree in his song ``Nebraska.'' A Johnny Cash video for
``Adelia'' found the Man in Black killing and burying a lover. And
two local bands, the Toadies and Old 97's, have dodged their share
of bullets for writing songs peppered with violent images _ the
Toadies for ``Possum Kingdom'' (the infamous chorus: ``Do you wanna
die?'') and the Old 97's for ``The Other Shoe,'' in which singer
Rhett Miller sings of a husband who kills his cheating wife and her
lover.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Earl's'' a little different: The music is upbeat, lacking
the tension of any of the aforementioned songs; most of the track's
lyrics are laced with humor; and the ``Goodbyyyye Earllll'' chorus,
well, it's downright infectious. It's difficult, in other words,
not to sing along.
</P>
<P>
   That was the whole point, according to Chick Emily Robison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a serious subject and did it in a way that makes it a
little bit easier to listen to,'' Robison said in a prepared
statement. ``Sometimes songs get so serious that they make people
very uncomfortable. `Earl' is meant to be lighthearted and fun, and
if in the process it brings a serious subject to the forefront,
then that's great. We're not promoting murder, and we even say that
in a disclaimer on our album.''
</P>
<P>
   The Denver-based National Coalition Against Domestic Violence
agrees. The organization recently released a statement applauding
the Chicks for ``Earl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The subject matter of the song is far too often a reality for
battered women,'' NCADV executive director Rita Smith said in the
statement. ``The NCADV wishes to express their gratitude to the
Dixie Chicks for raising public awareness'' of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Some stations have opted to supply phone numbers for the NCADV
and other violence prevention hot lines before or after ``Earl'' is
played.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stations that are afraid of it aren't even giving it that
opportunity,'' says Stark of Billboard and Country Airplay Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a station's listeners really do have a problem with it,
obviously they shouldn't be playing it,'' she says. ``But rampant
political correctness has made some programmers afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as KSCS is vowing not to play it, The Wolf is promising to
keep on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the talk of country music right now. So we're gonna latch
onto it,'' says Rivers of The Wolf. ``When was the last time you've
done a story on a country song that's gotten this much attention?''
Malcolm Mayhew, (817) 390-7713
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
