   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-FORFEITURE (Washington) _ Following years of complaints of
abusive government conduct, the Congress completed legislation
Tuesday that would make it harder for law enforcement authorities
to confiscate property before they actually bring criminal charges
in narcotics and other cases. The White House is expected to
announce that Clinton would sign the legislation, a compromise
measure approved unanimously by a voice vote of the House of
Representatives. The new law, which was approved by the Senate
three weeks ago, will add significant new safeguards that will make
it more difficult for prosecutors to seize homes, cars and other
property before trials begin. But it also expands the government's
authority to confiscate property after convictions. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ Conceding vulnerability on a hot
campaign issue, House Republican leaders Tuesday rushed a
Republican-written gun-crime bill to the floor and passed it so
they would have something to show before next week's anniversary of
the fatal shootings at Columbine High School. Lawmakers
overwhelmingly approved the measure to send $100 million in block
grants to states that impose mandatory prison sentences for gun
crimes. Currently, six states would qualify for the grants, but
supporters said that number would grow. The vote was 358-60. By
Eric Schmitt.
