Bush outlined a plan Tuesday to give the working poor tax credits
for health insurance and rental vouchers for home down payments. He
also said he plans to offer tax credits for banks that match the
savings deposits of poor people. The $42 billion plan expands on
tax-cut and education proposals previously offered by the
all-but-official Republican presidential nominee and continues his
outreach to independents and moderate Democratic voters by talking
about subjects often ignored by Republican candidates. By Alison
Mitchell.
