<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LABOR-SKILLS12-COX     04-11 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-SKILLS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS MUST HELP EDUCATE WORKERS, GREENSPAN SAYS
 &HT;    360&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To deal with the shortage of skilled workers caused
by rapid technological change, businesses must join with schools to
create a system that integrates work and training for both new and
older employees, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, if we are to remain pre-eminent in transforming
knowledge into economic value, the U.S. system of higher education
must remain the world's leader in generating scientific and
technological breakthrough and in preparing workers to meet the
evolving demands for skilled labor,'' Greenspan told more than 200
government officials, corporate leaders and educators at the
Department of Labor National Skills Summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' Greenspan said, ``the pressure to enlarge the pool
of skilled workers also requires that we strengthen the significant
contributions of other types of training and educational programs,
especially those with lesser skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five thousand technology jobs this year won't be filled
as a result of the skills shortage, said Steve Guengerich, whose
Austin-based Knowbility.org provides education and employment
opportunities in information technology for youth and adults with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The country's educational system is responsible for the shortage
of skilled workers, said Ray Marshall, a University of Texas at
Austin professor and former labor secretary. He said high school
graduates in Singapore, for example, have more math and science
skills needed for a technical entry-level position than their
American counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore and other technologically advanced countries, unlike
the United States, have standards that define what students should
know before they graduate from high school, Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   In other countries, ``the student and the teacher become allies
in meeting those standards,'' he explained. ``In American schools,
the teacher and the student become enemies because the student has
to learn only what the teacher wants him to learn. We don't know
what high school students know when they graduate, but with
standards we do.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Texas has made a lot of progress because ``we started developing
standards,'' Marshall added. He said former Gov. Mark White
implemented a system of standards and Gov. George W. Bush, when he
took office, continued the system.
</P>
<P>
   Guengerich agreed that Bush had taken significant steps in
reforming public education in the state. The standards system has
greatly improved the reading and math skills of students coming out
of high school in Texas, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long way to go, but I think we are improving. That's
because we have a system of standards and measurement,'' said
Marshall, UT's chair of economic and public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The skills summit, held on the Howard University campus, was
convened by Labor Secretary Alexis Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
