<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COPENHAGEN-THEATER-RE     04-11 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPENHAGEN-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COPENHAGEN': A FIERY POWER IN THE BEHAVIOR OF PARTICLES AND
HUMANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ghosts who have taken up residence at the Royale
Theater are a restless lot, filled with a crackling, questing
vitality rarely found even among the living. As embodied with
disquieting fierceness by Philip Bosco, Blair Brown and Michael
Cumpsty in ``Copenhagen,'' the endlessly fascinating new play by
Michael Frayn that opened Tuesday night, these spectral presences
just won't stop haunting one another with their questions and
revisions and caveats.
</P>
<P>
   Give them the courtesy of your full attention, and you'll find
them taking possession of your own imagination as well, probably
raising your blood pressure in the process. And who would ever have
thought it: that three dead, long-winded people talking about
atomic physics would be such electrifying companions?
</P>
<P>
   ``Copenhagen,'' a critical and (more surprisingly) popular hit
when it opened in London at the Royal National Theater in 1998, is
nominally about a subject with all the sex appeal of a frozen
flounder: a meeting in 1941 between the venerable Danish physicist
Niels Bohr (Bosco) and Werner Heisenberg (Cumpsty), his former
pupil and a German, during which no one to this day knows exactly
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   What was said or, equally important, not said takes on increased
significance when you consider the possible stakes: the success of
a German project led by Heisenberg. That project was the
development of atomic weapons, something in which Bohr would later
have a hand as a member of the legendary team at Los Alamos, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking that this means that ``Copenhagen,'' which
has been directed with surgical exactitude by Michael Blakemore, is
a tale of international intrigue, you're on the wrong tangent.
There's tension aplenty in the drama, which allows Heisenberg, Bohr
and Bohr's wife, Margrethe (Brown), to reunite after their deaths
to sort out what may or may not have happened on that September
evening.
</P>
<P>
   But the work's tenacious grip has little to do with
straightforward plot, the essentials of which are laid out early
on, or the solving of questions that are ultimately unanswerable.
</P>
<P>
   Frayn, best known here as the author of the blissful backstage
farce ``Noises Off,'' turns the encounter among the three
characters into a wide-ranging, intensely emotional consideration
of everything from quantum mechanics to the loss of a child, to the
fate of the world in the atomic age, to the ways that friendships
go sour; from the theories of complementarity and uncertainty to
the eternal ambiguity of human motives and memory.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressively, Frayn _ with a logic that keeps moving in
variously widening and converging circles for which Blakemore finds
wonderfully theatrical equivalents _ shows how every one of these
elements is bound to, and reflects, the others. The result is the
most invigorating and ingenious play of ideas in many a year and a
work of art that humanizes physics in a way no other has done. And
as fine as the play was in London, it has in crossing the Atlantic
turned from a work of slightly chilly elegance into something of a
fierier vigor.
</P>
<P>
   As Margrethe keeps insisting, everything under discussion, from
politics to the loftiest scientific abstractions, is finally also
personal. In a wonderful speech in the second act, Bohr speaks of
how 20th-century physics restored man to the center of the
universe, of how Albert Einstein demonstrated that ``measurement is
not an impersonal event that occurs with universal impartiality''
but ``a human act, carried out from a specific point of view in
time and space.''
</P>
<P>
   The unknowability of people, even to themselves, has long been a
concern of Frayn's, evident in both his plays (``Benefactors'') and
novels (including the recent, sparkling ``Headlong''). Here he
widens the perimeters to a cosmic level _ if man is the measure of
the universe, then nothing is really quantifiable _ without ever
getting lost in the stars.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a play to see after two martinis; it demands your
thorough concentration. But this critic, who barely squeaked
through a college course known as ``Physics for Poets,'' was moved
to tears not of frustration but of wondering comprehension. Frayn
and Blakemore lead you through the permutations and
interpenetrations of the different versions of what happened on
that one night, and the events that shaped and came out of it, with
care and clarity.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an aspect of grand theatrical hokum to
``Copenhagen'' that, in another context, might be hard to take.
This is a play, after all, that asks you to accept a trio of
aggravated phantoms who say things like: ``So why did he do it? Now
no one can be hurt, no one can be betrayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the hokum both grounds and enlivens the esoterica of the
scientific explanations. It's like combining strong, seemingly
incompatible spices in cooking: using one, as it turns out, lets
you get away with using the other, and they wind up bringing out
hidden notes in each other's flavors.
</P>
<P>
   I'll admit I had doubts when I heard ``Copenhagen'' was being
restaged in New York with an American cast. The actors I saw in
London (David Burke, Sara Kestelman and Matthew Marsh) lent an
exquisite (and utterly un-American) crispness to their performances
in which the enunciation of every word seemed to harbor several
layers of meaning. It was an approach that brought out the play's
poetry and its intellectual gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Working within what is essentially the same set _ a ravishingly
pristine laboratory in limbo, designed by Peter J. Davison and
eloquently lighted by Mark Henderson and Michael Lincoln _ Bosco,
Brown and Cumpsty have introduced their own element of uncertainty
into ``Copenhagen,'' and it pays off handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their English counterparts, they appear to be starting
less from the play's language than the feelings behind it. As a
consequence there's a deeper heat to the relationships portrayed
here and a more wrenching sense of personal loss throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Initially it seems as if the performers might not pull it off.
Wearing professorial vagueness like an old sweater, Bosco is the
only one who seems to have found a fully shaped character to play.
Brown and Cumpsty at first register as self-consciously theatrical.
</P>
<P>
   As the evening proceeds, however, with the characters brushing
against one another in different combinations, the resulting
friction causes each to emerge more clearly, and by the end you
feel you have to come to know them all from the inside out, rather
than the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   The ambivalent, fervid father-son relationship of the two men;
the mixture of sharp marital protectiveness and subliminal
resentment of Margrethe; the dizzying swings between hotly debated
historical abstractions and sad recollections of personal details
that evoke a lifetime of attrition: Bosco, Brown and Cumpsty summon
all this with a passion that scalds.
</P>
<P>
   They also transmit the spirit of ravenous curiosity in the face
of doubt that shapes ``Copenhagen.'' Skepticism may be a dominant
note here: no, we can't ever know exactly who we are or why we do
what we do; yes, we all exist in a state of contingency.
</P>
<P>
   Yet how much more interesting life is as a consequence. Definite
knowledge may be unattainable in ``Copenhagen.'' On the other hand,
aren't you familiar with that sensation of letdown that comes when
you arrive at the end of a mystery novel? In the world of
``Copenhagen,'' no such anticlimaxes are possible. The thrill of
the chase is infinite.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `COPENHAGEN'
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Frayn; directed by Michael Blakemore; sets by Peter
J. Davison; lighting by Mark Henderson and Michael Lincoln; costume
supervisor, Charlotte Bird; sound by Tony Meola; general manager,
Joey Parnes; production stage manager, R. Wade Jackson. Presented
by James M. Nederlander, Roger Berlind, Scott Rudin, Elizabeth
Ireland McCann, Ray Larsen, Jon B. Platt, Byron Goldman and Scott
Nederlander, by arrangement with Michael Codron, Lee Dean and the
Royal National Theater. At the Royale Theater, 242 W. 45th St.,
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Blair Brown (Margrethe Bohr), Philip Bosco (Niels Bohr)
and Michael Cumpsty (Werner Heisenberg).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MAGAZINE-ADS-ART-2NDT     04-11 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-ADS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: to read.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Yogi Berra's observation _ it's too crowded; nobody goes
there anymore _ holds true for advertisers: some shy away from the
fat magazines. Gene DeWitt, the chief executive of Optimedia
International (U.S.), an advertising services agency in New York,
said that if advertisers could not get highly trafficked pages in a
packed mag`zine, they might skip that issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the business category, we'll discuss Forbes, Fortune and
Business Week and advertisers will say, `Forget about Business
Week, it's too cluttered,''' he said. (Business Week's ad pages
have risen by 28 percent over last year.) ``And in some issues of
Vogue, if you can't get a good spot, you may say to yourself, `Why
would I want to be in there?' They won't drop the magazine
altogether, but a guaranteed position is required.''
</P>
<P>
   Does more advertising mean more articles? Not necessarily. Most
of the obese magazines stray from the norm for the average ratio of
advertising to editorial content, as measured by the Magazine
Publishers of America. The trade group reported last year that the
average ratio for American consumer magazines was 49.4 percent
advertising to 50.6 editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   Vanity Fair's March issue was 66 percent advertising; the
February/March Bride's _ with a whopping 1,180 pages of ads, said
Nina Lawrence, the publisher of Bride's _ was 93 percent
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Cona of In Style said that he is careful to monitor the ratio of
advertising to editorial pages, keeping it to an average of about
47 percent editorial to about 53 percent advertising. But the April
issue of In Style had 337 pages of advertising and 235 pages of
editorial content, or about 41 percent editorial to 59 percent
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The March issue of Vogue had 177 pages of editorial and 389
pages of advertising, or about 31 percent to 69 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All that advertising can complicate production. In Style has
grown so big in recent months, there have been delays in getting
the magazine to newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only bind 7,500 copies of In Style per hour, as
opposed to most magazines, where you can bind 11,000 copies per
hour,'' Cona said. ``As you slow down that process, you can have
delivery problems to wholesalers, which gets them out late on the
newsstand, which costs you sales.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of trucking the magazines has also risen. When In Style
was first published in 1995, 20 magazines fit into one bundle. Now,
only five do. Cona has had to hire extra drivers and trucks and has
also had to buy bigger, deeper newsstand racks _ but of course all
the cost is offset by the surging advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, there are worse problems to have in this world,'' Cona
said. ``As long as it thuds, it's good.'' He said that he is always
gratified when Don Logan, the chief executive of Time Inc., which
publishes In Style, calls to see the early copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He drops it on his desk and he listens,'' Cona said. ``And the
louder the thud, the happier he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3617 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LIBBY-PATAKI-ART-NYT &LR;      04-11 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBBY-PATAKI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR'S MANSION ISN'T WHERE LIBBY PATAKI'S HEART IS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT33, is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She wears a pink sweater set, pearls and navy pumps. She lives
in a 24-room Victorian mansion with a porch swing, blue willow
china and a Labrador retriever. She plays tennis, rides horses and
belongs to a prayer group. Her office is decorated with a tea set
and a ceramic stallion.
</P>
<P>
   She is Libby Pataki, first lady of New York state, and she knows
how easy she is to typecast. ``Yeah, I'm Waspy,'' she said the
other day, laughing at the admission. ``But not that kind of
Waspy.''
</P>
<P>
   The misconceptions come easily. Mrs. Pataki, 49, is the third of
six children of Col. Henry C. Rowland, an Army officer and diplomat
who had oversight of American military cemeteries in Europe. Her
childhood was spent overseas, in exotic ports of call. Her mother
is French. Sounds pretty snazzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a well-traveled, interesting childhood,'' Mrs. Pataki
agreed. ``But privileged? Well-heeled? No way.'' Again she burst
out laughing, her vivacity a contrast to her husband's phlegmatic
nature. He is said to be a charmer in private, but who would know?
</P>
<P>
   Money was tight, Mrs. Pataki said, especially after her father
retired from the diplomatic corps and had four children in college
simultaneously. She left Clark University in Worcester, Mass.,
after her freshman year to earn enough money to return later. There
was never a summer she did not work, she said, as a waitress or a
mother's helper.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first of her four children was born, there were six
years of glamorous employment, in the personnel department at
Warner Communications and running the international trading
operation at Paine Webber. But Mrs. Pataki saw quickly that her
husband, a lawyer, had political dreams that could not be realized
without a stay-at-home wife and mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children understand that they have to share their father,''
Mrs. Pataki said. (The children are Emily, 21; Ted, 18; Allison,
15; and George Owen, 12.) ``But there is nothing in the rule book
that says they have to share their mother. One of us gone is bad
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki began his climb in northern Westchester County, as
Peekskill's $6,000-a-year part-time mayor. Mrs. Pataki left the
fast track, living with her in-laws and running the produce stand
at the Pataki family farm, where her husband was raised and her
late father-in-law tended the orchard and vegetable plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Stew Leonard's we're talking about,'' Mrs. Pataki
said, conjuring a picture of herself as a lanky young woman in work
clothes, a baby on each hip, bagging apples and squash.
</P>
<P>
   The farm stand is gone now, and the first lady's widowed
mother-in-law lives with the Patakis in Garrison, in Putnam County,
halfway between the State Capitol and the governor's office in New
York City. Pataki so loves the setting, where eagles soar past the
bedroom window and he can hike the Hudson Highlands, that he tries
to make the 90-minute trip home each night.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting life in the Governor's Mansion was Mrs. Pataki's most
high-profile moment as first lady. ``I think it's very important
for my kids to see me cooking dinner or George cutting a hedge,''
she said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   She has no regrets. ``You have to keep your personal life at the
forefront,'' she said. ``That's what you have left when all this
other stuff is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pataki manages to say this without sounding smug, yet there
is an implied criticism of other first ladies. Could she be
thinking about Hillary Rodham Clinton? Donna Hanover, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's wife? She will not say.
</P>
<P>
   The same polite superiority surfaces when she talks of choosing
which ceremonial events to attend, distinguishing between ``splash
and substance.'' She never goes anywhere ``just to drink
Champagne,'' Mrs. Pataki said, sounding a bit like the junior high
school goody-goody.
</P>
<P>
   The events she chooses to attend, she said, are those that are
enriching for her children. There was the opening of the new
planetarium, which gave George Owen and a few of his friends a
chance to see the exhibit without waiting in line. Or the American
Film Institute gala for Ken Burns, who made a documentary about the
women's rights movement with seed money from a state commission
headed by Mrs. Pataki. It was a mother-daughter affair, and the
first lady took Emily, a junior at Yale, who is recovering from
reconstructive wrist surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, convened by the governor in 1998 for the 150th
anniversary of the first women's rights convention at Seneca Falls,
is Mrs. Pataki's proudest accomplishment as first lady. It produced
literature, maps and historical markers about the feminist movement
in New York state. It seems likely that a $125 million museum
proposed by the commission will be built in Battery Park City.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pataki's desk in the state office suite in New York City is
covered with architectural renderings. Her pride is evident. But
she is prouder that she runs her life ``in an orderly, mature
fashion'' that puts her children first. Of course, a parent is
there in an emergency, as the governor was on the day of Emily's
hand surgery, when he canceled a trip to visit Bill Gates. But Mrs.
Pataki puts the bar lower.
</P>
<P>
   Why, just the other morning, she said, Allison announced
unexpectedly that it was the opening day of softball season. Would
her mother be there and would she bring snacks?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sweet feeling for a mom to be able to do that,'' Mrs.
Pataki said. She cleared her calendar and baked cookies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
