<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3621 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-CHEFS-ART-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      04-11 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEFS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED A CHEF? HAVE YOUR PEOPLE CALL MY PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photos NYT1,2 sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In five years in New York, Richard Farnabe built up a
stellar resume. He started as a cook at Daniel, moved to Jean
Georges and eventually was promoted to executive chef at Mercer
Kitchen. Last year, he was hired away to cook at the Myriad Group's
Berkeley Bar and Grill. Shortly afterward, Tommy Hilfiger's
secretary came in to ask if he would like to cook for her boss.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he was approached by David Rabin, who was
opening a restaurant and needed a chef. Rabin also had a headhunter
seeking prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Farnabe came out on top. He took both jobs, cooking during the
day at Hilfiger's offices and at night at Rabin's Lotus, opening
next month. He had made himself marketable and played his cards
right, just like any young lawyer or investment banker trying to
get ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Farnabe's path represents just what has happened in the
restaurant world in recent years. Chefs have gone from being
essentially blue collar workers to true professionals, as much in
demand as athletes. Top players, like Daniel Boulud, Jean-Georges
Vongerichten and Alice Waters, have become brand names, and their
proteges, like Farnabe, use those brands as springboards.
</P>
<P>
   The vibrant economy has only accelerated the shift, with
restaurants opening seemingly by the second _ more than 250
restaurants opened last year in New York City, according to the
Zagat Survey _ and with an American public that has more money and
the ambition to eat well. Cooks who have beefed up their resumes
are more in demand than ever.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they are being lured away from these brand name
restaurants to cook in private homes, where the work is less
grueling and they can command higher salaries. At the same time,
competition among restaurants to find and keep good cooks is
intensifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most difficult labor market in any
restaurateur's memory,'' said Dennis Lombardi, an analyst at
Technomic Inc., a Chicago-based food-service consulting company.
``We used to have an ample supply of skilled and motivated
employees. Now, we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting chefs' jobs used to be an informal process, driven
largely by word of mouth. But now it is like any other highly
evolved profession: there are headhunters and agents to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them say I'm their secret weapon,'' said Alfred
Ehrlich, the owner of the Kitchen Maestro, an executive-chef search
and consulting concern in New York City, speaking of restaurants.
``And they don't want others to know about me.'' Ehrlich recently
helped Patricia Yeo, the former chef de cuisine at Hawthorne Lane
in San Francisco, become the chef at AZ, a restaurant opening in
Chelsea next month.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich, who was once a cook at La Reserve and worked in the
wholesale division of Gourmet Garage, is well connected in the
restaurant business. About a year and a half ago, after helping a
number of chefs and restaurateurs find cooks as a favor, he decided
to make a business of it. Some restaurants hire him for a single
deal, paying him a percentage of the chef's first-year salary. But
others, who want protection in the transient restaurant world, put
him on a retainer, so that if the chef he finds leaves, he can
search for a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   For Jack's Fifth, for instance, he found Herb Wilson to fill the
chef's position. But Wilson stayed for just a few months. Ehrlich
may soon have to find someone new.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's obviously a need,'' he said. ``Every day I get faxes
from people _ wish lists _ from chefs.'' Both restaurants and chefs
come to him.
</P>
<P>
   He is the reason Sam Hazen became the chef at Rue 57. Ehrlich
heard that Hazen had left Tavern on the Green, and he knew that
Marc Packer, a restaurateur opening Rue 57, was looking for a chef.
He made the match for Packer.
</P>
<P>
   Often, headhunting means poaching cooks from restaurants and
trading them like athletes. Phillip Alfus, an owner of the Alfus
Group, a Manhattan-based search firm, has found chefs for Tavern on
the Green and the Russian Tea Room. He won't steal from friends
like Daniel Boulud and Charlie Trotter, but ``outside of that
group,'' he said, ``everybody is fair game to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Yard, the pastry chef at Spago Beverly Hills, has had
headhunters take pastry chefs away from her. One went to the
Ritz-Carlton on Maui, another to Patina in Los Angeles. Laurent
Manrique, the chef at Campton Place in San Francisco, recently had
a cook lured away.
</P>
<P>
   An oral agreement is the traditional way to retain staff.
Restaurants like the Union Square Cafe and Chez Panisse in
Berkeley, Calif., offer cooks benefits that are standard in other
professions: medical insurance, for example, and paid vacations.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't always offer what wealthy families hiring private
chefs can. Gilbert Pilgram, the chef at Chez Panisse, had three of
his line cooks leave last year, hired away by families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I wasn't frustrated when it happened,'' Pilgram
said. ``Chez has an appeal. And people with money wanted to hire
senior cooks to be their private chefs.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Sherman was one of them. She had cooked at Chez Panisse
for seven years, working nine-hour days producing about 100 meals,
when she left to work for a family. Now, she works about seven
hours a day, cooking just dinner. The family she works for is well
traveled and knowledgeable about food _ and is familiar with Chez
Panisse and its bragging power. ``They definitely get some mileage
out of that, for sure,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Dickey was another. She works for a family in the Bay Area.
She gets to shop at the farmers' market, cooks just four days a
week, makes twice as much money and, she said, finally has the
energy to think about other things. ``Restaurants can really suck
the life out of you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman and a third Chez Panisse cook found their jobs through
Cindy Race and her partner, Susan Flynn, who three years ago
started Four Star Private Chefs, a placement agency in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Race became a private chef herself five years ago, after 17
years in restaurants. It changed her life, she said. ``I was
finally able to drive a car from this decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Most private chefs interviewed for this article said they were
earning at least twice what they made in restaurants and were
working about a third fewer hours. In New York City, salaries for
full-time private chefs hired through agencies start at about
$55,000 a year, said Keith Greenhouse, an owner of the Pavillion
Agency in Manhattan. They can go up to as much as $130,000.
Salaries are comparable in Los Angeles, but lower in San Francisco,
starting at around $45,000 for dinner only, Race said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the median hourly wage for a restaurant cook in New
York City, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, was $9.95
an hour, or $22,880 a year. And many cooks have hefty cooking
school loans to repay.
</P>
<P>
   The math is not difficult to do.
</P>
<P>
   With the influx of new money in places like New York City and
Silicon Valley, demand is booming. Steve Kelley, director of career
services at Peter Kump's New York Cooking School, said he gets
calls for private chefs all the time, most recently from young
couples with children. He has placed about a dozen chefs in the
last six months, including one with David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Race also has a busy phone line. ``And I have an unlisted
phone number and I'm not in the yellow pages,'' she said. Many of
her clients are couples in their '30s and '40s, looking for full-
or part-time cooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming a big status symbol,'' said Christian Paier, the
owner of Private Chefs Inc., an agency in Beverly Hills. ``It's
like having a personal trainer. Now, anyone who can afford it wants
to have their own chef.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of these families want just any chef. They want names _
brands, if you will _ that they can rely on. Race had a client who
wanted a cook who had worked for Nobu. Greenhouse had one who
wanted a cook from Bouley. Both found them.
</P>
<P>
   Clients are getting younger and younger, said Jo Lynne Lockley,
the owner of the Chefs' Professional Agency in San Francisco; many
are in their early '30s. And they want young chefs. ``These people
hiring someone who had been an executive chef would seem like
hiring their grandfather,'' she said. What they are getting is
talent in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   When Steve Kelley of Peter Kump's placed a cook with a family in
Southampton, N.Y., the cook was offered jobs by two guests. Now, he
cooks for the three families.
</P>
<P>
   These part-time arrangements, agencies say, are becoming
increasingly popular. Which is no surprise: it is much less
expensive than eating in a restaurant, which in places like New
York can easily cost $30 a person. For $200 to $250 a week, said
Robin Kellner, the owner of the Robin Kellner Agency, a family can
have three dinners prepared by an experienced cook.
</P>
<P>
   James Rafferty left a position as the chef at Boughalem in
Greenwich Village to become a private chef for a magazine publisher
in New York City. Having Bouley on his resume, he thinks, helped
him get the job.
</P>
<P>
   He cooks lunch and dinner for the publisher five days a week and
travels with him occasionally. When he goes to his house in Idaho,
Rafferty goes, too. And he snowboards in between meals. The stress
at his new job, he said, is a fraction of what it was at Boughalem.
</P>
<P>
   He used to work 12-hour days, finishing at midnight, and was
plagued with staff problems and tight costs. Now, he works
seven-hour days, can experiment with different styles of cooking
and has an unlimited food budget. He also gets to have dinner with
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   He got the job through Greenhouse at Pavillion. A few years ago,
Greenhouse also arranged a job for Franklin Becker as a private
chef for Ronald O. Perelman, the chairman of Revlon. Becker went
into it after working at a club, and catering, he said, simply to
save money. In less than two years, he did that, but there was more
to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped shape me,'' Becker said, ``as an individual and as a
cook.''
</P>
<P>
   And it provided the perfect stepping stone, which is why many
cooks do it.
</P>
<P>
   Becker parlayed his stint with Perelman into a job as the
executive chef at Local, an ambitious restaurant in Midtown
Manhattan. If he had stayed in that little-known club, he might
still be there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
