<HEADER>
A3623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FLOOD-AID12-COX     04-11 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-AID12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NORTH CAROLINA GOVERNOR PRESSES SENATE FOR FLOOD AID
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After meeting with White House officials, Gov. Jim
Hunt urged Senate leaders Tuesday to act on a bill that includes
more than $300 million in hurricane relief for North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers are on the verge of going out of business, Hunt said.
``They are considering right now whether or not they have to give
up, quit farming and sell their equipment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to get the funds, Hunt sent a letter Tuesday to
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who with other GOP
leaders has postponed action on a $12.6 billion emergency spending
package for the current fiscal year that includes the disaster aid.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans say the bill is bloated and that Congress
should deal with much of the spending, including flood relief, as
part of the normal appropriations process for fiscal 2001, which
starts Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said the agriculture and housing needs in flood-ravaged
areas are urgent and cannot wait for several months. More than
87,000 North Carolinians have applied for federal aid, more than
8,000 are still living in temporary trailers, and several thousand
others are living with family and friends, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many are older people who lost everything, Hunt said. ``It is
the saddest thing in the world. Those people need help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Lott, said that the senator
``is uniquely aware of the plight in North Carolina,'' and believes
the best way to deliver the aid is through the regular spending
process.
</P>
<P>
   The money could be available as soon as early summer if the
first spending bill is put ``on the fast track,'' Czwartacki said.
Last fiscal year, the first appropriations bill was signed into law
Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The $12.6 billion emergency spending bill is controversial for
reasons other than its size. It includes $2.1 billion for
peacekeeping operations in Kosovo and $1.7 billion for drug
intervention in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have lobbied against U.S. involvement in Colombia's
bloody civil war amid concerns about human rights violations and
drug trafficking by military and paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lott and other leaders decided to indefinitely
postpone scheduled committee votes on the overall spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   The action prompted a response from President Clinton, who said
in a statement that he was ``very disappointed that Senator Lott
plans to deny prompt consideration of the urgent and essential
needs ... including helping victims of Hurricane Floyd.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter Tuesday, Hunt asked the majority leader to allow a
Senate vote on the supplemental bill ``as urgently as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your leadership now in expediting congressional approval of
supplemental funding is critical for victims of this storm,'' the
letter says. ``It will help us make the necessary progress to get
people back in safe, permanent housing and to help our communities
recover.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergency spending package, which was approved by the House,
includes $81 million for tobacco farmers, $68 million for home
buyouts, $43 million for road repairs, $41 million for rental
housing and assistance, $12 million for a new Armed Forces Reserve
Center in Greenville, and $1.5 million for a U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers study on raising the dike on the Tar River in the
historic town of Princeville in Edgecombe County.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has sent nearly $2 billion in disaster
aid to North Carolina, but much of it was delayed for weeks last
fall in a budget fight between Congress and the White House. In
addition, the state legislature has provided $836 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said he is grateful to Lott for the federal aid that the
state received last year and is hoping Congress will finish the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that he (Lott) cares about the people in North
Carolina, but we need help. We need it now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
