<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3627 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-DICAPRIO-COLUM     04-11 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-DICAPRIO-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITIES AND THEIR CAUSES: A POLITICAL REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, April 11, or thereafter)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What if I told you someone had unearthed footage from a 1962
conversation between President John F. Kennedy and Paul Newman _
would you be interested in seeing something like that?
</P>
<P>
   Me too. The most powerful man in the world and one of the most
popular young movie stars of his generation could be talking about
the weather or the color of each other's ties and it would still be
a fascinating eavesdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's zoom forward to the year 2000. Instead of a
hypothetical situation, this time around we've got the real thing _
a conversation between the reigning president and the hottest young
male star in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Clinton and Leo DiCaprio. Together again for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   DiCaprio recently visited Clinton at the White House as part of
an ABC News special about Earth Day, that magical time when
environmentalists all over the world gather in public places and
leave behind piles of litter to be cleaned up by other people.
(Just kidding, environmentalists!) DiCaprio is chairing the
national Earth Day celebration, which is why he was at the White
House and not downing shots of tequila with 6-foot models in the
VIP room of some trendy club.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was for Clinton to take DiCaprio on a tour of the White
House, maybe show him the recycling bin for the Diet Coke cans. But
when the president and the actor sat down for something akin to a
real interview, journalists at ABC and elsewhere started hurling
themselves to the ground and howling in protest about this horrible
besmirching of their hallowed profession.
</P>
<P>
   I know. I'm giggling too, and I'm a card-carrying, multimedia
member of the press.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of the 15-minute interview, ABC News president David
Westin must have felt as if he was taking on more water than the
captain of the ``Titanic.'' Staffers in his division were
reportedly outraged that some mere actor had talked to Clinton with
an ABC News crew recording the moment.
</P>
<P>
   (Funny. I was more offended when ABC's legendary Barbara Walters
practically laid a wreath at the feet of John and Patsy Ramsey when
she interviewed them about the murder of their daughter. But I
guess it's easier and safer to protest ``Gilbert Grape'' boy than a
rollover by the grande dame.)
</P>
<P>
   Westin sent an e-mail to his disgruntled staff. It read, in
part:
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not send DiCaprio to interview the president. No one is
that stupid ... it's quite possible we'll use none of the
conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Come on Westin, are you nuts? You've got video of DiCaprio
hanging with Clinton and you might just leave it in the vault? No
one is that stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Westin also wrote: ``All roles of journalists must be played by
journalists (duh!).''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, that's Westin's ``duh!'', not mine. Good to know the
president of ABC News is up on the ``Buffy'' lingo.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters from ABC weren't the only ones stewing and fuming
about Leo's ``get'' with the prez. From a Scripps-Howard editorial:
</P>
<P>
   ``For all we know, DiCaprio handled his time with the prez just
fine, but that's not the issue. The point is that journalists are
practiced at getting to the heart of public policies without
letting too much unchallenged, self-serving folderol in the
backdoor, and when a network turns to untrained celebrities
instead, it is announcing that what it cares most about is amusing
all the folks out there, not getting at the truth of things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are not amused _ and should not be _ are the
journalists that take their calling seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh please.
</P>
<P>
   Do these media snobs seriously think the public can't
distinguish between a Leonardo DiCaprio and a Ted Koppel? What an
incredible insult to the news-consuming viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would expect DiCaprio to back Clinton against the ropes
with furious, unrelenting queries about serious matters, for crying
out loud. Nor would any fair-minded individual think ABC News had
lost any credibility because of this silly, harmless media event,
whether it's labeled an ``interview,'' a ``walk-through,'' a
``sit-down'' or a freakin' toga party.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that while ABC News employees and other
sanctimonious journalists were getting their credentials in a bunch
over Leo and Billy, nobody seemed to question what the hell Diane
Sawyer and her bosses were thinking when they exploited little
Elian Gonzalez on national TV. (At one point, Sawyer took off her
shoes and literally stood on her head. What, no barking like a
seal?)
</P>
<P>
   I guess when a movie star talks to the president, it's an
outrage. But when a TV superstar interviews a confused, 6-year-old
boy who only months ago saw his mother drown _ that's journalism.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
