<P>
   TECHJOBS-SOUTH _ The South leads the nation in the number of
information technology workers. Roughly 1.6 million new IT jobs
will be created this year; only half will be filled. These are just
some of the findings from a new study by the Information Technology
Association of America. (Joyner, Atlanta journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   COKE _ Following developments in the racial discrimination
lawsuit against Coca-Cola Co. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/COKE-BUS _The bus ``ride for justice'' to Coca-Cola's annual
shareholders meeting in Delaware will involve fewer people than
originally planned. ``We will have two buses instead of three
because there's less volume than we thought,'' said Larry Jones, a
former human resources manager at Coke and the trip's chief
organizer. Jones conceived the trip to pressure the company into
settling the racial discrimination lawsuit quickly. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-SKILLS _ WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan said Tuesday that improvements in job training are needed
to keep businesses and workers secure in times of rapid
technological change. Businesses will have to join with schools to
create a system that integrates work and training for both new and
older workers, Greenspan told a job skills conference. (Turay, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NETTAX-SENATORS _ WASHINGTON _ The top Republican leaders in
Congress plan an event Wednesday intended to establish the GOP as
the party standing steadfast against taxes on the Internet. But
behind the scenes, several Republican officials and business
leaders are trying to build a bipartisan coalition against a bill
that would extend a moratorium on new Internet taxes, including
sales taxes, until 2006. They say the bill, expected to clear the
Senate Commerce Committee this week, could erode the tax base for
state and local governments, forcing them to either boost income
and property taxes or turn to Washington for more federal grants
funded by income taxes. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA _ Delta Air Lines this fall will start flights to
Santiago, Chile, bringing to 12 the number of Latin cities it
serves from Atlanta as part of a 2-year-old buildup. Airline
executives say the Latin route network is performing well and
generating higher profit margins than the airline overall.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
