<HEADER>
A3638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPECIALIST-FILM-REVIE     04-11 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALIST-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SPECIALIST': EICHMANN TRIAL 40 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new documentary, ``The Specialist,'' comes at an interesting
time in the culture. The producer and director, Eyal Sivan, has
compiled and assembled black-and-white footage of the trial of the
SS officer and war criminal Adolf Eichmann, and his film is the
grimmest possible precursor to the occasionally frivolous ``Court
TV,'' which plays on the current fascination with watching the
judicial process grind exceedingly slow, and exceedingly fine.
</P>
<P>
   This year brings the 40th anniversary of Eichmann's capture; the
trial opened in Jerusalem a year later, in 1961. ``The Specialist''
is an amazing document, if only for the spectacle of watching
Eichmann, seated in a glass box with two armed guards, take in the
trial. The box exaggerates Eichmann's own natural remove, and as he
primly cleans his eyeglasses, it is hard to separate his demeanor
from his appearance: the sharp features, the thin, almost lipless
mouth that suggests the horrifying stereotype of dispassionate
cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   Sivan and his co-writer, Rony Brauman, have sifted through 350
hours of tape shot by the American documentary filmmaker Leo T.
Hurwitz, who was commissioned to film the trial, and found the most
dramatic footage. A scene in which the courtroom is darkened and
film evidence of atrocities is projected is both low-key and
unsettling. Reflections of those atrocities play across Eichmann's
box, and he stares ahead in detachment, peering through the
shadows, as the images are described by the prosecutor: ``A dead
man on an electrified fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Eichmann emerges as a different kind of ``Specialist'': the
title refers to his self-proclaimed ``expertise'' at
``emigration.'' His attempts to explain his position _ he calls
himself ``weak and powerless'' and actually utters the line ``I'll
simply obey orders,'' which might seem worthy of a laugh if it
weren't so repugnant _ are delivered in the same deadpan he uses
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Sivan's editor, Audrey Maurion, must deserve some credit as
well. The ``Specialist'' filmmaking team shows the prosecutors, led
by the cool Israeli attorney general, Gideon Hausner, whose
expression is bemused contempt whenever Eichmann speaks, make their
case with a startling lack of courtroom theatrics. As the horrors
pile up, their dignity in the face of Eichmann's cold lies seems
admirable, even as roiling stereo effects thunder on the soundtrack
to create an aural current of discord. There is enough drama here
that ``The Specialist'' doesn't require any extra emphasis.
(Another minor quibble: the subtitles are sometimes hard to see
against the black-and-white background.)
</P>
<P>
   When Hausner, addressing the judges, says that Eichmann ``was
born human but lived like a beast in the jungle'' and proves this
truth, point by point, the movie succeeds on much quieter _ and
more frightening _ terms.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE SPECIALIST'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Eyal Sivan; written (in English,
Hebrew, German and French, with English subtitles) by Rony Brauman
and Marc Sivan; archival footage by Leo T. Hurwitz; edited by
Audrey Maurion; music by Yves Robert, Krishna Levy, Beatrice
Thiriet and Jean-Michel Levy, and ``Russian Dance'' by Tom Waits;
released by Kino International. Running time: 128 minutes. This
film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Adolf Eichmann, Moshe Landau, Benjamin Halevy, Yitzhak
Raveh, Gideon Hausner and Robert Servatius.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EVERGLADES12-COX     04-11 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SENDS EVERGLADES BILL TO CONGRESS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Setting the stage for a congressional fight over
the scope and purpose of the proposed $7.8 billion, 25-year
Everglades restoration plan, the Clinton administration has sent
its version of the bill to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislative language would implement the plan
submitted last July by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to re-plumb
the South Florida water system in order to save the endangered
Everglades ecosystem and meet the water needs of the region's
population.
</P>
<P>
   Michael L. Davis, deputy assistant secretary of the Army for
civil works, called the bill, submitted late Monday, ``a balanced
approach.'' He said it guarantees that existing water users will
continue receiving water in roughly the same proportions as they do
now, while preserving the primary focus of the project to restore
federally owned environmental areas, including Everglades National
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to reach into that 70 percent (of water) that
goes into the urban and agricultural areas and take that away, but
we're also not going to reach into that 30 percent'' that goes for
environmental purposes, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure a proper balance in water usage between the competing
interests of the parks, agriculture and development, the bill calls
for a two-year process of identifying how much water each group
receives.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of the army would head that process, but would
need agreement from the secretary of the interior, who has
responsibility for the parks. Other federal and state agencies
would be consulted, but would not have authority to determine how
much water would be available to the parks. The two secretaries
also would determine how clean the water would be and when it would
be available.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have expressed some concern over the question of
who would decide how much water would be available to the competing
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a project which, in all senses of the word, is an
equal marriage'' between the federal and state governments, said
Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla. ``How that balance is struck will be a key
part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham joked that if an agreement can be worked out on sharing
authority between the state and federal governments, the
participants would be sent to the Middle East and Northern Ireland
to resolve those interminable conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Estenoz, director of South Florida programs for the
World Wildlife Fund, said environmentalists will insist that the
parks and the ecosystems receive top priority in the restoration
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American taxpayers need to be assure that they're going to
get what they pay for,'' Estenoz said. ``The primary purpose of the
Everglades restoration is the restoration of the Everglades. It's
critical that the American people, if they're going to contribute
$4 billion in this project ... be assured that the benefits
proposed to be delivered actually are delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Leary, associate director for natural resources of the
administration's Council on Environmental Quality, said he felt the
proper balance was assured because there were three safeguards over
allocation of water:
</P>
<P>
   _ The process by which the federal secretaries will set overall
goals for water distribution throughout the restoration effort.
</P>
<P>
   _ A requirement that each of the 68 different projects in the
restoration effort be approved, with individual regulations for
each project.
</P>
<P>
   _ The filing of joint reports to Congress every five years from
the secretary of the army and the secretary of the interior.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional action on the bill is expected as part of the
biennial Water Resources Development Act. The bill authorizes the
restoration project and $69 million in pilot projects to begin when
feasible. The cost would be shared equally by the federal
government and by state and local agencies. It also authorizes 10
``critical projects'' for a total of $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most controversial provisions is a $100 million,
10-year program of ``adaptive assessment'' of the project to
determine which new or expanded technologies work best in the
restoration effort.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said the bill faces serious challenges, but has strong
support from a united Florida delegation and key lawmakers
including Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., chairman of the Senate
Environment and Public Works Committee, and Rep. Ralph Regula,
R-Ohio, chairman of the House Interior appropriations subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   But other lawmakers, such as Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio,
chairman of the subcommittee that reviews the Corps' projects, have
questioned whether the Corps is moving too quickly on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., a Republican from Fort Lauderdale, sent a
warning to Florida legislators who have questioned the federal
commitment and role in the restoration project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need, in Florida, to get our signals straight,'' Shaw said,
adding that ``unfortunately, when somebody get critical of what is
going on ... that is the word that gets back up here. We need to
put those fires out before they become a blaze.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
