<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PHILLIPS-BOOK-REVIEW-     04-11 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLIPS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MR. PHILLIPS:' OBSESSIVE, COMPULSIVE AND UNEMPLOYED 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his masterpiece ``Ikiru,'' the Japanese director Akira
Kurosawa follows a faceless civil servant who, having learned that
he is dying of cancer, searches for meaning in a phantasmagoric
urban landscape. This 1952 film was a moral existentialist drama
about the loneliness of the long-distance bureaucrat who finds
redemption by helping victims of bureaucratic indifference.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurosawa classic is brought to mind by John Lanchester's
sardonic new novel, ``Mr. Phillips,'' a story set in contemporary
Britain, another island nation. The talented Lanchester's main
character, Victor Phillips, an accountant for a large bureaucratic
firm, has been fired from his job. Afraid to tell his wife and two
sons of his disaster, he wanders through London, his tie knotted
and his briefcase in hand, doing a sad imitation of what had been
his life.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Kurosawa's civil servant, this emotionally desiccated
nonhero fails to create much meaning; indeed, in his godless,
mechanized world of petty preoccupations there doesn't seem to be
much possibility of meaning at all, except perhaps in Lanchester's
own mordantly witty way of describing his character's plight.
</P>
<P>
   Lanchester is the author of the wickedly entertaining ``Debt to
Pleasure,'' which was a sort of murder confession in the form of a
literate cookbook. His new novel, while more deeply engaged in the
themes of hopelessness and repressed despair, is recognizably in
the Lanchester style. It has the originality of its voice, the
mocking lightheartedness of ``The Debt to Pleasure.'' There is much
to admire and enjoy in the new book, especially the hilarious
emotional detachment of its main character and the wickedly
off-center quality of its asides.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lanchester's novel is a brilliant semi-success, the kind
of semi-success that could only be wrought by a man of an engaging,
probing sort of intellect. Phillips' problem as a character is
suggestive of the ``Mr. Phillips'' problem as a novel. With one or
two welcome exceptions _ including a bank robbery near the end that
almost redeems the book all by itself _ the events within are
entirely inside the feckless accountant's mind. The main
characteristic of that mind is emotional avoidance, an idiot-savant
obliviousness that is grimly funny to encounter at first but that
begins eventually to wear out its welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has eliminated actual events from his life so that his
experience almost entirely consists of sexual fantasies of a
transgressive nature and compulsive attempts to describe the world
arithmetically. He wakes up next to his wife in the morning still
experiencing the priapic residue of some dream involving his former
secretary or his former boss' secretary. When he rides the train to
London, he sees a man looking at a photograph of a naked woman in a
tabloid newspaper and immediately calculates, on the basis of the
number of newspapers that publish such pictures, ``the number of
British women happy to take their clothes off for money per
annum.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has formally correct but intimacy-free relationships
with his sons and his wife. Life for him is going through the
correct motions, but not much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Staying away from home all day so he won't have to tell his wife
about his unemployment, Phillips observes the passing London scene
with a kind of resigned fastidiousness. He is painfully conscious
of industrial and human effluents. He reflects on the pervasiveness
of masturbation. ``Probably even the queen does it,'' he decides.
He is the kind of person who thinks about killing himself by
jumping off a bridge, but the thought is hijacked by his compulsive
statistical analyses8 he muses on the heights of different London
bridges and on the acceleration of falling bjects and calculates
how fast a suicide jumper would be going from each when he hit the
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beachy head, another popular spot, 535 feet, 5.6 seconds,
close to terminal velocity,'' he thinks. ``Severn Bridge, another
classic, 200 feet, 3.6 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his aimlessness, there is something admirable about
Phillips. He has no pretensions. He does not sink into self-pity.
His observations have an aesthetic, unillusioned sharpness to them.
He suspects that he lacks something most other men have: ``the
carapace which grows or solidifies around them as they get older,
and which involves an increasing lack of uncertainty about, or
interest in, anything they don't already know.'' Phillips is
curious and uncertain: he sees everything even if he hasn't done
much in his life.
</P>
<P>
   The differ%nce, in other words, between Phillips and other men
is that he is aware of his own particular soulessness in the more
general soulessness of contemporary, rationalized, commodified
existence. He sees a television personality who has excited
libidinous thoughts in him before and he notes that she is walking
out of a shop with a package labeled ``Chez Guevara'' under her
arm.
</P>
<P>
   That play on the revolutionary's name is a marvelous dig at what
the journalist David Brooks has been calling ``bohemian
bourgeois.'' The world Phillips inhabits is one in which his son
has a book on his shelf called ``Hitler Wins: Management Skills of
Germany's Greatest Leader.''
</P>
<P>
   This is funny in its absurdist way, too, as is Phillips' habit
of stopping in midstride to calculate over three pages or so the
amount of time spent in an average life doing nothing at all: ``a
weighted average of 16.375 percent, or 2.62 hourC, or 2 hours and
37 minutes, per day of, broadly speaking, free or nothing time.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an intellectual richness as Lanchester uses Phillips to
make his own understated but caustic commentary on the modern
sensibility, but not every incident in the novel rises to the level
of the best of its moments. That is what makes ``Mr. Phillips''
only a semi-success, that and the toll that the relentless exposure
to Phillip's anesthetized existence eventually takes. Unlike
``Ikiru,'' in which there is a moral resolution, Lanchester's
sensibility allows for no redemptive event. There is a great
honesty in that _ an unsentimental trueness _ and yet ``Mr.
Phillips'' remains a story about a life in which nothing happens,
and nothing happening, even as cleverly wrought as it is here, does
not generate much narrative force.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MR. PHILLIPS'
</P>
<P>
   By John Lanchester
</P>
<P>
   291 pages. G.P. Putnam's Sons. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
