<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, April 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Heavy snow over the mountains of northern New England will
gradually end as low pressure moves into the Canadian Maritimes. In
the wake of the low pressure, another day of unseasonable chill
will cover the Great Lakes and Northeast, despite ample sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southern states, from Texas to the Atlantic coast, a
front will be the focus of showers and some thunderstorms.
Recurrent heavy rain will raise the risk of flash flooding over
parts of central and northern Texas as moisture-laden air from the
Gulf of Mexico is forced to rise over cooler air to the north. Some
of the showers will reach the lower Mississippi Valley late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonable warmth will cover most of the West. Increasing
southwesterly breezes will draw the warmth into the Plains by
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: LAST FROST
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent bout with wintry chill and snow, the growing
season will soon begin in the Northeast. From mid-April to late
May, most of the Northeast typically has its last frost of the
spring. But, there can be dramatic variations in frost dates over
very short distances. The heat generated in cities can account for
up to 30 days' difference between the date of the last urban and
the last suburban frost. Nearby bodies of water can also help
prevent frost. Moreover, since cold air is heavier than warm air,
chill collects in lowlands on calm spring mornings, making valleys
more susceptible to frost than hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
