<HEADER>
A3644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-MEDIA-475&AMP;ADD-NY     04-11 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-MEDIA-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAIN JOURNALIST REMEMBERED AS GOVERNMENT LEVIES MORE MEDIA FINES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ As hundreds of people remembered a slain
journalist Tuesday, a man executed on the street a year ago as NATO
bombs were falling, the Yugoslav authorities stepped up their
campaign to intimidate and impoverish the independent press.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who came Tuesday to honor the journalist, Slavko
Curuvija, were not great fans when he was alive. But his death has
transformed him into a martyr figure he himself would probably not
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Curuvija, a publisher who had once been close to President
Slobodan Milosevic and his wife, Mirjana Markovic, had turned
against the regime. He was assassinated gangland-style on Orthodox
Easter Sunday a year ago as he walked with his wife. His killing
was understood to be a message to the independent press that overt
criticism would not be tolerated during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, as a plaque was unveiled on the street where he was
killed and ceremonies were held at his grave and at a downtown
media center, he was praised as having died for defending press
freedom and refusing to publish under wartime censorship. Nothing
was said of his former relationship to the ruling couple or his
role in the early 1980s as a political analyst for the state.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was a chance for opposition politicians and
journalists to show solidarity as the government continues a war of
nerves and court cases against the press.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the weekly magazine Vreme and its two top editors were
fined 350,000 dinars _ about $8,750 at the black market rate of
exchange _ in a suit brought by the culture minister for a February
article that said he arranged the firing of a theater director.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that Vreme, a magazine of opinion with a
circulation under 20,000, had been fined under Yugoslavia's
restrictive Public Information Law, passed in October 1998. The
first victim of the law had been Curuvjia and his magazine,
Evropljanin. Neither the magazine nor his successful tabloid
newspaper, Dnevni Telegraf, survived him.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Studio B, the Belgrade television station that is the
political opposition's main voice, was fined about $7,500 after a
suit by a police official. The station's editor, Dragan
Kojadinovic, was fined half that amount, the maximum under the law,
for which he is personally responsible.
</P>
<P>
   But Kojadinovic said neither fine will be paid. ``The government
can now do whatever they want, but we will defend our rights,'' he
said. The ruling could add fuel to an opposition rally planned for
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 law enables the government to indict, prosecute,
convict and fine a newspaper or television station within 48 hours
for violating a long list of rules. Equipment or bank accounts can
be seized if the fines are not paid.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since the conflict over Kosovo, the Belgrade authorities have
stepped up their use of the law and applied it more broadly to
radio and television stations, particularly those in the more than
30 cities and towns controlled by the opposition. The government
has also started confiscating transmitters and other equipment
belonging to stations that do not pay broadcast fees.
</P>
<P>
   The intention is to drain the independent media of funds _
though some of the fines have been paid by foreign supporters like
George Soros _ and to use fear to induce self-censorship, with
local and federal elections expected this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   In the towns of Kraljevo and Nis, government actions have
brought public protests. In Kraljevo, after fees were paid,
transmission equipment was returned.
</P>
<P>
   The government has also accused the independent media of
supporting the NATO countries that bombed Yugoslavia and want to
replace Milosevic. Journalists are being called traitors and
``Gestapo underlings'' by the Serbian information minister,
Aleksandar Vucic, a member of the nationalist Radical Party. The
party leader, Vojislav Seselj, accused journalists of causing the
assassination of Defense Minister Pavle Bulatovic in February.
</P>
<P>
   But Goran Svilanovic, president of Civic Alliance, an opposition
party, said the regime has another intention _ to point up the
opposition's inability to defend the press that generally supports
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic shows his muscles,'' Svilanovic said Tuesday. ``He's
showing that he can do these things to the media and that we cannot
protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   The regime has also used the courts to take over control of a
popular evening tabloid newspaper, Vecernje Novosti, and the
independent radio station B-92, now reborn under the wing of Studio
B as B2-92. The government has repeatedly brought successful court
cases against the newspapers Danas and Glas Javnosti; financial
cases against ABC Grafika, the Glas Javnosti publisher; and rolled
back small price increases for papers like the popular tabloid
Blic, making it much more difficult to cover the costs of
increasingly scarce and expensive newsprint.
</P>
<P>
   Officials deny that there is any campaign to muzzle the press.
The federal information minister, Goran Matic, said last week that
every station had to pay the broadcast fees it owes, as in any
other country. ``Stories about closing down media are lies and
manipulation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, at a commemoration for Curuvija, a former spokesman for
Milosevic, Aleksandar Tijanic, said that Curuvija had ``paid the
full price for his words and his thoughts'' and that all Serbs
should consider how brave they had been since the murder. In a
country where ``politicians and criminals work the same stage,'' he
said, the fact that Curuvija lies in the ground ``does not mean
that he is dead and that we are alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
