<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3646 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-SOPRANOS-ART-2TAKE     04-11 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOPRANOS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: CURTAINS FOR A 2ND SEASON OF LOVE, DEATH AND
ZITI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meadow may be going off to college, but she's still Daddy's
little Mafia princess. The second season finale of ``The Sopranos''
(to be repeated Wednesday night at 9 and Saturday night at 12:15 on
HBO) may have focused on the death of Big Pussy, who had spent the
season wearing a wire for the FBI and weeping in Tony Soprano's
bathroom about his betrayal. ``You were like a brother to me,''
Paulie Walnuts said, before he and Tony and Silvio shot Pussy and
dumped him in the ocean. (They made sure they removed his diamond
horseshoe-shaped pinkie ring first.)
</P>
<P>
   But while Pussy's family treachery drove much of the season's
plot, this year it became even more apparent that ``The Sopranos''
is as much about about social class, upward mobility and
all-American assimilation as it is about mob hits. Meadow, the
Sopranos' smart and spoiled high school senior daughter, is the
pivotal figure in that theme, the character poised to cross class
lines and escape the Sopranos' tacky, violent world.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the season finale, Meadow (Jamie-Lynn Sigler) is
embarrassed when she comes home with friends just as her father is
led away in handcuffs by the FBI. Her mother, Carmela, explains:
``Your father means well. He's given his life for you, for your
brother, for us.'' And Meadow seems to understand. ``This is who
Dad is _ my friends don't judge me,'' she says, and she'll drop any
friends who do. Though she has not announced where she will go to
college, in a quick dream scene Tony hears her choose Columbia.
This tension goes to the heart of ``The Sopranos.'' How will Meadow
reconcile the upscale life she and her family want for her, with
her background of gauche relatives and mob loyalty?
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Meadow was ever the most important character
in the series. One of the great achievements of ``The Sopranos'' is
that it weaves in trenchant social themes subtly, through realistic
characters and stories that keep the audience irresistibly
involved. Meadow was simply one of many elements in a rich season.
</P>
<P>
   Since new episodes began in January, ``The Sopranos'' was more
watched and, it seemed, more talked about than ever. Much of the
conversation involved wondering why this year wasn't measuring up
to last. A male colleague complained there wasn't enough of Tony's
mother, Livia (Nancy Marchand). A female colleague said Carmela had
gone haywire. (Edie Falco played her as perfectly as ever, but
Carmela did seem all over the place, uncharacteristically
threatening another woman into writing a college recommendation for
Meadow, and flirting with a handsome house painter who came to
redecorate the powder room.) The reasons were different, but
everyone had an opinion. Even my brother-in-law's golfing partner
sent a message: ``Tell your sister-in-law if she writes about `The
Sopranos' again I know what's wrong this season. Too many new
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one stopped watching or talking or complaining, which
simply proves how ``The Sopranos'' has raised the standard for
television, or at least for itself. However uneven, this season the
series remained surprising, daring, psychologically astute.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't perfect. There were far too many dream sequences in
the finale, including one in which Tony and his shrink (Lorraine
Bracco) make love on her desk. That's the kind of cheap trick the
networks fall back on. (Will and Grace kissed in an NBC promo but
it was all a dream!)
</P>
<P>
   Yet the season was also filled with high points. The
next-to-last episode, in which Tony's sister Janice (Aida Turturro)
shoots her fiance, the vicious Richie Aprile (David Proval), was
stronger and more surprising than the finale. Richie, after all,
had been holding a gun to  &UR; her &LR;  head during sex, and a sex-related
killing seemed all too likely. But throughout the season, the
series never made the obvious move. Even in the end, the whacking
of Pussy (Vincent Pastore) had the weight of inevitability rather
than an air of the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   There were other surprises that simultaneously deepened the
characters and kept the plot exploding. Christopher (Michael
Imperioli) was shot; no one is really guaranteed a long life except
Tony, the star. Christopher then had to choose between two
aspirations: Hollywood dreams and being a made man.
</P>
<P>
   And Tony became even more visibly a killer, shooting one of the
young men who had shot Christopher, even as the bloodied victim
squirmed and cried for his mommy. James Gandolfini's ability to
sink into the complex character of Tony and reveal him, without a
trace of overt acting, remains a wonder.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   However violent, though, the series always comes back to the
Sopranos' personal family dynamics, depicted with startling
crispness. These are the scenes that allow audiences to sympathize
with such corrupt characters, and the moments between Meadow and
her father continue to be among the truest. She is just old enough
to challenge Tony's life and career. Remember, it was Meadow who
asked point-blank last season if he was in the Mafia, in what may
be the best episode yet, when Tony took her to visit colleges and
garroted an informer along the way.
</P>
<P>
   One of this year's most powerful episodes was also about this
fraught, loving father-daughter relationship. Tony gave Meadow a
car that belonged to one of her friends, Eric, which he had taken
because Eric's father owed Tony money. It was a gesture of extreme
control, as Tony pushed his criminal life in Meadow's face and
obstinately refused to understand why she was upset. It was the mob
version of a father's not wanting his little girl to grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Tony's children are touchstones. This year his
pre-adolescent son, Anthony Jr. (Robert Iler), had a terrific and
witty existential crisis. He was drawn to the works of Nietzsche,
which he pronounced ``Neech.'' His pronunciation was corrected, not
by his father, of course, but by the son of another mobster, part
of Anthony Jr. and Meadow's better-educated generation.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the humor of ``The Sopranos'' comes from the gaudy
trappings of their lives, Tony with his gold bracelet and Carmela,
packed this season into too-tight pants. When Tony's men started
running a stock brokerage, the joke was seeing goons in a Wall
Street setting. Even while those details are exploited for their
humor they are immensely revealing.
</P>
<P>
   Just as last season ended with Tony, Carmela and the children
gathered around a table, toasting the supreme importance of family,
this season ends with a montage that starts at Meadow's high school
graduation party. It includes a snapshot taken of Tony, Carmela,
Anthony Jr. and Meadow in her cap and gown: a picture of bourgeois,
upwardly mobile American values. It ends with a close-up of Tony
lighting a cigar, a sinister look on his face, followed by an image
of the ocean, where Pussy (Tony had dreamed he was a talking fish)
now sleeps. That smooth continuity from one family to another
continues to make ``The Sopranos'' the best series on television.
What is the future of such a family? Where do they fit into
American society, a society whose viewers have embraced them so
vigorously?
</P>
<P>
   Repeats will begin in June and the third season sometime next
year, creating withdrawal pangs even for people who don't usually
watch television. HBO's ``Sopranos'' Web site
(www.hbo.com/sopranos) is a poor substitute, but it has its amusing
aspects. It includes the winner of this year's favorite-line
contest, voted on by viewers. Because the series' language is
uncensored, last year's winner cannot be printed in its entirety. A
polite version has Anthony Jr. complaining when he learns that
Livia isn't coming to his birthday party, ``What, no ziti now?''
This year's winner is an almost entirely unprintable line from
Uncle Junior (Dominic Chianese) telling where federal marshals are
in relation to his anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   How could voters have overlooked the line from the poker
episode, in which Frank Sinatra Jr., playing himself, was called
``chairboy of the board''? Or an even more gleeful line that
perfectly captures both the family dynamics and the clever style of
the season. Tony puts his murdering sister on a bus to Seattle and
says, with a wry delivery only Gandolfini could manage, ``All in
all, though, I'd say it was a pretty good visit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
