<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3648 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NETTAX-SENATORS12-COX     04-11 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETTAX-SENATORS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOME REPUBLICANS CALL FOR CAUTION ON INTERNET TAX BAN
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The top Republican leaders in Congress plan an
event Wednesday intended to establish the GOP as the party standing
steadfastly against sales taxes on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the scenes, several Republican officials and business
leaders are trying to build a bipartisan coalition to oppose a
five-year extension of a moratorium on new Internet taxes,
including sales taxes on out-of-state purchases.
</P>
<P>
   They say such a lengthy ban would erode the tax base for state
and local governments, forcing them either to boost income and
property taxes or turn to Washington for more grants.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, is emerging as the leader of
Republican legislators fighting the tax ban.
</P>
<P>
   State officials will ``come here with their hat in hand and
their tin cup out'' if sales tax revenue falls, Voinovich warned
last week at a news conference organized by an ally, Utah's
Republican Gov. Michael Leavitt.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich and Leavitt want Congress to extend the moratorium,
now set to expire in 2001, only by another year or two, just long
enough for states to simplify sales tax rules and rates. Once
streamlined, taxes should be collected by all retailers, whether
operating in a store, by mail, by telephone or on line, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to force online merchants to collect sales taxes could
cause Ohio alone to lose $2.5 billion by 2002, Voinovich said
Tuesday. Many senators have been ``shortsighted'' about what such a
loss might do to local services, such as police and fire
protection, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they had any idea the impact sales tax have on
states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Voinovich appears out of step with GOP leaders, who
Wednesday will accept an ``anti-tax'' report from Gov. James
Gilmore, R-Va., chairman of the Advisory Commission on Electronic
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was charged by Congress with making
recommendations on Internet tax policy. When it failed to reach the
prescribed ``supermajority'' of 13 votes to make a formal
recommendation, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told
Gilmore that Congress would accept a ``report'' based on a simple
majority.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 11-8, the panel approved a plan to keep the tax
moratorium until 2006 and provide tax exemptions for certain
Internet-based businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Lott and the top GOP leaders in the House, Speaker
Dennis Hastert of Illinois and Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas,
are expected to accept the report from Gilmore with glowing praise.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, in a speech Monday at the Information Technology
Association of America's national convention in Chicago, said ``the
Congress, under Republican leadership, will vote to extend the
moratorium on Internet taxes.'' He added: ``The party that believes
in more taxation is the Democrat Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Senate Commerce Committe Chairman John McCain,
R-Ariz., will hold a hearing on extending the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Prem, a partner with the accounting firm of Deloitte &AMP;
Touche, said that if the moratorium lasts until 2006, online
retailers probably will never collect the same sales taxes as
traditional retailers. ``The longer the status quo lasts, the
harder it will be to make changes later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Voinovich, a former governor of Ohio and mayor of Cleveland,
has been working with another former governor, Sen. Bob Graham,
D-Fla., to build a bipartisan support for the extension of sales
tax collection duties into cyberspace. They were joined last month
by 10 other senators of both parties who signed a letter to Gilmore
saying: ``We strongly urge that the commission recommend support
for a 'level playing field' for all retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who signed was Sen. Slade Gorton, a Republican from
Washington, home to the leading Internet retailer, Amazon.com.
While that company might benefit from avoiding tax collection
duties, the state derives about 59 percent of its revenues from
sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Many business leaders also are siding with Voinovich and Graham,
including executives from traditional retail chains.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Parrish, a lobbyist for Tandy/RadioShack, said he believes
lawmakers will tone down their rhetoric as they become more engaged
in the tax debate. ``It would be unfortunate if this became
partisan, because it's too darned important for that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Scott Montgomery of the Dayton Daily News contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.e-fairness.org.
www.ecommercecommission.org
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
