<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3650 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV11-     04-11 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV11-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A BOY CAUGHT IN A WHIRLWIND  
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday April 11) 
By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retired Judge Rex Sater can get quite passionate talking about
Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he yells at his TV and admits news reports send him
into a ``blind rage.'' But his opinion on where the little boy
belongs is simple and uncluttered: Elian should be with his father.
In Sater's mind it's a simple custody case, having nothing to do
with how awful Cuba is versus how wonderful America is. Take away
the political grandstanding, ideological tug of war, media circus
and bureaucratic dithering and it's a regular family law decision.
</P>
<P>
   Father had joint custody; kid goes back to the father.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonoma County Superior Court judge revolutionized the way
child custody and divorce matters were settled in California. In
the 1980s he began forcing disputing parents to sit together to try
to work something out - meet and confer in legalese terms - before
asking him to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Once the two agreed, Sater made sure neither parent wiggled from
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Once a mother took a child to Europe, stashed the child with
relatives and briefly returned to California. Sater charged her
with contempt of court, put her in jail and told her she'd get out
once the child arrived at San Francisco International Airport and
was met by the father.
</P>
<P>
   The way Sater sees it, the mother of Elian was breaking the
agreement with Elian's father by taking Elian out of Cuba. Had she
lived she might have kept the father from ever seeing his child
again.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week authorities caught up with a California divorced
mother who three years ago took her son from his father, moved to
Sweden, changed their names, moved on to Spain and then Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Sater says there are thousands of kids around the United States
hiding with a parent who has grabbed them from the other. ``It's a
cruel thing to do to a child,'' he says, ``to just go off and
vanish.'' It's also not tolerated by courts who immediately issue
an order to bring the child back when the offending parent is
found.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Elian's isn't an everyday story. There are plots and
subplots and relatives and advocates all over the place. However,
if you take away presidential politics and Virgin Mary sightings,
you can almost see through the cotton candy haze to a familiar
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Florida relatives are like the weekend parent. The
eternal fun parent, desperate to prove love and devotion. In Miami,
Elian lives in a world of baby rabbits one day, water slides the
next, slick new shoes and a cell phone. You wonder if this child
ever goes to school. Every photo shows him with a new toy and being
hugged and kissed by relatives.
</P>
<P>
   This is the world of the weekend father or mother, the parent
who for understandable but not necessarily healthy reasons, tries
to court a child with excess.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is often employed by desperate parents who think
that the way to a child's heart is through best seats at the ball
game, all-you-can-eat chili dogs and staying up past bedtime,
unlike the boring routine over at their other house. In the average
divorce scenario, the boring parent, whose task is to keep the kid
in clean socks and get him to school during the week, resents
losing the popularity contest to the weekend parent.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced parents and their relatives compete for the kids. They
do it out of love and fear and resentment, along with the often
honest conviction that they are the better parent and don't approve
of the second household.
</P>
<P>
   Kids can become tiny tyrants when they are the object of
competition. Usually this ends when the weekend parent gets tired
of puppet shows. Child says to Dad, ``What are we doing this
weekend?'' and he says, ``Nothing special. We're staying home and
mowing the lawn.'' The child, accustomed to privilege, wails but
finally adjusts and learns to make do with just Dad.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who say that a child can never have too many
people to love him.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced parents say this a lot, trying to make themselves feel
better about their child going back and forth between two houses
and eventually new step-families. In Elian's case, however, there
are almost too many people loving him.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteer bodyguards and the near-hysterical devotees who
beg for a chance to touch his hand must be scary to a little kid.
The angry human chain link outside his house would give anyone
nightmares. Yet, the passions of his Miami family seem sincere and
heartfelt. They've made sacrifices to become Americans and have
obviously come to cherish this little boy. It would be wrenching to
give up a beloved child to a place you don't believe in. But the
same could be said of Elian's only living parent.
</P>
<P>
   Following Judge Sater's strategy, now that Elian's father is in
the U.S., maybe he and the Miami relatives can do the adult thing
and allow Elian to go back, not just to Cuba, but to being a little
boy again.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
