<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CAMBODIA-COURTS-900(2     04-11 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-COURTS-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOB JUSTICE RAGES IN CAMBODIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ What most unnerved Olivier de Bernon as
he faced a violent mob not long ago was the sight of a group of
Buddhist monks in their bright orange robes, laughing and pointing
at him.
</P>
<P>
   De Bernon, a French historian, had come across the crowd as it
was kicking and punching a young man accused of stealing a
motorbike. Without stopping to think, de Bernon stepped into the
crowd, he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was already down and they were still beating him,'' de
Bernon said. ``At the beginning I had one leg shaking, a mixture of
fear and anger. I was so upset. I was so upset. I knew at once that
it was a lynching. They wanted to kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a word being spoken, the crowd fell back at the sight of
the determined foreigner. And then, for the next two hours until an
ambulance arrived, de Bernon stood over the unconscious young man,
face to face with the crowd, a dozen passive police officers and
the group of giggling monks, who had not taken part in the attack
but found de Bernon's behavior so unusual as to be amusing.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of mob justice, often abetted by police officers who
say they find the lynchings and beatings a short-cut around the
vagaries of the courts, has become an epidemic in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   The spread of mob killings in the past year is one of many signs
of the failure of a justice system that the United Nations tried to
put in place here nearly a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Critics both within and outside Cambodia say that the courts are
incompetent, politically subservient and thoroughly corrupt and
that well-connected people can commit the worst of crimes with
impunity.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has led most experts to agree that Cambodian courts
are unfit to conduct a fair and professional tribunal for the men
who led the Khmer Rouge from 1975 to 1979, when more than 1 million
people lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
   When their guerrilla movement collapsed in the past two years,
most of the Khmer Rouge leaders retired, unchallenged, to quiet
lives in Phnom Penh and elsewhere. They include five former members
of the Khmer Rouge standing committee, prime defendants in any
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, which has proposed an international court,
has reached an impasse with Prime Minister Hun Sen, who insists
that Cambodian prosecutors and judges dominate any tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   As this dispute continues, the spread of mob killings _ and the
number of ordinary Cambodians who support them _ offers its own
verdict on the quality of the judicial system: the lynchings have
become known as ``people's courts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's `instant justice,''' said a foreign diplomat with long
experience here. ```Since there is no justice, I'll do it myself.'
And the police are often present and encourage people to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the fragility or even the nonexistence of any form of
a just system at any level. I think it also shows the frustration
of the people and the brutality of this culture, still. This is a
way to kill people very similar to the way the Khmer Rouge did it.
You don't need a gun; you can do it more cheaply.''
</P>
<P>
   Most discouraging to those who want to reform the justice system
is that many Cambodians seem not to see the difference between the
workings of a court system and the rule of the mob.
</P>
<P>
   When de Bernon returned to his office in Phnom Penh, where he is
based, he said, his Cambodian staff _ like the monks who had
watched him _ found his behavior peculiar. They tried to educate
him: ``But he was a thief,'' de Bernon recalled them saying.
``People were upset.''
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent example of this blind spot in Cambodia's
development is a new campaign by Hun Sen _ at least partly aimed at
impressing foreign critics _ to whip the judiciary into line by
executive fiat.
</P>
<P>
   In what he called an anticorruption campaign, he ordered the
police to re-arrest scores of suspects who were released without
trial or freed before their sentences were complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government respects the independence of the courts,'' the
prime minister said, ``But we cannot allow bad people inside the
court system to act improperly.''
</P>
<P>
   This kind of attitude is at the nub of the dispute over a trial
of Khmer Rouge leaders, said Demelza Stubbings, a representative of
the London-based human rights group Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is going to be in charge of a tribunal of the Khmer
Rouge?'' she asked. ``Is the government going to tell the court to
try them again if it doesn't like the results?''
</P>
<P>
   More likely, experts here say, the outcome of any Cambodian-run
trials would be decided before they start. In what some people see
as a test case, one Khmer Rouge commander was tried last year for
killings committed after the group was driven from power. He was
found guilty; the trial took one day.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of these convictions by fiat is the debilitating
fact of life in Cambodia that people with power, influence or money
almost always go free.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phrase `culture of impunity' has become almost a cliche,''
said the New York-based group Human Rights Watch in a recent report
on the justice system. ``The problem ranges from the failure to
prosecute Khmer Rouge leaders to hundreds of more recent unpunished
crimes committed by current government authorities.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Government officials, their bodyguards, members of the military,
village leaders and their goons, well-connected brothel owners and
anybody with the money to pay for freedom _ rarely are any of these
punished.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been arrested in a grenade attack at an opposition
rally three years ago in which at least 17 people were killed and
more than 100 injured. No one has been arrested in more than 100
political killings that followed Hun Sen's coup in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When soldiers shot dead nine fishermen suspected of stealing
cows, the investigating judge told Human Rights Watch that she had
not taken any action on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about my safety because the case is connected to the
police, local authorities and the military,'' the investigator
explained. ``The police and the commune chief are OK, but the
military might be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if any of these cases were to reach a courtroom, the
administration of justice remains primitive.
</P>
<P>
   Most educated people _ including judges and lawyers _ were
executed during the Khmer Rouge period. Many of the survivors fled
as refugees in the 1980s, when Cambodia was occupied by Vietnam.
Real legal education has only begun here since the United Nations
tried to restore a civil society in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many judges have little or no legal education and
many have not been taught basic principles of justice.
</P>
<P>
   It is a paradox that Hun Sen has formally acknowledged the
inability of the courts to try the Khmer Rouge, while insisting
that they conduct the trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason people kill robbers in the streets is that they
have no trust in the courts,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   It was into this world of topsy-turvy ``justice'' that de Bernon
stepped the other day. The representative in Cambodia of the French
school of Asian affairs, l'Ecole francaise d'Extreme-Orient, he has
lived in Cambodia for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In less than two minutes it was clear that nothing would
happen to me,'' he recalled. ``I understood rapidly that none of
them was upset, enraged, angry. They were just giving way to their
bad instinct. Just because I was there I spoiled something, a
self-allowance beyond normal behavior. Physically I was nothing,
but I think I broke a game.''
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, he said, someone from the crowd would
approach the man on the ground and give a little kick or lift his
eyelids with a key to see whether he was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood next to him, two hours, and when they came sometimes
to play with the body I interfered, gently, saying nothing,'' de
Bernon said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he spoke to a member of the crowd only once.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I said was to a boy who kicked his head with
his heel,'' he said. ``I had a very bad glance at him and I called
him in Khmer, `You are a chicken with white ears.' A coward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
