<P>
   SCFLAG _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ State senators will debate for the
first time this year whether to remove the Confederate battle flag
from the top of the South Carolina Capitol. Already, the debate in
South Carolina _ where an NAACP tourism boycott is in effect _ has
taken its toll elsewhere. In Pensacola, Fla., the City of Five
flags, the city manager has removed the battle flag from city
property in favor of the national flag of the Confederacy. City
officials in Jackson, Miss., also removed the Confederate battle
flag from its buildings. Legislators in Mississippi, which uses the
battle emblem in its state flag, have debated whether to remove the
insignia. The emotional debate has seeped into Georgia, where the
SCLC has threatened a tourism boycott of the Peach State if the
General Assembly won't remove the Civil War battle design from the
state flag. South Carolina senators may debate the flag issue until
it reaches a compromise. Set up for debate starting Wednesday in
South Carolina senate. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
