<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3668 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA12-COX     04-11 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta will add Chile service on Nov. 1
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines will start service Nov. 1 between
Atlanta and Santiago, Chile. It is the carrier's latest move in a
2-year-old Latin route expansion that executives say is highly
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago will bring to 12 the number of destinations in Mexico,
Central America and South America that Delta serves from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   That's up from four in early 1998, when the airline and its
just-hired chief executive, Leo Mullin, launched a wave of new
Latin routes.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to make Atlanta a new gateway for Latin travel,
offering an alternative to Miami, where American Airlines has the
industry's biggest Latin hub.
</P>
<P>
   Delta remains well behind American and Continental Airlines in
numbers of passengers handled and destinations served, but it makes
more money on its routes, said Jorge Fernandez, Delta's director
for Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of profitability, we're No. 1,'' Fernandez said
Tuesday at a conference in Atlanta for Latin journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Delta executives say operating profit margin on Latin routes is
about 15 percent, 3 points higher than Delta's overall margin and
much higher than the Latin margins achieved by American and other
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation is that Delta has focused on flying to national
business centers rather than tourist destinations and more of its
passengers travel on higher, less-restricted fares.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin acknowledged the Latin expansion suffered early growing
pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first six months were demanding as we worked out snags and
overcame start-up costs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the airline's efforts to market Atlanta as a better
connecting point than Miami have taken root.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making that representation and selling that
representation, and the great thing is it happens to be true,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Santiago flights, which are made possible by
an ``open skies'' U.S.-Chile air treaty, Delta also hopes to start
Atlanta-Bogota, Colombia flights this year. But it faces
competition from Continental for flight rights available under the
U.S.-Colombia air treaty, with a decision by the U.S. Department of
Transportation expected by late summer.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also wants badly to add Atlanta-Buenos Aires, Argentina
flights, but cannot until pending air treaty issues are resolved
and the DOT awards routes to carriers. Destinations now served by
Delta from Atlanta are three cities in Mexico, two in Brazil and
one each in Peru, Panama, Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala and
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBEE-BABY-2TAKES-NYT     04-11 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBEE-BABY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBEE TAKES HIS DISAPPEARING BABY TO HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In Edward Albee's new play, ``The Play About the
Baby,'' which opens Wednesday at the Alley Theater, a young married
couple have a baby and soon find themselves bedeviled by two
strangers, an older man and woman. Eventually the child disappears.
Truth? Illusion? What happened to the baby? As usual, Albee leaves
it to the audience, except to say, yes, there was a real baby.
</P>
<P>
   When the play was first presented at the Almeida Theater in
London in 1998, as directed by Howard Davies, the reviews were
sharply divided. After a possible New York production was
postponed, Albee decided to do it at the Alley, a familiar regional
theater that allows him complete artistic freedom. He cast the play
with American actors, including Marian Seldes and Earle Hyman as
the older couple. Both have worked with him before, Seldes most
recently in ``Three Tall Women,'' Hyman in 1980 in ``The Lady From
Dubuque.''
</P>
<P>
   Albee is directing the play himself. During rehearsals, when the
director wanted to cut a page and a half of dialogue as
``self-indulgent,'' the playwright raised no objection. ``I spoke
to him,'' said the director. ``He trusts me.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then Albee has been restudying the play, cutting lines and
adding others, balancing a need for clarification against a wish to
retain a certain level of ambiguity. At the first preview, on
Friday night, some lines were missed and the voice of a prompter
was heard. On Saturday the performance was tighter, but there were
still rough edges, especially in the second act.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a passageway leading to the stage, unseen by the
actors or the audience, the playwright watched and made mental
notes. Was the audience following the story? Did the actors have
the right spontaneity? In the original script, the evening ended
with a coda. An oversize, puppetlike baby crawled on stage, an
attempt at a coup de theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Davies had excised the scene from the London production, and now
Albee has restored it, with a Houston actress inside the puppet.
But in previews doubts remained. Did the audience realize that this
baby was a metaphor? Was it confusing?
</P>
<P>
   While expressing his appreciation of Davies for ``teaching me a
lot about the play,'' Albee is trying to place his authorial
imprint on the production. Describing differences from the London
version, he said, ``It's an American play, being done in America,
by American actors.'' The older actors are also older by a
generation, with Seldes and Hyman assuming the roles created by
Frances de la Tour and Alan Howard.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston production is less naturalistic. In London the play
took place in a sparsely furnished loftlike space that could have
been the young couple's apartment. In Albee's version, the setting
is bright, almost bare _ two modular chairs and a bench simulating
a stage, or what he calls ``a presentational space.'' At various
times the actors address the audience directly: they are performers
and the play is, as intended, at least partly a vaudeville.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not A Couple,'' Albee said of the older pair. ``They
just have a job to do.'' And that job? Albee smiled and with some
reluctance said, ``My subject is the compromises we make and the
lies we tell ourselves because living on the edge is too dangerous.
The play is about how much pain and loss we can take, and when we
can take it.'' He paused and said in an aside: ``A rollicking
comedy about how much pain and loss we can take, he said,
laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he quoted a pivotal section from the play: ``Our reality is
determined by our need'' and ``The greater the need rules the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracing the origin of the play, Albee said there was a direct
connection to ``The Lady From Dubuque.'' Both plays share that
central theme of ``how we determine our own reality.'' In both,
there are two mysterious figures imposing themselves on a new
environment.
</P>
<P>
   With ``The Play About the Baby,'' the author's sympathies would
seem to be with the young people. As he said, ``When you come to
the end of your life, the most awful thing is to think you haven't
lived. Regret over what we have done is OK, but regret over what we
have failed to do or chosen not to do is unforgivable. And I
suppose that's a theme that runs through all my plays.'' He added,
``That won't stop a lot of people from misunderstanding, from
thinking my themes are all about my being adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was annoyed by interviewers who say: ``Well, Mr.
Albee, you've written another play about a baby. Obviously it
relates to the non-existent baby in `Who's Afraid of Virginia
Woolf?' and the destroyed baby in `The American Dream,' doesn't
it?'' His response is that it doesn't, and that it only perpetuates
a myth.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the young couple in ``The Play About the Baby,''
he said: ``There's an Adam and Eve quality to these kids. So
innocent, so pure'' _ until life comes along and knocks them down,
or, as he said, ``grows them up.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation backstage, Seldes carried the Edenic
comparison one step further. For her the young people are like Adam
and Eve and she and Hyman ``are the snakes,'' insinuating
themselves and then invading the romantic and parental paradise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that the wound that will stay with them forever?'' Seldes
asked. ``That the baby's gone, that people turn away for a moment
and a child falls into a pool and drowns. What is your most beloved
thing in life? Your child.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She drew a personal memory: ``Edward and I were born in the same
year, and the kidnapping of the Lindbergh baby was the first major
event outside my life, in the newspaper. I mentioned that to Edward
and he said he had a bow and arrow ready to kill the kidnappers
when they came.''
</P>
<P>
   In the play questions of kidnapping and child abandonment are
raised, and theatergoers may think about related cases in the news
and in other Albee plays. The author would prefer not to.
</P>
<P>
   Several moments in the play refer to the author's own life. At
one point, the older man remembers being host at a party and
standing next to a ``tall older woman.'' Trying to introduce her to
two of his friends, he realizes he has forgotten who she is. One of
his friends says, ``We know your mother, dear.''
</P>
<P>
   That incident and the momentary memory lapse happened to Albee
himself. But, as with all such episodes, it has been transferred to
a fictional character _ and it makes a point about parents and
children.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the themes of the play, Gregory Boyd, the artistic
director of the Alley, widens their relevance. ``It's back to
American subject matter,'' he said: ``pipe dreams, illusions
shattered, as in `The Iceman Cometh,' `Streetcar,' `Death of a
Salesman' _ and `Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'''
</P>
<P>
   While readying the play for its opening, Albee has also been
teaching playwriting at the University of Houston, as he has for
more than a decade. At his winter home in Florida, before returning
to Houston, he was working on a new play, tentatively titled, ``Who
Is Sylvia?'' It is, he said, tersely, ``about the limits of
tolerance.'' He is eager to return to that work, but for the
present he is preoccupied with ``The Play About the Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Between performances, rehearsals and revisions continue. Sunday,
Albee made a crucial change. He decided to remove that final image
of the larger-than-life baby. In place of it, he wrote new dialogue
for the young couple, trying to end the play on a sadder, more
intimate note. The director and the playwright were in complete
agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
