u e BC-LAUDER-GRAHAM-BOS &LR;      04-11 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUDER-GRAHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESTEE LAUDER TURNS TO OLDER MODEL TO BECOME ITS `FACE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elizabeth Hurley, a darling of Hollywood and the official face
of cosmetics company Estee Lauder since 1995, is being bumped from
the spotlight as the primary Lauder spokesmodel. At 34, she's too
old, right? Actually, she's been upstaged by a 54-year-old, Karen
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   A successful model in the 1970s and '80s, Graham appeared on the
cover of Vogue 20 times and served as the Estee Lauder spokesmodel
from 1970 to 1985, before she retired at 40.
</P>
<P>
   Now Estee Lauder has wooed her back for a new campaign,
promoting an eye and face cream line called Resilience Lift,
designed for women over 35. (Hurley will continue to represent
other Lauder products). Says Graham, ``This is not Elizabeth's
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham is one of a growing corps of older models, including
Cindy Crawford (33) and Isabella Rossellini (47), who are extending
their careers past 30, the typical retirement age for most models.
Part of their success stems from demographics. About 53 percent of
American women are 35 years old and older, according to the US
Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Society's attitude toward aging is changing as people live
longer and healthier lives. ``Society is getting rid of traditional
constraints and ideas that older women are just ready for the
garbage heap, that older women aren't sexy or shouldn't look
beautiful,'' says Ruth P. Rubinstein, an associate professor of
sociology at the Fashion Institute of Technology in New York.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, models like Graham don't exactly look old. At 5 feet
7, Graham, a green-eyed blonde, weighs just 128 pounds. Her skin
appears smooth, firm, and relatively wrinkle-free. (Graham says she
hasn't had surgery). ``You don't have to be young to be
beautiful,'' Graham says with laughter. ``I think there's beauty at
every age. I can remember my grandmother in her 80s had beauty. . .
. Beauty comes from within.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's secret may be her lifestyle. Since she retired in 1985,
the Mississippi native has shunned the city life, operating a
fly-fishing school in Rosendale, N.Y., with business partner Bert
Darrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout most of my adult life, I've always enjoyed fly
fishing,'' Graham says in her soft Southern accent. ``I always did
my best thinking on the trout trail. There's almost a zen-like
quality. I regain my perspective in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's skills are such that she was hired by ESPN recently to
cohost a fly-fishing show, which will debut in January 2001. ``We
just came back from filming in Patagonia last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham hadn't intended to be a TV host or a fashion model. The
daughter of two accountants, she attended the University of
Mississippi and the Sorbonne in Paris in the mid-1960s, with the
goal of becoming a high school French teacher.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, Graham moved to New York to look for a job.
She was shopping at Bonwit Teller one afternoon in 1969 when she
began chatting with a woman while walking down the back stairs.
``When we got to the street, she handed me her card,'' Graham
recalls. ``She said, `My name is Eileen Ford. I have the best
modeling agency in the world. Please call me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Graham hesitated. ``I was afraid my parents would be very
disappointed. In those days, daughters were not always given a full
college education. We were encouraged to go to secretarial
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Graham did call Ford, and her success was immediate.
Photographer Irving Penn pushed Vogue editors Diana Vreeland and
Grace Mirabella to use her. From 1970 to 1975, Graham landed on the
cover 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   She also began working frequently for Estee Lauder. ``I started
being known in the business as the Estee Lauder girl,'' she
recalls. ``I was getting so identified with them that I was losing
money from other companies.'' So Graham requested a contract, a
bold move back then when contracts were unheard of. Her gamble paid
off. Estee Lauder agreed to sign Graham initially for one year.
</P>
<P>
   Her lifestyle was far from glamorous. There were no limousines,
no Hollywood-style parties, no paparazzi. ``Models weren't
celebrities then,'' she says. ``I would leave my apartment, catch a
taxi, and go to the studio. I'd put my own makeup on, they'd shoot,
and I'd go back home. . . It was a very quiet life.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham retired at 40 because, she says, ``I had made up my mind
years prior that I was going to stop when I was on top. I wanted to
leave on my own accord. I didn't want to be phased out or asked to
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   When Estee Lauder called in 1998, she was thrilled. ``Now,
models are celebrities,'' she says. ``They're making tons of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I had this flash of terror. . . I said, `You must not
realize how old I am.' But Estee Lauder said they wanted to show
that women nowadays are active and vital, just like me. I said,
`You promise I don't have to look young and perfect?' They said,
`No, we don't want you to look perfect. That's the point.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
