<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOGEN-AVONEX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISSAPOINTING AVONEX SALES TRIM BIOGEN SHARE PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biogen Inc. shares plunged $12 to a 52-week low of $53 Tuesday
after the company's reported that sales of Avonex, its multiple
sclerosis drug, were lower than Wall Street analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   Investor reaction led to a dramatic sell-off which reached a
fever pitch as nearly 20 million Biogen shares were traded _ five
times its average daily volume in recent months. Barely 7 1/2 weeks
ago, Biogen shares reached a record high of $129 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic drop was so severe that it helped fuel a 3.8
percent drop in the Nasdaq Biotechnology index.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of new investors in biotech stocks and seeing
Biogen slip slightly has cast a pall over the industry,'' said Eric
T. Schmidt, biotechnology analyst at SG Cowen &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said the skittishness comes just before major biotech
companies such as Amgen Inc., Genentech Inc., and Millennium
Pharmaceuticals Inc. report their quarterly financial results.
Genentech shares dropped $21 to close at $135.50 while Millennium's
stock fell $15.50 to $134. Amgen stock rose 25 cents to $59.135.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Biogen reported Avonex revenues of $174.6 million for
the first quarter, a 33 percent increase over the first quarter of
1998. The jump came largely from the addition of 2,000 new
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts, however, were looking for $180 million
in Avonex revenue and upward of 3,000 new users for the first three
months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look shows that Avonex sales during the first three
months of this year rose only 1.5 percent over 1999's fourth
quarter _ a factor Schmidt claims was ``idiosyncratic.'' He and
other analysts said Biogen's results were partly due to retail
buyers stocking up on Avonex at the end of last year due to
concerns over a possible year 2000 computer glitch. A second factor
was increased competition in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A Biogen spokeswoman said the Cambridge, Mass. company had no
comment on its stock movements.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen's lower first-quarter results prompted Schmidt to reduce
his sales estimate for Avonex to $792 million for the entire year,
down from $825 million. Last year Avonex revenues were $621 million
and $395 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Jonas V. Alsenas, the biotech analyst at ING Barings LLC,
said Biogen could easily make up the Avonex revenue shortfall in
the second and third quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-FATHER-BOS &LR;      04-11 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-FATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXILES DOUBT FATHER'S SINCERITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ They don't believe him.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez says he wants to return to Cuba with his
son, Elian, and they call him a puppet. Gonzalez says he is
speaking from the heart, and they insist he's been brainwashed. No
matter what Gonzalez says -- unless he comes out with much of the
Cuban exile community wants to hear, that he wants to stay in the
United States -- they will accuse him of deceiving himself and
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I believe him? Unfortunately, no, because I know all too
well the pressure he is under,'' said Lourdes D'Kendall, a local
radio commentator who has a 6-year-old of her own. ``He is on free
soil, but he is not a free man. He is still under Fidel Castro's
thumb.''
</P>
<P>
   To many of the Cubans who boarded airplanes, boats and rickety
rafts to make their way to Florida and freedom, it is unfathomable
that any father would choose a communist dictatorship over
democracy for his son. They simply cannot accept the decisions
Gonzalez is making for his family.
</P>
<P>
   But even the exiles adamantly opposed to returning Elian to Cuba
say they can easily imagine what lies behind his choice: fear of
economic retaliation and fear of worse than that. Many of them know
first-hand the need to lie, or to shade the truth, in order to
spare family and friends still in Cuba punishment for acts in which
they had no say. Cuba, after all, is a country where political
opponents are imprisoned, where dissidents sometimes disappear
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the Cubans in exile, like those from Czechoslovakia or
Poland or whoever is living under a totalitarian regime, know that
even though you are on free soil you can still be hurt,'' said Luis
Aguilar Leon, a Cuba scholar and historian at the University of
Miami. ``You have friends, maybe family, who can suffer. Anyone in
high school in Cuba knows this.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gonzalez awaits his son in Washington, where he arrived
last week, Elian's grandmothers remain in Cuba. So do the friends
who have spoken highly of Gonzalez's parenting skills, even as
unsubstantiated rumors of alleged abusive episodes spread through
an exile community eager for any reason to discredit his claims.
</P>
<P>
   To exiles, the fact that he has family still in Cuba is evidence
enough that even when Gonzalez stepped before a bank of microphones
in Washington he could not speak openly. To them, it proves that he
is not free to defect even as he lives stays with his wife and
their infant son in a Cuban official's residence where diplomatic
immunity has been suspended for the duration of his visit. That,
they say, must be why he has not asked any of his visitors, US Rep.
James McGovern (D-Mass.) among them, for help in obtaining
political asylum and, instead, has pressed them to help his family,
once reunited with Elian, to return to Cuba intact.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he has told US Attorney General Janet Reno, who is
scheduled to meet Wednesday in Miami with Elian's relatives and
exile community leaders to try to resolve the custody standoff, is
what he has had to tell her, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional view is that people fake their feelings to
survive. . .,'' said Jaime Suchlicki, director of the Institute for
Cuban and Cuban-American Studies at the University of Miami. ``If
the father were to defect, it would be a major defeat for Castro.
He's a very vindictive guy so Elian's father would fear that kind
of thing. He would know that Fidel would not accept this laying
down.''
</P>
<P>
   But the signs that Gonzalez is not being upfront go deeper, at
least for the exiles who demonstrate daily outside the house where
Elian has been living with the great uncle now fighting for custody
of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   They note that Gonzalez appears to have known that his former
wife was fleeing Cuba with Elian. They mention that he did not
immediately fly to Miami upon learning of Elian's Thanksgiving Day
rescue after his mother drowned -- indicating, in their opinion,
that Castro has orchestrated Gonzalez' actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody believes the father,'' said Rene Martinez, a bank
teller attending the candlelight prayer vigil that brought out
thousands of Cuban-Americans Monday night. ``A lot of us have lived
under Castro and under his dictatorship. They pull so many strings
it's like they can turn you into a puppet.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Florida-born Annamaria Hernandez, who represents artists
and musicians and whose parents fled Cuba, ``We don't believe him
because we know how the Castro government and the dictatorship
regime works. It's obvious that we haven't gotten the truth. It's
all a show.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, many exiles say, is not only occurring in Miami, where
Elian's relatives refuse to cede custody, and in Washington, where
federal officials have so far been unable to persuade them to hand
over the boy. It is, they say, also taking place in Cuba, where
little Elian has become a powerful symbol to the communist
government.
</P>
<P>
   Often sneering, sometimes shouting, exiles point out that
Gonzalez has incentives to return that go beyond the safety of his
relatives still in Cuba. His house has been freshly painted. He now
has a TV or two, luxuries most impoverished Cubans are unable to
afford. He is all but guaranteed a standard of living out of reach
of ordinary Cubans and out of his reach before Elian came to
symbolize communist solidarity. Who, they ask, bought him the dark
suit he has been wearing and the leather dress shoes?
</P>
<P>
   As Luis Aguilar Leon put it, ``A totalitarian government is in a
distant way like the mafia: You say what we want you to say and
we'll give you things; if you don't, we'll make things very
unpleasant. It's a dual power that he has over Elian's father.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, of course, Gonzalez has maintained that he wants his
son and he wants him to live in Cuba. In an open letter to US
Senate leaders, published in Cuba last month, he urged legislators
to reject any attempt to grant him and his son permanent residency
status. His Washington attorney, Gregory B. Craig, has repeatedly
said that the Gonzalez family has no intention of defecting during
their stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Scripted words all, Cuban exiles claim, ones they recognize
almost instinctively.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else are we supposed to believe?'' asked Rene Iturrey, a
real estate broker who has made almost daily pilgrimmages to the
great uncle's house in Little Havana. ``When are we going to know
if he is speaking the truth? Will we ever know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
