<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3683 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-ELIAN-TRANSFER-HNS &LR;      04-11 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-TRANSFER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RENO PLANS TO TRAVEL TO MIAMI TO END ELIAN SAGA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno will likely travel to
Miami Wednesday to try to end the stalemate over the transfer of
Elian Gonzalez to his father, a Justice Department official said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision came as the Department prepared to send a letter
directing Elian's Miami relatives to turn over the 6-year-old boy
at a definite time and place, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Reno would like to meet with federal officials, community leaders
and Elian's Miami relatives. However, the source said Reno's
planned trip would not change the timetable being worked out for
Elian's return.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokeswoman Carole Florman said no decisions
have been made about precise transfer instructions because
officials were evaluating the advice of three doctors who had seen
the boy's father and the relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Mayor Joe Carollo and Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex Penelas
met with Reno here Tuesday and said afterward she was willing to
intervene personally to help resolve the family dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general stated to us that she would be very
willing to meet with Lazaro Gonzalez or any (other) member of the
Gonzalez family in Miami and that she wants to meet with community
leaders in Miami,'' Carollo told reporters gathered in front of the
Justice Department building.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle, has cared for the boy
since he was found in the ocean Thanksgiving Day. Elian was one of
three survivors of a shipwreck in which his mother, her boyfriend
and nine others drowned when their boat sank as they were trying to
flee Cuba for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision came hours after the boy's Miami relatives
offered to meet with his Cuban father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, at a
neutral site in South Florida. But the relatives said the proposed
meeting would be a face-to-face family talk, not a handover of
Elian _ something both Juan Gonzalez and the Justice Department
have demanded as a prerequisite for such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives have insisted that the boy remain in the
United States until their lawsuit seeking to overturn the
Immigration and Naturalization Service's decision in January to
return him to his father is concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Reno won a U.S. District Court ruling affirming the
INS decision.
</P>
<P>
   Reno settled on the transfer plan after conferring with INS
Commissioner Doris Meissner, who had been briefed Tuesday by the
three government-appointed doctors.
</P>
<P>
   These doctors _ two child psychiatrists and a psychologist _
held talks with Lazaro Gonzalez, in Miami Monday. A day earlier,
they met here in Washington with Elian's father, who arrived in the
United States last week to take custody of his son.
</P>
<P>
   The experts told Meissner that Lazaro Gonzalez is balking at the
idea of transferring Elian to his father at a neutral site outside
of South Florida, according to the government source.
</P>
<P>
   The family said it was willing to meet Juan Gonzalez at the
Miami area home of Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, a Catholic nun, or
``any other neutral place in South Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, O'Laughlin hosted a meeting between Elian and
his grandmothers from Cuba. Later O'Laughlin said she thought the
boy should remain with his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The family's proposal, which came in a letter to one of the
government's psychiatrists, said a private family conference with
Juan Gonzalez could be ``followed almost immediately by a meeting
to include Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   It also demanded assurances that Elian would not be taken from
them during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meeting should take place before any further action is
taken on the part of the INS or the Department of Justice,'' lawyer
Manny Diaz told reporters in Miama. Diaz added that the meeting
should be strictly among family members, with no lawyers or
officials present.
</P>
<P>
   Florman said the government would pass the proposal on to Juan
Gonzalez and that the decision to meet with the family would up to
him and not her department.
</P>
<P>
   She would not comment on whether the father would be willing to
travel to Florida from Bethesda, Md., where he has been staying
with a Cuban diplomat since arriving from Havana last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Miami relatives, pursuing another legal effort in
the nearly 5-month-old custody battle, filed a brief in Florida
Family Court Tuesday morning, asking for a full hearing to bar
Elian's return to Cuba until his father's fitness is considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many, many, many other issues concerning the best
interests of this child that are important,'' said Eduardo Rasco,
an attorney for the relatives. ``And those issues are never going
to be decided by INS.''
</P>
<P>
   The brief said Juan Miguel Gonzalez ``has engaged in abusive
conduct,'' allegations the attorneys said the federal court never
considered. It said Lazaro Gonzalez intends to prove that Juan
Miguel Gonzalez ``has lost all rights to control his (Elian's)
destiny,'' and that the boy would be subject to ``imminent
indoctrination'' if he returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The father's attorneys have characterized the abuse allegations,
which some relatives have made earlier, as a desperate tactic.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department asked the family court to dismiss the new
request, saying a state judge has no jurisdiction to overrule
federal immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
