<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3693 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-URLACHER12-     04-11 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-URLACHER12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Mexico's versatile Urlacher just ready to play
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brian Urlacher might be going through an identity
crisis. Ever since his workout at the scouting combine in March,
NFL scouts have been shaking their heads and wondering what
position he'll play.
</P>
<P>
   Urlacher, who last season was the Mountain West Conference
Player of the Year, played free safety at New Mexico. He also
returned punts and kickoffs and played tight end in the Lobos'
short-yardage offense.
</P>
<P>
   But Urlacher, 6 feet 3 and 258 pounds, is too big to play free
safety in the NFL. Some pro teams like him as a strong safety
because he is an aggressive tackler. Others have him at middle
linebacker because of his size. And still others have him at
outside linebacker because of his speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care where I play,'' Urlacher said. ``I just want to
get drafted the highest I can go. I really don't care where I play.
I just want to get on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Urlacher rarely left the field in college. He led the nation in
tackles as a junior with 178 and had 154 last season. As a senior,
Urlacher caused five fumbles and recovered three, intercepted one
pass, averaged 15.8 yards on punt returns and 26 yards on kickoff
returns. He also scored touchdowns on six of his seven receptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a phenomenal athlete,'' said Vinny Cerrato, the
Washington Redskins' director of player personnel. ``He covers
punts, returns punts, breaks up passes _ he even had six touchdown
catches. He loves to play the game. In terms of tackling ability,
he's one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Urlacher is widely regarded as the second-best linebacker in the
draft, behind Penn State's LaVar Arrington. He also might be the
draft's best prospect at defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bears reportedly are eyeing him with the ninth pick.
Chicago needs help at outside linebacker and strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a guy who is 6-3, weighs (258) and runs 4.5 or 4.6
(seconds in the 40-yard dash),'' Bears defensive coordinator Greg
Blache said. ``He played free safety, hits people hard, makes a lot
of plays and is very mature. He's impressive; the guy is a rare
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Urlacher played middle linebacker his first two seasons at New
Mexico. But he moved to strong safety as a junior and eventually
started playing on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew with the team we had this year, the coach was going to
ask me to do a lot,'' Urlacher said. ``In preparation each week,
I'd try to watch an hour of film every day before practice. Then
we'd watch film for two hours after practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``For conditioning, I tried to run everything as much as I could
because I knew I was going to be on the field a lot. That was the
biggest thing I was worried about toward the end of the game,
getting tired.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL draft begins Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
