<SLUG> BC-BBN-DON-BAYLOR12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baylor optimistic Cubs can be better
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ If ever there were a no-win situation, this is it. The
team Don Baylor chose to manage, over the Brewers and Angels, has
losing down to an art form.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs haven't won a World Series since 1908 and haven't won a
postseason series in 10 October trips since. And they don't have
any reason to expect much different this season, especially with
the new talent pumped into National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell that to Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be our final team,'' Baylor said. ``It's
going to get better with a healthy Kerry Wood and a healthy Ismael
Valdes.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has been mocked by Pete Rose for calling the Cubs rich in
tradition, beaten down by a 3-6 start and worn out by a whirlwind
offseason and a season-opening road trip to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa is hitting just .171. The Cubs pitching staff has a
6.09 ERA. The lineup is hitting only .229. They have lost three
games in the 11th inning and committed nine errors in the first
nine games.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cubs got their first sign of hope Monday afternoon
against the Braves, the team Baylor spent his yearlong managing
hiatus with as the hitting coach. A four-run ninth-inning rally and
a 4-3 victory gave Baylor reason to believe.
</P>
<P>
   During batting practice Monday, one of the many faithful but
realistic Cub fans held up a poster modeled after the Wrigley Field
sign that read, ``Maybe this millennium?''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 38,655 attendees on Monday stayed through 39-degree
cold and snow and were there at the end of the game to holler
through the breezeways of Wrigley Field as they left. Their shouts
echoed in the hallway leading up to the Braves clubhouse and made
it sound as if their team had just won a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a challenge to get people to think it can be
different here,'' Baylor said. ``I've noticed that when they lose,
they expect to lose, like, `What's going to happen wrong again.'
I'm trying to get us away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was talking about the players. And he knows how to change
attitudes. That's what he did with the Rockies in taking an
expansion team to the playoffs in its third season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's similar,'' Baylor said. ``Some of the frustrations are
the same. Pitching is the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs are still old and their pitching is still weak. But
they got better defensively up the middle with the additions of
shortstop Ricky Gutierrez and second baseman Eric Young. And they
have hope ahead for the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Wood is shooting for May to make his return from ligament
transplant surgery, and Valdes, who is recovering from shoulder
tendinitis, also will return.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor already has started putting his mark on this team. He
issued a challenge to the home-run slugging Sosa to be a more
complete player and set stricter guidelines about dress code and
player conduct. So far, the Cubs are buying into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Baylor) is a good man,'' first baseman Mark Grace said. ``I
just wish we were playing better for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
