<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATOR SAYS MEDICARE PRESCRIPTION DRUG PLAN IS LIKELY THIS
YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Medicare recipients have a ``very good'' chance of
seeing Congress add coverage of prescription drugs to their
benefits this year, Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., said at a news
conference here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was joined by Sens. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, and Ron Wyden,
D-Ore., in pressing for the passage of the measure before Congress
adjourns this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The substantive and political stars are lining up,'' Smith
said, referring to the pressure older voters are exerting on
politicians during this election year. ``The chances are very good
that we can make this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Senate and House passed budget plans
that would spend about $1.8 trillion for fiscal 2001. Lawmakers
from both houses are trying to work out a compromise budget, which
they hope to finish by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Each house would set aside $40 billion over five years for
prescription drugs to recipients of Medicare, the government's
health insurance program for the elderly and disabled. But further
action is needed to make sure the money for the drugs is actually
allocated.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate plan, if the allocation is not approved by the
Finance Committee by Sept. 1, lawmakers can take it directly to the
Senate floor for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is the one provision that does assure action
this year on a specific benefit program for seniors,'' Snowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Wyden, one of the Senate-House conferees, said they are expected
to decide by Thursday whether to accept the Senate timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Thursday we'll be able to tell who in the United States
Congress is serious about actually getting a prescription drug
benefit to older people in a timely way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and some members of Congress have opposed
granting a prescription drug benefit separately, without first
overhauling Medicare itself. Clinton's health policy adviser, Chris
Jennings, said the administration's ``strong preference is to
(include the drug benefit) in the context of reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The Snowe-Widen-Smith plan gives Congress an incentive to make
reforms in the next several years while ensuring that senior
citizens receive drug benefits right away, according to Snowe.
Their plan calls for $20 billion in drug coverage for three years
and another $20 billion beyond that if restructuring of the
fiscally ailing Medicare program is enacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that we should penalize senior citizens in this
country for Congress' inability'' to agree on reform now, Snowe
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
