<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BUS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fewer than expected to `ride for justice' to Coke meeting
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The bus ``ride for justice'' to Coca-Cola's annual
shareholders meeting in Delaware will involve fewer people than
originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have two buses instead of three because there's less
volume than we thought,'' said Larry Jones, a former human
resources manager at Coca-Cola and the trip's chief organizer.
Jones planned the trip to pressure the company into settling the
racial discrimination lawsuit quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the 1,300 mile, five-day round trip from Atlanta to
Wilmington, Del., was too long of a commitment for some former and
current employees.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 people have signed up so far, and Jones expects the
number to climb to about 100 before the buses leave on Saturday.
The two buses, each holding about 55 passengers, are scheduled to
stop for rallies in three cities before reaching the shareholders
meeting April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said $36,000 has been raised so far to pay for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the minimum amount of money needed to pay for the
hotel rooms and buses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
