<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, April 12 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECT (Lima, Peru) _ Final results of presidential election
are expected to be announced at 7:30 p.m. EDT as President Alberto
Fujimori edges closer to victory and his opponent demands a second
round. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   ASSET-FORFEITURE (Washington) _ Following years of complaints of
abusive government conduct, Congress completed legislation Tuesday
that would make it harder for law enforcement authorities to
confiscate property before they actually bring criminal charges in
narcotics and other cases. The White House is expected to announce
that Clinton would sign the legislation, a compromise measure
approved unanimously by a voice vote of the House of
Representatives. The new law, which was approved by the Senate
three weeks ago, will add significant new safeguards that will make
it more difficult for prosecutors to seize homes, cars and other
property before trials begin. But it also expands the government's
authority to confiscate property after convictions. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-HOLOCAUST-SUIT (London) _ David Irving, a British
historian who minimized the tragedy of the Holocaust,
``misrepresented and manipulated historical evidence,'' a judge in
London ruled Tuesday in throwing out Irving's libel suit against a
U.S. scholar who had accused him of distorting what occurred in
Nazi Germany. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-DRUGS (Boston) _ The Maine legislature has passed a bill
providing price controls for prescription drugs. (Preliminary
summary) By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITES (Washington) _ An exclusive on past difficulties with
American satellite systems. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS-IV (Gloucester, Mass.) _ The father of a slain
college student and the young man's killer try to understand the
senseless crime. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   Final story in a series of four; 4,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT14,15.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-POVERTY (Cleveland, Ohio) _ In the third speech designed to
support his claim to being a ``new kind of Republican,'' George W.
Bush outlined a plan Tuesday to give the working poor tax credits
for health insurance and rental vouchers for home down payments. He
also said he plans to offer tax credits for banks that match the
savings deposits of poor people. The $42 billion plan expands on
tax-cut and education proposals previously offered by the
all-but-official Republican presidential nominee and continues his
outreach to independents and moderate Democratic voters by talking
about subjects often ignored by Republican candidates. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-NAP-GUIDE (United Nations) _ Diplomacy is an exhausting
business, with all those late dinners followed by pre-breakfast
e-mail rockets from foreign ministries in distant time zones. So
where to catch a midday nap? At the United Nations Secretariat, a
building made mostly of glass, there would seem to be no place to
hide. Wrong! says Alain Dejammet, who has just returned to Paris
after four years as France's ambassador to the United Nations.
Wandering the corridors between Security Council sessions and
countless other meetings that force diplomats to leave their
comfortable missions for the austerity of United Nations
headquarters, Dejammet was _ unknown to anyone, including other
French diplomats _ conducting a secret survey. He has now
``published'' (in a computer print run of at least one copy) a
guide to napping, ``Dormir aux Nations Unies,'' in French, of
course, and with a Gallic love for detail that marks the Michelin
guides. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LOBBY (Washington) _ Ralph Reed, a senior consultant
to Gov. George W. Bush's presidential campaign, decided Tuesday
that it did not look good if his company also lobbied Bush on
behalf of the Microsoft Corp. Hours after it was disclosed that the
software giant had quietly hired Reed's firm, Century Strategies,
Reed's company put out a statement both expressing regrets and
attempting to clarify the arrangement with Microsoft, which is in
the midst of anti-trust litigation brought by the government. By
Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
