The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, April 12. If you
have any questions, please call The Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOMELESS (Phoenix) - The renewal of downtown Phoenix and
redevelopment of the Capitol Mall area mean that homeless people
are being crowded into a narrower and narrower area, worrying
officials and activists. Now Phoenix police want to move in and end
the reign of `unchallenged disorder` in the area. By BILL HERMANN.
Story will move in the `A' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SARAJEVO (Phoenix) - Mirsada Buric-Adam trained for the 1992
Olympics by running through the streets of Sarajevo as gunfire
echoed around her, a dramatic image that made the CBS Evening News.
Eight years later, the sniper fire is over, and so is her running
career. The former Bosnian Olympian sits in her north Phoenix
apartment and watches her daughter marvel at Teletubbies. he runner
who became a symbol of the Bosnian people's will to survive war
enjoys a quiet family life in Phoenix. We talk to her about the
statement of courage she made then , about the journalism degree
she has from Arizona State, and about her concerns _ from her
parents whose home in Sarajevo remains badly damaged to the future
of her homeland, where the suicide rate is high, the economy is
wrecked and a generation fled to other countries. By CHRIS FISCUS.
Story will move in the `A` category. &QL; 
