<SLUG> BC-CMGI-NOVELL-SUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI, NOVELL, SUN PLAN UNIT TO NETWORK DATA CENTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CMGI Inc. is joining with Novell Inc. and Sun Microsystems Inc.
to enter the growing market for services that speed data delivery
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The new enterprise could make CMGI a significant competitor to
Akamai Technologies Inc., now the leader in Internet
content-delivery services. But officials of both CMGI and Akamai
also said the two companies could end up as business partners
rather than rivals.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, Novell, and Sun will invest $40 million to create a new
company called CMGion, which is to begin operations early next
year. CMGion plans to build a network of 60 Internet data centers
scattered around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to be able to reach a significant part of the
world's population with these data centers,'' said CMGI chairman
David Wetherell, who will be CMGion's interim chief executive. CMGI
will own 82 percent of the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   These centers will use Novell's directory services software to
provide personalized data services to millions of users. Sun,
meanwhile, will provide massive Internet computers powered by its
Solaris operating system.
</P>
<P>
   CMGion's customers will be Internet service providers that serve
individual consumers, or major corporations that want to speed
delivery of Internet data to customers, business allies or
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Like Akamai, CMGion will use special software to automatically
store Internet information on computers that are close to the
people using the data. For example, if a user in China frequently
visits the Novell Web site, a copy of the site would be stored at a
data center in China. This would speed the delivery of the data,
becase the Chinese user wouldn't have to get the information
directly from a Novell Web site in the Unuted States.
</P>
<P>
   CMGion will go beyond Akamai's current offerings, by adding a
large dose of personalization. With Novell's directory software, it
will be possible for a CMGion user to log on anywhere in the world,
and instantly get complete access to his network services. ``It
allows you to have a very different and much more powerful Internet
experience,'' said Novell chief executive Eric Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   With one sign on, the system might log someone into his
corporate network and his favorite public Internet services,
deliver his e-mail, list his voice mail messages and tell him
whether a package has been delivered. Since the data is stored in
the network of CMGion data centers, it would be available anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   If the CMGion system catches on, it'll be a major success for
Novell, which hopes to make its software the worldwide standard for
network directory services. The company's chief rival in that
market is Microsoft Corp., whose Active Directory system is part of
its Windows 2000 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   But success for CMGion could also mean trouble for Akamai, which
became an industry darling last year by signing up dozens of major
Web sites for its data delivery technology. ``I would say that it
is a direct challenge to Akamai,'' said Michael Sheridan, the
Novell vice president of strategic businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai chief executive George Conrades said he wasn't so sure.
``I think there's plenty of opportunities for partnership,'' said
Conrades, noting that CMGI's Wetherell had contacted him about the
possibility of the two firms working together. Wetherell confirmed
that discussions have taken place.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Conrades said that for now, CMGion is just an
idea, while Akamai is a going concern. ``I think there's a big
difference between an announcement and doing what we do,'' Conrades
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors may not be as sanguine. Akamai stock soared as
high as $345.50 since the firm went public last October. Tuesday,
Akamai stock plunged $25.56 on the Nasdaq Stock Market, to $107.75,
a loss of over 19 percent for the day. Conrades blamed market
volatility, rather than the CMGion announcement, for the stock's
poor showing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
