<HEADER>
A3721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOREA-FAMILIES-750&AMP;AD     04-11 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-FAMILIES-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREANS HOPE FOR REUNIONS WITH RELATIVES IN NORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ When Park Byoung-gul heard the news Monday
that the presidents of North and South Korea would soon meet for
the first time, he had little use for the speculation over the
politics behind the diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for the hale old retiree who fled North Korea as a
young man and has never returned, there was a single preoccupation:
learning the fate of the family he left behind, and, if a detente
between the divided countries allows it, to see them at least once
before he dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain the joy that I felt in hearing the news of the
summit,'' said Park. ``In the past, I never thought there was any
point to it, but I've come to register today because I am 73 years
old, and with this news I felt I must hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran of the Korean War, who left his native North and
ended up fighting for the South, spoke at the entrance to a
government office where Koreans seeking to investigate the fate of
their relatives in the North have been encouraged to register for
the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   According to the South Korean government, 1.2 million people who
were alive when the two countries went to war in 1950 still have
families in North Korea. And suddenly today, although interest in
the family reunion support program has existed all along, there was
real excitement for many over the possibility of a meeting for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents would probably be over 100 years old now, so I must
assume they are no longer living,'' said Park. ``But even if I
can't see them, it would mean the world to me to hear from my
sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   South Koreans of Park's generation often tell visitors that
nothing in an outsider's experience could completely compare with
the trauma of separation that tens of thousands of people here have
felt. Unlike Germans, for example, whose country was also divided
by the Cold War, for almost all of the last half century South
Koreans have been unable to visit their relatives and were also
blocked by the North from exchanging letters or telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, as North Korea's economic situation has
grown more desperate, the barriers to communication have eased ever
so slightly _ in part, it seems, so the North Korean police,
soldiers and postal agents can skim off money sent to relatives by
South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A flourishing unofficial trade in family meetings has recently
sprung up in the region that borders China. South Koreans often pay
thousands of dollars to middlemen in China and North Korea to
arrange reunions. Some of these, South Koreans say, are brief and
tearful encounters on islands in the Yalu River, where aging
Southerners often learn of the death or disappearance of loved
ones. Other meetings are with North Koreans who have fled to China
but are stuck there in a legal limbo because Beijing generally
denies North Korean exiles political asylum status, treating them
as illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, President Kim Dae-jung sought to lower the expectations
surrounding the news of a summit meeting. He warned during a
Cabinet meeting that ``the national issues, which have been
divisive for a half century, cannot be resolved overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to priorities he laid out in a speech in Berlin last
month, Kim said that ``at the summit meeting, we will discuss the
four points, and I believe we can come to agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Berlin speech, Kim proposed government-to-government
assistance, the reunion of families separated during the Korean
War, dialogue between the North and South Korean governments and a
renunciation of the state of war that remains in force on the
Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of tension and unpredictable behavior in the North have
taught South Koreans to be anything but over-optimistic about a
change in relations. But still, in a country where ancestors, clan
and regional origins, and family matter far more than in most, the
fact that the South has listed family reunification as a top
priority for the June talks has given hope to many.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the first generation after the separation, and our
dream now is to meet our relatives again before we die,'' said Lee
Yeon-bin, 66, who also came to the government's Separated Families
Office to inquire about relatives. ``I didn't sleep last night for
excitement about this. I would have to put the chances of anything
coming out of this at only 30 percent, but when you have been
waiting for decades, that seems like a lot.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lee explained that her family had been considered wealthy
landowners in North Korea and declared ``enemies of the state.'' As
they fled to the South, she said, her one brother was arrested and
taken away.
</P>
<P>
   As people of North Korean descent gathered at the Separated
Families office Tuesday, they exchanged stories and expressions of
pain and doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left North Korea when I was 6 years old,'' said Woo Song-ja,
59, who carried her baby grand-daughter strapped on her back. ``All
of my ancestors must have died by now. Of course I want to find any
surviving relatives, but do you think we will be able to recognize
each other?''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, Kwan Young-jeo, 71, told of how her younger
sister managed to escape to China in 1997, crossing the frozen Yalu
River. At enormous expense, Kwan has visited her three times since
then, each time paying substantial sums to middlemen. Her obsession
now is to find her older sister who is still in North Korea,
although she confesses she does not know if she is alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that she has been through terrible hardship,'' she said
of the remaining sister. ``It is my duty to find out if she has
survived, and if so, to help her.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
