<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TAKING GUN MESSAGE TO DENVER
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton goes to Denver to press his
national campaign for federal gun controls Wednesday, one day after
the House approved an alternative plan to give $100 million to
states willing to impose mandatory jail terms on armed criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The dueling approaches to the problem of gun violence in America
have set the stage for a heated election-year debate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's line, which he will defend in a two-hour televised
town meeting from Denver, is that federal gun controls should be
tightened.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also plans to attend a rally, sponsored by a Denver
group called Sane Alternatives to the Firearms Epidemic (SAFE),
aimed at drumming up support for an upcoming statewide vote on
legislation that would require background checks for purchasers of
firearms at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Denver is bracing for the April 20 anniversary of the tragedy in
nearby Littleton, Colo., where two teenagers took their own lives
after shooting and killing 12 students and a teacher at Columbine
High School.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called for federal laws mandating childproof safety
locks on new handguns, a ban on high-volume ammunition clips, and
background checks on anyone who buys a firearm at a flea market or
gun show.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate narrowly approved those measures last May as part of
a larger juvenile justice bill. The vote was 51-50, with Vice
President Al Gore casting the tie-breaking vote.
</P>
<P>
   A companion bill in the House was approved without those
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   A conference committee charged with working up compromise
legislation acceptable to both houses has yet to resolve the
differences.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton went to Annapolis, the capital of Maryland,
to praise that state for passing its own childproof lock law and to
nudge Congress to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child in America deserves the protection you have given
Maryland's children,'' Clinton said in remarks to Gov. Parris
Glendening and state legislators. ``And only Congress can provide
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a jab at the Republican-controlled Congress and that party's
standard-bearer, presidential hopeful George W. Bush, Clinton said
the majority on Capitol Hill were thwarting the wishes of the
majority of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In truth,'' said Clinton, ``the people are ahead of most of
the politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   From the floor of the House, the Republicans fired back,
sponsoring a bill to provide $20 million a year, for five years, in
block grant assistance to states that approve mandatory minimum
prison terms for anyone who commits a crime while armed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is get-tough legislation,'' said Chris Paulitz, spokesman
for the Republican National Committee. ``This ensures that the
criminals who use guns in crimes actually go to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed by an overwhelming 358-60 majority vote, with
208 Republicans and 149 Democrats voting for it. Voting against the
bill were 56 Democrats, three Republicans and the body's sole
independent.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart denounced the bill as a
tactic employed by Republicans who want to appear tough on gun
violence but who do not support strengthened gun controls. He said
Democrats who voted for it did so only to avoid being painted as
soft on crime in November, when all House members are up for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats saw a political trap and decided not to fall for
it,'' said Lockhart. ``In reality, what it is is a cruel political
trick on the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart assailed the Republican leadership in Congress for not
taking up Clinton's request for $280 million in funding to hire
1,000 additional prosecutors and 500 additional agents for the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. Those resources
are needed, said Lockhart, to increase the prosecution of
gun-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan, said Lockhart, excludes the 44 states that
lack mandatory sentencing laws for criminals with guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get enforcement money, people in the courts, people on
the streets right now with the Democratic approach.,'' said
Lockhart. ``There is absolutely no likelihood that tomorrow, 44
states are going to go into their legislature and pass a law to
come into compliance with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lockhart, ``How are kids in those 44 states supposed to
feel when they've seen the Republican alternative? I think they'll
think it's a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulitz countered that it is the Democrats that are playing
politics with gun-related violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to say, but the Democratic Party goes into campaign
mode when there's a tragedy, instead of trying to find real
solutions,'' said Paulitz. ``They're using this for a political
tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
