<SLUG> BC-DISEASE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH LEADERS CALL FOR GLOBAL INFECTIOUS DISEASES PUSH
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the face of spreading epidemics of HIV/AIDS,
tuberculosis and malaria in much of the developing world, health
experts Tuesday called on Congress to fund new ``windows of
opportunity'' against infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta international health expert William Foege, World Health
Organization director-general Gro Harlem Brundtland and others
called on the Senate Appropriations Committee to sharply increase
appropriations to support global health initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Foege, an adviser to the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation,
which last year announced a $750 million grant to help protect poor
children around the world against disease, told the committee the
elimination of smallpox and the pending eradication of polio are
``a harbinger of what is to come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has never had so much power to improve the health of
children everywhere,'' said Foege, a professor of international
health at Emory University. ``The United States, because of its
science base, its experience in immunization programs and its
monetary and public health resources, will be key to realization of
that dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., announced at the committee hearing
that he would introduce a ``Global Health Act of 2000,'' which
would double the approximately $1 billion a year the United States
currently spends on health-related foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   And the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization, the group
that will receive the bulk of the Gates Foundation grant, issued a
report calling on world governments to spend an additional $350
million a year to extend infant vaccination programs among the
world's poorest babies.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 million of the 130 million children born ever year do
not receive basic immunization, the alliance report stated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This immunization gap represents a devastating toll on the
world's population,'' the report said. ``Every year, there are 3
million unnecessary premature deaths, because too many children
have not bee given the vaccine that could have saved their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
