<SLUG> BC-COURT-NOMINATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMINEE WOULD BE FIRST FEMALE SUPREME COURT JUDGE IN N.H. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ New Hampshire's first female governor Tuesday
nominated a Superior Court judge who would be the first female
member of the state's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Jeanne Shaheen called her nominee, Linda Dalianis, ``a
judge of unassailable integrity and character.'' New Hampshire is
one of only a handful of states never to have appointed a woman to
its highest court: it is the last state in New England to do so.
</P>
<P>
   If, as expected, Dalianis is confirmed by New Hampshire's
five-member Executive Council, she will join a state Supreme Court
frozen in the headlights of oncoming investigations by the state's
Judicial Conduct Committee and its 400-member House.
</P>
<P>
   The vacancy she has been nominated to fill was created by the
March 31 resignation of W. Stephen Thayer. A report by the state's
attorney general said Thayer tried to influence his fellow justices
in cases including his own divorce, from which he had recused
himself. Thayer resigned rather than face possible criminal
indictment on those charges.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's investigation also faulted Chief Justice
David Brock and fellow justices for routinely commenting upon cases
from which they had disqualified themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution directing the House Judiciary Committee to
investigate whether Brock and perhaps other Supreme Court justices
should be impeached was drafted Tuesday afternoon. The resolution
is set to be debated Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dalianis, 51, declined to discuss the past practices of the high
court. But she did say that if she disqualifies herself from a
case, she stays out completely. The Attorney General has said the
court allowed an environment in which some justices continued to
influence cases in which they had disqualified themselves because
of a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this point my personal approach to recusal has been if
there is any legitimate reason for me to be out of the case then I
am out of it period and I would expect to continue that policy in
the future,'' Dalianis said in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dalianis will be Shaheen's second high-court appointment this
year. Earlier, the governor chose fellow Democrat Joseph Nadeau, a
longtime family friend and chief justice of the Superior Court
system, to replace retiring Supreme Court Justice William Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Delianis was confirmed to her current position _ replacing
Nadeau as Superior Court chief justice _ less than one month ago.
``I think I will be an asterisk in the history books on that job,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of Shaheen's political opponents applauded her choice
of Dalianis. ``Needless to say I have been critical of the governor
on many accounts, but I want to give credit where credit is due,''
said former US Senator Gordon Humphrey, who plans to formally
announce his candidacy for governor later this month. ``This is an
excellent nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Placing two new members on the court should help rebuild public
confidence in the battered institution, said New Hampshire Bar
Association President George Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think that is a substantial infusion of new
energy and new judicial philosophies into the mix of the Supreme
Court and that any taint if you will that is left over from the
procedures and issues raised by the attorney general's office will
certainly be lessened by the advent of these two judges,'' Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dalianis, a Nashua resident, described herself as a ``registered
independent.'' Her husband, Griffin Dalianis, is a psychotherapist
and Republican state representative.
</P>
<P>
   Her appointment would mean the high court would comprise two
Republicans, two Democrats and an independent.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Suffolk University Law School, Dalianis became the
state's first female superior court justice when she took her seat
in 1980. As for joining the Supreme Court, she said, ``This is
something I have hoped for for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
