<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3735 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-11 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PANDER BEARS, ANYONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Question: In a presidential campaign, what is the
difference between pandering to some special interest, considered
bad, and merely making a smart political move, considered good?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: It's pandering when the targeted pitch doesn't work and
smart politics when it does.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush took
controversial policy positions recently, clearly aimed at buttering
up a specific, potentially powerful audience.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's astonishing stand was out of step with his party and
rang so hollow that he promptly dropped a few points in the polls.
Voters have yet to register any reaction to Bush's latest ploy, but
he may well get away with it because it is consistent with his
overall pro-business philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been trying to explain the inexplicable ever since he
broke with President Clinton over the fate of Elian Gonzalez. The
president, Attorney General Janet Reno and the Immigration and
Naturalization Service insist that the little boy belongs with his
father, who lives in Cuba and shows every sign of intending to
return there. But Gore called on Congress to pass a special bill to
give father and son permanent resident status here while a family
court decides Elian's fate.
</P>
<P>
   That aligned Gore with the conservative anti-communist crowd,
usually Republican, in opposition to the view of most Democratic
leaders and a majority of Americans that Elian should be sent home.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's position was aimed at the group that feels most deeply
about Elian, the Cuban-Americans in Miami who have sheltered him
since he survived a shipwreck in which his mother drowned. We're
talking votes here, a concentrated batch of votes in Florida where
Gore is playing catch-up to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But this is dubious politics. Cuban Americans make up only 7
percent of the Florida electorate, and most other voters in the
state support sending Elian home. And Gore is now stuck with a
strong, unmistakable panderer's odor. It will take great gobs of
perfumed rhetoric to blow it away in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for his part, was also busily catering to one particular
constituency this week. His target was the technology world
centered in California, a state in which he currently trails Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He spread the word that he did not approve of the Justice
Department's antitrust suit against Microsoft, the computer
software giant accused of malicious business practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand on the side of innovation, not litigation,'' Bush said
pointedly. And in case Microsoft's Bill Gates and his buddies
missed the message, Bush advisers slyly suggested that a Bush
administration would drop the suit that threatens to break up the
company's monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters have also made private overtures to Gates and
other Microsoft officials to encourage the firm to beef up its
political contributions to the GOP. They have been steadily
increasing since the Justice Department filed suit. A Microsoft
executive sits on the Bush finance steering committee. Since 1997,
top company employees have coughed up $1.8 million in political
contributions, the majority of which has gone to the Republicans in
the form of unregulated ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been careful not to comment on the merits of the
Justice Department suit, but he doesn't have to be specific. He has
done everything but paint a picture for Microsoft. And while his
position is certainly self-serving, it looks more like politics as
usual than a demagogic appeal to raw emotions.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Bush has consistently sided with business interests
over those of consumers and environmentalists. His philosophy is
similar to that of Calvin Coolidge, who once declared, ``The
business of America is business.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has little sympathy for federal regulators who try to
protect the public against predatory industry practices. Or for
trial lawyers who persuade juries to levy substantial judgments
against industries and institutions that knowingly or maliciously
harm clients, patients or consumers.
</P>
<P>
   So Bush is being consistent in preferring to leave a monopoly
intact rather than forcing it to compete fairly in the marketplace.
His position is wrong and harmful to the public interest, but he
has a philosophical basis for holding it.
</P>
<P>
   The full politics of this complicated case is unlikely to play
out until well after the election. A Newsweek poll this week showed
that a third of those surveyed supported the antitrust decision
against Microsoft and a third disagreed with it. Not everyone
understood what it was really all about.
</P>
<P>
   But in the short run Bush reinforced his pro-business
credentials and probably raised more money for his campaign. And he
stopped short of promising Gates a Cabinet post. Now THAT would be
pandering.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
