<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `SOPRANOS' RATINGS; WRESTLING ON TNT; DEBATES ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Going Out Blazing
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrating that it is not just a critical favorite but an
out-and-out hit television show, ``The Sopranos'' reached a new
ratings high for its season finale Sunday night, pulling in more
viewers than any other original entertainment program in the
history of HBO.
</P>
<P>
   With a rating of 17.6 in homes that receive HBO, ``The
Sopranos'' surpassed its previous high, a 16.2 for this season's
first episode. HBO's executives said that translated to about 9
million viewers, which beat the network's previous high of 6.9
million for the movie ``If These Walls Could Talk.'' Only the
biggest boxing matches have ever pulled in more viewers for HBO.
</P>
<P>
   To put this achievement in context, ``The Sopranos'' had more
viewers Sunday night than last week's episodes of ``Ally McBeal''
on Fox, ``Sabrina'' on ABC, the Sunday Night Movie ``My Fellow
Americans'' on NBC, ``Smackdown'' on UPN and ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' on WB. More to the point, it beat three episodes of
``Falcone,'' the CBS mob drama.
</P>
<P>
   And ``The Sopranos'' was only available in a quarter of the 100
million homes that the major networks reach.
</P>
<P>
   The huge rating for the finale underscores the hunger among HBO
viewers for ``The Sopranos,'' a hunger that now will go unfulfilled
for almost a year. HBO executives reaffirmed Tuesday that the show
would not start up again in January as it has in its first two
seasons, but would be delayed until March.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison to ``Falcone'' is surely not what CBS is looking
for, but given the similar plot lines, it is inevitable. Despite
being what he called ``pretty disappointed'' in the showing of
``Falcone'' last week, Les Moonves, the CBS president, said he
still held out hopes for the series because it had fared better on
Friday and Saturday nights, and ``if we picked it up for next
season it would probably go onto one of those nights.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ratings results from Monday for ``Falcone'' were not
encouraging; it was beaten by both ``Once and Again'' on ABC and
``Third Watch'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Moonves was happy with one bit of ratings news from
Sunday night. The experiment in live drama, ``Fail Safe'' was, as
Moonves branded it, ``a solid success.'' The show finished 13th
overall in the weekly ratings, 19th among young adult viewers, a
very good showing for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves said, ``We're surely going to be doing more live
drama.'' He has a new version of ``On Golden Pond'' set for next
fall and said he would ideally like to have a live drama each fall
and spring.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   New Plots for Champs
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner's World Championship Wrestling has undergone its
second makeover in seven months. It was shown in its new
incarnation on TNT on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The uninitiated who may have clicked upon TNT's ``Monday Nitro''
on their way to some other program wouldn't have noticed anything
so different. After all, sweaty, heavy men growling, snarling and
bleeding all over each other is to be expected from a wrestling
program.
</P>
<P>
   But those who regularly watch the show saw an epic, scripted
battle between the old guard wrestlers who have presided over the
show's ratings decline and a new team charged with reviving it. All
plotlines that had been running through the prior months were
dropped entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The new story line may have delighted longtime fans _ especially
when head writer Vince Russo took a white Humvee to Hulk Hogan's
limousine _ but it represents a real problem for Turner.
</P>
<P>
   As Vince McMahon's World Wrestling Federation continues to
capture the attention of young male viewers everywhere _ witness
the success this year of the UPN network, which is owed in large
part to its Thursday night WWF show _ Turner is watching his own
wrestling fortunes fade. Once it was the leading wrestling league.
Now the WCW does much worse than the WWF During the week ending
April 2, the WWF's 10 p.m. Monday wrestling program on the USA
network was the highest-rated show in all of cable, watched by 7.7
million people, according to Nielsen Media Research data. The WCW's
``Monday Nitro'' on the other hand, ranked No. 7, viewed by 3.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   The show's decline in ratings represents the loss of millions of
dollars, Turner Broadcasting executives concede. The league had
hired two top WWF writers in September, Vince Russo and his
partner, Ed Ferrara, to turn things around. At the same time, a WCW
executive vice president, Eric Bischoff, who led it to No. 1 in the
ratings before seeing it lose steam, was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The new writers brought heavier scripting to the WCW program,
along with more vulgarity and sexual innuendo. But the ratings
continued to plunge. Russo was forced out, and Ferraro was demoted.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest effort to revive the show, Russo has been brought
back, along with Bischoff. Proving just how much the league's
future means to Turner, Turner Entertainment President Brad Siegel
is spending a couple of days per week in the WCW offices in Smyrna,
Ga. Siegel said that just as the WWF revived itself after running
second to the WCW through most of the 1990s, his league will stage
a comeback, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're down in the ratings and we need to refocus our
business and refocus our storylines,'' he said. ``Somebody's got to
do the work right now, and I'd just assume it be me.''
</P>
<P>
   By midday Tuesday, it appeared the new approach had met with
some success. Preliminary figures showed the show's ratings were up
about 20 percent from its season average, though they remained far
below those of the W.W.F. program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Rutenberg
</P>
<P>
   The Gun Debate
</P>
<P>
   Tom Brokaw and NBC will take on the roiling question of gun
control in a series of programs on MSNBC and NBC on Wednesday and
Wednesday night. At 3 p.m. on MSNBC, Brokaw will moderate a town
hall meeting in Denver, beginning with an interview with President
Clinton, who will be attending the meeting. Portions of the
interview will be played on Brokaw's ``Nightly News'' Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   That town hall meeting will also be replayed on MSNBC at 10 p.m.
followed at 11 by a second town hall meeting, also moderated by
Brokaw. That one will include the Colorado governor, Bill Owens,
and numerous advocates and opponents of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The connecting point is the shooting tragedy at Columbine high
school, which is nearing its first anniversary. ``Colorado has
become ground zero in the gun debate,'' Brokaw said in a telephone
interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that his own background, growing up in the West where
boys learned to use guns with their fathers in a ``male ethos''
that continues today, has helped shape his own view that the gun
control debate has become too polarized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the middle on this issue has been heard,'' he
said. Brokaw, who still spends vacations at his ranch in Montana,
said, ``I live among gun owners,'' adding that many of them have
``totally the right attitude'' about how they should be used and
regulated.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had sold off his own collection of hunting rifles in
1968. ``I was raising daughters,'' he said, ``and I was
particularly troubled by what happened to Robert Kennedy and Martin
Luther King.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
</TEXT>
