<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN-SUICIDES-FILM (Undated) _ In ``The Virgin Suicides,'' the
dreamy first feature film written and directed by Sofia Coppola,
five sisters, ages 13 to 17, who live in a leafy Michigan suburb in
the 1970s inexplicably and matter-of-factly kill themselves. Their
story, an unsolved mystery laced with lust, obsession, longing,
fantasies and gilded memories, is recounted 25 years after by a
neighborhood boy, now a rueful adult, who worshiped Therese, Mary,
Bonnie, Lux and Cecilia Lisbon from afar. Adapted from Jeffrey
Eugenides's lyrical 1993 novel, the movie might have been a
prurient wander through the bedrooms of its lovely nymphs, an
exploitative riff on teenage angst, or a cautionary drama _ think
``Five American Beauties, Interrupted'' _ with an earnest social
message. But what Coppola has made of it is a haunting metaphysical
celebration with the aura of a myth. By Graham Fuller.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SISKEL-EBERT-FILMS (Undated) _ Watching ``Siskel and Ebert at
the Movies'' was a bit like being fed intravenously: you never
tasted anything, but eventually you felt a kind of ghostly
satiation. The show's appeal derived less from its film snippets
and critical insights than from the banter between the cheery,
chubby Roger Ebert and the diffident Gene Siskel, a dour presence
with the silhouette of a roll-on deodorant. As a team, these two
Chicago newspapermen lacked the easy rapport of, say, Hope and
Crosby, or the bittersweet camaraderie of Laurel and Hardy. What
they shared was a chafing testiness _ a novelty among TV co-hosts.
Siskel died at the age of 53 in February 1999. Since then, his
chair has been warmed by the rumps of reviewers drawn from a
defective Gene pool. Sessions have tended to play out like first
dates: guest critics seem more intent on pleasing Ebert than on
engaging him. By Franz Lidz. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KUBRICK-FILMS (Undated) _ Stanley Kubrick's death last spring,
followed by the release of ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' revived a
long-running argument among critics and fans about whether Kubrick
was one of the most important contemporary filmmakers or merely
among the most self-important _ an avatar of cinematic perfection
or a cold, detached perfectionist. The debate shows no signs of
ending any time soon. Last month, Vanity Fair published a long,
passionate defense of Kubrick, and in particular of his widely
unloved last work, by his friend and sometime collaborator Michael
Herr. And beginning Friday, Film Forum will provide fuel for many
nights of heated cafe-table contention as it mounts a three-week
retrospective of the director's work. By A.O. Scott. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SILVERS-DANCE (New York) _ Sally Silvers calls herself a dancer
and a choreographer, but by many conventional measures she
resembles neither. She has never succeeded at an audition, or
joined a professional dance company, or started a troupe of her
own. Even so, Silvers exerts a palpable force within the downtown
dance scene, both as a performer of striking intensity and as a
creator of wildly original movement. Her newest piece, ``Storming
Heaven,'' will have its premiere on April 26 at the Kitchen.
Inspired partly by Luigi Nono, who was Italy's leading postwar
avant-garde composer, it chronicles a series of revolutions from
the Paris Commune of 1871 to the Zapatista rebellion that began six
years ago in Chiapas, Mexico. By Christopher Reardon. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REAL-THING-THEATER (London) _ ``The Real Thing,'' which won
Jeremy Irons a Tony Award for best actor in 1984, is back on
Broadway this season, opening Monday at the Ethel Barrymore Theater
in Manhattan. The acclaimed revival originated last summer at the
Donmar Warehouse here and later transferred to a commercial run in
the West End. By Matt Wolf. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JACOBI-THEATER (Undated) _ The truth about Derek Jacobi, one of
the most emotionally potent British classical actors of his
generation, is that he has never known how to take a bow. He
loathes being singled out for approval. To him it is a degrading
spectacle, a charade. In fact, his aversion proved so vexing to his
mentor, Laurence Olivier, that one day, after a performance of the
Peter Shaffer play ``Black Comedy,'' Olivier took his protege aside
and offered a fatherly reprimand. ``He said,'' Jacobi recalled,
```If you have pretensions of being a leading actor you must learn
how to take a curtain call.''' Audiences at ``Uncle Vanya,'' the
new Roundabout Theater Company production in which Jacobi makes his
first Broadway appearance in more than a decade, will easily spot
him during the curtain call: he's the one looking as if he'd rather
be doing his taxes. By Peter Marks. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-SOUNDS (Windhoek, Namibia) _ Every composer, conductor,
musicologist and critic ought to be forced to spend time in places
like West Africa. The shrinkage of stature would both alarm and
instruct them. By day there is the overwhelming silence of the
bush. At night one hears the community and the competition. Lions
moan in tall grass; hippopotamuses grunt in bursts of three as they
come from the water to feed on the rushes around you; baboons
engage in high-decibel argument. Each is saying to the bush, ``I am
here, and this is who I am.'' Anyone pondering the meaning of art
might give a listen to the birds and animals of the Okovanggo
Basin. The sounds they make are both warning and welcome, but
mostly they are acts of self-expression and thus self-preservation.
By Bernard Holland. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-FIDELITY-FILM (Undated) _ These days, everyone assumes that
the serious music fan is an arrested adolescent. Nick Hornby's 1995
novel, ``High Fidelity,'' captured the paralyzed mental state of
smart males whose emotional lives revolve around cultural product,
not people. Now his characters have been made into Hollywood
archetypes by the director Stephen Frears and the actor John
Cusack. By Ann Powers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALTERNATIVE-COUNTRY (Undated) _ As Nashville, the music machine,
has become bigger and blander, Nashville the city _ along with its
kindred planet in Austin, Texas _ has become the center of an
increasingly diverse and intriguing array of American music rooted
in country with strains of folk, rock, bluegrass, rockabilly and
blues. At various times called Americana, alternative country, No
Depression or insurgent country, it's really too loose and untidy a
mongrel, or pack of vaguely allied mongrels, to fit into any real
niche _ certainly not the niche played on country radio. It's so
amorphous that No Depression magazine, the most clued-in
publication following the music, describes itself as ``the
alternative country (whatever that is) bimonthly.'' By Peter
Applebome. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-FILMS (New York) _ A few weeks ago at the Pioneer Theater
in Manhattan, the director Amos Poe introduced ``The Blank
Generation,'' his rough-hewn documentary of early punk rock shows,
shot on 16-mm film in 1976 and rarely seen since. But the program
of rare punk and new wave films being shown at the theater,
including several weeks of the intimate, sometimes amazing series
called ``Nightclubbing,'' shot at CBGB (the Dealey Plaza of punk
rock) and other New York clubs from 1975 to 1980, substantiate
Poe's showy claim for the era. (The series will end on May 24.) By
Rob Tannenbaum. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
