<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISO AND LOS ANGELES FEUD OVER AIDS MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Nancy Pelosi vowed Tuesday to preserve San
Francisco's $35 million federal AIDS funding despite efforts in
Congress to redistribute some of the money to other areas where the
epidemic is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said San Francisco stands to lose about $8 million in
funding from the Ryan White Care program that provides care and
medication for people with HIV and AIDS unless Congress continues
to provide the city with a special exception to the funding
formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply can't afford to have an increase in the unmet
needs'' of people with HIV and AIDS, Pelosi said, adding: ``The Bay
Area would be hit very hard by this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, a Democrat from San Francisco, said the move to
eliminate special treatment for San Francisco ``is something we
have to fight'' to ensure that ``the city does not have a
disruption in service.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles advocates for people with HIV and AIDS have combed
Capitol Hill recently urging lawmakers to kill an exception that
maintains federal AIDS funding level for San Francisco. They argue
that the exception provides San Francisco with a disproportionate
share of available funds at the expense of other cities and they
want the money dispersed to places such as Los Angeles with newer
waves of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbying is heating up as Congress prepares to extend the
Ryan White Care Act for five more years. This program, begun in
1991, empowers the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services to
pay for care and medication for people who aren't poor or sick
enough to receive Medicaid, but who don't have private insurance.
The Ryan White program is named after the hemophiliac teenager from
Kokomo, Ind., who contracted the disease through tainted blood and
died in 1990 at age 19. The program serves about a half million
people each year and, since 1991, has distributed $6.4 billion to
states and local governments for local use.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Senate Health, Labor and Human Services
Committee is expected to complete its draft of the new Ryan White
Care Act.
</P>
<P>
   Charles L. Henry, director of the office of AIDS Programs and
Policy for the Los Angeles County Department of Health, said the
exception for San Francisco is unfair because it ``keeps resources
in jurisdictions that have been historically impacted at the
expense of jurisdictions that are increasingly impacted.''
</P>
<P>
   According to estimates by the federal Centers for Disease
Control, Los Angeles now has 14,078 people living with AIDS,
compared to 7,703 people in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   However, Los Angeles is receiving $34.7 million in Ryan White
funds this fiscal year while San Francisco is getting $35.3
million, according to the federal Health Resources and Services
Administration that runs the program. Henry said that amounts to
$4,000 for each person with AIDS in San Francisco and $2,200 in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big difference,'' Henry said. ``It isn't fair.''
</P>
<P>
   That disparity exists because Congress decided in 1996 _ when it
updated the Ryan White program _ to maintain funding levels for San
Francisco even though the updated law changed the funding formula
that would otherwise have cut San Francisco's share.
</P>
<P>
   The new Ryan White formula was no longer based on a city's
cumulative number of AIDS cases over the years or on the ratio of
AIDS patients per capita.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Congress declared that funds should be distributed on
the basis of the total number of people living with AIDS in the
city. Under that formula, cities like San Francisco where the
disease had spread earlier in the epidemic would have received less
money. Congress approved the San Francisco exception to freeze its
funding so that the city's AIDS programs wouldn't be decimated by
the new formula. It's this San Francisco exception that is under
attack now.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi wants to add language that would freeze San Francisco's
share of the money at within 2 percent of the current $35.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that this is something that we have to fight
and can't settle for anything less than the 2 percent,'' Pelosi
said. ``We never fought in our fight for AIDS treatment, prevention
and research in any parochial way. It's hard to understand why
those of us who have been fighting the hardest should have our city
take a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi added that it's ``hard to understand why Los Angeles is
lobbying so hard against San Francisco, when it is the state that
would be the big loser.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said if the San Francisco exception were dropped, Los
Angeles would gain $500,000 in federal AIDS money, but the state of
California would suffer a net loss of about $7 million. Pelosi is
working with Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., to resolve the
impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfathomable and unthinkable that we would even have to
settle for this,'' Pelosi said. ``This is unfortunate that this is
happening within our state.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., an obstetrician, is pushing
legislation that would cut San Francisco's funding level by 10
percent a year over each of the next five years, allowing it to be
almost cut in half by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said the funding battle ``is about fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should one city be given a special advantage in terms of
federal AIDS funding over every other city in America? Is the
single mother living with HIV in inner city Baltimore not entitled
to the same care as a person living with AIDS in San
Francisco?``Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., who recently urged a
crowd of Los Angeles AIDS activists outside her office to stop
fighting for a cut in San Francisco's funding, said having the two
cities pitted against each other ``does not make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to get together and try to work it out,''
Feinstein said. ``I've asked them to sit down and work it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., noted that funding formulas
``always cause fights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that San Francisco can keep doing what
they are doing'' for people with AIDS and HIV, Boxer said. ``But we
also need to make sure Los Angeles has what it needs. My own view
is we need more money.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address Judy(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
