<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHUBARB-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHUBARB: SPRING'S HOT NEW DISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photos 5,6 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few days ago I had a Bellini made with rhubarb.
Then I came across dark chocolates from Richart with a rhubarb and
ginger filling. And lately, I've noticed that rhubarb is being
served with foie gras everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Since I love rhubarb, it's a pleasure to find it suddenly
showing up in such elegant company. It's also a surprising
turnaround for this vegetable that masquerades as a fruit and is
often merely pie filling.
</P>
<P>
   Rhubarb can be a challenge. It has such an aggressive nature
that it needs to be sweet-talked into being palatable. Yet it is so
vibrant a harbinger of spring that chefs are willing to exploit it
in new and unusual ways. Next month, Union Square Cafe is even
staging a whole meal built on rhubarb: rhubarb muffins, rhubarb
soup, rhubarb chutney with roast duck and rhubarb compote to top
tapioca pudding.
</P>
<P>
   The event _ a breakfast, despite the menu _ is timed to coincide
with an abundance of locally grown rhubarb at the nearby
Greenmarket and other produce stands. Although rhubarb is
sporadically available year round, what most markets carry
out-of-season is usually a relatively delicate hothouse variety,
often imported from Holland. Those who know their rhubarb prefer
the field-grown kind available from mid-April through June, because
the flavor and color are more intense.
</P>
<P>
   Rhubarb is classically paired with strawberries, in a seasonal
symbiosis of tart and sweet that results from a somewhat
simultaneous harvest. The combination, well sugared, softens the
rhubarb enough that even children may be persuaded to try it.
</P>
<P>
   But rhubarb, which looks for all the world like celery sheathed
in scarlet satin, is capable of far more than homespun pies,
crumbles and crisps. Its natural acidity makes it a superb foil for
rich roast pork or duck confit, for prosciutto and as a sauce for
succulent fish like salmon, arctic char or shad. At Firebird in the
theater district, it is paired with buttery chicken Kiev. But its
most stylish partner in New York this season is foie gras.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need the sweetness and sour of rhubarb against the fat of
the foie gras,'' said Paul Sale, the chef at Icon in midtown, who
sears the foie gras and wraps it in phyllo with rhubarb compote and
caramelized onion. ``In winter, we used cranberries and apples with
foie gras, but for spring, we switched to rhubarb,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Tesar at the new restaurant Vine in the financial district
and Joseph Fortunato at Quantum 56 in the Drake Swissotel in
midtown are also pairing rhubarb and foie gras. ``I use honey to
cut the tartness of rhubarb. It's great with the richness of foie
gras,'' Fortunato said.
</P>
<P>
   Rhubarb is usually simmered or stewed, but Michel Nischan at
Heartbeat in midtown glazes it with honey before briefly roasting
it. He then includes it in a fennel and onion salad to serve with
sea scallops or on its own with grapefruit and goat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Although rhubarb can be baked as long as an hour in a pie or
cobbler and still hold its shape, stewing should be at low heat and
brief. Overcooking renders it almost slimy. Stewed rhubarb is
excellent with ice cream; the puree is easily turned into sorbet.
Along with strawberries, raspberries are delicious with rhubarb,
and intensify the color. Ginger and orange enhance the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh rhubarb can also be cut up, blanched for a couple of
minutes in boiling water to set the color and then frozen to ensure
a year-round supply for baking.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its sugar dependency, rhubarb has been stymied somewhat
by an image as a slightly poisonous plant. The leaves can be toxic
_ not, as usually thought, because of oxalic acid, but from a still
unidentified toxin, said Harold McGee, a food scientist, in ``On
Food and Cooking'' (Collier Books, 1984). The leaves should never
be eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Rhubarb, which is actually related to celery, comes from
northern China and Siberia. The name is thought to derive from Rha,
once a name for the Volga River, around which it grew wild. In
China, the roots have been used for nearly 5,000 years for
medicinal purposes. It was also used for its medicinal roots in
Greece and Rome around the time of Christ and in medieval
monasteries in France and England.
</P>
<P>
   By the 17th century, English botanists began to try it as a
food, but it was not until the 19th century that it occurred to
English and American cooks to experiment with the stems in
preserves and pies. Rhubarb is still called pie plant in parts of
this country.
</P>
<P>
   The rhubarb coming into markets now is selling for about $2 a
pound. To get the most from it, select the brightest red stalks you
can find, and slender ones rather than thick ones, so they will be
less fibrous. One chopped stalk will yield about half a cup of
rhubarb. Rhubarb should not be peeled because most of the color is
in the skin. Although the flavor is what counts, it would be a pity
to strip its beautiful ruby tint.
</P>
<P>
   And that color is what makes a rhubarb Bellini so stunning.
Mario Batali and Joseph Bastianich, at their new restaurant Esca in
the theater district, are serving the shocking pink aperitif made
with sweetened rhubarb puree and sparkling prosecco. It's a great
moment for rhubarb. Finally, it has the dazzle it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   RHUBARB BELLINIS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Esca
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups rhubarb, about 4 slender stalks, trimmed and cut in
1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle prosecco or other sparkling wine, well-chilled.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place rhubarb, sugar, lemon zest and lemon juice in saucepan
with \ cup water. Bring to simmer and cook about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove from heat and place saucepan in bowl of ice and water
until cool, about 10 minutes. Puree in blender.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place about 1{ tablespoons puree in 8 champagne flutes. Pour
in prosecco until about one-third full. Stir well to blend in
rhubarb puree. Gradually top each serving with more prosecco,
stirring to prevent sparkling wine from bubbling over, then serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   RHUBARB, FENNEL AND GRAPEFRUIT SALAD WITH GOAT CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Heartbeat
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound rhubarb, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons honey, preferably tupelo
</P>
<P>
   1 large pink grapefruit, peeled and cut in segments
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-large fennel bulb
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-large sweet onion
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 3-ounce chilled goat cheese log, in 4 slices
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons balsamic vinegar at least 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Line baking sheet with foil. Cut
rhubarb into sticks about \-inch thick and 4 inches long. Toss in
bowl with 2 tablespoons honey to coat. Place on baking sheet and
bake about 5 minutes, until softened. Remove from oven and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Toss grapefruit segments with remaining honey in a bowl. Use
mandoline to slice fennel bulb paper-thin. Peel onion and slice
paper-thin. Combine fennel, onion, rhubarb and parsley in bowl.
Toss. Add olive oil. Transfer grapefruit to strainer over same bowl
and allow juice to fall into salad. Lightly toss and season with
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mound salad on 4 chilled plates. Place three grapefruit
segments to one side and a slice of goat cheese opposite. Drizzle
balsamic vinegar around edges and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   RHUBARB CHUTNEY
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus cooling
</P>
<P>
   6 cups coarsely diced rhubarb, about 2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   2 cups light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   { cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   { cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 Granny Smith apples, peeled, cored and coarsely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   10 black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   4 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 star anise.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place rhubarb, sugar and lemon juice in heavy saucepan. Bring
to simmer and add remaining ingredients. Cook gently about 10
minutes, until rhubarb and apples are tender but still hold their
shape.
</P>
<P>
   2. Transfer to containers and store in refrigerator. Or transfer
to sterilized jelly jars, seal with sterilized lids and place in
boiling water bath for 10 minutes. Cool, tighten lids and store on
pantry shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 cups.
</P>
<P>
   RHUBARB-BERRY COBBLER
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds rhubarb in one-inch pieces, about 5 cups
</P>
<P>
   { pint strawberries, hulled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   { pint raspberries
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour, more for dusting
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter, in pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons milk, approximately
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 pint vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Brush 8-inch square or 9-inch
round pan, attractive enough for serving, with little melted
butter.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whisk brown sugar and cornstarch together in large bowl. Add
rhubarb, berries, cinnamon and remaining melted butter. Toss to
combine. Transfer to baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place flour, baking powder and salt in food processor and
pulse briefly. Add butter and pulse until coarsely blended. Add
milk, pulse briefly, then transfer to bowl. Gather together by hand
to form soft dough, adding a little more milk if needed. Transfer
to floured board and roll to rectangle 8 by 10 inches. Cut in
one-inch-wide strips and arrange in lattice fashion over rhubarb
mixture. Dust with sugar.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bake about 50 minutes, until pastry is lightly browned. Cool
at least 30 minutes before serving with ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
