A3749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ARISTA-DAVIS-NYT &LR;      04-11 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARISTA-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SALUTE TO CLIVE DAVIS, OUSTED AT ARISTA RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Clive Davis, the beleaguered chief executive of
Arista Records, celebrated the 25th anniversary of the label he
founded with performances by some of its best-known acts Monday
night at the Shrine Auditorium here. The ceremony stretched from
three hours to an audience-wearying six so that it could be taped
properly for broadcast May 15 on NBC. Among those performing were
Santana, Sarah McLachlan, Toni Braxton, Puff Daddy, Barry Manilow,
Alan Jackson, Patti Smith and Whitney Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The event crowned what many in the music business have been
calling the year of Clive Davis. Since it was disclosed in November
that executives at BMG Entertainment, which owns Arista, had
decided to replace 66-year-old Davis when his contract expires in
June with a younger executive, Antonio (L.A.) Reid of the
rhythm-and-blues label Laface, Davis was put in the glare of the
spotlight like no recording executive in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, he has been inducted into the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame, one of the few executives to receive the honor with
such fanfare; been the subject of numerous feature articles; turned
his annual pre-Grammy Awards party into a self-tribute, which
culminated with Stevie Wonder comparing him to Jesus; been given a
lifetime achievement award by the National Academy of Recording
Arts and Sciences; and gotten in the last word at the Grammy Awards
after winning the top award for co-producing Carlos Santana's
comeback record.
</P>
<P>
   Now Davis, admired for the mainstream pop taste and hands-on
career guidance that have marked his run at Arista, has enjoyed
another massive tribute. At the Arista birthday party, Dick Clark
introduced a film of highlights from Davis' career, President
Clinton gave testimony to Davis in a letter included in the program
notes, Houston was introduced by a film that began with Davis
announcing her on an old Merv Griffin show, and celebrity
presenters introduced performers with long quotations from Davis as
if he were a pundit on the order of Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that nothing was planned,'' Davis said
in an interview before the show. As for all his awards and honors,
he said, ``I was told that the Grammys voted back in May, and we've
gotten requests for a 25th-anniversary special from networks for
years. Like Fifth Avenue buses, sometimes they all come at once.
And obviously, all these occasions are unrelated to each other, but
I'll take them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Many executives said that Davis was keeping such a high profile
because he was fighting to keep his job, but Davis denied ever
publicly protesting or being on bad terms with his superiors at BMG
and confirmed that he would step down from Arista.
</P>
<P>
   ``My contract ends June 30, and I've gotten tremendous offers,
including one from BMG,'' he said. ``I'm really going to be
weighing these, because it's a major new opportunity and I'm going
to do what makes me happy. It's been the biggest year in our
history _ not just in sales but in profits.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is Davis enjoying so much limelight if the battle for his
job is already over? Several executives at rival labels, some of
whom have been ejected from the companies they ran in similar power
struggles, answered that question on condition of anonymity. One
executive said he admired the ``perseverance and lunatic passion''
with which Davis ran Arista, adding that Davis ``can't let go, and
it's not in his nature not to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding an extra layer of drama to the Arista celebration was
Houston's first television performance since her canceled
performances at the Oscars and the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame
induction ceremony. Backstage at the ceremony, journalists were far
more interested in Houston's health than in Davis' job.
</P>
<P>
   Houston began on a troubled note: she had difficulty focusing,
tripped on the stage and forgot the lyrics to her hit, ``How Will I
Know.'' But she snapped into sharp focus midway through the set
with a slow-building, highly improvised version of ``I Will Always
Love You'' that brought the exhausted audience to its feet one more
time before the show's finale: the smiling, spectacled Davis
surrounded by Carole King, Melissa Etheridge, Dionne Warwick,
Manilow and dozens of other stars singing ``That's What Friends Are
For.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
