<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0412-COX     04-11 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0412-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RENO MAY TRAVEL TO MIAMI TO MEET WITH FAMILY, AS ELIAN TRANSFER
APPEARS CLOSER
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In a bid to bring the long-running saga of 6-year-old
Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez to a swift close, U.S. Attorney General
Janet Reno may travel to Miami Wednesday to meet with the boy's
Florida family and local officials to urge their cooperation in
transferring the boy to his father.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno's meetings would not upset the timetable for turning
the boy over, which Justice Department officials said would be sent
to the family in a letter late Tuesday or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Several South Florida television stations cited unnamed sources
saying the family would be ordered to turn the boy over on
Thursday, although federal officials refused to publicly confirm
any dates, times or places.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami family still hopes to delay the transfer by first
obtaining a meeting with Juan Miguel Gonzalez, Elian's father, who
_ along with his wife and baby son _ has been living at the home of
a top Cuban diplomat near Washington D.C. since his arrival from
Cuba last week.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, offered to
meet with Juan Miguel, suggesting the Miami Beach home of Barry
University President Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin as a possible site.
O'Laughlin hosted a brief reunion between Elian and his Cuban
grandmothers in January, but then became a figure of controversy
herself by announcing she felt the boy should remain in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter released to the media, Lazaro Gonzalez said a
meeting of the family's adults could soon be followed by a reunion
between Elian and his father.
</P>
<P>
   But the Miami family ``would want to be assured that Elian will
be allowed to return to his present home in Miami's Little Havana
neighborhood afterward so that the meeting does not become the
opportunity for his abrupt removal,'' Gonzalez wrote.
</P>
<P>
   That demand made the chances for such a meeting seem dim, as
Juan Miguel Gonzalez has insisted he wants his son turned over to
him with no strings attached. Gonzalez has also said he would not
travel to Miami, or that if he did, it would only be to pick up his
son.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez spent part of the day at the Cuban Interests Section in
Washington, meeting with supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not wish to meet with the Miami relatives until he has
Elian in his arms,'' said the Rev. Joan Brown-Campbell, former head
of the National Council of Churches, which has tried for months to
broker the boy's return to his father. ``Once he has his son, then
the adults can work on their relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez also refused to meet over the weekend with two Miami
relatives who traveled to Washington in hopes of setting up a
family ``kitchen-table'' conference.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter feelings between the branches of the family probably
weren't helped Tuesday when lawyers for the Miami relatives filed a
brief in a Florida family court alleging Juan Miguel Gonzalez has
abused his son. The brief asked for a hearing on the matter, but
Judge Jennifer Bailey said she was unlikely to grant such a hearing
because she feels federal law supersedes any state jurisdiction in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision to possibly visit Miami came shortly after she
met in her Washington office with Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex
Penelas and Miami Mayor Joe Carollo, who asked her to delay the
boy's transfer for 30 days and help set up a Gonzalez family
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that really should be decided between family
members,'' Penelas said, adding that he felt Miami's Cuban exiles
would respect whatever the family decides. Penelas has done a
dramatic about-face since he blasted federal officials two weeks
ago, warning that they were provoking Miami's exiles with their
insistence on returning Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Reno called the meeting ``productive,'' but again
stressed ``that the transfer of Elian to the care of his father
must move forward without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear whether Juan Miguel Gonzalez would remain in
the United States if his son is returned to him. He has stated that
he would be willing to remain here until an Atlanta federal appeals
court rules on the Miami relatives' lawsuit, but he has also said
he would prefer to return to Cuba immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta is scheduled to
hear arguments in the case May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's case also drew another flurry of attention in Congress,
with Florida's two senators urging that the hand-over of the boy be
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Connie Mack said he was upset that the
government would turn the boy over before the family had a chance
to work the issue out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is better equipped than Elian's own family to decide what
his future will be,'' Mack said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the House Republican leadership and two Cuban-American
members of Florida's congressional delegation invited Juan Miguel
Gonzalez to meet privately Wednesday in the Capitol. ``We want to
be sure that you are aware of all the options available to you as
you make your decision,'' they wrote in a letter delivered by
representatives of House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Washington correspondents Sue Schultz and Larry
Lipman contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
