<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALDWIN-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JAMES BALDWIN: A SOUL ON FIRE': GLIMPSING BALDWIN ON THE
PRECIPICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By DAVID DeWITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``James Baldwin: A Soul on Fire'' is the best sort of
theatrical biography: the sort that thoroughly entertains.
</P>
<P>
   The New Federal Theater's production of Howard Simon's short
play is funny, thrilling and wise, buoyed by the passionate
performance of Charles Reese in the title role. One minute he's
singing and leading the audience to hand-clapping unity; the next
he's speaking with urgent force on the desperate crisis of civil
rights. Reese even resembles Baldwin, with large eyes that suggest
a singular vision of the human experience.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Soul on Fire,'' Reese has a vehicle worthy of his
performance. Simon's script imagines a 1963 morning before Baldwin
and his colleagues _ the playwright Lorraine Hansberry, the
performer Harry Belafonte and the singer Lena Horne _ will meet
with Robert F. Kennedy, the U.S. attorney general. ``What shall I
wear to meet the man?'' Baldwin coos, echoing the title of one of
his most serious and horrific short stories. It's a disarming
reference because Baldwin is so plainly excited; Kennedy, he says,
``is so manly.''
</P>
<P>
   We see the giddy Baldwin planning his meeting in phone calls
with his collaborators, all performed by Forrest McClendon, who
serves the play well in a range of performance styles as a choral
confidant and force of nature called Ethereal. These exchanges
range from revolutionary dialogue to fey gossip (of Belafonte,
Baldwin tells Hansberry, ``I saw `Jamaica' six times just to see
his chest'').
</P>
<P>
   But the calls are interrupted by a blackmail effort that
imperils Baldwin. The night before, the writer had slept with the
wrong man, a barely literate trick who stole his manuscript and is
holding it for ransom. To retrieve his book, Baldwin must come up
with money and make the payoff himself, instead of meeting with
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a choice between artistry and activism? Between private
life and public life? The dilemma seems to have afflicted the real
Baldwin, who, while creating his fiction, wrestled with the call to
serve the demands of his time and sort out his identity as a gay
man, a black man and an American. It's a great hook for the play.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional crisis leads to a catharsis that isn't as fully
realized as its setup, though the director, Chuck Patterson, powers
it with a theatrical set of images. In one stomach-churning moment,
Reese's Baldwin speaks of his devout hopes for race relations as a
video image of the real Baldwin plays across the stage. The video's
closeups of the quietly dignified Baldwin reveal the haunting roots
of Reese's soaring rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the video, ``A Soul on Fire,'' presented in the
Abrons Art Center at the Henry Street Settlement, is a technically
modest production; a silk bedspread and scarf-covered lamp are the
most telling set pieces. Anita D. Ellis' costumes, however, are
thematically prominent. While the production at first dresses
Ethereal and Baldwin in white, it ends with a black-clad Ethereal
as Huey Newton, banging a drum and giving Baldwin a black power
salute. The moment has a forceful appeal, less a resolution of the
play than a blunt depiction of its conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In about 60 minutes, ``A Soul on Fire'' is of course not a
thorough evocation of Baldwin's life. But with humor, style and raw
emotion, it embraces its chosen territory with enthusiasm. All
stage biographies should be served so well.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `JAMES BALDWIN: A SOUL ON FIRE'
</P>
<P>
   By Howard Simon; directed by Chuck Patterson; production stage
manager, Jacqui Casto; sets by Terry Chandler; lighting by
Antoinette Tynes; costumes by Anita D. Ellis; video and sound by
Sean O'Halloran; technical director, Chandler; property mistress,
Laura Johnston. Presented by the New Federal Theater, Woodie King
Jr., producing director. At the Henry Street Settlement/Abrons Art
Center, 466 Grand St.
</P>
<P>
   With: Forrest McClendon (Ethereal) and Charles Reese (James
Baldwin).
</P>
</TEXT>
