<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHJOBS-SOUTH12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Information tech jobs still going unfilled
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More than 1.6 million information technology jobs will
be created in the United States this year, but only half of them
will be filled, according to a study released this week looking at
the size and scope of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a lot larger than originally thought, the Information
Technology Association of America study found. Roughly one in 14
U.S. workers makes a living by developing and supporting
information technology for companies. And more of them work in the
South than anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to show you the enormous change that's taken
place in our economy,'' said Bob Cohen, a senior vice president
with the Arlington, Va.-based trade group. ``This really and truly
is a new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, ``Bridging the Gap: IT Skills for a New Millennium,''
polled 700 IT managers in and outside the IT field.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly a third _ or 3.4 million _ of the nation's 10 million IT
jobs are in the South, making the region home to more information
technology workers than the West, site of the traditional high-tech
havens of Silicon Valley and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about the IT industry, most people tend to
think of the Silicon Valley, and their thoughts tend to drift
west,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for IT workers is expected to grow by 310,000 in the
South over the next 12 months, the study said. Still, the Midwest
and West are expected to need more workers than Southern companies
in the time period.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's lopsided supply and demand continues to
underscore the severe need nationwide for people who can develop,
run and maintain everything from computers to web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real concern,'' Cohen said. ``(It affects) the ability
of companies to grow and develop IT solution and use IT for
competitive advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The tight labor market has prompted many companies to pressure
Congress to relax immigration laws to allow more high-tech workers
in from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest job, the study found, is technical support, from
those who repair complex systems to people working on help desks.
Employers will seek to fill 600,000 tech support jobs in the next
year alone. Database developers were second, followed by
programmers and software engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the increased demand for e-business and the Internet,
workers with web experience are now the target of 13 percent of all
IT hiring, the study noted.
</P>
<P>
   As for skills, the traditional thinking has been that people had
to have very specific kinds of training to get jobs. Not so, the
study found.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one way to get these skills,'' Cohen said. ``There
are a variety of avenues: community college, technical school or
four-year university.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most surprising findings, Cohen noted, was the fact
that 90 percent of all the jobs and 70 percent of all the demand
for IT workers comes from outside IT companies such as the local
bank, insurance company or grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Where the supply of workers falls short of the demand, by region
</P>
<P>
   Region ....Demand ...Gap
</P>
<P>
   Northeast.....277,079.....145,272
</P>
<P>
   South.....310,346.....162,714
</P>
<P>
   Midwest.....566,530.....297,029
</P>
<P>
   West.....454,543.....238,314
</P>
<P>
   Source: Bridging the Gap, Information Technology Association of
America, 2000
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
