A3773 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS12-C     04-11 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons may reconsider 'best-player-available' theory
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nathan Davis did nothing to leave his mark on the
field in his brief career with the Atlanta Falcons. But he will be
on the minds of team officials, nonetheless, when the NFL draft
begins Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With no first-round pick, Falcons coach Dan Reeves concedes that
his team probably will scrap the best-available-player approach and
instead draft to fill a need in the 37th spot.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is the Falcons' biggest draft flop since Reeves was hired
in 1997. The former Indiana University defensive tackle, a ``need
pick,'' dressed for two games that season and did not make a
tackle. He quit on the first day of training camp in 1998, tried to
rejoin the team, and was waived. In his senior season at Indiana,
Davis suffered a serious and documented tear of a tendon in his
pelvis. The injury kept him from working out when he joined the
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   It became an excuse for a player whose weight ballooned while
his work ethic and will to compete disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in the Falcons' scouting department, which underwent
change in 1997, suggested that Davis was worth a fourth-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had seen some of the warning flags with Nathan Davis, we
never would have taken him,'' Reeves said. ``Our research wasn't as
good as it should have been. What you saw (on film) were flashes of
a guy who made some plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' director of college player personnel, Reed Johnson,
has a slightly different memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Need is an ominous word,'' Johnson said. ``With Nathan Davis,
there was a need factor there. There were hints of what would
happen, although I don't think anyone could have anticipated
someone being so not willing to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like watching a baby throw a tantrum. I had to leave
the field twice; I couldn't watch.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 2000 draft, the Falcons appear to need the most on the
offensive line and at running back, where four players are
rehabilitating knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the draft is perhaps deepest in offensive
linemen. Reeves on Tuesday described linemen as ``the most
important part of your offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson mentioned several top offensive linemen who could be
available _ Todd Wade (6 feet 7 3/4, 325 pounds) of Mississippi,
Marvel Smith (6-4 7/8, 320) of Arizona State, Michael Thompson (6-4
1/2, 305) of Tennessee State.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities include Adrian Klemm (6-4, 308) of Hawaii
and Darnell Alford (6-4, 355) of Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves declined to confirm his team's greatest needs, but he
conceded that his team's strategy Saturday probably will be a
little different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your needs always influence the best-player-available
(theory),'' Reeves said. ``At some point in the draft, and it
usually comes pretty early, you go past the best player available.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, with where we're going in the draft, that's
where you start looking for the best player available at a position
of need. Of course, you never want to pass up a player, regardless
of position, if you think he's sure to play and be a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Some top running backs who figure to be available in the second
round, and even in the third, are J.R. Redmond (5-11 1/2, 210) of
Arizona, Travis Prentice (5-11 1/2, 220) of Miami-Ohio, Sammy
Morris (5-1 3/4, 222) of Texas Tech, Reuben Droughns (5-11 1/4,
210) of Oregon, Doug Chapman (5-10, 210) of Marshall and Curtis
Keaton (5-10, 214) of James Madison.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a bunch of players at different positions bunched
in a group (on the draft board),'' Reeves said, ``you'd better not
pass on a player you're sure about, even if he's rated lower,
rather than take a (higher-rated) player you have questions about.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't think you should ever pass on a really good
running back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
