<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3776 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SCFLAG-COX     04-11 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCFLAG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. legislators to begin flag debte
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soren Dresch loves the ripple effect of South Carolina's
Confederate battle flag debate. The bluster's been great for
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd guess sales are up tenfold in the past three months,''
said Dresch, who owns the Ruffin Flag Co. in Crawfordville, Ga.,
between Atlanta and Augusta. ``This has really sparked interest.''
</P>
<P>
   He supplies South Carolina legislators with battle flags.
Lawmakers sell the banners to constituents who request them. The
former human resources major also supplies the Sons of Confederate
Veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so far behind in orders it's ridiculous,'' Dresch said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Dresch's heart _ not to mention his flags _ will be
aflutter: Leaders in South Carolina's state Senate expect to debate
a bill that would remove the controversial Civil War flag from atop
the Statehouse dome, where it's flown beneath the U.S. and state
flags since 1962. As supporters from both sides fill the Senate
gallery today, the eyes of the old Confederacy from Jackson to
Richmond will be fixed on Columbia looking for a clue what might
come next.
</P>
<P>
   The next full-fledged bouts could be in Georgia and Mississippi,
where there's already been political sparring. Both states use the
battle insignias in their state flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defenders of the flag claim, and I think they may be
right, that this is the camel's nose,'' said John Shelton Reed, a
Southern historian at the University of North Carolina. ``If they
lose this, then the fight moves to somewhere else. So, no
surrender, no retreat is the line they're taking.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the NAACP has tried to remove a plaque of the
Confederate battle flag on a wall at the state Supreme Court
building in Austin. In Alabama, a state legislator is fighting to
remove the slogan ``The Heart of Dixie'' from state license plates.
Last year in Iowa, the state speaker of the House complained to the
transportation department when he saw a battle flag flying at an
interstate work site.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson, Miss., city council last week voted to remove the
state flag, which contains the Confederate battle emblem, from the
council chambers. The next day, angry legislators voted against a
bill that would have helped Jackson fix its storm sewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the opinion of a lot of legislators the city of Jackson
has taken the first step of seceding from the state by banning the
state flag,'' said state Rep. Mark Formby (R-Picayune).
</P>
<P>
   In Pensacola, Fla., city manager Tom Bonfield decided in January
to head off trouble. Nicknamed the ``City of Five Flags,''
Pensacola for years has flown the battle emblem along with the
flags of the U.S., France, Great Britain and Spain. When civil
rights leaders during Super Bowl week in Atlanta began demanding a
change in the Georgia flag, Bonfield ordered Pensacola's battle
flags replaced by the first national flag of the Confederacy, the
so-called Stars and Bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt it was a matter of time before that issue came up
in Pensacola,'' Bonfield said. ``Barely a week goes by before
there's another city that deals with that. So for those cities that
have had some reason to fly a version of the Confederate flag, I
think the South Carolina debate is going to be something to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, there's been hopeful talk of compromise.
State senators begin debate around 11 a.m. today and may stay
through the weekend. If the Senate passes a flag bill, it goes to
the House, which then will be pressed by a fast-approaching
adjournment June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Today's debate will be the first time this year state lawmakers
officially have debated the issue. So far, the public fight over
the blood-red battle emblem marked by a deep blue ``X'' with 13
stars has been fought by marches, protests and
counterdemonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Flag proponents, most of them white, say the insignia represents
the heroic heritage of their Civil War ancestors. Black civil
rights groups, most notably the NAACP, claim the battle design is a
reminder of past oppression.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, the NAACP launched a boycott of South Carolina's
$14.6 billion tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the flag was simply a symbol that was tied exclusively to
the Civil War, then I think the debate might be a lot less
passionate,'' said Jim Cobb, a past president of the Southern
Historical Society and current head of the history department at
the University of Georgia. ``But because the issues there are not
quite as clear as the issue of the flag being the symbol of the
Klan, the American Nazi Party... the banner of the Dixiecrats,
there's just no getting around that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate has come down to almost a question of absolutes.
You either lock heels or give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
