<HEADER>
A3778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-AFTER-HOURS-N     04-11 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AFTER-HOURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LATER THE HOUR, THE MORE REFLECTIVE CLINTON GETS
</HEADLINE>
  By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is after hours, away from the White House, that
Bill Clinton loosens up.
</P>
<P>
   With no prepared text, his words flow more freely than during
daylight. One minute, he is talking of Pokemon cards or the best
love song of the last 25 years. The next, how he almost lost his
job as president. He abandons the cautious verbiage he uses from 9
to 5, sometimes lashing out at political opponents with the
ferocity of a behind-in-the-polls candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for instance, has never acknowledged publicly that he
feared he might become the first president in history to be removed
from office _ until, that is, he took the stage of a church in
Louisiana on Saturday night and suggested, in a deeply emotional
way, just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There, for a period of time _ a day or two at least _ was some
question about whether I would finish my term,'' Clinton told
members of a Pentecostal church in Alexandria, La., bringing up a
matter he does not typically bring up anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his presidency, Clinton has let his guard down
somewhat in his evening remarks. But in the twilight of his
presidency, with fewer big policy events on his schedule and more
late-night fund-raisers, Clinton's reflective side emerges more
often.
</P>
<P>
   Every presidential speech is recorded and transcribed, even
remarks uttered off the cuff. But the gaggle of reporters tracking
him thins after dark, sometimes to a lonely scribe. And the only
television camera at such moments is often operated by military
personnel collecting footage for the archives.
</P>
<P>
   The settings of Clinton's evening remarks are also more
conducive to casual chatter: the dining room of a big donor, the
back of Air Force One, a remote country church.
</P>
<P>
   And the later the hour, it seems, the looser the president.
</P>
<P>
   It was pushing midnight, White House time, when Clinton took the
stage at the Pentecostals of Alexandria after a rousing performance
of the ``Messiah.''
</P>
<P>
   The president stood alongside a pastor he has known for years
and a group of former drug addicts and convicts who had reassembled
their lives through religion. Clinton said he had cried throughout
the performance, which portrayed the life and death of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of reporters sitting in the balcony, the
president brought up his own ordeal in impromptu remarks. He said
the Rev. Anthony Mangun and his wife had visited him during the
heat of the impeachment furor, dropping off a recording of an
uplifting song and some biblical readings. He said the gifts helped
him get through the tough times.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recalled that the pastor had told him he was not sure
how the scandal would end, but he vowed to stand by the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said: `I know you. You are my friend. We have raised our
children together. I love you. I was here when you were going up.
If the ship starts to sink and other people start to bail out, you
call me. I want to go down with you,''' Clinton said
</P>
<P>
   Then he gave Mangun a bear hug.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the president's remarks, of course, are quite that
touchy-feely. Sometimes, after a long day of policy talk, Clinton
seems to relish speaking of nothing weightier than his favorite
movies. He is known to drop in on reporters in the rear of the
presidential jetliner and make movie recommendations for the
flight. Unlike a commercial airline, which picks the movie,
passengers in each cabin in Air Force One choose from a menu of
more than a dozen films.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent fund-raiser in New York, Clinton seemed proud of the
fact that he was in on one of the current crazes among children _
Pokemon cards. The young son of a political supporter gave him some
cards, which he passed along to a very appreciative nephew.
</P>
<P>
   At another New York gathering, Clinton called ``Evergreen'' the
best love song of the last quarter century after Luther Vandross
sang it for him at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the evening Clinton began his most spirited attacks
to date on the opponents of his wife and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In news conferences, Clinton avoids getting too involved in
Hillary Rodham Clinton's race for a U.S. Senate seat from New York.
But at a recent weekend fund-raiser in Washington, he said his wife
was being targeted by a ``right-wing venom machine'' allied with
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way they could win is to convince them that we're the
first cousins of space aliens,'' Clinton told members of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, Gore's presumed opponent to
succeed Clinton, has also been the subject of Clinton's needling.
Clinton criticized Bush at a New York fund-raiser for his positions
on abortion, hate crimes legislation and tax cuts. He also
criticized Bush for going to Bob Jones University in South Carolina
and not speaking out against its views on Roman Catholics and
inter-racial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has begun revealing in some talks that he is a betting
man. To make the point that his administration has eliminated
government programs without causing disruption, he has bet members
of audiences in recent speeches _ anywhere from $5 to $10,000 _ to
name three such discontinued programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've eliminated hundreds of programs, and I will give anyone
here the ticket price here, I'll give you your money back if you
can stand up right now and name three of them,'' Clinton said on
Saturday at a $10,000-a-person fund-raiser at a private home
outside New Orleans. ``Any takers?''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has ever collected.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aides sometimes squirm when he begins free-associating,
nervous that he might be so exhausted or unguarded that he will
unintentionally make news.
</P>
<P>
   Many aides still remember a late-night fund-raiser in Texas in
Clinton's first term in which he ad-libbed about how he had raised
taxes too much in his 1993 budget bill, a comment that prompted a
firestorm among Democrats who had risked their political futures to
back him.
</P>
<P>
   There had to be concern last week when Clinton, visibly
exhausted, began speaking at a fund-raiser in San Francisco after a
grueling 19-hour day.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Garen and Shari Staglin, Napa Valley vintners and
longtime Democratic contributors, the president said, ``I thank the
Staglins for co-hosting this event, and for the wine _ which I
could not resist tasting, even though I have been up since 3 a.m.
your time.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he gave what turned out to be a run-of-the-mill, if
somewhat rambling, speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
