<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CLOUD-CLUB-NYT &LR;      04-11 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLOUD-CLUB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIVING THE HIGH LIFE, IN THE CHRYSLER BUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has been 21 years since the last meal was served
here and the last ice-filled glasses clinked to good fortune. Since
then, the Cloud Club in the Chrysler Building, the onetime playroom
of Walter P. Chrysler and his fellow moguls, has been ravaged by
time, neglect, water and vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   But the wide bronze-and-marble staircase is still there and the
view through the arch of the two-story-high window, 67 floors up,
still gazes south over a bustling, energetic city.
</P>
<P>
   So why are restaurateurs not down on their knees in the
building's landmark lobby, begging for the chance to breathe new
life into the Cloud Club?
</P>
<P>
   ``New York doesn't lack for good restaurants,'' said Bernard
Goldberg, whose Gotham Hospitality Group was one of the finalists
in the bidding for the Chrysler Building in 1997. But a private
lunch club there would probably succeed, he added, if much of its
elegance was restored and the room was used at night for wedding
receptions and other private parties.
</P>
<P>
   Tishman Speyer Properties, a co-owner of the Chrysler Building,
said it preferred having a restaurant in that lofty space, but
would not turn down other tenants, including those who would use
the three floors as office space. In the meantime, construction
workers have been toiling in the dust and jumble of the 66th, 67th
and 68th floors, just below the Chrysler Building's stainless steel
pinnacle, trying to undo the effects of years of abandonment on the
Cloud Club's faded glory.
</P>
<P>
   The club opened in July 1930 as a private retreat for male
executives. The Chrysler Building itself had formally opened on May
28 of that year at the northeast corner of 42nd Street and
Lexington Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of the building and the club was William Van Alen,
who was born in Brooklyn and graduated from the Ecole des
Beaux-Arts in Paris. Before designing the Chrysler Building, he had
designed the Childs restaurant at 604 Fifth Avenue, at 49th Street,
among other notable buildings. But Van Alen, who died in 1954,
never enjoyed anywhere near the fame of his greatest creation.
</P>
<P>
   For many years the Cloud Club was the outpost for such movers
and shakers as Chrysler; E.F. Hutton; Juan Trippe, the founder of
Pan American World Airways, and Conde Nast, the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   The club's elite reputation lasted another four decades, as
evidenced by a roster that as late as 1971 comprised 300 members
from 180 corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Members enjoyed use of the club's amenities: a Tudor-style
paneled lounge, a humidor for cigars from around the world, a
wood-paneled bar and (a necessity during Prohibition) private
locker boxes where members stashed liquor supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The club was known for its black bean soup, Dover sole and
bread-and-butter pudding. It served melons grown on a member's farm
upstate, as well as ``No. 18'' pink grapefruit. Falco Witekamp, an
official with the Florida Department of Citrus, said that No. 18s
were ``huge, huge, huge; more than twice as big as any grapefruit
you're likely to find in a supermarket.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Chrysler Building began as a speculative venture by
William H. Reynolds, a former New York State senator, the entire
project was bought by Chrysler, who added touches like the
stainless-steel eagle heads that extend from the corners on the
61st floor, and the winged ornaments, on the building's lower
setbacks, that were modeled on the radiator caps of 1920s Chrysler
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   He also brought to the project a determination to make it the
world's tallest building, a goal also coveted by the Bank of
Manhattan, which was under construction at the same time at 40 Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler Building, 1,046 feet, won bragging rights, but held
them for only 11 months, until the 1,250-foot Empire State Building
opened on May 1, 1931. (Today the Chrysler Building is 19th
tallest, the Empire State Building 9th, according to the Council on
Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat at Lehigh University.)
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, corporations were leaving the city, and the Cloud
Club faced competition from some three dozen private executive
lunch clubs, including the Sky Club on the 56th floor of the nearby
Pan Am building, to which Trippe had defected in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, four years after the Massachusetts Mutual Life
Insurance Co. acquired the building in a foreclosure proceeding,
the club closed for good. But it has remained a fixture of New York
folklore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard all kinds of rumors, including that Walter
Chrysler's ashes are up there,'' said Valerie Peltier, senior
director of Tishman Speyer Properties.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Jerry I. Speyer, the president of Tishman Speyer, was taken to
the club by his father in the late 1940s and was so infatuated with
the view that he remembers having said at the time, ``I never want
to leave here.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Tishman Speyer and the Travelers Group bought
the Chrysler Building for $225 million.
</P>
<P>
   Various attempts in the early 1980s to fill the three floors
with everything from a nightclub to a disco to a lunch club for
bankers foundered, and the slump in office rentals in the early
1990s further discouraged prospects. Today, by contrast, Manhattan
office space is at a premium. So it is hard to argue that the Cloud
Club should continue to stand as a time capsule.
</P>
<P>
   But the restoration of the space has drawn the wrath of the Art
Deco Society of New York, which said last month that Tishman Speyer
had ``substantially destroyed'' the Cloud Club's ``historically
significant interiors.''
</P>
<P>
   Tishman Speyer refused entry to a New York Times photographer,
saying that with the former Cloud Club under construction, pictures
would probably give a misleading impression of the condition of the
rooms. But Peltier said the Art Deco Society's charges were untrue,
and pointed out that the Cloud Club, unlike the Chrysler Building's
facade and lobby, was not a designated landmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was little worth restoring when we bought it, except for
the spectacular views,'' she said, ``but we're saving what's of
historical value.''
</P>
<P>
   Tishman Speyer replaced the cracked pane in that large dining
room window. It removed the huge mural of Manhattan painted on
canvas by Gardner Hale, and will soon decide where to donate it. It
left intact a mural, painted directly on a wall, that Peltier
described as ``an oil refinery, with machines and a truck with the
Texaco sign painted on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners also removed from Walter Chrysler's private dining
room on the 67th floor t(e bas-relief figures of auto workers,
including chemists, draftsmen, machinists, painters and, if the
rumors are to be believed, even Chrysler himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We restored them and put them in crates,'' Peltier said, ``and
are awaiting their rebirth in the walkway between the Chrysler
Building and the East Building.'' (The Chrysler Building and the
32-story East Building, formerly the Kent Building, make up what
was recently named the Chrysler Center.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of the most ardent fans of the Cloud Club and the Chrysler
Building is Dr. Charles M. Weiss, a dentist who has had offices in
the building for more than 30 years and recently signed a lease for
eight more years. For about a decade, Weiss rented the 56th floor,
which had been Chrysler's oak-paneled office, complete with private
kitchen and bath. Weiss' current floors, 69 and 70, were once
Chrysler's private gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Weiss keeps a scrapbook in his office full of rare
photographs, postcards and articles about the building and the
club. Weiss said many of his patients took cameras with them on
appointments. ``And if they come up here and it's cloudy,'' he
added, ``many of them ask if they can reschedule their appointment
for another day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
