<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, April 12, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   ASBESTOS-TREATMENT (Undated) _ For decades, patients who
contracted asbestosis were told there was nothing medical science
could do for them. You lingered for years while your lungs scarred
over. Eventually, you suffocated. Although millions of dollars have
been poured into asbestos litigation on all sides, and although
companies and unions have invested countless hours in asbestos
screenings, almost no money has gone into investigating treatments
or better ways to manage asbestos disease.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ASBESTOS-HAMMOND (Seattle) _ The effects of deadly asbestos
fibers often don't start showing up for 30 to 40 years after
exposure, so the threat may seem remote to workers and consumers
who may be at risk. But for Richard Hammond, 69, the risk has
become reality.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ASBESTOS-MAHANEY (Auburn, Wash.) _ Bill Mahaney, a longtime
horse owner, was diagnosed with asbestosis in 1988 from decades of
working in shipyards and as a lumber-mill supervisor. He still has
the heart for horses, but he doesn't have the lungs to train them
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   COCKPIT-CAMERAS (Undated) _ The National Transportation Safety
Board recommends that the FAA require cameras, not just voice
recorders, in cockpits. Pilots have fought moves in that direction
saying it violates their privacy and worry the tapes could show up
in the media as a plane goes down. But the safety board says the
cameras could provide valuable details on the cause of many
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
