<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CORNELIUS-CASINO-ART-     04-11 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORNELIUS-CASINO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL HIM LUCKY. OR ELVIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds: Neil M. Cornelius Jr. is the general manager of Treasure
Island Resort and Casino in Red Wing, Minn.) 
 By NEIL M. CORNELIUS JR. Written with DEIDRE LEIPZIGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's important to get opportunities, to see them and to take
them. It's also important to see that other people get
opportunities, too.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't grow up with a silver spoon by any stretch. My dad, an
auto mechanic, was from the Oneida Indian Nation, and my mother,
who was a teaching assistant in a local school, was from the
Stockbridge-Munsee Band of Mohican Indians, and they kind of raised
us in the middle, in Shawano, Wis. The town was predominantly
white, with Native American all around. I've always felt
comfortable in both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   I have eight siblings. My older sister Carol and I are the only
ones of the kids who went to college and graduate school. She's a
college professor. I don't know why we accomplished what we did,
but we somehow got the message that we needed to do something to
get out of the environment unless we wanted to repeat the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   I got lucky when I was 14 or so _ I got invited to join Upward
Bound, a government program for poor kids with some potential. I
got to be with other kids like myself. I got to see some successful
people, and I got some coaching. It got me to college. The Rev.
Jerry Thompson, who headed the program, is one of the biggest
influences in my life. He was a cheerleader and a spiritual leader
and a father figure. He particularly liked beating us at
racquetball.
</P>
<P>
   After college, I went to work for IBM, where my sister Carol was
working. She got me the job _ no, she got me the interview; I got
me the job, stocking computer parts. The big thing for me was to
work for IBM; I didn't care what job. I soon got the opportunity to
get a job as a computer repairman in Milwaukee. I didn't have any
experience, but I somehow got tabbed as a guy who could succeed.
Eventually, I got into management.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was great to me, and I was great to IBM. It was a great
marriage. But in my 20th year there, I realized I wasn't going to
be chairman. I decided to seek out more opportunity, and I wanted
to come back and work with my people. The timing was right, too:
IBM was downsizing, and they offered a silver parachute, so to
speak. I had a few dollars in my pocket and I was unemployed, so I
went back to school and got my master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   I was living in Boulder, Colo., and took a summer driving trip
with my son, seeing baseball games along the way. In Wisconsin, we
came to see family, too. One thing led to another, and soon I got a
job with the Oneida tribe as director of the enterprise division.
</P>
<P>
   Indian gaming came to town in the early 1980s, and things had
changed dramatically. For the better? Yes and no. It has enabled
many things for some tribes that didn't have anything _ schools,
infrastructure, housing, jobs. But many smaller tribes now have a
new kind of welfare: wealth without having to work. It's worse than
poverty without work.
</P>
<P>
   For my new job at the Treasure Island casino, which is owned by
the Prairie Island Indian Community, I live at the casino hotel in
Red Wing, Minn., during the week. I very much look forward to going
home to Green Bay on Friday. My family saves all my chores, of
course, but I'm a big Packers fan and if there's a game I get to
go.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough being away, but my job is extremely fulfilling. One
of the most fun times I ever had was about two years ago, when I
was the gaming general manager at Oneida. I did a sky dive with the
Flying Elvi _ those entertainers in Elvis costumes. I didn't get a
costume, but I did get pictures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
