<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3784 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TINA-TURNER12-COX     04-11 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINA-TURNER12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With diva on her final tour, we take a look at what we'll miss
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If only we could all retire like this: with a second home in the
south of France, a Bentley in the three-car garage and profits in
the bank from selling more than 50 million albums over the past 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention legs worth more than all that combined.
</P>
<P>
   Sigh. In December, Tina Turner announced that the tour that
stops in Atlanta tonight would be ``the biggest and the best
because it's the last.'' (``I know I have the energy to do it one
more time,'' she said. ``But I don't want to diminish the memory of
my great little dresses, my great legs.'')
</P>
<P>
   As if anything could! So we decided, instead of complaining,
we'll follow the 60-year-old pop singer's example. Hold our heads
up high. And fight back the years as we consider what we'll miss
the most.
</P>
<P>
   The music: Our favorite Tina Turner tape would have to start
with her first single ``A Fool in Love'' (1960). Then ``River Deep,
Mountain High'' (1966), to get things rolling. What next? Oh yeah,
the autobiographical ``Nutbush City Limits'' (1973) and that cover
of Al Green's ``Let's Stay Together'' (1983); followed by ``What's
Love Got to Do With It?'' ``Better Be Good to Me'' and the title
track from her breakthrough solo effort ``Private Dancer'' (1984).
Maybe ``We Don't Need Another Hero'' (1985) from the soundtrack of
the post-apocalyptic Mel Gibson movie ``Mad Max Beyond
Thunderdome.'' But definitely, definitely, the last song would be
her remake of Creedence Clearwater Revival's ``Proud Mary'' (1971).
Why? Because we like it rough and easy on one song.
</P>
<P>
   The unforgettable performances: You have to start with that
hip-shaking and fringe-moving Tina did with her backup singers, the
Ikettes, back when the Ike and Tina Turner Revue hit TV _
``American Bandstand,'' to be exact _ in the mid-'60s. And who can
forget the vamp she did with Mick Jagger at 1985's ``Live Aid''
benefit? Her Grammy Awards performance that same year of ``What's
Love Got to Do With It?'' was the big triumph, though. (She also
took home four Grammys). And don't forget the January 1988 show she
did for 182,000 in Rio de Janeiro _ it was the largest paying
audience ever to gather for a single performer, which got her in
the Guiness Book of World Records until 1990, when Paul McCartney
broke her record.
</P>
<P>
   The way she bridged genres: Turner's edge, coupled with her
church upbringing, helped R&AMP;B and rock converge in the '60s and
'70s. In the '80s, she helped create an atmosphere in which those
distinctions didn't matter so much. Before ``Private Dancer,'' she
collaborated with former members of British new wave bands Human
League and Heaven 17. Jeff Beck showed up on ``Private Dancer,''
while that album's title cut was written by Dire Straits frontman
Mark Knopfler. Colorblind and uncategorizable as either rock or
R&AMP;B, it was just good music.
</P>
<P>
   The Ike factor: She left her first husband _ an alleged abuser _
with 36 cents and a gasoline card in her pocket. But she still
credits the formidable guitarist with discovering her when her
older sister Alline refused to sing for his Kings of Rhythm one
night. He also changed Anna Mae Bullock's name to Tina. (Never mind
that he did so because it reminded him of Sheena, queen of the
jungle, from the TV series.) He's also the man behind those
infamous wigs. And by first taking her out on the road in 1960 as
part of the Ike and Tina Turner Revue, Ike can be credited with
officially introducing her to us.
</P>
<P>
   Er, some of the movies: Her turn as the Acid Queen in the '70s
film version of the Who's rock opera ``Tommy'' was a great screen
debut. But that pairing with Mel Gibson as Aunty Entity in ``Mad
Max Beyond the Thunderdome,'' well, hmmm...
</P>
<P>
   And though she personally had a problem with the film adaptation
of her autobiography (``It didn't show my strength,'' Turner told
one newspaper. ``(It) went all `Superfly' into drugs and the
ugliness'') there's no way we can ignore Angela Bassett and
Laurence Fishburne's dynamic performances in ``What's Love Got to
Do With It?''
</P>
<P>
   That accent: So what if she was born in Brownsville, Tenn., and
raised in the city limits of Nutbush. Her primary home has been
overseas for more than a decade (Zurich, with longtime
boyfriend/record executive Erwin Bach) and her speaking voice has
long had the clipped and proper British affectations to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   The persona: Tina's arrival in pop music did a whole lot for
women in music at a time when most of them _ particularly black
women _ were of the sweet, production-line, girl group variety.
(The exception, of course, being Aretha Franklin.) Her long hair,
gyrating dance moves and raucous smirk had middle America hot and
bothered, and broke down race barriers with pure seduction. Her
confidence was also attractive to women, who _ particularly in the
'60s _ weren't used to another woman grabbing the microphone by the
collar and giving it a good talking-to.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, those legs: Not only are they insured by Lloyd's
of London for a reported $3.2 million, but in 1996 they snared her
a hefty endorsement contract with hosiery giant Hanes _ and the
envy of younger and older women alike.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Miriam Longino and Shane Harrison contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   To hear selections from recordings by Tina Turner, dial 511 and
enter 8600 and Soundline number 421. Each call costs 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B: For more about Tina Turner: www.tina-turner.com
</P>
<P>
   Tina Turner with Lionel Richie. 7:30 tonight at Philips Arena, 1
Philips Drive N.W. Atlanta, $35.25, $55.25 and $79.25.
404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
