<HEADLINE>
HOME DEPOT EMPLOYS OLYMPIC ATHLETES FOR MUSCLE AND MORALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphics are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Olympic Games open in Australia this summer,
about 30 athletes will represent Egypt. Sixty will make up the
contingent from Turkey. Eighty will run, jump, swim and play for
Ireland. Nearly 100 will make up the delegation from Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   The company's orange logo will not appear on the the Olympic
athletes' uniforms, of course, and television commentators probably
won't even mention the giant retailer's name. But in cities and
towns around North America, thousands of Home Depot employees will
stay up late to root for the athletes on TV and get up the next
morning to devour the accounts of their exploits in the sports
pages.
</P>
<P>
   That, it turns out, is the audience Home Depot executives are
trying to reach. When a company employs 210,000 people in an
industry with one of the highest turnover rates in the country _ in
the midst of one of the tightest job markets in more than three
decades _ it does what it has to do to hold onto every last one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   So, at a cost of several million dollars, Home Depot has hired
116 Olympic athletes from the United States, Canada and Puerto Rico
_ more than all the other 50 or so companies in the official
Olympic Games jobs program employ combined _ to pace its floors and
advise customers on everything from screws to lawn mowers. It is
using their presence not to increase sales in a national
advertising campaign, but to pump up employee morale.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In this economy, in other words, the imperatives of management
can trump the demands of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot has spread the 116 Olympic contenders among its 958
North American stores, where local managers enlist them to motivate
employees and attract new ones. The athletes autograph their
colleagues' aprons, and those who have won medals show them off at
company parties. Company managers point to the athletes as
real-life examples of corporate nostrums like ``going for the
gold'' and ``giving it your all.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Hammill, Home Depot's senior vice president for marketing,
who oversees the program from company headquarters in Atlanta, said
of the athletes: ``They're disciplined. They're on time. They work
hard. It rubs off.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Home Depot athletes will fail to qualify for the
Sydney games. But because national Olympic committees require that
athletes be highly ranked in order to participate in the jobs
program, most should qualify, officials said. Ranging from
unheralded rowers and wrestlers to stars like the runner Butch
Reynolds, the athletes work about 20 hours a week for about $400
and spend the rest of their time training.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies in the jobs program, like United Parcel Service,
have run TV ads promoting their athletes to the general public. In
contrast, Home Depot is only now planning its first commercial
starring one of its Olympians _ and the setting is expected to be a
send-off party a store gives to wish good luck to an athlete on the
way to an event.
</P>
<P>
   So intent is Home Depot on finding qualified employees that it
has even made some of its commercials the equivalent of help-wanted
ads. Earlier this year, for example, it began broadcasting a spot
that showed employees and ended with the words, ``The Home Depot.
Great Careers Built Here.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are pursuing a similar strategy. Last year,
McDonald's ran a television ad, set to feel-good music, in which
captions like ``future software engineer'' and ``future elementary
school teacher'' appeared under its young burger flippers. At
Hewlett-Packard, Carleton S. Fiorina, the chief executive, has said
that a primary target of its current television campaign that
describes the company as ``the original start-up'' is the company's
work force, which could be easy pickings for dot-com firms.
</P>
<P>
   A host of companies, including both Home Depot and Microsoft,
are starting to use outdoor billboards to seek job candidates.
Around the country, spending on help-wanted billboards almost
tripled last year, to $16 million, according to the Outdoor
Advertising Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot, however, is in a category all its own. At a time
when few skilled workers remain unemployed, it aims to more than
double its current payroll, to nearly 500,000, within four years.
That is a monumental task for a company in a traditional field that
pays entry-level employees about $10 an hour to perform work that
can be both exhausting and repetitive.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain the gung-ho workplace culture that many experts say
has helped fuel its remarkable growth, it has had to attack the
great bane of retailers: high employee turnover. For years,
executives have held pep rallies and allowed store managers to
spend the company's charity money on local causes that are often
dear to the hearts of employees. ``It's the internal people that
are the target'' of many Home Depot initiatives, said Frederick F.
Reichheld, a consultant at Bain &AMP; Co. and author of ``The Loyalty
Effect'' (Harvard Business School Press, 1996) who has studied the
company.
</P>
<P>
   That is the rationale behind the company's Olympic sponsorship.
The retailer paid $40 million to sign up as a sponsor eight years
ago, when Atlanta was getting ready to be host of the 1996 Summer
Olympics and the company was expanding across the country, Hammill
said. By the time the Atlanta games opened, Home Depot had more
than 90 American athletes on its payroll. Combining results from
the Atlanta games and the 1994 and 1998 Winter Olympics, its
athletes have won 16 gold medals, six silvers and nine bronzes _
more medals in the four-year span than Belgium, Denmark or Britain
has brought home. In the last two years, the company has created
similar versions of the jobs program in Canada and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   For all the glory that the Home Depot athletes aspire to, they
follow a pretty ordinary workplace routine. On a recent Wednesday,
27-year-old Derek Mills, a runner, spent the morning and early
afternoon stocking shelves and answering questions in the
electrical department of the store in Alpharetta, Ga., an Atlanta
suburb. Wearing his orange Home Depot apron with ``Hi, I'm Derek''
emblazoned in the upper right corner, he paused at one point to
tell a colleague using a forklift that he was about to bump against
a ceiling lamp and send a stack of outdoor barbecue grills tumbling
to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   There was little to suggest that Mills was the owner of a gold
medal for the 1996 400-meter relay _ until one of his colleagues
walked by and said, ``Hey, Speedy!''
</P>
<P>
   The nickname is apt, in more ways than one. Within an hour,
Mills was driving 25 miles to a training session on the campus of
Georgia Tech, where he received an engineering degree in 1995. The
next day, he was crossing the Atlantic, off to Glasgow, Scotland,
for an indoor track and field competition.
</P>
<P>
   Like other athletes in the Olympic jobs program, Mills continues
drawing his pay when he is on the road. It is a perquisite that
participants, injury-prone and financially strapped as many of them
are, greatly treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, for example, has suffered nagging hamstring and Achilles'
tendon injuries over the last three years, making it more difficult
for him to earn appearance fees at track meets. ``It's not the
early stages for my career anymore,'' he said ruefully.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   For athletes in less lucrative sports, the wages can make an
even bigger difference. ``I would not be training if I didn't have
this job; it's too much of a struggle,'' said Julia Chilicki, 28, a
rower who was in the 1996 Olympics and recently transferred from a
Home Depot in Massachusetts to one in Georgia so she could train
with her team.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot is one of the few big successes that the Olympic jobs
program can claim. J.C. Penney, part of the program since its
founding in 1977, now has 16 athletes on its payroll. But all other
companies in the program limit themselves to just a few athletes,
given their unpredictable schedules and the prospect of paying them
for hours they do not work.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many of the 600 American athletes who will be in
Sydney _ as well as hundreds of others who are training but will
fail to qualify _ cobble together part-time jobs and appearance
fees to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In return for their pay, Home Depot's athletes take a public
role as company cheerleaders. Mills, for example, went to his
store's annual party last year dressed in his track uniform and
with his gold medal hanging around his neck. ``He let everybody
touch it,'' said Craig Denton, a colleague who himself was a member
of the Olympic jobs program as a kayaker.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Mills also starred in a mock newscast that was broadcast to all
210,000 employees in advance of a recent videotaped speech by
Arthur Blank, chief executive of Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The company's generosity toward its Olympic athletes _ paying
them a week's wages for half a week's work and keeping the checks
coming when they are traveling _ clearly has the potential for
creating resentment among the rank and file. That has not happened,
employees say, largely because the regular workers look up to the
athletes and realize how hard they have to work at their training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years from now, I may be able to tell my kids I knew someone
who won an Olympic medal,'' said Richard Faber, who works alongside
Colleen Rosensteel, a member of the women's judo team, in Palatine,
Ill. ``Everybody's living a little vicariously through Colleen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
