<HEADER>
A3789 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-ASSET-FORFEITURE-NYT     04-11 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSET-FORFEITURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS APPROVES BILL MAKING IT HARDER FOR PROSECUTORS TO SEIZE
PROPERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following years of complaints of abusive government
conduct, Congress completed legislation Tuesday that would make it
harder for government officials to confiscate property before they
actually bring criminal charges in narcotics, terrorism,
racketeering and other cases.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that President Clinton would sign
the legislation, a compromise measure approved unanimously by a
voice vote of the House of Representatives on Tuesday and by the
Senate two weeks ago. The new law adds significant safeguards that
will make it more difficult for prosecutors to seize homes, money,
cars, boats and other property before trials begin. But it also
expands the government's authority to both discover tainted assets
and confiscate property after convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court and other courts have criticized the
current law, saying that lax standards had repeatedly permitted
prosecutors to confiscate assets of innocent people long before
criminal trials began. Congressional hearings had documented many
instances where the asset seizures had created enormous hardships
and required onerous litigation in order to try to win back money,
cars, homes and businesses that were never part of any criminal
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., the chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee who introduced the first bill to change forfeiture laws
seven years ago, said that the legislation approved Tuesday, which
he had co-sponsored, struck a fair balance between protecting
property owners while continuing to permit the government to
confiscate assets upon proving that they may have been part of a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is one we can all be proud of,'' Hyde said. ``It
returns civil asset forfeiture to the ranks of respected law
enforcement tools that can be used without risk to the civil
liberties and property rights of American citizens. We are all
better off that this is so.''
</P>
<P>
   The laws that were amended Tuesday were enacted as part of a
trend that began 30 years ago to expand the authority of law
enforcement at the height of what were then called the wars on
drugs and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Those laws were challenged this term in Congress by a remarkable
coalition of liberal and conservative lawmakers and a diverse array
of organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The groups critical of the current law included the American
Civil Liberties Union, the National Rifle Association, the American
Bankers Association, the National Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, the Americans for Tax
Reform, and pilot, boating, hotel and housing organizations.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the groups generally applauded Congress Tuesday
for taking an important first step in making it more difficult for
the government to confiscate assets without sufficient evidence of
wrongdoing, some said further legislation was necessary to remedy
the abuses that had already been documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is so bad that even modest reforms are
important,'' said Rachel King, legislative counsel of the American
Civil Liberties Union. ``We think this just begins to address the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation both flips the burden of proof to the government
and raises the legal standard for seizures prior to conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Under the existing law, once the government makes a relatively
low showing of probable cause that the property is subject to civil
forfeiture, the same standard required for a search warrant, the
onus shifts to the owner to establish that the property is
``innocent.'' Codified into federal law, the standard has its roots
in a legal fiction that an inanimate object can itself be
``guilty'' of wrongdoing, a fiction that grew out of English common
law and was adopted by the First Congress in 1789.
</P>
<P>
   Since the standard for confiscating property remains so low, an
owner is not automatically entitled to a return of confiscated
property even if he is ultimately acquitted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, the government can confiscate property only
if it first shows there was a substantial connection between the
property and the crime ``by preponderance of the evidence,'' a
higher burden than probable cause.
</P>
<P>
   The new law also expands possible defenses, awards lawyers fees
to owners who successfully challenge the seizure of their property,
and provides government-paid lawyers to indigent property owners in
many instances. It allows federal judges to release property to the
owner if the government possession causes substantial hardship to
the owner and extends the time a property owner has to challenge
the seizure of an asset.
</P>
<P>
   It also eliminates a provision that had required owners of
confiscated property to post a bond when they tried to contest the
forfeiture.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation also offers some benefits to law enforcement
officials, which was necessary to win the support from the Justice
Department. It will make it easier, for instance, for prosecutors
to seize property after convictions. It also eases the statute of
limitations in criminal forfeiture actions; sets up a new procedure
for federal courts to enforce forfeiture judgments of foreign
nations; and gives the government greater access to financial
records in instances where the property may be held in secret
accounts overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Those provisions helped the chief sponsors of the legislation _
Reps. Hyde and John Conyers, D-Mich., in the House and Sens. Orrin
G. Hatch, R-Utah, and Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., in the Senate _ to
win the support of the Clinton administration. At the urging of the
Justice Department and local law enforcement groups, the White
House had opposed legislation that had overwhelmingly passed the
House last June that would have imposed even more restraints on law
enforcement authorities.
</P>
<P>
   That legislation had required the government to prove that the
assets in question were part of a criminal scheme by ``clear and
convincing evidence,'' a higher standard than the ``preponderance''
test adopted Tuesday. The Senate ultimately watered down the
measure, added new provisions that the Justice Department had
sought, and adopted it by voice vote last month following little
debate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
