<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE SLAMS BRAKES ON EFFORT TO REPEAL FEDERAL GAS TAX 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate turned aside an effort Tuesday to repeal
4.3 cents of the federal gasoline tax, as Republican lawmakers
sought to use the April 17 income tax filing deadline to promote
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The gas tax repeal measure failed by a vote of 56-43 in the wake
of the decision by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries to increase production, a move that is expected to lower
costs at the pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., criticized the vote
as short-sighted, insisting that prices would rise again despite
the OPEC action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that gas prices are going to go up, and in fact we're
going to be more dependent on foreign oil,'' Lott said, calling on
his colleagues to begin working on a comprehensive energy strategy
that will reduce the nation's dependence on foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not this, what, and if not now, when?'' Lott asked.
``There's a danger here and we need to find a way to address it.''
</P>
<P>
   The gas tax repeal legislation was the first tax issue to be
brought up this week by Republican leaders who traditionally have
sought to use the annual income tax filing deadline as a way to
focus attention on their calls for lower federal taxes of all
kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Before the week is out, Senate Republicans led by Kay Bailey
Hutchison of Texas hope to force a vote on a measure eliminating
the so-called marriage tax penalty, which would cut taxes by an
estimated $248 billion over the next 10 years for qualifying
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Texas, is trying to focus attention on tax issues in a
series of hearings dealing with alternative proposals to the
current income tax system. The alternatives include a flat tax
measured favored by House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, and
a national sales tax, which Archer has been pushing for years.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders also planned to hold a series of mostly symbolic
votes on measures that have little chance of becoming law, but will
give Republicans an opportunity to show their support in an
election year for reducing taxes. The measures scheduled for debate
include a constitutional amendment requiring a two-thirds vote of
Congress to enact any new tax increases, and a measure that would
end the current tax code in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Topping off Republican efforts to highlight tax issues, Senate
Commerce Committee Chairman and former GOP presidential candidate
John McCain of Arizona planned to hold a hearing on a bill that
would extend the moratorium on internet transaction taxes for
another five years.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the airing of different tax measures, the heart of
the Republican effort this week is centered on the marriage rule,
which taxes some married couples filing jointly at a higher rate
than couples with the same income who file separately.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison has practically turned the effort to eliminate the
marriage penalty into a personal crusade, taking the lead on the
issue in the Senate. She called on her colleagues Tuesday to
approve her measure before Congress adjourns for a two-week Easter
holiday recess Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She planned to highlight what she called the ``inequities'' of
the marriage penalty at a news conference Wednesday, complete with
a wedding cake to make her point that couples should not be
penalized for making one of the most important decisions of their
life.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty legislation is just one of several
provisions that were part of the failed $792 billion GOP tax cut
bill that Clinton vetoed last year and are now being recast as
separate measures to put pressure on the Democrats in an election
year.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats agree that voting against the Hutchison bill
could be a risky move. But Clinton has vowed to veto the measure,
and polls still indicate that most Americans are more interested in
paying down the debt and increasing funding for education and other
important programs than getting a tax break.
</P>
<P>
   That view, coupled with falling gasoline prices, enabled
opponents of the gas tax repeal to turn back an attempt by Lott on
Tuesday to force an up-or-down vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   If it had been approved, the bill would have temporarily rolled
back the 4.3 cents of the 18.4 cent federal tax on a gallon of
gasoline through the end of the year. The measure was opposed by
all 45 Democrats and a number of Republicans, who argued that it
would jeopardize the Highway Trust Fund, which uses the gas tax to
help states pay for the upkeep and modernization of the nation's
roads.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have replenished lost trust fund revenues from
this year's estimated budget surpluses. But Sen. John Warner,
R-Va., said that idea would set ``a dangerous precedent'' of trying
to finance programs with surpluses that do not yet exist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
