<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY SHARES CONTINUE SHARP FALL; BLUE CHIPS RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks were hammered again Tuesday, pulled
lower by disappointing reports from Motorola and Biogen.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 3.2 percent, or 132.30 points,
to 4,055.90. By the close of trading the index was lower than at
the start of the year, and nearly 20 percent below the peak reached
on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, money continued to move into blue chip stocks from
technology companies that carry much higher price to earnings
ratios.
</P>
<P>
   Helped by strong gains in stocks like Alcoa and Minnesota Mining
&AMP; Manufacturing, the Dow Jones industrial average gained 100.52
points, or 0.9 percent, to 11,287.08. The Dow, which gained 75
points on Monday, is now down less than 2 percent from its closing
level on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``When sentiment has turned against technology, old-line stocks
come to the fore,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, a market analyst at
Prudential Securities. ``There is no reason to think that this time
is any different.''
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which has traded in a
very narrow range so far this month, did so again Tuesday. It
dropped 3.87 points, or 0.3 percent, to 1,500.59.
</P>
<P>
   Gains in stocks like General Electric, Bristol-Myers Squibb and
American International Group mostly offset a disastrous performance
by Motorola, and weakness in technology bellwethers Cisco Systems
and Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday's trading, analysts said the reaction to a
first quarter earnings report from Motorola would likely dictate
the direction for technology shares. Motorola's earnings were very
good _ more than double what the mobile telephone maker earned in
the same period last year. But in a conference call with analysts
before the market opened Tuesday, the company warned that second
quarter earnings will fall short of Wall Street forecasts. The
comments triggered a sell-off in computer and telecommunications
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, a component of the S&AMP;P 500, fell 27 Tuesday, to 124.
</P>
<P>
   And biotechnology stocks were slammed in reaction to Biogen's
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's market close, the company reported first quarter
profits that missed Wall Street estimates by one cent a share,
partly because of lower-than-expected sales of Avonex, its multiple
sclerosis drug.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings report dragged down the Nasdaq's biotechnology
index by 3.4 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen closed at 53, down 12. But Genentech lost 20, to 136{; PE
Corp Celera fell 11[, to 88~; and Millenium Pharmaceuticals slumped
15{, to 134.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp slide in technology share prices has happened quickly,
but analysts noted that the spring and summer quarters have
traditionally been difficult months for technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   And they expressed doubt about the conviction of the move into
well known blue-chip stocks, which for all the safety they may
provide do not offer the growth potential of technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some think this might be an important secular shift,'' said
Greg Smith, chief investment strategist at Prudential Securities.
``But in fact this is pretty normal seasonal stuff. The only thing
unusual about this is that it started about a week early.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems was the most active Nasdaq stock Tuesday. The
stock fell 2 9/16, to 70 a share. Since it peaked on March 27,
shares of Cisco have fallen by nearly 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa, the Dow's best performer last year, led the blue chip
index up. It gained 2 11/16, to 70].
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
