<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES FALL SHARPLY, PUZZLING ANALYSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury prices dropped sharply Tuesday, puzzling
some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, everybody is scratching their heads,''
said Thomas Connor, head government trader at J.P. Morgan
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's selling, which followed a short rally in the morning,
was across the board in the Treasury market and came as the Nasdaq
composite index dropped 3.2 percent. In the last couple of weeks,
as investors sold stocks in the technology-heavy Nasdaq index, many
of them took the money and put it into the Treasury market, often a
haven for worried investors.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond fell 1.46, to 106.94. The
bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price,
rose to 5.76 percent, from 5.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 10-year note fell as the yield rose to 5.87
percent, from 5.77 percent, and the yield on the Treasuries
two-year note climbed to 6.33 percent from 6.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for the bond's decline was a shift by investors
from longer-term Treasuries into corporate bonds and debt of the
two government-sponsored agencies, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac,
which help finance home mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said that these two markets had fared so poorly compared
with Treasuries in the last several months that they may suddenly
have become attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-March, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac debt has been under
extra pressure because of the Treasury Department's support for a
proposal to strip the two of some of their tax and regulatory
advantages over investment and commercial banks. One advantage is a
conditional line of credit from the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of Treasuries against other fixed-income markets
is measured in the difference _ or spread _ between the yields on
comparable maturities. When that spread widens it means that
Treasuries are outperforming the other markets. For example, the
spread between 10-year Treasury notes and 10-year Fannie Mae notes
was under one percentage point in mid-March. But during trading
Tuesday it was as high as 1.3 percentage points in the morning,
before agency and corporate bond markets rallied.
</P>
<P>
   Late in trading, the spread on 10-year Fannie Mae notes had
narrowed to 1.20 percentage points, from 1.23 percentage points
Monday. The spread on 10-year corporate bonds with a double A
credit rating had narrowed to 1.30 percentage points, from 1.32
percentage points Monday and a high of 1.41 percentage points early
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors were taking advantage of the ever widening spread
between agencies and Treasuries'' said Kevin Flanagan, money market
economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. But he said it was too
early to say that the negative sentiment toward Fannie Mae and
Freddie Mac generated by the threat from the Treasury had changed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in congressional testimony Tuesday, Rep. Richard Baker,
a Republican from Louisiana and sponsor of legislation to tighten
regulation of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, compared the financial
risk from the growth of these two agencies with that posed by the
near-collapse of the hedge fund Long Term Capital Management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
