<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3815 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BIGDIG-ANLYSIS-BOS &LR;      04-11 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-ANLYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CRITICAL DECISION FOR A BESIEGED GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In what could prove to be the most important decision
of his term, Governor Paul Cellucci has turned to Andrew Natsios,
his highly trusted and oldest political friend, to bail out the Big
Dig.
</P>
<P>
   But Natsios has another mission, one perhaps as important to the
governor: help salvage Cellucci's political career and save his
administration from being swallowed up by the biggest public works
project in the country.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the Big Dig debacle has put Cellucci on the
defensive, eroded his once-strong standing in the polls, and raised
questions about his ability to lead the state. His political future
in Massachusetts _ and, some say, his potential for landing an
administration job should George W. Bush reach the White House _ is
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   By firing James Kerasiotes as the project leader Tuesday,
Cellucci made a move that he and his aides hope will stop the
free-fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a great weight being lifted,'' said one top
administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the public, inundated for months with dire predictions
of huge cost overruns, incendiary headlines, and talk-show bombast,
seemed to anticipate sweeping changes.
</P>
<P>
   The central political issue, however, is twofold: can public
confidence in the Big Dig _ and, ultimately, the Cellucci
governorship _ still be restored? And is Natsios the man to do it?
</P>
<P>
   Todd Domke, a Republican political consultant and a sometime
critic of the Weld and Cellucci administrations, says Natsios has
the integrity and political skills to handle both jobs. Domke,
however, feel the stakes go beyond Cellucci's own political future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether the Massachusetts Republican Party,
which depends on its image as a fiscally responsible party for its
credibility, can recover from these events,'' Domke said.
</P>
<P>
   For Cellucci, much depends on how well he can rebound from a
dismal fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   From the ``booze cruise'' scandal at Massport to the turbulence
that rocked Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift, Cellucci has
increasingly appeared indecisive and his administration seems
adrift, allowing other Beacon Hill figures to fill the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas Reilly, a Democrat trying to establish
himself on Beacon Hill, has earned credit for resolving the Harvard
Pilgrim financial meltdown and pursuing tougher state gun control
laws. Secretary of State William F. Galvin, too, has easily moved
in on issues well within the governor's reach, from price controls
on prescription drugs for seniors to a crackdown on unscrupulous
lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Big Dig crises has added to the perception that the
governor is neither bold nor innovative.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, his shakeup of Big Dig management Tuesday had some
dramatic moments, but it was hardly breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   Firing Kerasiotes was easy: he had inadvertently insulted
Cellucci in print and had become a symbol of the administration's
declining credibility, a serious political liablity for a governor
who was fast losing the public's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But it would not have been any easier had Cellucci moved more
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the financial disaster, most close observers and even
his enemies agree that Kerasiotes has managed the massive, complex
project relatively well. He is highly regarded in the Boston
business community, whose leadership is concerned with his firing.
</P>
<P>
   Administration sources said Kerasiotes had also earned
considerable political capital with Cellucci and former Governor
William F. Weld through the years; their confidence in him ran
deep, and aides said Cellucci personally likes him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone realized Jim had a tough job and he was cut a lot of
slack,'' said one administration insider. ``There was a feeling of,
`Let Jim be Jim,' and let him get the project done. We need a real
jerk to manage this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the relationship between Kerasiotes and Cellucci had
become strained in recent days as details of the federal audit
emerged. Some aides to the governor said Cellucci was not pleased
at Kerasiotes' moves to save his own job, including attempts to
prevent himself from being barred from federal projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was unauthorized,'' said one aide.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Cellucci's political problems will continue. The
scapegoat may be gone, but the residual bad feelings among the
public still linger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
