<HEADLINE>
RENO GOING TO MIAMI TO SEEK SOLUTION TO DISPUTE OVER CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno prepared to fly to
Miami Wednesday to play a personal role in resolving the dispute
over Elian Gonzalez, intensifying the drama over the boy's fate and
raising the stakes for everyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said Tuesday that Reno would meet
with Cuban-American leaders in Miami, federal authortities who have
been negotiating Elian's fate, and probably with the Gonzalez
relatives who have had custody over the 6-year-old refugee since he
was rescued off the Florida coast last November.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said Reno would not haggle with anyone over the
terms or timing of Elian's reunification with his father, but
wanted to personally explain the US government's position to
Cuban-Americans and ask them to make the process as peaceful as
possible. A letter was to have been delivered Tuesday night to the
Miami relatives laying out the Justice Department's demands for
where and when it wants them to surrender the boy.
</P>
<P>
   By physically placing herself into the center of the
controversy, Reno not only puts her prestige on the line, but also
raises expectations that a resolution may be imminent. Her presence
also seems certain to trigger street demonstrations by a Cuban
exile community that considers her an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Reno's personal involvement also applies
pressure on the Cuban-Americans, including Elian's relatives in
Miami, because they will literally be seen as bucking the authority
of the chief US law-enforcement officer if they do not comply with
whatever demands she makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agreed that helping to bring the family together to
work out this orderly transition would be desirable, but I also
stressed that the transfer of Elian to the care of his father must
move forward without delay,'' Reno said in a statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was issued after she met with two mayors from South Florida
who proposed that any transfer of custody take place over a
monthlong period to ease the emotional transition for the boy. They
also urged that Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, work out
reunification and custody arrangements himself during a meeting
with the Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives floated a similar plan Tuesday. Outside their
Little Havana home, they distributed copies of a letter they had
sent to a government-appointed psychiatrist with whom they had met
Monday. In it, they suggested a two-stage meeting with Juan
Gonzalez at a ``neutral'' spot in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   First, they said, they wanted to meet with Elian's father alone,
presumably to try to persuade him to stay in the United States or,
at least, not to take his son back to Cuba. It would be followed
``almost immediately by a meeting to include Elian,'' said the
letter, which was signed by the boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The family also sent a letter to President Clinton late Monday
asking him to issue an order himself to prevent Elian from leaving
this country until a federal appeals court hears the case next
month.
</P>
<P>
   While the relatives' tone remained defiant, their apparent
willingness to discuss the terms of a relinquishment indicated that
they perceive a conclusion is drawing near. The mood in the crowd
outside the family's home reflected a similar sense of resignation,
even as the demonstrators continued to wave placards denouncing the
Clinton administration and demanding that Elian have his day in
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be the voice of Elian's mother, no matter what,''
said Maria Cancio, 27, whose son is about the same age as Elian.
``I know deep down inside that the father wants his child to stay.
I know what it looks like, but we can't give up yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The relatives, who are trying various legal maneuvers to keep
Elian in the United States, filed a brief in Miami Family Court
Tuesday asking for a hearing to determine whether Juan Gonzalez is
fit to raise his son. They alleged that the father had ``enagaged
in abusive conduct'' _ a charge his attorney and US officials
adamantly deny _ and that the boy could be subjected to ``imminent
indoctrination'' if he went back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government asked the court to dismiss the request,
saying a state judge has no jurisdiction to overrule federal
immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Lynda Gorov of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
