<SLUG> BC-RITEAID-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RITE AID REFINANCES DEBT, AT A SUBSTANTIAL COST 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rite Aid Corp., having failed to find buyers for its PCS
Health Systems subsidiary, announced a plan Tuesday to refinance
its debt for more than two years, giving it access to more than
$640 million in additional funds. The deal came at a cost of higher
interest rates on some of its borrowings and substantial dilution
for its stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a solution that is good for everybody,'' said
Bob Miller, who was hired away from the Kroger Co. in December to
become the new chief executive of Rite Aid, a chain of 3,800 drug
stores that has been buffeted by problems for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Citibank, Fleet Retail Finance and Heller
Financial will provide a $1 billion credit facility, maturing on
Aug. 1, 2002. Of that, $60 million will go for expenses connected
with the refinancing and $300 million will go to repay another debt
issue, leaving the company with $640 million in additional cash.
</P>
<P>
   Other loans will also be extended until 2002 if the refinancing
plan wins approval from all the company's lenders, something Miller
said he was confident would occur. Miller said he had prepared a
plan to get the company back on its feet by then, but declined to
give details.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual twist, the company's offer to exchange new
securities for $350 million of publicly held junk bonds will be
made only to institutional investors. Individuals who own the bonds
and are not eligible to buy private offerings will not be able to
make the exchange, although they could sell their bonds to an
institutional investor.
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid has been in turmoil since last spring, when the
company's auditors at KPMG forced the company to report lower
earnings for 1999 than had been previously announced. The audit
firm later resigned, saying it had no confidence in the company's
management, and the management team was forced to resign. The
company's new auditor, Deloitte and Touche, is expected to produce
audited financial statements for the last three years by July 11.
</P>
<P>
   When Miller took over, his immediate plan was to sell PCS, which
administers pharmacy benefits for health plans, for at lest $1.3
billion, and use the money to pay down debt. But Tuesday he said
that while the company ``will continue to explore opportunities to
sell PCS at some point,'' the price the company could get for PCS
now was ``very depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan announced Tuesday involves J.P. Morgan exchanging $200
million in bank debt for Rite Aid common stock, at $5.50 a share,
and allows other banks to convert as much as $85 million in loans
to common stock at the same price. Last October, Leonard Green and
Partners purchased $300 million of convertible preferred stock,
which was to be convertible at about $7.50 a share. The conversion
price on that issue would be reduced to $5.50 under this plan.
</P>
<P>
   If all the conversions are completed, the banks and Leonard
Green would wind up owning about 29 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid shares, which sold for as much as $51.125 in January
1999, rose $1.625 to $7.3125 Tuesday in New York Stock Exchange
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the first Rite Aid debts that would come due
would be the new $1 billion facility, which would mature on Aug. 1,
2002, two weeks before the other bank debts would mature and one
and one-half months before the company's extended junk bonds would
come due. The new facility would also be secured by the company's
inventory and receivables, giving the lenders a better chance of
being repaid even if efforts to turn around Rite Aid do not bear
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The two junk bonds being refinanced are an issue of $200 million
of 5.5 percent notes that are due in December and an issue of $350
million of 6.7 percent notes due in December 2001. The latter issue
was sold to public investors, although most of the bonds are held
by institutional investors, including junk bond mutual funds. The
offer calls for the interest rates on the deals to be raised to
about 10.5 percent, and the maturity extended to Sept. 15, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The notes due in 2001 had traded on Monday at 62.5 percent of
par value, said one trader. The bid rose to 76 percent of par value
Tuesday. The 2000 notes, which had been bid at 75 percent of par
value on Monday, rose to a bid of 82 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The differing bids for the issues, which are to be exchanged for
identical notes, may have indicated some hope that holders of the
December 2000 issue, with its earlier maturity date, might be in a
position to hold out for better terms.
</P>
<P>
   The new notes will be issued under Rule 144a of the Securities
and Exchange Commission, which allows unregistered securities to be
sold to qualified institutions and to certain wealthy individuals.
The notes evidently cannot be registered, as would be required if
they were to be offered to all holders, because the company has no
audited financial statements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
