<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-ENGINEERING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON SEEKING BUYER FOR ENGINEERING, CONSTRUCTION UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. is in talks to sell or spin off its troubled
engineering and construction division, setting aside previous
pledges that it would hang on to the unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington, Mass. defense contractor also warned Tuesday that
the division would report an operating loss in the first quarter,
the latest in a series of earnings disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts approved of Raytheon's steps to dispose of the
Cambridge, Mass. engineering division, known as Raytheon Engineers
&AMP; Constructors, or RE&AMP;C, as a way to raise cash and pay down debt.
RE&AMP;C last year had an operating loss of $61 million on revenue of
$2.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon wouldn't say with whom it is holding talks, though
speculation centered on Morrison Knudsen Corp. in Boise, Idaho.
Morrison Knudsen did not return messages seeking comment. Raytheon
said it is also considering setting up a joint venture with another
company to run RE&AMP;C.
</P>
<P>
   Few have seen RE&AMP;C as a good fit with Raytheon's major aerospace
and defense business lines, and pressure to sell it has mounted
since Raytheon disclosed an order slowdown and other problems last
fall, causing its stock to drop sharply.
</P>
<P>
   But RE&AMP;C had symbolic importance for Raytheon and its chief
executive, Daniel Burnham, who made improving the unit's
performance a chief goal when he took over at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pressure from investors, Raytheon had insisted for
months that it wasn't seeking a buyer for RE&AMP;C and that the unit
could prosper under its new top officer, Shay Assad.
</P>
<P>
   But Burnham shifted gears Tuesday and said in a statement that
while ``RE&AMP;C has growth potential within certain markets,'' it ``is
not central to Raytheon's strategy. A sale, joint venture, or
spin-off of RE&AMP;C is in the best interests of Raytheon shareholders
and RE&AMP;C.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Burnham wouldn't elaborate and wouldn't discuss
whether Raytheon was considering the sale of other operations.
Assad, the division head, was not available for comment. His
employment agreement was recently amended to allow him to receive a
severance package in case of a change in control of RE&AMP;C.
</P>
<P>
   The division had about 8,000 employees at the end of last year,
including about 300 at its headquarters in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they approved of the announcement, though some
wondered if the unit would fetch much at auction. ``Raytheon has
proven to just about everyone on Wall Street that they can't manage
RE&AMP;C,'' said Bill Fiala, analyst with Edward Jones &AMP; Co. in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   RE&AMP;C once was known as an overseer of nuclear power plant
construction. In the early 1990s, it was merged with several other
construction firms Raytheon bought in a diversification effort.
More recently, RE&AMP;C's fortunes have sagged along with its
construction-industry peers, including Boston-based Stone &AMP;
Webster, because of a general slowdown in new construction
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Assad tried to focus the company on domestic work,
and recently won contracts to build new power plants in Everett and
Weymouth, Mass. But other problems remain. Tuesday, Raytheon said
the engineering unit would report a loss of 15 to 20 cents a share
for the first quarter, due mainly to performance issues at one
international project that it did not identify.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the talks with potential buyers, Raytheon said it
wouldn't account for RE&AMP;C as a continuing operation in its
financial results for the three months ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Raytheon said, it expects to meet consensus earnings
expectations. Analysts surveyed by First Call expected the company
to earn around 24 cents a share for the quarter. Results are due
April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also expects to report its net debt rose about $500
million during the quarter, less than some expected. At the end of
last year, its total debt was $9.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's widely traded Class B shares fell 6.25 cents Tuesday
to close at $20.625 in New York Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
