<SLUG> BC-STATES-TXFARM-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  FARM AND ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS SAY FARM BUREAU A ``SHAM,''
DEMAND CONGRESSIONAL INVESTIGATION
</P>
<P>
   By Alison Vekshin
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, April 11 - Accusing the American Farm Bureau
Federation of representing the interests of agribusiness and
insurance companies instead of family farmers, a coalition of farm
and environmental organizations Tuesday urged Congress to
investigate the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a sham that they claim to be a legitimate force for
family farmers or ranchers,'' said Rodger Schlickeisen, president
of the Defenders of Wildlife, a national conservation group
advocating the preservation of endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the Farm Bureau was in its earlier years, it is now a
gigantic agribusiness and insurance conglomerate that masquerades
as a protector of family farmers,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Defenders of Wildlife, the National Family
Farm Coalition and Friends of the Earth called on lawmakers to
examine whether the bureau unfairly misrepresents its membership.
About 180 other groups signed onto a petition urging the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Farm Bureau dismissed the accusations and urged
Congress to consider the motives of the groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find it disconcerting that groups would call for a
congressional investigation of any organization simply because they
disagreed with the policies of that organization,'' said Bob
Stallman, the Farm Bureau's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allegations voiced by Defenders of Wildlife and their
supporters are baseless,'' he added. ``We operate lawfully and
ethically.'' More than 4.9 million families in 50 states and Puerto
Rico belong to the Farm Bureau. As the nation's largest farm
organization, it represents the country's farm and ranch families.
</P>
<P>
   The groups criticized the bureau's support for the 1996 Farm
Bill and for ``unfair trade policy.'' They also said the bureau
hinders the family farmer's competitiveness by supporting
corporate-friendly legislation and agendas that control markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going broke,'' said Chris Peterson, an Iowa farmer for 26
years and a bureau member. ``Agribusiness is eliminating us by the
thousands while our government and Farm Bureau stand by and do
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Christison, president of the National Family Farm Coalition
and a fourth generation farmer from Missouri, criticized the
bureau's support for granting permanent normal trade relations for
China, saying the policy would harm farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gene Hall, a spokesman at the Texas Farm Bureau, defended
the bureau. He said the organization helped secure $14 billion in
emergency disaster relief in 1998 and 1999 to help farmers recover
from droughts and low commodity prices. 8eu[}$~`fu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2017EDT &QL; 
