A3824 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-CAR-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     04-11 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERTA SURVIVES IN `FICKLE BUSINESS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ As late as last week, Bryan Herta's plans
for Grand Prix Sunday were the same as most fans of the annual race
through the streets of Long Beach: Buy a ticket and watch.
</P>
<P>
   That's an odd place to be for a driver who has stood on the
winner's podium the last two years and been one of Long Beach's
most consistently successful drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Since finishing 26th in his first Long Beach Grand Prix in 1995,
Herta has been running at the end of every race and improving each
time out: 12th in 1996, sixth in 1997, and third in 1998 and 1999.
He's finished a mere 35 seconds behind the winners the last three
years. In six years overall on the CART (Championship Auto Racing
Teams) circuit, Herta has two wins, nine podiums (top three) and 41
top 10 finishes in 94 races.
</P>
<P>
   But the vagaries of racing economics almost forced the Valencia
resident to relive his days as a spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Riding for Team Rahal, Herta finished in the top five in three
of the final four races of 1999, a win at Laguna Seca, fourth in
Houston and fifth in Australia. But racing team dynamics sent him
shopping for a new ride during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually signed late with Forsyth Racing, only to find the
team plagued by mechanical problems, from switching chasis to
getting a car ready to race. The earliest the team will be ready to
race will be May.
</P>
<P>
   It took an injury to rookie Shinji Nakano for Herta to catch a
ride Sunday with Walker Racing. He's on loan with the blessing of
Forsyth and engine maker Honda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bumpy offseason,'' said Herta Tuesday between
practice sessions. ``There was a lot of interest from different
teams this winter, but they were all struggling to find the money
to compete. A lot of them were looking for drivers who could bring
(sponsorship) money with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forsyth looked like a great opportunity, and I think it has
great potential. It's just that the early testing wasn't very good,
and we weren't ready for the start of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Herta's ordeal is common. The viewing public marvels at the
speed of the cars and the courage of the drivers, but there's a lot
of politics and economics going on behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fickle business,'' Herta said.
</P>
<P>
   Teams often change drivers in the offseason despite good
performances. They also switch to different engines and chassis,
all looking for an edge or better financial teams. Even Chip
Ganassi's team, which has won four consecutive CART season titles,
tweaked its operation for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit frustrating,'' Herta said. ``You put up a
few strong races, you've been around six years, and you think you
shouldn't need to prove yourself. It's part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot that goes into performances. It's never just the
driver alone or the team alone. It's a complex equation, so you
take an opportunity when it comes by.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Sunday. Walker Racing has a unique history, so perhaps it
isn't surprising Herta found a ride in their car.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Derrick Walker is a Scotsman who worked at Penske
Racing for several years before launching his own team in 1990.
Among his drivers have been Willy T. Ribbs, the first
African-American to race in the Indy 500, young racing heirs like
Scott Goodyear and Christian Fittipaldi, local heroes like Robby
Gordon, and Japanese drivers like Hiro Matsushita, Naoki Hattori
and Nakano.
</P>
<P>
   Despite stepping into a new car and new driving team, Herta
believes he will competitive Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a different feel the seat, the steering wheel,
the shift,'' he said. ``But it's nothing insurmountable. We don't
have the familiarity of having worked together for years we've
never done a pit stop together, and that's important but each day
(of practice) gets a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``My motivation is to win the race. If I didn't feel that was a
possibility, I wouldn't have agreed to drive. I wouldn't predict
how we'll do, but I wouldn't dismiss a win or a top 10 finish.''
</P>
<P>
   In one respect, Herta is to be admired to be here at all. All
paths in auto racing now lead to the successful NASCAR circuit,
which has been blessed with tremendous growth in exposure, revenue
and sponsorships the last half-decade.
</P>
<P>
   CART has become a bit of the foreign legion the last few years,
with many well-sponsored European and South American drivers and
teams. Herta will be one of only three American drivers on the
streets Sunday. A race once owned by the Unsers has seen Italy's
Alex Zanardi and Colombia's Juan Montoya win the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really wanted to do was stay in CART,'' Herta said.
``Most of the sponsor dollars in the U.S. are going to NASCAR. I
don't think American drivers are having trouble, but teams are
finding it difficult. They're being put in a position where they
have tough choices to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the opportunity the last several years to do
different things. It's not like I couldn't have driven something
else. But Long Beach is my favorite race. It's the race I went to
as a kid, and I fell in love with the (CART) cars. I've been living
a dream all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a dream he won't let end. He just can't predict where it
will take him. He'll race for Walker again later this month, then
check the progress at Forsyth and adjust accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one respect, my year is shot,'' he said. ``There's no way
for me to compete for the (series) championship, and there's no
(sponsorship) pot of gold waiting for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the (Forsyth) team is still intact, waiting at the shop
anxiously for a car, and I have to take (Forsyth) at his word that
we'll race this year. I have to just ride it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it's someone else's car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
