<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3827 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     04-11 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV16-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB AIR DEALS: CAVEAT SURFER 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB TEDESCHI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few months ago, I struck gold on the Internet: a
coast-to-coast round-trip flight to Oakland for $208 after taxes,
to attend a friend's wedding. I hit the ``confirm'' button on
Southwest Airlines' Web site and gloated about it to all my
friends, who exhibited the proper amount of envy.
</P>
<P>
   The other shoe dropped somewhere over Texas, when I realized I'd
misunderstood the travel itinerary on the site, which listed
``PHX/3'' under the list of stops. I assumed that meant the plane
stopped only in Phoenix _ maybe for three hours, but who cares? The
printed confirmation Southwest mailed to me gave me no reason to
doubt this logic.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I stopped in Memphis, then Phoenix, then Ontario,
Calif., before heading to Oakland, where I arrived with a sore
backside and a renewed hatred for salted peanuts. Our wry flight
attendant tried to lift the cabin's spirits on the last leg. ``In
the event of a water landing, remember: kick, paddle, kick, paddle
_ all the way until you reach that shore,'' she told us.
</P>
<P>
   I barely cracked a smile. And when I finally reached Oakland, I
greeted my friend with all the warmth of a Soprano. I was toast. I
blamed the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But since I was just as much to blame as the Web, I will be
back. I may not hit the buy button quite as quickly next time, but
given the increasing ranks of the online air fare discounters,
there will still be plenty of good deals available.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, online travel executives and experts said that
consumers could expect this year to be the high point to date for
discount air fare offerings online, as newcomers to the low-price
travel category vie with the airlines, who are working feverishly
to convert their customers to Internet booking.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily because of that competition, sites have improved their
features significantly in the past several months. In addition to
offering low rates on flights you might actually consider booking _
as opposed to, say, the Milwaukee-to-Duluth February special _
airlines and others have made it easier to check flight information
with just a few clicks.
</P>
<P>
   In short, industry experts said comparison shopping would
increasingly pay off _ if consumers will accept higher degrees of
risk and lower levels of customer service, and plenty of surfing
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a buyer's market online,'' said Laurie Berger,
editor of Consumer Reports Travel Letter. ``You just have to be a
smart buyer.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried not to take that as a slight.
</P>
<P>
   Any education in discount travel begins with a short course in
yield management, the airline term for determining how many seats
to sell at what cost. In general, airlines know they can't sell
every seat at the high prices business travelers pay on short
notice, so they reserve some seats for the high-price customers and
some for buyers of midrange scheduled fares.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the seats are often sold to consolidators, who buy
the cheap tickets in bulk at widely varying discounts, and resell
them. Because different airlines will have difficulty selling
different routes, there is no set range for the number of seats an
airline will reserve for consolidators.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the quantity, though, the cheapest online tickets are
often available either through virtual travel agents that have
established relationships with consolidators, or through the
consolidators themselves. Lowestfare.com, for instance, is the
consolidator for TWA, and is expanding its offering of consolidator
tickets through agreements with other airlines, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Cheaptickets.com works directly with a number
of airlines to offer their discounted tickets, as does
Priceline.com. With Priceline, the airlines set aside some
discounted seats, and allow the company to sell a seat if it is
within 30 percent of the lowest price the airline has ever sold it
for. Priceline checks to see if it can buy the ticket for less than
the customer's requested price, to ensure some profit. If it can,
it buys the ticket and sells it to the consumer. ``You might think
you're naming your own price for a ticket on Priceline, but you're
really not,'' said Berger. Rather, she said, the company simply
agrees to buy seats from the major carriers at cut-rate prices, and
sells the seats for any price above a certain threshold. Any bid
below that level is declined.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should approach consolidators and those who sell on
their behalf with caution. Since they do not own an unlimited
inventory of seats, they do all they can to discourage customers
from changing flights. In fact, for a number of them, including
Cheaptickets.com and 1Travel.com, domestic tickets are
nonrefundable, and the flights cannot be changed once the ticket is
bought.
</P>
<P>
   These terms are typically offered before you buy the ticket
online, so read every possible link that may contain such language
before entering credit card information.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the final prices for discounted ticket are not
always obvious, analysts said. Cheaptickets.com recently listed a
flight from Hartford to San Francisco on US Airways for $285. On
the ``check availability'' page, the flight suddenly cost $310.50,
not including $3.95 shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On another part of the site, the company stated that ``prices
shown may not include certain taxes, fees, and/or surcharges,'' but
the company asked for credit card information before revealing that
flight's final cost, leaving a customer to e-mail the company
directly for that information or risk clicker shock after
committing to the purchase. (In fact, the company said, the first
price shown reflected the final price.)
</P>
<P>
   While the name-your-own-price offerings _ which now include not
just Priceline but Expedia.com _ include airport taxes and fees
within a user's bid limit, there are other potential glitches to
avoid. Customers can choose the dates they want to fly, but they
cannot currently make a more specific request about what time of
day they will fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone I work with went through Priceline for a three-day
weekend to Florida,'' said Melissa Shore, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications, an Internet research firm. ``The flight she got was
cheap, but she had to leave on the last flight Saturday and come
back on the first flight Monday, so instead of a three-day weekend,
she got one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Priceline said recently that it would allow consumers to be more
specific about flight times in the near future. ``So for now, I see
it as a really great thing for college students, who aren't that
concerned about when they fly,'' Shore said.
</P>
<P>
   Other pitfalls await the online buyer. Carl Schmehl, a theater
director in Manhattan, said that he bought a bargain ticket through
Lowestfare &QC; .com last month _ or so he thought. After paying with a
credit card and logging off the site, Lowestfare.com e-mailed him
what he thought was a confirmation notice. In fact, he said, the
message asked him to confirm the flight reservation. When he failed
to respond, he was charged a higher price. Many hours of phone
haggling later, Schmehl said, he got the original price.
</P>
<P>
   Technology can also get in the way of a bargain. My father tried
to reserve through Travelocity last year, but when he hit the buy
button, the site stalled. He restarted the computer and _
suspecting a poor connection _ reordered the tickets. Turns out, he
bought three pairs of tickets, a fact he was alerted to by a phone
call from Travelocity. The site eliminated the charge, but he had
to wait a month for American Express to credit him with the refund.
</P>
<P>
   Shore said that the airlines themselves had gotten much more
aggressive about offering low fares online, in part because they
can fill seats more efficiently through the Internet. Northwest
Airlines has even rolled out a site to compete with consolidators,
airoutlet.com. The site doesn't mention Northwest Airlines _ a
practice followed by many other consolidators because the airlines
prefer not to be known as cut-rate among consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are also getting more aggressive about using their
e-mail newsletters to sell seats they haven't committed to
consolidators, and haven't sold to higher paying customers. Most of
the major domestic carriers either have or are in the process of
running an e-mail fare program, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we'll start to see more airlines allow you to filter the
flights, so the e-mail only shows the destinations you're
interested in,'' Shore said. ``I just got a great rate to Dublin
for the weekend through an e-mail newsletter, so it worked for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Brag, brag, brag. I'm so happy I'm not like that.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, of Consumer Reports Travel Letter, said that although
consumers might find isolated bargains that were not last-minute
deals, ``in general good deals happen much closer in, at the last
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   And while e-mail newsletters cater to those looking for
last-minute deals online, they aren't the only mechanism for doing
so.
</P>
<P>
   Lastminutetravel.com, for instance, offers the equivalent of an
e-mail newsletter, in real time, from multiple carriers. According
to David Miranda, the company's chief executive, the site allows
carriers to offer their last-minute fares in one place, and drop
their rates if the seats aren't selling. Consumers who click on a
fare are taken to the carrier's site directly to buy the tickets.
In addition, Miranda said, his site automatically sends an e-mail
message to users when offers of possible interest become available.
</P>
<P>
   More mainstream travel sites are also doing more to cater to the
discount traveler, said Terrell Jones, the chief executive of
Travelocity &QC; .com. Jones said Travelocity had a partnership to sell
tickets through Cheaptickets.com on Travelocity's site. The company
also recently announced a deal with Priceline.com. ``Consumers who
want to bid for tickets will have a link to Priceline on our site,
and people on Priceline who read the rules and decide they don't
want to buy that way will have a link to our site,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the dozens of online choices for discount tickets, Berger
said, some consumers may be better served by simply using a travel
agent. ``I can get a great price online because I check the
Internet, travel agents and the airlines directly, even though I
usually book on the Web,'' she said. ``But if you don't know your
way around, there are a lot of opportunities for confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you only go online occasionally, and you don't want to
take the time to really understand how things work, I'd suggest
going the traditional route.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents agree. ``We're not worried about the Internet,''
said Elizabeth Dale, an agent with Dale Johnson Travel in Palo
Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Dale said travel agents could frequently offer more creative
ways to find bargains. For instance, she said, someone traveling
from the East Coast to the West Coast with one connection in
between might get a quote online for one fare. ``But we could break
that into two separate round-trip fares _ from the West Coast to
the connecting city and back, and from the connecting city to the
East Coast and back _ and save them money that way.''
</P>
<P>
   One connecting city? Cheaper fare? I took her number down for
future trips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
