<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LEBANON-SYRIA-ART-2TA     04-11 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-SYRIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANON CHAFING AS SYRIA'S PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ A huge billboard faces the hotels that line
the seafront here. It shows a smiling President Hafez Assad of
Syria with his arms outstretched like a welcoming host. ``We did
not create the bond between Syria and Lebanon,'' he is saying.
``God did.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a sentiment that most Lebanese share. But 24 years
after Syrian soldiers marched into Lebanon, ostensibly to enforce a
cease-fire in the civil war, Assad remains the man who pulls the
strings in this fractious nation.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing Syrian influence can be seen in the flow of
Syrians into Lebanon to work for $10 a day at Lebanese construction
sites and sell plastic trinkets to motorists at Beirut
intersections. It can be seen in Lebanese markets, where the
unrestricted dumping of cheap Syrian produce has nearly ruined
local farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's hand is seen in Lebanese elections, where candidates
openly critical of its military overlordship suffered such bullying
that they no longer even bother to run for office. Syria controls
the direction of Lebanese foreign policy, particularly the pace and
form of peace negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 Syrian soldiers, buttressed by an unknown number of
intelligence agents, are based in Lebanon, controlling the legal
and illegal flow of goods across the border as well as the shipment
of arms to the Hezbollah militia, the main group doing battle with
Israeli soldiers in the southern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are everywhere, the Syrians _ stupidly,'' said Walid
Jumblatt, the leader of Lebanon's Druse minority whose authority as
a clan chieftain affords him some freedom to speak his mind and who
believes the Syrian behavior unnecessarily creates hostility.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to weaken your opponent, you go to Syria. If you
want to help someone, you go to Syria. If you want a service from
the judiciary, you go to Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   Jumblatt, like many others here, acknowledged that tiny Lebanon
cannot afford to have a hostile relationship with Syria. Still the
Lebanese chafe under the often heavy-handed Syrian dictates, even
as they have come to admit that their faltering country desperately
needs Syria as an economic partner.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship has undergone changes from both sides in the
past few years, with the Syrians more subtle in their management
and the Lebanese more open in their desire to define its terms. But
it is still a lopsided arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``After nearly 25 years, they weren't able to swallow this
country,'' said Gibran Tueni, managing director of Lebanon's
largest daily newspaper, An Nahar. ``So we are asking Syria to open
a frank dialogue. We want to be partners _ part of the process and
equal.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Lebanon is weary of ``lying on the table,'' like a card
to be played by one side or the other, ``as the price for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Syrian dominance might be of little concern to anyone but the
Lebanese except for the state of unwavering hostility that exists
between Syria and Israel. Wedged between the two, Lebanon is the
arena where its two more powerful neighbors play out their
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese officials have not negotiated directly with Israel for
years, leaving their fate up to Syria. But the unalloyed
trepidation with which officials in Beirut greeted Israel's plan to
withdraw from the strip it occupies in south Lebanon has
demonstrated most clearly the force of the ties that bind Lebanon
and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than welcoming the unilateral retreat, which Lebanon had
always argued should not be connected to the vagaries of the larger
Middle East peace efforts, President Emile Lahoud now says it must
be accompanied by the resettlement of Palestinian refugees and by
Israel's return of the Golan Heights to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Lahoud, the former chief of staff of the 65,000-member Lebanese
army, has so far refused even to say if his country will take
charge of liberated Lebanese territory once the Israelis are gone.
He has suggested the south may remain as it has been for years: the
realm of independent warlords and armed militias.
</P>
<P>
   His ambivalence was widely taken to reflect the calculations of
Syria, which has warned that a unilateral withdrawal could be
``suicide'' for Israel and should take place only if and when Syria
decides to make peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The resumption of Israeli-Syrian negotiations earlier this year
stirred hopes here that Lebanon might soon become a less important
military card for Syria and, theoretically, could gain more freedom
of maneuver in its own affairs. A peace treaty, it was thought,
would also prompt the protectionist Syrian economy to open up to
the benefit of Lebanon, which has become saddled with debt as it
tries to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Those talks are now stalled. But many Lebanese have now focused
their hopes on a different benefactor _ Assad's son and heir
apparent, Bashar Assad. His office in Damascus has become the home
away from home for Lebanon's political and business elite who are
looking for Syrian patronage.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The younger Assad _ he is 35 and studied ophthalmology in
England _ is seen by entrepreneurs in both Lebanon and Syria as a
man open to the introduction of modern technology, free markets and
a more relaxed rein on Lebanon. The appointment of a new Syrian
Cabinet last month, promoted as one that will be tough on
corruption, is credited to Bashar Assad's influence.
</P>
<P>
   His image as a progressive has already encouraged Tueni to
broach a topic rarely discussed in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have visited Lebanon often, and have met with politicians
who undoubtedly told you what you want to hear, not what you ought
to know, about what many Lebanese think of Syrian policy in
Lebanon,'' he wrote in an open letter to Bashar Assad published on
the front page of An Nahar last month. ``Many of those politicians
speak more out of fear of Syria than love.''
</P>
<P>
   Tueni called on Syria to forge a partnership with Lebanon, not
the Lebanese ``political elite,'' as he called them, installed by
Syria. Hundreds of Lebanese expatriates sent the newspaper e-mail
messages congratulating it for confronting Syria. Assad did not
respond.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many people here say that Syria has tried to be more
subtle in its relationship with Lebanon in recent years. Not long
ago, President Assad's photograph still adorned every pillar in the
decrepit Beirut international airport, and Syrian soldiers operated
checkpoints at numerous intersections in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   A modern new airport has now been built, and the Syrian's face
no longer greets arriving travelers. A few Syrian army posts remain
in Beirut, but the bulk of the soldiers are based in the Bekaa
region and the cities of northern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   On the economic side, the big contracts for the reconstruction
of battle-scarred Beirut have been awarded, ending the wholesale
pursuit by Lebanese entrepreneurs of well-placed Syrian partners to
help them.
</P>
<P>
   But Lebanon, which 30 years ago was a financial and service
center for the Arab world, can no longer compete with newer
financial hubs like the one in Dubai, especially with Lebanon's
debts and its university graduates leaving because of the lack of
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is the Lebanese who are pushing for economic access to
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who say we will become a financial center _ they're
deluding themselves,'' said Makram Sader, secretary general of the
Association of Lebanese Banks. ``If Syria does not open, we will be
in deep trouble. We will have enormous problems creating new jobs
and economic growth. The Syrian market is vital to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese businessmen, ever hopeful, are banking on hints from
the new Syrian government that it will soon loosen currency
restrictions and allow Lebanese to extend credit and invest there,
whether or not Syria signs a peace treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Syrians want to be prepared for this opening that would
come with peace,'' said Taha Mikati, a confidant of Bashar Assad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DOTCOM-HARASS-ART-2TA     04-11 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOTCOM-HARASS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARASSMENT SUITS HIT THE DOT-COMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MELINDA LIGOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dot-com workplace is a magnet for young
Americans, with its promise of adventure, riches and a casual work
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, the environment may be getting too casual. Managers
at some Internet companies are rethinking their corporate cultures
as a smattering of sexual harassment lawsuits begins to roll into
their high-technology world. Some legal experts think these cases
might be the beginning of a wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet start-up community is going to be a major target
for sexual harassment litigation,'' said Gregory I. Rasin, a senior
partner at the Manhattan office of Jackson Lewis Schnitzler &AMP;
Krupman, an employment law firm that has several dot-com clients.
</P>
<P>
   By nature, these companies are at legal risk because the
entrepreneurs who start them are often eager to create the ultimate
anticorporate environment, said Corey Sprague, director of human
resources at the RiskMetrics Group, an Internet start-up on Wall
Street. ``I get a lot of calls from people who are setting up
dot-com companies and want to create a no-holds-barred, wild
culture, free of rules and policies,'' said Sprague, whose company
is one of the few start-ups that hired human-resources personnel
from the beginning. As a result, she said, most are not eager to
create policies and training programs that address traditional
human resources concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Even managers who are sensitive to issues like sexual harassment
are so focused on raising capital and expanding their businesses
that they neglect to create a human resources department to address
them, said John Iorillo, co-founder of the Ambrose Employer Group,
a provider of human resources services in New York that has more
than 120 dot-com clients. ``For the first few years, most start-ups
are just in survival mode,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case at Pseudo Programs, a Manhattan-based Internet
TV network that was sued in January by a former employee who says
the company had a hostile work environment for women. In her
complaint, the employee, Kelly Alfieri, said male employees at
Pseudo frequently referred to female employees as ``bimbos'' and
forced them to look at sexually explicit material on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo's male employees ``were allowed to do whatever they
wanted,'' said David Jaroslawicz, Alfieri's lawyer. ``It was like
they were living in the Wild West and the sheriff was out of
town.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Meyer, senior vice president for marketing at Pseudo,
said Alfieri's accusations were ``completely without merit.'' The
company acknowledges that it created a human resources department
only after Alfieri quit Pseudo two years ago. ``As with most
start-ups, our senior management did everything in the beginning,
from putting toilet paper in the bathrooms to payroll,'' Meyer
said. But now, she said, its new department ``continually
reinforces the company's sexual-harassment policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the lack of formal policies and training at many
start-ups is a culture of long hours and close quarters. ``People
are working 80 or 100 hours per week, so the only social contact
they're having is in the context of the workplace,'' said Daniel
Weisberg, an employment-law specialist at Brobeck, Phleger &AMP;
Harrison, a Manhattan-based law firm. As a result, he said,
inner-office dating is rampant, and relationships that go sour have
the potential to turn into sexual harassment complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In one highly publicized example, Juno Online Services, an
Internet company based in Midtown Manhattan, was sued last fall by
two former female employees who said they had been told they would
lose their jobs if they broke off their relationships with senior
executives they were dating. Juno's lawyer, Terri Ross, said the
company denies the accusations in both lawsuits. One lawsuit has
since been referred to arbitration by a New York state court, and
Juno has applied to send the second complaint to arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Another common theme in cases he handles, Weisberg said, is that
``the one who was spurned gets terminated or doesn't get the
promotion they thought they should get and decides to sue.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Internet start-ups are often small, with many staff
members working in the same space, other employees are often
unwitting witnesses to office liaisons, according to Garry G.
Mathiason, a partner at Littler Mendelson, a San Francisco
employment-law firm that represents more than 1,000 dot-coms
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Mathiason offered the example of a company he represents, where
an employee recently complained that she had walked in on two
co-workers having sex on the office floor. The woman was so
offended, he said, that she immediately quit her job and is
threatening to bring a claim against the company.
</P>
<P>
   While such reports of sexual harassment seem fairly blatant, the
majority of sexual harassment complaints at dot-coms are more
subtle, according to Weisberg. ``The most common problem we hear
about are employees who are offended by all the sexually explicit
e-mail jokes that bounce around these offices,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mathiason recently received a complaint from an employee who
said she had received an e-mail, later traced to a co-worker, that
read, ``I see you're wearing black today. You're a very bad girl,''
and directed her to an X-rated Web site. At another dot-com,
Mathiason said, female employees complained that their male
colleagues were continuously logging onto a Web site featuring
co-eds taking showers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of activities seem to predominate in the dot-com
world,'' Mathiason said. ``A lot of these guys haven't been out of
school for very long, and they're still experimenting with this
kind of juvenile stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all managers turn a blind eye to such antics, of course.
Weisberg said his office had fielded several calls from dot-coms
looking to provide sexual harassment training to managers. His
office recently assisted two larger Manhattan-based Internet
companies, DoubleClick Inc. and About.com, in setting up
anti-discrimination training programs. ``We're definitely seeing
more companies take a pro-active stance,'' Weisberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Another start-up, Boutique Y3K, recently appointed a
human-resources manager to oversee its 12 employees. ``We intend to
take issues of harassment and discrimination seriously,'' said Lisa
Tisdale, the new manager.
</P>
<P>
   Those that do not take such issues seriously are looking for
trouble, Mathiason said. ``Right now, you're not seeing as much
litigation as you might expect'' in the dot-com world, he said.
That is partly because the economy is so robust that would-be
plaintiffs are ``getting six job offers on the way to their
lawyers' offices,'' Mathiason said.
</P>
<P>
   But the minute the economy slows, he warned, disgruntled
employees will have fewer opportunities to move on and will be more
likely to go after their deep-pocketed former employers. ``It will
be like an earthquake hit,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
