<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDWARDS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Louisiana governor denies casino handlers bought his
influence
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ Former Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards said
Tuesday he never took any money in exchange for his political
influence from friends who were applying to the state for riverboat
casino licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got a cent from Robert Guidry,'' said the 72-year-old
four-time governor, referring to a former colleague who pled guilty
to giving Edwards and his son, Stephen, $1.5 million in payoffs for
help in securing a license for the Treasure Chest casino in
suburban New Orleans. He denied Guidry's testimony that the payoffs
were put in the back of his Chevrolet Suburban and in Dumpsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That never happened in my car,'' he said. ``And Mr. Guidry is
too smart and too cautious to leave money in Dumpsters. It just
didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, his son, and five other men are on trial for allegedly
corrupting the state's casino licensing system for financial gain.
They have been on trial for 14 weeks, facing 34 counts of
extortion, money laundering and racketeering. Edwards was tried in
the 1980s on federal racketeering charges relating to hospital
contracts, but he has not been convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards spent the morning painting a picture of himself as a
poor Cajun who achieved the American dream of self-made prosperity
and political fame. He said his mother, a midwife who delivered
babies free of charge, taught him the value of doing favors without
asking for compensation. He sometimes made courtroom observers
laugh as he relaxed in his chair and spoke with his trademark
folksy charm. But the jury sat stonefaced, often not looking at
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by federal prosecutor Jim Letten,
Edwards admitted he gave a fellow politician advice on how to
circumvent state campaign finance laws. In a videotape secretly
recorded by the FBI, Edwards gives the lesson to state Sen. Cleo
Fields, a former U.S. congressman and gubernatorial candidate. He
said Fields did not take his advice, so no laws were broken. Letten
countered that even giving the advice was a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to stay within the law, sometimes I don't,'' Edwards
said. ``But I did not violate the federal laws that bring us here
today.''
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, Edwards is seen giving Fields $20,000 in cash,
which Fields stuffs in his pants pocket. Edwards testified that the
cash was a gift to help Fields with debts incurred in his run for
governor. But he had trouble explaining why he told Fields he
should be careful how he used the money. Asked how he thought
things were going with his testimony, Edwards smiled and said,
``This is the easy part.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
