<HEADER>
A3837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CLINTON-DICAPRIO-NYT &LR;      04-11 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DICAPRIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC WILL SHOW PORTION OF DICAPRIO INTERVIEW WITH CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After deliberating for days over whether to use it at
all, ABC News announced Tuesday that it would show some of the
interview of President Clinton by the actor Leonardo DiCaprio in an
upcoming special on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The special is scheduled for broadcast on April 22, which is
Earth Day. DiCaprio is the chairman of the Earth Day 2000
celebration committee.
</P>
<P>
   News of the interview angered some ABC News personnel, who said
it was improper for the organization to dispatch a celebrity to do
what they consider to be the job of a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   David Westin, the president of ABC News, initially said that
DiCaprio had been sent to the White House for a walking tour
focusing on energy efficiency there and that it was the president
who requested a sitdown interview. Because a formal interview
between the celebrity and the president was not what ABC had in
mind, Westin had said, it might not be shown.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said this version of events was
``rife with inaccuracies.'' Westin later confirmed that DiCaprio
did in fact arrive at the White House with questions in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, seemingly weary of the controversy, declined Tuesday to say
exactly how much of the interview would be shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been enough conversation before the fact,'' said
Eileen Murphy, an ABC News spokeswoman. ``We prefer to be judged on
the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the project said that the editing process
was continuing but that they expected to use footage of the
interview that focused on what people could do on their own to
protect the environment, not on specific policy issues. DiCaprio is
said to come across as nervous during the interview.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said they decided to use the interview because
DiCaprio _ who is a celebrity co-host to the ABC correspondent
Chris Cuomo for the program _ is serving in the role of an informed
star and is not acting as a journalist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
