<SLUG> BC-BBA-TWINS-REDSOX-EVERETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR EVERETT, GAME WAS ANYTHING BUT A LOST CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The phone rang inside Carl Everett's locker.
</P>
<P>
   The new Red Sox center fielder had just spent the better part of
an hour explaining how he hadn't been able to find Fenway Park six
hours earlier, driving back and forth along Massachusetts Avenue,
Boston's streets a maze to him, no landmark Green Monster spotted
to guide him, but finally guided home by Red Sox traveling
secretary Jack McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the park at last, Everett promptly homered on his first
Fenway at-bat, against Twins righthander Joe Mays. Then, adding
even more quirkiness to his day, Everett patiently explained how he
is a ``semi-switch hitter,'' sometimes batting left against
lefthanders.
</P>
<P>
   Against Minnesota's Mark Redman, a lefthander who relieved Mays
in the Red Sox' eight-run second inning, Everett first batted
lefty. But after injured third baseman John Valentin chastised him
for such foolishness here (``You're not hitting lefty against no
lefty with that Green Monster out there''), Everett switched to the
right side in the sixth inning. Only to homer again.
</P>
<P>
   And now, all talked out about his zany day, Everett reached for
the cell phone ringing inside his locker.
</P>
<P>
   It was his wife, Linda.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' said Everett. ``What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Linda Everett had been driving the streets of Boston for 3
1/2 hours, only to find Fenway Park just as the 33,114 fans were
streaming out, many of them singing the praises of her husband, who
went 3 for 4, with two homers and 3 RBIs in his first game in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife's outside now,'' said Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Where did she watch the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``She was driving around the city.
That's what she told me.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he give his wife directions?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving anyone directions after what happened to me,''
said Everett. ``It kind of scared my wife. I was worried about them
getting lost _ my wife and the kids _ not so much me. I'm a big
boy. I can take care of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett then was able to chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife,'' he said, ``she still hasn't seen any of my
two-homer games.''
</P>
<P>
   And fortunate it was that Everett was able to poke those two
homers Tuesday. Everett had left his new home in Lexington early in
the morning, and while anyone familiar with Eastern Massachusetts
would promptly suggest Route 2 as the easiest way to Boston, no one
dared suggest that route to a newcomer. There aren't enough words
in the English language to explain to a newcomer what to do about
finding Fenway Park after reaching Fresh Pond Circle in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   So Everett went along Route 128 to the Mass. Pike, headed east,
``and I did exactly as they told me to do _ get off at Exit 22
(Copley Square). They said it would be easy from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hah!
</P>
<P>
   Everett got as close to Fenway as Massachusetts Avenue, then
lost his way. Back and forth, up and down Mass. Ave., Everett went
before surrendering. He called McCormick's cell phone (``thank God
he had my number,'' said McCormick), and the traveling secretary
asked the lost center fielder to name the nearest cross street.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was near Columbus Avenue,'' said McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   OK. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little ambiguous,'' said McCormick about guiding a lost
soul from Mass. Ave. to Fenway. Getting over to Beacon Street was
merely a straight line, but what to do after taking a left on
Beacon and finding the right way through Kenmore Square? Beacon
Street goes where Commonwealth Avenue should go, and Comm. Ave.
goes where Beacon Street should go.
</P>
<P>
   So McCormick used the old reliable technique for guiding
tourists through Boston. Don't give them streets, but places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to look out for Pizzeria Uno (in Kenmore Square)
and take a left at Pizzeria Uno,'' said McCormick. ``Then I said,
`You'll see the Cask 'n Flagon and take a left there down Lansdowne
Street.' And I told him he'd see the Green Monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Paydirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame 'em,'' said McCormick. ``Honest to God, it's
hard if you're new to Boston. Those light stanchions, you can't see
them from too many places.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett was thrilled about hitting a homer in his first Fenway
at-bat, batting lefthanded off Mays, but that was routine compared
with what happened next. Everett prefers to bat lefthanded against
lefties who throw more soft stuff than heat.
</P>
<P>
   His first time up against Redman, on his second at-bat in the
second inning, Everett batted left and struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go up there either side against lefties,'' said Everett,
``but that first time a guy was on base and I wanted to hit
lefthanded. And I was swinging good lefthanded at the time. And I
didn't know that much about (Redman) except he doesn't throw that
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett said he decides ``by feel'' whether to hit righty or
lefty against lefties.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I feel good lefthanded and I feel I can hit the guy
lefthanded, I'll go up there lefthanded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But when Everett went back into the locker room after striking
out and then walking in the fourth, Valentin told him to bat
righty.
</P>
<P>
   Which Everett did the next time against Redman, in the sixth,
and hit his first blast over the Monster.
</P>
<P>
   And his first impressions of Fenway?
</P>
<P>
   ``Small,'' he said. ``Very small.''
</P>
<P>
   So small it's hard to find.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
