<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA A HIT, BUT SO WAS EVERETT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The crowd around the locker in the Red Sox clubhouse
was four-deep. Nomar Garciaparra, strolling out of the shower, took
one look, shook his head, and did a U-turn into the trainer's room.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, Garciaparra came out again for a look. The
area around his locker was still hip-deep in mini-cams. He moved to
the food station, loaded up his plate, sat at a table, and waited
some more.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he looked up and saw some daylight. The crowd
surrounding center fielder Carl Everett had finally dispersed.
</P>
<P>
   Everett deserved the attention after hitting a pair of home runs
and leading a 16-hit Red Sox attack that produced a 13-4 victory
over the Minnesota Twins in Tuesday's home opener at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's contribution was four hits, three runs batted in.
Yet for a solid 40 minutes after the game, the shortstop couldn't
get near his locker.
</P>
<P>
   A sign of things to come?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I think Carl being the new guy, they just wanted to get
near him,'' said manager Jimy Williams with a smile and a shrug.
``Having him around helps everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially Garciaparra, who at times last season carried the Red
Sox offense on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't leave this stuff on anybody's shoulders,'' said
Garciaparra, whose opening week of the season had produced only
four hits in 22 at-bats, which had Nomar fans looking for every
excuse from cold weather to bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's 45-degree game-time temperature could hardly be
considered mild, but Garciaparra's hitting luck had changed. It
started in the first when he hit a Joe Mays pitch up the middle for
a run-scoring single. A week ago, it might have been an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar had a good day, as did a few others,'' said Williams,
who watched in delight as the Red Sox broke open the game with an
eight-run second inning that was highlighted by a two-run single by
Garciaparra and the first of Everett's home runs.
</P>
<P>
   After a season-opening West Coast trip that might have ended 0-6
were it not for the magical presence of Pedro Martinez, the Red Sox
need some sort of jump-start.
</P>
<P>
   With snow at the worst and cold at the very best in the forecast
for the home opener, they needed something to invigorate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could feel the energy out there,'' said Garciaparra, who
in one afternoon raised his average from .182 to .296 and doubled
his hit total for the season. ``The hits were falling today. Last
week they weren't. I guess I had better aim.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Fenway fans had seen the Red Sox was Oct. 18,
in a 6-1 loss to the Yankees in the fifth and final game of the
American League Championship Series. The West Coast struggles
already had some gloom-and-doomers wondering what was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The slow start by Garciaparra _ last year's American League
batting champion _ seemed to be another warning sign. When
Garciaparra went three games without a hit last week, it marked the
first time he had such a streak since May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday eased the concerns. Not only for the Red Sox, but also
for Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra came up in the seventh, looking for his first career
five-hit day. A sharp grounder to second was the best he could
manage, and Williams pulled him after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it goes around here,'' Garciaparrra joked.
``Make an out and you're out of there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
