<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3848 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-11 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON MARTINEZ COOL _ THROUGH THE BAD AND THE GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Carl Everett hit a home run. Ramon sat and watched.
Wilton Veras doubled. Ramon sat and watched. It was the beginning
of an eight-run second inning. Ramon Martinez, he of the surgically
repaired shoulder and the Domincan Republic birthplace, sat and
watched.
</P>
<P>
   The game-time temperature was 45 degrees. It was a typical
Fenway Park Opening Day, which is to say it was a fine afternoon
for football. A man can live a hundred lifetimes in the Dominican
Republic and never have to pitch in 45-degree weather.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon sat and watched through walks and base hits and even an
error. Was he tightening up? For a man with his background and
medical history, that was a fair question. On and on it went until,
finally, Veras lined to third for the final out. It may have been a
10-1 lead, but this was going to be a test for Martinez, who is
generally regarded as the key to the Red Sox' hopes this season. A
good pitcher says thank you to his offense after a big inning by
returning them to the dugout as soon as possible. There was no way
Martinez was going to be allowed to blow the game, but there also
was no way Jimy Williams wanted to get into his bullpen early in
this game, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleven pitches,'' beamed pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``Eleven
pitches. 1-2-3, boom. We had the momentum for the rest of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez disposed of the Minnesota Twins on 11 pitches in the
third inning. He likewise sailed through the fourth and fifth
before retiring for the day, his W in this 13-4 game intact and his
spirits on the up-tick. You can forget about that first night in
Seattle. That guy doesn't exist. At least, that's what everyone is
saying. And what everyone also says is that the Ramon Martinez who
got out of a bases-loaded, one-out, one-run in jam in the first and
threw four subsequent scoreless innings was merely a
tip-of-the-iceberg Ramon Martinez, that before the season is over
we're all going to see the real Ramon Martinez, and then we'll know
why Dan Duquette was so eager to get him.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get technical, we can get technical. After
getting leadoff man Todd Walker in the first, Martinez went walk,
single, single, walk. That's right. He walked in a run. But then he
and catcher Jason Varitek figured out that if his two-seam fastball
was so lively that it was drifting outside the strike zone, then
perhaps things might get better if Varitek would move to his right,
setting up outside the plate and giving Ramon a target that would
allow his ball to become a strike. He got Corey Koskie on a foul
pop to third and Marcus Jensen on a fly to left. Then he came back
to the dugout and vented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon was really upset when he came off the mound following
the first inning,'' reported Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins had a run that Martinez figured would never have been
scored if he had analyzed the situation properly from the get-go.
You must understand that when you're talking about a Martinez
brother, you're talking about someone for whom the game is, as Yogi
Berra would say, ``90 percent half-mental.'' These men pride
themselves on being thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset with myself,'' Martinez said. ``I said, `This is
not going to happen again. I am going to get my rhythm and I am not
going to pitch like that. I may walk four or five guys, but in
seven or eight innings.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are learning a lot about Ramon Martinez. They know,
for example, that just because he is a Dominican, that doesn't mean
they can't count on him for help when the temperature dips a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little worried,'' said Williams, ``but then I saw him
out there in short sleeves. I said, `The man must be feeling pretty
good.' And he never did change. But some guys don't like long
sleeves. They feel freer. They're not restricted.''
</P>
<P>
   Good guess, Skip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel comfortable with long sleeves,'' said Martinez.
``Yes, it was cold, but I decided to go with short sleeves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan had his own weather worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned,'' he said. ``Not from a physical standpoint,
but with the idea of the slickness of the ball. The feel of the
ball is very important to him. He needs to have that feel because
of having two grips on his fastball and his changeup.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitching coach has full confidence that Martinez is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bounces back well,'' said Kerrigan. ``We saw that in spring
training. And the day after his start in Seattle he was throwing
long ball and practicing from the stretch. And he wasn't lobbing
the ball, either. So right away we know his arm is healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those people who gained more needed insight into the Ramon
Martinez phenomenon Tuesday was his catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got to stay out there and find his rhythm,'' Varitek said.
``He made a big adjustment in the second inning, and an even bigger
adjustment in the third, after we scored all those runs. It was
important to see what he would do with the lead. Your mind can
float a little bit. Ramon did an excellent job of keeping his focus
and throwing a lot of strike ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Do keep in mind that Martinez is just starting his comeback
following major shoulder surgery. He is building arm strength. It
is April. There's a lot of baseball to play. We haven't even had
the Marathon yet. In those terms, he has barely hit Ashland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to get better,'' Martinez said. ``I know I
will pitch better. I've got to keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the team has already seen enough of Ramon to know he
is a cut above the ordinary in the categories that transcend mere
physical ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon knows how to forget about his last start, good or bad,''
said Derek Lowe. ``And the way he pitched in that third inning,
after we scored the eight runs . . . he put up that quick zero.
That's very important. It was a tremendous job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't ever get comfortable in Seattle,'' said Varitek,
``and he didn't get off to a great start today. But he found
himself before he got out of that inning, and then once we gave him
a nibble he knew what to do. I hadn't caught him enough to have a
frame of reference, but now I can see what he does when he gets his
feel. And he is a definite `feel' pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   What he can do when he has his feel is get guys out. That
happens to be the basic job description.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
