u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-FATHER-NYT &LR;      04-11 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-FATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN'S FATHER GREETS ARRAY OF SYMPATHETIC GUESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CUBAN-BOY, CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ He has received the likes of the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, bearing comfort for the spirit, and Vicki Martin of
Madison, Wis., bearing cheese for the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   He got his first taste of snow, Washington traffic and the media
glare, from the 20 television cameras trained on the house of
Cuba's top diplomat here that is, for now, home.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez, 31, an employee at a tourist resort
seeking custody of his 6-year-old shipwrecked son, Elian, left Cuba
on Thursday with a sendoff from President Fidel Castro and then
flew in a private jet to Washington. In short order, over the next
five days, he sat down with Attorney General Janet Reno, chatted
with members of Congress, thanked the fishermen who rescued his son
and greeted 100 people at a reception in his honor at Cuba's de
facto embassy.
</P>
<P>
   If Gonzalez has not exactly taken the town, the town is somewhat
taken by him. His whereabouts are staked out by the news media and,
some assert with dismay, by the Cuban government. But Gonzalez no
doubt has received a memorable taste of America, however limited or
unintended.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Gonzalez sits on the landing of the brick house here
or sees visitors off on the driveway with a wave, now and then
glancing at the media pack.
</P>
<P>
   In private moments, he hands out snapshots of Elian taken in
Cuba. He repeats over and over that he wants his boy and that he
wants to go back to Cuba. He is getting impatient. He speaks to the
boy by phone but only sees him on television. He is concerned that
it looks like Elian has lost weight and chafes when the boy flashes
the victory sign, a sure influence from the Miami relatives whom
visitors say Gonzalez has come to loathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more he sees his son on TV, it's like so close yet so
far,'' said the Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, the former general
secretary of the National Council of Churches, who has visited
Gonzalez several times since his arrival. ``It's like having a
baby. You wait nine months and then the last week is
interminable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has seen at least five members of Congress: a
Republican, Bob Ney of Ohio, and four Democrats, Jose E. Serrano of
New York, Maxine Waters and Barbara Lee of California and Donna
M.C. Christensen, the delegate from the U.S. Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the human thing to do to see how he was doing,'' said
Lee, who visited Gonzalez on Sunday. He showed her the photographs,
explaining it was his way of demonstrating his relationship with
Elian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad this thing is so politicized he has to justify
his fitness as a father,'' said Lee, who had visited Gonzalez in
Cuba in February while attending a trade show.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his most spontaneous contact with an American came
Saturday with Martin, who is secretary of the Madison,
Wis.-Camaguey, Cuba Sister City Association. After she told members
of the group she would be in Washington on an unrelated matter,
they suggested she leave a basket of cheese _ a symbol of the state
_ for Gonzalez at the Cuban Interests Section.
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived, an official there, struck by the gesture,
arranged for Martin to visit with Gonzalez the next day, she said.
They chatted on the green leather sofa in the living room, which
she said is sparsely appointed with modern furnishings but no
prominent photographs or icons of Cuba or Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discussed Wisconsin as being the heartland,'' said Martin, a
real estate agent, who visited Cuba three times in the last year.
``He was interested in that. Camaguey is similar. He told me Elian
was very smart, and he thought it was because of the school system
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who attended a reception Sunday night at the interests
section and met Gonzalez there, said Gonzalez expressed ``great
interest'' in U.S.-Cuban relations but ``right now he is guarded in
his comments because he is anxious to get his son back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Gonzalez's visitors all have expressed the
belief that the boy belongs with his father in Cuba, and a number
have visited the country and believe the United States should have
stronger ties. But the contacts have drawn the ire of those who
oppose Castro and who, despite the denials of Cuban officials and
Gonzalez's lawyer, believe Gonzalez's movements and words are
strictly controlled by Castro.
</P>
<P>
   The three Cuban-American members of Congress, who have opposed
Castro for years, said they never received a response to their
invitation to have lunch with Gonzalez, his wife and baby.
</P>
<P>
   Jaqueline Stevens, a spokeswoman for Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart,
R-Fla., one of the Cuban-American congressmen seeking a meeting,
said it was impossible for Gonzalez to speak or visit freely ``when
he is surrounded by people who we believe intimidate him and I'm
sure have done something to scare him.''
</P>
<P>
   She said, and a State Department official confirmed, that
although Fernando Remirez de Estenoz, the diplomat in whose home
Gonzalez is living, said on national television last Thursday that
he would waive diplomatic immunity for the residence, the Cubans
never followed through with a formal request to do so. Therefore,
she said, Gonzalez is living on Cuban territory and subject to the
travel restrictions it places on its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Campbell, who has been close to the Gonzalez
family, said she had seen no evidence that Gonzalez's activities
were restricted. She said he has focused his energy on reuniting
with Elian and little else.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is more limited by the press,'' she said. ``He could go out
and walk freely if that is what he wish or that were possible
without being accosted by the press.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
