u s BC-HKN-STANLEY-PREVIEW12     04-11 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY-PREVIEW12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The West looks the best in NHL playoffs
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most dominant team in the NHL this season enters
the most magical part of the season tonight _ the part that makes
51-win years suddenly evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the playoffs, St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's, `What have you done for me lately?''' Blues defenseman
Chris Pronger said. ``Who cares what happened in the past?''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis won the Presidents Trophy this season with the
league's best record at 51-20-11. The Blues should not have any
problems in their first-round series against San Jose when the
Stanley Cup playoffs begin tonight at the Kiel Center. But as the
Blues attempt to follow up the Rams' post-season success and make
St. Louis an unlikely City of Champions, there are two statistics
worth noting:
</P>
<P>
   _ Only four of 14 Presidents Trophy winners have gone on to win
the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Blues had a composite record of only 6-7-1 against Dallas,
Colorado and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is particularly important because the balance of
power in the NHL clearly tilts to the West. The Blues, Dallas
Stars, Colorado Avalanche and Detroit Red Wings arguably are the
best four teams in the league and potentially could sweep their
respective first-round series. What follows could be the two best
series of the post-season: St. Louis vs. Detroit and Dallas vs.
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think the Cup winner is in the West,'' said
Thrasher center Ray Ferraro. ``The only way it's not in the West is
if they all killed each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado was the league's hottest team the last three weeks of
the season, going 14-2-1 and ripping teams on the power play since
the acquisition of defenseman Ray Bourque from Boston. The Avs did
little celebrating after clinching the Northwest Division title,
for as goalie Patrick Roy said, ``The object is the silver thing in
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   In the East, New Jersey, Toronto, Philadelphia, Washington and
Florida all took turns looking like the team to beat. Now it's
easier to decipher why each team won't reached the finals. The
Flyers beat out Jersey for the top seed but are missing coach Roger
Neilson, who is recovering from bone marrow cancer, and center Eric
Lindros, who is nursing a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Philly's first-round opponent is Buffalo _ as in goalie Dominik
Hasek plus 19 other guys. Hasek said of the Flyers, ``They had more
than 100 points, and they have the home-ice advantage. But that
doesn't mean they're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
