A3856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HUD-KIOSKS12-COX     04-11 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUD-KIOSKS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AUDIT CALLS HUD STOREFRONT OFFICES, KIOSKS WASTEFUL
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development has spent more than $8.5 million to set up
``customer-friendly'' storefront offices and outdoor kiosks that
have little practical value, according to HUD's inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   The audit, to be released Wednesday, charges that HUD began
building the new facilities without a clear plan or justification
and has failed to provide evidence of their usefulness.
</P>
<P>
   Costs for the storefronts are ``excessive and the benefits
derived by the customers are not measurable,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The audit examined neighborhood-style offices in six cities, as
well as 73 kiosks, which provide information on touch-screen
computers around the clock. Most states have at least one of the
unstaffed kiosks, which are placed in public sites such as shopping
malls, city halls and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Cities that now have HUD storefronts include Albuquerque, N.M.;
Baltimore, Buffalo, N.Y.; Reno, Nev.; Sacramento, Calif., and
Washington. HUD plans to establish at least 10 more storefronts
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's storefront opened on Marietta Street near the Five
Points MARTA station on Feb. 28, too late to be part of the audit.
</P>
<P>
   The new style of office was launched two years ago by HUD
Secretary Andrew Cuomo, who predicted the new service centers would
``translate the lofty ideals of government reinvention into the
down-to-earth reality of improved performance.''
</P>
<P>
   More accessible than a high-rise office, the new facilities are
designed to provide sites for community meetings, training
sessions, and brochures on federal housing programs.
</P>
<P>
   HUD Deputy Secretary Saul N. Ramirez defended the concept as a
plan ``to remove the distance between government and people.'' He
disputed the conclusions of the inspector general report, saying
that they were ``simply wrong'' or ``demonstrate a lack of
understanding of the purposes'' of the storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ramirez conceded that the program could use
better monitoring of its customer service and storefront
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the offices includes a nearby kiosk. Operating just six
of the new offices and kiosks will cost $3.8 million a year, the
inspector general said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal auditors concluded that the storefronts were only
marginally useful because HUD's ``primary'' customers are not
walk-in clients but public housing authorities, lenders and
community groups. The study found these customers generally met
with HUD officials at sites other than the storefront offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customer service provided by the storefront staff was not very
effective,'' the audit concluded after surveying a list of local
contacts provided by the HUD offices. The report said that no
reliable statistics exist on how many people are using the kiosks.
</P>
<P>
   The audit also noted that the storefront offices were designed
to be staffed by so-called HUD's ``community builders.'' That
program was killed by Congress, amid charges from Republicans that
it had become a haven for political patronage.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
