r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     04-11 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 LESS IS MORE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fitness magazine's regular ``Fit People'' column this month
focuses on  &UR; Hilary Swank &LR; , who just won an Oscar for her
performance in ``Boys Don't Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you think she looked a little thin when she received the
award? The magazine describes her training regime and passes along
several of her exercises. ``In six weeks,'' said her personal
trainer,  &UR; Rich Guzman &LR; , ``she dropped her body fat from 22 percent
to 12 percent, and at 5'8'' weighed 115 at her leanest.''
</P>
<P>
   Standard body fat recommendations at high levels of fitness are
21 to 24 percent. Even the editors feel compelled to note that at
Swank's height, ``125 to 160 pounds is a healthier range.''
</P>
<P>
   And 5-foot-1  &UR; Janeane Garofalo &LR; , Marie Claire magazine cover
girl, said she's ``down to 110 pounds. But I'm not proud of losing
weight. It's been a sell-out. I lost weight so I could be
considered for a wider range of acting jobs. I don't pretend that
it's a health kick or that it's just to feel better about myself.
I'm smoking a lot more _ about a half a pack to two packs a day _
and drinking more coffee and Diet Coke and more water, which I
hate. I joined Crunch gym and went for three weeks, but then I
stopped because I couldn't handle the workouts. I continue to
fantasize about what I really want to eat every f_ day. I don't
think I'm sexy, but I do get a lot more compliments now.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the British government's minister for women has
announced a June conference of fashion executives, models and
health experts on the pressure on young women to be thin. Many
young women suffer, said  &UR; Tessa Jowell &LR; , ``because they can't match
the thin ideal that they so often see in the media.'' (And see Who
Said What, below.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; READING MATTERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Best-selling author of financial advice books  &UR; Suze Orman  &LR; _
``The 9 Steps to Financial Freedom'' and ``The Courage to Be Rich''
_ was one of 34 Bay Area authors honored at the San Francisco
Library's Laureates dinner on Monday, April 10.
</P>
<P>
   Orman said that a childhood speech defect had resulted in
reading difficulties, and that she'd read her first two novels only
last January. She called herself ``only laureate who's written more
books than she's read.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``At Hollywood power lunches, I don't feel like I can say, &LR; 
 &UR; `Give me a burger and fries' because I don't want the producer &LR; 
 &UR; and director thinking that's what I eat all the time. I'm afraid &LR; 
 &UR; they'll think, `He's a big fat pig.' So I always say, `Oh, just &LR; 
 &UR; a salad.''' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Nathan Lane &LR;  in TV Guide's spin-off Celebrity Dish, a
magazine about what the stars eat. Celebrity Dish alternates
dieting tips with recipes for such healthful concoctions as One-Pot
Chocolate Peanut Butter bars.
</P>
</TEXT>
