<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOSTON-BIG-DIG-ART-NY     04-11 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-BIG-DIG-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIG DIG' CHIEF FORCED OUT IN BOSTON AND ACCUSED OF HIDING COST
OVERRUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT28 was sent March 10 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The overseer of the most expensive public works project
under way in America, Boston's ``Big Dig,'' was abruptly asked to
step down Tuesday after federal auditors denounced him for staying
deceptively mum for months about $1.4 billion in looming cost
overruns.
</P>
<P>
   The dig, its price tag expected to be possibly $2.8 billion over
budget, at $13.6 billion and rising, is about two-thirds finished.
</P>
<P>
   At its completion, scheduled for 2004, it will have sunk
Boston's raised Central Artery underground, erected two bridges
across the Charles River and linked the Massachusetts Turnpike with
Logan Airport.
</P>
<P>
   For all the criticism of the ousted supervisor, James J.
Kerasiotes, the chairman of the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority,
the Big Dig will tunnel onward, but under different leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts governor, Paul Cellucci, announced Tuesday
that after reviewing a 48-page audit report by the Federal Highway
Administration criticizing the dig's management, he had asked
Kerasiotes to resign and would replace him with Andrew S. Natsios,
the state's secretary of administration and finance. About 60
percent of the dig's money comes from the federal government, but
its management is under state control.
</P>
<P>
   One of the auditors' most serious criticisms of Kerasiotes was
that he knew of the cost overruns two months before a bond issue
for the project in December, but said nothing about the budget
problems until February.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors' report said the silence kept by dig managers about
cost overruns ``stands as one of the most flagrant breaches of the
integrity of the federal/state partnership in the history of the
nearly 85-year-old federal-aid highway program.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, who did not appoint Kerasiotes but has defended him in
the past, took a more understanding view. ``In his zeal to finish
this project,'' Cellucci said, ``he forgot something that's pretty
fundamental in a democracy, and that is that the citizens have the
right to know what it's going to cost. Certainly, the Federal
Highway Administration has the right to have the information.''
</P>
<P>
   The new top digger, Natsios, speaking with Cellucci to reporters
in Boston, said he understood that one of his jobs now was to keep
the project ``completely transparent,'' along with looking for ways
to save money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the big dig needs now is a change in culture,'' said
Natsios, who is known as being so fiscally stingy that a conference
table in his office displays a red sign with the simple word
``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's action, Cellucci said, apparently came as a surprise
to Kerasiotes, who has overseen the project since its beginning in
1991 and has been saying for weeks that despite the mounting
criticism of him, he planned to see the project through to its end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult phone call,'' Cellucci said. ``It was not
what he was expecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes was not available for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The direct source of trouble for Kerasiotes was his long and
aggressive insistence that the project would come in on its $10.8
billion budget and on time. When he suddenly announced in February
that in fact the project was going to be $1.4 billion over budget,
the critics he had been quashing rose up against him with renewed
energy. And the federal officials responsible for the dig's
oversight were unpleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   The deeper problem, it would seem, was his personality. He has
been called a bully by his critics, and is known for his fierce and
bullish style. An aggressive nature seemed in place when he could
argue that it took a tough man to build a tough project
efficiently; but with the cost overrun and recent reports in The
Boston Globe that Big Dig contractors were routinely running amok
financially, he no longer looked tough where it counted most.
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes has not said what he plans to do next, but in a
recent interview he said that he had given up plans to hold public
office and expected to return to the private sector when his work
with the dig was done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
