<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BARAK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MEETS WITH ISRAELI LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although President Clinton had hoped to give a
nudge to the Middle East peace negotiations, he emerged from an
hourlong meeting on Tuesday night with the Israeli prime minister,
Ehud Barak, without any new proposals, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The visit at the White House, suggested by the Israelis, came at
an especially crucial time, with negotiations with Syria stalled,
the deadline for a framework agreement with the Palestinians
looming and the troop withdrawal from Lebanon also nearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are difficult negotiations and discussions, and it's
important that from time to time they meet face to face to take
stock and look at ways that we can ensure that the process stays on
track,'' said the White House's spokesman, Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, speaking to reporters before the Oval Office meeting,
said he hoped the session would provide ``new energy and momentum
to the timeline that we have set.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Clinton said the session was not intended to produce
any dramatic developments. Instead, Clinton sought to hear Barak's
views before a planned session with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also sought to brief Barak on his recent meeting in
Geneva with Hafez Assad, the Syrian president, which revealed
differences that appeared irreconcilable in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said at a brief public appearance before the meeting
with the Israeli leader that while there were ``still differences''
with Assad, ``that's no bleaker than before we met.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility of violence accompanying Israel's
withdrawal from Lebanon, Clinton remarked: ``If Israel pulls out in
accordance with the United Nations resolution, what justification
will anyone have for violence? They've been asking for this for
years and years.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he was asked if he expected the reaction to be peaceful
or serene, Clinton said, ``Serene is a word not normally used in
the context of the Middle East these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other issues Clinton raised was Israel's sale to the
Chinese of military technology, which critics argue was produced
with American financial and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Raising particular concern at the Pentagon is the proposed sale
to China of the Israeli-made Falcon early-warning radar system,
which is similar to the aerial reconnaissance radar in Boeing AWACS
planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about that,'' Clinton told reporters in the Rose
Garden before the session. ``You know I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who also met with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and Sandy Berger, the president's national security adviser, turned
aside questions about the sale, offering only, ``We'll discuss
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
