<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HIGH COURT RULES AGAINST GIRL, 17, IN ABORTION CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Supreme Court on Tuesday ruled a
17-year-old girl cannot have an abortion without first notifying
her parents, even though her parents kicked an older sister out of
the house when that girl revealed she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling in the case of Jane Doe 4 marks the first time the
state high court has rejected a minor girl's plea for a judicial
bypass around telling her parents that she is seeking an abortion.
The parental notification law was passed by the Texas Legislature
last year and signed by Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Three other girls have had their requests for judicial bypass
turned down by trial courts, but the Supreme Court returned each of
those cases to the lower court for further consideration. Because
of the cloak of confidentiality on these cases, it is unclear what
has happened to those girls.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Doe 4's plea for judicial bypass was rejected by a trial
court last month, but the Supreme Court returned it for further
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   That triggered a tirade by Justice Nathan Hecht that some of his
colleagues were trying to undermine the new law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five or six justices in an Austin courthouse are ensuring that
minors throughout the state, sight unseen, can obtain abortions
without telling their parents,'' Hecht wrote in his dissent to the
6-3 ruling.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, all nine justices ruled against the girl.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain a judicial bypass, a girl must demonstrate to the
court that she is mature and informed enough to make a decision or
that it would not be in her best interest to tell her parents.
</P>
<P>
   An opinion signed by seven of the justices said the girl lacks
the maturity and information to make a decision on an abortion
without notifying her parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told the judge she spoke to a doctor and testified that a
past medical problem may make an abortion more complicated, but
(she) was unable to explain how or in what way it might be,'' the
opinion said. ``This demonstrated a lack of comprehension about the
specific risks of the procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices said the girl's increased medical risk also
enhanced the justification for a trial judge to have ruled against
her on the question of what is in her best interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial judge could have determined that the girl's
particular physical needs and possibility of physical danger
outweighed the potential disruption of her family relationship,''
the opinion said.
</P>
<P>
   In the court's March 22 ruling in the case, the justices noted
that the girl told them that when her sister told her parents about
being pregnant, the parents kicked the girl out of the house, cut
off support and have not spoken to her since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doe believes that her parents would treat her similarly if
notified that she is pregnant and seeking an abortion,'' the
justices wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But the court also noted that the girl's testimony left gaps in
the story as to whether there were other reasons why the parents
kicked the older sister out of the house and cut off contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no clear evidence that the minor would suffer the
same fate as her sister should she tell her parents,'' the court
said.
</P>
<P>
   While Hecht and Justice Priscilla Owen joined the majority in
Tuesday's ruling, they also criticized it in a concurring opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Court's reasoning shows that it continues to minimize
parents rights to help children decide whether to have an
abortion,'' Hecht and Owen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Kae McClaughlin of the Texas Abortion Rights Action League said
nothing in Tuesday's ruling will force the girl to carry a baby to
term.
</P>
<P>
   McClaughlin said the girl might tell her parents, might go to a
state like New Mexico or Oklahoma that do not have parental
notification laws or might just seek out an unlicensed abortionist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to note that no court, no judge, no law can
tell the girl to tell her parents,'' McClaughlin said. ``It just
leaves her without a safe medical procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
