<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3874 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-JUDGES-WIVES-BOS &LR;      04-11 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-WIVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGES' EX-WIVES SAY SUIT WILL ALLEGE MALE-BIASED LEGAL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Wendelboe is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest fallout from the infamous New Hampshire divorce
that sparked a judicial crisis, the ex-wives of five New Hampshire
judges have banded together with plans to file a federal lawsuit,
claiming that a close-knit network of lawyers and judges prevented
them from getting a fair shake in divorce court.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing complaints made by Judith O. Thayer in her divorce from
former Supreme Court Justice W. Stephen Thayer, the women claim
that New Hampshire's old-boy legal community denied them proper
legal representation, forcing two of the women to rely on a
non-lawyer who describes himself as a ``legal reformer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Thayer resigned from the court a week and a half ago
amid charges he had tried to intervene in cases in which he had an
interest, including his own divorce. The Chief Justice is facing
impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   While some fear the crisis is causing the state's legal system
irreparable harm, the ex-wives of some judges and lawyers say it
may have served some public good. Finally, they say, others are
seeing just how unfair that system is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief to know that I'm not alone,'' said Betsy
Millard, who got divorced in 1985 from a trial attorney who has
since become a state Superior Court Judge. But ``to feel that I'm
not so isolated _ that's not comforting. That's profoundly
disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Millard and at least four other women, whose ex-husbands are
judges on various levels in the state, have expressed interest in
the not-yet-filed suit. The effort is being spearheaded by Caroline
Douglas, a lawyer whose torrid divorce from former Supreme Court
Justice Charles Douglas drew national attention. It is unclear
whether Judith Thayer plans to be part of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The women plan to argue that their divorce court troubles
represented gender discrimination and violated their rights to
equal protection under the law.
</P>
<P>
   And while some legal experts say the lawsuit's chances of
success are slim, some New Hampshire attorneys and political
leaders say the case still highlights a difficult truth about the
New Hampshire legal community. It's sometimes hard for the spouse
of a lawyer or judge to get represenation at all, they say, in a
small, close-knit state where the chances are high that a judge's
and lawyer's paths will cross again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty small world up there in New Hampshire, in the
judicial circles,'' said Millard, who now lives in New Mexico. And
some lawyers, she said, seem to fear that ``if they know they're
going up before a judge, that they may have to pay a price down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   When her case began, Millard said, she felt coerced into taking
what she now considers bad legal advice: accepting every intial
demand from her ex-husband, who later became a Superior Court
judge. In the protracted child-support battle that has followed,
Millard said, she has felt bombarded with motions. And she has
wound up braving the New Hampshire legal system without a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire state Representative Francine Wendelboe said she
has heard similar complaints from a number of judges' and
attorney's ex-wives. She has become a clearinghouse of sorts for
their complaints, after she raised public concerns about similar
patterns in the Thayer and Douglas cases.
</P>
<P>
   After Thayer's resignation, Wendelboe sent a letter to state
legislative leaders, suggesting the state should examine every
divorce case involving a member of the judiciary, and perhaps every
member of the bar. After a story about her quest ran in the
Union-Leader of Manchester, she said, ``all of a sudden, I started
having these women calling me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some were ex-wives of judges, she said. Others were ex-wives of
lawyers. Many had similar complaints. Some said their cases had
been bounced around to different courts, or that they had been
bombarded with motions from hyper-aggressive lawyers. Others said
that while their ex-husbands could get free representation from
friends, they had to scramble to pay for legal help _ and sometimes
had to search to even find it.
</P>
<P>
   It can be tough to find representation in such highly-charged
cases, said Karen Heller, who practices family law in Manchester,
N.H., and recently tried to find representation for two different
judges' wives. She had declined their cases herself, she said,
because she has a policy of not handling open cases. But when she
shopped around for other lawyers, she found few who would touch the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Many didn't want to get themselves into legal battles that would
lead to future conflicts of interest for themselves or their firms,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a problem because New Hampshire is so small,''
Heller said. Many lawyers practice across the state and deal with
many judges, she said, instead of concentrating their work in
particular counties with more self-contained legal system.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers have the option of settling their disputes with binding
arbitration, but some choose not to do so, Heller said. And while
it's possible, in some cases, to try divorce cases in other states,
she said, many divorce lawyers are far more comfortable practicing
in their own states, where the judges and legal precedents are more
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, complaints about unfair treatment in divorce courts
are more often raised by men, who sometimes complain that the
courts demonstrate bias against fathers, said Jack Beerman, a
professor at the Boston University School of Law, where Stephen
Thayer has taught.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-wives' legal challenge, Beerman said, would likely face
some serious hurdles in the federal courts, which are reluctant to
touch family-law cases in general, and tend to avoid broad attacts
on the way state courts operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal courts stay out of these kinds of disputes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wendelboe questions how many women will ultimately join the
case, after all. ``It's a disorganized effort,'' she said. ``They
have not filed a suit yet. I don't think they've signed on the
dotted line.'' Because it is so early in the process, it is unclear
who would be named as defendants in the suit, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although they might be willing to go public with their
stories, they might not be willing to go through the expense and
the emotional turmoil'' of reopening proceedings, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the divorce court controversy has sparked much discussion
in legislative circles, Wendelboe said. Since the majority of
judges in New Hampshire are men, some have seen the case as a
feminist issue, she said. But some male legislators have raised
concerns about the saga, as well, she said, wondering if judges and
lawyers have been able to shield themselves unfairly from
divorce-court woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides aren't particularly happy,'' Wendelboe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-ART-NY     04-11 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE GOP TO PROPOSE USING PRIVATE INSURANCE TO HELP PAY FOR
MEDICARE DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also MAINE-DRUGS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT34 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans said Tuesday that their proposal
for Medicare coverage of prescription drugs, to be announced this
week, would use private insurance subsidized by the government to
help pay the drug costs for millions of people who are elderly or
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement will be a milestone on the road to such
coverage, a firm proposal by leaders of the majority party in the
House that says how they would spend up to $40 billion over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican working on the proposal said Tuesday: ``Our plan is
very similar to the president's, but better. We'll offer a
voluntary drug benefit, available to all Medicare beneficiaries and
run by the private sector, as the president wants.''
</P>
<P>
   In his plan, President Clinton specifies details of the basic
drug benefit, including the co-payments charged to beneficiaries;
House Republicans will invite private insurers to offer a variety
of competing drug plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could pick the policy that best suited you, depending on
your needs and your income,'' said a Republican working on the
proposal. ``There would be more choice, more variety in the design
of benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans will announce their proposal a few days before
the spring recess, when Democrats plan to hit the issue hard in
political events around the country. ``Our guys couldn't go home
empty-handed,'' one representative said.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing their proposal with Clinton's, House Republicans said
their plan would provide more definite protection to people with
high drug expenses; less insurance for routine, ordinary drug
expenses; and less of a subsidy to affluent Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's plan, the government would directly
subsidize premiums for everyone who signed up for drug benefits.
Under the House Republican plan, the main subsidy would be
indirect: the government would pay most of the costs for a small
number of beneficiaries with the highest drug expenses, so that
insurers could charge lower premiums to everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the House said that they, like Clinton, would
also provide financial assistance to low-income beneficiaries. The
details have not been decided, they said, but they want to pay the
premiums and perhaps other costs for people with incomes up to 35
percent or 50 percent above the poverty level. Under federal
guidelines, a couple is classified as poor if has less than $11,250
of income this year.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, the health policy coordinator at the White
House, said he did not know all the details of the House Republican
proposal. ``But from what we gather,'' he said, ``it appears to be
a structurally unworkable policy that does not ensure access to
affordable prescription drugs for all beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans said they had consulted with the presidential
campaign of Gov. George W. Bush. But the proposal was devised
mainly by senior Republicans on the two House committees that share
authority over Medicare. Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois
supervised the process; Rep. Bill Thomas of California had the
biggest role in shaping the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and the Senate have approved budget blueprints
that would provide up to $40 billion over five years for Medicare
drug benefits, roughly the same amount envisioned in the first five
years of the Clinton plan.
</P>
<P>
   In a document describing their proposal, House Republicans said
it would provide ``a voluntary private drug coverage option for all
seniors.'' This approach is favored by the drug industry but
opposed by the Health Insurance Association of America, which says
its members are not interested in selling drug insurance because
they could not keep the premiums affordable.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans said they would try to overcome the insurance
industry's objections by having the government pick up most of the
cost for a small number of beneficiaries with very high drug
expenses. This would permit insurers to charge lower premiums _ and
is therefore a kind of indirect subsidy _ to all Medicare
beneficiaries who buy drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Drug expenses are highly concentrated; 5 percent of Medicare
beneficiaries have drug costs exceeding $5,000 a year, but they
account for 29 percent of all spending on drugs by people in
Medicare's conventional fee-for-service program.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans will not be too specific this week. But they
said that under their proposal, the government might pay 80 percent
of the costs for the 5 percent of beneficiaries with the highest
drug expenses. Insurers would be responsible for the remainder of
those costs, so they would have a financial incentive to control
the use of prescription drugs, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   While clearly not embracing the House Republican plan, Charles
N. Kahn III, president of the Health Insurance Association of
America, said: ``This proposal is different from others we have
seen in the past. We need to study it before we decide what
position to take on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa J. Raines, senior vice president of Genzyme, the
biotechnology company, said: ``The House Republican proposal for a
high-risk insurance pool, with significant federal subsidies, is an
important intellectual contribution to the debate. This could bring
down premiums 25 percent below what they would otherwise be. It
would help drug-benefit plans manage their financial exposure,
thereby making the Medicare market more attractive to them.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans said they would create a new entity, separate
from the agency that now runs Medicare, to administer the drug
program. Republicans said the new entity, known as the Medicare
board, could eventually supervise the health maintenance
organizations that now provide care to 6.6 million of the 39
million Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of the Republican proposal, prepared by the House
Commerce Committee, describes it this way: ``All Medicare
beneficiaries would have the option of purchasing drug coverage
through the board. The board would contract with insurers operating
on both a local and national basis and would provide information to
beneficiaries about their options.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans said they assumed that insurers would work
with companies that have years of experience in managing drug
benefits. Such ``pharmacy benefit managers'' typically negotiate
with drug manufacturers to obtain large discounts for their
customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
