u f BC-AETNA-SUIT-NYT &LR;      04-11 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AETNA SETTLES TEXAS SUIT AND AGREES TO CURTAIL DOCTOR INCENTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aetna Inc., the nation's largest managed-care insurer, settled a
lawsuit in Texas Tuesday by agreeing to change several practices
that doctors and consumer advocates portrayed as undermining
patient care, like rewarding physicians who stayed within cost
limits.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna said it was ready to make similar changes in other states,
but officials in New York and Connecticut said that, on first look,
the Texas concessions were not far-reaching enough to satisfy their
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were the first since the company's new chief
executive, William H. Donaldson, pledged last month to improve
Aetna U.S. Healthcare's relations with doctors.
</P>
<P>
   John Cornyn, the attorney general of Texas, said the agreement
would curtail financial incentives that ``tempt doctors to deny
necessary medical care'' by linking their incomes to holding down
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna said it would stop paying a set amount for each
health-plan member to doctors whose practices have fewer than 100
health maintenance organization members; instead, they would be
paid a fee for each service. Doctors with more than 100 HMO members
would continue to be paid per member.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said he hoped the settlement would be a precedent for
settling other lawsuits against insurance companies like Humana
Inc., PacifiCare and the NYLcare unit that Aetna was forced to sell
to Texas Blue Cross and Blue Shield.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the changes, resulting from a year-long
negotiation with the attorney general, would also let patients take
appeals to independent reviewers when payments are denied for
prescription drugs, emergency care, and procedures regarded as
experimental.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to recently passed laws in most states that require
outside reviews, Aetna had earlier established external review for
denials of other types of care that are deemed medically
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna will also publish a pamphlet explaining how it pays
doctors in Texas, and it will establish a company omsbudsman to
support customers who have health insurance complaints. The
attorney general's office will oversee the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the American Medical Association and the Texas
Medical Association said the agreement was a step in the right
direction. But they said it showed the need for national patients'
rights legislation that would remove obstacles to medical
malpractice lawsuits against insurers. Employers and insurers
strongly oppose that right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna officials said the agreement, in which the company
acknowledges no wrongdoing, would take the wind out of the sails of
class-action lawsuits pending against Aetna and other managed-care
companies. But a spokesman for lawyers in several of the suits
argued Tuesday that the agreement would strengthen the plaintiffs'
criticism of Aetna and other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Ross, a vice president of the Texas Medical Association,
said Aetna had made ``a significant shift, for complex reasons that
I am sure were associated with their stock price.'' Aetna's shares
have rebounded recently after dropping sharply when the lawsuits
were filed. They gained 18.75 cents Tuesday, to $58.25 each, on the
New York Stock Exchange, still 40 percent lower than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In another move long demanded by medical associations, Aetna
said that it would no longer insist that Texas doctors in small
group practices accept low-paying members of health maintenance
organizations or give up the business of other, better-paying Aetna
networks. The rule still applies to groups of 10 or more primary
care doctors and 25 or more specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fundamental change in our business model,'' said Dr.
Arthur Leibowitz, chief medical officer of Aetna U.S. Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   David F. Simon, chief legal counsel of the health care unit,
said he had offered to discuss changes based on the Texas agreement
with Richard Blumenthal, the attorney general of Connecticut, and
Eliot L. Spitzer, the attorney general of New York. Both officials
said they would meet with Aetna but also planned to proceed with
previously announced investigations of its practices.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, who has sued Physicians Health Plan, a big
Connecticut-based HMO, said the practice of paying a set amount for
each patient should be ended for all doctors _ not just those with
relatively few HMO patients.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brown, a spokesman for Spitzer, said his investigation
would also continue. The New York attorney general has been
examining Aetna's methods of approving or denying payment for care.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said that the ``No. 1 concern'' of the HMO industry was to
set up procedures that would resolve their problems without facing
lawsuits in which individuals have won awards as high as $100
million. There are 40 individual suits pending against Aetna in
addition to seven class-action suits.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Texas agreement, he noted, Aetna could be fined or
held in contempt, but there would not be punitive damages like
those that the class-action lawyers, fresh from lucrative victories
against cigarette makers, were expected to seek.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no money in it for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Joey Langston of Booneville, Miss., national coordinator for
many of the class-action lawyers, said that Aetna, in the Texas
agreement, acknowledged problems that ``are part of the factual
basis for our claims.'' The plaintiffs will ask Aetna to ``make
accommodations to patients and enrollees who have been harmed by
these policies over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   A special panel of federal judges is expected to decide soon
whether the class-action suits nationwide should be consolidated in
one court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
