<HEADLINE>
QUARTEY READY, WEIGHTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS - Felix Trinidad, who had difficulty making 147 pounds
when he was a welterweight, was like a new fighter when he moved up
to 154 to challenge David Reid in March. He seemed to be stronger,
faster, better. And he won easily.
</P>
<P>
   Will Ike Quartey experience the same thing when he faces IBF
junior middleweight champion Fernando Vargas here on Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   One of few knocks against Quartey is that he tends to fade late
in fights. He seemed to do so against Oscar De La Hoya in February
of last year, when De La Hoya rallied in the late rounds to win a
controversial decision that Quartey still disputes.
</P>
<P>
   If Quartey (begin ital)did(end ital) fade, adviser Godwin Asifo
suggested, it was because he had difficulty making the 147-pound
weight limit. He reportedly had to lose more than 10 pounds in the
final weeks to reach that figure.
</P>
<P>
   If true, that might also explain at least in part Quartey's
uncharacteristic lack of aggression against De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a difficult time (with weight),'' Asifo said. ``And
when you have a difficult time, you don't want to spend yourself.
You want to pace yourself. That limits your aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (154) is comfortable, this is where he should be. Just
like Trinidad.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Vargas is expected to face Trinidad if he can get
by Quartey, and one would think Quartey would have the same option
if (begin ital)he(end ital) wins.
</P>
<P>
   However, Quartey said he'd rather fight De La Hoya again first.
</P>
<P>
   He said the fact he lost a controversial decision to De La Hoya
no longer bothers him, but he seems to remain bitter - ``I think I
won the fight, that's it'' - and clearly wants to set the record
straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer to fight Oscar (rather than Trinidad). I want to
prove I'm the best fighter in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, there's a problem: De La Hoya fights at 147 pounds
while Quartey fights at 154.
</P>
<P>
   Neither would be willing to move to the other's weight, but
there might be an opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be willing to do it at a catch weight (between the
two weights),'' Asifo said.
</P>
<P>
   No respect: Quartey isn't showing Vargas much respect.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas has repeatedly employed the fight's slogan in pre-fight
hype, ``Two Warriors, One War,'' the implication being he will
stand toe-to-toe with a fighter known for his physical strength.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey doesn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's going to fight (aggressively),'' he said.
``He's not as strong as (Jose Luis) Lopez (with whom Quartey drew).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too young (22) to go to war.''
</P>
<P>
   New 'do: Quartey, from Ghana, Africa, is sporting striking
bleach-blond hair ``to change my image,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good idea, but Quartey has a long way to go: He's one of
the most soft-spoken, taciturn fighters around. And while English
is a primary language of Ghana, his accent is so thick it's
difficult to understand him.
</P>
<P>
   That's unfortunate for him because fighters rely heavily upon
self promotion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
