<HEADER>
A3883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PHILLY-GUN-SUIT-NYT &LR;      04-11 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-GUN-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA SUES 14 HANDGUN MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Texas, Conn., Ga.)   By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philadelphia filed a lawsuit against 14 handgun makers Tuesday,
despite a new Pennsylvania law that prohibits such suits, charging
the manufacturers with negligently distributing their products to
make it easy for criminals and juveniles to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's action brings to 31 the number of cities or
counties to sue the gun industry over the past year and a half and
adds to the pressure on the firearms companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia lawsuit, like most of the other cities', has a
dual purpose. The cities hope to receive damage awards to offset
the costs of hospital care and police services related to gun
crime, and they also hope the courts would order gun makers to
change their practices.
</P>
<P>
   One of the gun makers named in Philadelphia's suit is Smith &AMP;
Wesson, even though several cities, along with the states of New
York and Connecticut and the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development, have dropped claims against the company after it
agreed to broad restrictions on the ways it makes and distributes
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   A Philadelphia official said the city was unwilling to waive
claims against Smith &AMP; Wesson without a better agreement that
forced the company to give documents to the cities that would be
useful in the suits against other gun makers, and that provided
some financial settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's lawsuit is in many ways similar to those brought
by a number of the other cities and counties, said David Kairys, a
professor of law at Temple University who is an adviser to
Philadelphia and many of the other municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how the lawsuits against the gun makers are
spreading, a number of organizations representing community groups
joined Philadelphia. These included Guardian Civic League, a group
representing black police officers in Philadelphia, Aspira Inc., an
organization that provides services for Hispanic youths in the
city, and the Residents Advisory Board, which represents public
housing residents.
</P>
<P>
   The groups do not give Philadelphia any greater legal claim,
Kairys said. ``But I think they will help in court because it makes
it clear that this kind of reckless proliferation of handguns
really is a nuisance with a significant effect on the tenor of
everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   One challenge for Philadelphia is that the state legislature
passed a law late last year barring cities from suing the gun
industry, a law similar to that passed in more than a dozen states,
including Texas and Georgia, where the legislature is sympathetic
to the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Trujillo, the Philadelphia city solicitor, said he did
not believe the law would be an obstacle because it only prohibited
cities from filing suits against legal marketing practices by the
gun manufacturers. But, Trujillo said, ``Our lawsuit is based on
the claim that their marketing practices are illegal and a public
nuisance, and under Pennsylvania law a public nuisance is a
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit contends that the gun makers have made no efforts to
stop what are known as straw purchases, when a person without a
criminal record buys a gun on behalf of a criminal who is barred
from buying the gun himself, nor have they attempted to cut off
suspicious customers who make repeated purchases of large numbers
of cheap semiautomatic pistols that are likely destined for
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, one straw purchaser in Philadelphia bought 41 handguns
in six weeks, the suit said, while another bought 57 in three
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendants knowingly and recklessly market and distribute
handguns _ a product designed to kill that is the primary tool for
violent crime _ in a manner that facilitates their use in crime in
the city of Philadelphia,'' the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on studies by the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms, the suit also said that the ``defendants produce, market
and distribute substantially more handguns than they reasonably
expect to sell to law-abiding purchasers, knowingly participating
in and facilitating the criminal handgun market.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the 13 other gun makers named in the suit were Beretta USA
Corp., Bryco Arms Inc., Colt's Manufacturing Co., Glock Inc. and
Sturm, Ruger and Co.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, in the past two weeks, the gun makers have been hit
by the announcement that six states have begun an antitrust
investigation of the gun industry to determine whether it has
engaged in a conspiracy to damage Smith &AMP; Wesson after it agreed to
the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3884 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PERU-ELECT-735(2TAKES     04-11 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECT-735(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION LEADER CALLS FOR PROTESTS UNLESS THERE IS RUNOFF
ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ Preparing for what appeared to be an expected
announcement that President Alberto Fujimori had squeaked out a
victory in Sunday's election, his opponent, Alejandro Toledo, said
on Tuesday that he would not accept anything short of a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   And he insisted he would take part in a second round only if the
electoral agencies were totally revamped since the first round
provoked charges of fraud from official election monitors and the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Joe Lockhart, a White House spokesman, said on
Tuesday that the United States would raise ``serious questions'' if
Peru did not hold a second round of voting. ``We expect there will
be a runoff, and I think serious questions will be raised if the
vote count indicated something otherwise,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   With 90.82 percent of the official vote count complete, the
central election authority reported on Tuesday evening that
Fujimori had won 49.79 percent of the vote to Toledo's 40.39
percent.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate needs 50 percent plus one vote to avert a runoff.
The latest count actually showed a slight decrease in Fujimori's
percentage from tallies earlier in the day, but his vote percentage
could climb again as ballots come in from remote jungle and Andean
villages where the president is strongly supported by Indian
voters. International election observers also say that election
controls were least stringent in such areas.
</P>
<P>
   The government said final results will be released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, who is running for a third five-year term, has denied
that anything but minimal irregularities took place, and said he
would resist suggestions by the Clinton administration, several
European governments and Peru's congressionally-appointed ombudsman
that a second round vote be held.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to accept the will of the Peruvian people,''
Fujimori told reporters on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, the Organization of American States and several
Peruvian and international election monitoring and polling groups
reported that quick-counts of sample vote tally sheets indicated
that Fujimori fell at least two percentage points short of a
majority. Several polls of voters leaving the voting sites actually
had Toledo, a 54-year-old business school professor, ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Organization of American States observation team
has publicly criticized long and unexplained delays in the delivery
of ballots and tally sheets to computer centers, and he said
monitors could not determine where the counts were taking place.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reports that on some ballots the names of rivals
to Fujimori were waxed over, so that only his name could be marked;
that in some cases ballots had been printed without Toledo's
photograph, and that some ballots were pre-marked.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, election authorities completed their count by midnight
of election day and released total unofficial results the next day.
In that election, Fujimori vanquished several opponents with almost
two-thirds of the official count.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Peruvian election officials said they would deliver a
reliable _ if not the absolutely official _ total vote count within
24 hours of the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Toledo said he would lead nonstop peaceful
demonstrations across Peru. But he also reached out to the
military, appealing to it not to take part in election fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to invoke the pride of the Peruvian armed forces,''
Toledo told a throng of thousands of people who gathered in
downtown Lima on Tuesday afternoon, ``so that they resist the
pressures they are now under to block the will of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that ``we need a change of chef and waiters,'' he
demanded that he be allowed the equal access to television networks
that he had been denied in the first-round campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing his words carefully, Toledo appealed to the people to
remain calm, adding, ``I am not going to be responsible for putting
fuel on the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's calls for protests came as tens of thousands of
demonstrators gathered in Lima, Iquitos, Arequipa and several other
cities, blocking traffic, honking car horns and picketing outside
government facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The police stepped up patrols of the cities with armored trucks
mounted with water canon. Army and police units around the
presidential palace were reinforced.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Toledo replaced the faded jeans and red bandanna he has worn the
last few days with a dark suit and tie.
</P>
<P>
   While calling on Fujimori to meet with him to resolve growing
tensions, Toledo provocatively suggested that there was a growing
level of discontent over the election process in the armed forces,
which remain a powerful political force in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know I can't reveal,'' he said. Then directing his
remarks to the armed forces, he said, ``I am asking that they not
be pressured to continue breaking the rules. I ask that they not
participate more in the polarization among Peruvians.''
</P>
<P>
   A restructuring of the military command late last year put
allies of Fujimori's intelligence chief, Vladimiro Montesinos, in
all the top assignments in the Defense Ministry and in regional
headquarters. But many junior officers, spurred on by retired
senior officers, are said to be upset with the way the election was
handled and the way promotions in the military now depend on
political connections to Fujimori and his inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   Leading a chorus of criticism by former officers has been
retired Gen. Francisco Morales Bermudez, the last military dictator
who ruled Peru in the late 1970s. In an interview with the
newspaper El Comercio published on Tuesday, he was quoted as
saying, ``This is the most fraudulent and aberrant election process
in our national history. Toledo was really the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the campaign, Toledo appealed for support among the army
and police, promising to raise salaries and give soldiers the right
to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Senior aides to Toledo said he was in contact with influential
officers in the army, but they did not reveal the content of the
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has never held high government office, and he is
virtually untested as a leader. His political party, Peru Posible,
is little more than a civic group and does not have a strong
organization. But in his surprising surge in the final weeks of the
campaign, he connected strongly with working- class urban voters,
millions of whom like him are of mixed Indian-Latino blood. He
attracted large crowds in the campaign throughout the country, even
though he did not have the funds to offer supporters food or
transportation as is customary in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a bricklayer and fish monger, one who shined shoes as
a boy and won scholarships to earn two masters degrees and a
doctorate in the United States, Toledo was viewed as the embodiment
of a Peruvian dream come true. He has promised to be ``the
president of the poor'' even while offering a centrist platform
that includes government loans to small business to create jobs and
tax incentives to export-oriented industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo has been widely criticized for leading tens of
thousands of people on the presidential palace Sunday night before
more than a few official results were even counted. Protesters set
bonfires in front of the palace before police fired tear gas to
disperse the crowd, and some businesses in downtown Lima were
vandalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
