u p BC-GORE-SCHOOLS-NYT &LR;      04-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: OHIO)  
 GORE BRUSHES UP ON POLITICAL LESSONS WHILE ATTENDING ELEMENTARY
SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ The last time a vice president tried to help a
student spell a word with the national press corps watching, he put
an ``e'' at the end of ``potato,'' suffered national humiliation
and lost the election that fall.
</P>
<P>
   So it was perhaps with Dan Quayle in mind that Vice President Al
Gore stayed mum Tuesday while observing first graders at Avondale
Elementary School struggle to spell ``sincerely.'' (The kids and
their teacher spelled it ``sincerly.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous, I guess,'' said the teacher, Stacie
Magill.
</P>
<P>
   And who could blame her, with the room packed with television
crews, newspaper reporters and photographers recording the second
installment of what Gore calls ``school days,'' his all-day tours
of public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The events have provided Gore, the presumptive Democratic
nominee for president, a forum in which to show his concern about
education, praise the work of teachers _ whose national unions
support him _ and talk up his proposals for expanding
prekindergarten programs, rebuilding aging schools, reducing class
sizes and helping parents afford college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Avondale offered a useful backdrop for many of those issues. The
109-year-old building, though in good condition, needs an
air-conditioning system and is overcrowded: during recess, children
watch television sitting in hallways; art and music classes are
held in a trailer.
</P>
<P>
   And the school, which is in one of Columbus' poorest
neighborhoods, is a showcase for an array of government programs:
more than 90 percent of its children qualify for subsidized
lunches, it receives federal Title I funds and many of its students
attend remedial reading classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to be doing a lot more to bring revolutionary
improvements to our schools,'' Gore told parents and teachers in
the school's library. ``If I'm entrusted with the presidency,
that's going to be my top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics, of course, was not far from the surface. Columbus is a
potential swing city in a battleground state that many Democrats
say Gore needs to win to defeat his Republican rival, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, who leads him in polls here.
</P>
<P>
   Though both city and state tend to vote Republican, President
Clinton and Gore took Ohio's 21 electoral votes in 1996, and
finished a respectable second in Columbus that year.
</P>
<P>
   As he did before his first school-day event, in Michigan, Gore
spent the night at the home of a teacher, Susan Fadley, keeping her
up past midnight with chit-chat about their families and education
policy. This morning, Fadley's husband, Rick, cooked Gore an omelet
before the vice president made his way through a cold drizzle to
the heavily guarded school.
</P>
<P>
   Gore greeted children in the cafeteria as they ate breakfasts of
cold cereal and juice, helped students in Fadley's kindergarten
class spell their names and make a collage from magazine scraps
depicting the African continent in art class.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting with parents and teachers in the library, Gore
argued that the government could help working parents spend more
time with their children by raising the minimum wage, encouraging
more flexible work hours and requiring businesses to provide
family-leave time.
</P>
<P>
   He also used the meeting to attack Bush's proposal to take
federal funds from failing schools and allow parents to use the
money to send their children to other public or private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most cases, that means the kids would be moving to the next
school district over, crowding into classrooms that are already
overcrowded,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, Gore taste-tested a government-subsidized meal of
wrinkled-looking sausages, French toast, milk and an apple. And he
tried his hand at co-teaching Juanita Mitchem's fifth-grade
geometry class.
</P>
<P>
   Hands on hips, he strolled between the desks, offering helpful
tips with problems and looking every bit like a stern-faced vice
principal _ except for his occasional nods and winks at the
assembled press corps.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gore's presence here was meant to speak to voting-age
parents through their children, he also did something any fifth
grader could appreciate. As Mitchem was completing her lesson, Gore
raised a hand to his lips and, with a sheepish glance at the
reporters, suppressed a yawn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
