<HEADER>
A3891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH12-COX     04-11 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush invokes Lincoln in `new prosperity agenda'
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday brought his
presidential campaign to a working-class neighborhood that
Republicans often bypass to talk about a subject Republicans often
ignore.
</P>
<P>
   In a no-frills meeting room at Cleveland's West Side Ecumenical
Ministry, Bush unveiled his $41 billion ``new prosperity agenda,''
designed to lift the working poor into the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the names of Abraham Lincoln and Theodore Roosevelt,
Bush said the Republican Party has a ``higher and older tradition''
of using government to ``promote the rewards of work.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Lincoln, Bush told the crowd of 250 community and
religious leaders, who financed colleges, welcomed immigrants and
used the Homestead Act to give Americans a ``piece of land and a
start in life.''
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Bush said his initiative would cut taxes for the
working poor, improve access to health insurance, help them buy
homes and make it easier for them to save their hard-earned money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for a new prosperity initiative that reflects the
spirit of Lincoln's reforms _ a plan to help remove obstacles on
the road to the middle class, a plan to clear a path for all.
Instead of helping people cope with their need, we will help them
move beyond it,'' said Bush, who was introduced by Gov. Bob Taft,
his Ohio campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Bush targeted those just leaving welfare, American's new
immigrants and Americans who for years have struggled from paycheck
to paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economy must also honor and reward the hard work of
factory and field, of waiting tables and driving cabs _ not just
enterprise, but sheer effort, not just technology, but toil,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His pledges rang hollow, however, to supporters of his
Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign aides were outside the community center with a
written statement attacking Bush. It cited, among other things, a
New York Times story Tuesday that said as governor of Texas, Bush
had not made health care a priority, despite his state's long
record in poor public health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is more interested in a tax giveaway for the wealthy than
health care for working people,'' Douglas Hattaway, Gore's
spokesman, said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a Bush senior campaign adviser, said the Times
article did not accurately represent Bush's record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Ecumenical Ministry community center, which provides
a variety of social services to 51,000 people _ mostly single
mothers _ Bush received a warm reception. Before the speech, Bush
toured El Barrio, another West Side community center that serves
the city's Hispanics. While at El Barrio, he chatted in Spanish,
visited a training class for bank tellers, and posed for a picture
with a mother and her two children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has previously discussed the tax cut proposals that were in
his speech, but the other proposals Tuesday were unveiled for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the tax cut plan would reduce the current 15
percent tax bracket to 10 percent for the first $6,000 of taxable
income for single taxpayers with no children, to $10,000 for single
parents and $12,000 for married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said a single-parent family of three now starts paying
federal income taxes at about $21,000 in income. ``Under my plan,
federal taxes don't begin until $31,000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His health insurance plan would ``promote individual choice''
and ``rely on private insurance,'' he said. It would provide a
credit of up to $2,000 per family to cover up to 90 percent of
health insurance for uninsured families earning less than $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   To promote home ownership, Bush would permit participants in the
federal government's Section 8 rent voucher program to use a year's
worth of rental payments as a down payment. For those not in the
voucher program, Bush proposed using a federal subsidy of up to
$1,500 to help make a down payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in private property so strongly, and so firmly, I
want everyone to have some,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for the working poor to save, said Bush, so he wants
to help them by giving banks a federal tax credit to match savings
of up to $300. The participants could withdraw their savings
tax-free for education, to help start a business or to buy a home.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to fight poverty a new way, said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``For decades our government tried to fight poverty by
redistributing income, often leaving a legacy of dependence,'' he
said. ``The great promise of our time is to fight poverty by
building the wealth of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of Bush's $41 billion initiative to help the working
poor
</P>
<P>
   Tax relief:
</P>
<P>
   _ Current 15 percent tax bracket would be cut to 10 percent for
the first $6,000 of income for single taxpayers, the first $10,000
for single parents and the first $12,000 for married couples.
</P>
<P>
   _ Existing child tax credit would be increased from $500 to
$1,000 per child.
</P>
<P>
   _ The percentage of total income taxes paid by those earning
more than $100,000 would increase from 62 percent to 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Health care
</P>
<P>
   _ A credit of up to $2,000 per family to cover 90 percent of
health insurance costs for families earning less than $30,000 not
already covered by a government health program or an employer plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reduce health insurance costs for small businesses and their
employees by allowing them to buy policies from multi-state
professional associations.
</P>
<P>
   Home ownership opportunities
</P>
<P>
   _ Permit participants in federal government's Section 8 rental
voucher program to use up to a year's worth of vouchers to finance
down payments on homes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide $1 billion in matching grants to lenders to help
650,000 low-income families not enrolled in Section 8 make down
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Help build savings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide tax credits to banks that match savings deposits of up
to $300 by low-income investors. Savings can be withdrawn tax-free
for education, to help start a business or buy a home.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
