<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3894 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-POVERTY-2TAKES(T     04-11 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POVERTY-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES TAX CREDIT FOR PURCHASE OF HEALTH INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Fleshing out his frequent pledge to remove
``obstacles on the road to the middle class,'' Gov. George W. Bush
entered the national debate over health care policy Tuesday by
proposing a tax credit of up to $2,000 a family to help low- and
moderate-income working people buy health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The credit, worth $34.7 billion over five years, was the most
costly of an array of proposed tax incentives and vouchers for
health care and home ownership that Bush packaged Tuesday as ``a
new prosperity initiative'' intended to help immigrants, former
welfare recipients and other low-income Americans make poverty a
``stage, not a fate.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall program, another step in Bush's effort to position
himself as a ``new kind of Republican,'' would cost $41.6 billion
over five years. His aides said it would help as many as 18 million
of the nation's 44 million uninsured buy health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing the plan here in Cleveland at the West Side
Ecumenical Ministry, a faith-based charity, the Texas governor, who
has been steadily trying to reach out to independents and
moderates, spoke of ``those living in prosperity's shadow.'' He
also quoted Lincoln's exhortation that ``every poor man should have
a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for a new prosperity initiative that reflects the
spirit of Lincoln's reforms,'' Bush said. ``A plan to help remove
obstacles on the road to the middle class. A plan to clear a path
for all. Instead of helping people cope with their need, we will
help them to move beyond it. With the same energy and activism that
others have brought to expanding government, we must expand
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech, delivered in a battleground state in the
presidential campaign, was Bush's first of the campaign to address
health care, an issue the Democrats consider one of their strongest
in this election. The Democrats say Bush is particularly vulnerable
on the issue because his state has the nation's second-highest
number of uninsured and some of the highest rates of AIDS,
tuberculosis and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the campaign of the apparent Democratic nominee, Vice
President Al Gore, attacked Bush over Texas' record, saying that
with his new proposal he was trying to ``divert attention from the
deplorable state of health care and other issues in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides defended his health care record, distributing a
fact sheet that said Texas had slowed the growth in the number of
uninsured to 3 percent in his five years in the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign distanced the governor from remarks made by the
state's health commissioner, Dr. William R. Archer III. In an
interview with The New York Times for an article published Tuesday,
Archer said among other things that Texas' high teen-age pregnancy
rate had come about because the state's Hispanic population lacked
the belief ``that getting pregnant is a bad thing.'' Ari Fleischer,
a spokesman for Bush, said Tuesday that Archer's remarks were ``not
in keeping with the spirit of the governor's comments'' on health
care.
</P>
<P>
   (Archer himself issued a statement Tuesday apologizing for his
remarks. ``I deeply regret that I have created an erroneous
impression about Hispanics and teen pregnancy,'' the statement said
in part.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech in Cleveland was the third he had made since
effectively winning the Republican nomination last month in which
he moved away from the conservative tone of the primary campaign.
Last week he visited another swing state, Pennsylvania, to propose
a series of environmental measures to hasten the cleanup of
abandoned industrial sites. And a week before that, he unveiled a
five-year, $5 billion program that would provide grants to states
for teacher training and other measures to improve childhood
literacy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan he introduced in Cleveland, which was modeled on
bipartisan legislation in Congress, Americans without health care
coverage and not poor enough to qualify for Medicaid could receive
a tax credit of up to $1,000 an individual or $2,000 a family to
cover 90 percent of the cost of insurance. The credit would phase
out with rising income, so that individuals earning $45,000 a year,
or families earning $60,000, would no longer be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said the credit would be refundable, meaning that
people would qualify even if they had no federal tax liability. And
the tax credit could be ``assignable'': any refund due could go
directly to the insurance company, either monthly or yearly, to
help cover the premium.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed a more expansive, more government-based health
care plan, whose cost he estimates at more than $346 billion over
10 years. It would try to guarantee access to health coverage to
all children by 2005, by expanding eligibility for the Children's
Health Insurance Program, established three years ago for children
in families not poor enough for Medicaid but not affluent enough to
buy private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would also allow their uninsured parents to enroll
in the program. And it would allow many uninsured Americans ages 55
to 65 to buy into the Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   But the costliest part of the Gore plan would be a $200 billion
provision to create a prescription drug benefit under Medicare, an
issue Bush was silent on Tuesday. His aides said the governor would
address health care issues relating to the elderly later in the
year.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush took pains Tuesday to distinguish his approach from
that of the Democrats. ``We will not nationalize our health care
system,'' he said. ``We will promote individual choice. We will
rely on private insurance. But make no mistake: in my
administration, low-income Americans will have access to
high-quality health care.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the tax credit would help buy only basic coverage.
``In most places in America,'' he said, ``that means visits to a
doctor, discounted prescriptions and hospitalization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The basics,'' he said, ``but enough to ensure against sudden
poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's approach does have some bipartisan support in Congress
and is a favorite of some New Democrats, who often differ with
their party's orthodoxy. But the Gore campaign questioned whether
it would truly provide health insurance for the poor. Gore aides
cited a recent study in Health Affairs magazine saying that similar
proposals covered less than a third of the costs of a typical
nongroup family insurance policy and were not sufficient to help
those most in need.
</P>
<P>
   Further, a leading expert on health care costs, Diane K. Rowland
of the Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation, voiced skepticism Tuesday
over how much insurance the tax credits would cover. Rowland said
that ``the average cost in 1998 for a group family policy was
$4,092.'' That, she said, is what fairly large employers would have
to pay; individuals buying family insurance would find their rates
``much higher.'' If less expensive policies could be created, she
said, they ``would not cover much.''
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions of Bush's plan would give states more leeway in
how they administer the Children's Health Insurance Program. He
would also encourage the development of multistate health plans
among small businesses, and would expand and make more flexible two
programs that give favored tax treatment to medical savings.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush also ventured into the area of home ownership Tuesday,
noting that while the level of home ownership among whites was 73
percent, it was only 47 percent among blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   He embraced legislation, already overwhelmingly passed by the
House, that would allow families that get rent subsidies under the
Title 8 housing program to instead opt to use up to a year's worth
of rental vouchers to make a down payment on a home. He would also
create a $1 billion fund that would give banks incentives to help
with a down payment for first-time home buyers earning less than 80
percent of their area's median income.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, to encourage savings, he would provide tax
incentives to financial institutions that match deposits of up to
$300 made by people earning less than 60 percent of their area's
median income.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
