<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: COSTLY COKE
</P>
<P>
   In a move against American hegemony, the village of Ste.-Marie,
in southwest France, wanted to ban Coca-Cola outright. Told this
was against trade law, the local council decided to triple the
price. From now on a Coke will cost about $4.50. The gesture
follows a wave of such actions that started last summer after
America decided to tax various European luxury goods because Europe
declined to buy hormone-enhanced beef.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUE REBELS REGROUP
</P>
<P>
   Three commandos seen as hard-liners have wrested control of the
armed Basque separatist group ETA from the leaders who guided a
14-month cease-fire that ended last December, the conservative
daily ABC reported, citing government officials. Some political
analysts say hard-liners have ousted so-called moderates in every
major reorganization of the rebels since they began fighting for
independence in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: CONVERSION CASE
</P>
<P>
   A 12-judge High Court panel briefly opened a sensitive
discussion on the validity of non-Orthodox conversions by Reform
and Conservative rabbis. The government is appealing a district
court ruling that the state must recognize the conversions and
register the converts as Jews. The judges stopped the hearing after
two and a half hours, disappointing representatives of the liberal
Judaism movements, who have been protesting the court's gingerly
handling of the issue for years.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: GOLAN CONSTRUCTION
</P>
<P>
   As hopes for peace with Syria dim, the freeze on construction in
the Golan Heights has been lifted by the government. In Katzrin,
some 200 new housing units are being built, and 20 have already
been sold.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SETTLERS ACT
</P>
<P>
   Jewish settlers in the West Bank, angry that the government has
turned down from 60 to 70 requests to authorize new construction,
said they would start carrying out their expansions illegally. They
began bulldozing on Olive Hill near Efrat.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN: JOINS WTO
</P>
<P>
   Jordan became the 136th member of the World Trade Organization,
the body that sets international trade rules. Its membership was
due to be approved last year, but was waylaid by the collapse of
the WTO ministerial meeting in Seattle. Some 30 other countries,
including China, are seeking to join the group.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: GOVERNOR DENOUNCED
</P>
<P>
   Government officials denounced the governor of Tokyo, Shintaro
Ishihara, for saying that immigrants were likely to stage riots
after a major earthquake and asking the military to be ready to
quell such uprisings. Foreign Minister Yohei Kono said Ishihara's
use of a derogatory term for people of Korean and Chinese descent
may have offended them and that Japanese ``should not use the word
carelessly.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: UNION BARS LIE TESTS
</P>
<P>
   The union representing nearly 4,000 employees of the top federal
law enforcement agency says its members will not submit to lie
detector tests designed to root out bureaucrats working for drug
traffickers. After his top aide committed suicide during a
corruption investigation, Attorney General Jorge Madrazo said all
18,000 people on his staff would undergo the tests.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: WILDLIFE BILL
</P>
<P>
   Canada introduced its first bill to protect endangered species,
a measure that would impose stiff fines and prison sentences for
harming rare flora and fauna. About 340 of Canada's 70,000 plant
and animal species are classified as being at risk. Several
environmental groups object to the bill, saying politicians rather
than scientists would decide which animals and plants to list.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: ELECTION DUE
</P>
<P>
   Parliament adjourned in anticipation of national elections,
which by law must be held in the next four months. President Robert
Mugabe said the vote would be held in May, but the commission
drawing the boundaries of voting districts says it needs at least
three months to finish. Mugabe's party, which has dominated
Parliament for 20 years, is facing a tough challenge from the
Movement for Democratic Change, a new party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
