<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DRUG-PATENT-NYT &LR;      04-11 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-PATENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF ROCHESTER GETS BROAD PATENT FOR NEW PAINKILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The University of Rochester said on Tuesday that it had been
awarded a broad patent covering the use of a new type of painkiller
that has become the pharmaceutical industry's fastest-selling new
product.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the university estimate that the patent could bring
in billions of dollars in royalties over its 17-year-life, which
would make it the most lucrative patent ever held by a university.
</P>
<P>
   The patent supposedly covers all medical uses of drugs known as
Cox-2 inhibitors, which are sometimes called ``super-aspirin'' for
their ability to alleviate pain while minimizing side effects,
particularly stomach ulcers, associated with frequent use of
aspirin, ibuprofen or similar painkillers.
</P>
<P>
   The first such Cox-2 inhibitor drug to reach the market, G.D.
Searle &AMP; Co. Celebrex, had sales totaling $1.5 billion in 1999, its
first year on the market. Some 17.5 million prescriptions were
written in the United States last year, eclipsing Viagra as the
fastest-selling new drug in history, according to IMS Health, a
health care information company.
</P>
<P>
   On receiving the patent, the university filed a
patent-infringement suit against Searle and Pfizer, which helps
market Celebrex. It sought, among other things, an injunction to
stop sales of the painkiller now used by an estimated seven million
people, mainly to relieve arthritis pain.
</P>
<P>
   While scientists at Rochester and other universities first
discovered the Cox-2 enzyme, Searle developed a drug to block the
action of that enzyme but did not know of Rochester's request for a
patent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine waking up in the morning and having a patent on
aspirin,'' said Gerald P. Dodson, a lawyer representing the
university. ``Well, these people at Rochester woke up this morning
and have a patent on a substitute for aspirin that is even
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger A. Williams, associate patent counsel at Searle, said the
company believes that the Rochester patent is invalid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overly broad,'' he said, agreeing that it does seem to
cover all uses of Cox-2 inhibitors. He also said that work done by
others before Rochester could nullify the patent. Searle is the
pharmaceutical division of Monsanto, which is now part of the
Pharmacia Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said his company had not yet seen the lawsuit, which
was filed in Federal District Court in Rochester, N.Y. But he
added, ``I would question why a university would want to take a
therapeutically beneficial product off the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Rochester officials say they do not really want to take the drug
off the market, but rather want to negotiate royalty agreements
with Searle and other manufacturers of such drugs. The suit is
really to put pressure on the company to negotiate, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be able to work with them as amicably as
possible,'' Jeanine Arden Ornt, general counsel for the University
of Rochester Medical Center, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Merck &AMP; Co. also sells a Cox-2 inhibitor, Vioxx, which had
United States revene around $373 million last year, after being
approved for sale in May, according to IMS. Lawyers for the
university said they want to talk with Merck as well but did not
sue because they want to concentrate for now on Celebrex, the
bigger-selling drug.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John H. Klippel, medical director of the Arthritis
Foundation, said his group would be concerned by any prospect,
however remote, that Celebrex or another Cox-2 inhibitor would be
taken off the market. He said it was hard to say whether Vioxx
could be a substitute for Celebrex, adding, ``They have different
compounds and different labeling indications.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for big royalties, assuming that the university
can defend its patent, is based on forecasts that sales of Cox-2
inhibitors will rise to several billion dollars a year. Other
companies besides Searle and Merck are developing such drugs.
Moreover, the drugs are now being tested to see if they can prevent
cancer and Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Jackson, president of the University of Rochester, called
the patent ``extraordinarily exciting for us,'' both for the
potential income and the recognition it would bring the university
for a contribution to public health.
</P>
<P>
   The private university now gets $150 million to $200 million a
year in federal research grants and is in the midst of adding
buildings and scientists to bolster its medical research. Any
income from the patent would be ``a significant augmentation of our
basic research efforts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The patent is based on the work done in the late 1980s and early
1990s by Dr. Donald Young, a professor of medicine and biochemistry
who is now semi-retired.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, it was thought that a different Cox, which is short
for cyclo-oxygenase, was involved in pain and inflammation. But
Young, assisted by Michael K. O'Banion and Virginia D. Winn,
suspected that a new type of Cox enzyme, now known as Cox-2, was
the culprit and they cloned the gene responsible for producing it.
The original enzyme, now known as Cox-1, turned out to be involved
in protecting the lining of the stomach from acids.
</P>
<P>
   Aspirin, ibuprofen and other so-called nonsteroidal
anti-inflammatory drugs work by blocking both Cox-1 and Cox-2. So
while they reduce pain and swelling, they also cause ulcers and
gastrointestinal bleeding that lead to thousands of deaths in the
United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   But once they knew of the difference between the two enzymes,
drug companies set out to develop drugs that inhibit Cox-2 without
affecting Cox-1, thereby reducing the risk of ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   The patent, filed in 1992, took eight years to work its way
through the patent office, which turns out to Rochester's benefits
because the drugs have just gone on the market. But it is bound to
be a disappointment to two other universities _ the University of
California at Los Angeles and Brigham Young University, where
scientists were making the same discoveries at about the same time
as the Rochester team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They filed for a patent and we didn't,'' said Dr. Harvey R.
Herschman, a professor who led the work at UCLA, somewhat ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   Dodson, the attorney representing Rochester, said the patent
should survive because it made it through an eight-year examination
by the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
