<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3908 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HIGH-FIDELITY-FILM-$A     04-11 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-FIDELITY-FILM-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOYS OF ROCK: FOREVER BOYS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, everyone assumes that the serious music fan is an
arrested adolescent. Nick Hornby's 1995 novel, ``High Fidelity,''
devastatingly captured the paralyzed mental state of smart males
whose emotional lives revolve around cultural product, not people.
</P>
<P>
   Now his characters have been made into Hollywood archetypes by
the director Stephen Frears and the actor John Cusack. Once, record
geeks made fun of themselves. Now mainstream America is talking
about how lovably pathetic they can be.
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll has long given men, its dominant players, a route
to rebellion and self-transformation. But when did its focus
change, from boys wanting to become men to men wanting to stay
boys? Although the music has always been linked to youth, and, some
would say, immaturity, many early rockers used it to prove their
virility.
</P>
<P>
   There was rage in the recklessness of those stars, many of them
poor white and black Southerners whom the mainstream considered
less than men. Chuck Berry may have written ``Sweet Little 16''
about a girl he admired, but he wrote ``Brown-Eyed Handsome Man''
about himself.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, being young became its own political stance. But
rock 'n' roll's flower children still wanted the full participatory
rights society granted adults. The counterculture called for a
different kind of grown-up, as spontaneous and questioning as a
teen-ager but able to shoulder the weight of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The 1970s may be when the grown-boy stereotype merged with that
of the rocker. Rock became just another official periphery, a
bohemian enclave like many before it, and some music lovers used
its otherworldliness to facilitate their retreat.
</P>
<P>
   This is the tribe ``High Fidelity'' explores so effectively:
shaggy guys who display their esoteric knowledge on their
promotional T-shirts, who lack basic social skills but can recite
Bob Dylan's catalog at will. Hornby's second novel, ``About a
Boy,'' went even further in telling the stories of these sweet
nerds. He's recently been joined by the writer Camden Joy, whose
second novel, ``Boy Island,'' depicts musicians even more eager to
escape maturity's traditional commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Such grown boys are overwhelmingly white and middle class,
exiles from manhood rather than invaders. The impulses they honor _
to follow your passion instead of money, to express individuality
even when it's messy, to play by the gut, not the rules _ fed the
social movements rock 'n' roll helped inspire. Detached from a
shared context, though, these values become sources of weakness
instead of power.
</P>
<P>
   Rock's grown boys don't want to become regular men but can't
imagine how else to thrive. One of the few improvements the film
makes on Hornby's novel is to turn the masculine cliche grown boys
despise into a fleshed-out character. Played by Tim Robbins with
the smarmiest of New Age smiles, this avatar of mellowness is the
same pompous oaf who gets the boot in Jane Austen novels. Resting
too surely in his power, he's destined to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Grown boys act jealous of the authority such men have, but they
could attain it if they wanted. A dream deferred can be a
comfortable thing, if your reality isn't that bad to start with.
Because they don't feel engaged with any larger rebellion, grown
boys combat straw enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly they battle the women in their lives, who have replaced
``the Man'' of social protest as embodiments of convention. ``High
Fidelity'' denigrates this old bohemian view of the feminine as a
trap, but only hints at how it might be dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the game, a writer named Caroline appears; unlike any
other female character, she's a music expert too. Had she been a
full player, grown boys in ``High Fidelity'' would have tangled
with a big change, if only an interior one caused by confronting
their own sexism. Instead, Hornby's grown boys, like many real
ones, spin their wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Rock obsessives have needed self-critiques like Hornby's to
expose their solipsism, but it's important to remember that other
story, of manhood's definition expanding under rock's impact.
That's one message of ``The Filth and the Fury,'' Julien Temple's
homage to the working-class rebellion of English punk.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary's subjects, the Sex Pistols, were the sort of
public-housing lads whose futures held little promise of the
satisfactions adulthood can bring. Like the 1950s stars before
them, they railed against a culture that wanted to keep them boys.
</P>
<P>
   Grown boys and the rockers who would be men both refuse to
reconcile with manhood as their elders defined it. Yet they keep
pushing, inspired by rock 'n' roll's mandate to try for more. And
sometimes a narrative captures the excitement that can come from
taking that dare.
</P>
<P>
   One such tale is the new novel ``War Boy'' by Kief Hillsberry.
It follows its teen-age hero, the deaf skateboarder Rad Boy, as he
embarks upon manhood guided by a cadre of grown boys he meets in
the California punk scene.
</P>
<P>
   Always treated differently because of his hearing loss and
starting to realize that his homosexuality will also mark him as an
outsider, Rad Boy finds solidarity with extremists _ radical
environmentalists and speed freaks. They let him down, but he
survives, moving through tragedy toward maturity. He's inspired by
the music he hears in his head _ and his favorite band is the
all-female Sleater-Kinney. The end of his road doesn't look like a
trap. It is lit with the sense of possibility rock has always
offered its confused, blessed boys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2128EDT &QL; 
