<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS CLOSE TO DEALING JOHNSON TO BUCS FOR DRAFT PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA and MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the latest upheaval of their tumultuous off
season, the Jets were on the brink Tuesday night of a trade that
would send All-Pro wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson to Tampa Bay in
exchange for the Buccaneers' two first-round picks in Saturday's
National Football League draft.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Stanley, the agent for Johnson, spent Tuesday night in
Tampa, Fla., trying to complete an agreement on a new long-term
contract. According to a league official, the deal would pay
Johnson almost $7 million per year, and would include a signing
bonus of between $12 and $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets and the Bucs have already agreed to the terms of the
trade, leaving it up to Johnson and the Bucs to come to terms on a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   According to the league official, several teams tried to get in
on the deal within the last 48 hours, telling the Jets to hold off
on finalizing the trade until they could make offers. The Jets
declined, and the Bucs have a self-imposed deadline of Wednesday to
complete the deal with Johnson or end negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley did not return repeated messages and Jets Coach Al Groh
did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   If the trade gets done, the Jets would have four picks in the
first round of the draft, including their own (16th and 18th) and
the Bucs' 13th and 27th. That would put them in position to either
make a blockbuster trade to move up to nab one of the draft's
premier players, or to stockpile young talent by exercising all
four picks.
</P>
<P>
   But it means the Jets, handicapped by salary cap woes and
determined to avoid what seemed an increasingly likely holdout by
Johnson, would also be bereft of their best player and one of the
critical members of a team that was thought to be in position to
make a run at the Super Bowl next season.
</P>
<P>
   And if they trade their most visible star, the Jets will have
crafted a deal that will surely bewilder some Jets players and many
fans. Johnson has been a controversial figure from the start of his
career _ he held out for 24 days before his rookie season and wrote
a book critical of some of his teammates. But he is also a premier
playmaker. Last season was his best as a pro, with 89 receptions
for 1,170 yards and eight touchdowns. The team's next most
productive receiver was Wayne Chrebet, one of the subjects of
Johnson's rookie season ire, who had 48 receptions for 631 yards
and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's draft is generally regarded as having four premier
players: defensive lineman Courtney Brown, linebacker LaVar
Arrington, receiver Peter Warrick and offensive lineman Chris
Samuels. With four first-round picks the Jets could offer a package
to any of the teams holding the top four picks. But the Cleveland
Browns, who hold the No.1 pick, would likely demand at least three
of those picks to make a trade, the team's director of football
operations Dwight Clark has said. And the Redskins seem intent on
trying to grab Arrington and Samuels with their picks, No. 2 and
No. 3. The Bengals, with the No. 4 selection, have said they would
listen to offers to move down. The Baltimore Ravens at No. 5, have
entertained offers for their fifth overall pick. But Ravens Coach
Brian Billick wondered yesterday whether the Jets could offer
enough to pry the fifth pick from his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they'd have enough juice,'' Billick said. ``If
they were trying to go to the fifth, they'd give us the 13th and
they'd probably to have throw in one of those later ones and then a
fourth-round pick.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week, Groh indicated that the Jets might be wary of
pursuing a high draft pick because signing him might put as much of
a cramp on the salary cap in future years as restructuring
Johnson's deal would have. Instead, the Jets might choose to use
all four picks to fill numerous needs in an attempt to continue
what Groh called the ``success cycle'' without forcing the team
into future dire financial straits. In addition to trying to
acquire a receiver to replace Johnson in the receiver-deep draft,
the Jets need a tight end, a pass-rusher and help in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
