u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-11 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A NATION AT RISK _ OF ENNUI 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton is nervous.
</P>
<P>
   The risk-addicted president is worried that he may have taken
one risk too many. The independent counsel is once more mulling
indicting him in the Monica magilla.
</P>
<P>
   While he stews, the rest of the country indulges in risk
nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   The hot new Broadway play is ``Copenhagen,'' the Michael Frayn
``imaginative reconstruction'' of a 1941 meeting between Werner
Heisenberg, a physicist on the German atomic bomb project, and his
mentor, Niels Bohr, a quantum theorist who went on to Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   On CBS on Sunday night, George Clooney and a starry cast did a
live black-and-white remake of ``Fail Safe,'' the Cold War
nightmare about nuclear bombs gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   America is so comfortable and glossy now, a Pottery Barn catalog
of a country, Clooney figured he could give us a good scare, if not
with the tense nuclear tale at least with the prospect of movie
stars muffing their lines on live TV.
</P>
<P>
   Critics shrugged. ``It was a bunch of middle-aged white guys
talking for two hours,'' said MSNBC's Dana Kennedy. (Bet she can't
wait for the Bush-Gore debates.)
</P>
<P>
   At the end, producers made a bid for relevance by listing
countries with nuclear capability. But, as The Washington Post's
Tom Shales wrote, the list was ``somehow not as chilling or
horrifying as, say, last week's plunge in stock prices on the
Nasdaq exchange. The world has changed a lot since `Fail Safe.'
It's all about money now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Elian lunacy must be seen through the prism of risk
nostalgia. As Hendrik Hertzberg wrote in The New Yorker: ``If the
real Cold War was grand opera, this tiny remnant, this Cold Spat,
is operetta, and comic operetta at that ... the nuclear shadow that
once darkened every Cuban crisis has lifted, taking existential
terror with it.''
</P>
<P>
   We've grown so coddled on the glide path to riches that when the
Nasdaq went kerflooie last week, brokers had to remind their
clients to get reacquainted with that old market fundamental, risk.
</P>
<P>
   The cheap thrills of the Nasdaq roller coaster can't compare to
those sweaty-palm, hide-under-your-school-desk days of the Cuban
missile crisis. The anarchists and Ruckus Society and Birkenstock
anti-globalist guerrillas descending on Washington are trying to
replace the threat of the end of the world with the threat of one
world.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ``No Nukes'' and ``Down With the Military-Industrial
Complex,'' the Capitol was awash in signs like ``No to Debt, No to
Structural Adjustment Programs.'' Not quite the same ring.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one place where existential terror still lurks: the
White House. The president's pals say he is upset about the threat
by Kenneth Starr's replacement, Robert W. Ray, to indict him after
he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews Ray has said Clinton is still in the
cross-hairs. ``The process has to be vindicated,'' he told The
Times. ``No person is above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of closing the books, Ray has hired six new prosecutors
and an investigator and is planning to spend $3.5 million over the
next six months, The Washington Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who was hired by Rudy Giuliani to work in the U.S.
attorney's office in Manhattan in 1989, is the latest victim of
Clinton poisoning _ a malady that causes normal people to become
obsessive.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, camera crews will be waiting at Ray's home
to watch him take out the garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr may be gone. The independent counsel law may have
lapsed. But like a Potomac Hydra, the independent counsel is
gearing up again to hunt down Bill Clinton. Even Javert jumped into
the Seine at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-two million isn't enough?'' harrumphs James Carville.
``They want to spend another $50 million?''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton always performs best at the brink, and almost seems
to enjoy being the scamp who dances away from his pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   But now he must be having nightmares about a split-screen
departure from office. Just as Jimmy Carter had to watch the Iran
hostage release as Ronald Reagan was sworn in as president, Clinton
must visualize a split screen with his successor parading down
Pennsylvania Avenue even as federal marshals wait with handcuffs
for Citizen Bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
