<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-PILLS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPRIMA: NEW SEX DRUG AROUSES INTEREST _ AND ALARM  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 425-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Men in the United States who may still be having
trouble stiffening their resolve before sex will soon have an
alternative to the little blue lozenge known as Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for Uprima, a smaller pill that slides under the
tongue and promises, within 30 minutes, to assist with arousal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of increasing blood flow to the penis, this drug is
meant to raise levels of dopamine in that part of the brain
involved in causing erections.
</P>
<P>
   Just approved for consumer use by an advisory committee to the
powerful U.S. Food and Drug Administration, Uprima can, indeed,
cause a steep drop in blood pressure. Steep enough to cause a man
to faint.
</P>
<P>
   There are other possible side effects that would not seem
conducive to efficient sexual union, like sleepiness, sweating,
vomiting and nausea.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the blood pressure factor that gave the FDA panel
some pause. (In the end, its members voted 9-3 to allow the pills
onto the market.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some people who will probably lose their lives
because they pass out at the top of the stairs or are operating a
car,'' agreed Dr. Peter Kowey, who voted in favor of approval.
</P>
<P>
   Among men tested for the drug, one in thirty suffered a collapse
in blood pressure or fainted. One, indeed, blacked out while
driving home from the doctor's office and crashed into a fence.
Another passed out in surgery, fell down and cracked his skull.
</P>
<P>
   But in the trials, Uprima did help some men regain their
strength sufficiently to engage in sexual intercourse _ and because
many of the America's estimated 30 million impotent men have shown
an intolerance to other medications _ the panel voted 9-3 that
Uprima should sell as long as men and their doctors get clear
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA does not have to heed its advisers' decisions but does
so in eight out of ten cases.
</P>
<P>
   TAP Pharmaceuticals, which manufactures Uprima, said men
``desperately need'' alternative treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra became a huge seller when it hit the market in 1998 as
the only oral impotence treatment but is not without its risks. It
can in fact be fatal when taken by men on certain forms of heart
medication.
</P>
<P>
   TAP said in studies of 3,000 patients, most that lasted a month,
no one died.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the pills should carry this warning: to be taken
after you have entered the bedroom and when you are already lying
down. Not to be taken while climbing the stairs. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 425-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
