<HEADLINE>
RULING UPHOLDS TOUGHER PENALTIES FOR FATAL CHILD ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Missouri appeals court on Tuesday upheld a
new, tougher approach that sent a Kansas City man to prison for
murder in the beating death of his 2-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling, combined with one last month in another Jackson
County case, upholds prosecutors who used murder charges against
people who unintentionally beat children to death.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County prosecutors said the rulings mean more people who
kill children during vicious discipline will be charged with
murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy the ticket,'' County Prosecutor Bob Beaird said, ``and you
can take the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers say the rulings improperly allow murder
convictions without proof of intent to kill. They said the issue
would be appealed to the Missouri Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling by the appeals court in Kansas City upholds
John J. Williams' 1998 convictions for felony murder, endangering
the welfare of a child and armed criminal action.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 32, is serving life plus 30 years. Williams beat
Michael Scott to death with a frayed belt in 1997 after the boy wet
his pants.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, another Kansas City appeals court panel
upheld the felony murder conviction of Robert A. Bouser, 27. The
Grandview, Mo., man is serving 18 years in the 1997 beating death
of 1-year-old James Matthew Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, prosecutors used felony murder charges in hope of
getting stiffer sentences. Missouri prosecutors had rarely
attempted the tactic since the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Felony murder charges allow a murder conviction and up to life
in prison when someone dies during a serious crime, such as a
robbery. Prosecutors argued that the children's deaths were felony
murders during child abuse or child endangerment.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers in both cases argued at trial that their clients
did not intend to kill and so committed no more than involuntary
manslaughter _ which carries a maximum sentence of seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about felony murder in child abuse cases go back to an
1878 Missouri Supreme Court decision. The court ruled that felony
murder could not apply in the case of a man who beat a child to
death with a fishing pole.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed, the appeals court ruled, when Missouri enacted
a 1984 law that said felony murder charges could be used for almost
any crime resulting in death.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' appeals attorney argued in legal filings that the
appeal should have bypassed the appeals court and gone straight to
the Missouri Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew A. Schroeder, Bouser's appeals lawyer, said he would
appeal to the Missouri Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings tilt the law far too much in favor of prosecutors
and impose harsh penalties on people who never intended to kill,
Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have another option in child beatings.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri General Assembly enacted a law in 1997 that allows
for up to a life sentence when child abuse results in a death.
</P>
<P>
   But that law, unlike the felony murder statute, does not require
a defendant to serve 85 percent of the sentence before parole.
Because of that, Beaird said, prosecutors will use felony murder
charges in the worst cases.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon said the 85 percent
requirement means those who kill children will serve many more
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly a bad day for child abusers,'' Nixon said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Popper, a Kansas City law professor, said such tougher
laws reflect changes in social attitudes that affect what has been
the heart of criminal law _ mental state at the time of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you're morally culpable for the result,'' Popper said,
``even if you didn't intend it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
