<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT FEELINGS FLY HEATEDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Nothing, it seems, inflames reader passions like a
column saying something in defense of Microsoft, the company many
Americans love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   Not even at the height of Standard Oil's symbolism as the
quintessential robber barony has a company been able to generate
the magnitude of public enmity Bill Gates' empire elicits.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to Friday's column was typical of what happens in the
aftermath of a favorable Microsoft commentary. The column posited
that Microsoft found itself suffering the wrath of Washington's
trustbusters because it had failed to grease the political wheels
with adequate amounts of campaign largess.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 or so Microsoft-related e-mails waiting Monday
morning, there were slightly more con responses than pro. The tone
of the supportive mail, however, paled in comparison to the vitriol
of the column's critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give you credit for being one of the stupidest SOBs
in journalism,'' said one particularly pungent missive. ``If you
have no idea what you're talking about, which you don't, then stop
misleading the public with your nonsense. This article is so
wrongheaded it isn't even funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, incidentally, failed to address any of the column's
specifics. It was more a rant than a considered response, which is
always the case when it comes to Microsoft haters. Read on:
</P>
<P>
   ``Your article is filled with specious reasoning, and your
statements appear to have been taken directly from a Microsoft
press release,'' charged one reader. ``Microsoft wields far too
much power, and if you will read all of the court documents related
to the trial, you will see that they wield it like a bludgeon,
smashing everything that threatens their dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   Another dissenter apparently took issue with Chairman Bill's
attempts to create a warm and fuzzy image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to disagree. ... They should have been prosecuted and
punished long ago for the companies they put out of business and
unfair tactics. ... Bill wearing nice sweaters and giving a few
billion to charity doesn't change anything legally. ... If you rob
someone, and then do something good later, it doesn't change the
fact that you robbed someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the comedians, doing their sarcastic best to
emulate H.L. Mencken:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderful piece of breathtakingly shallow reasoning. Brought
by the same folks that gave us `creationism' in their public
classrooms. No wonder so many people think the oxygen is cut off in
the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some roses amid the brickbats, though. This was my
personal favorite:
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations on your column,'' said one perspicacious
respondent. ``You have a better grasp of economics than most
university professors. It seems most politicians are determined to
wreck all American industry. Could it be simple jealousy of REAL
productivity, or is it blackmail?''
</P>
<P>
   Another letter got right to the heart of Microsoft's appeal and
success:
</P>
<P>
   ``I really appreciate what Microsoft has done for standardizing
an operating system that I think is inexpensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the enduring wonder of it all is the emotional
intensity. And given the widespread hostility toward Microsoft,
bashing this company is obviously good politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
