<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SAN FRANCISCO, OPENING DAY FOR BIG WALLETS AND NEW STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moving in `s' category) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gerry Needham was desperate, for all the world
to see. So was Carole Cunningham. And John Patel. And the three
guys in red Microsoft golf shirts who preferred to remain
anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   They were all standing pathetically in front of San Francisco's
new monument to baseball, holding ``Need Giants Tickets'' signs,
hoping against hope five minutes before game time that some greedy
scalper might come along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd pay up to a grand,'' said Needham, a salesman for an
Internet ad company. ``Five hundred _ for a bad seat,'' said
Cunningham, a designer for an online design firm. ``The sky's the
limit,'' said one of the three Microsoft guys, who said he was ``in
software.'' ``Whatever the market will bear.''
</P>
<P>
   This being opening day at Pacific Bell Park, with the San
Francisco Giants playing the Los Angeles Dodgers, the home team's
most hated rivals, those hoping for exorbitantly priced tickets
would have to settle for a $10 program or $25 commemorative T-shirt
to prove they were here on what Needham, 36, called ``one of the
historic days in San Francisco and baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not alone. Opening day, celebrated on the front pages of
the local newspapers, with continuous coverage on news radio and
with sidewalk salespeople giving away everything from coupons for
free videos to free massages, is the closest San Francisco has come
to having its own private holiday since a blackout stopped the city
in its tracks a year ago last fall. From the fireworks, which shot
rainbow colors into the pale blue sky, to the five F-15s to the
40,800 fans who skipped work or school on a Tuesday afternoon to
see the game, opening day took over the city like a Thanksgiving
Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if San Francisco, one of the biggest tourist cities
in the world, needed another attraction. But this seemingly
sophisticated urban enclave has a proud baseball history, what with
baseball greats Joe DiMaggio and Willie Mays (who is honored with a
statue in front of the park) local heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The $319 million Pacific Bell Park _ the utility company paid
$50 million to put its name on the park _ replaces Candlestick
Park, one of the most notorious in baseball. While Candlestick had
the pretty name, it was one of the windiest, foggiest parks in pro
baseball, forcing fans to huddle in blankets to see a game in July.
Like Baltimore's Camden Yards and other new parks, Pac Bell appeals
to the nostalgia for old stadiums, with a red brick facade and
large multipane windows. The closest seats are just 46 feet from
home plate. And passersby can gaze into right field, which abruptly
ends where it meets the waters of China Basin, in San Francisco
Bay. In one exhibition game last week, outfielder Barry Bonds hit a
home run over the right field fence right into the bay, and boaters
were plunked Tuesday in position near the field, hoping they might
catch a flying ball.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hoopla, however, the new ballpark has its critics.
It has only 4,800 dedicated parking spots, and while repeated
warnings from city officials to take mass transit or walk from the
financial district made traffic flow smoothly for the game's start,
it is not at all assured that the fans will continue to forgo their
cars during the course of 81 home games. The concessions, which
sell everything from garlic fries to sushi, are pricey; beer and a
dog will set you back $9, and the lines, at least during exhibition
games, were so long that fans nearly rioted. And the stadium's
location, in a formerly forlorn backwater of the city that
warehouses and factories called home, had an immediate gentrifying
effect even before the foundation for the park was laid, driving up
both commercial and residential rents and marking every vacant
patch of land for development, most of it for Internet companies
willing to pay more than landlords ask for.
</P>
<P>
   The best seats costs $42, making the park the sixth most
expensive in pro baseball. But that is clearly not too expensive
for some people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could have bought a $42 seat, I would die a happy man,''
said Gerry Needham, who was so desperate for a seat by the second
inning that he was willing to pay $2,000 for a ticket. ``Maybe,''
he said, ``even two and a quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the game, he could console himself upon hearing
that his beloved Giants had lost, 6 to 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
