<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ANDRETTI-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDRETTI STILL HAS DESIRE TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The calendar on the wall reports, as of
today, that Michael Andretti is 177 days shy of his 38th birthday.
That same calendar informs us that only only one current CART FedEx
Championship Series driver - 41-year-old Roberto Moreno - is older
than Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   However, there hasn't been a calendar invented that measures
aggressiveness in a race car and desire to win races. And, for that
matter, even if there was, where do you hang a calendar in a race
car?
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is a guy that has been in the series for a long time
and every year he comes back as strong, if not stronger than the
year before,'' said Dario Franchitti, one of the young stars of the
series. ``So there is no loss of motivation, which you have got to
look at and say he is pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in his 17th season, Andretti has more race wins (38) and
laps led (6,119) than any other CART driver and has more poles (32)
than anyone but Rick Mears (39). A win this season would push
Andretti's consecutive seasons with a victory streak to 13 years,
which is one more than Mears.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, the Newman-Haas Racing veteran, bristles a bit when
broaching the subject of age and chuckles uncomfortably when
hearing tales of some of the younger CART driver's admiration of
the veteran star.
</P>
<P>
   ``My very first race and I'm starting next to Michael
Andretti,'' second-year driver Cristiano da Matta said of his CART
debut at the 1999 Grand Prix of Miami. ``I remember thinking that
was pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   He also remembers that Andretti sped his way to a second-place
finish that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I am the old guy, if you want to put it that way,''
said Andretti, whose father, Mario, was 53 when he won his last
race and is the patriach of one of America's first families of
racing. ``That's just the facts of life. But I don't feel old.
Experience is something you can't buy. I still like to think I'm as
aggressive as ever, which made me successful in this business.
Maybe I'm a little smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   When Andretti rolls into town this weekend for the Toyota Grand
Prix of Long Beach it will be the 252nd start of his career.
Chances are he'll take a minute to reminisce about his first CART
victory when he outdueled another young sensation from a racing
family Al Unser Jr. in the 1986 Long Beach Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long Beach is really special to me and my family,'' said
Michael, who has one of four Andretti victories and three of the
family's six pole positions in Champ Car events at Long Beach. ``My
first time there to watch my dad was in 1976. It's a good feeling
to go back every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti has come to Long Beach as well as every other CART
facility the past three years with a Swift-Ford package that
trailed the Honda-Reynard setup which allowed Target/Chip Ganassi
Racing to win four consecutive championships. For the first two
years of that span, he was running on Goodyear tires, which were
second-best to Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   He managed to scratch out consecutive wins at the season opener
at Homestead-Miami Speedway in 1997-98 and had a victory in the
1999 Motorola 300 in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Four more podium finishes in 1999 two seconds and two thirds
helped Andretti finish in fourth place in the championship, which
was his best showing since tying with Alex Zanardi for second place
in 1996 behind Jimmy Vasser. It could have been better without
struggles on road courses as 236 of the 237 laps he led came on
ovals.
</P>
<P>
   It's not Andretti's style to compete for fourth place - or for
that matter second or third. During the off season, Andretti and
fellow Newman-Haas driver Christian Fittipaldi returned to the Lola
chassis that Michael used to secure a season-high five victories in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The testing went very well on oval tracks, but Andretti's opener
on the Miami oval ended with disappointment as an engine part
caused an oil pressure drop to ended his day after 37 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christian had the same problem in the (race) warmup and they
fixed it,'' Andretti said of his teammate, who finished seventh.
``He was lucky he had his problem before the race. It was
unfortunate for us that it was a 10 cent part which did us in.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a disappointing start to what Andretti hopes is his
second championship CART season. Team managers from 15 CART teams,
in fact, voted Andretti as the pre-season favorite to win the 2000
championship. And Max Papis, the race winner in Miami, agreed with
that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel like Michael is the favorite,'' Papis said.
``Michael is very experienced and he has a tremendous background
and lot of personality. He knows what he's doing out there.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, the CART champion in 1991, greets the expectations
with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they are right,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Right or wrong, Andretti will continue his career long enough to
satisfy the final three years on his Newman-Haas contract. After
that, depending on the strength of his racing desire, he'll make
come career decisions.
</P>
<P>
   There is one thing he's certain of, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely won't drive as long as Dad,'' Michael said. ``I'm
not sure that can be done again. Nobody has more passion for the
sport - or maybe another sport - than Dad has for racing. I know
he's dying to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   When Michael does join his father on the sideline, he'll have
plenty of business ventures to keep him busy. And he can thank his
racing career for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary to think about what my life would have been like
without racing,'' Andretti said. ``I have no idea what I would have
done. Who knows, maybe I would have sold vacuum cleaners door to
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, maybe he would have sold calendars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
