<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PRIEST-PROSTITUTES-AR     04-11 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-PROSTITUTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIEST, ON A MISSION, PAYS PROSTITUTES TO COUNSEL THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT35 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Shrouded in darkness on the tough streets of the South
Side, a Roman Catholic priest, Michael Pfleger, is looking for
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pfleger, the 50-year-old pastor of St. Sabina Church, pays cash
for a half-hour, typically $50, and then uses the time to talk to
the women about ways to escape the indignity and danger of selling
their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of three parishioners from St. Sabina, sometimes without
Pfleger, make the rounds to rescue prostitutes. One of the women
they found was Kathy Ellis, a 40-year-old drug addict and
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ashamed of the way my life is,'' she told Pfleger, ``but I
got six kids and lots of problems, and I don't know what else to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfleger told Ellis that the church would help her get drug
counseling and job training, would clean her clothes and even pay
for a haircut at a beauty salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody cares,'' said Ellis, who now attends Narcotics
Anonymous meetings. ``It's a feeling I never did feel before. When
you're out there prostituting, you don't think anybody cares.''
</P>
<P>
   Using cash from church collections to buy time to counsel
prostitutes and drug dealers, Pfleger is once again raising
eyebrows among the leaders of the Archdiocese of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   A '60s-style social activist who has long been highly critical
of the church hierarchy, Pfleger has staged sit-in protests at drug
paraphernalia shops and has whitewashed liquor billboards in poor
neighborhoods. In his latest street campaign, Pfleger says that
more than a dozen prostitutes have left the streets with the aid of
St. Sabina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church has spent too much time concentrating on fish frys
and workshops,'' Pfleger told parishioners at one recent Sunday
Mass. ``We ought to be doing things like paying for haircuts for
homeless people, so they can go on a job interview.''
</P>
<P>
   The parish initially raised $2,000 in a special collection at
Sunday Mass. Since word has spread about the campaign people
outside the church have sent another $4,000. A stock broker from
the wealthy North Shore sent money, and an 80-year-old man pedaled
a bicycle from miles away to give a check for $500.
</P>
<P>
   In the 25 years since Pfleger started his work at St. Sabina,
transforming a dying Irish Catholic parish into a vibrant black
congregation, some of the more conservative leaders of the
archdiocese have regarded him as something of a troublemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Francis George, the conservative leader of the Chicago
Archdiocese, the largest in the nation, has made no public comment
about Pfleger's work.
</P>
<P>
   Pfleger said he crossed paths with the cardinal recently, and
that the church leader ``made a comment that seemed sarcastic.''
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese has referred calls about Pfleger to Bishop
Joseph Perry, who characterized the notion of paying prostitutes as
``somewhat out of the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   But Perry said church leaders, including George, had no
animosity for Pfleger, and did not doubt his sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Pfleger has expressed frustration with the church
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get calls and offers of help from everywhere but my
archdiocese,'' said Pfleger, sitting in his office one recent
afternoon. ``I want to ask them: How is what I'm doing not part of
the gospel? The church leaders talk about evangelization. Well, if
this isn't evangelization, I don't know what is.''
</P>
<P>
   In his street work with prostitutes and drug dealers, Pfleger
organizes three-man teams to search the streets; one of the men
sits in a nearby car with a two-way radio, ready for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago police, who have praised Pfleger's work, also keep
tabs on the street mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Pfleger works hand-in-hand with the police,'' said
Dexter Yarbrough, a community policing officer in Chicago. ``He
consults us before he does these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarbrough said he has watched Pfleger knock on the doors of
``crack houses'' and issue his warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll say, `What you're doing is wrong, and I'll use the power
of prayer _ and the power of the Chicago Police Department, if I
have to _ to stop it,''' the officer said.
</P>
<P>
   In talks with gang leaders last year, Pfleger elicited a promise
from gang leaders that young people who want to leave a gang be
allowed to do so _ as long as they do not join a rival gang.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Wallace, 22, a former drug dealer and gang member, is
one of the men of St. Sabina who walks the streets to talk to
prostitutes and drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in jail six times,'' he said. ``And now I don't have
to look over my shoulder anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfleger said the prostitutes the church has found have been of
virtually all ages, from girls 13 years old to women in their 50s
and 60s.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, he said, women are terrified of the pimps who
control them. St. Sabina has helped move at least two of these
women to other neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman pulled up her shirt to show me how her pimp had
burned the nipples of her breasts,'' Pfleger said. ``She apparently
had come back one night without bringing in enough money.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfleger shook his head in anger and sadness, and cursed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
