<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3931 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-POVERTY-HNS &LR;      04-11 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POVERTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES TAX CREDIT TO EXPAND HEALTH COVERAGE TO WORKING POOR
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ After months of avoiding the campaign debate on
national health care, George W. Bush on Tuesday offered a tax
credit plan to expand health coverage to the working poor and
former welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the $39.6 billion proposal would help expand health
coverage to as many as 18 million Americans who can't afford
insurance now but earn too much to qualify for Medicaid. Bush
called them people who ``live in a world above welfare's
assistance, but beneath prosperity's promise.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Every low-income, working family in America must have access
to basic health insurance _ for themselves and for their
children,'' he said. ``For a family without health insurance, a
single doctor bill can be a financial disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed a refundable health insurance tax credit, which
would be worth as much as $2,000 a year to a family earning less
than $30,000 and could be spent only to purchase health insurance.
The credit could be advanced to insurance companies to pay
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee, called for expanding tax-free medical savings accounts.
His plan also calls for changing federal law to allow the creation
of insurance pools to make health coverage more affordable for
small businesses that don't now offer such coverage to their
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative groups and the National Federation of Independent
Business hailed Bush's plan, while the more liberal FamiliesUSA
called it ``trivial'' and ``a placebo for the growing uninsurance
epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, has
made health care a major element of his campaign. His aides Tuesday
challenged Bush's sincerity on expanding health care coverage for
the needy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Bush's record in Texas I think it is obvious
that these issues are new to him. He hasn't done anything to
improve health care in Texas,'' said Gore spokeswoman Kathleen
Begala.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, for example, ranks 49th among the states in the
percentage of children with health insurance. Nearly one-fourth of
Texas' 5.8 million children don't have health insurance, although
the state began enrollment last week for a new
government-sponsored, low-cost Children's Health Insurance Program,
or CHIPs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush laid out his health care plan as a key part of his ``New
Prosperity Initiative,'' which he unveiled at a faith-based social
services ministry in a working-class neighborhood in this
Midwestern city.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also proposed programs to help low-income Americans buy
houses and open savings accounts. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; He said that too many Americans were being left behind in this
``age of unmeasured prosperity.'' Greater opportunities to obtain
health insurance, own a home and save money in the bank were
crucial to offering them hope, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our society, it is easy to be secluded in success, in gated
communities and separate schools. Yet our growing nation must not
be allowed to grow apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His five-year health care tax credit plan covers as much as 90
percent of the cost of coverage _ up to a maximum of $1,000 a year
per individual and $2,000 per family _ for eligible recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals earning $15,000 or less a year and families with
annual incomes of $30,000 or less would be eligible for the maximum
tax credit. The government's share of the cost would be decreased
as a family's income rises. Individuals earning more than $45,000,
families making more than $60,000 and people who are offered health
insurance through their employers would be ineligible for the
program.
</P>
<P>
   To help low-income children and their parents, Gore has proposed
expanding the existing CHIPs program and for expanding the
eligibility limits for the federal program to about $41,000 for a
family of four. The vice president claimed that this expanded
funding would ensure that all children have access to health care.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also proposed a 25 percent refundable tax credit on
premium costs for individuals who cannot buy health insurance
through employers.
</P>
<P>
   John Goodman of the National Center for Policy Analysis called
Bush's plan ``bold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a moderate income family, the Bush credit is twice as
generous as the Gore credit,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Pollack, executive director of FamiliesUSA, said the
Bush plan falls short because it would pay for no more than half
the actual cost of buying insurance for a typical low-income
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the primary reason families are uninsured is because
they can't afford coverage, these tiny tax credits will do little
to change that equation,'' Pollack said.
</P>
<P>
   Federation of Independent Business president Jack Faris praised
Bush's health plan as a means of allowing small businesses to buy
health insurance for their employees.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's campaign noted the bipartisan Congressional Budget
Office released a report in January that found overall enrollment
in employer-sponsored health care plans would only increase by
about 330,000 people nationally under a system of association
health plans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
