<HEADER>
A3933 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AFRICA-SOUNDS-$ADV16-     04-11 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-SOUNDS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ART SHOULD YIELD TO NATURE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDHOEK, Namibia _ This time every year, when the gingko tree
outside my door in Manhattan begins to bud, I advise art to run for
cover. Wagner and Bach have been doing well at Lincoln Center, but
hibernation deserves some serious thought. The flowering pear trees
are acting up on city sidewalks, and nothing going on under any
roof can compete with them.
</P>
<P>
   Art should lie low until October and then come out of hiding.
Although nature and art in a single bundle (at Tanglewood in
Massachusetts, Ravinia in Illinois and Blossom in Ohio) may sound
like a bargain, open-air concerts end up as either greenery with
Muzak or high art with low-flying Cessnas. The antagonism is built
in.
</P>
<P>
   Music won't go away, however. Too many musicians' salaries to
pay, too many seats to sell, too many boring evenings in the
country to fill with culture. It is an awful thing to admit, but
behind the most high-minded art lurks money. Not many make much of
it in classical music, yet enough has to be ground out to keep the
paychecks coming.
</P>
<P>
   The status we city folk assign to high art is a presumption born
of our surroundings. We make everything around us with our own
hands. Even the bushes in our backyards are where we want them to
be. There are rats and cockroaches to remind us that we are not in
complete control, but such things tend to be mentally pushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   Every composer, conductor, musicologist and critic ought to be
forced to spend time in places like West Africa. The shrinkage of
stature would both alarm and instruct them. The roads of Botswana
are less invitations to travel than warnings to stay home. The
airstrips are several hundred feet of rough clay cut out of the
bush. Pray that they are not mud and that a herd of impala has not
camped on your taxi space. Africa barely notices your presence.
</P>
<P>
   People count for little in a country of 230,000 square miles
inhabited by 1.3 million citizens. Given the vastness and variety
of life, the works of man rate only a small entry in a very large
catalog of experience.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary beauty of living and growing things in the
Okavango Delta in Botswana makes one forget the equally
extraordinary danger to the relatively helpless human being.
Hippopotamuses may be the endearing clowns of Walt Disney's
``Fantasia,'' but hippos kill more people than any other animal in
Africa. (Never get between them and the water.)
</P>
<P>
   By day there is the overwhelming silence of the bush. At night
one hears the community and the competition. Lions moan in tall
grass; hippopotamuses grunt in bursts of three as they come from
the water to feed on the rushes around you; baboons engage in
high-decibel argument. Each is saying to the bush, ``I am here, and
this is who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone pondering the meaning of art might give a listen to the
birds and animals of the Okavango. The sounds they make are both
warning and welcome, but mostly they are acts of self-expression
and thus self-preservation. If animals can be said to have an art,
it is in the unequivocal announcement of their presence. The
message to their own kind is, ``We are the same''; to others, ``We
are different from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Wagner and Bach are doing the same thing, even if we,
having exalted our presence in the world beyond all reality, are
too presumptuous to realize it. Instead of calls or cries, people
have language, be it visual, verbal or musical. Language is more
complex and flexible than the squawk of the gray lory, and not as
uniform. The message changes from person to person.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe our art is what we create as a substitute. Perhaps our
music is simply a way of telling ourselves and the inhabitants of
the next tree who we are and what we are not. Just as the sight and
sound of one stork incorporates the evolutionary story of a
species, so Wagner's ``Ring'' encapsulates a genetic history of its
own. It also says to the squirrel on the lawn, ``I am different
from you.''
</P>
<P>
   If we could bring ourselves to renounce art and music in the
months when nature is at its most powerful, we might be disabused
of the notion of our special connection with the almighty. The
Beethoven Ninth Symphony, which seemed so close to God in January,
would take on a very different look in August, heard at a place
where people have little presence and almost no influence. The
Beethoven Ninth without a roof over its head is just another
birdcall. It proclaims that humans write Beethoven Ninths and that
other animals don't.
</P>
<P>
   Another antidote to human arrogance are the colossal red sand
dunes of western Namibia. Drive among them, and you will feel awe
and a few twinges of fear as well. You are not where you belong,
and there is nothing but emptiness behind you and up ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Windhoek, the Namibian capital, looks tidy. An orchestra or
opera company might pass through yearly, usually from Cape Town,
but table conversation tends toward land and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Civilization puts up a brave front, but the surrounding Kalahari
Desert has its crushing psychic effect. Human beings do best in
bigger cities, where they can assure themselves of their mutual
importance. We may think that the sounds of Bach and Wagner reach
to the heavens, but Africa tells us that they are minor peeps,
identifying humans to themselves and to any other creature that
might care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
