<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO-PERFORMANCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCH BRINGS ANOTHER RECORD FOR KANSAS CITY AREA CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ March is always a very good month for the
casinos, but last month's performance stands alone.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gaming Commission reports show the area's four casinos
raked in an astonishing $48.3 million on record admissions of 2.4
million. That shattered the previous high marks of $44.6 million
and 2.2 million, set in February.
</P>
<P>
   Those dollars are gamblers' combined losses, and the growing
tally concerns foes of legalized gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people are gambling. That's a fact,'' said Steve Taylor,
executive director of the anti-gambling lobby Casino Watch. And
that's thanks mostly to open boarding, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more and more people gamble, more and more people will wind
up being addicted. Those are the people that we are concerned about
_ those that can't handle it,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The big numbers hardly raised an eyebrow at the region's
economic think tank.
</P>
<P>
   David Reisdorph, a senior researcher at the Mid-America Regional
Council in Kansas City, noted that $48.28 million a month _ $579.36
million a year _ represented a 1.3 percent sliver of area
residents' $46 billion in annual after-tax income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given all the things we can consume, it barely registers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, consumers in the 11-county metropolitan area this
year are projected to spend $6.46 billion at area restaurants and
bars, $3.2 billion on new furniture and household goods, and $950
million for gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Reisdorph added that a similar free-spending phenomenon occurred
around the same time every spring and early summer on new cars and
durable goods, such as refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conventional wisdom is that everybody had recovered from
their Christmas spending,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maxine Odell of the Convention and Visitors Bureau of Greater
Kansas City speculated that another factor for the riverboats'
March Madness might be the annual Big 12 men's and women's college
basketball tournaments. The games attract around 10,000 out-of-town
visitors to Kansas City who are looking for entertainment between
games.
</P>
<P>
   Gaming Commission financial analyst Jim Oberkirsch has another
theory: ``The early (federal income tax) filers are already getting
their refund checks.''
</P>
<P>
   John J. Finamore, Station Casino's president for Midwest
operations, sees the effects firsthand. ``People are getting money
to burn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri boats in the metropolitan St. Louis market also set a
record in March by topping $37.4 million, leading to a statewide
revenue record of $90.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of open boarding in St. Louis last summer and in
Kansas City last fall is certainly one of the biggest factors for
the overall bump in gambling activity. Admissions and revenues have
been climbing at unprecedented rates since those changes.
</P>
<P>
   But spring is also a factor, Finamore said.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, like clockwork, Kansas City casinos' best months are
March and the peak vacation period in July. If the past is any
guide, the market should fall back to the low to mid $40 million
level until midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   The irony isn't lost on Finamore.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago in March we were talking about $42 million being a
record that month,'' he said. ``Now we're wondering if we'll slump
back to that level.''
</P>
<P>
   But the past may no longer be prelude.
</P>
<P>
   The customer-friendly dynamics of open boarding appear to have
rewritten the laws of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   Before open boarding, casino patrons had to plan and time their
arrival to coincide with phantom two-hour ``cruise'' departures or
wait up to 75 minutes for the next chance to get in.
</P>
<P>
   Now casino doors are open all the time. Statewide last month,
riverboat admissions were up 27 percent from March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to a casino is now a spur-of-the-moment thing,'' said
Bill Edwards, founder of the Kansas City-based International
Association of Slot and Video Players.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area's battle for market share, longtime
leader Harrah's trailed Station Casino for the third straight
month. But give Harrah's an A-plus for trying.
</P>
<P>
   The North Kansas City casino in March topped $15.9 million,
breaking Station's July 1999 record of $15.6 million for the
richest month in Kansas City riverboat history.
</P>
<P>
   But Station posted an even better March _ $16.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Station entertained more than 850,000 patrons last month,
topping the monthly admission record of 838,000 it set in February
1997. That was Station's first full month of operation, when the
sprawling entertainment complex was still a ``must see'' novelty.
</P>
<P>
   While Station is the market's new leader, Harrah's is still more
efficient at making money.
</P>
<P>
   In March the Kansas City marketplace had 9,249 ``gaming
positions,'' or places for gamblers at any one time. Harrah's
operates 27.6 percent of those positions but last month captured
almost 33 percent of the market's dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Station owns almost 45 percent of the positions but took in 34
percent of the dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity means Harrah's frequently is operating at
capacity, while Station must absorb the overhead expense of excess
slot machines and table games that no one is playing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
