<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-U.S.-BANK-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE TO PAY $7.7 BILLION FOR FLEMING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Chase Manhattan formally agreed Tuesday to acquire
Robert Fleming Holdings for $7.7 billion, part of an effort by
Chase to strengthen its presence in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which had been widely expected, means the end of
independence for Fleming, one of the last privately held investment
banks based in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   It also illustrates the intensifying pressure on midsize firms
like Fleming to merge with larger institutions on favorable terms
or risk being swallowed up or driven out of an increasingly global
business.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said its motive in acquiring Fleming had little to do with
saving money by trimming overlapping businesses. Rather, the
American bank said, the purchase would help vault it into a
position that would allow it to compete more effectively around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will give Chase, the third-largest bank in the
United States, a quick presence in Asia, where Fleming's asset
management business has been flourishing, and in Europe. The
addition of Fleming also gives Chase new revenue streams from asset
management.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is expected to be completed by July or August.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about expense synergies,'' said William B. Harrison
Jr., Chase Manhattan's chief executive. ``If you like the growth
prospects for Asia and Europe, then you will like this
transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all investors and analysts viewed the deal so favorably,
with some saying Chase might have overpaid for Fleming. Under the
terms of the agreement, Chase will pay about $4.1 billion in cash
and $3.6 billion in its stock. In New York on Tuesday, Chase
Manhattan shares fell $2.125, to $86.
</P>
<P>
   ``It clearly took a bit for Chase to leverage it away from the
family,'' said Julian Bird, an analyst with Credit Lyonnais
Securities here.
</P>
<P>
   Chase acknowledged that the acquisition would dilute earnings
the first year, but maintained that the dilution was not
significant.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, which is not a publicly traded company, is 29.4
percent-owned by the Fleming family _ which included Ian Fleming,
the writer who created the character James Bond.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was founded 127 years ago by Robert Fleming, a onetime
bookkeeper who saw a future in investing in the cattle ranches and
railroads of America, then the world's most promising emerging
economy. Fleming formed the Scottish-American Investment Trust,
which expanded into one of Britain's biggest asset managers by the
time of his death in 1933 at age 88.
</P>
<P>
   It has since grown to operate in 40 countries with a staff of
7,500, managing $140 billion in clients' funds. The company also
owns Jardine Matheson Holdings, one of Asia's leading investment
management and banking groups.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that the new company, which will be called
Chase Flemings, would still operate in a second-tier league to
larger and more powerful investment banks like Merrill Lynch and
the Goldman Sachs Group.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Fleming, a loss of independence may have been inevitable
if it is to ultimately survive in the face of aggressive global
expansions by American firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same dilemma that Schroders faced,'' said John Tyce,
a banking analyst at SG Securities here, referring to the
acquisition by Citigroup of that British investment bank in
January. ``In case no one has noticed, the Yanks are here and they
are making people squeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The only remaining independent British investment bank is now
Cazenove &AMP; Co., which, interestingly, advised Fleming during the
negotiations with Chase Manhattan. Chase's own
mergers-and-acquisitions unit acted as its adviser.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Fleming sold its half-stake in a joint
venture with T. Rowe Price Associates for $780 million to Price,
the Baltimore-based mutual fund company and money manager. Rowe
Price Fleming manages about $43 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the arrangement, Fleming's current chief executive,
William Garrett, will continue to run the business. Chase said no
layoffs are expected.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Fleming reflects Chase's strategy of building
its business by making several smaller acquisitions rather than
merging with one of the bigger banks. Last year, Chase bought
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist for $1.35 billion, strengthening itself in
technology-related investment banking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
