<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3937 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-KUBRICK-FILMS-$ADV16-     04-11 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUBRICK-FILMS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING EYES TO A KUBRICK MASTERPIECE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick's death last spring, followed by the release of
``Eyes Wide Shut,'' revived a long-running argument among critics
and fans about whether Kubrick was one of the most important
contemporary filmmakers or merely among the most self-important _
an avatar of cinematic perfection or a cold, detached
perfectionist.
</P>
<P>
   The debate shows no signs of ending any time soon. Last month,
Vanity Fair published a long, passionate defense of Kubrick, and in
particular of his widely unloved last work, by his friend and
sometime collaborator Michael Herr. And beginning Friday, Film
Forum will provide fuel for many nights of heated cafe-table
contention as it mounts a three-week retrospective of the
director's work, ranging from the limpid black-and-white of
``Killer's Kiss'' to the deep red of ``Eyes Wide Shut'' _ from Kirk
Douglas to Jack Nicholson to Tom Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget _ though many have tried _ Ryan O'Neal, who
played the title role in ``Barry Lyndon.'' Film Forum's series
opens with a full week of Kubrick's slow, gorgeous interpretation
of William Makepeace Thackeray's obscure, semi-parodic homage to
the picaresque novels of Fielding and Smollett. This film _
legendary for its length, its cinematography and its costumes _ has
never figured very prominently in the squabbling over Kubrick's
oeuvre. Now audiences can set aside their preconceptions and view a
clean new 35-mm print with fresh eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But our eyes may be more jaded than they were 25 years ago, when
``Barry Lyndon'' was released to bafflement, exasperation and only
an occasional note of praise. It was nominated for eight Academy
Awards and won five, for cinematography, set decoration, art
direction, costume design and adapted score. (Milos Forman's ``One
Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' swept the major Oscars.)
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's previous two films, ``2001'' and ``A Clockwork
Orange,'' had been successful enough to entice Warner Brothers to
invest $11 million in 183 minutes of episodic storytelling complete
with third-person voiceover narration and printed chapter headings.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, as Vincent Canby noted in The New York Times,
movies in which characters write ``with a feather'' were a hard
sell in the movie industry. ``Barry Lyndon'' may not have restored
the prestige of the literary costume drama (``period _ or feather _
films,'' as Canby put it) in Hollywood. But in hindsight the film
seems to prophesy the ascendancy of James Ivory, Ismail Merchant
and Ruth Prawer Jhabvala, whose tastefully decorated, scrupulous
adaptations of literary masterworks have been among the most widely
praised and influential films of the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But resemblances between ``Barry Lyndon'' and the renderings of
E.M. Forster, Jane Austen and Henry James that constitute a minor
genre unto themselves are misleading. For one thing, the literary
feather film is usually a festival of big acting, and Kubrick was
never more indifferent to his cast than in ``Barry Lyndon.'' Within
the movie's formal restraints, however, the acting is nearly
flawless. O'Neal and Marisa Berenson (as the preternaturally pallid
Lady Lyndon) are surprisingly affecting.
</P>
<P>
   But a deeper distinction lies in Kubrick's canny choice of
literary source, and his brazen subversion of it. Most films
adapted from books strive, above all, to be faithful. With good
exceptions (Amy Heckerling's ``Clueless'') and bad (Pam Densham's
``Moll Flanders''), fidelity to a book is commonly taken to require
the careful preservation of its every nuance and detail.
</P>
<P>
   But this approach dooms even intelligent and sensitive readings
like Ivory's ``Howards End'' or Ang Lee's ``Sense and Sensibility''
to charming mediocrity, as though they were school essays on the
great books rather than fully imagined versions of them. This is
because part of what makes the books great _ what makes them live _
is their modernity, the sense of vital contemporaneity we get when
we read.
</P>
<P>
   Austen did not set out to recreate Regency England; she lived in
it, and the country house dramas of status, ambition, and desire
she wrote are also dramas of incomplete social change.
</P>
<P>
   But not costume dramas. The line of English novelists that
followed from Austen _ the great tradition, as F.R. Leavis defined
it, of George Eliot, Henry James and D.H. Lawrence _ is relatively
unconcerned with recreating the past. To be faithful to them by
means of painstaking recreation is thus, necessarily, to betray
them.
</P>
<P>
   Thackeray's first novel, which nobody has ever called a
masterpiece, is a different kind of literary beast. It is, for one
thing, a costume drama in its own right. Published in 1844, ``The
Memoirs of Barry Lyndon, Esq.'' not only unfolds in the latter
decades of the 18th century, but is a self-conscious throwback to
the literature of that era, which its author viewed as superior to
the work of his contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows then,'' Thackeray wrote in a coda he later
suppressed, ``but the old style of Moliere and Fielding, who drew
from nature, may come into fashion again, and replace the terrible,
the humorous, always the genteel impossible now in vogue?''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick, always an enemy of the ``genteel impossible,''
responded to this provocation, and applied it against the cinematic
vogue of his own time by making a movie at once florid in its
realism and brazenly, gluttonously formalistic. His shots duplicate
18th-century prints and paintings, as though he were Hogarth
telling stories by tableau. And like Hogarth's prints, ``Barry
Lyndon's'' static compositions teem with life.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the futures Kubrick painted in ``2001'' and ``A Clockwork
Orange,'' his past does not feel out of date. More than most movies
drawn from antique literature, ``Barry Lyndon'' recreates in the
viewer the leisurely absorption of reading a 19th-century novel. It
is also a masterpiece of 18th-century cinema _ the kind of movie
they used to make back before movies were invented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
