<HEADLINE>
HOUSE HOPES TO COMBAT TREND TOWARD ABANDONING BABIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Tuesday urged federal, state and local
health agencies to track the number of newborn babies discarded in
trash bins, bathrooms and other public places, as part of a
nationwide effort to stop parents from abandoning their infants.
</P>
<P>
   In passing a nonbinding resolution, lawmakers said the federal
government currently relies on media reports to determine the
number of abandoned babies, a flawed method that undermines efforts
to remedy the problem. Having health officials count each abandoned
child will spur policy-makers to develop ways to combat the
problem, House members said in passing the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Department of Health and Human Services, in its
informal media survey, said 105 babies were found abandoned
nationwide in 1998, including 33 who died.
</P>
<P>
   In its resolution, the House praised Texas for its landmark law
enacted last year that excuses from criminal prosecution adults who
abandon children at medical-care facilities. The law, similar to
legislation being considered in 24 other states, is intended to
stop infant abandonments that end in death by allowing desperate
parents to leave their children in a safe place without fear of
being sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, a chief sponsor of the
resolution, called the measure an important step in combatting the
crisis of infants being left in trash cans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must know how bad the situation is before we can stop it,''
DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of babies left in unsafe public places is
unknown, the federal government estimates that more than 30,000
babies are abandoned at hospitals each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These babies are the lucky ones,'' DeLay said, noting they
have instant access to health care. ``The little ones left in trash
bins often don't live past their first day.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay added that lawmakers and community leaders must join in
trying to end abandonments.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, called the resolution, which
lacks the force of law, ``an important first step'' in finding a
solution to the problem of abandonment. Jackson Lee has introduced
legislation that would require the Justice Department to conduct a
study and report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thirteen babies were found abandoned in Houston last year, mostly
in trash bins and alleys. Three of these children died, local
officials reported.
</P>
<P>
   The rash of abandonments in Houston last year prompted local
officials to form the Task Force on Baby Abandonment, which has
mounted an advertising campaign to help parents in crisis. The task
force also has a toll-free hot line (1-877-904-SAVE) to advise
these parents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
States considering laws like that in Texas are Alabama, California,
Colorado, Connecticut, Florida, Georgia, Illinois, Indiana, Kansas,
Kentucky, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, Mississippi, New Jersey,
New Mexico, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon,
Pennsylvania, Tennessee and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
