<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN GET A LESSON IN THE LAW FROM FAIRY TALE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE OLIVA  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The prosecution cringed as the defendant took
the stand Tuesday and insolently explained how a family treasure
got turned into toothpicks on the morning of Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat in the little chair ... rocking back and forth, and it
felt so nice,'' she said, twirling a blond lock around her finger.
``And then it just broke. It must not have been put together very
well. It was obviously a very cheap chair. But I did feel just
awful about it. It was a complete accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gold E. Locks was acquitted of criminal damage, a jury
of 12 eighth-graders from Foreign Language Middle School found her
guilty of criminal trespass.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of the State vs. Gold E. Locks was just one of several
Kansas City Metropolitan Bar Association events scheduled for Law
Week 2000. Young lawyers took on the roles of Locks, Pop A. Bear,
Babe E. Bear and Mom A. Bear, while Jackson County Circuit Judge
Jack Gant presided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tries to show them how it really is and how the process
works from beginning to end,'' said lawyer Sybil Renick, who played
Locks. ``Sure, we threw in some of the dramatics ... to make it a
little bit more enjoyable, but it shows them how you have to really
listen to what people are saying. Hopefully they realize how
important of a duty it is as a juror to listen to all the evidence
and try to make the right and just decision in a case.''
</P>
<P>
   Renick, who works at the law firm of Armstrong Teasdale said
this was the first year Locks had not lost on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   Eighth-grader Laura Sellers, one of the jurors, said that she
knew someone was lying, but that there was not enough evidence to
prove Gold E. Locks damaged the property on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   On the stand, Locks said she had just stopped by because Babe
had broken her bedroom window playing baseball the night before.
When she found the house unoccupied, she went in to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knocked on the door a bunch of times, but no one answered,''
she said. ``The door was open, so I peeked in. ... Where I come
from, if you go to see a neighbor and the neighbor isn't home, you
just sit on the front porch and wait for him to return. If it's too
cold, then you go inside and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   But ignorance of the law is no excuse, the jurors decided. Locks
was not invited in; therefore, she was guilty of trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's amazing when you see how they rationalize and
come to the verdict, because you don't get to see that in an actual
trial,'' said Law Week chairwoman Jennifer Hannah, who acted as
Locks' defense attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The students who sat on the jury said deciding someone's fate
was more difficult than they thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to harm anybody,'' said eighth-grader Makila
Williams, ``but you have to do the right thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
