r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     04-11 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS' SEASON `NOT ACCEPTABLE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- There were times when Pierre Gauthier tried to smile,
but not even a faint smile could disguise his anger and frustration
at the Mighty Ducks' failure to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sugarcoat anything, this is not acceptable,''
said Anaheim president and general manager. ``We said we were going
to make the next step and we didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 18-point point increase and sixth-place finish in the
Western Conference last season, the logical next step would have
been a move up the standings, not a ninth-place finish. The Ducks
completed the 1999-2000 season with the same number of points (83)
and only one less win (34), but while they treaded water others
swam past, including the rival Kings who open their first-round
series Thursday in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier is determined not to let it happen again. He knows he
has two of the elite players in the league (Paul Kariya and Teemu
Selanne) and a solid young defense (led by Oleg Tverdovsky), but he
also was adament that changes will be made during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you right now we aren't coming back with the same
team,'' said Gauthier. ``We need to find some other players. We
should be in the playoffs, but were not a top tier club (yet).
</P>
<P>
   ``This a huge summer for us. The step is right there for us to
make, we just have to make the right moves. We need to get
immediate results here and it's my responsibility to look at every
part of the operation, coaching, scouting, player personal
decisions. I have to have a discussion with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But as frustrated as Gauthier is, he also insists that Anaheim
is closer to being a top tier team than it was a year ago,
especially with the development of defensemen Tverdovsky, Vitaly
Vishnevski, Niclas Havelid and Pavel Trnka.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a team to break up, it's a team to add to,'' he
said. ``We don't need to build a team through free agency, we need
to find pieces to the puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   A big part of that puzzle figures to be finding players that
could help take some of the scoring burden off the No. 1 line of
Kariya, Selanne and Steve Rucchin. Gauthier wouldn't address
specfic needs, but the need for a proven, physical scorer would
appear to be obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, despite playing with a sore hip and a broken foot at
times during the season, still scored 42 goals, Selanne, hampered
by a bad back scored 33 and Rucchin, who missed 11 games due to a
staph infection in his foot and was never at full strength again,
scored 19. No other forward scored more than Matt Cullen's 13.
After Kariya, Selanne and Rucchin the leading goal scorers were
defensemen (Tverdovsky and Fredrik Olausson both had 15).
</P>
<P>
   ``We scored very few hard goals,'' said Gauthier. ``We scored a
ton of nice goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite outside criticism of Craig Hartsburg's system and the
rumors of his dismissal, a head coaching change doesn't appear
likely. One thing for sure Hartsburg has the support of his two
stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he knows the game,'' said Selanne. ``I think he did a
good job and I hope he is back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaching staff did an excellent job,'' said Kariya. ``It's
the players that didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier didn't give Hartsburg, who has one year remaining on
his contract, a complete vote of confidence, but it's hardly
unusual for the Ducks GM not to lay all of his cards on the table,
especially with the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of places there might be an emotional reaction and
fire the coach,'' said Gauthier. ``In our case we are going to sit
down with Craig and discuss solutions. The plan is to stay with
Craig as long as we have the solutions to address our fallbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to win and he's taken this very, very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg, who looked as somber after a meaningless loss to the
Kings on Sunday as he had all season, was asked Monday how much of
a burden he places on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge,'' he said. ``I feel I should have done better. I'm going
to look at myself. I'm involved in this game because of the team
and when you lose you feel like you've let people down.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hartsburg did say the season will not be a total failure if
you learn from it.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Ducks certainly learned was the importance of
special teams and goaltending. It was those two areas that probably
doomed the Ducks to an early vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty killing unit finished last in the league, while the
power play dropped from No. 1 last season to No. 14. And Anaheim
had to go on a tremendous late-season surge (the Ducks were No. 1
after Feb. 1) to move up that high.
</P>
<P>
   But by that time the damage had been done. The Ducks were four
games over .500 (18-14-4-1) on Dec. 26 despite their horrendous
special teams play, but a power play goal here, a key penalty kill
there and Anaheim might have been leading the Pacific Division.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Ducks had little room for error when the underrated
Rucchin was out for 11 games, and a 3-11-2 slump knocked them out
of a playoff spot for good.
</P>
<P>
   Normally a good second-half team the Ducks spun their wheels as
Hebert, usually an excellent second-half goalie suffered through
the most inconsistent period of his career. Soft goals became an
all too common sight, leads were lost as were valuable points.
Anaheim wasn't good enough to overcome them and a 14-12-6-2 mark
over the last 32 games wasn't good enough to sneak into postseason
play.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the Dec. 22 game versus Phoenix the Ducks were
second in the league in defense (allowing 2.15 goals a game). They
finished the season 16th (2.73 per game).
</P>
<P>
   To his credit Hebert hasn't ducked the issue and has been quite
candid about his failures down the stretch. He said his play
``didn't make me very happy and nobody else as well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was whicked see-saw type season,'' he added.``A good-game,
bad-game type. A couple more good games and we'd be talking about
going into the first round of the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Ducks now have almost six months to think about
what might have been. The lost leads, the losses to inferior teams
(i.e. Montreal, the Islanders and Tampa Bay) and a lack of
consistency. Anaheim's longest winning streak was four games and
their longest unbeaten streak was five (3-0-2). The only the
consistent thing about the Ducks was their ability to hover around
the .500 mark all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look back at the way we played we didn't deserve to
get in. We played like a .500 team all year,'' said Kariya. ``We
were up and down. We showed some good things then went into the
tank for three or four games. You can't expect to win like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But doesn't make it any easier to take. ``I woke up and it (the
season) was all over,'' said Tverdovsky. ``You play all year to
experience the playoffs. You never know how many chances you are
going to get ... We just lost a chance and it's not returnable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
