<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-FILMS-ART-$ADV16-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BANKRUPT CITY RICH WITH REBELLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT28 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  
 Rob Tannenbaum's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
the Eagles' ``Greatest Hits, 1971-1975,'' the best-selling pop
album ever.  
 By ROB TANNENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few weeks ago at the Pioneer Theater in Manhattan,
the director Amos Poe introduced ``The Blank Generation,' his
rough-hewn documentary of early punk rock shows, shot on 16-mm film
in 1976 and rarely seen since. The sound and video in Poe's film
are not synchronized, which can be disorienting _ it was like
watching one movie while listening to another. But themes develop
fortuitously, and the film has a strangely disjunctive and
imagistic power.
</P>
<P>
   Before the screening, Poe likened ``The Blank Generation'' to
the Zapruder film of President John F. Kennedy's assassination.
</P>
<P>
   His implication was clear: viewers who closely examine the
blurry pictures can spot a historic event. Poe's analogy was
brazen, and skeptics may discount it. But the program of rare punk
and new wave films being shown at the Pioneer Theater, including
several weeks of the intimate, sometimes amazing series called
``Nightclubbing,'' shot at CBGB (the Dealey Plaza of punk rock) and
other New York clubs from 1975 to 1980, substantiates Poe's showy
claim for the era. (The program will end on May 24.)
</P>
<P>
   These documentaries, shot in the innocent era before MTV made
rock musicians irremediably self-conscious about performing for
cameras, show that those five years represent the apex of New York
rock history, a rampage of weird creativity and unkempt inspiration
spawned in a city so different from today's, it may as well be
Atlantis.
</P>
<P>
   After only 20 years, the approach taken in ``Nightclubbing'' now
seems vestigial: no backstage interviews and little production
trickery, just live performances videotaped at close range. The
director Pat Ivers and the producer Emily Armstrong _ whom a
journalist described in 1980 as ``the Lewis and Clark of new wave
video'' _ had a nose for truffles.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Live From CBGB'' episode includes a tentative six-song set
by Talking Heads from December 1975, almost two years before the
band's first album was released. The performance captures a band in
its awkward adolescence, like a pimply high school class photo.
</P>
<P>
   The Ivers and Armstrong series offers clips of punk, post-punk,
new wave, no wave, hardcore and avant-jazz figures, most of whom
play with spirit, invention and colorful style. Some, like Blondie,
went from Hurrah or Danceteria to fame; others, like Pylon and the
Lounge Lizards, rose to cult status and linger there as ambered
legends.
</P>
<P>
   These films, shown 20 years ago in clubs, galleries and on cable
television, illustrate the fertility of the era, but cannot explain
the conditions that created it. The city was almost bankrupt.
Streets and parks where children now play were filthy and unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   But Felix Rohatyn's fiscal nightmare was punk rock's delight;
these conditions were ideal for musicians. When the Tuff Darts sang
of New York, they said with palpable ambivalence, ``If I didn't
love it, I swear I'd burn it to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   As always in any discussion about New York, real estate is a
major theme. Artists could easily earn their cheap rents by working
a few nights as a bartender, a cabdriver (like Philip Glass) or
even a male hustler, as the Ramones sang about on ``53rd and
Third.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1971, new laws allowed artists to live in lofts that
had previously been zoned for manufacturing use only. The Ramones
and Talking Heads lived together in large spaces where they could
rehearse at odd hours. Other bands encamped in derelict apartments
near CBGB on the Bowery, in a former red-light district for
sailors.
</P>
<P>
   The guitarist Rhys Chatham, who founded the music program at the
Kitchen, recalls living in a 2,000-square-foot loft in SoHo in 1971
for $180 a month. Today, only an Internet millionaire could afford
it.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's city who read the 1996
book ``Please Kill Me,'' Legs McNeil and Gillian McCain's oral
history of punk rock (Grove Press), might find the New York of the
late '70s as unrecognizable as any distant urban life described by
Luc Sante, if not Jacob Riis. Although the book's narrative often
voyages to Los Angeles, Cleveland, Detroit or London, it returns to
New York as its true north.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Young artists who had read about Andy Warhol in their parents'
issues of Life flocked to New York, much as the Lost Generation did
to Paris in the 1920s, because it was cheap. (In ``Please Kill
Me,'' Stiv Bators of the Dead Boys urges his oddball Cleveland
bandmates to move to New York, saying, ``We'd be normal there.'')
</P>
<P>
   The city's music scene was led by outsiders: gays, junkies,
strippers, transvestites, poets, former mental patients. After
Warhol, divisions between rockers and musicians were obliterated,
so middle-class art graduates mingled with Bronx truants.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream music was suffused with a healthy ambition that rock
purists viewed as pretentious. The effect was a kind of
deconstruction of the rock band, with widely varying ideals of
performance and skill.
</P>
<P>
   In one compelling scene from ``Nightclubbing,'' Lydia Lunch of
Teen-age Jesus and the Jerks sneers at an unseen crowd. ``We
(italics)are(end italics) great, (italics)aren't(end italics) we?''
she says, and the band races into a distorted racket that hops
between two harsh chords, like kids bashing at instruments during
an unsupervised recess. After 30 seconds, the noise halts suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   The music incorporated the flamboyant showmanship of Charles
Ludlam's Ridiculous Theater Company and internalized the city's
violent energy. ``I understand all destructive urges,'' Tom
Verlaine of Television sang, over a distorted guitar riff. In
another scene, Stiv Bators twitches onstage like a hamster during
electroshock. Dressed in black, he drinks beer, chews bubble gum,
takes down his jeans, and, having created the mayhem he sought,
dives into a mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   To pare the city's budget, Mayor Abraham D. Beame fired 65,000
municipal workers beginning in 1975, leaving far fewer police on
patrol. ``Please Kill Me'' would give Giuliani an anxiety attack.
It describes a city that's all but unregulated, more like the scene
of a Cormac McCarthy western or ``Lord of the Flies'' than our
current boomtown.
</P>
<P>
   One musician tells an anecdote about being caught by cops with
heroin and a needle and then released. So much for zero tolerance.
In a song from Television's 1977 debut album, Tom Verlaine sings
about a friend who suggests they dress up like the police, adding,
``Think of what we could do.'' Verlaine replies with caution
(``Something said, `You better not''') because he's wary of
impersonating the law in a lawless town.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the music was driven by the madness and, yes, the
occasional inspiration of cheap and abundant drugs. But also, in a
day when politicians left artists alone, there was an abundance of
publicly supported places to perform like Artist's Space, the
Kitchen, Franklin Furnace and P.S. 122, as well as the poetry
series at St. Mark's Place, where Patti Smith and Jim Carroll
regularly read. All these places were kept full because New York
was slow to get wired for cable, and there were fewer reruns and
sports broadcasts to keep people dormant.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the music died of too much freedom. Drug use turned to
addiction. The last chapters of ``Please Kill Me'' are full of
nervous breakdowns and death, lots of death. The economic
conditions that drew immigrant vagabonds changed. They emerged
later in the outer boroughs, where they engendered hip-hop culture,
and in other towns, like Athens, Ga., or Seattle, then vanished
there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Reed's old refrain, ``Those were different times,'' remains
an urban constant. But for half a decade, New York's filthy,
libertine conditions fertilized a great rock scene no future
residents are likely to equal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
