<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3952 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SILVERS-DANCE-ART-$AD     04-11 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILVERS-DANCE-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POSTMODERN BORROWER WHO GOES HER OWN WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn.)   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT30 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  
 Christopher Reardon's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about the choreographer David Parsons.  
 By CHRISTOPHER REARDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sally Silvers calls herself a dancer and a
choreographer, but by many conventional measures she resembles
neither. She has never succeeded at an audition, or joined a
professional dance company, or started a troupe of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Silvers exerts a palpable force within the downtown
dance scene, both as a performer of striking intensity and as a
creator of wildly original movement. Working mostly with pick-up
troupes, she has gained an ardent following over the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Her choreography _ marked by dense layers of imagery and sudden
shifts of weight and mood _ owes as much to improvisational music,
independent film and experimental poetry as it does to modern
dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sally is one of the brightest people downtown,'' said Mark
Russell, who directs PS 122 and was an early champion of her work.
``There are plenty of postmodern choreographers out there borrowing
from other art forms, but she's one of the few who really grasp the
concepts behind the music and poetry scenes she's plugged into.''
</P>
<P>
   Her newest piece, ``Storming Heaven,'' will have its premiere on
April 26 at the Kitchen. Inspired partly by Luigi Nono, who was
Italy's leading postwar avant-garde composer, it chronicles a
series of revolutions from the Paris Commune of 1871 to the
Zapatista rebellion that began six years ago in Chiapas, Mexico.
The two-act piece, which focuses on four female rebels, puts
psychology before polemics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more interested in the moment of mobilization than in what
happens after, or why so many revolutions go bad,'' Silvers, 47,
said over lunch recently at her East Village apartment. ``This
piece explores the internal struggles: the decisions to get
involved, the doubts, the hesitations, the process of learning to
think as a group.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to sketch the contours of her life as an independent
artist, from the periodic thrill of breaking new ground to the
constant struggle to get grants to pay the dancers. But while she
inhabits a world just outside the spotlight, her work has not gone
unnoticed. She won a Guggenheim fellowship in 1988, a Bessie award
in 1993 and five grants from the National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   A compact woman with deep brown eyes and a hushed voice, Silvers
grew up in Greenville, Tenn., a tobacco town in the Appalachian
Mountains. Around the age of 6, she started taking classes in
ballet, tap, jazz and acrobatics at the local VFW post. Yet it was
not until her sophomore year at Antioch College in Ohio that she
took dancing seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The college's artist in residence that year was Cecil Taylor,
the trailblazing pianist who helped invent free jazz, and he had
with him a modern-dance choreographer named Ken Miller. For
Silvers, it was an epiphany. ``Ken was an artist, not a teacher,''
she said. ``Working with him that year turned my head around.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1975, she considered writing for an
alternative newspaper in West Virginia's coal-mining communities,
but the muse beckoned. In New York, dance classes with Douglas Dunn
and Dana Reitz made her yearn for the old Judson Dance Theater, the
loose collective of artists who expanded the limits of dance in the
1960s. But with Judson long gone, she turned to a circle of
experimental artists that included John Zorn, the prodigious
saxophonist and composer, and Bruce Andrews, a writer intent on
developing new literary forms and new methods of composition.
</P>
<P>
   Like them, she began using improvisation as a way to generate
fresh material, filling untold hours of videotape and then
fashioning the most unusual movements into new dances. (For many
years, Zorn helped provide live accompaniment for her
performances.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't stuck in the dance tradition of making lyrical,
academically structured work,'' she said. ``I could compose a dance
the way experimental poetry is constructed or the way a film is
edited.''
</P>
<P>
   Silvers later was co-director of two short films, including
``Little Lieutenant,'' which won a silver award at the 1994 Dance
on Camera Festival. Her affinity for cinematic techniques, and
montage in particular, is readily apparent in ``Storming Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking her cue from films about workers' revolts by Eisenstein,
Pudovkin and Godard, Silvers is constructing scenes that function
like close-ups. While rehearsing a segment about the 1968 student
uprising in Paris, for example, eight dancers assembled in two
facing rows to frame a narrow tunnel. Suddenly, someone's hand
reached across the empty space to take a leaflet from someone
standing opposite.
</P>
<P>
   A visual artist, Antonio Martorell, will remain onstage
throughout the piece, creating props on the fly. Martorell, whose
lacework maps were shown at the 1997 Whitney Biennial, has also
designed several set pieces for the production, including a cyclone
made of copper tubing that will hang upside down above the stage.
At one point, he will dance a tango with his daughter, Alejandra,
who frequently performs in Silvers' work.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, who composes electronic music as well as experimental
poetry, is creating a soundscape modeled on the life and work of
Nono, who died in 1990. Last winter, he and Silvers visited the
composer's archives in Venice, where they met his widow and watched
a videotape of the 1978 La Scala production of ``In the Sun's
Love-Provoking Light,'' Nono's opera about the Paris Commune.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said the encounter had made his music ``much less
jumpy'' than the soundscapes he had created for dozens of earlier
dances by Silvers, his longtime partner in life and art.
</P>
<P>
   Silvers tends to develop new material on her own and then gather
a group of dancers when she is ready to present it _ an approach
that limits her to a few engagements each year but gives her access
to talented performers. Many of them _ including Cydney Wilkes,
Andrea Kleine and David Neumann _ are choreographers themselves.
(Neumann is in the midst of a two-week season at P.S. 122, where he
is performing a duet with the poet John Giorno and staging an
ensemble work, ``Oyinbo,'' that uses square dancing as a vehicle
for exploring cultural identity.)
</P>
<P>
   Between rehearsals, Silvers reports to her day job at the Labor
Institute, which produces health and safety videos and organizing
materials for labor unions. She has been there 18 years, working 20
hours a week in return for a regular paycheck, a health-care plan
and a pension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I would want the career of the
dancer-choreographer whose life was touring and teaching and doing
residencies,'' she said. ``Even though I make wildly abstract
works, I feel it's important to stay connected to the social world,
to keep myself grounded in something real.''
</P>
</TEXT>
