<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore promises improved education for nation's children in Ohio
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS _ Vice President Al Gore was back in school Tuesday
solving math problems, drawing pictures, writing letters and trying
to convince voters that he will do more to improve education than
his rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But in between classes and a hot-dog lunch, Gore's visit to a
Columbus' elementary school focused on much more serious questions
from parents and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Questions such as, Why are so many kids being killed in schools
or bringing guns into their classroom? Why are young students
judged so heavily by proficiency tests? And how can teachers be
effective when their classroom are overflowing with kids?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the largest generation of students in our nation's
history and all of our classrooms are crowded. That's why education
is my top priority and will remain that way if I'm entrusted with
the presidency,'' said Gore, who was making his second in a series
of visits with students, teachers and parents that his campaign is
calling School Days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence in our schools and the way we measure our schools'
performance are primary concerns of people I have talked with
around the nation,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce school violence, Gore said parents need to become more
involved with kids, the nation needs fewer guns on the street and
schools need more counselors and smaller class sizes that would let
teachers better identify kids with problems.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit to low-income Avondale Elementary School reinforced
the importance of the education issue in this year's presidential
campaign _ an issue on which Gore, a Democrat, and Bush, a
Republican, have continually sparred. Campaign officials for Gore
on Tuesday again called attention to a 1999 study that ranked the
condition of Texas school buildings near the bottom nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who visited a Michigan middle school last month, told
Avondale's parents and teachers that making preschool available to
all students and communities is the cornerstone of his education
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids can catch up, but some never do, and dollar for
dollar, pre-school is the best investment in education we can
make,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his campaign, Gore has touted a plan to spend $115
billion over 10 years on a host of education programs, including
preschool, expanded after-school programs, modernizing schools and
reducing class sizes by providing local school boards with more
money to hire teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Avondale Principal Mary Ann Burns said Gore's visit with her 400
students wasn't staged.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to see what a real school day was like, so we tried
to give him one,'' Burns said. ``A lot of our schools' problems and
the problems of most other schools could be solved if more parents
would take an active role in their children, and the vice president
talked about that a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's all-day visit included solving math problems with
fifth-graders, writing a letter to Mother Earth with first-graders
and creating a collage with a third-grade art class.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a funny guy to talk with and it was cool to have him in
our school,'' said Anthony Fisher, a third-grader who sat next to
Gore during lunch.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
