<SLUG> BC-OMNICOM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: OMNICOM MOVES TO EXPAND ITS INTERACTIVE EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In another step to expand an already extensive
interactive empire, the Omnicom Group in New York is investing in
an innovative agency that specializes in creating offline campaigns
for online marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Omnicom, which has interests in such Internet powerhouses as
Agency.com, Razorfish and Red Sky Interactive, is acquiring what is
being described as a significant minority stake in Eisnor
Interactive in New York, a shop with projected billings for this
year of $36 million from such dot-com clients as About.com,
CarOrder.com, Cnet, Dealtime.com, Homestead.com and MapQuest.com.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal, scheduled to be announced Wednesday, are not
being disclosed. Eisnor, founded an eon ago in Internet time _ 1997
by the regular calendar _ will work principally with Merkley Newman
Harty in New York, a midsize shop owned by Omnicom with billings
estimated at more than $300 million from clients like BellSouth,
Fila, Forbes, JetBlue Airways and Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   The investment by Omnicom, which also owns Madison Avenue
mainstays like BBDO Worldwide, DDB Worldwide and TBWA Worldwide,
comes as reports in the traditional media are resuming an alarmist
tone about the future of dot-coms, particularly those devoted to
consumer businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But even if a significant shakeout takes place among Internet
marketers, there would remain at least some that had grown into
successful enterprises requiring advertising services. That view
seems to be shared by a principal rival of Omnicom, Interpublic
Group of Cos., in New York, which said Tuesday that it would
strengthen ties with a leading interactive services agency, Icon
Medialab International in Stockholm, by making additional
investments in that company.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Di-Ann Eisnor, chief executive at
Eisnor, which has nearly 50 employees at its New York headquarters
and at offices in Boston and San Francisco, acknowledged the
daunting challenges that dot-coms face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients have so much pressure to build their brands and at
the same time generate results'' in the form of sales, said Ms.
Eisnor, 27, a graybeard in Internet time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's increasingly difficult to stand out from the
clutter,'' she added. ``That's why we try to think through how
people consume media and then how different media work together, so
we can use each tactic as necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's a promotion, sometimes it's event marketing,
sometimes it's a TV spot,'' said Eisnor, whose agency has also
produced wireless telephone ads for TheStreet.com, attached
billboards to bicycles to pitch Healthshop.com and paid commuters'
toll and subway fares to promote CarOrder.com. ``We're media
agnostic; we'll do whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that spirit prevailing among Eisnor and her colleagues
that appealed to the executives of Merkley Newman, said Stephen
Harty, managing director there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy level, the inventiveness, is amazing,'' Harty said.
``They're people who don't observe the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been, you could say, less adventurous with dot-coms,''
he added, referring to the small roster of such clients at the
agency that includes CareerMosaic.com, Computer.com and the
Forbes.com unit of Forbes. ``Eisnor offers a refreshing influx of a
different perspective on our business.''
</P>
<P>
   The pairing of Eisnor with Merkley Newman is the most recent in
a series of steps by Omnicom to broaden the offerings of Merkley
Newman since that agency was awarded the Mercedes-Benz of North
America account in March 1999. Merkley Newman now also operates an
agency in Atlanta, Bayless Cronin; an agency specializing in
pharmaceutical advertising, Consumer Healthworks; and an agency
specializing in direct marketing, Team South.
</P>
<P>
   While Merkley Newman ``will be home base for Eisnor within
Omnicom,'' Harty said, Eisnor will also work with other Omnicom
agencies. Eisnor will report to the Diversified Agency Services
division of Omnicom rather than to Communicade, which manages
Omnicom's investments in Internet agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Interpublic and Icon Medialab, the new commitments
from Interpublic represent a deepening of a relationship that began
13 months ago when Interpublic allied with Icon Medialab through
steps that included an investment of $20 million in exchange for a
stake of just less than 20 percent. In November, Nicholson NY, an
interactive shop that was 25 percent owned by Interpublic, agreed
to be acquired by Icon Medialab and has subsequently served as the
first U.S. office of the Swedish company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We helped them get their U.S. business off the ground,'' said
Sean Orr, executive vice president and chief financial officer at
Interpublic in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Interpublic has committed more money to help Icon Medialab
expand in Asia as well as to make an additional investment in the
company that brings the Interpublic stake back up to just less than
20 percent; the stake had diminished over the last year because of
issues of stock and options.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship has been a very, very good one,'' Orr said of
the ties between the Interpublic and Icon Medialab executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, they know how to make money,'' he said,
laughing. ``When they are in a market for more than 18 months, they
are profitable. They're also technically very proficient, very
bright and very entrepreneurial.''
</P>
<P>
   Icon Medialab clients include Coca-Cola, Motorola, Nestle and
the Opel unit of General Motors, all of which are also clients of
Interpublic agencies like the McCann-Erickson World Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
