<HEADLINE>
YOU KNOW YOU'RE A HARD-CORE BUSINESS TRAVELER IF ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (Duplication notice: also sent with `t' code)  
 By JOE SHARKEY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frequent business travelers, who tend to spend a lot of time
alone on the road, increasingly are congregating at various
Internet sites to share practical information and, given the
inexorable relationship between humor and adversity, crack jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Here, culled from postings in various business-travel chat
rooms, news groups and bulletin boards (primarily
www.flyertalk.com, sponsored by the publisher of InsideFlyer
Magazine), is a Top 10 list that could be titled: ``You Know You're
a Hard-Core Business Traveler If ...''
</P>
<P>
   1. You've noticed that despite America's reputation as a melting
pot, some people in some cities bear a frightening resemblance to
one another.
</P>
<P>
   2. You walk out into the hotel parking lot and have no idea of
the make, model or color of your rental car.
</P>
<P>
   3. You are amazed by people who cannot pack a week's worth of
clothing and needed work items into a single rollerboard and a
carry-on bag.
</P>
<P>
   4. You know the menu by heart at every TGI Friday's, Bennigan's,
Applebee's, Ruby Tuesday's and Olive Garden.
</P>
<P>
   5. You've driven more models of cars than Consumer Reports
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   6. You can tell at a glance which customs line has the
time-wasting troublemakers queued up in it.
</P>
<P>
   7. You aren't fazed by writing checks to American Express or
Visa every month for $5,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   8. You actually know the names of all the meteorologists on the
Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   9. You can recite the safety-instruction spiel word-for-word
along with the flight attendant.
</P>
<P>
   10.You press ``9'' on your home phone before dialing a number. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Side Trips
</P>
<P>
   The average daily room rates for hotels in major cities in the
United States grew by 4.4 percent during the second half of 1999
from the comparable period in 1998, according to PKF Consulting's
Hospitality Research Group. Among the reasons the research firm
cited for this increase, which occurred despite a continuing
oversupply of hotel rooms and slight declines in occupancy rates,
was the ``wealth effect'' in a booming economy that has prompted
``a loosening of tight corporate travel budgets and personal
pocketbooks.'' Reflecting this, higher-priced hotels are faring
best right now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The annual airline quality rating study jointly conducted by the
business school at Wichita State University and the Aviation
Institute at the University of Nebraska always gets a lot of
publicity with its customer-service performance rankings of the top
10 airlines in the United States in areas such as on-time arrival,
boarding availability and mishandled baggage.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2000 survey, which placed Southwest Airlines in first
place and United Airlines last, has some footnotes and observations
intended to put the overall industry on notice. Among them:
``Continued declining industry performance quality in 1999 gives
cause for Congress to again seriously consider the passage of an
Airline Passengers' Bill of Rights'' that would provide an
enforceable alternative to existing in-house attempts by the
airlines to define standards for handling customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the study warns, the decline in comfort and
reliability in air travel is leading to ``consumer retaliation''
that shows up in a doubling of informal complaints made to the
Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot, according to the study is that ``soon, consumers
will become driven by price and schedule only'' without regard to
loyalty for any particular airline.
</P>
<P>
   The study also faults the industry for ``targeting'' regional
and start-up airlines with practices like temporarily adding
flights to block upstart competitors.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Airways is accusing Northwest Airlines of trying to do
just that. AirTran recently filed a complaint with the government
saying that Northwest ``dumped'' seats onto its Minneapolis-Atlanta
routes to thwart AirTran's plan to introduce flights on that route
in June, using 100-seat Boeing 717 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This over-aggressive capacity increase eliminates the
possibility for AirTran to profitably enter the market,'' AirTran
said in a statement. But Northwest denied acting unfairly toward
AirTran, saying that it filed for expanded service on the
Minneapolis-Atlanta routes in mid-February _ weeks before AirTran
filed for its new routes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
