<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSPLANT-FIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY DOCTOR IN SENATE TO ENTER TRANSPLANT DEBATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When shots were fired at the U.S. Capitol two years
ago, Tennessee Sen. Bill Frist, M.D., sprinted from his office
across the street to aid the wounded.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as the only doctor serving in the Senate, he will
be called upon again to use his medical expertise.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Frist, a former heart transplant surgeon, will
attempt to heal a wound that has been festering for decades as the
federal government has struggled to fairly distribute a scarce
supply of donated organs to tens of thousands of patients in need
of lifesaving transplants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point where everybody is tired of the fighting,''
said Bob Spieldenner, spokesman for the Richmond, Va.-based United
Network for Organ Sharing, the private contractor that has run the
country's transplant network since its creation in 1986. ``We all
want to work this out and move forward to come up with the best
system we can, so we're hopeful that Senator Frist can find a
workable compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   With 20,000 organs expected to be donated this year, about 5,000
of the nearly 69,000 patients in line for transplants of hearts,
livers, kidneys or other organs will die waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The issue before Congress is who should write the rules
transplant doctors follow in deciding who will get a transplant and
who will not.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration says the federal government, which is
accountable to taxpayers, should have the sole authority to decide
how the country's organ supply should be used. UNOS argues that
since a medical decision is required, it should be made by
transplant professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Each side has drawn support from transplant surgeons, hospital
administrators and organ bank officials, as well as donors'
families and the transplant patients themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy heated up two years ago, when, frustrated by a
disparities in the amount of time patients around the country must
wait for a transplant, U.S. Heath and Human Services Secretary
Donna Shalala announced a new set of rules. Her plan was to change
the current system of distributing organs locally or regionally
first to a system where organs would be shared on a national basis,
with the sickest patients given top priority regardless of where
they live.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement sent a shock through the transplant community,
with smaller transplant centers and organ banks complaining that
they would have to compete with larger hospitals that have long
waiting lists for organs. Many transplant surgeons also argued that
if all the organs go to the sickest patients, survival rates would
plummet, wasting organs that could be better used in patients who
might have a better chance of surviving.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana sued to try to stop the rules from taking effect. At
least seven states, including Texas, Louisiana and Oklahoma, passed
laws giving them the right to hoard organs in-state if it comes to
that. Then the fight moved to Washington, where Congress succeeded
in holding off implementation of the rules _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   On March 16, the rules, toned down considerably from their
original insistence on national sharing and the sickest-first
criteria, finally took effect, essentially giving full authority
over transplant policy to the government.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, the House voted 275-147 to throw the rules out
and give authority to UNOS. Shalala criticized the bill as a ``step
backwards,'' and President Clinton threatened to veto it if it
reaches his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Frist, 48, will step in Wednesday to offer a compromise to
fellow members of the Senate Health, Education, Labor and Pensions
Committee: Let the medical community write the policy, but give the
government oversight to ensure that UNOS treats all patients as
fairly as possible. His bill also creates an independent commission
that would resolve disputes between UNOS and HHS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to have medical decisions made by the transplant
community, with strong oversight and strong accountability,'' the
Republican senator said last week as he introduced his compromise
bill. Despite nearly a week of negotiations, Frist had not been
able to convince Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., to sign onto his
bill as a co-sponsor, but aides for both senators said talks would
continue until the committee meets Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sen. Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., on Tuesday introduced
his own bill, essentially giving HHS what it originally wanted _
strong authority over UNOS and broader sharing of organs with the
sickest patients at the front of the transplant line. His bill also
would abolish state organ-hoarding laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House bill, in my judgment, is indefensible. There is no
public accountability for this private contractor. It's completely
inappropriate,'' Fitzgerald said. ``And Senator Frist's bill tries
to split the baby and gives HHS no real regulatory authority over
UNOS.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said seven co-sponsors had signed on to his bill and
predicted that Frist may face ``vigorous opposition'' to his plan
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Frist, who once served as head of the Vanderbilt University
Multi-Organ Transplant Center, performed more than 200 heart and
lung transplants during his medical career. He also held hands with
dying patients who could not hold on long enough for a donor organ
to become available.
</P>
<P>
   His ability to share that 20-year experience is expected to be
crucial, both in Wednesday's debate, and, if he is successful, in
an eventual conference committee to work out differences in the
House and Senate bills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
