Following years of complaints of abusive government conduct,
Congress completed legislation Tuesday that would make it harder
for government officials to confiscate property before they
actually bring criminal charges in narcotics, terrorism,
racketeering and other cases. Rep. Henry J. Hyde co-sponsored the
bill, which administration officials said that President Clinton
would sign into legislation. (Carol T. Powers/The New York Times)
