<P>
   (NYT36) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- April 11, 2000 -- LEBANON-SYRIA --
The continuing Syrian influence here can be seen in the flow of
Syrians into Lebanon to work for $10 a day at Lebanese construction
sites and sell plastic trinkets to motorists at Beirut
intersections. Hoping to be hired as unskilled laborers, Syrian
workers waited under a Beirut bridge bedecked with posters of the
Syrian president, Hafez al-Assad. (Courtney Kealy/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) CHICAGO -- April 11, 2000 -- PRIEST-PROSTITUTES -- The
Rev. Michael Pfleger, the 50-year-old pastor of St. Sabina Church,
has been searching for prostitutes on Chicago's South Side. He pays
cash for a half-hour, typically $50, but then talks to the women
about how to escape their vicious cycle. Pfleger recently spoke to
Kathy Ellis, a 40-year-old drug addict and prostitute. ``I'm
ashamed of the way my life is, but I got six kids and lots of
problems, and I don't know what else to do,'' said Ellis who,
thanks to Pfleger's intervention, now attends Narcotics Anonymous
meetings. (Steve Kagan/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
