<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A GREEN SHIP LOST AT SEA ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, someone on the good ship Jets shouted: ``Land,
Ho!'' Maybe Bill Parcells called land, maybe it was Leon Hess. In
any event, for long-suffering Jets fans, this Promised Land was a
sight for sore eyes: the Super Bowl was close.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets lost to Denver in the 1998 American Football Conference
championship game. No matter. The team was young and fiery:
Keyshawn Johnson, the brazen wide receiver, was returning.
Parcells, the gruff captain, was coming back. The ship was intact.
</P>
<P>
   Last season was an injury-induced disaster, and Tuesday came the
news came that Keyshawn Johnson was probably headed to the Tampa
Bay Buccaneers in a blockbuster trade.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, in the midst of snow and rain, the vibrant land of
a Super Bowl that loomed so large two seasons ago seems to be
rapidly shrinking. The great green ship is being pulled out to sea
by a dastardly undercurrent so familiar to Jets fans.
</P>
<P>
   Jets fans will probably find a way to rationalize the loss of a
great player: if the deal goes through, the Jets, who already have
two first-round picks, would receive Tampa Bay's two No. 1's. They
might even get one of the Bucs' starting wide receivers. Of course,
that's no loss for Tampa Bay, whose passing game is miserable.
That' why they're willing to mortgage their future for the All-Pro
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Another scenario has the Jets trading at least three of those
picks to Cleveland for the first pick of the draft, which they'll
use to get Penn State linebacker LaVar Arrington or defensive end
Courtney Brown. If you think that solves the Jets' defensive
problems, you're crazy. With their primary offensive threat gone,
and the defensive genius, Bill Belichick, gone, the Jets face a
daunting challenge in the league's most competitive division.
</P>
<P>
   The great problem with this trade for the Jets is that Tampa Bay
knows exactly what it's getting: a navigator they've sorely missed
on offense. The Jets are getting promising players, some of whom
may be deck hands. Who knows if there are any navigators in the
group. That leaves a first-year coach and a new owner to battle the
turbulent seas of the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was fourth in the American Football Conference last
season in receptions with 89 for 1,170 yards and 8 touchdowns for
the 8-8 Jets. He has caught 305 passes for 4,108 yards since being
drafted No. 1 out of Southern Cal.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who has followed the Jets' recent rise knows that
Johnson's value goes beyond numbers. His value is his attitude,
even though ``attitude'' is what initially turned critics off to
Johnson. He played by the rules: No off-field problems. He
graduated from USC, converted his NFL fame into endorsements,
opening a restaurant. But Johnson was cocky. And direct. He'd look
anyone in the eye _ Parcells, Al Groh, Woody Johnson _ and speak
his piece. Not everyone likes that.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells liked it because he knew that what the bland, nameless,
faceless Jets needed was a blustery coach and a brazen star
receiver. The Jets are saying this is strictly a salary-cap issue,
and during the owners meeting last week, Johnson gave the
law-and-order spin about the sanctity of contracts:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a member of the team _ he has a contract with the team,''
Johnson said. ``I think that contracts are a part of society.
Contracts are important. I think if you sign an agreement with
somebody and agree to do something, you should take that for what
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But Johnson's manner can be intimidating to a rookie coach
and a rookie owner. Especially if the ship begins to drift.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Al Groh promised that the Jets would never trade
Johnson. ``We want Keyshawn on the team, therefore, we're not
trading Keyshawn,'' he said. ``I think the statement stands on its
own legs. There's nothing more to add to it. We have no trades in
the works right now, and we're not attempting to put any
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Buccaneers were like the Jets in 1998: one game, one
quarter, one missed call away from the Promised Land. Tampa Bay
upgraded its equipment: it fired an offensive coordinator and is
trying to bring in a world-class navigator in Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets may be sending their brightest ray of light to sunny
Tampa, leaving themselves with no compass; and no winds in their
sails.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Jets fans have seen this scene before. Dark clouds,
deep thunder, a ship facing storm after storm, sailing from one
bizarre encounter to another without ever seeing land.
</P>
<P>
   The horizon is shrinking and by mid-November fans will ask:
``Didn't someone say `Land, Ho?'''
</P>
<P>
   That's how mutinies begin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
