The Simensky rule pretty much sums up the ethos of the cannily
successful Cartoon Network: find people who write funny and draw
funny, and let them loose on America's children. The formula has
worked so well that the network, started eight years ago, has
evolved into a supplier of some of the most innovative new
animation on television. Case in point: The sassy tykes of ``The
Powerpuff Girls.'' (Cartoon Network/The New York Times)
