<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some art centers are born with well-defined missions
in mind and sizable budgets to help make their most ambitious
programming dreams come true. Others are fueled more by can-do
spirit and make-do inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, some seemingly well-financed places flounder or
disappear even after presenting good, memorable shows. (Remember
the IBM Gallery or the short-lived Center for International
Contemporary Arts?) And then there are the offbeat, sometimes more
impulsive art outposts that pop up and, despite the odds, hang on
for years and unexpectedly become important, even treasured
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Exit Art/The First World is one such irascible survivor. Now,
with a retrospective exhibition titled ``The End: An Independent
Vision of Contemporary Culture, 1982-2000,'' the nonprofit arts
center, which has become an essential stop for professionals and
enthusiasts alike, is celebrating _ and analyzing _ its own history
since its founding 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The large show, wide-ranging in its themes and content, will
remain on view through April 29. At a time of millennial fever, and
as something of an answer to other museums' splashy surveys of
20th-century art, ``The End'' offers its organizers' distinctive
take, in particular, on the art of the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see all art as a dynamic of opposites,'' said Papo Colo, an
artist, writer and performer who is a co-founder of Exit Art,
during an interview at the offices he shares in SoHo with its other
founder, Jeanette Ingberman, and a small staff. Colo, who was born
in Puerto Rico, is a restless thinker and a peripatetic voyager in
various creative fields. He speaks passionately of a commitment to
fostering artistic expression that cuts across disciplines and
cultures. He calls his outlook ``transcultural.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Colo watched the flurry of activity at a television
station next to his home; his father was a prizefighter, and from
those early influences, he acquired an appreciation of performing
and of how images, ideas and information can be persuasively
packaged. He came to New York in 1971, in his early 20s, hung out
at the Chelsea Hotel and then studied literature for a year at
Columbia University. ``I went to Mexico, did the Don Juan thing,
then spent a decade making art and going back and forth between New
York and Barcelona,'' Colo recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The product of a postcolonial society in an increasingly
multicultural world, he became fascinated by the meaning of
cultural identity _ an individual's, a nation's _ and how it is
formed. For a while, Colo created false documents as works of art,
including a fake Puerto Rican university diploma whose Latin
inscription questioned _ or mocked _ the notion of one culture
conferring legitimacy on another. That piece is on view in the
current exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Colo around 1980, when I was a curator at the Bronx
Museum,'' Ingberman said. A native New Yorker of Polish-Jewish
descent, she raised eyebrows when she focused, as a graduate
art-history student at Columbia in the late 1970s, on the still-new
topic of art and the law. A subsequent spot in the Whitney Museum's
curatorial program led to her job in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Of the early days of her collaboration with Colo, she said:
``Colo was making wound paintings when I first visited his studio;
he slashed his canvases and then sewed them back together so they
looked severe. He was involved in performance art, poetry,
painting. Immediately we had an exciting dialogue. We came from
very different backgrounds, which is what Exit Art would be about,
informed by all sorts of cultural ideas. We don't just have an idea
and try to fit artists' work into it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Colo and Ingberman mounted their first exhibition, the
sex-themed ``Dirty Pictures,'' in the Franklin Furnace Archive
space in TriBeCa. Two years later, they inaugurated their own space
on lower Broadway, effectively helping expand the SoHo art district
eastward. In 1993, they opened Exit Art's present space at 548
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the spirit of his and Ingberman's work, Colo said,
``A curator is a translator of ideas.'' But Exit Art has helped
shape the art discourse of its time, too. Others who have followed
its programming add that Colo and Ingberman's exhibitions have
responded to and reflected the strong emerging trends that their
research has turned up long before commercial galleries or
mainstream museums caught up with them.
</P>
<P>
   In their early years they gave solo, mid-career shows to
artists, including Martin Wong, David Wojnarowicz, Cecilia Vicuna
and Krzysztof Wodiczko, who had created substantive bodies of work
that establishment venues had ignored or shunned.
</P>
<P>
   Exit Art earned a place on the front lines of the culture wars
with shows like ``Illegal America'' (1990), which examined artists'
run-ins with the law and censorship. Other notable offerings have
included ``The Design Show'' (1993), a survey of exhibition
invitations; ``Comic Power'' (1993), a look at artists whose work
was influential in underground and independent comics; and
``Counterculture'' (1996), which explored alternative media from
the underground press to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Exit Art has also presented films, music events, performances
and numerous panel discussions, as well as curiosities like ``La
Tradicion: Performing Painting'' (1997), in which 10 painters lived
and worked in the exhibition space for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Hess, a former art critic for The Village Voice, said:
``Exit Art's attitude and the art it showed came out of certain
social issues and a certain edgy place. What keeps it fresh is that
Jeanette and Colo have never stopped visiting artists' studios,
even now, when everyone is so busy. Working critics and curators
absolutely have to visit studios.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is that unusual name. ``People like myself have
been marginalized by those who wield cultural power in our
society,'' Colo said. ``We've been lumped together as `the Third
World.' But in fact, the hybrid culture of our age is being
nourished by `outsiders' of all kinds _ Asians, Africans, the
peoples of the Americas. It is they who are actually creating the
new prevailing culture of the first world with their diverse
contributions. We say `exit' to suggest moving away from the
established art system and its stereotypical way of thinking. Every
exit is an entrance. Thus our name: Exit Art/The First World.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The End,'' which refers to the end of one phase of Exit Art's
mission and the beginning of another, consists, in part, of
posters, photographs, slide projections and other materials that
document the gallery's major exhibitions to date. They are
presented in the kind of spare, accessible installation for which
Colo is known. A second section features paintings, drawings,
sculptures, prints and videos from past shows. Among them are
Laurie Anderson's ``O Superman'' video (1982), Wodiczko's sleeping
container on wheels for the homeless (1988), samples of the
comic-irreverent painting style of the 1980s, and David Hammons'
untitled sculpture from 1989, a big wheel of green glass bottles
anchored in a heap of beautifully sinister charcoal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike conventional museums, Colo doesn't overly aestheticize
the work he installs,'' said Mary Anne Staniszewski, an art
historian who has served on Exit Art's board of directors and is
the author of ``The Power of Display,'' a book about the history of
exhibition design at the Museum of Modern Art. ``Instead, it's set
up in a way that articulates the meaning of what's being shown.
Often you can touch the objects. The viewer can have diverse
experiences in different kinds of installations.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Exit Art served as a significant steppingstone to
the mainstream system of commercial galleries and museums for some
artists. Although Wojnarowicz would die of AIDS two years later, at
the age of 38, his career received a boost after Exit Art exhibited
his controversial work in 1990. It pointedly addressed social and
sexual taboos and antigay bigotry. That show had originated at
Illinois State University; other New York sites were reluctant to
pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists genuinely feel welcome, and our work is presented in
ways that engage viewers in the issues it deals with,'' Wodiczko,
who comes from Poland, said of his experiences as part of what he
called ``the Exit Art family of artists'' from around the world. He
added, ``If we address sensitive issues like homelessness, even if
they may be difficult for the public or confrontational, Exit Art
is willing to consider and show the work.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be because, by insisting on their independence, even
while learning to play the inescapable fund-raising game, Colo and
Ingberman have made sure that they can show such work. (Exit Art
has received support from the National Endowment for the Arts, Dow
Jones &AMP; Co., the Lannan Foundation and others.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ingberman said, ``We're constantly asking ourselves:
`What (italics)is(end italics) an exhibition, anyway?''' Similarly,
``The End'' is more than just a salute to past achievements; it is
an introspective exhibition about the making and meanings of
exhibitions themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Colo and Jeanette are busy writing the unwritten
history of modern and avant-garde art,'' said Martha Wilson, a
performance artist and the founding director in 1976 of the
Franklin Furnace Archive, the downtown alternative-art space.
</P>
<P>
   Colo would probably concur with her, albeit with an explanatory
proviso. ``For me,'' he said emphatically, ``Exit Art has been the
great party of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
