opening in Manhattan's Chelsea neighborhood next month. (Frances
Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 11, 2000 -- GEFILTE-FISH -- Gefilte
fish became a Passover staple because of a suggestion in the Talmud
to eat fish. Since cooking on the Sabbath is prohibited, the fish
balls were cooked in advance and served cold. Eventually gefilte
fish be came the Eastern European first course for holiday
celebrations. Buba Khotoveli with gefilte fish at his restaurant,
Primorski, in Brooklyn. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- April 11, 2000 -- RHUBARB-2 -- Rhubarb can be
a challenge. It has such an aggressive nature that it needs to be
sweet-talked into being palatable. Yet it is so vibrant a harbinger
of spring that chefs are willing to exploit it in new and unusual
ways. Rhubarb salad with fennel, onion, grapefruit and balsamic
vinegar at Heartbeat, a restaurant in midtown. At right, a rhubarb
bellini, one of a special drink concocted at Esca in Manhattan.
(Marilyn K. Yee, left, Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- April 11, 2000 -- RHUBARB -- Rhubarb can be a
challenge. It has such an aggressive nature that it needs to be
sweet-talked into being palatable. Yet it is so vibrant a harbinger
of spring that chefs are willing to exploit it in new and unusual
