A3981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      04-11 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: NEW YORK)  
 MRS. CLINTON PRODS GIULIANI TO TAKE STANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton asserted Tuesday that
Rudolph Giuliani was avoiding discussion of how he would vote in
the U.S. Senate, and said it was not enough to ask voters to judge
him based solely on his record as mayor of New York, as Giuliani
has suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am running a campaign that will tell you what I will do,''
Clinton said in a hall packed with cheering municipal workers. At a
news conference later on Tuesday, she added, ``I think this
campaign should be about issues and about how each of us would vote
in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   With her remarks, Clinton sought to lay out a framework for how
voters should judge the Senate contest. The candidates, she said,
should be evaluated primarily based on how they would vote in the
Senate, a formula that would presumably favor Clinton in New York,
a Democratic state. By contrast, Giuliani has presented the
election as mainly a referendum on his performance as mayor, saying
that voters could look to New York City to judge his potential
effectiveness as a senator, an assessment that would also appear to
play to his greatest strength.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asserted that Giuliani ``won't tell you where he
stands'' on issues like the Republican tax-cut proposal in Congress
and increasing the minimum wage. In truth, Giuliani has discussed
these issues, though only in a limited way and only in response to
questions. He has yet to give a major policy speech in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Giuliani's campaign spokeswoman, Juleanna Glover
Weiss, condemned Clinton's attack, saying Giuliani has
unhesitatingly offered his views on controversial subjects, like
the fate of Elian Gonzalez, while Clinton has held back. ``Mrs.
Clinton is everywhere and nowhere simultaneously,'' she said,
``while Mayor Giuliani talks about issues every day and has the
record to back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered a new response to complaints that she is running
for office in a state she only recently moved to.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're trying to recruit somebody for the Yankees or the
Mets,'' she said, ``we wouldn't care where they were born.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
