 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Wednesday, April 12, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at
415-777-6055 or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business
stories running in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PASTAPOMO _ &LR;  Two years ago, San Francisco's Pasta Pomodoro was
on the verge of boiling over.
</P>
<P>
   The chain of moderate-priced Italian eateries had grown from a
single, tiny North Beach location to eight neighborhood restaurants
in just three years. It doubled in size, from four to eight
locations, in just 12 months during 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The first four Pasta Pomodoros were so successful, ``We thought,
`This is easy. Let's speed it up,''' recounted Adriano Paganini,
the company's 33-year-old founder. ``It's that invincible syndrome
that's so dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Milan-born Paganini, who has been working in
restaurants since he was 17, presides over a successful, 12-outlet
chain that generated about $15 million in sales last year and is
poised to expand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PENDER _  &LR; Location, location, location may be the three most
important words in the real estate business. But when it comes to
managing Internet funds, location seems not to matter.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 23 open-end, actively managed mutual funds
that invest exclusively in Net stocks, but only two are based in
the Bay Area _ the epicenter of the Internet industry.
</P>
<P>
   That might sound pathetically parochial, until you consider that
many blue-chip companies _ including Wal-Mart, Kmart and NBC _ have
planted their Internet subsidiaries in the Bay Area, and Wall
Street firms are moving or hiring scores of technology analysts out
here. By Kathleen Pender &QL; 
 &UR; VENTURE  &LR; _ In what could be the largest first-round venture
financing of a startup, GTCR Golden Rauner of Chicago announced
yesterday that it has invested $200 million in Brience Inc. of San
Francisco. By Peter Sinton
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POOR _  &LR; A consumer watchdog group plans to file a complaint
with state regulators today claiming two upstart phone companies
have been gouging low-income customers by charging them as much as
$80 per month, when many of them should qualify for a subsidized
``Universal Lifeline Service'' that costs just over $5 per month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3987 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-POOR-POOR_SFCHRON &LR;      04-11 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POOR-POOR </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 2 Upstart Phone Firms Irk Watchdog  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A consumer watchdog group plans to file a complaint with state
regulators today against two upstart phone companies that target
customers who've had their local phone service shut off because
they didn't pay their bills.
<P>
   The Utility Consumers Action Network of San Diego claims Tel
West Communications of Seattle and Smoke Signal Communications of
Houston have been gouging low-income customers by charging them as
much as $80 per month, when many of them should qualify for a
subsidized ``Universal Lifeline Service'' that costs just over $5
per month.
</P>
<P>
   Many customers wind up paying the higher fees, consumer
advocates said, because they feel they have no other option for
telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   UCAN's Charles Carbone claims that neither company offers the
cheaper lifeline service, as required by state rules. The group
plans to complain to the California Public Utilities Commission
today.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the group claims that Tel West, which offers
service in most of California, including the Bay Area, neglected to
file required documents disclosing their prices and other
information.
</P>
<P>
   Tel West President Jeff Swickard said he first learned about
UCAN's accusations Monday, and immediately asked an employee to
make sure the company is complying with all of the state rules and
regulations. ``We want to work with the PUC,'' Swickard said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the company has never been named in a customer
complaint filed with the PUC. And Swickard said he doubted many
customers would qualify for lifeline service. He said customers
typically aren't poor, but have had problems managing their money.
Smoke Signal, also known as Choctaw Communications, could not be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have been aggressively recruiting customers with
financial problems. Smoke Signal, for instance, has been running
television commercials in Southern California featuring actor Erik
Estrada, famous for his role as a state trooper in ``CHiPS.''
</P>
<P>
   The firms will generally offer service to anyone, but ask
customers to prepay their bills in advance. And they charge higher
rates. Smoke Signal charges $50 per month for local calls, plus
another $30 for local toll calls (beyond 12 miles but too short to
be considered long distance). Tel West charges $40 a month for
local calls only.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Pacific Bell's rates start at about $11 per month
and lifeline service costs half that. A family of four must have an
income of $25,090 or less to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   UCAN's Carbone said the group hopes it can put the companies out
of business by pressing the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a submarket created for low-income people,'' Carbone
said. ``They are offering a worse service at a much higher price.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
