<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE, CONGRESS TAKE OPPOSITE APPROACHES TO GUN VIOLENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the first anniversary of the Columbine
massacre approaching, the Democratic White House and the
Republican-controlled Congress are reacting to increasing public
concern over gun violence but in starkly different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Intensifying a Democratic push for new gun-control measures,
President Clinton on Tuesday attended the signing of a Maryland law
requiring trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress should follow Maryland's lead,'' Clinton said in
Annapolis as Gov. Parris Glendening, a Democrat, signed the
legislation that requires external locks on all guns sold in the
state beginning Oct. 1 and mandates built-in locks on new handguns
sold in the state beginning Jan. 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with Republicans claiming Clinton has not enforced gun
laws already on the books, the House passed 358-60 a program to
send $100 million in block grants to states that impose at least a
five-year additional sentence for gun crimes.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Republicans acted
because ``they feel like they're vulnerable on this. They've got to
do something.'' He faulted the measure, contending that only six
states would be eligible for funds because the other 44 states do
not have the sentencing rules required in the House measure.
</P>
<P>
   Despairing of congressional action on anti-gun measures he
favors, Clinton flies Wednesday to Denver to boost the drive to put
on the Colorado ballot in November a measure to require background
checks for purchasers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to speak at a rally in a convention center just miles
from suburban Columbine High School, where last April 20 two
teen-agers shot to death 12 fellow students and a teacher before
killing themselves _ the deadliest school shooting in the nation's
history.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed measure, which needs 62,000 signatures to get on
the ballot, is sponsored by a bipartisan group, SAFE Colorado. The
acronym stands for Sane Alternatives to the Firearms Epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Their proposal would require buyers at gun shows, where some
sellers are unlicensed vendors, to undergo a background check
similar to that faced by a purchaser at a registered gun shop. Some
of the weapons used at Columbine were purchased at a gun show and
then sold to the two students shooters, Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the proposal are considering several legal
challenges to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it's written right now, it wouldn't even pass muster
in traffic court,'' Dudley Brown, executive director of the Rocky
Mountain Gun Owners, said.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative process began after the Republican-controlled
Colorado Legislature refused to enact any gun-control measures,
even though the state's Republican governor, Bill Owens, supported
what he called ``common-sense'' firearms controls, such as an end
to the gun show loophole.
</P>
<P>
   While in the Colorado capital, Clinton also is to participate in
a live, hourlong MSNBC ``town hall on guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., voicing a view
widely held by Republican lawmakers, questioned if the legislation
supported by Clinton and many Democrat would curb murderous
outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of fact, more gun control laws would probably not
have effected what happened in Columbine,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Columbine shootings, the Senate passed a bill to
close the gun-show loophole in federal law, but the House defeated
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said the Senate had adopted more sensible measures in a
juvenile justice measure, such as providing federal funds for metal
detectors in schools _ ``devices that could have made a difference
in Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott called for the Clinton administration to adopt a ``zero
tolerance'' attitude toward crimes committed with guns, a step
taken by several federal and state prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said many Democrats, although
not enthusiastic about the House measure, voted for it because they
``saw a political trap and decided not to fall for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the House bill was ``a cruel political trick on
the American public'' because only six states would be eligible. He
said Republicans have blocked consideration of gun safety measures
as well as Clinton's more generous enforcement proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton's $280 million package would fund 1,000
new prosecutors and 500 more federal Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
agents.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, which has not been considered by the Senate,
uses the same name, Project Exile, as the ``zero tolerance''
program begun by a U.S. prosecutor in Richmond, Va., a city with
one of the nation's highest crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-related crimes have dropped 65 percent and violent crimes 35
percent since the program began. Critics of the House bill said
nearby jurisdictions had seen a similar decline without using the
get-tough program, even though Virginia has since adopted a similar
statewide plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
