<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3993 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PENDER-PENDER_SFCHRON     04-11 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENDER-PENDER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH/KATHLEEN PENDER 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Many Fund Managers View Their Internet Investments From Afar 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Location, location, location may be the three most important words
in the real estate business. But when it comes to managing Internet
funds, location seems not to matter.
<P>
   There are at least 23 open-end, actively managed mutual funds
that invest exclusively in Net stocks, but only two are based in
the Bay Area _ the epicenter of the Internet industry.
</P>
<P>
   That might sound pathetically parochial, until you consider that
many blue-chip companies _ including Wal-Mart, Kmart and NBC _ have
planted their Internet subsidiaries in the Bay Area, and Wall
Street firms are moving or hiring scores of technology analysts out
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a global phenomenon, but the Bay Area is
definitely one of the leading if not the leading locations'' for
Internet activity, says Peter Doyle, manager of the Internet Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Yet New York City is home to more Internet funds _ nine,
including five run by Doyle's company _ than anywhere else. They're
also managed out of unlikely places like Atlanta, Tampa, Houston,
Cincinnati and Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest and biggest, Munder NetNet, is based in Birmingham,
Mich., although it has just hired one person for a new Bay Area
office and plans to add a few more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of fund families reside east of the
Mississippi,'' explains Geoff Bobroff, a mutual fund consultant in
East Greenwich, R.I. ``The natural inclination is to put your
portfolio manager in your home office. This makes sense from the
standpoint of compliance and control.''
</P>
<P>
   But does it make sense from an investment standpoint?
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to say. Of the 23 Net funds listed on page D9,
only four are older than 12 months and six were started this year.
None are doing as well as they were a few weeks ago, and that could
squelch another 10 Internet funds in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Some Net-fund managers say where they work doesn't matter,
because the Internet makes the same information available
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But most Internet companies don't have any earnings. And that
makes quantitative, computer-based analysis less important, and
fundamental research _ especially field trips _ more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think you have to be really close to your companies to
understand their businesses,'' says Mitch Rubin, manager of New
York's -based  &LR; Baron iOpportunity fund. ``I come to the West Coast
at least once a week. But there are also tremendous pockets of
Internet companies in and around Boston, Washington, D.C., and
Silicon Alley in New York. Do you have to be in Silicon Valley to
be a good tech investor? I don't think so. But you have to be out
there regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   If visiting the Bay Area is good, then living here is even
better, according to local Net-fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the home-field advantage,'' says Kevin Landis, manager
of the Firsthand e-Commerce fund, in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Landis hires only investment people who have engineering or
technical experience, and most of them grew up in Silicon Valley.
If they have a question about a company, they don't have to rely on
the word of the CEO. They call their friends, family and former
co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Callinan, manager of the RS Internet Age fund in San
Francisco, says that ``being here gives us an advantage. We can
network with people at the sandlot games. And we can sniff out a
hype faster than East Coast people.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also easier to do ``due diligence on CEOs,'' Callinan says.
``All the personalities out here are recycled.''
</P>
<P>
   Lise Buyer has seen the situation from both sides. She used to
be a buy-side analyst with the T. Rowe Price Science and Technology
fund, in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she's a sell-side analyst for Credit Suisse First Boston in
Palo Alto. ``The information you pick up at the dry cleaner,
Saturday soccer practices and the grocery aisle is arguably as
valuable as what you read on the tape,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, when she was with T. Rowe Price, ``I spent my
life on airplanes. We had almost as much access (as local fund
managers) to company management, but we had a clearer perspective
on the rate at which the rest of the world was adopting new
technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Houlton, manager of the Strong Internet fund in Milwaukee,
is about as far from the madding crowd as you can get. ``In some
ways it's a disadvantage. I'm not in the tight buzz of the
Valley,'' he says. ``But a lot of that can be noise. If one-fourth
is useful, and three-fourths is noise, is that a net positive?''
</P>
<P>
   Some out-of-town fund managers say it's better to be closer to
customers than to companies they invest in. ``Ninety-five percent
of our shareholders are in Ohio, Indiana and Kentucky,'' says Lee
Mazler, who manages the tiny ($2 million in assets) Analysts
Internet.fund cq &LR;  in Cincinnati. Because his customers are a tad
conservative, he keeps the fund well-diversified and focused on
bigger companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Sears, manager of the Investors Capital Internet fund in
Lynnfield, Mass., says he could work anywhere because his
quantitative fund invests only in companies that have earnings.
``We don't do IPOs or dot-coms. And we only invest in companies
whose data is readily available through public forums,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   David Alger, manager of the Enterprise Internet fund in New
York, takes an opposite approach. ``We do fundamental bottom-up
analysis,'' he says. This might be hard to do in the Midwest, ``but
if you're in New York, every company you follow will come through
at least once a year,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he adds, ``it's not important for us to be incredibly
early on new technologies. By the time companies become public,
we're pretty much on top of what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, where a fund is based is much less important than
what happens to Internet stocks overall. If tech stocks continue to
slide, these funds could get creamed, no matter how many CEOs the
manager takes to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   That's why any money you have in Internet funds _ probably the
riskiest, least diversified investment going _ should be money you
can afford to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
