<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PASTAPOMO-PASTAPOMO_S     04-11 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTAPOMO-PASTAPOMO </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 A World of Pasta-bility  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Two years ago, San Francisco's Pasta Pomodoro was on the verge of
boiling over.
<P>
   The chain of moderate-priced Italian eateries had grown from a
single, tiny North Beach location to eight neighborhood restaurants
in just three years. It doubled in size, from four to eight
locations, in just 12 months during 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The first four Pasta Pomodoros were so successful, ``We thought,
`This is easy. Let's speed it up,''' recounted Adriano Paganini,
the company's 33-year-old founder. ``It's that invincible syndrome
that's so dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Milan-born Paganini, who has been working in
restaurants since he was 17, presides over a successful, 12-outlet
chain that generated about $15 million in sales last year and is
poised to expand.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Paganini expects to finalize Pasta Pomodoro's first
round of venture funding. In the next four years, he plans for
Pasta Pomodoro to grow to 60 restaurants, including its first
locations outside the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adriano is a great chef and a very savvy businessman, and
that's a rare combination,'' said Mark Saltzgaber, a principal with
Dorsett Capital, a San Francisco venture firm that will invest
between $3 million and $7 million in Pasta Pomodoro.
</P>
<P>
   Paganini ``doesn't sacrifice anything when it comes to the food,
but he's created a concept that allows him to (keep prices low),''
Saltzgaber said. ``I think Adriano has created an unmatched
price-value equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples from the current menu include spaghetti with mussels,
scallops, calamari and roasted garlic in white wine sauce ($7.75)
and shell pasta with grilled radicchio, Gorgonzola and pine nuts
($6.95).
</P>
<P>
   The restaurants, which are intimate, averaging 2,000 to 2,500
square feet, tend to be located in neighborhoods rather than in
suburban shopping complexes.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts credit Paganini for attaining a combination of
good food quality and low prices that stands out in a sea of
unremarkable chains.
</P>
<P>
   `It's a very, very tight concept,'' said Pete Mattson of Mattson
&AMP; Co., a restaurant consultancy in Foster City. ``All the (venture
capital) guys have been sniffing around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Paganini, the former executive chef at San Francisco's Donatello
restaurant, is the first to admit that today's success comes after
several touch-and-go years.
</P>
<P>
   Paganini opened the first Pasta Pomodoro in 1994 in North Beach
with his then-wife, Deborah Blum. (The couple have has &LR;   &LR; since
divorced.) They also owned the nearby Cafe Adriano; Paganini would
run back and forth between the two kitchens cooking dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not really have a clue what we were doing,'' Paganini
said. ``We just sort of did it.''
</P>
<P>
   They hit their first major bump six months later, in January
1995, when the second Pasta Pomodoro opened on Union Street. Unlike
the first location, the second took a few months to attract a
following, leaving the young restaurateurs financially squeezed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the word `cash flow,' but I learned that concept
very quickly,'' Paganini said. The Union Street location stabilized
after a few months, and his thoughts again turned to expansion.
once again. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Still winging it, Paganini opened six more Pasta Pomodoros and
then found the company teetering. ``On paper, we were generating a
lot of cash, but the bottom line (profit) was getting thinner and
thinner,'' Paganini said. ``The whole operation was shaky.''
</P>
<P>
   Paganini realized that he couldn't run eight restaurants in the
same seat-of-the pants way he had run one, or even four. He began
to slow down the openings, manage his money more carefully and
build a team to help train employees and manage the business. He
closed one underperforming location in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Paganini also gave Pasta Pomodoro a face-lift, renovating its
interiors with a more sophisticated look. Recently, he revamped the
menu, adding slightly pricier dishes such as brasato _ braised beef
and pasta served in a red wine and porcini mushroom sauce ($8.95).
Rotisserie chicken is also being introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Pasta Pomodoro's transformation is nearly complete,
readying the company for its next stage of growth. Paganini expects
to open the first South Bay restaurant this fall in an
as-yet-undetermined location.
</P>
<P>
   A second Marin County Pasta Pomodoro (the first is in San
Rafael) will open this summer in Mill Valley. A San Ramon outlet
will be added to the company's existing East Bay locations in Union
City and in Oakland's Rockridge neighborhood. The other nine Pasta
Pomodoros are in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of next year, Pasta Pomodoro plans to expand
into its first market outside the Bay Area, either Los Angeles,
Denver or Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   As it grows, Pasta Pomodoro faces the challenge of maintaining
its quality. This is the struggle for every restaurant, but it is
particularly difficult during times of rapid growth, industry
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been pretty highly thought of around the Bay Area, but
it's easy to lose it if you're not careful,'' noted Mattson. In
recent years, such well-known chains as Taco Bell and Olive Garden
have undertaken quality initiatives after losing their focus.
</P>
<P>
   Pasta Pomodoro's chances of success are ``pretty good'' if it is
able to maintain its current standards, Mattson said. ``Pasta is
perceived as healthy, it's contemporary and people love Italian
food.''
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage is that pasta is inexpensive _ only 45 to 50
cents a pound wholesale, according to Mattson. Saltzgaber said
Pasta Pomodoro's return on investment of 30 percent is on par with
successful chains like the Cheesecake Factory.
</P>
<P>
   For Pasta Pomodoro, volume is the primary key to keeping prices
low. For example, its 1,200-square-foot Castro location serves up
to 500 people a day _ two to three times the number of most
restaurants of that size, according to Paganini.
</P>
<P>
   Pasta Pomodoro's recipes, most of which Paganini develops
himself, are ``simplified to the maximum'' and tested repeatedly to
ensure they can be re-created quickly, on a large scale , &LR; and with
consistently high quality, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the current menu, Paganini started six months ago with 200
entree ideas and wound up with a total of seven new dishes. ``If
you're really organized, it's quicker to make a pasta than to make
a sandwich,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paganini, who has worked as a chef in England, France and Italy
as well as San Francisco, also uses tricks to make his dishes seem
seems  &LR; fresher, such as adding diced fresh tomatoes to the
signature pomodoro sauce and sprinkling dishes with fresh, chopped
basil.
</P>
<P>
   To get diners their dinners as quickly as possible, Paganini has
organized his kitchens into super-efficient stations. Near the
stove top are refrigerated drawers holding ingredients like chopped
eggplant, scallops and partially cooked pasta.
</P>
<P>
   When an order comes in, a line chef pops the pasta into a
special pasta cooker that is made in Italy. Then the chef _ usually
there are two per restaurant, each manning four to six burners _
reaches into pulls from  &LR; the drawers and nearby containers to
assemble the sauce ingredients, which are heated in a pan and
tossed with the pasta before serving.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is hardly lacking in restaurants, but the good
news for Pasta Pomodoro is that Americans are spending more on
eating out. In 1999, restaurant sales rose 5 percent, to $252.6
billion, and another 5 percent increase is expected this year,
according to the National Restaurant Association.
</P>
<P>
   Paganini notes that despite fierce competition in San Francisco,
nine Pasta Pomodoros are thriving in the city.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carol Emert at cemert(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
