<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGING FRAUD, PERU CHALLENGER DEMANDS RUNOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) 
By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ President Alberto K. Fujimori's principal opponent,
Alejandro Toledo, said on Tuesday that he would not accept anything
short of a runoff after a first round that election monitors have
challenged.
</P>
<P>
   And Toledo insisted he would take part in a second round only if
the electoral agencies were revamped. The first round, which
Fujimori is on the brink of winning, provoked charges of fraud from
election monitors and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Joe Lockhart, a White House spokesman, said on
Tuesday that the United States would raise ``serious questions'' if
Peru did not hold a second round of voting. ``We expect there will
be a runoff, and I think serious questions will be raised if the
vote count indicated something otherwise,'' Lockhart said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 90.8 percent of the official vote count complete, the
central election authority reported on Tuesday evening that
Fujimori had won 49.8 per to Toledo's 40.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate needs 50 percent plus one vote to avert a runoff.
The latest count actually showed a slight decrease in Fujimori's
percentage from tallies earlier in the day, but it could climb
again as ballots come in from remote jungle and Andean villages
where the president is strongly supported by Indian voters.
International election observers also say that election controls
were least stringent in such areas.
</P>
<P>
   The government said final results would be made public on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, who is running for a third five-year term, has denied
that anything but minimal irregularities took place, and said he
would resist suggestions by the Clinton administration, several
European governments and Peru's congressionally appointed ombudsman
that a second round vote be held.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to accept the will of the Peruvian people,''
Fujimori told reporters on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of American States and several Peruvian and
international election monitoring and polling groups reported that
quick counts of sample vote tally sheets on Sunday night indicated
that Fujimori fell at least two percentage points short of a
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Several polls of people leaving the voting sites actually had
Toledo, a business school professor, ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Organization of American States observation team
has criticized long and unexplained delays in the delivery of
ballots and tally sheets to computer centers, and he said monitors
could not determine where the counts were taking place.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reports that on some ballots the names of rivals
to Fujimori were waxed over so that only his name could be marked,
that in some cases ballots had been printed without Toledo's
photograph, and that some ballots were pre-marked.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, election authorities completed their count by midnight
of election day and released total unofficial results the next day.
In that election Fujimori vanquished several opponents with almost
two-thirds of the official count.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Peruvian election officials said they would deliver a
reliable total vote count, if not the absolutely official count,
within 24 hours of the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   A senior State Department official said he did not think the
slight decrease in Fujimori's vote percentage necessarily meant
that the government was shifting toward favoring a second-round
vote after all. ``We're doing a lot of work but I don't know if it
is doing any good or not,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Toledo, 54, said he would lead peaceful
demonstrations across Peru. But he also reached out to the
military, appealing to it not to take part in election fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that ``we need a change of chef and waiters'' among
election authorities, he also demanded that he be allowed the equal
access to television networks that he had been denied in the
first-round campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing his words carefully, Toledo appealed to the people to
remain calm, adding, ``I am not going to be responsible for putting
fuel on the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's calls for protests came as tens of thousands of
demonstrators gathered in Lima, Iquitos, Arequipa and several other
cities, blocking traffic, honking car horns and picketing
government facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The police stepped up patrols of the cities with armored trucks
mounted with water canon. Army and police units around the
presidential palace were reinforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to invoke the pride of the Peruvian armed forces so
that they resist the pressures they are now under to block the will
of the people,'' Toledo told a throng of thousands of people who
gathered in downtown Lima on Tuesday afternoon,
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside five other opposition presidential candidates,
he added, ``I call on all Peru to mobilize peacefully so they will
hear our voices.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Toledo replaced the faded jeans and red bandanna he has worn the
last few days with a dark suit and tie.
</P>
<P>
   He provocatively suggested that there was a growing level of
discontent over the election process in the armed forces, which
remain a political force in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know I can't reveal,'' he said. Then directing his
remarks to the armed forces, he said: ``I am asking that they not
be pressured to continue breaking the rules. I ask that they not
participate more in the polarization among Peruvians.''
</P>
<P>
   A restructuring of the military command late last year put
allies of Fujimori's intelligence chief, Vladimiro Montesinos, in
all the top assignments in the Defense Ministry and in regional
headquarters. But many junior officers, spurred on by retired
senior officers, are said to be upset with the way the election was
handled and the way promotions in the military now depend on
political connections to Fujimori and his inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   Leading a chorus of criticism by former officers has been Peru's
last military dictator, Francisco Morales Bermudez, who ruled in
the late 1970s. In an interview with the newspaper El Comercio,
published on Tuesday, he was quoted as saying: ``This is the most
fraudulent and aberrant election process in our national history.
Toledo was really the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the campaign, Toledo appealed for support among the army
and police, promising to raise salaries and give soldiers the right
to vote. Aides to Toledo said he was in contact with influential
officers in the army, but they did not disclose the content of the
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has never held high government office. His political
party, Peru Posible, is little more than a civic group and does not
have a strong organization. But in his surprising surge in the
final weeks of the campaign, he connected strongly with
working-class urban voters, millions of whom are of mixed Indian
and Latino ancestry like him. He attracted large crowds in the
campaign, even though he did not have the money to offer supporters
food or transportation as is customary in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a bricklayer and fishmonger, he shined shoes as a boy
and won scholarships that enabled him to earn two master's degrees
and a doctorate in the United States. He has promised to be ``the
president of the poor'' even while offering a centrist platform.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo has been criticized for leading tens of thousands of
people on the presidential palace Sunday night before more than a
few official results were even counted. Protesters set bonfires and
some businesses were vandalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
