<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SAUDI-DIVERSIFY-1STLD     04-11 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-DIVERSIFY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDI ARABIA TO EASE RESTRICTIONS ON FOREIGN INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Subs throughout for additional details and some editing
changes) 
By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Eager to demonstrate a new economic openness that
could help its bid to join the World Trade Organization and expand
private business, Saudi Arabia announced a new law Tuesday that
would permit foreigners to own their investments and property in
the country without a Saudi partner.
</P>
<P>
   The law, approved Monday, also promises to strengthen judicial
protection for investments, foster greater public disclosure in
financial dealings and lower corporate taxes on foreign companies
with profits that exceed 100,000 rials a year, or about $26,000,
the official Saudi Press Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The easing of restrictions on foreign investors has been under
discussion for some time, but it increased in the last six months
after King Fahd told the country that it could not ignore the trend
toward globalization and free markets. The new investment code is
being supported by Crown Prince Abdullah, who has taken on a wide
role in the nation's affairs from his ailing brother, Fahd.
</P>
<P>
   Hashem Yamani, the industry and electricity minister, said in a
statement carried by the Saudi Press Agency that ``this law aims to
improve the investment environment in the kingdom, remove existing
obstacles, improve efficiency and ensure flexibility,''
</P>
<P>
   Yamani's ministry now licenses most direct foreign investment,
but investors in some projects have sometimes had to apply to
several ministries.
</P>
<P>
   The new law would set up a single agency to consider investment
projects and reduce bureaucratic delays. The agency would be
required to act within 30 days on proposals from foreigners, who
would now have the right to appeal its decisions.
</P>
<P>
   For more than four years, Saudi Arabia, a famously insular
country, has been negotiating for entry into the WTO, the
Geneva-based group that makes the rules for global commerce.
Membership in the organization improves a nation's ability to
export goods and services. The Saudi Arabian application for
membership has been hindered by the laws, regulations and
traditions that favor Saudis, impose high tariffs and subsidize
exports like petrochemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, foreign investors in the country needed a Saudi
national in order to do business _ first as a sponsor in order to
obtain a work visa and then as a majority partner in any project.
Foreigners were allowed to hold a maximum stake in any business of
49 percent and could not own property, or engage in distribution or
internal commerce.
</P>
<P>
   A common method for members of the country's extended royal
family to gain extra income has been to act as a paid sponsor for
foreigners, who must relinquish their passports to the sponsor
while in the country,
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, most gulf nations have searched for ways
to diversify their economies and wean themselves away from
near-total dependence on oil revenue, a quest that took on new
urgency when world oil prices fell sharply a few years ago. The
Saudis, too, tried to branch out.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at enormous cost, Saudi Arabia became a major wheat
exporter by investing in agriculture as part of a plan to become
self-sufficient in food. But up to 85 percent of its export
earnings and about 40 percent of its gross domestic product still
come from oil.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment is now centered on oil-related industries
like petrochemicals, and the Saudis are expected to maintain a
government monopoly on exploration and development. But
representatives of 10 oil companies have been invited to Riyadh,
the capital, later this month to discuss proposals for investing in
other areas of the oil industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
