<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, APRIL 12
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MICROSOFT-LOBBY-NYT (moved on Monday, April 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, April 10,
about a lobbying campaign by Microsoft misstated the company's
explanation at one point for hiring Century Strategies, Ralph
Reed's firm. As the article noted, a Microsoft spokesman said
Century Stategy's specific aim was to counter a lobbying campaign
against the company being waged by its competitors. The spokesman
did not say that its aim was to curry favor with Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TEXAS-BUSH-HEALTH-NYT (moved on Monday, April 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, April 10,
about health care in Texas misstated the extent of Gov. George W.
Bush's public discussions on the subject. According to his
presidential campaign office, Governor Bush has given at least two
speeches on the subject _ on Sept. 15, 1995, to the Texas Medical
Association and on June 2, 1998, to the Texas Health Care
Association. His gubernatorial press office had said, and the
article reported, that he had never made a speech on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-NYT (moved on Monday, April 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, April 10,
about a nuclear plant supervisor who was declared unfit for duty
after he complained about safety misattributed a statement about
the case. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission official who said his
agency would not follow up on a finding by the Labor Department
that the worker was fired improperly, because the agency had to
husband its resources, was Thomas P. Gwynn, the deputy regional
administrator for the commission's western region. It was not Gary
F. Sanborn, the region's enforcement officer.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PULITZER-PRIZES-HIGHLIGHTS-NYT (moved in Monday, April 10.)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, April 10,
about the composer Lewis Spratlan, winner of the Pulitzer Prize for
music for his ``Life Is a Dream, Opera in Three Acts: Act II,
Concert Version,'' misstated the site of the work's world premiere
on Jan. 28. It was first played at Amherst College in Amherst,
Mass., not in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
