<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Friday, April 14) 
 
By MICHAEL LONSFORD  
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On this date in 1918, Lt. Douglas Campbell became the first U.S.
flying ace when he shot down his fifth German airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Also on this date in 1939, what famous John Steinbeck novel was
published to great acclaim? &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Well, this week's featured wine will shoot down preconceived
notions that fine wines have to be expensive. The 1999 St. Supery
Sauvignon Blanc _ 4 stars _ is a crisp, clean, slightly herbaceous
white wine that has the requisite flavor and acidity to pair with
anything from shellfish to Indian curry.
</P>
<P>
   The $12.59 price tag is so reasonable you won't feel the wrath
of grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: ``The Grapes of Wrath.'' It won the Pulitzer Prize the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
