<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SPRINGTRAIN-TAX12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida spring training bill advances
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Tax breaks designed to keep Major League
Baseball teams from moving their spring training homes out of
Florida got another boost Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The House Finance and Taxation Committee unanimously approved a
$2.5 million annual sales tax rebate. The bill, which has already
been endorsed by two other legislative committees, has one
committee stop in each chamber before a full vote.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is designed to help up to five spring training cities,
including Vero Beach, retain teams that have been courted by
Arizona and Las Vegas. It is expected to cost $75 million over 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gov. Jeb Bush vetoed a bill that would have given the
Vero Beach Dodgers $7.5 million over two years. And this month,
Bush said he would not support a tax on cruise passengers designed
to pay for a $400 million stadium for the Florida Marlins regular
season home games.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Charles Sembler (R-Sebastian) said he worked with the
governor's office in crafting the spring training bill this year
and expects his support.
</P>
<P>
   The bill sets up eligibility and relies on the Office of
Tourism, Trade and Economic Development to hand out the money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
