u f BC-COKE-GARY12-COX     04-11 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-GARY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida lawyer's record impressive
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you're going up against a corporate Goliath like
Coca-Cola Co., some observers say Willie Gary might be a guy you'd
want at your side.
</P>
<P>
   The flamboyant Florida lawyer rose from migrant farm worker's
son to multimillionaire by winning civil verdicts of up to $500
million against large companies on the behalf of accident victims,
patients and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gary, 52, is described as a crack litigator who uses the lilting
delivery and simple, parablelike phrases of a country preacher to
make his points. He's expected to rely on those techniques in
representing several of the plaintiffs in the racial discrimination
case against Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   He won his first personal injury case in 1975, a year after he
started his firm in Stuart, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Since that $250,000 verdict, he's built a firm with about two
dozen lawyers and a hefty list of victories and multimillion-dollar
settlements. They include a 1985 confidential settlement reportedly
in the $50 million range from Florida Power &AMP; Light for the
accidental electrocution deaths of seven members of a Florida
family.
</P>
<P>
   Gary's biggest win so far is a $500 million verdict in 1995
against funeral home operator Loewen Group. With the verdict in
hand, he negotiated a $175 million settlement on behalf of his
client, a Mississippi funeral home operator who claimed the
Canadian company tried to drive him out of business.
</P>
<P>
   While known for representing plaintiffs in personal injury,
malpractice and breach-of-contract cases, he has had a few
corporate clients. Forbes magazine reported last year that he
represented Flo-Sun Inc. in a class-action wage dispute involving
20,000 migrant farm workers from the West Indies.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary has also been the subject of investigations over
alleged rules violations since 1993, according to the Florida Bar
Association. The group said he was admonished by its grievance
committee in 1993 and by the Florida Supreme Court in 1994 for
rules violations. Two other inquiries by the bar association into
alleged rules violations were closed last year without action, the
bar association said.
</P>
<P>
   Various profiles paint the picture of a indomitable, 5-foot-8
fighter who has given a share of his wealth to those who helped him
or with whom he shared a bond.
</P>
<P>
   Born the sixth of 11 children a few years after World War II,
Gary said he spent much of his school-age days cutting sugar cane
under the Central Florida sun. In 1967, he talked his way into a
football scholarship at Shaw University, a traditionally black
school in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   He then went on to law school, despite suffering from dyslexia,
a disorder that makes reading difficult. He still relies on
associates to do most of his legal research and exhaustively
rehearses and prepares before trials using notes printed with large
type.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Gary has amassed enough trappings of wealth _
including a $10 million mansion, luxury cars and extensive real
estate holdings _ to be featured on Robin Leach's ``Lifestyles of
the Rich and Famous.'' He flies around in a Gulfstream jet
emblazoned with his signature and sporting the name ``Wings of
Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Gary donated $10 million to Shaw University.
He has made other contributions to help support disadvantaged
children and migrant workers, including co-founding an educational
foundation in 1998 with the Rev. Jesse Jackson and boxer Evander
Holyfield. Gary is a legal adviser to Jackson and has helped raise
funds for the civil rights activist's RainbowPush Coalition.
Jackson recently has taken a higher profile in the case against
Coca-Cola, calling on the company to settle the suit quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Gary spokeswoman Lori Metoyer Brown said the attorney also is
part owner
</P>
<P>
   of Atlanta-based Major Broadcasting Corp. Other part owners in
the cable TV network include Holyfield, former major-league
baseball player Cecil Fielder and Marlon Jackson, brother of singer
Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a network that promotes family values,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
