<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-PROFILES12-COX     04-11 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-PROFILES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Profiles of plaintiffs opposing Coke
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The movement of three of the eight plaintiffs to new
legal representation in the racial discrimination case against
Coca-Cola creates two legal teams now battling the Atlanta-based
soft drink company.
</P>
<P>
   One group will now be represented by Florida attorney Willie
Gary of the law firm Gary, Williams, Parenti, Finney, Lewis,
McManus, Watson &AMP; Sperando. Those plaintiffs include Motisola
Malikha Abdallah and Gregory Allen Clark, two of the original four
plaintiffs in the case, and Ajibola Laosebikan, one of four
plaintiffs added in December.
</P>
<P>
   The other group of plaintiffs will continue to be represented by
attorney Cyrus Mehri and his law firm Mehri, Malkin &AMP; Ross of
Washington; the Atlanta law firm of Bondurant, Mixson &AMP; Elmore; the
Marietta firm of DeVille, Milhollin &AMP; Voyles; and the newly added
Birmingham, Ala., firm of Gordon, Silberman, Wiggins &AMP; Childs. The
plaintiffs in this group include Linda Ingram and Kimberly Gray
Orton, two of the original plaintiffs, and Elvenyia Barton-Gibson
and George Eddings Jr., the two others who were added to the case
in December.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Tuesday, there was a dispute about which legal team
represented plaintiff Wanda Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a look at each of the plaintiffs and their allegations
against the company:
</P>
<P>
   MOTISOLA MALIKHA ABDALLAH
</P>
<P>
   Abdallah worked for Coca-Cola for more than three years as an
administrative assistant. She worked in strategic channel
marketing, a division that had only one other African-American
employee, the suit says. The suit says Abdallah had asked to be
promoted to a higher-paying grade level over a two-year period. In
1998, when she applied for her administrative assistant position,
she again asked if it could be upgraded to a higher grade. Her
request was refused, the suit says. Abdallah said her predecessor,
however, was given a higher pay grade. The suit also says managers
made Abdallah feel like their ``black maid.''
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY ALLEN CLARK
</P>
<P>
   Clark has been a security officer at Coca-Cola since 1996. The
suit says that despite his extensive education and experience, he
has been ``consistently denied promotional opportunities given to
his Caucasian counterparts.'' The suit says Clark has been turned
down for promotions in security despite past experience as a
security and correctional officer. During 1997, the suit says,
Clark applied for ``multiple jobs outside of security at Coca-Cola
and did not get interviews for any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   AJIBOLA LAOSEBIKAN
</P>
<P>
   A former information systems specialist, Laosebikan alleges that
he effectively went eight years without a promotion, while white
employees with less experience, education or seniority advanced
more rapidly than he did. He also alleges he was wrongfully
terminated in retaliation for making complaints about race
discrimination and after attending a hearing in the current case.
</P>
<P>
   WANDA WILLIAMS
</P>
<P>
   Williams is an assistant scientist who has been working at
Coca-Cola for about 15 years. She alleges that she has been denied
promotions because of her race. She also says she has been treated
differently from her white counterparts in performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   LINDA INGRAM
</P>
<P>
   Ingram began working at Coca-Cola in 1990 as a customer service
representative in Dunwoody. The suit said she was ``quickly
promoted'' to technical dispatch adviser and by 1993 was project
coordinator in the national accounts department, where she
performed data analysis. In 1995, she was promoted to senior
information analyst. But as a senior information analyst, the suit
says, Ingram has ``never been paid what her position merits'' and
is underpaid when compared with her white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   KIMBERLY GRAY ORTON
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the company in October 1998, Orton was a 13-year
veteran of Coca-Cola. She began in 1985 in a field sales position
and by 1992 was a manager of promotional packaging graphics for
Coca-Cola USA, supervising about 15 workers. In 1994, she moved to
Coca-Cola's corporate headquarters as a company director. The suit
says Orton was ``grossly underpaid'' for her work at the company,
earning ``tens of thousands'' less than her white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ELVENYIA BARTON-GIBSON
</P>
<P>
   Barton-Gibson, who has worked at Minute Maid since 1996, is
currently employed as an executive assistant to the chief marketing
officer. She alleges that she has been denied the chance to compete
for promotions. Barton-Gibson also alleges that eight other
African-American marketing professionals were terminated or left in
frustration over their inability to advance.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE EDDINGS JR.
</P>
<P>
   Eddings is a former Minute Maid employee who left the company in
1997 after he said he was denied a long-promised promotion. He had
worked for the company for five years, most recently as a category
development manager.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
