<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA SHARES PLUNGE ON CONCERN THAT GROWTH MAY BE SLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Shares of Motorola Inc. plummeted 17 percent Tuesday
over concerns that the company's growth could be slowed by
weaker-than-expected profits in its cellular telephone division.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of feasting on stellar sales and earnings
growth and an explosive runup in the company's stock price,
investors ran for the exits in droves Tuesday on news that
Motorola's second-quarter and full-year earnings would come in
below analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff, which reduced the company's market value by $20
billion, came a day after Motorola said that first quarter sales
had jumped 19 percent and that its profit had more than doubled
from a year earlier, just exceeding analysts' projections.
</P>
<P>
   But the company also said that profitability was down in its
cellphone division largely because of a component shortage and
because its lower-cost handsets _ which yield lower profit margins
_ were selling better than its more expensive models, particularly
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, several Wall Street analysts downgraded the stock
Tuesday, and the stock fell $26, to $124 a share, in heavy trading.
Less than a month ago, shares of Motorola hit a record $184 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said they were worried that tighter margins in the
cellphone unit and stiff competition in lower to middle tier
cellular handset market could upset the company's noteworthy
turnaround in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's not obvious the margins will get meaningfully
better,'' said Todd Koffman, an analyst at Raymond James. ``It
seems the sweet spot of the market is the mass consumer market, and
that's not Motorola's bread and butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials, however, said they were baffled by the sharp
selloff, which came after an upbeat conference call in which top
executives said they were expecting profit of about 67 cents a
share in the second quarter and about $3.14 this year, up from an
earlier company estimate of $3.12 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are surprised by the negative reaction to what we thought
was positive news,'' said Albert R. Brashear, a spokesman at
Motorola headquarters in Schaumburg, Ill., near Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street analysts had already been projecting earnings of
70 cents a share for the second quarter and about $3.18 a share for
this year. After the conference call Tuesday, several analysts cut
their estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But some Wall Street experts said investors over-reacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly didn't justify the hit it took this morning,''
said Charles Hill, director of research at First Call/Thomson
Financial, which tracks analysts' estimates. ``It's the kind of
fickle market we're in. The littlest thing is a big hit to your
stock.''
</P>
<P>
   According to First Call, second-quarter Wall Street estimates
were revised downward Tuesday, but several analysts actually raised
their year-end projection to $3.20 a share on the strength of
Motorola's other businesses, including its semiconductor products
division.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the company said revenue was up nearly 20 percent to
$8.8 billion in the first quarter, but operating profit in the
cellular telephone unit fell to $49 million from $83 million a year
ago, partly because the company was paying a premium for some
components.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
