<SLUG> BC-NBC-DOBBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC MAKES RADIO DEAL WITH EX-CNN PRODUCER 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ NBC announced another deal with Lou Dobbs, the former
CNN financial executive and anchor on Tuesday, expanding their
relationship into radio in a collaboration with a syndicator of
programming, United Stations Radio Networks.
</P>
<P>
   The move is the latest in a partnership between Dobbs and NBC
that is widely expected to eventually bring him to NBC's
all-business news cable channel, CNBC. CNBC is the leading
competitor to CNNFN, the financial news network operated by CNN
that Dobbs once headed.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs left CNN last year after a dispute with the channel's news
management. Under the terms of his exit, he was forbidden to appear
on any other television outlet for the next three years. NBC has
pushed the boundaries of that agreement by using Dobbs as a regular
guest on its ``Today'' program.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC has also signaled its intention to be in business with
Dobbs whenever he is free to re-appear on television. The network
entered into a partnership with Dobbs last October for both a radio
program and a financial newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   And an NBC executive acknowledged that Tuesday's move was one
more way for NBC to establish its relationship with Dobbs. ``The
play here is, we're beginning to find holes in the mountain pass,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   CNN executives declined to comment on the latest announcement
about Dobbs and NBC, citing a previous statement which said that
CNN expected Dobbs to live up to his contractual agreement. So far,
one CNN executive said, nothing NBC has done with Dobbs seems to
have violated that agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs said on Tuesday that he expected both the radio show and
the newsletter to start up in July. He will appear three times a
day on a one-to two-minute feature called ``The Lou Dobbs/NBC
Financial Report.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be syndicated by the United Stations Radio Networks,
mainly to news, information and talk stations, said Nicholas J.
Verbitsky, the president of United Stations. The company said it
supplies programming to more than 2,600 stations.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he left CNN last year, Dobbs said his chief plan was
to start up a Web site called Space.com. That Web site is now in
operation, and Dobbs said it just raised $50 million in a second
round of capital financing.
</P>
</TEXT>
