<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plaintiffs split in case against Coke
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a stunning development just as settlement talks
enter a critical stage, three of the eight plaintiffs in the racial
discrimination case against Coca-Cola have hired a new lawyer after
being dropped by the attorneys seeking class-action status.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much this will affect the settlement
negotiations now underway between the soft drink company and the
existing attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good sign _ plaintiff schism in the middle of the
settlement talks,'' said Lee Parks, a legal expert whose Atlanta
firm specializes in employment law. Parks also said it is unusual
for such a split to develop ``this late in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the plaintiffs' attorneys already involved in the
settlement talks, Cyrus Mehri, said his legal team withdrew its
representation of the three plaintiffs because they were no longer
acting in the best interest of all members of a prospective class
of employees.
</P>
<P>
   As ``class representatives'' the plaintiffs are supposed to
focus on what is best for the 2,000 current and former black
employees they are seeking to represent. The schism may have been
caused by a disagreement over how a possible monetary settlement
would be divided between the suit's named plaintiffs and the
prospective class members.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the right to pursue their individual claims,'' Mehri
said of the plaintiffs he no longer represents. ``The rest of us
have a unity of purpose to fight as hard as possible to achieve the
best possible settlement for the class.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola security guard Gregory Allen Clark, one of the
plaintiffs who left Mehri to retain prominent Florida attorney
Willie Gary, said the shift was made because ``we felt the need to
have at least one African-American lawyer on the team that's
representing approximately 2,000 African-American workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehri's team, however, recently brought on African-American
attorneys with the Birmingham, Ala., civil rights law firm Gordon,
Silberman, Wiggins &AMP; Childs.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Gary said the plaintiffs have ``suffered grave
injustices'' and that ``Coca-Cola is going to have to answer to the
people of this community.'' He is a trial lawyer who has won civil
verdicts of up to $500 million against large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's statement appears to indicate that Gary will be seeking
to represent the prospective class of employees. But that may be
hard for him to do, according to legal experts. That is because
Mehri's team is the one the federal judge in the case recognizes as
being the representative of the prospective class in settlement
talks. Gary has not been approved by the federal judge in the case,
and he may not be able to get court approval at this late date.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 52-year-old Florida attorney can represent individual
employees who are not attempting to represent the class. And if a
settlement is reached, legal experts said, Gary could be a magnet
for other employees who would rather go it alone in fighting the
company than agree to accept whatever terms are negotiated in the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, if too many employees opt out of a settlement, the
benefits of an agreement could be considerably diminished, legal
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary's representative, Lori Metoyer Brown, said Gary now
represents Clark, information systems specialist Ajibola Laosebikan
and former administrative assistant Motisola Malikha Abdallah.
Brown also said that Gary is representing assistant scientist Wanda
Williams. But Mehri said he has not been informed that Williams no
longer wants to be represented by his team.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that Coca-Cola has discriminated against
African-Americans in pay, promotions and performance evaluations.
The company has denied the suit's allegations and opposed
plaintiffs' efforts to make it a class-action case.
</P>
<P>
   But, legal experts said, if a settlement is reached, it is
likely to include members of the class. The plaintiffs already have
submitted a detailed settlement proposal to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer David McNaughton
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
