<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-1STLD-WRITET     04-11 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL TO TRADE KEYSHAWN TO TAMPA BAY ON HOLD UNTIL WEDNESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs with talks ending Tuesday without a deal;
Pickup 4th graf, According to ...; adds some optional material with
background on contract dispute.)  
By JUDY BATTISTA and MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiations between the Tampa Bay Buccaneers and the agent for
Keyshawn Johnson ended late Tuesday night without a final agreement
that would have led to a trade sending the All-Pro wide receiver to
Tampa Bay for the Buccaneers' two first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets, in the latest upheaval of their tumultuous
off-season, remained on the brink of completing a trade, with talks
between Jerome Stanley, the agent for Johnson, and Buccaneers
officials scheduled to resume Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   According to a National Football League official, the parameters
of the deal are intact. Johnson would receive a new long-term
contract that would pay him almost $7 million a year, and would
include a signing bonus of between $12 million and $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   The differences that remain are largely in the language of the
complicated deal, and the official said that no one left the
bargaining table angry. But the official said the deal could
collapse at any time.
</P>
<P>
   According to the league official, several teams tried to get in
on the deal within the last 48 hours, telling the Jets to hold off
on finalizing the trade until they could make offers. The Jets
declined, and the Bucs have a self-imposed deadline of Wednesday to
complete the deal with Johnson or end negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   If the trade _ which only one month ago seemed unfathomable _ is
made, the Jets would have four picks in the first round of the
draft, including their own (16th and 18th) and the Bucs' 13th and
27th. That would put them in position to either make a blockbuster
trade to move up to nab one of the draft's premier players, or to
stockpile young talent by using all four picks.
</P>
<P>
   But it means the Jets, handicapped by salary cap woes and
determined to avoid what seemed an increasingly likely holdout by
Johnson, would also be bereft of their best player and one of the
critical members of a team that was thought to be in position to
make a run at the Super Bowl next season.
</P>
<P>
   And if they dump their most visible star, the Jets will have
crafted a deal that will surely bewilder some Jets players and many
fans. Johnson has been a controversial figure from the start of his
career _ he held out for 24 days before his rookie season and wrote
a book critical of some of his teammates. But he is also a top
playmaker. Last season was his best as a pro, with 89 receptions
for 1,170 yards and eight touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The team's next most productive receiver was Wayne Chrebet, one
of the subjects of Johnson's rookie season ire, who had 48
receptions for 631 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's draft is generally regarded as having four premier
players: defensive lineman Courtney Brown, linebacker LaVar
Arrington, receiver Peter Warrick and offensive lineman Chris
Samuels. With four first-round picks the Jets could offer a package
to any of the teams holding the top four picks. But the Cleveland
Browns, who hold the No.1 pick, would likely demand at least three
of those picks to make a trade, the team's director of football
operations Dwight Clark has said. And the Redskins seem intent on
trying to grab Arrington and Samuels with their picks, No. 2 and
No. 3. The Bengals, with the No. 4 selection, have said they would
listen to offers to move down. The Baltimore Ravens at No. 5, have
entertained offers for their fifth overall pick. But Ravens Coach
Brian Billick wondered yesterday whether the Jets could offer
enough to pry the fifth pick from his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they'd have enough juice,'' Billick said. ``If
they were trying to go to the fifth, they'd give us the 13th and
they'd probably to have throw in one of those later ones and then a
fourth-round pick.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week, Jets Coach Al Groh indicated that the Jets might
be wary of pursuing a high draft pick because signing him might put
as much of a cramp on the salary cap in future years as
restructuring Johnson's deal would have. Instead, the Jets might
choose to use all four picks to fill numerous needs in an attempt
to continue what Groh called the ``success cycle'' without forcing
the team into future dire financial straits. In addition to trying
to acquire a receiver to replace Johnson in the receiver-deep
draft, the Jets need a tight end, a pass-rusher and help in the
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson situation began just four weeks ago, when the Jets
began quietly talking to a handful of teams about trading him.
Johnson, the No. 1 overall pick in the 1996 draft, had made it
clear to the Jets that he was unhappy with his current contract,
which had two years remaining and which would have paid him about
$2 million, well below the current market value. The Jets told
Johnson that, with just a few million dollars remaining under the
$62.17 million salary cap, they were in no position to renegotiate
his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has not attended the Jets' off-season conditioning
program and has made it clear that he would likely hold out during
training camp and perhaps for the start of the season.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the Jets issued a surprising announcement: that
Johnson was off the trading block for the time being, but that they
would not renegotiate his contract. At the owners' meetings two
weeks ago, the Jets' owner, Robert Wood Johnson IV, made it clear
that he expected Johnson to abide by the deal he signed four years
ago and Groh infuriated Johnson by comparing his demands to a child
seeking an increased allowance.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, in a conference call with reporters, came close to
demanding a trade then, saying he was close to not wanting to play
for the Jets. And last week, in a predraft news conference, Groh
put Johnson back on the trading block, saying the Jets would listen
to offers this week. Late last week, the Jets gave the Bucs
permission to negotiate directly with Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Bucs General Manager Rich McKay flew to Los Angeles and spent
Friday and Saturday negotiating with Stanley. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
