<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0412-1STLD     04-11 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0412-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: writes thru to reflect Miami family trip to Washington;
other developments
 &HT;    ELIAN'S MIAMI FAMILY TO TRAVEL TO WASHINGTON FOR MEET WITH
FATHER
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Miami relatives of 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian
Gonzalez may travel to Washington D.C. Wednesday in hopes of
meeting with the boy's father, Cuban exile leaders said late
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The last-ditch effort to keep the boy in the United States comes
as federal immigration officials are expected to send a letter to
the family _ also on Wednesday _ outlining the timetable for when
and where Elian will be handed over to be returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Several media outlets reported late Tuesday that a draft of the
letter being prepared by U.S. Justice Department officials calls
for Elian to be brought to the U.S. Coast Guard Station at
Opa-Locka Airport a few miles north of downtown Miami on Thursday
at 10 a.m. (EST).
</P>
<P>
   Also late Tuesday, a Wednesday trip by U.S. Attorney General
Janet Reno to Miami to meet with Elian's Miami relatives and local
officials was apparently called off, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
   The late developments come as the Miami relatives who want to
keep the boy in this country are clearly running out of options.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, offered to
meet with Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, at a South Florida
location. In a letter released to the media, Lazaro Gonzalez said
that a meeting between the family's adults could quickly be
followed by a meeting that would reunite Elian with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez has repeatedly said he would only take
custody of his son if there were no conditions attached by the
Miami relatives. He has also been reluctant to travel to South
Florida, saying that if he did, it would only be to pick up his
son.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Jorge Mas Santos, of the Cuban American National
Foundation, announced at a Washington press conference that the
Miami relatives and Elian would meet alone with the boy's father on
Wednesday at a neutral location in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``After four and a half months, the private meeting that this
family has yearned for tomorrow will be a reality, `` Mas Santos
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the family members, the only people present at the
meeting will be Deputy U.S. Attorney General Eric Holder and Sen.
Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the family summit could resolve the months of bad
blood and anger that have built over the case remained to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter feelings between the branches of the family probably
weren't helped Tuesday when lawyers for the Miami relatives filed a
brief in a Florida family court alleging Juan Miguel has abused his
son. The brief asked for a hearing on the matter, but Judge
Jennifer Bailey said she was unlikely to grant such a hearing
because she feels federal law supersedes any state jurisdiction in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Reno met in her Washington office with Miami-Dade
County Mayor Alex Penelas and Miami Mayor Joe Carollo, who asked
her to delay the boy's transfer and help set up a Gonzalez family
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that really should be decided between family
members,'' Penelas said, adding that he felt Miami's Cuban exiles
would respect whatever the family decides. Penelas has done a
dramatic about-face since he blasted federal officials two weeks
ago, warning that they were provoking Miami's exiles with their
insistence on returning Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Reno called the meeting ``productive,'' but again
stressed ``that the transfer of Elian to the care of his father
must move forward without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear whether Juan Miguel Gonzalez would remain in
the United States if his son is returned to him. He has stated that
he would be willing to remain here until an Atlanta federal appeals
court rules on the Miami relatives' lawsuit, but he has also said
he would prefer to return to Cuba immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta is scheduled to
hear arguments in the case May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's case also drew another flurry of attention in Congress,
with Florida's two senators urging that the hand-over of the boy be
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Connie Mack said he was upset that the
government would turn the boy over before the family had a chance
to work the issue out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is better equipped than Elian's own family to decide what
his future will be,'' Mack said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the House Republican leadership and two Cuban-American
members of Florida's congressional delegation invited Juan Miguel
Gonzalez to meet privately Wednesday in the Capitol. ``We want to
be sure that you are aware of all the options available to you as
you make your decision,'' they wrote in a letter delivered by
representatives of House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Washington correspondents Sue Schultz and Larry
Lipman contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
