</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI GIVES POLITICAL EVENTS A RAIN CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani abruptly postponed four
upstate political events for his Senate campaign on Tuesday, saying
unapologetically that he wanted to go to Wednesday's rescheduled
Yankee opening game instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long before I was a politician, I was a Yankee fan,'' Giuliani
said at his daily City Hall news briefing as he grinned broadly and
put on a Yankee cap. ``What can I tell you? This is me. I'm a
Yankee fan. I love the Yankees. I haven't missed an opening day
since I've been the mayor. I'm not going to have another opening
day as the mayor, maybe, if I get my wish, right?''
</P>
<P>
   At least one of Giuliani's upstate Republican hosts reacted
plaintively. ``I hope in the future that he'll find some time for
us up here,'' said Stephen Minarik, the Republican Party chairman
in Monroe County, who was expecting the mayor in Rochester on
Tuesday at a Lunch With Rudy for more than 400 women. ``I'm not
going to kid you and say that there's not disappointment. A lot of
people did put a lot of time into this event.''
</P>
<P>
   One was Minarik's wife, Renee, a chairwoman of the event. She
and the other organizers called 400 people Tuesday and told them
not to come. The other upstate events _ a women's forum, a
question-and-answer session at a center for the elderly and a
$1,000-a-person fund-raiser _ were planned in the Buffalo area
Wednesday. In Rochester, some organizers of the lunch first heard
of the cancellation from New York City reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans reacted with astonishment to Giuliani's
decision. ``If he keeps this up, it won't be his last chance to go
to opening day as mayor of New York,'' said one state Republican
political consultant. ``And that's all I can say, because otherwise
it's like tossing a match into a fireworks display.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to admire him, though. Because nobody else would
admit it, that `I'm blowing it off to go to opening day.' They'd
come up with come cockamamie excuse like `I've got to go to a
ribbon cutting.'''
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to the mayor's opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
reacted to the decision with astonishment and then delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know he's had a tough couple of weeks,'' Clinton
said, alluding to the mayor's sagging polls. ``It might be good for
him to go to a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she added brightly: ``And you know, I've had a great couple
of weeks traveling around upstate New York. Last week I was in
Binghamton and Greene and Rochester and Corning and Albany, and I'm
back in Albany today. I'll be back in Buffalo tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans north of the Bronx County line have been complaining
for months that the mayor is ignoring them and that Clinton is
receiving alarmingly lavish news coverage from her frequent trips
upstate. Last week, when a New York Times/CBS News poll showed that
Clinton was 8 points ahead of the mayor overall and was even with
him upstate _ an unusual situation for a Democrat _ Republicans
consoled themselves that at least the polls might propel Giuliani
out of City Hall and into Broome County.
</P>
<P>
   They apparently did, even though Giuliani says he pays no
attention to polls, even though the mayor left a Broome County
dinner last Friday after a 22-minute speech, before dessert. But he
stayed long enough to plead for understanding from the 1,000
guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've felt I haven't been here enough, I ask you to please
give me a break: I have a fulltime day job,'' Giuliani said to
laughter and applause. ``Tell your friends and neighbors that. Tell
them that the mayor of New York City is like them. He works for a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has frequently said that the first lady has no fulltime
job and that she is free to campaign as much as she chooses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
