<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AT FUND-RAISER; BUSH AD ON YAHOO; 3 SURVEYS FAVOR BUSH;
SENATOR FIGHTS LAWYERS GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORE AT FUND-RAISER
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore kicked off another week of
multimillion-dollar fund-raising for the Democratic National
Committee with a dinner last night at the Mayflower Hotel in
Washington. Andrew Tobias, the financial writer and gay activist
who is treasurer of the committee, was the host of the dinner,
where 50 people paid $20,000 each, raising $1 million for the
party.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AD ON YAHOO!
</P>
<P>
   For months, Gov. George W. Bush has had a link on his Web site
(www.georgewbush.com) called a ``tax calculator.'' Put in marital
status, number of children, annual income and percentage of income
from a second earner, and it tells how much would be saved under
Bush's proposed $483 billion tax cut. With tax returns due on
Monday, the Bush campaign has begun to advertise the tax calculator
on Yahoo, the popular Internet portal. A caution: The calculator
only accepts income up to $100,000; more than half the savings
under the Bush plan would go to taxpayers with incomes above that.
</P>
<P>
   THREE SURVEYS FAVOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Three recent nationwide surveys show George W. Bush leading Al
Gore. In a poll conducted by the Gallup Organization for CNN and
USA Today, Bush was preferred by 50 percent, Gore by 41 percent; 8
percent of the 502 likely voters surveyed April 7-9 were undecided.
Marist College in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., surveyed 817 registered
voters in a nationwide poll April 3-5. Bush was the choice of 45
percent, and Gore 40 percent; 15 percent were undecided. The Zogby
America Poll, conducted April 1-4 with 842 likely voters, found 46
percent backing Bush, 42 percent for Gore and 12 percent undecided.
The advantage Bush has in each poll is within its margin of
sampling error. The margin for the Zogby and Marist polls was plus
or minus three percentage points and for the Gallup Poll, plus or
minus five percentage points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SENATOR FIGHTS LAWYERS GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rod Grams of Minnesota, a Republican facing a tough
re-election battle from a crowded field of opponents, has also had
to contend with tough television advertising in the Twin Cities.
Issue ads sponsored in part by the Association of Trial Lawyers of
America attack Grams for supporting legislation that would make it
harder for victims of asbestos-related illnesses to sue asbestos
companies. This week, Grams held news conferences in Minnesota and
Washington to accuse the trial lawyers of attempted blackmail and
bribery, saying a lobbyist for the group left a taped telephone
message for the senator's campaign aide suggesting that the ads
would not run if Grams dropped his sponsorship of the bill. Kurt
Zellers, Grams' campaign press secretary, said the tape had been
turned over to the Justice Department for possible investigation.
The president of the trial lawyers' group, Richard Middleton,
dismissed Grams' charge as ``not only absurd, but libelous on its
face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
