<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-LEE-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      04-11 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS SAY IBF DEMANDED BRIBES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Robert W. Lee Sr., the founder of the
International Boxing Federation, corrupted the sport by demanding
bribes from boxers and their managers and promoters in return for
favored rankings and shots at championship bouts, federal
prosecutors contended Tuesday during opening statements in Lee's
trial on charges of racketeering and bribery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about the boxers who got left behind, who had
managers or promoters unwilling or unable to pay bribes,'' said
Jose Sierra, an assistant U.S. attorney as he ticked off a list of
promoters who would testify about the alleged bribes to Lee, who,
he said, ``never broke a sweat in the gym or took a punch.''.
</P>
<P>
   But in his own opening statement, Lee's lawyer painted a
contrasting picture, in which he described Lee as the ``proud
creator'' of the only major boxing sanctioning organization run by
African-Americans. The defense lawyer, Gerald Krovatin, said that
Lee had been operating a private business in an arena that was more
entertainment than sports _ one in which sanctioning bodies like
the IBF were locked in a ``love-hate relationship'' with promoters
and cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   Krovatin told jurors that in such an atmosphere, what is
considered a bribe depends on ``your perspective and your agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are the promoters, television all aligned with the
government in this case?'' Krovatin asked. ``Some of these
promoters have been trying to get rid of the sanctioning
organizations for years. That's why I say agendas.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxing itself seemed to be on trial here Tuesday in U.S.
District Court as Lee, 66, and his son, Robert Lee Jr., 38, faced
35 counts of bribery, racketeering, money laundering and tax
evasion, allegations that have rocked the sport and sullied its
already tarnished image. Testifying for the prosecution will be a
half dozen promoters and managers who are unindicted
co-conspirators in the case and who, under nonprosecution
agreements, are expected to describe what they said were bribes
paid to Lee and others in the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   Indicted with Lee and his son were Donald W. Brennan, 86, of
Warsaw, Va., who was chairman of the IBF championship committee,
and Francisco Fernandez, of Columbia, the IBF South American
representative. Brennan's trial was severed because of his ill
health; Fernandez has not been taken into custody.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, U.S. District Court Judge John W. Bissell turned down
a defense challenge of the government's planned use of hours of
videotapes taken in motel-room meetings in which Lee appears to
accept and talk about bribes with C. Douglas Beavers, the former
IBF rankings chairman and a cooperating witness for the
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in addition to describing some of the videotapes,
Sierra, the federal prosecutor, described in great detail the
workings of boxing's sanctioning commissions, specifically the IBF,
which is based in East Orange. The coin of the realm in boxing,
Sierra said, is a shot at the championship, because ``to paraphrase
a bank robber, `that is where the money is.''' But access to such
fights is determined by rankings and, Sierra said, Lee structured
the IBF so that he had absolute control of the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Among those from the boxing world expected to testify under
immunity from prosecution are Beavers, who prosecutors say was the
intermediary in many of the bribes, as well as a beneficiary; Ivan
Ferris Chadid, a Colombian promoter who allegedly paid to have his
fighters ranked for lucrative bouts; and Stan Hoffman and Wilfred
Sauerland, promoters who figured in nearly $200,000 in alleged
bribes in connection with a June 1995 heavyweight championship bout
between George Foreman and Axel Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   Krovatin said the case was really not about the fighters, but
about the business of boxing and promoters. ``They are the ones at
the top of the food chain,'' he said. ``And they are fickle lot,
who one day love you and the next day talk about you like a dog.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
