<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-USHERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LAST YANKEE USHERS, IT'S BOTTOM OF THE 9TH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo, NYT10, was sent on April 10 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By COREY KILGANNON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the days of the Babe, Mickey and even Reggie,
going to Yankee Stadium usually meant being seated by an old-timer
in a red suit and cap who took your torn ticket and showed you to
your seat. After giving the chair a quick wipe, he handed back the
ticket stub, and maybe dispensed a bit of Bronx baseball wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Ushers were once as familiar a sight at the Stadium as players'
pinstripes, but when the Yankees take the field Wednesday for their
home opener, there will only be eight of the traditional
seat-finders.
</P>
<P>
   Used to be, more than 300 ushers worked a sold-out game at
Yankee Stadium, but over the years, the Yankees organization
allowed the staff to dwindle through attrition, steadily replacing
them with security guards. Now, it is likely that Yankee Stadium
ushers will be extinct when their latest union contract expires
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin Schifren, an usher since 1954, said that when he started
working at the Stadium, the team gave each usher a snappy uniform,
a fluffy mitt for wiping seats and a measure of respect.
</P>
<P>
   But things have changed. The uniform _ red slacks and blazer, a
peaked cap and a blue tie _ has given way to the nondescript khaki
slacks and windbreaker. In the old days, six-man crews often worked
a single section of seats. Now, ushers stand at the openings of the
tunnels. A`ter the game, they used to line up on the field. Now
they can leave after the third inning. They may no longer accept
tips, walk fans to seats or even brush seats off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're the ones getting brushed off,'' said Schifren, 78,
who asked that other critical remarks against the club not be
printed ``because I love Yankee baseball.'' He thought it best to
stick to the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   For the ushers, the good old days were over by 1987, when the
club renamed the 20 remaining ones ``directors'' and reduced their
role to pointing out seats to fans. By last year, there were 10
ushers left, and when their contract expired last month, Yankee
management met with leaders of Local 366 of the Ushers and Ticket
Takers Union to talk about eliminating their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The team wanted to replace the last of the ushers with security
guards, said Douglas Menna, a lawyer for New York State's Central
Labor Council who helped the ushers negotiate. ``They said they
needed the money to pay the salaries of the ballplayers,'' he said.
``I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ushers make about $72 per game. The players' payroll is
about $92.5 million, the highest in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Menna argued that eliminating the jobs _ which all belonged to
men in their 60s, 70s and 80s _ might violate age discrimination
laws. In the end, the two sides agreed to a new two-season contract
through the fall of 2001, with the union agreeing to give up two
spots held by ushers who were ready to retire.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The ushers fear this will be their last contract, Menna said.
``The elimination of the jobs over the years has left a sense of
bitterness in these old-time New Yorkers that have been loyal fans
and employees and true to the Yankee tradition.''
 &UR;  &LR;  END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cerrone, a spokesman for the Yankees, would not comment on
the negotiations or the team's handling of the ushers, other than
confirming that security guards were taking over their role. ``I've
been here five years, and this is the first time anyone has asked
me about the ushers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Across town at Shea Stadium, the Mets still have more than 100
full-service ushers on staff. Most ballparks around the country
still have them, said Roger Hayden, director of ballpark operations
for the Baltimore Orioles, who attends annual conventions for
major-league stadium directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``At our convention in Seattle this year,'' Hayden said, ``most
of the directors I spoke to around the league said they still have
a full usher corps.'' The Orioles, who opened a new stadium in
1992, have kept roughly 200 ushers since 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Yankee Stadium ushers declined to be interviewed
for fear of endangering their jobs, and others, like Schifren,
stuck mostly to baseball, insisting that their most critical
comments not be printed. During his first season, Schifren said, he
was assigned to tend the bleachers. From there, he watched Mickey
Mantle patrol center field and saw his favorite Yankee moment: Don
Larsen's perfect game in the 1956 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Schifren worked the mezzanine when Reggie Jackson hit his three
home runs in one World Series game against the Los Angeles Dodgers
in 1977. He tended the box seats when David Wells pitched his
perfect game in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, we were part of history,'' Schifren said. ``We
enjoyed a certain rapport with the fans. It was a real family
thing. We offered a service because we knew the city and had a
history of what New York was like, all the old ballparks. You felt
like you were wanted there, and you felt proud that you were part
of the Yankee organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Stepman grew up five blocks from Yankee Stadium and began
working as an usher there in 1947, when the salary was $3 a game. A
good day of tips netted an additional $15.
</P>
<P>
   The longest batted ball he ever saw was hit by Mantle. Stepman,
80, a linen supply manager by day, was working in the right field
seats. The Mick knocked a ball that shattered lights mounted on a
support beam over the right field wall, Stepman recalled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shot has remained frozen in my memory,'' he said. ``If
that ball was hit six inches to the left, it would've landed on
River Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominick Bamburi, 70, grew up in the Bronx, 10 minutes by bus
from the Stadium, where he has worked as an usher for 42 years. His
days working in a steel mill on East 116th Street in Manhattan have
become a blur, he said, but he still recalls watching from his
section in the right field stands when the fans swarmed the field
when Chris Chambliss hit the home run that won the 1976 pennant. He
also recalled Tommy John's often having coffee with the ushers,
whose locker room was near the players' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The need for ushers is as vital as ever at the Stadium, Bamburi
said, since there are more first-time fans than ever visiting. ``So
many people still ask to be taken to their seat,'' he said. ``You
know, not everyone comes here from the Bronx anymore. People come
from all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepman agreed: ``Without us, they get sent in 10 different
directions.''
</P>
<P>
   The ushers were the keepers of Yankee lore, Bamburi said, with
older ushers passing down stories to the younger ones. ``They used
to say, `If you had a question about the Yankees, ask the ushers,
because they've been here from Day 1,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Steiner, 77, on the job since 1947, said the ushers
continue to serve that role: ``We still have kids coming up to us
asking, `Wow, did Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig really play here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what will happen when the ushers themselves fade into
history, Stepman said, ``The team is winning and attendance is up,
but the fans will be poorer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
