<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-HOME-RUNS-ART-NYT     04-11 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOME-RUNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME THE COMMISH: HIS SIGNATURE IS ALL OVER THIS SEASON'S HOME RUN
DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the signature; it has to be the signature. The pitchers are
the same, the hitters are the same. Oh, there's a new park that's
smaller than its predecessor, but not all the games in the first
week or so of the season have been played in Houston's Enron Field.
So it has to be the signature.
</P>
<P>
   Allan H. Selig, the baseballs say this season. Not Leonard S.
Coleman Jr. or Gene A. Budig, as they did last season, when the
balls were also identified as National League or American League.
The league distinction has been obliterated, first by the
elimination of the league presidents' jobs, then by the unification
of the separate league umpiring staffs, then by the signature on
the balls.
</P>
<P>
   Allan H. Selig.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be the reason.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for what? The reason for all of the balls' being
launched over fences in these early games of the season. They're
flying out so fast the statisticians have had to work overtime to
keep track of the numbers. Here a home run, there a home run,
everywhere a home run.
</P>
<P>
   More home runs _ 262 _ were hit in the first week of the 2000
season than were hit in any week of any previous season, Elias
Sports Bureau has determined. More home runs _ 57 _ were hit last
Friday than on any other day in major league history. The St. Louis
Cardinals hit more home runs in their first seven games than any
team had previously hit in its first seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Tuesday's schedule, major league players had hit 23
percent more home runs than they did in the corresponding period a
year ago, and that period, the first eight days of the season,
ignited a cascade of home runs that didn't ebb until the record for
a season was shattered.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Twins, for Bud's sake, hit six home runs in a game
the other day. That would have been a good week for the Twins last
season. In fact, they had a week last September when they didn't
hit any home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins' uncharacteristic barrage produced one of 15 instances
when teams hit four or more home runs in a game in the first eight
days. Last year at this time, that type of outbreak had occurred
only twice.
</P>
<P>
   The home run theme of this season seems to be a variation of the
Ernie Banks exhortation of ``let's play two.'' Hitters have been
saying, ``Let's hit two.'' One is not enough. Twenty-two times
players have slugged two home runs in a game, more than triple the
seven times it happened in the first eight days last season. On the
ninth day Tuesday Carl Everett added his name to the list, which
included Jeromy Burnitz of Milwaukee twice.
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin Elster, the Los Angeles shortstop who had retired from
baseball before the 1999 season, went all 23 of those players one
better Tuesday. He hit three home runs on opening day Tuesday at
Pacific Bell Park, the San Francisco Giants' new home.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Drew of St. Louis is on the list, too. Drew, in fact, had
hit four home runs in his 11 times at bat entering the Cardinals'
game Tuesday night in Houston, where Enron Field is far friendlier
to hitters than the Astrodome ever was. Come to think of it, the
Astros pitchers may want to stage a wildcat strike on the ground
that they never had an opportunity to negotiate that change in
their working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little scary in this park,'' Walt Jocketty, the
Cardinals' general manager, said Tuesday by telephone from Houston.
``The ball just really jumps out of here. We had a one-run lead
going into the ninth inning last night and luckily we got out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, the commissioner's chief of baseball operations,
attended the Pacific Bell Park opener and said, ``The ball was
jumping out of there today.''
</P>
<P>
   The new parks, however, are not the sole reason for the early
eruption of home runs. Looking for reasons, some pitchers
apparently have cited the silver ink on the 2000 baseballs. They
say it smudges easily and gets into the seams, making it difficult
to grip the balls.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said he hadn't heard that one. The home run
explosion, however, had not escaped his attention. He said he
talked about it the other day with Alderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Sandy,'' Selig said by telephone from Detroit,
``because people keep talking about the ball. But they don't have
any evidence that the ball is juiced up.'' He said tests done on
the balls last year showed they were the same as they had been.
Tests will most likely be done again this year just to silence the
conspiracy theory about the souped-up ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thoughts are not any different than the last year or two,''
Selig said. ``I really believe it's a combination of things. I
think it's the smaller ballparks; players are bigger and stronger;
you've had two expansions in the '90s. There's no question we've
had an offensive explosion. I don't think people can pinpoint one
particular reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he was told, there might be one reason. Given a hint, he
said, ``Because my signature's on it?''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, the owners enhanced the powers of the
commissioner. The additional potency apparently extends to the
commissioner's signature. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
