<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-NYT     04-11 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CLEAN SLATE, TEAMS FACE OFF FOR A POLISHED CUP  
 BY JOE LAPOINTE  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hockey people like to think that players and teams can redeem a
bad or mediocre regular season with a good showing in the Stanley
Cup playoffs. In this spirit, perhaps the National Hockey League as
a whole can use the tournament, which begins Wednesday night, to
burnish an image left smudged by some events of the 1999-2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   Not that everything was negative during the last six months. The
St. Louis Blues, an emerging power in the West, won the
regular-season championship with an emerging star in goalie Roman
Turek.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Pavel Bure regained his superstar status by scoring
58 goals to lead the league. In Los Angeles, the Kings returned to
the playoffs in a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York area, Scott Gomez of the Devils and Mike York of
the Rangers were among the best of a promising crop of rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Among the veteran stars, Steve Yzerman of the Detroit Red Wings
and Brett Hull of the Dallas Stars crossed the 600-goal threshold,
and Hull also tied his father, Bobby Hull, at 610 goals.
</P>
<P>
   In overtime this season, the four-on-four format led to fewer
ties and more excitement. On television, ABC took over from Fox and
immediately improved upon the incomprehensible telecasts of the
previous seasons. Chugging along steadily were ESPN and ESPN2,
which produced the ABC product on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   But television also transmitted disturbing images that damaged
the public perception of a sport still struggling for recognition
as it prepares to expand to 30 teams. In the first week of the
season, Mike Modano of the defending champion Stars left the ice on
a stretcher after taking a hit into the boards and sustaining a
concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the season, Marty McSorley of the Boston Bruins was
suspended by the league and also charged with assault with a weapon
by Canadian authorities for his stick attack against Donald
Brashear of the Vancouver Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   In nonhostile accidents, Trent McCleary of the Montreal
Canadiens nearly died after he was struck in the throat by a puck
and Bryan Berard of the Toronto Maple Leafs lost sight in one eye
after being poked with a stick. Many players have complained about
ice quality in many places, and that is unlikely to improve during
the warming weather of spring.
</P>
<P>
   In television ratings, the audience growth was ``flat,'' to use
the euphemism of the industry. And the playoffs begin without major
markets such as New York and Chicago or traditional teams like the
Canadiens and the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   While the Zambonis repair and prepare the playing surfaces,
medical experts tend to the physical injuries and spin doctors tend
to image wounds. Among those in sell mode is Commissioner Gary
Bettman.
</P>
<P>
   ``On balance, this has been an excellent season,'' Bettman said
recently in a conference call with reporters. ``Scoring is up.
Penalty minutes are down. A little perspective is in order.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone noted that David Letterman recently mocked hockey
violence with a Top 10 list on his television show, Bettman said:
``If he thinks we're important enough to be worth talking about,
that's not terrible. I like it better when David Letterman invites
the Stanley Cup champions on with the Stanley Cup, which he does
now on a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the possibility of the Stars repeating as
champions, Bettman said: ``Whatever happens is great as long as we
have a terrific playoffs. And that's what we're looking forward
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there is promise for an interesting tournament. The
Stars, defending their first championship, represent the Western
Conference, which has the better teams. The Stars open against the
Edmonton Oilers, a difficult opponent in recent years. Because the
Colorado Avalanche's Peter Forsberg is out with a shoulder injury
until further notice, the Stars' toughest competition could come
from the Detroit Red Wings, who won the trophy in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leaders for the Red Wings are Coach Scotty Bowman and
defenseman Chris Chelios, both experienced and ornery as the
occasion demands. The Red Wings open against the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Turek, the Blues boast two top defensemen in Chris
Pronger and Al MacInnis and a forward line called the Slovak Pack.
Pierre Turgeon has revived his career as the best center of the
Blues. But it is difficult for a team such as St. Louis to surge to
the championship level so suddenly. Those seeking a dark horse in
the West might consider either the San Jose Sharks, who face the
Blues, or the Phoenix Coyotes over the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, the lower-seeded teams have a better chance, as the
Buffalo Sabres and the Washington Capitals demonstrated in the last
two seasons. The eighth-ranked Sabres open against the Philadelphia
Flyers, the top-seeded team in the bracket, and the Sabres have the
best angle for an upset.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres finished strong; they added good players through
trades; and their goalie, Dominik Hasek, got healthy and back to
top form. Plus, the Sabres will play a traumatized Flyers team.
</P>
<P>
   Flyers Coach Roger Neilson is being treated for cancer. He hopes
to return for the second round. The team's former captain, Eric
Lindros, is being treated for a concussion. He hopes to return for
the second round, although the team demoted him from captain during
his feud with General Manager Bobby Clarke. The veteran goalie John
Vanbiesbrouck has been replaced on the first string by Brian
Boucher, a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils squandered the conference lead, which they held until
the final week of the season. They open against the Florida
Panthers, who have not won a post-season series since reaching the
finals in 1996. But the Devils have won only one round since taking
the Stanley Cup in 1995. According to NHL rules, one of these teams
has to win this series.
</P>
<P>
   Another upset looms in the Pittsburgh-Washington series. The
Capitals have been dull but efficient since the turn of the
millennium. The Penguins have rebuilt from bankruptcy under the
ownership of Mario Lemieux. General Manager Craig Patrick changed
coaches, traded players and has done much with little.
</P>
<P>
   North of the border, they will not play ``The Star-Spangled
Banner'' before the Ottawa-Toronto games, but everyone, including
the news media, will wave one team flag or another in the first
ever ``Battle of Ontario.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
