<SLUG> BC-NY-DOCTOR-ACQUITTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RETRIAL, DOCTOR ACQUITTED OF SEXUALLY ABUSING A PATIENT
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID ROHDE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Griffin was something of a prodigy. He
received a full scholarship to attend Columbia University at age
16, he said, and was appointed director of medicine at St. Luke's
Hospital in Manhattan at 33.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1995, a patient accused Griffin, a gastroenterologist
with a lucrative practice on Central Park West, of sexually abusing
her while she was sedated. He denied the charge, but in 1996 he was
convicted of sodomy and falsifying business records, stripped of
his medical license and sentenced to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Released on bail while he appealed the conviction, Griffin spent
the next several years working on a horse farm and driving a truck
to support himself. In 1998, an appeals court ruled that Griffin's
first trial was unfair and ordered him retried.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin's second trial _ and his legal odyssey _ ended on
Tuesday with a jury in State Supreme Court in Manhattan acquitting
him of all charges. Griffin, 45, wept in court after the verdict
was read and vowed to regain his medical license. ``I don't know
what to say,'' he said. ``I'm still a little bit numb. It's been
something indescribable that's happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had no comment on the acquittal, which cannot be
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In her testimony, the patient said she had gone to Griffin's
office for a colonoscopy and endoscopy on Jan. 13, 1995. She was
given a combination of two sedatives, Versed and Demerol, in
preparation for the procedures. When she woke up, the patient said,
she found Griffin performing oral sex on her.
</P>
<P>
   A juror at the second trial who would not give his name said
doubts emerged after the panel heard testimony that those sedatives
can block patients' memory and cause them to experience sexual
fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin's lawyer, Paul F. Callan, said the case showed the
dangers posed by the sedatives, which are widely used by doctors.
``This case is a nightmare example of what can happen,'' Callan
said.
</P>
<P>
   In striking down Griffin's conviction, the Appellate Division of
the State Supreme Court voted 3 to 2, finding that Justice Marcy L.
Kahn improperly prevented defense lawyers from asking the victim
about a $10 million civil lawsuit she filed against the doctor,
Callan said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Bridget Fleming, also asked a series of detailed
questions in the first trial about an alleged affair between
Griffin and another patient, despite being told by the judge not to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin's accuser was not in court on Tuesday, and prosecutors
have not released her name, as is customary in sexual abuse cases.
Callan said her civil lawsuit is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Another piece of evidence in the case was a secretly recorded
conversation where the doctor repeatedly denied sodomizing the
woman but admitted kissing her. In his testimony, Griffin denied
kissing the woman and said he made the false admission to calm her
before she created a scene in his office. Griffin, who once lived
in a luxurious condominium on Manhattan's Upper West Side, has
recently been sleeping on his great-aunt's living room couch in
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, I never used to question people,'' he said.
``Now, I know this is a world where you have to be on guard every
minute of every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000411.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-11 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TONY BLAIR'S BABY _ SOME DECISIONS LAST LONGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By LISA BELKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last we heard, Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain was deciding
(and deciding, and deciding) whether or not to take paternity leave
when his fourth child is born in May. ``I've got a country to
run,'' he sputtered to the BBC. ``I honestly don't know what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   That has led to the predictable jokes about nappies and a less
predictable debate over the importance of paternity leave _ a
spanking new concept in Britain, which just passed a law allowing
parents up to 13 weeks of unpaid time off from work during the
first five years of each child's life.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest voices seem to think Blair should go for it. ``Show
new dads the way, Tony,'' screamed a front-page headline in The
Mirror, which argued that the prime minister had a duty to spend at
least one week at home. His wife, Cherie Blair, seems to agree. A
powerful lawyer with ambitions to be a High Court judge, she has
praised Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen of Finland for taking six
whole days off for the birth of a daughter last month. ``I, for
one, am promoting a widespread adoption of this fine example,''
said Blair, who, for the record, plans to take at least 13 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Here on this side of the Atlantic, certain circles are watching
closely. We too have a law (the 1993 Family and Medical Leave Act)
that was intended to encourage paternity leave, but so far it has
not sent men home to their newborns in droves. A poll by Oxygen
Media and the Markle Foundation found that although a decisive
majority of us believe fathers should take more than two weeks of
paternity eave, 71 percent couldn't think of any male friend or
relative who had actually done this.
</P>
<P>
   That is mostly because here (as in Britain) the law fails to put
any money where its mouth is, providing only for unpaid leave. But
it is also because changing the law is not the same as changing the
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women who take time off are seen as responding to a higher
calling,'' said Suzanne Braun Levine, the author. ``Men who take
time off are seen as being henpecked and letting the operation
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine spoke to scores of men for her new book, ``Father
Courage: What Happens When Men Put Family First'' (Harcourt), and
found that those who do stay home with their newborns disguise it
as something else _ unused vacation, comp time, sick leave. What
men need, she has decided, is a good role model, and she thinks the
British prime minister would do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   But what is he to be an example of? To hear some of the talk on
this side of the Atlantic, you'd think he was to be lauded simply
for being so darn supportive. ``He should take some time off and
help his wife with the wee one,'' suggested one editorial. Hmm. How
nice of him to help. And how helpful his wife has been, earning an
estimated three times his salary these last few years.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more constructive to focus for a moment on the ``wee
one.'' In her forthcoming book, ``Flux: Women on Sex, Work, Kids,
Love and Life in a Half Changed World'' (Doubleday), Peggy
Orenstein cites studies showing that the more time a man spends
alone with a baby during the early months _ and we're talking
full-time here, not ``helping'' Mom when she takes an hour off to
run to the supermarket _ the more involved he is as a parent for
all the years afterward. ``Paternity leave has lifelong benefits to
a child,'' she says. ``Why aren't women storming the ramparts over
this?''
</P>
<P>
   Why indeed? And why, while we're asking, aren't men? After all,
this is about men. Women take maternity leave because they want to
be with their new babies. If they didn't want to, they would
recover physically, then dash back to work. Yet nothing I've read,
no talk show chat that I've heard, has suggested that time with his
baby is a gift that Blair should give to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it because I couldn't imagine not doing it,'' Ed
Tagliaferri, a vice president at Dan Klores Associates, said of the
three weeks he cobbled from vacation time and comp time seven years
ago when his son was born. ``I wanted to experience it all and
throw myself into it from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, Tony Blair should take paternity leave because someone
needs to set a good example. And yes, he should take paternity
leave because studies show it will be good for his child. But
wouldn't it be something if this man could take time with his baby
because he passionately wanted to? What better role for the rest of
us to model?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2335EDT &QL; 
