u a BC-NY-CONEY-ISLAND-STADI     04-11 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONEY-ISLAND-STADIUM--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL SECURES A BALLPARK FOR CONEY ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIAN E. BARNES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leaders of the City Council and the Giuliani
administration agreed Tuesday to build a new minor league stadium
in Coney Island and return professional baseball to Brooklyn as
part of a $91 million redevelopment plan for the area.
</P>
<P>
   The deal removes the last obstacles to a $31 million, 6,500-seat
stadium and kills a nearly decade-old plan to build an amateur
athletic arena on Coney Island's Steeplechase Park, where the new
ballpark is now planned. In return for the council's support of the
stadium plan, the city's Economic Development Corporation agreed
Tuesday to spend another $30 million to improve the boardwalk and
build playgrounds, bathhouses, retail shops and volleyball courts.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and the City Council also agreed to create a
local development corporation to plan sports, recreation and
entertainment programs in Coney Island and surrounding
neighborhoods. Council officials said that the group would be given
the $30 million that the city had earmarked for the amateur arena,
commonly called Sportsplex.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plan would mean the return of a professional team
to Brooklyn for the first time since the Dodgers moved to Los
Angeles in 1958, council members talked more Tuesday about economic
rejuvenation than shagging fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a plan that was dying on the vine and we made it into
a package that will result in the redevelopment of Coney Island and
all of south Brooklyn,'' said Herbert Berman, the chairman of the
council's finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   The deal swells the price tag of what was once advertised by
administration officials as a $20 million ballpark, and comes after
the council approved a $71 million minor league ballpark for Staten
Island. But Michael G. Carey, the president of the city's Economic
Development Corporation, said the latest deal would do far more to
reverse the economic decline of Coney Island, which has failed to
reverse its sagging fortunes even as once-faded gems like Times
Square have rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall effect here is to rejuvenate the neighborhood,''
Carey said. ``We are bring back an area that has been neglected.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Brooklyn borough president, Howard Golden, fought the
plan for the minor league stadium, saying the borough deserved
better than a low-level minor league team. Greg Brooks, his chief
of staff, said the city should have made improvements like the new
bathrooms and pavilions without foisting the team on Coney Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The borough president wouldn't argue against funding for the
boardwalk,'' Brooks said. ``But such funds could have been
appropriated without bringing a short-season minor league team to
Coney Island, which will provide minimal economic benefit at a very
high cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The city and the New York Mets organization, which owns a Class
A minor league team that will play at Coney Island, hope to open
the stadium at Steeplechase Park in June 2001. This year, the minor
league team hopes to play at St. John's University's baseball
field.
</P>
<P>
   After Carey, Berman and other City Council leaders worked out
the details of the agreement Tuesday afternoon, the council land
use committee voted 16-0 to approve the plan for the stadium and
improvements to Coney Island. Council leaders said they expected
the full body to approve the deal on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to build the stadium has been contentious. The Mets
had wanted to make a temporary home in the Parade Grounds, a park
deluged with soccer and Little League players each weekend, but
Golden filed suit and stopped the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Golden and Brooklyn Community Board 13 had also opposed the
Coney Island proposal during the city's land use review procedure,
forcing Tuesday's City Council vote. Community Board members had
argued that the stadium should not be built unless the city also
committed to Sportsplex.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the community board dropped its demand for the
arena in return for the city's promise of neighborhood improvements
and a commitment from the Mets to provide scholarships to baseball
clinics and job opportunities to neighborhood schoolchildren.
Martin Levine, the chairman of Community Board 13, said that even
with the approval of Giuliani, which was not forthcoming, it would
have taken at least two years to begin Sportsplex, and that was too
long to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Kiernan, who had led the effort to build the Sportsplex
as chairman of the Brooklyn Sports Foundation, said he expected few
new amateur athletic facilities to be built as a result of
Tuesday's deal. ``One thing that is painfully clear is that there
is no constituency for amateur sports,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
