u k BC-EDIT-HINCKLEY-NYT &LR;      04-11 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HINCKLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JOHN HINCKLEY'S REQUEST 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, April 12:
</P>
<P>
   The criminal trial of John Hinckley Jr. for shooting President
Reagan and three others in 1981 ended with a jury verdict of not
guilty by reason of insanity. Since then, the would-be assassin has
been confined to St. Elizabeth's Hospital in Washington for
treatment of his severe mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a disconcerting Washington Post report that officials
at the facility are recommending that he be released for
unsupervised daylong visits with his parents. The hospital's recent
letter to the court that oversees his case notes that Hinckley has
been living without incident in a minimum-security ward, has been
walking unescorted around hospital grounds for years, and
cooperates with every aspect of his treatment. It also says that
for the past six months Hinckley has taken field trips to several
restaurants and shopping malls under the watchful supervision of
hospital staff. ``In our opinion,'' the letter concludes, ``
Hinckley has sufficiently recovered from his mental illness to be
granted a limited conditional release without danger to himself and
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet granting Hinckley that kind of freedom is a risky step not
warranted by the full public record. Hospital officials say they
believe the disorders that led to his obsession with the actress
Jodie Foster and his violent assault on Reagan are now in remission
and that he requires no medication. But a psychiatrist called in by
prosecutors when the issue last arose, in 1997, warned the court
that Hinckley had the ability to hide serious problems, appearing
fine even to those treating him. Moreover, the hospital has been
wrong before. In the late 1980s the hospital withdrew its request
for Hinckley's conditional release after learning that he had
corresponded with Ted Bundy, the convicted serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office, which opposes the request, has asked
Senior Federal District Judge June Green for a hearing. It is right
to do so. The decision should not be based solely on the advice of
hospital doctors. The judgment of the court and respected outside
psychiatrists not involved in Hinckley's treatment should be
brought to bear. Green, who has shown skepticism in the past about
claims of Hinckley's progress, should not abandon that skepticism
now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
