<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAWYER-ATTRITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS, PUBLIC DEFENDERS MAY GET STUDENT LOAN RELIEF 
BY WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On most days, John M. Ryan, a senior prosecutor in
Queens, and Susan L. Hendricks, who oversees criminal defense
lawyers for the Legal Aid Society, make their living on different
sides of the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, they and scores of district attorneys and
senior public defenders around the state have formed an unusual
alliance to support legislation they hope will halt the attrition
that is draining experienced lawyers from the ranks of prosecutors
and public defenders.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, pending before the Senate and Assembly budget
committees, would appropriate $3 million to pay for loans incurred
in law school by assistant district attorneys and Legal Aid
lawyers, most of whom start out earning less than $40,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In Queens, where the district attorney, Richard A. Brown,
oversees 320 assistant district attorneys, 68 percent of the
lawyers hired between 1992 and 1996 have left, said Ryan, the chief
assistant district attorney. Lawyers hired in those years make up
the core group of felony trial assistants who have enough
experience to handle serious crimes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing too many talented young prosecutors because
they're drowning in their student loans,'' said Brown, who is
leading the effort for the legislation. ``It would be a shame if
the great strides that we've made in the fight against crime were
to be compromised by a lack of experienced professional
prosecutors.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's office surveyed hundreds of assistant district attorneys
around the state and found that about two-thirds have outstanding
student loans averaging $60,000, and that nearly 70 percent owed
between $50,000 and $125,000. Many have been unable to lower their
indebtedness during their tenure as prosecutors and have seen the
total actually increase, Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Law school tuition hovers around $20,000 a year, and entry-level
jobs at the city's better law firms pay roughly triple the starting
salary offered by the city's five district attorneys, so it is
becoming harder and harder for prosecutors to retain the lawyers
beyond the usual three-year commitment they demand.
</P>
<P>
   The loan burdens are affecting prosecutors' offices in the city
and across the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Legal Aid Attorneys, a union that represents
the lawyers, surveyed members on their loans and found that on
average, they spent nearly 30 percent of their annual income on
loan payments. ``For the vast majority of law school graduates,
this is an enormous issue, and it deters them from taking
public-interest jobs, or they do it but can't continue that for the
rest of their careers,'' Hendricks said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
