<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-BARAK-0412-CO     04-11 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BARAK-0412-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, BARAK DISCUSS MIDEAST PEACE PROGRESS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak huddled for nearly four hours in the Oval Office Tuesday
night, trying to press a difficult set of Middle East peace talks
toward a so-far elusive finish line.
</P>
<P>
   In extended talks that touched on all aspects of the peace
process _ including Israeli negotiations with the Palestinians, the
Syrians and Lebanese _ Clinton and Barak made apparent headway in
clarifying areas of agreement and defining the remaining gaps.
</P>
<P>
   After talks wrapped up at 10:20 p.m. (EST), though, a White
House official designated to brief journalists on background
indicated that the substance of any progress would be kept private
at least until Clinton meets with Palestinian Authority President
Yasser Arafat here on April 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good, productive, serious discussion about all
facets of the Middle East peace process,'' the official said,
speaking on background in the White House briefing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Clinton) feels very encouraged there is intensification,
renewed energy in the Palestinian track,'' the aide said, but he
warned that substantive differences continue to divide Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the midst of dealing with the real heart and soul of
the hardest issues,'' dividing the two sides, the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Clinton apparently won a pledge from Barak to not go
ahead immediately with the proposed sale of advanced airborne radar
equipment to China.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials worry that the sale of the $250 million
PHALCON system could give China a strategic edge in controlling air
strikes against neighboring Taiwan, a close U.S. economic and
strategic partner.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Defense Secretary William Cohen has said the sale of
sophisticated weaponry to China could boomerang on Israel,
particularly if China were later to share it with Israel's Arab
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton voiced U.S. concerns directly to Barak, who agreed to
discuss the issue further with U.S. officials, said the senior
White House aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister indicated that he understood our concern
and that it would be something we would talk about further,'' the
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak left Washington and was scheduled to return on Wednesday
to Israel, where he was to host Chinese President Jiang Zemin for
the first-ever visit to Israel by a Chinese head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Originally slated as an hour-long conversation, Tuesday's
session turned into an Oval Office mini-summit when, after an hour
and a half of businesslike talks, the two leaders grew hungry and
had the White House mess bring in hamburgers and mixed vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later aides saw trays of cookies being ferried into
the Oval Office, where Clinton and Barak met with only notetakers
accompanying them.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the men emerged at 10:20 p.m. (EST) _ nearly four
hours after their meeting began _ Clinton was in a jovial frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president had a big smile on his face,'' the White House
official said, ``and, standing next to the prime minister, he said
'We've solved everything.'''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat and Barak are working against a self-imposed May 13
deadline for agreeing to a blueprint for peace. They have set a
Sept. 13 deadline for wrapping up the so-called final status issues
dividing their two peoples _ including the contentious matters of
the future of Jerusalem, the question of Palestinian statehood and
the right of Palestinian refugees to return to lands controlled by
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The broad outlines of any peace accord between the two call for
Israel to relinquish control of certain territories in the Gaza
Strip and the occupied West Bank in exchange for security
guarantees and an end to anti-Israel attacks from Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hosted Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Sharaa for a week of peace talks last January in nearby
Sheperdstown, W.Va. The talks broke down, however, over issues near
the heart of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was the first time Clinton had met Barak since
Sheperdstown. It was the first time the two leaders had spoken
since a pair of telephone calls two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
