<HEADER>
A4207 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-DRAFT-TEX     04-11 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-DRAFT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS RELY ON LACEWELL'S DRAFT EXPERTISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Pound for pound, Larry Lacewell is the most
valuable person in the Cowboys' organization.
</P>
<P>
   The 63-year-old director of college and pro scouting _ all
5-foot-6, 174 pounds of him _ has coordinated Cowboys drafts since
1993, one year after walking away from a 30-year college coaching
career that included two national championships (1974 and 1975) as
defensive coordinator at the University of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell, from Fordyce, Ark., is a disciple of the late Paul
``Bear'' Bryant, who grew up in nearby Moro Bottoms, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and Arvel ``Chink'' Lacewell, Larry's father who died
when Larry was in the ninth grade, were teammates on the Fordyce
High School Redbugs. In giving young Larry his first coaching job
(''I was in charge of just the left guard _ ``seriously'''') on
Alabama's 1959 football team, Bryant became the more influential
person, before or since, living or dead, on Lacewell's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world lost a lawyer because I fell in love with
coaching,'' Lacewell said during a lunch break this week at Valley
Ranch, where evaluations by 19 scouts and coaches are being made
for this weekend's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have five picks, beginning Saturday in the second
round with the 49th selection overall, then not another selection
until the fourth round, 109th overall, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Two wall artifacts particularly stand out inside Lacewell's
executive-size office. One is an oval-shape painting of Bryant. The
painting, which was signed in December 1982 just before Bryant's
death, hangs directly over Lacewell's desk. Across the room is a
framed newspaper account of the 1930 state champion Fordyce
Redbugs, including full-length uniform photos of Bear' Bryant and
Chink Lacewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team beat Don Hutson's team,'' Lacewell said proudly,
referring to the Hall of Fame great from Arkansas, who starred with
the 1935-45 Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   To trace Lacewell's background is to explain his success in
coaching and now scouting. He is truthful in a business where
hiding behind the truth is common and usually considered safer. He
knows talent. He appreciates speed. He knows what he does is not
brain surgery, but you do need to use your brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were geniuses doing this,'' Lacewell said, ``they'd
be making more money than Troy Aikman.''
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in a mill town. He honed his people skills by working
in the local pool hall. He bonded well with blacks and later used
those experiences to recruit players of all color at a time when
many parts of America were segregated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably the last of a generation with my kind of
background,'' Lacewell said. ``We were mill people. We were poor
... but everybody was poor. I drove a truck at the mill because my
mom had been left to raise four children on her own. On Saturdays,
I'd drive 110 miles, all inside the Fordyce city limits. Let me
tell you now, that's hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell is a natural-born storyteller and humorist. He draws
from both his small-town upbringing and his big-arena
accomplishments to make points. Lacewell is the first to admit that
his background has allowed him to knock on doors in small towns
across America in search of quality football players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Allen is a great example. If you're from Fordyce, Ark.,
you don't walk away from a trip to Sonoma State very well,''
Lacewell said of the Cowboys' 1994 second-round pick (46th overall)
who has been selected to five consecutive Pro Bowls as a starter at
three different offensive-line positions for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell, meanwhile, is considered by Cowboys owner Jerry Jones
to be more than just a war-room confidant at draft time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Lacewell is a treasure, just a tremendous asset to the
organization, because of his experiences and his background at
every level,'' said Jones, who has numerous business ventures aside
from the Cowboys. ``To me, Larry is as valuable a person with whom
I can consult, on a wide range of subjects, as I have available to
me in any walk of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones describes Lacewell as a closet intellectual.
</P>
<P>
   Because while Lacewell doesn't come across as a scholar, he
knows as much about Civil War history as he does the 40-yard times
of cornerbacks in this weekend's NFL draft. He has coached and
taught at the college level. As a student, he received his
bachelor's degree in three years and his masters in one. His
favorite TV shows are A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' and just about anything
on Documentary or the History Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking Lacewell's coaching career becomes something of a blur
after 1959 with Bryant at 'Bama: Arkansas State, Arkansas A&AMP;M and
Kilgore Junior College, Oklahoma, Wichita State, Iowa State, and
back to Oklahoma under Barry Switzer and two national
championships, plus three near misses. He finished at Tennessee in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to Kilgore Junior College in 1964 for $10,000, I
thought it couldn't get better than that,'' said Lacewell, only
half-jokingly. ``I was single. I had money in pocket, and I had the
Rangerettes in my classroom. It just don't get better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was working with Jimmy Johnson at Wichita State (1967)
and Barry Switzer at Oklahoma (1966 and 1969-78) that paved his way
to success in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry has had the respect of Jimmy, Barry, Chan \RGailey\S and
now Dave Campo,'' Jones said. ``Because he has been a coach, he has
that perspective, and they know it. And because of his background,
starting at such a young age and achieving success at such high
levels, Larry Lacewell makes no excuses. Yet, he has a tolerant
side when it comes to seeing talent and letting others inside the
\Rwar\S room have a voice on matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he does his homework,'' Jones added. ``He's a grinder. In
what the Dallas Cowboys do, he is invaluable.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
