<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-LENDING-LAWSUIT-2NDTA     04-11 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENDING-LAWSUIT-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ done anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not engage in predatory lending practices,'' said Anne
Duffield, a lawyer for Centex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The borrower was not happy with the performance of the home
improvement dealer. But we are not involved or connected in any way
to the home improvement dealer,'' she said. ``I think that we are
very honest and up-front with our borrowers.''
</P>
<P>
   By September 1999, Anderson's lawsuit was settled and her case
dismissed. Settlement terms are confidential. Poulikidis said he
paid nothing toward the settlement. Another contractor completed
the improvements.
More safeguards needed
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Anderson was lucky. Not all cases end with the
homeowners getting their repairs, or even keeping their homes,
despite legal protections.
</P>
<P>
   The federal truth in lending law requires creditors to explain
the cost of borrowing so customers can shop for the best deal. In
recent years, Congress amended the law to give borrowers
disclosures in writing at least three business days before loan
closing _ including a warning that they could lose their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Now Missouri and Kansas legislators are considering new laws.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri would make it a felony to arrange home improvement
loans for consumers without regard for their ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will emphasize the fact,'' said Rep. May Scheve, a
Grantwood Village Democrat, ``that we in Missouri aren't going to
allow these haphazard businesses to set up shop and take advantage
of our senior citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   A Kansas Senate committee considered a similar bill: The Unfair
Home Improvement Loans for Senior Citizens and Disabled Persons
Act. But that proposed legislation is likely to expire this year
for lack of interest among elected officials, according to banking
and insurance committee staff.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's bill, meanwhile, has been passed by the House and has
a good chance of Senate approval, sponsors said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, the mayor's staff recognized similar problems in
home-improvement lending. It was the story of a widow and her son
that spurred Mayor Kay Barnes' staff to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Williams and her son, who has cerebral palsy and uses a
wheelchair, faced foreclosure because she unwittingly had signed up
for a $14,000 home improvement loan. Eventually, she fell behind in
payments and faced eviction.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends began working in her behalf, calling various
agencies. Neighborhood advocates in the mayor's office enlisted
Legal Aid lawyers. Concerned citizens set up a fund, and Legal Aid
attorneys bought back Williams' home with $9,000 in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Now a city-sponsored task force _ of lawyers, credit counselors
and city staff _ is ready to take up the cause by educating
homeowners and fighting unscrupulous contractors and lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard about people within certain ZIP codes getting
hit with this stuff,'' said task force leader Donovan Mouton. ``We
can use the same methods, get the same lists and get people this
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson still gets mail from other home improvement
contractors, but she's more cautious now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust them,'' she said. ``I throw their letters in the
trash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
