<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PERU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FLAWED ELECTION IN PERU 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, April 12:
</P>
<P>
   Peru's presidential election reeks of fraud. This is not
surprising, given President Alberto Fujimori's disdain for
democratic principles, but even he should recognize that the
balloting irregularities invalidate the re-election victory he is
eager to claim. There must be a new, independently monitored
election.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's vote was marred by unexplained counting delays,
credible allegations of fraud and a suspiciously rising vote total
for Fujimori. His main opponent, Alejandro Toledo, stormed out of
obscurity in recent weeks to challenge the incumbent. Election Day
exit polls and counts organized by the Organization of American
States and Transparencia, a private monitoring group largely
financed by the United States, showed that Toledo had apparently
forced Fujimori into a runoff. A day later the government released
partial returns showing Fujimori with 49.6 percent of the vote, and
by Tuesday it had climbed to 49.8 percent, just short of the 50
percent required to avoid a second round of voting.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, first elected in 1990, revived a moribund economy and
defeated two dangerous terrorist groups. But throughout his
presidency he has governed autocratically. In a 1992 army-backed
coup, he closed down Congress and the supreme court. In their place
he created a more subservient legislature and judiciary, while his
intelligence service intimidated critics.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori amended the Constitution to permit a second term in
1995. He then unwisely decided to seek a third term and forced the
dismissal of three judges who insisted such a bid would be
unconstitutional. During this year's campaign his allies conducted
smear campaigns against his opponents and disrupted their rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a business school professor and former World Bank
official, benefited from a backlash over Fujimori's manipulations
and his identification with the country's Indian majority, which
has long been excluded from power. Only a fresh vote can produce an
outcome the people of Peru and the rest of the hemisphere can
trust. The United States and Latin American governments should
refuse to recognize Peru's election results until a scrupulously
fair and carefully monitored runoff is conducted. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-00 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
